<HEADLINE>
EMMYS GO TO `PRACTICE' AND TO `ALLY MCBEAL' 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The 51st annual Emmy Awards ceremony was marked on
Sunday night by plenty of deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``The Sopranos,'' the acclaimed new HBO series about a
Mafia family in suburban New Jersey, was expected to walk off with
numerous awards, it won only two. Veteran shows like ``The
Practice,'' ``Ally McBeal'' and ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' emerged as
significant winners. ``Ally McBeal'' won for best comedy series and
for the second year in a row ``The Practice'' won for best drama
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for dazzling new shows to break through at the
Emmys,'' said the actor John Lithgow, who won as best actor in a
comedy series for NBC's ``Third Rock From the Sun.'' He cited the
scarcity of awards to ``The Sopranos'' and said, ``The old guard
never seems to like new kids on the block.''
</P>
<P>
   David Chase, the creator of ``The Sopranos,'' won the Emmy for
writing of a drama series.
</P>
<P>
   And Edie Falco won the best-actress Emmy for a drama series for
her role as the shrewd and complicated Mafia wife in ``The
Sopranos.'' She beat such veteran television stars as Gillian
Anderson (``The X-Files''), Christine Lahti (``Chicago Hope'') and
Julianna Margulies (``E.R.''), as well as Lorraine Bracco, who
plays a psychiatrist on ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Falco said that she felt a little lonely as a winner when
some of her colleagues were passed up.
</P>
<P>
   The big winner of the night was David E. Kelley, creator of
``The Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal,'' two shows that took the top
drama and comedy prizes.
</P>
<P>
   And Dennis Franz won his fourth Emmy for his role as Andy
Sipowicz in ``N.Y.P.D. Blue.'' His rivals included James Gandolfini
of ``The Sopranos,'' Dylan McDermott of ABC's ``Practice,'' Sam
Waterston of ABC's ``Law and Order'' and Jimmy Smits of ``N.Y.P.D.
Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase told reporters that he was unsure why ``The Sopranos'' had
been so resonant for many television viewers. ``It goes beyond the
success of `The Sopranos.' There's something about mob stories that
people love. It has to do with loyalty, high-stakes living. And
people identify oddly enough with that family.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the the top acting prizes went to Holland Taylor of
``The Practice'' on ABC; she won the supporting-actress Emmy for a
drama series. The supporting-actor award for a drama series went to
Michael Badalucco, also of ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taylor, who is in her 50s, paid tribute to Kelley, thanking
him for creating ``a woman who is a viable human being over 40,
which America doesn't seem to want to go along with.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the three-hour ceremony began, Emmys were awarded
to previous winners of several longtime hit comedy shows.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Johnston of NBC's ``Third Rock From the Sun'' was named
best supporting actress in a comedy series. It was the second time
Ms. Johnston had won for that role.
</P>
<P>
   Once again David Hyde Pierce of NBC's ``Frasier'' won the Emmy
for supporting actor in a comedy. It was his third Emmy for the
role. And Stanley Tucci won a leading-actor award for his role as
``Winchell,'' about the gossip columnist, over HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Under a pulsing sun, hundreds of television celebrities as well
as writers, directors and producers surged over the red carpet to
attend the ceremonies at the Los Angeles Shrine Auditorium, near
the campus of the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   What stamped the Emmy show this year was the ascendancy of cable
television, namely the 16 nominations given to ``The Sopranos.'' It
was the most nominations given to a single show this year, and was
followed by 13 nominations for Fox's ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos,'' had been rejected by the leading television
networks before HBO agreed to produce it. It was the first cable
series nominated for best drama.
</P>
<P>
   Besides HBO, such cable networks as Showtime, TNT and A&AMP;E also
competed for awards, a sharp contrast to the Emmy presentation a
decade ago when cable scored only 4 percent of the nominations and
were barely taken seriously by the voters of the Academy of
Television Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Several Emmy hopefuls cited the impact of cable television on
the networks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the networks were getting more daring, Smits of
``N.Y.P.D. Blue,'' said, ``Because of what's going on in cable,
they have to get edgier.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnston told reporters after she won the Emmy that she
never missed an episode of either ``The Sopranos'' or ``Sex and the
City,'' both HBO shows. ``It's a great force in television,'' she
said referring to the cable network.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of the awards ceremony winners for directing
included Thomas Schlamme for ABC's ``Sports Night'' and Paul Miller
for staging the 1998 Tony Awards on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   John Leguizamo won the Emmy for his performance in a variety
series in HBO's ``John Leguizamo's `Freak.''' Leguizamo called HBO
``the Hispanic Box Office'' for championing his shows. ``The Latin
voice is very lacking and missing in the media,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Rock, the comedian, also accepted an Emmy for the writers
on HBO's ``Chris Rock Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Kogen, a top television comedy writer, won for writing
``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   Barclay of ABC's ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' said he supported any
pressure on the networks to change.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Bancroft won for supporting actress in a mini-series for
the CBS drama ``Deep In My Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Peacock won for writing the HBO drama ``A Lesson Before
Dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter O'Toole won the supporting-actor award as Bishop Cauchon
on CBS's ``Joan of Arc.''
</P>
<P>
   The hosts for the awards were Jenna Elfman, a star of the ABC
comedy ``Dharma and Greg,'' and Pierce. Ms. Elfman was nominated in
the comedy actress field.
</P>
<P>
   The show began at 8 p.m. Eastern time. It was broadcast live on
Fox across most of the country, except in states like California,
which were on Pacific time. In those Western states, the broadcast
was delayed until 8 p.m. local time to gain the widest audience.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the Academy Awards, the Emmy winners in the 77
categories are not selected by a large number of voters. Nominees
are determined by a popular vote of the 9,500 members of the
American Academy of Television Arts and Sciences. But the winner of
each category is then selected by judging panels of Academy
volunteers who watch videotapes submitted by the nominees as
examples of their best work from the previous season. Perhaps 100
people pick the winner for best comedy, for example. A smaller
number select the winners of individual and technical categories.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The panels are sometimes older and unemployed academy members,
which can skew the vote against more unconventional choices. For
years ``Roseanne'' was ignored by the Emmys. In 1990 the risky
series ``Twin Peaks'' was the leading Emmy contender with 14
nominations, but walked off with only two technical awards. Critics
said the Emmy Awards were marked by middle-class stuffiness.
Similarly, HBO's acclaimed ``Larry Sanders Show,'' starring Garry
Shandling as a cynical talk show host, had 19 Emmy nominations
during its run, but failed to win the top prize for best comedy
series. In the show's last season in 1998, however, Shandling and
Peter Tolan won Emmys for best writers in a comedy series.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Academy Awards, the Emmys can save a winner from
oblivion. Such series as ``Hill Street Blues, `` ``Cagney and
Lacey,'' ``Cheers'' and even ``Mission: Impossible'' were
struggling to find audiences and in danger of being canceled until
they were named Emmy winners.
</P>
<P>
   The nominations for ``The Sopranos'' included ones for best
drama, best actor and best actress. It was the first cable series
nominated as best drama. Its fellow nominees, ``The Practice,''
``E.R.,'' ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' and ``Law and Order,'' have already
earned Emmys in the drama category.
</P>
<P>
   The show had won perhaps the best reviews for a television
series this year. Its level of violence, often blunt street
language and sex would have disqualified if from any traditional
network. What potentially hurt the show somewhat in the voting was
that because it was on a pay-cable channel as opposed to a network,
the series was seen by a relatively small audience.
</P>
<P>
   HBO's comedy series ``Sex and the City,'' starring Sarah Jessica
Parker, also picked up the nomination for best comedy. Its rivals
were last year's winner, ``Frasier,'' as well as ``Friends,''
``Ally McBeal'' and ``Everybody Loves Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall HBO, which waged an aggressive Emmy campaign for its
shows, received 74 nominations, second to 82 for NBC, which has
hits like ``Friends'' and ``Frasier.'' ABC was third with 58,
followed by CBS with 46 and Fox with 33.
</P>
<P>
   Two long-standing hits suffered setbacks this year in terms of
Emmy nominations, a clear result of their longevity. ``E.R.,'' the
hospital series that received 16 nominations last year, earned only
6 this year, the lowest tally for the show since its first year of
eligibility in 1995. Cast changes played a role in the show's
decline. Similarly, ``The X-Files'' dropped from 16 nominations
last year to 8 this year. By contrast, ``Law and Order,'' which
broke into the top 20 for the first time last season, earned 9
nominations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
