<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS' BUMBLING DEBUT DEFIES POLITE DESCRIPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The adjective ``inauspicious'' lacks the firepower to
describe Sunday's seasonal debut of the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   The words that do pack proper ordnance fail to meet this
newspaper's minimum standard for polite society.
</P>
<P>
   So we'll settle on this:
</P>
<P>
   Jets, '97 season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the horror. Oh, the humanity.
</P>
<P>
   That 41-3 loss was the worst opener in Seahawk history. While
the 28-20 defeat doesn't seem as gruesome on the scoreboard, the
opponent, along with the expectations for the Seahawks, make this
one every bit the same high dive into an empty pool.
</P>
<P>
   For coach Mike Holmgren, who for the past several seasons has
been living a fairy tale, this was a kiss from Broomhilda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that could go wrong, seemed to go wrong,'' said
Holmgren, normally a loquacious sort reduced to rummaging the
clich &UR; gfacute &LR; e bin. ``I was very surprised by it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only indecisive aspect about this whipping was who was
laughing louder: Joey Galloway or Dennis Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   Fergawdsakes, this was the Detroit Lions, 5-11 stiffs last year
and nine-point underdogs who were rocked by the retirement of
superstar running back Barry Sanders. Down three injured offensive
linemen _ they also lost standout wide receiver Herman Moore five
minutes into the game _ the Lions used a fifth-year stumblebum off
special teams, an ex-Nebraska bowling ball named Cory Schlesinger,
as a primary offensive weapon. He killed the Seahawk defense.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, the Seahawks rushed for 31 yards. Until Ricky
Watters staggered about for a 9-yard gain in the fourth quarter,
forward progress was measured in lengths of lint.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the worst first half of football,'' tight end
Christian Fauria said. ``We couldn't do anything right. We saved
face a little bit in the second half, but ... just to give them
points like we like them, man, it's just so hard to stay mentally
in it when that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Down 25-7 at the half, the Seahawks weren't the only ones not
into it. Several thousand fans in the non-sellout sellout (the
goofs at Motorola covered the ticket-sale shortfall, so the game
could be locally splattered, er, telecast) abandoned their seats
for the second half. Perhaps they trundled across the street to the
Guilty Pleasure, where they have become used to a bad result, but
at least it's in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   No greater symbol of the day's ghastly nature existed than the
Kingdome's humble north-end service entrance: Not only did an
ambulance pass through it with the team's best player, linebacker
Chad Brown, a Seahawk punt snap went in the same general direction.
</P>
<P>
   Brown turned out to be OK, but was done for the day. The punt
snap is still going.
</P>
<P>
   Much was foretold on the Seahawks' first play from scrimmage, a
flea flicker in which Watters took the handoff and flipped the ball
back to quarterback Jon Kitna, who presumably would see the Detroit
secondary in various stages of flimflammery.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren had the play scripted in the first series of 15, then
the night before decided to go with it at the top as a sort of
show-biz splash that would underscore the annoyingly ubiquitous
marketing phrase, ``It's Now Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Kitna was smashed for a 7-yard sack. The only ones
fooled were wearing bird helmets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real excited about the play,'' Watters said. ``I thought
it would be a touchdown right away. I flipped the ball back, looked
downfield and saw Charles Jordan wide open. Then I looked back ...
aaaah!''
</P>
<P>
   The play was representative of the Seahawks' most obvious flaw:
Too much too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when you run a reverse or any other special, goofy
play, it's either real good or real bad,'' Holmgren said. ``There
is no middle ground. We had a chance, we just didn't block it
right. We have some young guys playing, and they didn't do that
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have a lot of young guys playing, especially on
offense and particularly with the holdout of Galloway and Sunday's
injuries. There is so much to learn from so many new coaches that
the force-feeding inevitably makes for a lot of sloppy burping.
</P>
<P>
   Five minicamps, a full training camp and four exhibitions might
seem like a lot of time to introduce a new way. But it isn't, as
Sunday proved. Building winners usually takes a while, especially
when losing is just as stitched in as the Kingdome rug.
</P>
<P>
   Confusion still reigns, particularly among the receivers, nearly
all of whom are new this year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about how Jordan's first-quarter injury absence affected
an already thin receiving corps, tight end Fauria, who also has
been out of action until Sunday with an injury, looked at the
reporter blankly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have Jordan,'' he said. Suddenly, he shook his head
hard and sheepishly. ``Oh, I thought you meant Michael. You mean
Charles.''
</P>
<P>
   Told you the Seahawks were thinking big.
</P>
<P>
   And, so far, playing small.
</P>
<P>
   It's not time.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
