<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAGNE LOSES BATTLE BUT NOT WAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Most rookies wouldn't get the chance to pitch the
sixth inning. Not after the Los Angeles Dodgers rallied from two
runs down to take a one-run lead in the bottom of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   But righty Greg Gagne's tenacity and toughness isn't
characteristic of a rookie, so Dodgers manager Davey Johnson let
the 23-year-old stay in.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term it backfired. The Mets scored three runs in
the sixth and then rolled to a 10-3 victory Sunday to take three of
four from the Dodgers in their lone visit to Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   What long-term effects Johnson's confidence in the
French-Canadian produced will have to wait, but both said the
experience was good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a good day to learn,'' Gagne said. ``I didn't have
very good stuff. I had to battle. I'm sorry I let (Johnson) down.''
</P>
<P>
   It was much different than Gagne's major-league debut last
Tuesday against Florida, when he allowed two hits and struck out
eight in six scoreless innings. That effort prompted Johnson to
stick with Gagne for the sixth inning against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne nearly rewarded Johnson, but he made a few mistakes. With
the bases empty and two outs, he walked Mike Piazza on a curveball
instead of challenging him. Robin Ventura then singled and Shawon
Dunston doubled in two runs. Benny Agbayani added an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was still a good outing,'' Johnson said. ``I liked what I
saw. After (Edgardo) Alfonso's (first-inning homer), he (bore) down
and didn't let it affect him. The way he handled it after two runs,
he was clean to the sixth, and I think he was good in the sixth. .
. . He didn't let the previous hitter affect him. He went right
after him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gagne (0-1) allowed five runs on six hits in six innings. He
walked three and struck out four.
</P>
<P>
   __ Judd shut down: First the Mets wracked right-hander Mike Judd
for four runs on three hits and three walks in a third of an inning
of relief, and then the Dodgers lowered the boom, perhaps ending
Judd's season because of tendinitis in his pitching shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take any chances with him,'' Johnson said.
``We might shut him down the rest of the way. We'll have to see how
it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Judd has felt the soreness in his shoulder since the club
returned from Florida last week, but he said he wanted to pitch
through it. However, after getting smacked around by the Mets, that
was put to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Johnson said Judd's dud of a performance doesn't hamper
what the organization thinks of him. Judd impressed the Dodgers
with four solid starts before Gagne took over his spot in the
rotation so the club could get a look at another young arm.
</P>
<P>
   __ FYI: Dodgers right-hander Antonio Osuna pitched 11/3
scoreless innings in a rehab stint for Class-A San Bernardino and
is expected to be activated Tuesday. . . . Right-hander Robinson
Checo returned from a 41-game hiatus on the disabled list because
of a groin injury and uncorked a wild pitch on his first attempt.
He settled down and retired both batters he faced. . . . Dodgers
lefty Jeff Williams became the ninth Australian to pitch in the
major leagues when he made his debut in the ninth inning. He
allowed one run on one hit. . . . When Alfonso hit a two-run homer
in the first inning, it gave him 100 RBI and marked the first time
in club history three players drove in 100 runs in a season. Robin
Ventura (112) and Mike Piazza (112) also reached the century mark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
