<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRUDZIELANEK COULD MOVE TO SECOND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If the Los Angeles Dodgers accomplish their
mission of trading Eric Young during the offseason, they might
replace him by moving shortstop Mark Grudzielanek to second base.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, the Dodgers have had backroom talks about
Grudzielanek changing positions and are considering it if they can
acquire the appropriate replacement at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming free-agent market is weak in comparison to others
years, particularly at the shortstop position. But it doesn't rule
out the Dodgers' making a deal that would include a shortstop,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Moving Grudzielanek to second would also give the Dodgers more
flexibility in the offseason. Instead of having to fill a need at
second base (if Young is traded), they could look for either a
second baseman or shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our shortstop,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone
said. ``That's all I'm going to say about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, who went 4 for 5 in the Dodgers' 10-3 loss to the
Mets on Sunday, said he wouldn't be receptive to such a move. But
he also said he could be talked into it under the right
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the situation,'' Grudzielanek, 29, said. ``The
first instinct would be no. Who would be coming in? It would be no
one here. Right now, there's no way I would change. I'm thinking I
have a lot of years left at shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the possible change is that Grudzielanek
spent most of the offseason working on his defense with Bucky Dent,
and in a season gone awry, Grudzielanek is one of the few bright
spots. After averaging 31 errors in the last three seasons,
Grudzielanek has committed 11 this season.
</P>
<P>
   He also leads the Dodgers regulars with a .326 average. Since
leaving the disabled list July 6 after a broken hand, Grudzielanek
is hitting .355 (89 for 251). He is also trying to become the first
Dodgers shortstop to hit .300 in a season (minimum 100 at-bats)
since Maury Wills did it in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many shortstops are hitting well over .300 and cut their
errors in half,'' Malone said. ``If we can get better, we'll look
to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek leads National League shortstops in batting
average, but his bat at second base would add zing to the Dodgers'
lineup if they could acquire a strong offensive shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek has limited experience as a second baseman. When he
was promoted to Montreal in 1995, he started 10 games at second. He
also started 25 games at third base. If the Dodgers ask
Grudzielanek to move over on the infield, they would want him to
work at it during the offseason, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he plans to give Alex Cora a
strong look at shortstop the remaining 19 games, but there are
questions in the organization as to whether Cora can hit at the
big-league level. Cora's status is unrelated to Grudzielanek's
situation, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Cora is a player the Dodgers don't know well; he missed many of
the spring- training games with a broken hand. Cora, 23, hit .310
with Triple-A Albuquerque this season, but there is skepticism
since he was consistently overmatched in hitting .121 in 29 games
for the Dodgers last season. Sources said the Dodgers won't have
Grudzielanek change positions for a player of Cora's caliber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this year, I (thought about it) once or twice,''
Grudzielanek said of a position change. ``It was to the point where
I needed to improve what I was doing out there or make a change. No
question. But I went and worked with Bucky Dent and now I feel
comfortable with how I've played shortstop this season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
