<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT CLEMENS FOR SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-YANKEES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is not about one man, as Yankees outfielder Paul
O'Neill claimed Friday night, when he said, ``We didn't get beat by
the Red Sox, we got beat by Pedro Martinez.''
</P>
<P>
   This is, as it has been for nearly six months, about something
else: The collective energies and will of an unflappable team that
has been undersold all summer but now, after winning, 4-1, Sunday
at Yankee Stadium to complete a stunning three-game sweep of the
Yankees in the Bronx and registering their first-ever win over
Roger Clemens, must be taken seriously as a threat in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``What (O'Neill) said is really how people look at this team,''
said outfielder Darren Lewis, whose bloop single off Clemens broke
a 1-1 tie in a three-run, eighth-inning rally touched off by rookie
Trot Nixon's single. ``We're not a bunch of superstars, just a
bunch of guys who play the game hard, play it right, and don't take
even one day lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has a bunch of guys where not one person is looking
for any credit. Nobody wants the credit. Everybody just wants to
show up and contribute what they can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have not yet assured themselves of a playoff spot,
even after their first sweep in Yankee Stadium in 13 years, all
three wins coming in front of full houses. The biggest of the three
(56,028) bore witness Sunday afternoon to a team that not only
refused to bow to Clemens's intimidation tactics, but responded
with some steel of its own, whether it was Bret Saberhagen throwing
in retaliation at Yankees third baseman Scott Brosius,
mild-mannered designated hitter Reggie Jefferson leveling Yankee
catcher Joe Girardi with a cross-body block to score the tying run
in the fourth, or flyweight Donnie Sadler flinging himself into
Girardi in a futile bid to score in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland A's won for the third straight time against the
expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays Sunday, leaving them three games
behind the Sox in the wild-card race. But this is no longer just
about making the playoffs as a bonus qualifier. The Sox have a shot
at winning the American League East, which in some ways is just
window dressing but nonetheless still makes a statement.
</P>
<P>
   With 19 games left, the Sox trail the Yankees by 3 1/2 games.
Time is short, but they've made up the same ground on the Bombers
when even more urgency was required: In 1978, the Sox were 3 1/2
back with 14 games to go and won their last eight to force the
Bucky Dent playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   And in the last 13 days, the Sox have shaved five games off a
Yankee lead that stood at 8 1/2 on the morning of Aug. 31. They are
as close to first place Monday as anytime since July 16, when they
were three games back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's going to quit or get scared or anything like that,''
said Yankees manager Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go over and ask Jimy, I'll still take this situation,'' Torre
said, referring to Sox counterpart Jimy Williams. ``A four-game
bulge in the loss column, I'm sure he'd take that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams insists he doesn't concern himself with such matters.
``I don't think we've changed from the first day of spring
training,'' he said when asked how the sweep might have altered the
Sox' approach to the final three weeks. ``It's just about the same.
We played good against a very good team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know who we were playing. These guys are the world
champions.''
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the top of the third, Clemens yelled at rookie
Wilton Veras for taking a big swing, then hit him in the back with
a 95-mile-an-hour fastball with the next pitch. Later that inning,
Clemens also barked at Jose Offerman after Offerman took offense to
a third-strike call by plate umpire John Hirschbeck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was griping about the pitch and I liked the pitch, so
that's where the disagreement came in,'' said Clemens, who further
displayed his disgust with Offerman by firing his glove into the
Yankee dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman barked back and had to be restrained by Williams from
heading in Clemens's direction. He refused after the game to
discuss what he said to Clemens, but there was no mistaking the
message from Saberhagen, who hit Scott Brosius in the derriere to
start the bottom of the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to let Roger know he can't control the game,'' said
Saberhagen, who gave up a leadoff home run to Chuck Knoblauch but
gave the Yankees just two more hits while striking out five in five
gritty innings that served as his first test in almost a month
since coming off the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's yelling at Veras after he took that big swing, and
then hits him with the next pitch, that's not a coincidence. Then
he yelled at Offerman. You've got to come back and establish that
you're going to throw inside, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big game, and he might have got caught up in the
emotion. We'd won the first two games, this was really the first
big game he's been in, and it's against the Red Sox, so his
emotions might have been on edge as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen was poker-faced when he hit Brosius, then even more
coolly picked him off second base, after shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra sneaked in behind the runner. The pickoff play was
typical of the Sox' crisp execution Sunday after making four errors
the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, who had doubled to center for the Sox' first hit off
Clemens in the fourth, reacted to Troy O'Leary's single to right by
throwing himself into Girardi just as O'Neill's throw from the
plate arrived.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, rookie first baseman Brian Daubach pulled
Offerman's relay out of the dirt to complete a double play as
lefthanded reliever Rheal Cormier came in after John Wasdin gave up
back-to-back singles and induced O'Neill to hit into the twin
killing before striking out Bernie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman, with Nixon on the move after his leadoff single in the
seventh, reached beyond the strike zone to slap a low-and-away
Clemens serving into left for a hit-and-run single. Then Lewis put
his bat on the ball, dropping a hit in front of Williams as Nixon
scored. After Jefferson drew a walk to load the bases, Offerman
came home on Garciaparra's shallow fly to center, as Williams's
throw was on line but took a big bounce over Girardi's head. The
Sox final run came home on another blooper, this one by O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Clemens already had left, saddled with his first loss
in seven starts against the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him the ball today,'' Torre said of Clemens. ``That's
what I wanted and I got it. This was a big-game performance for
Roger. We just didn't hold up our end of the bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, meanwhile, continue to raise the bar on what has
been a remarkable trip: They are 7-2 on this 13-day, four-city
tour, with three games left in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good feeling,'' Lewis said of the sweep. ``These guys
(the Yankees) can explode at any time. For us to come in here in
the middle of a long road trip and do what we did says a lot about
this team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
