<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BLAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2ND DEADLY APARTMENT BLAST HITS MOSCOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A predawn explosion leveled a large apartment building
in southern Moscow on Monday morning, killing at least 19 people.
It was the second blast to hit an apartment building in the city in
less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Security Service called the blast a terrorist act,
adding that it was clear that ``professionals'' were at work.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion occurred about 5 a.m. Moscow time (9 p.m. Sunday,
Eastern time) along a busy highway leading to downtown Moscow from
the south. The Interfax news service reported that the building had
been destroyed and that the explosion had thrown chunks of debris
as far as 350 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities rushed dozens of ambulances and fire trucks to the
scene, and the state-owned NTV television said that 11 dead had
been pulled from the debris by daylight.
</P>
<P>
   Only this weekend, the police rounded up 15 suspects in an
investigation into an explosion in an apartment building last
Wednesday in which 94 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   They cited new evidence that terrorists, using the identity
papers of a dead man to conceal their own identities, moved
explosives into a ground-floor office of the nine-story building
before the explosion occurred.
</P>
<P>
   No one has claimed responsibility for either blast. But the
mayor of Moscow, Yuri M. Luzhkov, said over the weekend that he was
certain that the first explosion was the work of terrorists who
were retaliating for Russia's efforts to suppress an invasion of
Dagestan by Islamic rebels from neighboring Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure Chechnya is to blame,'' Luzhkov said on an NTV
program. ``It was a promised expansion of hostilities and terrorist
acts by Chechen warlords.''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion on Monday morning appeared to be the third major
act of terrorism in Russia in recent weeks. Two weeks ago, shortly
after Russian jets bombed the villages of an Islamic sect in
Dagestan, terrorists blew up an apartment housing Russian military
familes in the region, killing at least 64 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
