<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SURPRISE JETS, PARCELLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Bruce Armstrong said he couldn't sleep
all week, so he reluctantly watched the preseason football shows
that either made no mention of the Patriots or trashed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the Vikings or Tampa Bay in the Super Bowl, the
Jets winning the AFC East. You wonder whether you should even show
up for the season,'' said Armstrong. ``We didn't get any credit for
anything last season. Well, a funny thing happened on the way to
the coronation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots beat the Jets Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And the season-opening 30-28 nail-biter, which was decided on
Adam Vinatieri's 23-yard field goal with three seconds remaining,
came in the most hostile of conditions _ before 78,227 people,
nearly all of whom appeared to be dressed in green and shouting
``Jets, Jets, Jets!'' the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   To make it all the better for their fans, the Patriots, who face
the Indianapolis Colts next Sunday, beat Bill Parcells after losing
the last three meetings with their former coach. They took
advantage of Jets mistakes, didn't allow their own miscues to shoot
them in the foot, and were able to capitalize on a rash of Jets
injuries, none greater than the season-ending ruptured Achilles'
tendon suffered by quarterback Vinny Testaverde with 7:12 remaining
in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And not one bit of the win came easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a remarkable effort by the Jets,'' said Patriots
coach Pete Carroll. ``They hung and hung and hung, and they made it
a really tough game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots did not score any points for artistry, winning
because Drew Bledsoe completed 21 of 30 passes for 340 yards and
one touchdown and threw one interception; because Willie McGinest
had two sacks, scored a touchdown on a fumble recovery, and
pressured the quarterback all game; and because receivers Terry
Glenn (7 catches, 113 yards) and Tony Simmons (a 58-yard touchdown
reception early in the second quarter following a Lawyer Milloy
interception) made big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was brilliant until throwing an interception at the
worst possible moment _ when trying to hold a 27-22 fourth-quarter
lead. Linebacker Bryan Cox stepped in front of Troy Brown, the
intended receiver, and raced 27 yards unscathed for the go-ahead
score with 9:34 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was late with the throw,'' said Bledsoe. ``I needed to hit
it early to Terry, and really, I shouldn't have thrown it at all
and taken the sack. Fortunately our defense stiffened at the end
and we got another shot at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe didn't get it back right away. On the next series, the
11th of the game for the Patriots, Bledsoe was sacked by backup
nose tackle Jason Wiltz, who had spelled the injured Jason
Ferguson, for a 9-yard loss on third down.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Jets possession, Rick Mirer, who was 4 of 11 for 28
yards and two interceptions in relief of middle man Tom Tupa, threw
an ill-advised pass intended for Keyshawn Johnson (8 catches, 194
yards) into triple coverage. The ball tipped off Johnson's hands
and into the arms of Chris Slade, and the Patriots took over at the
Jets 49, giving Bledsoe his last chance.
</P>
<P>
   First he hit Glenn on a 12-yard sideline throw, then veteran
running back Terry Allen ran up the middle for 7 and 2 yards. On
third and 6, following a motion penalty, Bledsoe connected with
Troy Brown for 18 yards to the Jets 15. Allen, who was the
Patriots' leading rusher with 54 yards on 15 carries, converted on
third and 2 for a first down at the 3.
</P>
<P>
   After Allen lost a yard with a run to the left, the Jets called
their final timeout with 22 seconds left. Bledsoe then took a knee
at the 6, and Vinatieri booted the winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   But with three seconds remaining, there was still the kickoff,
which had proved adventurous in the Patriots' final exhibition
game, when Carolina converted a squib kick on a similar play into a
last-second, 61-yard winning field goal. Vinatieri tried a squib
again and hit this one out of bounds, giving the Jets the ball at
their 40. Mirer tried a Hail Mary pass to Johnson, but Ty Law
batted it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played very well today,'' said Parcells of the Patriots.
``They took advantage of our mistakes. I pretty much anticipated it
would be a tough game like this. I expect those to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots trailed, 16-10, at the half after Tupa's first pass
after replacing Testaverde was a 25-yard touchdown pass to Johnson
to make it 14-10. Testaverde ruptured the tendon as he took a step
toward a loose ball after Steve Israel stripped Curtis Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Big defensive plays by Slade and McGinest prevented further
scoring by Tupa, who on the next series hit a 50-yarder to Johnson,
putting the ball at the Patriots 33. But Tupa was forced to punt
after McGinest sacked him for a 7-yard loss, as the Patriots
continued to pressure their former teammate, who had seen no snaps
at quarterback in the exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells went with Tupa because had put only one backup
quarterback, Tupa, on the active game roster, with Mirer designated
as the emergency quarterback. By NFL rules, if Mirer were inserted
before the fourth quarter, Tupa would have been ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   Right before the end of the half, with the Patriots in punt
formation at their 7, Mike Bartrum snapped the ball out of the end
zone to give the Jets a safety and a 16-10 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was completely my fault,'' said Bartrum. ``I messed up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' game plan after intermission was simple: Disrupt
Tupa and create turnovers. On the Jets' first possession, Israel
blitzed on first and 10 from the right corner, sacked Tupa, and
forced a fumble. After Brandon Mitchell, trying to scoop up the
loose ball, batted it toward the end zone, McGinest pounced on it
for the score. Vinatieri's extra-point gave New England a 17-16
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots put another score up with 11:35 left in the third
quarter after Brown returned a punt 26 yards to the Jets 31. After
Bledsoe went to Glenn for 7 yards and Kevin Faulk ran for 2,
setting up third and 1 at the 22, Allen busted through an
impressive hole on the left side (Armstrong and Heath Irwin
throwing key blocks) for the score and a 24-16 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri kicked the lead up to 27-16 when he booted a 21-yarder
with 6:06 left in the third quarter, the score set up by a
Bledsoe-to-Glenn 45-yard pass play.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it appeared the Patriots were headed toward a blowout,
``a funny thing happened on the way to the coronation.'' New
England couldn't run the ball well enough to comfortably ice the
win.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets took over at their 35 after a 27-yard kickoff return by
Aaron Glenn. On a slant pattern, Law and Chris Carter converged to
intercept Tupa's throw, but Johnson got the ball instead and raced
65 yards to the Patriots 5. Three plays later, Tupa and backup
tight end Fred Baxter combined for a 7-yard score. A 2-point
conversion attempt failed, leaving the score 27-22.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking a dependable ground attack, Bledsoe tossed to Ben Coates
for 17 yards and Shawn Jefferson for 19 to the Jets 46 before
Bledsoe was sacked by linebacker Roman Phifer and fumbled. The Jets
recovered at the Patriots 49.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer moved the ball well, getting a big interference call on
Law at the New England 35. On a third-down play from the 14, one
official again called interference on Law, but following a
conference it was ruled the pass was not catchable and the penalty
was waved off.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets lined up for a field goal, but Tupa took the ball and
ran toward the first-down marker. But Larry Whigham stopped him,
and the Patriots took over on downs at the 10.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the end of the afternoon's big plays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9683 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-13 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE BACK TO LEAD WAY IN BIG-PLAY WAY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Now it can be told. The man with the
great Stone Face was very scared. Every time he looked at his ugly
right index finger, he started thinking about his future. Would he
ever throw for 340 yards and make big play after big play for his
team again?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' admitted Drew Bledsoe, ``there were nights like that.
When I had to sit out those games last year, I definitely started
thinking about my football mortality.''
</P>
<P>
   That cloudy future is, well, somewhere off in the future. Back
in the here and now, Drew Bledsoe is still Drew Bledsoe. He can
still throw for 340. He can still air it out. He can still shove
the ball into infinitesimal openings and hit receivers a half-step
before they go out of bounds. He can still be the most important
man on the football field, which is exactly what he was as the
Patriots eked out a weird and wonderful 30-28 victory over the
suddenly mortal and mortified New York Jets at Giants Stadium
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Messing up his finger might have become some sort of
epiphany for the quarterback, who has never been one to wear his
heart on his sleeve or, frankly, anywhere on the outside at all.
And even Sunday he was dead-panning the win in Tuna Bowl V as only
he could, to wit: ``I don't know if you guys believe me when I say
it's simply a division win on the road. We won it. It's a good win
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   That's standard-issue Bledsoe rhetorical pabulum, but behind
closed doors he was in something of a fire-and-brimstone mode. The
New England Patriots occasionally get to see a different Drew
Bledsoe than the media and fans ever do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game,'' reports Terry Glenn, ``he was going around
saying, `We're gonna win this game!' And any time he does that, he
sends a message to this team. It lifts all our spirits. When Drew
Bledsoe does something like that, it gives us a boost.''
</P>
<P>
   As welcome as the Bledsoe rhetoric was, what mattered
exponentially more was his actual play. And it was evident from
what you call your basic get-go that Number 11 had gotten off the
bus in firm possession of his A-game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was terrific,'' said an ebullient Pete Carroll.
``Right from the opening drive, he played a beautiful game. It's
too bad he had the one pick, but overall, it's what I've been
telling you: That's who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   He is 27 now, and this is Bledsoe's seventh NFL season. He is
entering what should be the most productive phase of his career.
For the next five or 10 or however many years, he has got the
requisite combination of raw talent and experience to make him a
superior NFL quarterback. The simple truth is that not very many
can do what Drew Bledsoe did here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how he did statistically,'' said veteran tackle
Bruce Armstrong. ``But he made big plays, and that's what he's got
to do all year. It's not as if he has to put the whole team on his
shoulders, but he has to make big plays. I think he'll be as good
as anybody in the league this year.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not quantum physics. The man is 6 feet 5 inches, 235
pounds, and he can zing the football. He can throw the killer
crossfield sideline pass and he can stretch the defense with a bomb
such as the 58-yarder to Tony Simmons that provided the Patriots
with their first touchdown of the '99 season. He'll make a mistake
now and again, such as the unfortunate interception on a pass
intended for Glenn in the fourth quarter, but who doesn't? And when
he does, he's man enough to take the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw it late,'' he confessed. ``I should have thrown it
early or not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It could have cost his team the game. It didn't because Rick
Mirer, the third New York quarterback of the day, made a very bad
judgment that resulted in a vital Chris Slade interception with
3:30 remaining and the Jets leading, 28-27. Bledsoe took the team
from the Jets 49 to the Jets 1, and with three seconds left Adam
Vinatieri kicked the winning 23-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   His 21 completions went to nine different men. Not bad, huh?
``I've said all along that with all the weapons we have if I can
just play well _ I don't have to be great _ we can win games,''
Bledsoe declared. ``We've got four excellent (wide) receivers.
We've got Ben (Coates). We've got running backs who can catch. I
don't have any problems throwing to any of those guys in any
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Now with all due respect to the Coateses, Simmonses, and Shawn
Jeffersons of the world, not all receivers are created equal.
Nothing happened on the Giants Stadium turf Sunday to alter the
universally held opinion that if Drew Bledsoe is Mr. 1 on this
team, then Terry Glenn is Mr. 1A. Having Terry Glenn (seven catches
for 113 yards) back in the lineup means there are residual benefits
for everyone in a Patriots uniform. Bledsoe-to-Glenn is on the very
short list of most dangerous NFL passing duos. The trick, of
course, is to keep Mr. 1A in the lineup, but Mr. 1 has no control
over that.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know is that when Drew Bledsoe has some offensive
weapons he is one dangerous dude. We also know that he really is
passionate about the game, even if we must depend on an occasional
leaked locker room anecdote, as well as his own sparse testimony,
as proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot last year when I was hurt,'' he confided. ``I
learned what the game meant to me. I was a lot more emotional about
this than I thought I would be.''
</P>
<P>
   So now Drew knows what the game means to him. Sunday's little
show reminded the rest of us what he means to the team. Pretty much
everything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
