<SLUG> BC-TEN-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI CAPTURES US OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's Agassi again.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi, Comeback Kid II, did it once more in the US Open
Sunday by rallying to a 6-4, 6-7 (5-7), 6-7 (2-7), 6-3, 6-2
championship victory over a game and gutsy Todd Martin.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so at 29, Agassi is not exactly a kid. But what a comeback
artist.
</P>
<P>
   When Agassi won his first US Open in 1994, he was dressed all in
black, had long hair flowing out of the back of his black cap, and
was completing a comeback from a wrist injury and the depths of the
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi won this US Open with a shaved head and chest, capless,
and completing a tremendous comeback year as he recovered from
disinterest and the depth of the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you play for,'' Agassi said. ``It does mean a lot
to win when it really matters most.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, who bashed his customary forehands and served
tremendously, collected $750,000 for his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Agassi got to the fourth round here but it was the
only major he played and a couple of months later he sunk to No.
141 in the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he rose dramatically in the rankings but did not do
well in the major tournaments. But he had a base for this year and
he focused on getting even more fit. And he focused on the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Missions accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi went out in the fourth round at the Australian, but has
been pretty much unstoppable since. He won the French Open, lost to
Pete Sampras in the finals at Wimbledon, and then came here.
</P>
<P>
   The French victory gave him a win in each of the Grand Slam
events and now he is starting on a second set of titles. This is
his second US Open, his fifth major overall.
</P>
<P>
   And he did it playing well, against an opponent playing well, in
front of a crowd of 23,053 that included five-time winner _ and now
retired _ Steffi Graf, who called the match ``incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   None of which takes away from what Martin, known more for guts
than glory as he quietly turned himself into one of the world's
best players, accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, also 29, did not seem bothered a bit by the hoopla or
the stage, Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was hanging by a thread for much of the match,''
Agassi said. ``He knows how to boil it down to tennis out there and
he was really executing in a way that was giving me all sorts of
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin missed more than half of 1997 with elbow problems, sunk
in the rankings as well, and will be No. 4 _ behind Agassi, Yevgeny
Kafelnikov, and Sampras _ when the rankings are released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been Agassi's year.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, eventually, it was his day.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, the best returner in the game, was perfect on his serve.
Martin had eight break points and could not convert a single one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember any five-setter that I ever played that I
didn't lose my serve,'' Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth set, Martin managed only three points on Agassi's
four service games. It wasn't until the fourth set that Agassi
could do much with Martin's serve.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the fifth, Agassi broke Martin to jump in front early.
And broke again for the match. Agassi was simply marvelous in
putting Martin in a love-40 hole in the deciding game. Backhand
down the line. Backhand off the net and over. Great forehand off a
tough serve. Martin got it to 15-40, but would get no closer and
when his backhand went into the net, it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Championship clinched, Agassi raised high his arms. Saluted
coach Brad Gilbert and trainer Gil Reyes and the others in his
corner. And waved and bowed to each side of the Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's winners (45) far outnumbered his unforced errors (23).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not easy with a guy that hits the ball as well as him
on a fast court,'' Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin had 77 winners and 60 errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything else, it was the relentless pressure he put
on me,'' Martin said. ``Not just with his serve, not just with his
feet, not just with his returns, but every game he seemed to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first five-setter in an Open final since Mats
Wilander outlasted Ivan Lendl in 1988 and only the second since
1980.
</P>
<P>
   The play was efficient, if not overly inspiring through nearly
two sets. Agassi broke Martin in the first game of the match and
survived a couple of break points in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the second, the pace picked up. At 4-4, Martin
escaped two break points. Next game, Martin had his two break
points of the set, but could convert neither and they headed to the
tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi went up, 3-1, but Martin rallied to win it with a volley.
</P>
<P>
   Third set, same as the second. And back to a 'breaker. Agassi
double faulted to open it and never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi began to take command early in the third set, breaking
for 2-1. He wriggled free of a couple of break points in the eighth
game, then broke Martin again in the ninth. And Agassi broke again
early in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, he had his championship. He has his eye on more.
``I definitely feel I have more titles in me,'' Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   It might be tough to find anyone who disagrees with him today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
