<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILL GETS TWO-YEAR CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One week into the holdout life, defenseman Hal Gill
came to contract terms with the Bruins Sunday and is expected on
the ice Monday afternoon when workouts resume in Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Gill signed a two-year deal believed to be worth an average of
$750,000 per season _ a significant increase over the $410,000 he
made in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good about it,'' said Gill, speaking by phone
from his Lynnfield home Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. ``I'm ready to get going,
get started, and start doing what I do out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two key Bruins, one in California and one in Sweden,
remain without contracts for the fast-approaching 1999-2000 season.
It doesn't sound as if Gill's deal portends anything in the near
future for either Byron Dafoe or P.J. Axelsson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great for Hal,'' said Boston netminder Dafoe, reached
at his home Sunday &UR;  &LR; night in Manhattan Beach, Calif., where he
continues his holdout vigil. ``That's one piece of the puzzle
solved.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe is looking for a three-year deal worth approximately $12
million, about a million dollars per year more than the Bruins have
offered. Axelsson, still home in Sweden, recently began talking
about a two-year deal to return to Boston, but his agent, Neil
Abbott, said Sunday &UR;  &LR; night that he was not optimistic about
completing a deal in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't think it's going to get done,'' said Abbott, who
says Axelsson has multiple offers to play this season in Sweden and
possibly another offer to play in Switzerland. ``Clearly, they
think Hal is a more valuable member of the team than my guy. They
think (Axelsson) is a replaceable part. There's a clear difference
as to where we think P.J. ranks in the hierarchy of the team, from
a salary standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Gill initially sought a three-year contract, but
negotiations progressed slowly through the summer. Late last week,
the Bruins and Gill's agent, Mark Witkin, began negotiating a
two-year deal which would include the 2000-2001 season, which would
be the first year that the former Providence Friar would be
eligible for arbitration. When the length of term got narrowed, the
deal got done.
</P>
<P>
   The second year of Gill's deal is likely worth slightly more
than $800,000. Two years from now, he'll be 26, and his qualifying
offer would have to be at least $900,000. Given his impressive
development his first two years in the league, he'll likely land a
multimillion dollar deal with his next pact. Nice work for the
207th pick in the '93 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about figures,'' said Witkin, asked to
confirm the $1.4 million salary. ``I think there's too much
emphasis on it. Overall, I'd say (Gill) is pretty happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe's agent, Ron Salcer, and Abbott are expected to continue
talks Monday with Boston bosses Harry Sinden and Mike O'Connell.
O'Connell said Saturday that the club offered added incentives to
Dafoe, but the goalie said Sunday the sweetening of the pot wasn't
enough to entice him to sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incentive they offered was based on winning the Stanley
Cup _ an all-or-nothing kind of thing,'' said Dafoe. ``The
incentives they've offered are fine _ it's just the base we're
worried about.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe, who opted not to go to arbitration earlier this summer,
said he is willing to talk about a new deal of one, two, three, or
four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's one year, that's fine with me,'' said Dafoe.
``I've worked with short contracts all my career, had to go out
there each year and prove myself. If that's what it takes this
time, no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden, the club's president and general manager, quibbled last
week with Salcer's attempt to use New Jersey goalie Martin Brodeur,
who will make $3.75 million this season, as the netminder most
comparable to Dafoe. Sinden argued that Dafoe has not won a Stanley
Cup, a feat accomplished by Brodeur in the spring of '95.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dafoe, the Bruins on Friday forwarded Salcer their
list of comparables, names that included the likes of Tommy Salo,
Jocelyn Thibault, Damian Rhodes, and Ron Tugnutt, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they're all great goaltenders; I'm not knocking any of
them,'' said Dafoe. ``But their numbers don't compare to mine the
last two years. Ron (Salcer) took the statistics for the top 12
goalies in the league and looked at their numbers in about eight
categories _ things like save percentage, goals-against average,
wins, all the key numbers _ and when you blend them all together
for the last two years, I came out second overall _ that's second
to you-know-who (Dominik Hasek). I'm looking for money that ranks
down around 10th in the league, and I think that's reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will work out the next three days in Wilmington
before heading to Portland, Maine, to face the Canadiens in their
second preseason game. They then head to Florida for a pair of
games vs. the Panthers . . . Ray Bourque should get his first
preseason action vs. the Habs, but it's unlikely he'll play against
Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
