<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEEP DREAMS COME TRUE IN N.Y. 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We are New Englanders. New York is all things rude,
evil, powerful, and loud. It takes our best, laughs, and never
looks back. It dismisses us. That's what's so infuriating. We hate
New York, but Gotham doesn't give us much thought at all.
</P>
<P>
   And this is why Sunday was one of the greatest days in the
history of New England. On a splendid Sunday in New York, the
oft-mocked Boston Red Sox beat Roger Clemens, 4-1, in front of
56,028 to complete a three-game sweep at Yankee Stadium. Less than
10 miles away, in Northern New Jersey, the maligned Patriots upset
Bully Bill Parcells and the New York Jets, 30-28, in their NFL
season opener.
</P>
<P>
   It simply doesn't get any better. If you are a New Englander
working in a brokerage house or law firm, or studying in a college
dorm, you are sick of obnoxious New Yorkers rubbing it in your
face. They took Babe Ruth, the 1949 pennant, the Tuna, Leonard
Bernstein, Curtis Martin, Clemens, Jordan Marsh, the 1978 pennant,
the Boston Globe, and two thirds of Nantucket. They forever ruined
clam chowder, polluting it with tomatoes, then had the gall to call
it Manhattan clam chowder.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday we fought back, if only for a day.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox' sweep was their first in New York since 1986, when
young Clemens went 24-4 and took the Sox to the seventh game of the
World Series. The Yankees have won 24 world championships to
Boston's zero since Sox owner Harry Frazee sold Ruth to New York
some 80 years ago. The Sox have earned a reputation as the team
that always chokes.
</P>
<P>
   Look who's gagging now. The defending world champion Yankees,
winners of a record 125 games last year, led the Red Sox in the
American League East standings by 8 1/2 games on Aug. 30, but the
Sox have cut that margin to 3 1/2 with 19 games
</P>
<P>
   to play. Boston this year went 8-4 against the so-called
``greatest team ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Beating Clemens made it that much sweeter. He always told us he
hated New York. Couldn't stand the place. Then he got himself
traded to the Yankees and started talking as if he had Mickey
Mantle's poster on his wall when he was a child in Dayton, Ohio.
Boston fans didn't like Clemens as a Blue Jay, but seeing him in
pinstripes was intolerable. Sunday marked the first time the Sox
beat Clemens in seven tries against the onetime Boston ace.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket, who was loudly booed when introduced at Fenway
during All-Star Game festivities in July, again claimed there was
nothing special about pitching against Boston, but we know he's
lying. He pitched 12 years for the Red Sox, which would make it
impossible for him not to know what this weekend meant. He is no
stranger to the Curse of the Bambino and used to wipe his sweat on
the Babe's center-field monument at the Stadium in an effort to
turn the bad karma back in favor of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Are the 1999 Yankees panicking?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that nobody's sitting back or waiting or any
kind of panic at all,'' said Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre, suddenly confronted with questions we
used to put to Don Zimmer, Darrell Johnson, John McNamara, and Joe
Morgan, assumed the same position. ``Nobody's gonna quit or get
scared or anything like that,'' said Torre. ``If we get beaten,
it's just because we get beaten. Go over and ask Jimy (Williams,
the Sox manager). I'll still take this seat. We've got a four-game
bulge in the loss column. I'm sure Jimy would take it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, with his good-luck Baby Ruth candy bar still on his
desk, downplayed the obvious and said, ``It's good to sweep
anytime. We're just playing that schedule. We know they're the
champs.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, beating Parcells goes down as one of the greatest
moments in the history of the Patriots franchise. The Tuna led New
England to the Super Bowl in 1996, then inherited a 1-15 Jets team
and immediately made it better than the Patriots team he left
behind. In Foxborough, Mass., Patriots management became obsessed
with all things Parcells, dismantling what he built and even firing
a secretary who made a couple of phone calls to the Tuna. New
England's victory in the Meadowlands will go a long way toward
putting the Ghost of Parcells to rest. And just try wiping the
smile off the face of Patriots owner Bob Kraft today.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to underestimate what the victory means to the
Patriots. It is temporary vindication for Kraft, general manager
Bobby Grier, and all the Patriot players who were in New England
under Parcells. Most of all, it saves coach Pete Carroll from more
of the darts and abject ridicule that have marked his two-plus-year
tenure as unfortunate successor to the Tuna. At least for a while,
Pete gets to tell his critics to shut up.
</P>
<P>
   Happy day. Boston has been Mudville for too long. Today we are
Pleasantville and woe is the New Yorker who crosses our path.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
