<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL CAN'T MUSTER PASSERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's bumbling, rumbling, stumbling edition of The Sporting
Muse:
</P>
<P>
   The most important position in football is quarterback. And
there is mounting evidence that the second-most important position
is backup quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   On opening day of the NFL, also known as the official start of
hunting season among defenses coast-to-coast, the postgame accent
again was on casualties and a lack of depth over center. In the
time it took Vinny Testaverde to scream, the New York Jets went
from Super Bowl contender to a team staring 15 games in the face
with Rick Mirer or Tom Tupa over center. Bill Parcells had better
be a genius.
</P>
<P>
   It took Atlanta's Chris Chandler only three quarters to retire
with an injury, Cincinnati's Jeff Blake left his game with cramps,
and Green Bay's Brett Favre and Arizona's Jake Plummer played on
courageously despite injuries to their throwing hands.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to see the league put a skirt on quarterbacks and
render them untouchable. Testaverde's ruptured Achilles had more to
do with age and artificial turf than the Patriots. But with
sophisticated defensive packages and bigger players, the game has
evolved to the point where quarterbacks are an endangered species.
With the exception of demigods named Aikman, Favre and Marino,
quarterbacks are either physically or mentally lame.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure who had a worse day Sunday, Parcells or those
coaches stuck with the following:
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, where Doug Pederson went 12 for 26 for 91 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, where Elvis Grbac threw eight straight
incompletions with the game on the line against Chicago, and where
Warren Moon, who turns 43 in November, is the backup. Baltimore,
where Scott Mitchell was 17 for 40 with two picks and 188 yards
against the Rams, and where another failure, Tony Banks, is the
backup.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina, where Steve Beuerlein, Steve Bono and Jeff Lewis are
poised to make George Seifert regret his decision to unretire.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, which is testing fate with Danny Kanell and Tony
Graziani as Chandler's backup.
</P>
<P>
   New York, where Giants coach Jim Fassel watched Kent Graham go
12 for 23 for 91 yards, and where Ryan Leaf mentor's, Kerry
Collins, is the backup.
</P>
<P>
   Or Tampa Bay, which saw the Giants (107 net yards) turn two of
five Trent Dilfer mistakes (four picks, one fumble) into defensive
touchdowns and force Tony Dungy to yank Dilfer for Eric Zeier.
</P>
<P>
   I'm willing to predict that the next quarterback injury will be
to Dilfer, and it will happen Tuesday when he is the victim of
friendly fire during practice. ...
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the smartest teams in the league are the few who chose
to secure a reserve quarterback with some credentials, and those
who spent a first-round draft pick on a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (Rob Johnson), San Diego (Erik Kramer), Denver (Bubby
Brister), Pittsburgh (Mike Tomczak) and Minnesota (human retrovirus
Jeff George) all armed themselves deeper than other teams in case
of emergency. I'm willing to bet that Buffalo and Minnesota will
get offers for Johnson and George by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The Cade McNowns, Tim Couchs and Donovan McNabbs may be
inexperienced, but that works to their advantage. We already know
Mitchell, Graham and Dilfer suck. ...
</P>
<P>
   McNabb, Pederson's backup in Philadelphia, and the Browns' Couch
are likely to start by October, if not sooner. McNown played Sunday
for the Bears behind Shane Matthews. Akili Smith (Cincinnati) could
be on the sidelines if Jeff Blake plays back to 1997. Daunte
Culpepper (Minnesota) gives the Vikings the chance to entertain
offers for George. ...
</P>
<P>
   One of the subtle shifts in the NFL has to do with the
quick-strike ability of defenses. There were 10 defensive
touchdowns and a pair of safetys Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When you think about it, defenses now employ more skill players
on the field these days than offenses. Offenses employ five huge
linemen and a pair of blockers at tight end and fullback. Depending
on the scheme, defenses can have as many as nine great athletes on
the field at any time. ...
</P>
<P>
   Official 1999 coaching hot seat rankings: 1, Bruce Coslet,
Cincinnati; 2, Norv Turner, Washington. 3, Gunther Cunningham,
Kansas City. Those excused this week: Bobby Ross, Detroit; Pete
Carroll, New England. ...
</P>
<P>
   It would be disingenuous to say I believed the Lions would beat
the Seahawks Sunday. But Bobby Ross got the Chargers to a Super
Bowl, and this isn't a running back league any more. ...
</P>
<P>
   Based on their first effort, it's 50-50 whether the new
Cleveland Browns score an offensive touchdown by Halloween. You'd
think $530 million would buy more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
