</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Sammy Sosa was the main drawing card in a weekend series that
attracted more than 150,000 fans to the Astrodome. But in the end
he was a mere bit player in the unfolding drama that is the Astros'
quest for a third consecutive division title.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astros upstaged Sosa once again, defeating the Chicago Cubs
7-1 Sunday to extend their winning streak to a
franchise-record-tying 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Under most circumstances, that would have been enough to take
the mystery out of the National League Central race. But the
second-place Cincinnati Reds refuse to go away. The Reds have won
nine of their last 10, including Sunday's victory over Florida that
kept them three games behind the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been very special because of what the Reds are
doing,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said of his team's winning
streak. ``It's almost like we're going to have to win every game to
win the division.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's highly unlikely that will happen, you would never
know by watching the Astros over the last 10 days. Of course, the
competition hasn't exactly been the best the NL has to offer, but
the Astros have done exactly what they're supposed to do against
the likes of Montreal, Philadelphia and Chicago, which became the
Astros' 11th sweep victim of the season and their third in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Holt's resilient pitching and a balanced offensive attack
led by Cubs-killer Carl Everett made it an easy victory for the
Astros. Holt overcame a shaky start and worked out of a couple of
jams to notch his first victory since Aug. 14 and only his fourth
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Holt (4-13) allowed a run on four hits in six innings, and
relievers Jose Cabrera, Jay Powell and Doug Henry combined for
three shutout innings. The Astros have held their opponents to 2.7
runs per game during the winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for our pitching staff,'' Astros second baseman
Craig Biggio said. ``They've been the story of our season. If it
weren't for them, I don't know where we'd be.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for Everett, who has been an absolute
terror to opposing pitchers, particularly those who receive their
paychecks from the Cubs. Everett was 4-for-4 with an RBI and three
runs Sunday, and he hit .522 with six homers and 20 RBIs against
the Cubs this season.
</P>
<P>
   Since being activated from the disabled list Aug. 6 at Chicago,
Everett has hit safely in 18 of 20 games, compiling a .432 batting
average with 10 homers and 29 RBIs. What makes those numbers even
more impressive is the fact Everett recently missed 11 games
because of another injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carl is hitting everything right now,'' Dierker said. ``It's
almost impossible to defend him, because he's hitting the ball in
every direction. He's really hot right now.''
</P>
<P>
   As well as the Astros are playing, most of them believe their
best is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we continue to play like this, who knows what might
happen?'' said Everett, who tied a career high for hits in a game.
``I don't think we've played our best baseball yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt certainly didn't appear to be at his best after he walked
the first two batters of the game, prompting a visit to the mound
from pitching coach Vern Ruhle. Holt stranded both runners, coaxing
an infield popout from Sosa and striking out Mark Grace and Henry
Rodriguez. Holt finished with seven strikeouts, one shy of his
career high.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was overthrowing a little bit in the beginning,'' Astros
catcher Tony Eusebio said. ``But after he settled down, he was
hitting his spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt retired 10 consecutive batters after the two first-inning
walks, and by the time he finally allowed a run, the Astros already
had given him a two-run lead on Everett's RBI single in the first
and Biggio's third-inning solo homer _ the 150th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs scored their only run in the fourth inning on Jeff
Reed's sacrifice fly, which scored Grace. Eusebio drove home a run
with a ground ball in the fourth, and Daryle Ward's sixth-inning
sacrifice fly gave the Astros a three-run lead. Eusebio, Ken
Caminiti and Russ Johnson each drove in a run in the Astros'
three-run eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti had three hits in the game, and Bill Spiers added two
as six Astros combined for 12 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was 2-for-4 Sunday, but he had only three hits (none a
homer) in 14 at-bats during the three-game series. It marked the
first time Sosa, who leads the majors with 59 round-trippers, went
homerless in a series since Aug. 6-8 when the Astros visited
Wrigley Field, a span of 10 series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
