<HEADLINE>
GALLANT VICTOR A VICTOR IN DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was supposed to be a wonderful US Open, the last
of the so-called American century, but nowhere was the name of an
American, Todd Martin, mentioned as somebody who would rescue the
men's proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Martin? Good fellow, relentless tryer, top 10 resident off
and on, kind to people and dogs. However, Martin was maybe the last
good player you'd expect to find unpacking his bags at Flushing
Meadow Sunday and suiting up to save the title bout from one-sided
oblivion. Nevertheless, it was this self-effacing Ichabod Crane in
knee-pants who made the tournament that Andre Agassi inevitably
won.
</P>
<P>
   Andre became the `99-er, the game's man of the year, adding a
second major to his French conquest, yet the odyssey of
over-achiever Martin through a fortnight of viruses, IV drips,
escapes, and bone-weariness earned at least an asterisk in the
honor-roll book.
</P>
<P>
   1999 _ lost final but won hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, there was also a male go-round at the Meadow. Nobody to
upstage Serena, of course, but the guys were hanging out. Sort of.
And there were people who believed it wasn't wrong to deal them
equal prize money. Guys gotta eat, too.
</P>
<P>
   But when the top half of the draw immediately started to look
like the earthquake scenes in ``San Francisco'' when champs Sampras
and Rafter crumbled and others of name value like Kuerten and
Ivanisevic vanished in the rubble, you wondered if anybody would
remain to contest any kind of a final with Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was Martin as the lone ranger. Swaddled in all
sorts of bandages and braces and resembling a refugee from the set
of ``The Mummy's Curse,'' he may have been nowhere in the pundits'
reckonings, but he was surviving. Going grayer with every match,
looking older than springtime _ sometimes more like 92 than 29 _ a
self-declared ``late bloomer,'' he was to bloom latest and best at
the end of the line: the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had me hanging on by a thread,'' whewed Agassi, who pulled
himself together and into focus in time to triumph, 6-4, 6-7 (5-7),
6-7 (2-7), 6-3, 6-2. For 3 hours and 23 minutes, Martin roughed-up,
hassled, and much of the time outhit the peerless shotmaker with 23
aces, backhand blasts, and twinkle-toe volleys.
</P>
<P>
   Todd made Agassi prove his greatness, and in doing so he wowed
23,053 witnesses surrounding him. It was neck-and-neck all the way,
although Andre's relentless counter-punching began to cut Martin's
legs out from under him and erode the big guy's serve.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-feet-6, Martin was the loftiest individual to grace a US
final, and it's been clear that a huge percentage of that frame is
heart. He feared three years ago that his career was ending,
discourtesy of a gimpy right elbow, but surgery and a long spell of
rehab pulled him through.
</P>
<P>
   The game was a beneficiary, too, because Martin is a guy who
appreciates ``being in the arena,'' win or lose. He started out
barely eluding a no-name qualifier, Stephane Huet, in a fifth set
tie-breaker, and didn't think he was long for this Open.
</P>
<P>
   Todd caught a break in the third round when the dangerous Swede,
Magnus Larsson, quit with a wobbly knee, and realized ``euphoria''
in the fourth by improbably overtaking 1997 finalist Greg Rusedski
in a post-midnight resurgence. He wouldn't let Greg loose even
though the Brit led by two sets, served for victory at 5-4 in the
third, and led again in the fifth, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Dividing his time between medical treatment and the court, ``and
a little sleep,'' Martin saved the Open from a final-round occupant
named Slava Dosedel or Cedric Pioline. Fine fellows _ but 1999 US
Open finalists? Spare us, please _ and Martin did.
</P>
<P>
   He did it with style and moxie, understatement, good humor, and
crushing shots that flattened six foes and put some tremble into
Andre. When Martin looked at his end of town and saw it in ruins,
and that Pete Sampras and Patrick Rafter had disappeared, did he
decide to be a good citizen and do what he could as a one-man
salvage crew?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're great players. I never think about being great. I
figure I just have to be better than the guy across the net.'' He
was, six-and-two-fifths times. He took it to the limit and brought
the last major of the century to a splendid crescendo.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Martin probably won't win a major. This was as close as
he'll get. But give him that major asterisk. 1999 _ lost final, won
hearts, rescued men's tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
