<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9692 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-OPEN-HNS &LR;      09-13 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Call him Andre the giant. Andre the gallant, too.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And, yes, Andre the gutsy. The Andre Agassi who once drew
criticism for failing to play to the best of his ability, for
spending more time selling products than selling out on the tennis
court, is but a distant memory.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing 30, having returned to the top of the tennis rankings
after free-falling well into triple digits just 24 months earlier,
Agassi completed the best year of his wildly careening career
Sunday with a 6-4, 6-7 (7-5), 6-7 (7-2), 6-3, 6-2 comeback victory
over Todd Martin for his second U.S. Open championship.
</P>
<P>
   No U.S. Open titlist had rallied from a two-sets-to-one deficit
since John Newcombe defeated Jan Kodes at Forest Hills in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   But kudos to Martin, too. In this, just his second major final,
he didn't choke, as he has been wont to do. Rather, Agassi choked
him with a brilliant one-two punch of power and finesse on the
serving and receiving end, beginning with the final game of the
fourth set.
</P>
<P>
   They played for almost 3{ hours, which took more of a toll on
Martin's weary body than on Agassi's. The runner-up was hit by a
stomach virus early last week and then had to dig himself out of a
two-set hole in the fourth round Tuesday night against Greg
Rusedski.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame somebody had to lose,'' said Agassi, who was
seeded second. ``I was hanging by a thread for the longest time. It
was exciting tennis. It really speaks a lot for his spirit because
he knows how to boil it down to tennis out there. Todd was really
executing in a way that was giving me all sorts of problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was serving so well. I think the statistics really reflect
what a great match it was. I only had 22 unforced errors. Through
the course of a five-set match, that's not easy with a guy who hits
the ball as well as him on a fast court. I was very worried. He
gave me a lot to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi broke his fellow American's serve, a weapon strong enough
for Martin to have belted 22 aces up to that juncture, three times
in the last five games to secure the fifth major title of his
career and his second of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   At the French Open, Agassi, had rallied from a two-set deficit
to beat Andrei Medvedev, a victory that made him only the fifth
player to complete a career Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi also reached the Wimbledon final, where Pete Sampras beat
him in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, trying to become the first man to win 13 Slam titles,
had pulled out of the U.S. Open the day it began, having injured
his back practicing.
</P>
<P>
   Twice-defending champion Patrick Rafter retired from his
first-round match with a shoulder injury. Sampras and Rafter were
slotted in Martin's half of the draw. But he seized the opportunity
and came within a set of the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be disappointed with what happened today, or over the
last two weeks,'' the seventh-seeded Martin said. ``I feel very
good about the way I played.''
</P>
<P>
   And so for the fourth time in the 1990s _ but for the first time
since '95 _ U.S. men won three of the four Slam stops. Agassi last
prevailed here in 1994, beating Michael Stich.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras then defeated him 12 months later, a loss he admits
plunged him into a competitive free fall it took him almost three
years to escape. To get his game back, he was reduced to entering a
couple of Challenger Series events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to make a choice if I was going to really play the game
or quit,'' he said. ``If I was going to play, I had to do a lot of
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi had sent a U.S. Open final to a fifth set for the first
time in 11 years _ Mats Wilander beat Ivan Lendl in five in 1988 _
by breaking Martin twice in the fourth while saving two break
points himself in the eighth game, the last time he would be on the
brink of losing his serve.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 29, was 0-for-8 on break opportunities up to then but
had stayed a leg up in the match by managing the tiebreakers better
than the world's new No. 1, a ranking Agassi locked up with his
semifinal win over Australian Open champ Yevgeny Kafelnikov.
</P>
<P>
   He took the first one 7-5, winning three of Agassi's six service
points, and the second 7-2, taking five of six.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of Martin's tennis until the last set _ the shortest
of the afternoon at 28 minutes _ was unquestionably the highest of
a career that had seen him advance to only one previous Grand Slam
final, a loss to Sampras in Australia in 1994. His ranking is
fourth, a personal best.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I did have my opportunities on Andre's second serve,''
Martin said, ``I probably didn't do enough with them. I was up
love-30 countless times. I missed a lot of chances, although that
was due to the way he played as much as anything. But I did not
expect to go five sets without breaking his serve.''
</P>
<P>
   After he incurred a break in the opening game, the 6-6 Martin's
crushing serve routinely bedeviled Agassi, the game's best
returner. He was effective in pulling Agassi off the court by
kicking the ball wide to the forehand. But as he has done all
summer against everyone except Sampras, who gave him three of his
four defeats in 39 matches beginning with the French Open run,
Agassi found an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really had to make every point incredibly important,''
Agassi said. ``It was crucial that I took care of my own service
games because I knew I would not get many chances (to break him).''
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth set, he left no doubt his No. 1 ranking _ 140
notches above where it had fallen in 1997 _ is in deserving hands.
He lost just three points on his serve and was so energized, he
sprinted to the chair for the final two changeovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important in a five-set match if you feel strong,'' he
said, ``to let your opponent know you feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi won two of his fifth-set service games at love and broke
at love in the second game. He then broke for the championship at
15-40, when Martin netted a backhand off a blistering, deep Agassi
backhand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible,'' Agassi said. ``It's been a long road back
for me, one I'm quite proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   What if somebody had told him, in mid-1997, that he would be
where he is today, all by his lonesome on top of his sport again?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell them to stop smoking that crack pipe,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
