<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS TUNED OUT THE TUNA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Drew Bledsoe and Ty Law believe they
understand what happened to their team Sunday at the Meadowlands.
It won a game to be sure, but maybe, just maybe, it did something
more important.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, this time, it also grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't pretty; in fact, it was pretty damn ugly,'' Law said
after his team had rallied to catch the scrappy New York Jets at
the buzzer, 30-28, winning the season opener on the road with three
seconds on the clock and their season on the line as early as it
possibly could be.
</P>
<P>
   It had been an up-and-down afternoon when it should have been
something far smoother. It had been a day when the Jets lost their
starting quarterback for the season and two other starters for a
while and still held the Patriots off with a stoic defense and a
punter under center.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a day when Law's Patriots did many good things but a
few things so exceedingly poor that, in another lifetime, they
would have surely cracked under the weight of their own series of
faux pas and let this opportunity slip away after the Jets
intercepted a Bledsoe pass and ran it in for a touchdown to take a
28-27 lead midway through the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   By then the game should have been long over. It should have been
a game no longer. But it was and the Patriots were not discouraged
by it. They were displeased but not discouraged, which was as it
should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a roller-coaster ride for us but it was a good ride,''
Law said. ``It was the best ride we could have had. It was good for
our team because it boosts our confidence. It showed us we can play
when it's tight. We can win as a team, not with just a few
individuals making plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play our best. We know that. If we had gotten them
off the field when we should, we would have won easily but out of
all the crap that went on they could have blown us out of the
water. But we wouldn't let them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were without not only Vinny Testaverde but also nose
tackle Jason Ferguson, kick returner Leon Johnson, and, for a time,
tight end Eric Green as green-and-white clad men fell to the ground
one after another. They had Tom Tupa, their punter, at quarterback,
and he rallied them when all appeared lost by throwing two unlikely
touchdown passes, the latter of which helped reduce an 11-point
Patriot lead to dust in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Yet still the Patriots hung on until they finally hung one on a
team that had haunted them for two years. Haunted them until
Saturday night, when Bledsoe had a notion the Jets would haunt them
no longer even if they did beat them from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to win this game on Saturday,'' Bledsoe
said after he had recovered from Bryan Cox's 27-yard interception
return for a fourth-quarter touchdown by marching his team 44 yards
in 10 plays to set up Adam Vinatieri's winning, 23-yard field goal
with three seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could feel the difference in us last night. You could
sense it was just a football game again and we were ready to win
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference this time was that the game was not between the
Patriots and The Ghost of Christmas Past. It was not between the
Patriots and Bill Parcells. This time it was just a football game,
not an exorcism, although the way it ended may have allowed it to
function in both capacities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely over,'' safety Lawyer Milloy said of the
feared Curse of the Tuna. ``We'll treat them like the next opponent
from now on. It will be a rivalry but it was a different feeling
this time. I'm not saying we'll dominate them. We're rivals so
every game will be tough and the best team on that day will win,
but we'll be fundamentally sound now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't running around all hyped up, like we did last year.
We understand now that they use that to their advantage. Today our
coaches did a good job of getting us into base defenses if we
weren't ready to make adjustments, and we played from there.''
</P>
<P>
   They played hard from there all afternoon, spectacularly at
times and disastrously at others but never once did they lose their
poise. Never once did they waver. Never once did they let the Jets
destroy them where it counts _ in their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat one of the teams that people were giving the respect
to on the road, the respect we once had,'' Milloy said. ``When
things went bad, we stayed calm. We remained focused on one thing _
winning the game. It was a sticky situation for us for a while, but
we stayed together and we won. Now we move on to Indianapolis.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving on after success has not been easy for this Patriot team
of late. Two years in a row they have followed 4-1 starts with 1-4
collapses. That has made for roller-coaster years that were akin to
Sunday's roller-coaster game, except this time, with the exception
of nitwit linebacker coach Bo Pelini cursing out members of the
local media after the game as if they had been found trying to put
a mojo on his team, they not only said the right things, they
seemed to mean them this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a damn good team we beat, but it's just one game,''
said Willie McGinest on a day in which he had two sacks, forced a
fumble, and recovered another for a touchdown. ``That's all it is.
One game. We're not playing this season for the Jets. We're playing
for the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always weird here. The coaches told us to be prepared for
three or four things that would be very unusual. It happened, but
you've just got to keep going and tune things out. We did that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have to stay focused and stay humble. You don't win the
season on one game.''
</P>
<P>
   No, you don't. But knowing that is the case may have been the
Patriots' biggest victory of all Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
