<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     09-13 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Well, hooray. The American century ends with a blooming
American tennis renaissance, with as glorious a summer as the Old
Glory brigade has enjoyed in a generation.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last two majors of the 1900s produced a clean sweep by the
Yanks, who took the men's and women's championships at Wimbledon,
then repeated the feat at the U.S. Open. This after Sunday's king
of Queens, Andre Agassi, had claimed the French Open title, too.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a distinction to be made. On the women's side, a
new era beckons. The sisters Williams have announced themselves
worthy heiresses to the legacy of Helen Wills Moody, Billie Jean
King and Chris Evert, the greatest of our home-grown heroines.
Serena, 17, opened the door here. Venus, still a teen-ager herself,
will follow her through it next year.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday, the deluge. They conspired to win the doubles
Sunday, just to make sure we were paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Only their dual presence likely will prevent one or the other
from breaking all the records, but together they're certain to
collect more Grand Slam titles than any family in history, unless
the sheer boredom of terrorizing the Women's Tennis Association _
soon to stand for Williams Tennis Association _ Tour short-circuits
their careers ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   A not-very-bold prediction: Between them, Venus and Serena will
surpass Margaret Court's record of 24 Slams won.
</P>
<P>
   Inside of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   As for the U.S. men, though, the smashing year they're having
smacks more of a last gasp than a second wind, at least at first
glance. Agassi and Todd Martin, Sunday's game runner-up, are
crowding 30; Pete Sampras isn't far behind them. Jim Courier, the
only other U.S. player ranked in the top 50, is right there as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Five years from now, they figure to be off playing golf and
preparing to steal a bunch more money on the senior circuit.
</P>
<P>
   And, no, there are no heirs apparent popping off the current
ranking charts or the junior draw sheets. Jan-Michael Gambill and
Justin Gimelstob aren't on the cusp of accepting the baton.
Regarding the latter group, Mardy Fish is the U.S.'s closest thing
to a big kahuna _ and he's just 10th on the junior computer. At the
Open, Fish was the only U.S. lad to advance as far as the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the next Pete (12 majors won) or Andre (five
after Sunday) is not even a faint blip on the radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   But, short term, everything is fine. Couldn't be finer,
actually.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' pursuit of Slam history _ one more victory and he holds
the all-time record by his lonesome _ stalled two weeks ago when he
suffered a fluke back injury preparing for the Open, but it was a
temporary setback. He will be a force to reckon with at every major
he enters save Roland Garros through at least 2002 and likely
longer at Wimbledon, where the length of his points are timed in
nanoseconds.
</P>
<P>
   If he stays in shape, Pete could still win on the grass at 35.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's shelf life can also be as long as he wants it to be. I
mean, here's a guy who has been in three consecutive Slam finals,
winning two of them, after his career had appeared over, for the
second time, two years ago. Agassi, the master of self-reinvention,
has far fewer miles on his body than any of the game's other
gracefully aging elite players.
</P>
<P>
   His style of play also minimizes wear and tear. Unless he falls
in love again with a beautiful actress, his next couple of years
should cement his place among the greatest of the game's greats.
Having squandered numerous opportunities to make his mark in his
early 20s, Andre is like the college dropout who returns to school
late in life, determined to get his degree. He's hungry, something
he rarely showed during his image-is-everything period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely feel I have more titles in me,'' Agassi argued
after defeating Martin in five sets. ``I feel like I can get
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, meanwhile, is an altogether different case study.
Ostensibly a peer of Pete's and Andre's, he was barely good enough
to survive on the tour at an age when the aforementioned
Wunkerkinder were the toast of same.
</P>
<P>
   After a short stint in college, he turned pro in 1992 and then
spent the next six years trying hard to stay invisible. When he did
surface, he didn't enhance his reputation much, losing the
Australian Open final of 1994 in straight sets to Sampras, then
choking away a '96 semifinal at Wimbledon, a tournament he might
have won.
</P>
<P>
   But clean living makes him a young 29, and he believes his best
tennis is ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately, I've been thinking of the tortoise-and-the-hare
analogy,'' Martin said before the Open. ``I'm the tortoise. I'm
slower than a lot of other players. I'm also very deliberate. But I
show up every day and work hard. If I continue to do so, I stand
the best chance in my career of competing for an important
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps winning one. For three sets Sunday, he was good
enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
