<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DEFENSE STOPS AT NOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Sunday's victory, of course, was a
mini-Super Bowl for the Patriots, beating the despised Jets here
when thoughts of the real Super Bowl already were sweeping the
Meadowlands early in the first Sunday of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, as New England defensive lineman Chad Eaton pointedly put
it, ``there's something wrong with the Jets' offseason conditioning
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words had been said time and again about New England since
the dismal end of last season. If it had been New England coaches
who had sat down Tom Tupa (6 of 10, 165 yards, 3 TDs) and brought
in shaky Rick Mirer as quarterback on the first play of the fourth
quarter, even after Tupa had his team on the move and had just
completed a nifty 14-yard pass to Keyshawn Johnson, critics would
have been hoarse by sunset.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, even though the Patriots defense had its
``ugly'' moments, as cornerback Ty Law said, it was the defense
that helped save New England's sweetest victory in months, if not
years. Players who had been beat earlier in the game _ Chris Slade,
Steve Israel, and Law the most prominent _ came back to make key
plays in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Law has to be first. The Patriots corner said he was ``bored out
there'' for much of the game as New York's offensive formations
often left him guarding running backs. In other words, Law was
looking for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   That matchup came as coach Pete Carroll grew more and more
worried as the game clock wore down to 6 minutes left, then 5, then
4, then 3:45. The Jets were in control of the ball, the clock, and
seemingly the game as Mirer stepped back to throw on a
second-and-10 situation from his 45-yard line. The Jets were lined
up in a familiar formation, ``the one they called me for pass
interference before,'' and Law was on Johnson and sensed Johnson
was going for a short slant route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keyshawn had been coming up big for them all day long,'' said
Law, ``and so maybe I would have thrown to him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Jets came out in formation, ``I kind of sensed what they
were going to do,'' said Law. ``It was me and Keyshawn on the back
side (of the formation) and I was on him one-on-one and I knew nine
times out of 10 he was going to get the ball. So I was right on his
hip pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept my eyes on the quarterback, and I kind of knew what he
was going to do. And then I just broke when Keyshawn did, and for
that one split second I was looking for an interception. But then I
thought if I didn't come up with the interception, maybe Keyshawn
would come up with the big ball.''
</P>
<P>
   So Law did what his reputation now demands and the millions of
dollars paid to him now require. He went head-to-head against the
Jets' best receiver with the game hanging in the balance, and made
the play that had to be made. As Johnson cut quickly to the inside,
Law shadowed him and ``got a good piece'' of the pass.
</P>
<P>
   The ball spun crazily into the air, and the only defender near
it was Slade. As much as _ or more than _ any Patriot, the outside
linebacker wanted to beat Bill Parcells's team; ``It's been a long
time coming against this team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the first quarter it was Slade who had been beaten, and
beaten badly, when Vinny Testaverde fired a 27-yard touchdown pass
down the right sideline to running back Richie Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got beat on that play,'' said Slade. ``But, hey, there are a
lot of big plays to be made in a game. I tried to forget about that
and just keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mirer's deflected pass ready for the taking, Slade leaped
to pull in the interception.
</P>
<P>
   The play was made, just as Willie McGinest had made his plays
earlier and just as Law had initiated the interception with tight
coverage on Johnson. Slade, McGinest, Law, Lawyer Milloy, and a few
others are counted on to make plays in these situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain guys are counted on to make big plays on this team as
opportunities come, to change the whole game,'' said Slade. ``I
consider myself one of those guys. Willie (McGinest) considers
himself one of those guys. We're guys who try to make a difference
when it counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Also beaten earlier, and also very confused, Israel twice came
up with big plays in the second half. But in the eerie silence of
Giants Stadium after Testaverde had just been wheeled off the field
with his torn Achilles' tendon, a confused Israel had allowed
former teammate Tupa to complete an embarrassing 25-yard TD pass to
Johnson on his first pass attempt in three years. Instead of being
dispirited and down, with the game and their season perhaps over,
the Jets again were alive.
</P>
<P>
   Israel made amends in the second half, though, blind-siding Tupa
on a corner blitz on the third play of the third quarter, a big
play that led directly to a New England score. And then, in the
fourth quarter, Israel shadowed receiver Dedric Ward and
intercepted a lazy pass from Mirer at the Patriots 2-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   The corner blitz was ``a picture-perfect call'' by defensive
coordinator Steve Sidwell, said Israel, ``and they never saw me
coming. I came clean, and once you come clean you've got to make
sure to make something happen. So I'm thinking, `They never saw me
coming and a sack's not going to be good enough.' I had to look for
a way to get the ball out, and that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel pounced on Tupa from the blind side and knocked the ball
loose. The ball was batted around until finally, in the Jets end
zone, it was McGinest who recovered it for an easy New England
touchdown and 17-16 lead. As important as the score, the play
showed an aggressiveness missing from the Patriots defense when
Tupa first replaced Testaverde in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For McGinest to score the TD was also a symbolic recovery.
``Last year was hard for me to take,'' he said of his
injury-plagued campaign. ``And it was great to win this, but we got
to remember we don't just have to beat the Jets. We're trying to
win the AFC East. And now we've got to worry about the Indianapolis
Colts.''
</P>
<P>
   But not until after many Patriots and Patriots fans savor this
win over the Jets for a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
