<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-MISSILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA AGREES TO END MISSILE TESTING IN EXCHANGE FOR ECONOMIC
AID 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ North Korea has tentatively agreed to end its
testing of long-range ballistic missiles in exchange for a
commitment from the United States and Japan to move forward with
economic assistance for the Communist government there, American
officials said on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which was reached on Sunday in Berlin after five
days of negotiations there by American and North Korean diplomats,
appears to end the immediate threat that North Korea will test a
new long-range missile this autumn.
</P>
<P>
   American officials cautioned, however, that the agreement was
dependent on what one described as ``the always questionable
sincerity of the North Koreans,'' and that North Korea could
quickly reverse course and resume tests of its long-range missiles
within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could be back in business with the missiles in a hurry,''
said one Clinton administration official. ``This is one positive
step in what has proved to be a long, frustrating process.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Koreans have begun preparations for a new test of
their latest long-range missile, which is believed to be capable of
striking portions of Alaska and Hawaii. Washington officials have
been monitoring activities at the North Korean launching site by
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese have been particularly alarmed by the threat of a
new test, because the last long-range missile tested by the
Pyongyang government flew directly over Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The talks in Berlin were being held about the time that the
administration thought the North Koreans might test the new
Taepodong 2 rocket. North Korea is marking the 50th anniversary of
Communist rule this month, and some analysts had suggested that the
missile test would be staged as part of the celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, South Korea and Japan had shown an unusually
high degree of diplomatic coordination in condemning North Korea
and pledging to slow down food and oil assistance if the test was
carried out. On Sunday, while meeting in Auckland, New Zealand,
during the Asian Pacific Economic Cooperation forum, President
Clinton, Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi of Japan and President Kim
Dae- jung of South Korea committed to penalizing North Korea if it
conducted the test.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Japan and the United States also agreed to conduct
joint research on a missile-defense system that in theory could
destroy ballistic missiles from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a U.S. envoy, former Defense Secretary William J.
Perry, laid out proposals essentially offering to lift some trade
sanctions and to begin a formal recognition of North Korea in
return for a halt to its missile testing and an end to its export
of missile technology to the Middle East and Pakistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
