<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9699 &Cx1f; tdt-z
b x ufvj &LR;  &UR; BYLINE &LR;      09-13 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 ufvj  BYLINE 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Michael Madden
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Globe Staff
</P>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ True, Adam Vinatieri had little more
than an extra point for the Patriots to win the game that so few
thought they could win. A field goal from the 13-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Routine?
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to take it like a normal kick,'' said the Patriots
place kicker, whose 23-yard field goal with three seconds left put
the official stamp on the Patriots' 30-28 victory. ``I tried not to
get too messed up in the head about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The same might not be said of New England fans. This magnificent
game for those who love wild and wacky football already had had its
weird kicking moment. It came when Patriots long snapper Mike
Bartrum hiked the ball virtually into the mez- zanine of Giants
Stadium, instead of to punter Lee Johnson, giving New York a safety
just before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking of Bart doing that (again),'' said Vinatieri
of the moments just before the winning kick. ``That's about the
first and only time I've seen Bart do something like that, in
practice, games, any- thing. He's a great snapper and I guess he
was just trying to show he was human.''
</P>
<P>
   The heavy lifting for these win- ning points had been done by
Vina-H tieri's teammates _ quarterback L Drew Bledsoe, wide
receivers Troy Brown and Terry Glenn, running back Terry Allen and
the offensive line. The Patriots twice got seldom- seen first downs
on running plays in  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  the winning drive, even
if one was called back because of a motion pen- alty.
</P>
<P>
   But Vinatieri still had to put foot to ball, even if he was
thinking as he trotted onto the field, ``this team has so much
heart ... they got us nice and close and worked the clock L down.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -------------------- &LR;  Vinatieri swung his foot as L smoothly
and calmly as a golfer swinging a wedge, and the ball sailed
through the uprights. The Patriot victory seemed certain ... well,
until the kickoff following the field goal. Just as happened in the
final exhibi- tion game against Carolina, Vinatieri did not do what
he wanted to do on  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  the kickoff after making
a clutch field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing to happen on the kickoff in this situation would
be a Jets return for a touchdown. The second-worst thing would be
what Vinatieri did in Carolina, a very short kick that would give
the Jets a last-gasp field-goal attempt. The L third-worst thing
would be a kickoff out of bounds, allowing New York one more play
from scrimmage when anything could happen.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri kicked the ball out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to do a power squib,'' said the kicker, ``and I
was trying to hit it down the middle. Un- fortunately, I don't know
if the refs started the (25-second) clock wrong but as I started
taking my steps, I saw the (other Patriots on the kick- off team)
just starting to pan out and line up. But I looked up at the clock
and there was only 4 seconds left.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri was torn. Kick the ball quickly even though his
teammates might not be ready or allow the clock to run down, take
the penalty and bring the ball a crucial 5 more yards closer to the
Patriot goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I sprinted up to the ball, I approached it too fast and my
steps got kind of screwed up,'' he said. ``Personally, I didn't
know whether it was better to take the penalty or get the ball
off.''
</P>
<P>
   All's well that ends well for the Patriots. A Hail Mary pass
from Jets QB Rick Mirer was batted down by the Patriot defense as
time expired and the saga of Adam Vinatieri con- tinued.
</P>
<P>
   His clutch field goals now are getting routine. It's the
kickoffs fol- lowing those clutch field goals that aren't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
