u s BC-FBN-JETS-TUPA-BOS &LR;      09-13 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-TUPA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUPA FARES WELL, BUT MIRER BLOWS SAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Want to be a backup quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   Imagine watching on the sideline while the starter suffers a
season-ending Achilles' tendon injury with your team trailing,
10-7, in the second quarter. Consider the confidence that is likely
drained from fans _ and possibly teammates _ when you take the
field. Then try to go out and win the game.
</P>
<P>
   New York Jets backup quarterback Tom Tupa, who is used almost
exclusively as a punter, came close to pulling it off in Sunday's
contest with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with his fifth team in 11 seasons (including a
three-year stint with the Patriots), Tupa, who last started at
quarterback in 1991 with Phoenix, completed 6 of 10 passes for 165
yards and 2 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always prepared during the whole offseason for this, and
I was at all the quarterback meetings, so I knew there's always a
chance this could happen,'' said Tupa, who entered the game having
thrown 11 touchdown passes in his career, two since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of games I was supposed to go in, but with the way we
were going, they wanted to see a little bit more of the guys so I
didn't see any snaps this year in preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   His performance wasn't bad considering Jets coach Bill Parcells
put him in merely to keep the Jets honest in what he called ``a
holding pattern'' until the fourth quarter, when he could put
regular backup Rick Mirer in.
</P>
<P>
   NFL rules state you must designate an ``emergency'' quarterback
prior to the contest, and if you insert that quarterback prior to
the fourth quarter, you lose the services of your backup
signal-caller for the remainder of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells had designated Mirer as his emergency QB. So if he had
brought Mirer in when Vinny Testaverde ruptured his Achilles'
tendon in the second quarter, he would have lost Tupa's punting
services for the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said later that Mirer would be the starter, but at
least he knows he'll still have a solid player on the bench. ``Tom
came in, got us a touchdown right away, and took us back down
again,'' said Parcells. ``Two touchdowns, not much else you can
expect from a guy that's second string.''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa's first touchdown came on his first pass of the game, a
25-yard toss to wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson that put the Jets
ahead, 14-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me a great play to start off with, because (the
Patriots) were still back in zone,'' said Tupa. ``They were off the
guy I was going to throw to, so I got him the ball. I knew they
would be back a bit, and I told the coaches let's try to go deep a
few times.''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa said he felt the quick touchdown pass gave the Jets
confidence. ``Vinny had a great year last year, and the last few
years,'' he said. ``I think when the quarterback goes down you have
a tendency to let down a little bit but after that play we got
going a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of a most eventful day for Tupa, who threw
for his second touchdown in the third quarter, a 7-yarder to tight
end Fred Baxter that gave the Jets a 27-22 lead.
</P>
<P>
   He also had a 4-yard run on a fourth-quarter fake punt on fourth
and 5 from the New England 14. Tupa was stopped by tackle Chad
Eaton and defensive back Larry Whigham just shy of the first down.
</P>
<P>
   After the Jets challenged the spot of the ball and officials
checked the replay, the call was upheld.
</P>
<P>
   ``The official on the play got knocked for a loop, and then he
went and spotted the ball,'' said Parcells. ``That's the way it is.
I'm not disputing the call. I'm just saying that's why I challenged
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I made it, but obviously they saw something
different,'' said Tupa. ``I don't know what they saw on television,
but I thought it was pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa had a better day than Mirer, who completed 4 of 11 for 28
yards and two interceptions. But Tupa has no illusions about who
the new starter is. ``I think going into next week, we're going to
have a great week of practice with Rick and just move forward,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
