u s BC-FBN-MCDONOUGHCOLUMN-B     09-13 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' SUPER THOUGHTS TURN TO SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Throughout the preseason, Jets fans and
the New York media wondered ``what would happen without Vinny?''
</P>
<P>
   Now they'll find out.
</P>
<P>
   The talk has moved rapidly from Super Bowl to survival.
</P>
<P>
   When Vinny Testaverde went out for the season in the second
quarter of Sunday's season opener against the New England Patriots
with a ruptured Achilles' tendon, so went the hopes of another big
season for the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   It was evident backups Tom Tupa and Rick Mirer cannot do the
job. At least not like Testaverde, who was coming off a Pro Bowl
season and was expected to do it again in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa played very well in an emergency role. He seemed to have
the Jets on the verge of an incredible victory when his coach, Bill
Parcells, made the decision that changed the game.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells decided to bring on veteran Rick Mirer, whom he traded
for during training camp and who played well in New York's final
exhibition game against Minnesota, throwing for three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer was given a 28-27 lead to protect and couldn't do it. He
threw a critical interception with time running down in the fourth
quarter that the Patriots turned into the winning field goal with
three seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrible throw by Mirer, into heavy coverage, that
bounced into the hands of Chris Slade. The game seemed to be
slipping away from the Patriots after a tough Jets defense made a
succession of big plays. But Mirer gave it back with one throw.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells found himself in an unusual situation in the second
quarter. Early Sunday morning, concerned with the Patriots' fast
wide receivers and their ability to spread out the field, he
decided to add untested defensive back Jermaine Jones from the
practice squad and take Ray Lucas off the active roster.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas is a combination backup quarterback/special teams player.
The gamble backfired when Testaverde went down. Vinny is one of the
most durable and better-conditioned athletes in the NFL. He has
missed just eight games since 1987 because of injury. He doesn't
figure to get hurt. But he did this time.
</P>
<P>
   Now Parcells had another decision to make. If he played Mirer
for Testaverde right away, Tupa, who is also the Jets' punter,
would be done for the day. The reason: Parcells had put only one
backup quarterback, Tupa, on the active game roster, with Mirer
designated as the emergency quarterback. By NFL rules, if Mirer
were inserted before the fourth quarter, Tupa would have been
ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa played well, completing 6 of 10 passes for two touchdowns
and 165 yards, but Parcells took him out at the start of the fourth
quarter. Mirer did not play well, throwing two interceptions. He
looked very nervous in the pocket, and several of his throws were
wobbly.
</P>
<P>
   It was a devastating day for the Jets. Testaverde's loss is a
backbreaker. But New York was crippled by other injuries as well.
Leon Johnson, a solid running back and special teams player,
suffered ligament damage to his knee and likely is out for the
season. Parcells counts on him for 30-35 plays a game. Tight end
Eric Green left in the second half with a neck injury. The Jets
were thin at tight end to begin with as Kyle Brady, who started all
of last season for them at that position, left for Jacksonville via
free agency. The Jets signed Green and hoped second-year man Blake
Spence would come along fast behind him. But Spence was hurt twice
in preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Jets built a powerful offense around Testaverde's
ability to throw the ball quickly and to the right man. That's just
what he was doing Sunday until he suffered the freak injury,
without being hit.
</P>
<P>
   His understudies are not to blame, but it became evident Tupa
and Mirer could neither make the decisions as fast as Testaverde,
nor deliver the ball nearly as well.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells had said during preseason that the thing he liked about
the Jets offense was the number of big weapons he had at his
disposal. Testaverde, Wayne Chrebet, Keyshawn Johnson, Curtis
Martin. Now two of them, Testaverde and Chrebet (who broke his foot
in an exhibition game, also without being hit), are gone. Johnson
was brilliant in defeat, making one spectacular play after another,
but will now see double coverage everywhere he goes.
</P>
<P>
   Next week the Jets go on the road to play Buffalo, which was
surprised by the Colts Sunday in Indianapolis. New York could
easily start the season 0-2. That happened last season, and
Parcells got the Jets to the AFC Championship Game. But he had
Vinny.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells also lost the first two games in his last season with
New England, when the Patriots went to the Super Bowl. But he had
Drew.
</P>
<P>
   This time there is no one at his disposal who can throw the ball
like either of those guys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
