r s BC-BBO-DIAMONDS-MONEY-TE     09-13 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DIAMONDS-MONEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS FIND OUT WHAT MONEY CAN BUY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Promise Keepers are coming to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The men's religious organization started by former Colorado
football coach Bill McCartney has booked Bank One Ballpark on Oct.
22-23 for the final stop on their latest nationwide tour. The
stadium is expected to be filled both days, although there's no
word yet on how they'll utilize the swimming pool beyond the
right-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one problem. The World Series is scheduled to open
on Oct. 22, a Saturday, in the National League city, putting
Promise Keepers on a collision course with the Arizona
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll deal with it when it becomes an issue,'' stadium booking
manager Charles Johnston said. ``But no one in the Promise Keepers
organization thinks it's going to be an issue, because they don't
think the Diamondbacks are going to go to the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Promise Keepers, with a much more important
agenda on their minds, haven't been keeping up with the latest
trend in sports. There was a time when it was completely
unreasonable to expect a second-year expansion team to make the
playoffs, much less go all the way to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. All that is needed is a little faith, a little hope
and a lot of money. This is the sports era of instant
gratification: If an owner can afford to buy himself a pennant,
there is nothing in the way to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Huizenga did it with the Florida Marlins in 1997, and
Jerry Colangelo is doing it with the Diamondbacks. With less than
three weeks to go in the season, the Diamondbacks, in their second
season of existence, have a seven-game lead in the National League
West and, barring a complete collapse, have all but wrapped up a
division title.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a record for an expansion team making the playoffs.
The Colorado Rockies snuck in as a wild-card team in 1995, their
third season in existence.
</P>
<P>
   But as Colangelo pointed out last week, ``The Rockies didn't win
their division. We're in a position not only to get there, but win
our division. We have an opportunity to make history.''
</P>
<P>
   The price has been steep but Colangelo has never wavered, even
when his fellow owners demanded a $130 million franchise fee. When
Travis Lee, the second overall pick in the 1996 draft, was made a
free agent after the Minnesota Twins failed to offer him a
contract, the Diamondbacks stepped in and signed him for a
staggering $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   That was just the start. Baseball officials around the country
were further appalled when the Diamondbacks, before the 1998
season, signed shortstop Jay Bell to a five-year, $34 million deal
and gave third baseman Matt Williams a five-year, $45 million
extension.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks then paid $118.9 million this off-season for
free-agent pitchers Randy Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre, Greg Swindell
and Armando Reynoso, center fielder Steve Finley and first baseman
Greg Colbrunn.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching was most important, and adding the four free agents to
a staff that already included Andy Benes, Omar Daal and Brian
Anderson caught people's attention. Suddenly, the Diamondbacks had
a staff to compete with the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching is the No. 1 ingredient, and this team has it,''
Finley said. ``When you've got a rotation like ours, especially
with Randy Johnson leading it, your goal is to make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrewd trades also have helped, especially on offense. They
dealt fifth outfielder Karim Garcia to the Detroit Tigers for Luis
Gonzalez, who is third in the league in hitting, and they got Tony
Womack from the Pittsburgh Pirates for two minor-leaguers, thus
solving their leadoff problems. Womack leads the league with 64
stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks scored 667 runs last season, fourth-fewest in
the National League. But, because of the trades and because
Williams and Bell are enjoying their best seasons ever, the
Diamondbacks are on pace to score 884 runs this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the reasons we are where we are,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest trade was made on July 9 when the
Diamondbacks acquired closer Matt Mantei from the Florida Marlins
for pitchers Vladimir Nunez and Brad Penney, reinforcing the
Diamondbacks' one troubled spot. They were 47-40 on the day the
trade was made and 36-17 since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where would we be if we had Matt Mantei all year?'' Colangelo
said. ``When you are close and you can smell it, you better go for
it. You just don't know when the opportunity is going to come
again. My input _ we go now.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said the Diamondbacks are in this for the long run and
won't be another one-year wonder like the Marlins. They already
have the fan support, averaging 37,577 fans a game, fourth in the
National League.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks are hoping for a long run that includes many
Octobers with full stands, and not just for late-month Promise
Keepers rallies.
\Nsubheds:Evaluating the expansion teams \Nsubheds:Anaheim Angels
1st season: 1961. 1st title: 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: The Angels did well in the first expansion
and had some good young players. But they never could win with them
and eventually went heavy for free agents. \Nsubheds:Texas Rangers
1st season: 1961. 1st title: 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: This organization was in total chaos when
they were the Washington Senators, with absolutely no discernible
plan at all. It was a long climb to respectability once they got to
Texas in 1972. \Nsubheds:New York Mets
1st season: 1962. 1st title: 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: The Mets were a joke when they first
started, but they put together an outstanding farm system in the
1960s. That brought about a miracle in 1969. \Nsubheds:Houston
Astros
1st season: 1962. 1st title: 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: The Astros also landed some decent young
players early, and they've been respectable for much of their 38
seasons. But they've never had the financial power to finish the
job. \Nsubheds:Montreal Expos
1st season: 1969. 1st title: 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: The Expos went for veterans in the expansion
draft and tried to be contender early. They failed, but by the
mid-'70s, they had put together a farm system that remains one of
the most productive in baseball. \Nsubheds:San Diego Padres
1st season: 1969. 1st title: 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: They went for young players and did a
terrible job. Then they tried to buy players and weren't very good
at that. \Nsubheds:Kansas City Royals
1st season: 1969. 1st title: 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: They went young from the start and did it
right, needing only eight seasons to win their first division
title. They were a model franchise until owner Ewing Kauffman died.
\Nsubheds:Milwaukee Brewers
1st season: 1969. 1st title: 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: They started as the Seattle Pilots and went
with too many veterans early. The franchise turned the corner in
1978 when Harry Dalton became general manager and he built a strong
farm system. \Nsubheds:Toronto Blue Jays
1st season: 1977. 1st title: 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: The best expansion franchise ever because
Pat Gillick did it right from the start, building up an impressive
farm system. They won 89 games in 1983 and remained competitive
until the 1994-95 strike crushed their attendance.
\Nsubheds:Seattle Mariners
1st season: 1977. 1st title: 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: They went with young players early, but bad
ownership doomed the franchise from the start. Everything started
to change on June 2, 1987, when they drafted Ken Griffey Jr.
\Nsubheds:Florida Marlins
1st season: 1993. 1st title: 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: They were going nice and slow until owner
Wayne Huizenga decided to splurge in 1997. Then they dismantled and
started over again, basically as a second expansion franchise.
\Nsubheds:Colorado Rockies
1st season: 1993. 1st title: none.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: Their geography has set the rules. All
hitting, no pitching. They won the wild card in 1995 with their
offense. They're trying to develop sinkerball pitchers, but are
having limited success. \Nsubheds:Tampa Bay Devil Rays
1st season: 1998. 1st title: none.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: They went hard on some free agents without
any real success. The farm system is being developed properly.
\Nsubheds:Arizona Diamondbacks
1st season: 1998. 1st title: none.
</P>
<P>
   Original blueprint: Spend money. Owner Jerry Colangelo came out
with his wallet wide open and hasn't slowed up yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
