<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIES LEAVE JETS LICKING THEIR WOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ New York Jets quarterback Vinny
Testaverde suffered a season-ending rupture of his left Achilles'
tendon with no one within five feet of him. Running back Leon
Johnson tore the anterior cruciate and medial colateral ligaments
in his left knee; he also is out for the season. Defensive tackle
Jason Ferguson suffered a sprained right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   And, for two minutes, tight end Eric Green couldn't feel a
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole body went numb. I couldn't feel my legs, my arms. It
was a scary feeling,'' said Green, who suffered a neck injury
following a head-first hit in Sunday's 30-28 loss to the Patriots.
He returned to action and will be evaluated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   New England suffered injuries as well. Tackle Zefross Moss
sprained his left ankle, guard Heath Irwin suffered a right knee
sprain, and running back Lamont Warren had a right thigh contusion.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots' injuries paled in comparison to those of the
Jets, who lost not only one of their leaders in Testaverde but
another key player in Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   That meant within hours all the talk about the team making it to
their first Super Bowl since 1969 shifted to whether the team could
salvage the season amid an onslaught of misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see where we're at,'' said Jets coach Bill Parcells.
``Johnson and Testaverde are gone for the year. That's two of our
big losses, two guys that are productive offensive players.''
</P>
<P>
   It marks the first time Testaverde will miss a game since 1997,
when a knee strain kept him out of the last three weeks of the
season. Sunday's injury came after he took a couple of steps
forward to pounce on a Curtis Martin fumble then went to the turf,
wincing in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' said Martin, the former Patriot.
``I got the ball and I believe (Patriots defensive lineman Willie)
McGinest stripped it, and I fell on it. I looked up and I could see
that Vinny was down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You usually don't see him lying there. If he falls down, he
just gets right up. I said, `Come on, Vinny.' When see him lying
there like that, you know it's serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde was helped off the field and carried via a cart out
of the arena, a towel draped over his head. He was scheduled to be
operated on Sunday night at Lenox Hill Hospital in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's life in the big city,'' said Parcells, who initially
brought in Tom Tupa to replace Testaverde but later subbed Rick
Mirer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very humbling game. It's a game that can turn very
quickly. We have 15 games to go, and we have to figure out how to
approach those and keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Jets took the injuries with the same mindset.
Linebacker Bryan Cox said the team has enough players to make up
for the losses and praised his teammates for almost winning the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure guys are going to make it. Just as you were hooping
it up, `Super Bowl, Super Bowl,' you're going to say, `We're dead,
we're dead, we're dead,' '' he said. ``The bottom line is we still
have to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Green reminded one and all that last year's team lost its first
two games and came back to make it to the AFC Championship Game. He
did add, however, that the NFL should consider switching to a
surface other than artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want us to be around for a great period of time, they
definitely should do something about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson, who had a field day (8 catches
for 194 yards), didn't take the injuries as well.
</P>
<P>
   He began his postgame press conference calmly. Then, when asked
about losing Testaverde, one of the team's most durable players,
for the season, he whispered an expletive then said, ``What can you
do? You can't do anything. Nothing. You can't do (expletive). We
couldn't (expletive) throw. We were throwing interceptions. Man,
this is just . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson then slammed his fists on the podium and stormed out of
the interview room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
