<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION FIT TO BE TIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Argentine writer Dante Panzeri described
soccer's attraction as ``La Dinamica de lo Impensado'' _ the
dynamic of the unexpected _ in his book published in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   So many imponderable occurrences, the ball played hundreds and
hundreds of times, players interacting, each decision accompanied
by dozens of options, everyone trying to tame the ball and bring a
sense of order to the chaos through the sheer force of their
intelligence and skill.
</P>
<P>
   When the stakes are high and the teams are low in the standings,
pragmatism takes precedence over beauty. But so many things can
happen that an analysis of the game is incomplete without an
explanation of most of them.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, after the Revolution and Miami Fusion played to a
1-1 regulation-time tie, the story of the game Saturday night
became the post-match shootout. Revolution goalkeeper Jeff Causey
was ejected by referee Ricardo Valenzuela for taking down Miami's
Welton, and was replaced by striker Joe-Max Moore in what became a
parody of a gimmick. The Fusion won the shootout, 3-2, and moved 1
point ahead of the Revolution in the battle for the final playoff
spot in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, more enticing and important questions went
unanswered, as the shootout took precedence over the 90 minutes of
drama.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Mike Burns and Brian Dunseth switch positions after
Miami's goal? How bad was Ivan McKinley's concussion and will he be
in condition to make his international debut for South Africa this
week? Is Imad Baba prepared to be thrown head-first into a playoff
race after missing six months with a groin and hip injury? Why did
Paulo Dos Santos look like an accomplished veteran when he was in
central midfield, and why did he and John Harkes switch roles
midway through the second half? Was Leonel Alvarez so upset to have
been replaced that he felt compelled to run straight to the locker
room? How could Joe-Max Moore flub such great chances? Was Giovanni
Savarese offside on what appeared to be the winning goal?
</P>
<P>
   Why did the role of Miami's Edwin Gorter devolve from captain of
the team to substitute? What compelled Gorter to spike Mario Gori
in the second half? Is Miami going to permanently switch to a 4-4-2
alignment? Since Welton was evicted by the Revolution, why have
they gone seven successive games without defeating his team in
regulation time? Is Eric Wynalda prepared to be thrown head-first
into a playoff race after missing six months with a knee injury? Is
Longmeadow's Jay Heaps disappointed that he did not play for the US
against Jamaica last week and is he suited to midfield for Miami?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has been in the mood to examine these questions since the
shootout, after which player-coach Walter Zenga and Moore clashed
with security guards. The theme has been that the Revolution felt
unjustly treated in the shootout, and this will continue until
attention turns to Saturday's opponent, the Columbus Crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything can happen in soccer,'' assistant coach Giuseppe
Galderisi said. ``But let us lose because we made a mistake or
because they were better than us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy with the team. Maybe if we win this game we have a
good chance to qualify for the playoffs, but we are still in the
right frame of mind and we kept our confidence high. We didn't lose
and we are still a good team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
