u s BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      09-13 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH WEEK AT POLLS FOR SEMINOLES, NITTANY LIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Florida State barely beats Georgia Tech. Penn State
edges Pittsburgh. Naturally, both were punished this week by the
pollsters, losing some votes.
</P>
<P>
   It's only fair. Tennessee lost three first-place votes a couple
of weeks ago and the Volunteers didn't even play.
</P>
<P>
   It's only September, and poll watching already has started in
earnest.
</P>
<P>
   For those lucky enough to see it (not in Boston without a dish
or a pay-per-view package), Florida State and Georgia Tech staged a
classic, with FSU coming out a 41-35 winner.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Florida State isn't as good as people thought. The
Seminoles are every bit as good, but they have set the bar so high
that a 6-point win over a tough opponent is not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   What people fail to realize is that Tech may very well be a
great team as well. And that quarterback Joe Hamilton has vaulted
into the Heisman race after an astonishing (22 of 25 for 387 yards
and four touchdowns) effort. Included in that performance was a
streak in which Hamilton, who had been knocked out of the last two
games against the Seminoles, completed his last 14 passes as the
Yelllow Jackets desperately tried to pull off the upset of the
early season.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the Doug Flutie-Bernie Kosar battle of 1984 in the
Miami-Boston College ``Hail Mary'' game has the state of Florida
witnessed such as Saturday night's battle.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton wasn't the only one who established himself in the
Heisman race. All Florida State's Peter Warrick did was catch a
touchdown pass, run for another score, and gain 167 yards in total
offense as FSU extended its home unbeaten streak to 42.
</P>
<P>
   Is FSU as good as most observers think? Maybe not. But by
outlasting Georgia Tech in a true gut-check game, the Seminoles
proved they can trade shots with the best teams around and still
finish on top.
</P>
<P>
   And that may be as true a sign of a champion as any one-sided
win over East Cupcake State.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Penn State, there also probably are mutterings by some
Nittany Lion bandwagoners who feel their team is invincible.
</P>
<P>
   Shed no tears for the Lions over their 20-17 win over
Pittsburgh. Truth be told, Penn State coach Joe Paterno is not all
that disappointed, despite the votes it will cost his team this
week. With two blowouts in a row, the Lions were getting a little
cocky going into next week's game against Miami. Pittsburgh was a
reality check.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew a game like this would come for us because things have
come so easy for us,'' said Paterno. ``You've got to be able to win
a game like this if you've got aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alabama might not be in anyone's national title picture, but the
Tide does know how to get off to a good start. With Saturday's
37-10 win over Houston, the Tide is 2-0 for the eighth consecutive
season. Of course, one could argue that the Tide doesn't generally
extend itself in its nonconference games. This year's first two
victims were Vanderbilt and Houston . . . Ron Dayne continues to
pile up yards _ he had 158 in Wisconsin's 50-10 win over Ball State
_ but until he puts up those numbers against what people consider
more serious Big Ten competition, his Heisman chances will be slim
at best . . . Don't expect Alabama-Birmingham to criticize the way
Virginia Tech plays. UAB was limited to 63 yards in total offense
in Saturday's 31-10 loss to the Hokies. In three games, Tech has
outscored UAB, 109-10 . . . Nebraska backup QB Eric Crouch is
trying to win his battle with starter Bobby Newcombe with his
versatility. In Saturday's 45-0 win over California, Crouch came in
and ran for a touchdown, passed for a touchdown, and caught a
touchdown pass, becoming the first Nebraska player since Johnny
Rodgers in 1971 to accomplish that. All told, Crouch scored three
TDs and passed for one . . . Someone needs to give Notre Dame a
lesson in time management. For the second straight week, the Irish
were not so much beaten on the field but beaten by the clock as
time expired in the throes of a final Irish drive. In Saturday's
28-23 loss to Purdue, time ran out with Jarious Jackson trying to
run a final play inside the Boilermakers 10. It was just like last
week, when the Irish lost to Michigan in the final seconds, 26-22.
Part of the problem is that the Irish offense seems to take its
time coming out of the huddle in crucial situations. Now they have
two losses and a game coming up against unbeaten Michigan State . .
. Hmmm. Danny Ford gets inducted into the Clemson Hall of Fame and
the Tigers upset Virginia. The coach of the Tigers' 1981 national
championship team, who was honored at Death Valley for the first
time in 10 years, might be feted every week if the Tigers can keep
pulling off upsets like that . . . Don't look now, but college
football might have another great passing combination ready to move
into prime time _ Georgia QB Quincy Carter and wide receiver
Terrence Edwards, who had seven catches for 90 yards, including a
47-yard TD pass from Carter. All of which contributed to Georgia's
24-9 win over winless South Carolina and coach Lou Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florida's pattern for the season seems to be developing nicely.
The Gators may not have the best defense around, but few, if any
teams are going to outscore them. The Gators crushed Central
Florida, 58-27, on Saturday, a result similiar to the Gators' 55-26
win over Western Michigan last weekend. Tennessee looms next week
in what shapes up as the Southeastern Conference game of the year.
In two games, Florida's offense has produced 1,193 yards . . . Glad
to see Temple is off to its usual start. Two games, two losses, and
the Owls have yet to score. Kansas State beat them, 40-0, a week
after Temple's 6-0 loss to Maryland . . . Ronald Curry, who has yet
to decide if he wants to play basketball or football full time at
North Carolina, continues to gather evidence that he may be what
the scouts said he was coming out of high school: a good basketball
player, but a great QB. Curry ran for a TD and passed for 241 yards
and two more scores in the Heels' 42-30 win over Indiana . . . Give
credit to Division 1-AA UConn for hanging with 1-A Kentucky through
three quarters before getting blown out by the Wildcats in the
weekend's other ``basketball'' matchup . . . UMass's 34-19 victory
over New Hampshire proves how good a coach Mark Whipple is. The
Minutemen have only marginally beter talent than New Hampshire, but
Whipple, who is surely on a fast track to a 1-A job next season if
UMass comes close to repeating its championship campaign of a year
ago, and his staff broke down the UNH defenses, calling plays
throughout the day that pounced on every UNH weakness or breakdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
