<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STIGMATA' TOPS LIST; OH, THE HORROR!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The supernatural continued to hold sway at the
nation's multiplexes as ``Stigmata'' edged out ``The Sixth Sense''
with a better-than-expected $18.5 million at 2,899 theaters during
the Friday-Sunday period in the first weekend following the
record-setting summer, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stigmata,'' MGM's tale of demonic possession with echoes of
``The Exorcist,'' pulled the plug on the five-week winning streak
by ``The Sixth Sense'' by taking advantage of the sizzling market
for horror movies. ``It was the right movie at the right time,''
said industry tracker Arthur Rockwell, a former MGM executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stigmata,'' with a reported $30 million budget, became the
fifth horror film in the past two months to meet or exceed
forecasts following ``The Blair Witch Project,'' ``The Haunting,''
``Deep Blue Sea'' and ``The Sixth Sense.'' The quintet has grossed
about $515 million; ``Stigmata'' is likely to wind up its domestic
run with $60 million, according to Robert Bucksbaum, president of
the Reel Source tracking service.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is that these horror films don't cannibalize
each other,'' Bucksbaum said. ``They play off each other so when
one sells out at a multiplex, people are likely to go see the other
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum also credited long-suffering MGM -- which has scored
its first box office victory since 1996's ``The Birdcage'' -- with
releasing an attention-grabbing trailer featuring lead actress
Patricia Arquette in the throes of a takeover by evil spirits.
``Everyone is going to see these movies right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing the top spot, Disney's ``Sixth Sense'' continued
to post impressive results with $17 million at 2,782 theaters, down
only 25 percent from the previous Friday-Sunday period, to push its
overall take to $198.2 million. The tale of a haunted 8-year-old
boy replaced ``Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade'' for 29th place
on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Horror-hungry moviegoers also offered moderate support to
Artisan's opening of ``Stir of Echoes,'' which finished a distant
third with $6.2 million at 1,888 theaters. ``Echoes,'' a murder
mystery with Kevin Bacon's character acquiring paranormal powers,
gave the top three films an impressive 55 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't recall a time when three films that were this similar
have done this well,'' Bucksbaum noted.
</P>
<P>
   The trio of chillers lifted overall box office to $75 million,
or 37 percent up from the same weekend last year when ``Rounders''
led with $8.5 million. They also kept up Hollywood's hot streak,
with year-to-date grosses now topping $5.1 billion to lead the same
period of 1998 by about 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is normally one of the slowest weekends of the year since
there's so much attention on going back to school,'' Rockwell
noted. ``The aggressive demand for product by audiences continues
to be phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Holdovers took the remaining slots in the top 10, led by a
continued solid performance from Paramount's ``Runaway Bride'' with
$3.9 million at 2,773 theaters in its seventh weekend. That pulled
the 45-day ``Bride'' total to $140.5 million, replacing ``Deep
Impact'' as the 82nd-highest domestic grosser of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's fifth weekend of ``Bowfinger'' followed in fifth
with $3.7 million at 2,452 screens to top $60 million overall while
Disney's third weekend of ``The 13th Warrior'' continued to fade
with $2.9 million at 2,283 locations. MGM's sixth weekend of ``The
Thomas Crown Affair'' came in seventh with $2.8 million at 1,849
theaters to pull it past $61 million overall.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros., which suffered through a disappointing summer,
took the next two spots with its fourth weekend of ``Mickey Blue
Eyes'' with $2.3 million at 1,975 theaters and its second weekend
of ``Chill Factor'' with $1.9 million at 2,558 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Artisan's ninth weekend of ``The Blair Witch Project,'' a key
factor in triggering the late-summer surge in moviegoing, finished
10th with $1.6 million at 1,933 theaters to push its overall total
to $136.2 million. The $35,000 project has become the 88th-highest
grosser of all time, replacing ``Godzilla,'' which carried a price
tag of well over $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's third weekend of ``In Too Deep'' came in 11th with
$1.3 million at 641 theaters, followed by its second weekend of
``Outside Providence'' with $1.2 million at 1,052 locations. They
and several other holdovers finished ahead of the debut of romantic
comedy ``Love Stinks,'' starring French Stewart and Tyra Banks,
with a deadly $950,000 at 1,325 theaters in the first release from
Independent Artists.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend also saw Universal generate strong response from
sneak Saturday screenings its romance-drama ``For the Love of the
Game,'' starring Kevin Costner as an aging baseball pitcher. More
than 80 percent of the shows sold out and 94 percent of viewers
polled ranked ``Game,'' which will open Friday at 2,800 theaters,
as ``excellent'' or ``very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony also held sneak screenings Saturday of ``Blue Streak,'' its
Martin Lawrence action-comedy which also opens Friday. Bucksbaum
said both new entries should perform well, along with Paramount's
revenge-drama ``Double Jeopardy'' on Sept. 24 and Warner's Gulf War
action project ``Three Kings'' on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studios are going to be offering a lot of diversity this
fall,'' he noted. ``They saw that `Rush Hour' and `The Waterboy'
did very well last fall in part because they were so different from
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Final results for the Friday-Sunday period will be released
today.
</P>
<P>
   TOP MOVIES!off! &QL; 
Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at North American
theaters: &QL; 
1. ``Stigmata,'' $18.5 million. &QL; 
2. ``The Sixth Sense,'' $17 million. &QL; 
3. ``Stir of Echoes,'' $6.2 million. &QL; 
4. ``Runaway Bride,'' $3.9 million. &QL; 
5. ``Bowfinger,'' $3.7 million. &QL; 
6. ``The 13th Warrior,'' $2.9 million. &QL; 
7. ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' $2.8 million. &QL; 
8. ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' $2.3 million. &QL; 
9. ``Chill Factor,'' $1.9 million. &QL; 
10. ``The Blair Witch Project,'' $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 0140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
