<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9712 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-STEELERS-BROWNS-H     09-13 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STEELERS-BROWNS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CLEVELAND _ Although they had the first pick in the NFL draft, were
given extra draft choices and took advantage of the salary cap to
load up with veterans who had started for other teams, the new
Cleveland Browns looked like just another horrendous expansion team
against the Pittsburgh Steelers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because Art Modell moved the old Browns to Baltimore and renamed
them the Ravens, Cleveland was forced to endure three seasons
without the NFL. When the new Browns were reborn Sunday night in
their new stadium before a national television audience, they
looked like the worst team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Steelers ruined the Browns' coming-out party with
a 43-0 victory before 73,138 fans who barked like Dawgs for about
one quarter, then howled at the moon over the beating they absorbed
from Pittsburgh, which always has been Cleveland's most bitter
rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I'm impressed with our performance, but I can't get too
caught up in it because it's only one game,'' Steelers coach Bill
Cowher said. ``We need to see what happens over the long haul, but
it is hard to find fault with anything tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers dominated the Browns in every possible way. They
generated 460 yards and limited the Browns to 40. Cleveland had
only nine yards rushing and two first downs, none in the second
half. The Browns failed to convert a third-down situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played very poorly,'' Browns coach Chris Palmer
said. ``Defensively, we couldn't get them off the field.
Offensively, we couldn't stay on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one game, but we really have no place to go but
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Under new offensive coordinator Kevin Gilbride, Pittsburgh
scored five offensive touchdowns. It didn't score that many in any
game last season.
</P>
<P>
   After being stopped on fourth down on their first series, the
Steelers scored on their next eight possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make a lot of big plays, but in terms of
consistency, we played about as well as you can,'' Gilbride said.
``Our guys needed something like this to feel good about
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbride and quarterback Kordell Stewart got off to a successful
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did some things to take advantage of Kordell's
athleticism,'' Gilbride said. ``We wanted to get him on the
perimeter because it opened things up in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart finished 15-of-23 passing for 173 yards and a touchdown.
He was not intercepted. He also ran six times for 33 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I like to play my first game,'' Stewart said.
``I had to make a lot of decisions. He (Gilbride) was calling plays
to make me comfortable, and he did a great job. There's still more
to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers ran for 213 yards, which enabled them to control
the ball for 47 minutes, 49 seconds to Cleveland's 12:11. Jerome
Bettis, who sat out the preseason after undergoing arthroscopic
knee surgery, led the team with 89 yards on 18 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the game went on, I got the rust off,'' Bettis said.
``Coach Gilbride gave us every opportunity to succeed. He called a
great game. Give him a lot of credit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers dominated from start to finish. Steelers strong
safety Chris Oldham intercepted quarterback Ty Detmer to put
Pittsburgh in position for its first touchdown. Stewart rolled to
his right and just made it inside the goal line. Kris Brown kicked
the extra point for the 7-0 lead with 5:16 left in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Brown added field goals of 18 and 28 yards in the first half.
Pittsburgh's other first-half TD came on Stewart's five-yard
scoring pass to running back Richard Huntley.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, the Steelers kept up the pressure on both
sides of the football. On their first series, they went 76 yards on
14 plays. Huntley scored on a three-yard run. Brown's extra-point
attempt was blocked, leaving Pittsburgh with a 26-0 lead with 5:38
left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   After Brown kicked a 19-yard field goal to give Pittsburgh a
29-0 lead early in the fourth period, Stewart went to the bench and
was replaced by veteran backup Mike Tomczak.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't seem to matter who played quarterback for the Steelers
in this game. Even Mark Malone or Todd Blackledge could have put
points on the board against the overmatched Browns.
</P>
<P>
   After Brown's field goal, the Browns fumbled the kickoff at
their 21. On the first play, Tomczak threw a 21-yard scoring pass
to Huntley, who gained his third touchdown. Brown's extra point
made it 36-0.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, there was 10:38 left in the game. Quarterback Tim
Couch, the first pick in the draft, entered the game in place of
Detmer.
</P>
<P>
   Couch, the franchise quarterback, will remember his first pass
because it was intercepted by free safety Scott Shields. The
interception led to Tomczak's one-yard touchdown pass to receiver
Hines Ward with 6:28 left.
</P>
<P>
   And at that point, Cowher cleared his bench.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
