</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPOTENT-IRAQI-FOES-ECONOMIST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHATEVER HAPPENED TO THE IRAQI OPPOSITION?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 475-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 11 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever happened to the Iraqi opposition? Last year, the
American Congress passed a law granting $97 million-worth of
military equipment to groups trying to topple Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   The government duly named seven factions worthy of such
largesse, and even persuaded them to coalesce into a newly
revitalized umbrella group, the Iraqi National Congress (INC).
</P>
<P>
   In February, the INC announced that its parliament-in-exile
would meet in April for the first time in seven years.
Inexplicably, the date slipped to July. July came and went without
a peep from the INC, not even a new date for a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   More embarrassing still, a scheme to hold the session in the
autonomous Kurdish areas of northern Iraq was abandoned when
America said it could not guarantee the safety of the participants.
</P>
<P>
   Not a penny of the $97 million has yet reached the opposition _
and when it does, America says, it will come in the form of office
supplies, not the arms that were promised.
</P>
<P>
   Some defiant INC members insist the meeting should nonetheless
go ahead in Kurdistan. But the local Kurdish authorities are
lukewarm. Even if the session is eventually held, events so far
show that America is not serious about helping the Iraqi
opposition. That, at least, is what INC figures say.
</P>
<P>
   n theory, of course, America would be delighted for the INC to
have a go at Hussein. But in practice the administration does not
think the group up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting in northern Iraq, or an attack launched from there,
might, the Americans fear, draw them into an ill-conceived and
embarrassing military adventure.
</P>
<P>
   The memory of 1996, when Hussein's troops overran the Kurdish
capital, Arbil, and wiped out both INC and CIA staff there, lingers
on. But whereas the American government has doubts about bold
initiatives, Congress chafes at inaction.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats have complained about the effects of nine
years of United Nations sanctions on Iraq and, in defiance of the
State Department, have sent representatives to Baghdad to
investigate. Others are concerned too.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials are frustrated because humanitarian aid is
hampered by bureaucratic delays by both America and Iraq. The pope
has expressed concern and promised a high-profile visit to Iraq
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   There are also those, including many in Congress, who want to
get tough with Hussein. The question is how. One idea is to start a
war-crimes investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Austrian authorities were arresting a Serb suspect
last month, they were also playing host to Hussein's deputy, Izzat
Ibrahim al-Douri, before letting him go home safely to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   And would more military action be effective? America has
launched almost as many air raids against Iraq this year as were
launched against Serbia by NATO. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
