 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Tornadoes are almost unheard of in Salt Lake
City, but in August one struck right in the middle of the Outdoor
Retailers Summer Market.
</P>
<P>
   It was the talk of the show _ until, that is, the sellers of
camping gear and climbing boots began to consider their other
problems. Not all of these are immediately apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for goods for hiking, camping, mountaineering and the
like remains strong, with sales worth about $5.5 billion a year.
The green inclinations of baby-boomers, their growing spending
power and their yen to turn vacations into something between a
forced march and a spiritual retreat, have been the making of an
industry that barely existed 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Backpacks at $400, hiking boots at $250, seaworthy kayaks at
$2,000, are all snapped up.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, says Lee Fromson, a vice-president with Cascade
Designs in Seattle which specializes in outside sleeping equipment,
anyone getting into this sector could expect their business to grow
by 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   But times are changing. For many outdoor-gear sellers, sales are
flat _ or worse.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, baby-boomers are getting older. They are no longer
so eager to tote a 50-pound pack for a week in the Tetons, nor
hoist themselves up icy Mount Rainier in Microsoft's backyard (Al
Gore's recent ascent of that peak notwithstanding).
</P>
<P>
   Many sellers of the ponderous recreational vehicles seen
lumbering down the interstates during the summer now report that
their fastest-growing market consists of people between 35 and 50
who have finally hung up their boots.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of outdoor equipment are aging, too, and find it hard
to fathom what younger people want.
</P>
<P>
   There are other challenges. At the Salt Lake City show, there
was hardly a black or brown face in sight: outdoor sport remains a
white enclave, meaning that makers of outdoor equipment are simply
ignored by a huge and growing portion of the population.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is proving a formidable competitor, not only
because most outdoor-gear makers run small businesses that lack the
know-how or financing to launch websites, but because surfing the
Net takes up leisure time that used to be spent hiking or biking.
</P>
<P>
   Even the strong economy works against the outdoors industry,
which has found that people who hike in Montana in hard times would
rather lounge in Italy once they have money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some in the industry are optimistic. Certain activities,
notably kayaking and rock climbing, are proving popular with young
enthusiasts and are showing strong sales growth.
</P>
<P>
   Several large clothing and investment companies are snapping up
distressed outdoor-gear makers with strong brand names and applying
up-to-date stock-keeping, manufacturing and marketing techniques.
</P>
<P>
   And there is hope that today's teenagers, many of whom are
fanatically green, will adopt the hobbies that their parents once
embraced. Until then, equipment makers can only pray that their
latest ultra-light tent or load-lightening pack will put some
spring into the steps of grey-haired hikers _ and dollars into
tills. &QL; 
