<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-MISS-DELTA-ECONOMIST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VEGAS-ON-THE-MISSISSIPPI: CASINO HEAVEN RESCUES DELTA HELLHOLE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: MISS., TENN., Southern-State Editors)   (This excellent 675-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 11 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUNICA, MISS. _ What a shame Elvis did not live to see it.
Thirty miles from Graceland a new Las Vegas has sprouted in the
Delta, and lights blaze along the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   Times have certainly changed. In 1990, Tunica County was
officially listed by the Census Bureau as the poorest county in the
United States, a place famous mostly for open-ditch sewers and
clapped-out cars rusting in cotton fields.
</P>
<P>
   Now thousands of visitors descend every day, and think it
heaven. Last year, Tunica's casinos grossed a record $2 billion in
gaming revenues. Taxes on that revenue generated more than $126
million for the county between December 1992 and the end of 1998,
and sales taxes rose by $213.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Mississippi, which takes 8 percent of the casinos'
gross revenues, received more than $250 million in taxes.
Unemployment is almost nonexistent in Tunica, and income per head
has tripled.
</P>
<P>
   Once, the key to prosperity was to leave the South for the
north. Now the flow has reversed. Casino workers from Chicago,
Atlantic City and even abroad descend on the Delta to deal cards
and serve drinks in gambling dens built to resemble Irish castles
or Southern antebellum mansions.
</P>
<P>
   Tunica is now the fifth most profitable gambling area in the
country, outranked only by the Las Vegas Strip, Atlantic City, the
Foxwoods complex in Connecticut and a clutch of casinos close to
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi legalized casino gambling in 1992. As in several
other states, the legislation required the casinos to float on
water.
</P>
<P>
   But whereas the other states allowed gambling only on
riverboats, Mississippi added an ingenious loophole that let
gambling halls be constructed on barges that float in moats. This
means that casinos can spring up further away from rivers, and with
giant fountains playing on every side.
</P>
<P>
   When the casinos first opened, visitors had a choice of 20
hotels in all of Tunica County. Today there are more than 6,000
hotel rooms, and on most nights most of them are filled. The
31-story Gold Strike Casino Hotel is the tallest building in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Although most visitors still arrive by bus, the tiny airport is
being upgraded with a $32 million extension to the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Casinos in Tunica, as in most places, are keen to lure families
to stay an extra day and spend their winnings at golf courses,
amusement parks and theatres. The next wave of development is
therefore in this direction.
</P>
<P>
   The newly opened Isle of Capri casino plans to build two Wayne
Newton theatres, where the ex-lounge lizard and Las Vegas superstar
will perform several nights each year.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not just classic Vegas names that jet into Tunica now.
Duran Duran (to be slightly more up-to-date) recently played to a
sellout crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Only the neighbors are sulking. Last year, fewer tourists than
usual went to Beale Street in Memphis, Tenn., one of the
birthplaces of the blues, and this was widely blamed on the fact
that nearby Tunica is awash in cheap liquor and discounted motel
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Memphis's Hard Rock Cafe, which opened only a year ago, no
longer even offers live music, citing tough competition from Tunica
to lure popular bands.
</P>
<P>
   And Tunica is only just starting to dream about the extravagant
things it can do. This summer, the city began constructing an $18.5
million exhibition center, covering 132,000 square feet (12,260
square meters), for trade shows, rodeos, car shows, concerts,
banquets, tractor-pulls and other attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, when Mississippi was fighting the demonic aspects
of high-stakes gambling in its state legislature, no one could have
foreseen the impact the industry would have on the poorest part of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Now, seven years later, there are few doubters left. Like it or
not, Tunica was sick of being poor. With wise investment, it hopes
it will never go hungry again. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
