<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9780 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n BC-EMMY-AWARDS-2TAKES-LA     09-13 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMY-AWARDS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIAR FACES TAKE TOP ACTING AWARDS, BUT THERE'S A NEW KING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY VALERIE KUKLENSKI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The 51st annual Emmy Awards on Sunday night belong
to David E. Kelley _ the critics' favorite claimed top Drama Series
for ABC's ``The Practice'' and best Comedy Series for Fox's ``Ally
McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, the hands-on head writer and executive producer for both
shows, was stunned by the back-to-back honors, the ninth and 10th
Emmys of his career. It was the first time a producer has won both
categories the same year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can see from the looks on our faces we're a little
surprised, but we'll take it,'' Kelley said, accepting the second
consecutive drama Emmy for ``The Practice.'' Then in a variation on
Camryn Manheim's speech last year, he added, ``This is for all the
underdogs,'' referring to beating out the favorite, HBO's ``The
Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, seconds later, when ``Ally McBeal'' won, Kelley was back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said backstage you gotta go back up, and I thought there
had been a mistake (and that) `The Sopranos' won best drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley apparently was not alone in that perception.
</P>
<P>
   HBO, however, scored well overall, taking the most of any
network _ seven awards Sunday and 23 overall, including those from
earlier ceremonies. NBC won a total of 17, ABC 13, CBS 11, Fox 7,
A&AMP;E 5, PBS 4, WB 2, UPN 2 and Showtime 1.
</P>
<P>
   But the humor-tinged mob drama ``The Sopranos'' won only two of
Sunday's categories: lead actress in a drama series for Edie Falco
and writing for its ``College'' episode, by James Manos Jr. and
David Chase. It won two others in the pretelecast event.
</P>
<P>
   The series, which led with 16 nominations, was a critical hit
and a personal viewing favorite of many in the industry. In fact,
Falco drew one of the loudest ovations of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the 51st awards echoed past ceremonies. In
addition to ``The Practice,'' repeat winners included Helen Hunt of
``Mad About You,'' Dennis Franz of ``NYPD Blue,'' David Hyde Pierce
of ``Frasier,'' and John Lithgow and Kristen Johnston of ``3rd Rock
From the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice'' also took both supporting acting honors among
drama series.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Badalucco, who plays the insecure Jimmy, claimed the
supporting actor honor, topping co-star Steve Harris as well as
Benjamin Bratt and Steven Hill on ``Law &AMP; Order'' and Noah Wyle of
``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   Badalucco said later he has had very little experience accepting
such awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a bowling trophy back in Brooklyn but that's it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Holland Taylor's sex-starved judge character in ``The Practice''
took best supporting actress in a drama, beating out co-stars Lara
Flynn Boyle and Manheim as well as Kim Delaney of ``NYPD Blue'' and
Nancy Marchand of ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Overnight!'' the veteran actress said.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Johnston picked up her second Emmy in her third
nomination for Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series, playing Sally
Solomon on ``3rd Rock From the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   She choked up a bit on stage when thanking Lithgow for holding
everything together, explaining later that he was a unifying force
when the show struggled through NBC management changes and
time-period moves.
</P>
<P>
   David Hyde Pierce collected his third statuette as the fussy
Niles Crane on ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest honor the academy has ever given me is to put me
in a category with John Mahoney,'' he said, referring to the
co-star who plays his father.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Tony Awards brought special honors to the Miller family
as father Walter picked up the variety, comedy or music special
prize as its producer, following son Paul's win as best director in
the same category.
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS, STORY CONTINUES ON SECOND TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   The pilot of comedy ``Sports Night'' won the directing award for
Thomas Schlamme.
</P>
<P>
   John Leguizamo won the first Emmy of his career for his comedy
special, ``John Leguizamo's Freak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can write a one-man show,'' he said. ``All you need is
one year, a paper and pen and a messed-up life.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO's ``The Chris Rock Show'' took outstanding writing for a
variety or comedy show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conan (O'Brien) has the best show. I do 13, but he does a
hundred,'' Rock said. ``Conan, you should have got it, but I'm
going to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The tearful ``NYPD Blue'' episode dealing with Bobby Simone's
death brought the drama series directing award for Paris Barclay,
his second in as many years.
</P>
<P>
   Barclay told reporters that directing the emotional episode was
a wrenching experience for everyone involved. He watched the scenes
from a distant monitor because he was sobbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jimmy (Smits) laid down in that bed he was so
believable,'' he said. ``When you look at Kim Delaney, she wasn't
acting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Lesson Before Dying'' on HBO was awarded best writing of a
movie or miniseries for Ann Peacock.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year running ``The Late Show With David
Letterman'' on CBS took the prize for top variety, music or comedy
series, winning over its ratings nemesis, ``The Tonight Show With
Jay Leno.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Mirren, playing the title role in ``The Passion of Ayn
Rand,'' won the Emmy for best actress in a movie or miniseries, her
second award.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great, it feels shamefully wonderful,'' she said
backstage.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E broke into a realm long dominated by the broadcast networks
and pay cable, winning outstanding miniseries for ``Horatio
Hornblower.'' It topped ``Joan of Arc on CBS,'' ``The Temptations''
and ``The '60s'' on NBC and ``Great Expectations'' on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Tucci was surprised to win best actor in a movie or
miniseries as the title character in HBO's ``Winchell.'' His rivals
in the category were Don Cheadle in ``A Lesson Before Dying,'' Ian
Holm in ``King Lear,'' ``Jack Lemmon in ``Inherit the Wind,'' and
Sam Shephard in ``Dash and Lilly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you very much _ you've made a huge mistake,'' Tucci
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt won her fourth consecutive Emmy, a record for a performer
in a leading role.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Mad About You'' now off the air,' Hunt paid tribute to
her co-star, Paul Reiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``How will I ever find someone to act with who I trust and love
so much,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lithgow won his third award as Dr. Dick Solomon, his fourth Emmy
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know how I won this,'' Lithgow said. ``As far
as I can tell every actor in this town thinks what I do on `3rd
Rock' is disgraceful. You saw it tonight. `Good for yoooo,''' he
said in his over-the-top style.
</P>
<P>
   Franz was a surprise winner in the drama series best actor
category. It was his fourth win as Andy Sipowicz, and he was
surprised to have beat co-star Smits, whose death scenes dragged
out over several episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling pretty comfortable down there because I was sure
I wasn't going to have to get up and say anything. I was sure Jimmy
was,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
