<SLUG> BC-LIGHTRAIL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHT-RAIL LEADS RAPID TRANSIT ALTERNATIVES IN PHOENIX AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ While backers ready more details for a Phoenix-area
light-rail train, other folks are leaning hard on the brake,
arguing for alternative forms of rapid transit.
</P>
<P>
   To them, monorails, or Jetson-like travel pods suspended from a
guide-rail, or even buses that run on rubber tires but operate like
a train, are better than launching an electric train on a 17-mile
track from central Phoenix to downtown Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   To these dreamers, the rail plan is nothing but an ``electric
street car,'' a 19th century rail holdover, a rapid-transit plan
that will not be rapid and won't attract riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're forging ahead to board the trolley car, which is a
technology we gave up in the 1940s,'' scoffed James Ellmore, a
proponent of building an elevated rail network that would rise over
the Phoenix area's major thoroughfares.
</P>
<P>
   But local city planners say they looked at everything from
monorails to subways and concluded that an electric train, running
at street level, is the best way to start building rapid-transit in
the Valley of the Sun, as the Phoenix is known. They hope a train
could be running by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The decision boiled down to practicality: It costs less, and is
less controversial, to build a light-rail line at street level than
it is to put the system up in the air or tunnel it underground,
planners say.
</P>
<P>
   Elevated systems, for all the promise they hold of literally
gliding above traffic congestion, drive straight into a brick wall
of public opposition, said Jyme Sue Olson, media manager for Valley
Connections.
</P>
<P>
   The group is sponsored by Mesa, Phoenix, Tempe, the Maricopa
Association of Governments and the Regional Public Transportation
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aesthetic values, the loss of views of our mountains, the
privacy of citizens _ it's the most contentious part of the
light-rail effort,'' she said of elevated train systems.
</P>
<P>
   The ValTrans rail project failed at the ballot box a decade ago,
in part, because residents near the planned rail lines blanched at
the idea of trains full of passengers looming over their back
yards, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other ideas are so futuristic that they don't operate anywhere,
except on the Web pages of their backers.
</P>
<P>
   The SkyTran proposal, for example, envisions two-person pods
suspended from an elevated guide-rail, or perhaps gliding along a
ground-level rail.
</P>
<P>
   The driverless cars would be available anytime, all the time, to
zip above town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's ever done it,'' said Steve Beard, deputy project
director for the light-rail effort.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody knows what it would cost.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the ground-level train system likely will cost up
to $40 million a mile, and would produce a rail system with a
40-year lifespan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since light-rail operates in a growing number of cities, from
San Diego to St. Louis, they have track records that can be studied
and adapted to the Phoenix metro area, planners say.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative to light-rail, Maricopa County Supervisor Don
Stapley and a handful of adherents are pushing a rapid-bus network.
Their idea is to copy a system that has brought international
acclaim to the Brazilian city of Curitiba, a major urban center of
more than 1.4 million people southwest of Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm calling this a precursor to the light-rail,'' said
Stapley, who as a member of the Regional Public Transportation
Authority voted in the past to proceed with rail planning to serve
the Valley's nearly 2.8 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   Stapley is trying to sell local officials _ specifically Tempe,
which has a transit tax, and Phoenix, which will hold a transit
election next spring _ on the merits of the bus system as a
cost-effective transition to rail.
</P>
<P>
   Beard said the rapid-bus idea could work, especially along
Phoenix area freeways, which have high-occupancy-vehicle lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't build rail everywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to run rail on the ground was made by local
planners early last year. The planning process is deep into such
details as where exactly the rail should run, how it might cross
Tempe's Town Lake, and how far apart stations should be.
</P>
<P>
   A series of open houses, starting Tuesday and running through
the end of September, will seek the public's ideas on those plans.
</P>
<P>
   Planners in early 1998 also decided that the best place to
launch a rail line would be from central Phoenix to central Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at Central Avenue and Indian School Road, the 17-mile
rail would run through Phoenix's midcity and downtown business
districts, picking up at other people-intensive places such as the
Deck Park, Phoenix Public Library and the sports venues downtown.
The line would continue east along Washington Street, skirt past
the north side of Sky Harbor International Airport, sweep into
downtown Tempe past the Town Lake and Sun Devil Stadium, and end at
Dobson Road and Main Street in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Planners decided against running directly into the airport
because of the costs and logistics involved.
</P>
<P>
   But every time light-rail plans are aired, alternatives pop up.
</P>
<P>
   Ellmore, the founding dean of ASU's College of Architecture, has
shown his meticulously sketched plans for a 36-mile aerial rail
system to movers and shakers Valleywide ever since rail talk
renewed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction?
</P>
<P>
   ``Practically none,'' Ellmore said.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that it's more expensive to build an elevated
system. But that's only looking at half of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   Planners need to balance the greater costs against the benefits,
such as development rights for the space above and along the
elevated rail lines, Ellmore said. In his view, elevated rail would
open a treasure trove of high-rise offices, condominiums and lofts
along the elevated rail network.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bowling, a Phoenix resident who follows transit issues,
hopes to persuade Phoenix officials that their transit election
next spring should steer away from light rail and buses, which he
considers a passe system. Instead, he'd like to see the city invest
some money in the brave new world of personal rapid-transit.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no such system operating, Bowling said the
technology needed to make it happen exists and simply needs to be
pulled into a functioning package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it makes it a hard sell,'' Bowling said of the lack of
precedent. But he thinks it's a better buy _ although there are no
cost estimates. The ground-level light-rail train, he believes, is
doomed to failure because of its cost relative to the number of
people who would use it.
</P>
<P>
   But Valley Connection's Beard said that just because individual
rail-car technology exists doesn't mean the Phoenix metro area
should be its testing ground, nor the public purse its bankroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public agencies have a lot of responsibility to put something
out there that is safe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Personal-rapid transit _ as well as some of the other ideas _
could have potential applications down the road, he said. For
example, airports could use the automated people-mover concept of
personal rapid-transit to shuttle people between terminals and
parking lots or transit stops.
</P>
<P>
   And elevated rail is not impossible, especially in cases where a
rail line would be needed to cross over congested intersections, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not 110 percent set that every inch of this will be at
grade,'' Beard said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over which form of transit the Phoenix area should
adopt could shift again, and soon, as Phoenix gears up for a
transit election in the spring. A date has not been picked, but the
election likely would be in March or May.
</P>
<P>
   Without Phoenix's financial support, light-rail cannot be built,
Beard said.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Councilwoman Peggy Bilsten said the city likely will
rely on the light-rail plan as the ``backbone'' of a Phoenix
public-transit system.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other ideas, Bilsten said, her mind is open.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're able to have a good, intelligent discussion,
hopefully they'll see we've got to start somewhere,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If people approach transit with an attitude that it's their
idea, or nothing, ``We won't get anywhere,'' Bilsten said. &QL; 
Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at (602) 444-8963 or at
maryjo.pitzl(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
