u s BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     09-13 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRICKERY LEAVES HAWKS TRAPPED IN LIONS' DEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For the record, let it be noted that the Mike Holmgren
era opened at the Kingdome Sunday with a bit of trickery.
</P>
<P>
   The first play from the Seahawks coach (among other titles)
called upon veteran running back Ricky Watters to take the handoff
from young quarterback Jon Kitna, then relay the ball back to Kitna
who, apparently, was supposed to heave da bomb downfield, maybe
even looking for a first-strike touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, friends, the old flea flicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, considering what that play could have been, it could have
been a great start,'' Watters said, giving a revisionist look at
the Hawks' 28-20 opening-day defeat to the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hits the bomb and scores, well, that's a whole other
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the attempt at da bomb was a bomb _ a stink bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna was sacked, dropped for a bruising 8 yards as the Seahawks
failed to block the Lions' rush on the designer play.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, Kitna, Watters, Holmgren and the Hawks were
in a deep hole against Detroit from which the Hawks would never
emerge.
</P>
<P>
   As for symbolism, you can understand that none of the culprits
in the botched play saw it as an omen. But that doesn't mean the
ol' flea flicker call did not dare Holmgren's fledgling Hawks to be
a little more sophisticated and a little more lucky than one could
reasonably expect _ at least at this early stage of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the learning curve and the execution curve are going to
be greater than predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when you run a reverse or any other special, goofy
play, it is either real good or real bad. There is no middle
ground,'' Holmgren said after his team's dismal debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, we had a chance, we just didn't block it right. It
was one of those frustrating things. We have some young guys
playing and they didn't do that right.''
</P>
<P>
   As opening-day disasters go, Holmgren can at least rest easy
knowing that Dennis Erickson's 1997 inaugural meltdown against the
Jets should stand as a testament to mind-bending lack of execution
and boneheadedness.
</P>
<P>
   However, this was the debut of the vaunted West Coast offense.
And the things that the Hawks did not do right were scattered all
over the field, starting with special teams breakdowns and a
defensive snafu that allowed the Barry Sanders-less Lions to run
like the bulls at Pamplona.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit collected 167 yards on the ground on 36 attempts for an
average of 4.6 yards per carry, while the Hawks managed a mere 31
yards on 16 carries _ Watters accounting for 13 carries and 21
yards.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the result of the Seahawks not paying Joey Galloway
monster cash to help open up the offense, Game 1 of the season
demonstrated how much extra pressure Kitna and Watters will have to
assume in the weeks to come.
</P>
<P>
   Watters, whose troubles in finding or making holes Sunday were
second only to his inability to swing outside, was the first to
draw boos from the 66,238 with just three minutes gone in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Down 10-0 and the Hawks on their own 20-yard line, Watters took
the handoff on second-and-3 and was immediately cut down for no
gain, which was pretty much how it went all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Holmgren said he expects the running game will
improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we lost (receiver Charles) Jordan, they crowded us pretty
good,'' Holmgren said, adding, ``That's what I would do, since we
were pretty thin at those positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren was unwilling to single out Kitna, even when it was
clear that Holmgren was frustrated by some of what the young QB was
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to help him, the best thing I can do is go
through the growing pains together,'' Holmgren said. ``It would be
counterproductive for me to ... say something that might be
emotional. I'd much rather see the film first.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kitna suffered under the heavy attack from the Lions'
defense, he said he felt fine during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I saw the field pretty well. Better than I
expected, actually. I didn't feel a lot of pressure, although once
we dug ourselves a hole, it was a little hard to get out,'' Kitna
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of the heavy Detroit rush, however, Kitna held the
ball several times when he should have tossed it away, which is why
he was knocked for six sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Holmgren refused to let his emotions undermine the
long-term process he knows he must undergo with this quarterback,
this offense and this Seahawks team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches were pretty good out there,'' Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us not to press and if you look at everything we
did, it all came within the system. We didn't play well in the
first half, but we pulled it together in the second half because we
believe in what they're telling us,'' Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Coach was very supportive. ... Coach remained very
calm on the sideline, though I'm sure he was frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Results are going to matter very soon to Holmgren, not to
mention to the fans and to the Seahawks' spend-to-win owner. But
even in the face of a somewhat embarrassing beginning, Holmgren did
his best to keep his two main offensive cogs from slipping into a
tailspin _ a destination they seemed headed from the opening play
of the brand-new era.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
