<HEADLINE>
TESTS SHOW BROWN SUFFERS NO SERIOUS INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Seahawks already were losing the game when it
suddenly appeared they had lost even more. Much more.
</P>
<P>
   All-Pro linebacker Chad Brown lay motionless on the Kingdome
turf for several minutes near the end of the first half in Sunday's
28-20 season-opening loss to the Detroit Lions.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, as is customary for a player who made 150 tackles last
season, had stuck his head into a play while trying to make a play.
Only this time, Brown didn't get up.
</P>
<P>
   He was strapped to a stretcher and taken from the field by
ambulance to Harborview Medical Center for tests that showed he has
suffered no neurological damage. His condition will be re-evaluated
today.
</P>
<P>
   But the loss of Brown, and just the thought that he could have
been lost for more than just a game or two, was an extra dose of
downer on an already bummer of a day. Brown, remember, was involved
in a helmet-to-helmet collision with linebacker Winston Moss two
years ago. Moss fractured two vertebra in his neck, ending his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad's injury definitely gives you a bad feeling for him, his
family and friends,'' defensive tackle Sam Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was down on the field, that was the worst feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Brown's body being loaded into the ambulance wasn't
exactly uplifting either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad's the leader of this team,'' said linebacker James Logan,
who replaced Brown in the lineup for the second half. ``You just
have to step up and play a little harder when something like that
happens. But it's not an easy thing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
