<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLMGREN ERA OPENS WITH THUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Excuse the misprint. That's the Mike Holmgren error,
not the Mike Holmgren era.
</P>
<P>
   In their first regular-season game under their new coach, and
amid all the expectations Holmgren's January hiring spawned, the
new-look Seahawks too closely resembled the same old Seahawks in
dropping a 28-20 decision to the Detroit Lions at the Kingdome
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest part is doing the things that got us beat in the
past,'' guard Pete Kendall said after yet another embarrassing
season-opening loss under yet another new coach.
</P>
<P>
   Things like:
</P>
<P>
   -- Wide receiver Sean Dawkins' fumble ending the Seahawks'
opening possession and setting up the first of two field goals by
Lions kicker Jason Hanson;
</P>
<P>
   -- Center Chris Gray's high snap leading to a missed 32-yard
field goal by Todd Peterson that would have tied the game near the
end of the first quarter, and instead set up a 16-yard touchdown
pass from Lions quarterback Charlie Batch to wide receiver Germane
Crowell on the first play of the second quarter to give Detroit a
10-0 lead;
</P>
<P>
   -- Rookie Charlie Rogers muffing a punt return that was
recovered by the Lions Brock Olivo at the Seahawks' 5-yard line to
set up Batch's 5-yard TD pass to tight end David Sloan;
</P>
<P>
   -- Long-snapper Deems May taking his job description a little
too literally as he sailed a snap over the head of punter Jeff
Feagles and out of the end zone for a second-quarter safety that
pushed the Lions lead to 18-0.
</P>
<P>
   Three special-teams gaffs that led to 12 Lions' points in an
eight-point loss. Shades of 1997, when mistakes by the special
teams cost the Seahawks at least four games and any chance they had
of making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A lackluster effort by the offense, which included only 31
rushing yards and six sacks of a constantly pressured Jon Kitna.
Shades of 1998, when an inconsistent offense cost the Seahawks at
least five games and any chance of making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A couldn't-stop-them-when-they-really-needed-to effort by the
defense, which allowed 369 yards to a Lions offense that was
without Barry Sanders and three of its starting linemen and then
lost Pro Bowl wide receiver Herman Moore to a sprained knee in the
first quarter. Shades of, well, pale shades of gray to match the
Kingdome roof.
</P>
<P>
   And, adding Seahawks injury to insult, All-Pro linebacker Chad
Brown was taken from the field in an ambulance late in the first
half after jamming his neck; cornerback Fred Thomas is probably
lost for the season after fracturing his right leg; tackle Todd
Weiner could miss up to a month after spraining his right ankle;
and wide receiver Charles Jordan could be sidelined just as long
after pulling his left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   One of the only good pieces of news on this day was that tests
performed at Harborview Medical Center detected no neurological
damage for Brown, who was released from the hospital Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The prognosis isn't nearly as good for the rest of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit played well, and this isn't me on my soap box trying
to take anything away from them,'' Kendall said. ``But you can look
at what we gave away, you can look at stupid things we continue to
do, and say maybe this could have been different.''
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be different. These weren't Dennis
Erickson's Seahawks. Or Tom Flores' Seahawks. But the outcome was
the same _ another disheartening opening-day loss, where the
Seahawks made an inferior team look better than they really are by
looking ill-prepared and being outplayed in every phase of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised that Coach didn't rip us,'' cornerback Shawn
Springs said. ``Actually, he was very positive and told us we just
have to continue to work. We're all professionals and we know what
we have to do to correct those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   And everyone made them. There were missed blocks on offense, at
least one missed tackle by every member of the defense and, of
course, the costly special-teams plays that were anything but
special.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren appeared as if he was nearing a meltdown several times
during the game, but he was uncharacteristically subdued afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dug a pretty good hole for ourselves in the first half,''
Holmgren said. ``We tried to climb out in the second half. I was
pleased with the effort in the second half. They did not fold up
their tents. It would have been easy to do, as poorly as we played
in the first half. Everything that could go wrong seemed to go
wrong. We were just not very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when they were, it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Like in the second half. Kitna found Dawkins twice with
touchdown passes to cut the Lions' lead to 25-20. One more
defensive stop, and the offense would have had one last chance to
pull a rabbit out of their skunk-filled helmets.
</P>
<P>
   Five times in the second half the Lions had the ball. Five times
the Seahawks forced punts.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Seahawks most needed their defense, what they got
was Batch passing to Crowell for 15 yards; Ron Rivers running for
12 and 9 yards; and Batch and Rivers hooking up on a 19-yard pass
play that pushed Hanson into range for a 49-yard field goal with
2:10 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very disappointing,'' defensive tackle Sam Adams said.
``It was a situation where they wanted it. They won the battle. We
didn't have a very good showing. We were good at times. But we
weren't very good at other times.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
