u a BC-KOREAN-LAWSUIT-SPI &LR;      09-13 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREAN-LAWSUIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN MAN IN TACOMA SUING JAPANESE COMPANIES FOR FORCED LABOR
DURING WWII 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jae Sik Choe remembers the Japanese Imperial army soldiers who
came to his Korean village in 1943. Korea was a Japanese colony
then, and Japan was at war and needed young men such as Choe for
their factories and construction sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese told me that I would make good money and that I
would be treated well by working in Japan,'' he said. But at the
Yawata steel mill, Choe said, he worked sunup to sundown, six days
a week, performing tasks such as lifting steel onto trucks. Most of
his pay was withheld as ``patriotic deposits'' and never returned.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old was not allowed to quit, and his net pay was
``about three yen per month,'' which he said amounted to being a
slave.
</P>
<P>
   Now 76, Choe who emigrated to Tacoma, Wash., in the 1980s with
his wife, last week filed a first-of-its-kind lawsuit in federal
court there: a class action on behalf of all Koreans living in the
United States who were subjected to forced labor in Japan. It asks
for unspecified damages and ``a declaration that Defendants are war
criminals who should be barred from doing business in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   His affidavit says he tried to run away, ``but because I had no
money to return to Korea, I surrendered myself.'' Later, he was
allowed to attend his mother's funeral, but was forced to return to
Japan. When he left at the war's end, a time when food was short
even for the Japanese, he said through a translator that he was
``skin and bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Choe's lawsuit names Nippon Steel Inc., which it says is the
successor of the company that owned the Yawata mill.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese attorney Etsuro Totsuka, who is researching
human-rights issues at the University of Washington in Seattle,
helped on the lawsuit. He said that from Choe's description of a
tunnel he helped dig at Mizushima, Japan,it was at an aircraft
plant of Mitsubishi Heavy Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Choe is suing Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, too: a first on this
issue, Totsuka said. Nippon Steel was sued in Japan, and in 1997
became the first Japanese company to pay a forced-labor claim _ a
settlement to 11 Korean families of about $15,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney for Nippon Steel, Bob Sacks of Sullivan &AMP;
Cromell in Los Angeles, said he has not been served with the
complaint, and could not comment. Mitsubishi's Heavy Industries'
New York office did not return a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   Choe did not sue the Japanese government, though his complaint
states, ``it is obvious that the Japanese government is largely
responsible.'' Japan settled all war-era claims against it by South
Korea with a payment in 1965 of $500 million. The money went to the
South Korean government. Japan has also settled all war claims by
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Japan allowed foreign individuals to sue Japanese
employers for wartime deeds. ``Given the separation of powers,''
reads a statement issued by the Japanese consulate here, ``the
judgment must be passed by these courts, and the Government of
Japan intends to await their decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Choe's lawsuit was filed by Lakewood, Wash., attorney Eddie
Yoon, who emigrated from South Korea in the ninth grade, attended
the University of Washington Law School and became the first
Korean-American attorney in Washington state. Yoon is suing under
the Alien Tort Claims Act, a law signed by George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   That law was nearly forgotten before it was used against former
Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos. Yoon also wielded it against
former South Korean presidents Chun Doo Hwan and Roh Tae Woo for
allegedly torturing a plaintiff during anti-government
demonstrations in Kwangju in 1979. Though his case went to the U.S.
Supreme Court, he lost. The high court ruled last year that the
United States had no jurisdication because Chun and Roh didn't live
here or have known assets here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mitsubishi Heavy and Nippon Steel have offices in New York, so
there's no problem about jurisdiction,'' Yoon said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the case Yoon filed last week, California passed
a law this summer that allows forced-labor claims against foreign
nations. The law was sponsored by California state Democratic Rep.
Tom Hayden. According to the Center for Internee Rights, three
claims have been filed under Hayden's law, all by former American
prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   However, Yoon says Hayden's law, which embroils a state in
foreign affairs, might not be constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Yoon says Choe's lawsuit based on the 200-year-old Alien Tort
Claims Act is on more solid legal ground. His effort now is to add
both claimants and defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were about a thousand Japanese corporations that
benefited from forced slave laborers,'' the lawsuit states, ``and
their names will be added at a later date.'' But identifying
companies then and their connections to companies today are
difficult tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Word about the lawsuit has prompted several members of the
Tacoma Korean Seniors League to come forward. Last week, Yoon
interviewed Yong Hwan Kim. Kim, 76, may not be able to join the
lawsuit, because his employer was the Japanese navy and the
government had settled all claims earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said that in 1942 he also was promised good pay during his
two-year contract in Japan, and got it _ the equivalent in today's
money of $1,500 to $2,000 per month _ plus a raise after six
months. But he said he was punished for violating the rules, and
was beaten so badly with a knotted rope that he couldn't bathe for
a week. He said his cheek was burned with a hot iron.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said American POWs were stationed near where he worked, and
that he can remember visiting the camp on his Sundays off to see
what Americans looked like. He recalls handing a cigarette through
the barbed wire, and seeing the Americans pass it from man to man.
They had been working with concrete, he said, and looked to be in a
condition ``worse than the Koreans.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim said the Japanese extended his contract without his consent,
but allowed him to leave in March 1945. He returned home with 400
yen in his pocket, a respectable amount. Years later, his daughter
married an American, and in 1987 Kim and his wife came to America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
