<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-COYOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG STARS PLAY COYOTES TO STANDOFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAULA CABALLERO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Phoenix Coyotes forward Jeremy Roenick was without his
mortal enemy last night. The Stars played not only without
defenseman Derian Hatcher, whose hit broke Roenick's jaw last
season, but also without Mike Modano, Brett Hull and Joe
Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes took the opposite approach, using a lineup complete
with players such as Roenick, Keith Tkachuk, Teppo Numminen and
Keith Carney.
</P>
<P>
   For a mismatch, the no-namers held their own in this 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great test for us,'' Stars forward Blake Sloan said.
``I think it's a great compliment to our team that we can go out
there without a bunch of our quote-unquote NHL guys and really
battle hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock seemed genuinely pleased with his
young squad's performance, pointing specifically to the play of
winger Keith Aldridge, who had a goal and an assist, and both
goalies, Marty Turco and Manny Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock also noted that the play of center Derek Plante
continued to be strong and that defenseman Warren Luhning ``got
better and better as the game went on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a very competitive game,'' Hitchcock said.
``This was really good because we played against a lot of good
players and the game was a real good evaluation of a lot of our
young guys.''
</P>
<P>
   A five-minute overtime period, using the new four-on-four format
as an experiment, was played before regulation. Neither team
scored, however.
</P>
<P>
   The contest was not completely without ugliness, as during the
last 36 seconds of regulation an otherwise quiet Roenick got into
it with Sloan, and that started a short brawl in the corner. After
that fracas was cleared, Tkachuk went off on Luhning, dropping his
gloves at the drop of the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams contend the scraps were simply the result of hard
play, not leftover bad blood. Tkachuk said he reacted because of a
hit Luhning put on Phoenix defenseman Numminen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a preseason game, and I don't want to see Teppo get hurt.
I'm sure it was a good, clean hit,'' Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to send a message, I'm working on my game. ...
We'll worry about the Dallas Stars when we see them in the first
game of the regular season. You can't say anything bad about the
Dallas Stars. They're Stanley Cup champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman John Erskine and Coyotes winger Kevin Saywer
engaged in a fight in the first period, but that, too, was written
off to the heat of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids were fighting for jobs,'' said Stars winger Mike Keane,
who had a goal and an assist. ``That's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Turco played the first two periods of regulation, turning back
21 of 23 shots in a steady performance amid the discombobulation
created by the green group in front of him, anchored by veterans
Darryl Sydor, Keane and Brian Skrudland.
</P>
<P>
   Turco turned back at least four point-blank shots, including one
in the second period from Tkachuck, who stood on the left doorstep
with a rebound on his stick. Turco managed to make the save while
sprawled on his side. Fernandez made eight saves in the third
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some hang-in-there performances,'' Hitchcock said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
