<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 08:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     09-13 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 19)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN: A Tale of Murder, Insanity, and
the Making of the Oxford English Dictionary &LR;  By Simon Winchester.
Harper Perennial, $13. In 1896 the editor of the Oxford English
Dictionary tracked down and befriended one of his most prolific and
dependable contributors, an American Civil War veteran who was
incarcerated at an asylum for the criminally insane. Last year the
reviewer David Walton called this an ``elegant and scrupulous
retelling'' of ``one of the strangest modern literary stories.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIRDS OF AMERICA &LR;  By Lorrie Moore. Picador USA, $14. These
stories feature articulate, romantically frustrated characters,
usually women, whose predicaments allow the reader to infer a
lifetime from a moment of crisis. Some of the tales in this
collection, which was selected as one of the best books of 1998 by
the editors of The New York Times Book Review, concern adults or
children with cancer, yet somehow they manage to find humor even as
they sharply probe issues of mortality. ``Fluid, cracked, mordant,
colloquial, Moore's sentences hold, even startle, us as they glide
beneath the radar of ideological theories of behavior to evoke the
messy, god-awful behavior itself,'' James McManus wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COLLECTED TALES OF NIKOLAI GOGOL &LR;  Translated by Richard
Pevear and Larissa Volokhonsky. Vintage Classics, $15. These 13
stories by the Russian fantasist include early tales of Cossacks
and devils set in his native Ukraine, and later classics like ``The
Nose'' and ``The Overcoat,'' written after he became famous in his
early 20s. Last year one critic called this ``a superb new
translation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOMCAT IN LOVE &LR;  By Tim O'Brien. Broadway, $13. This novel's
narrator is a snide linguistics professor (and Vietnam veteran) who
is obsessed with his ex-wife and driven by a need to seduce every
woman he meets. ``Like all comic novels, `Tomcat in Love' is a
complex affair that invites a complex response and offers a complex
reward,'' Jane Smiley wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MINOR CHARACTERS: A Young Woman's Coming-of-Age in the Beat
Orbit of Jack Kerouac &LR;  By Joyce Johnson. Penguin, $13.95. The
former girlfriend and caretaker of the guiding spirit of the Beats
describes her growing up bright and sensitive in the 1950s
counterculture and her years with Kerouac's subterranean boys'
club. In 1983 the reviewer Helen Chasin said her stories are ``not
only interesting and vivid but in several respects have more
dimension than the adventure tales and clubhouse philosophizing
that captured America's imagination in the late '50s.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SORT OF RICH &LR;  By James Wilcox. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $12.95.
In this comic novel, a New Yorker settles down with her wealthy new
husband in tranquil Tula Springs, La., where her hopes for a
simpler life are dashed by the exotic household help, including a
mysterious hippieish handyman and his arthritic stepniece. ``Wilcox
is both a fine storyteller and a skilled novelist,'' Jill McCorkle
wrote in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has also reissued  &UR; POLITE SEX &LR;  ($13),
Wilcox's novel about the shifting fortunes of two lifelong friends,
an idealistic actress and an aspiring model, who flee Tula Springs
for the bright lights of New York. In 1991, Elinor Lipman admired
the author's ``sly social satire.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOT ENTITLED: A Memoir &LR;  By Frank Kermode. Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $13. With tact and restraint, the renowned literary critic
recalls his childhood on the Isle of Man, his six-year stint in the
Royal Navy during World War II and his long career in academia and
letters. The result is ``a triumph of tone,'' David Bromwich wrote
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AN EMPIRE WILDERNESS: Travels Into America's Future &LR;  By Robert
D. Kaplan. Vintage Departures, $14. A journalist combs the West and
foresees a nation of privately guarded housing developments,
corporate fortresses, homogenous suburban pods and
automobile-dominated cities. Believe it or not, he finds it all
``not so bleak.'' In 1998 the reviewer Thurston Clarke said, ``His
theories are brave and provocative, and I cannot imagine anyone
will concoct a more convincing scenario for the American future.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNDERCLASS &LR; , by Ken Auletta (Overlook, $16.95), is a
revised and updated edition of the author's 1982 journalistic study
of the chronically poor welfare recipients, criminals and drifters
whose problems defy simple solutions _ conservative, liberal or
otherwise. This is an ``important and impressive'' book, Charles
Peters wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THIS IS MY DAUGHTER &LR;  By Roxana Robinson. Scribner, $13. This
novel is about innocence lost _ that of two children of divorce,
and that of their parents, who are stricken by rage, guilt and
shame. In 1998 the reviewer Diana Postlethwaite noted that while
the author's fiction is often called Cheeveresque, this time she
``made me think of an earlier literary forebear, Henry James.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRUTH: Four Stories I Am Finally Old Enough to Tell &LR;  By Ellen
Douglas. Plume, $12.95. In her first nonfiction book, the Southern
novelist meditates on events that fueled her fiction, including a
lifelong illicit romance, her grandfather's suicide and the
execution of some local slaves. The result is a ``curious, lovely
book,'' Laura Jamison wrote earlier this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 0827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
