<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9871 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-CLEMENCY-REVIEW-ART     09-13 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLEMENCY-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARDONS MEAN HAVING TO SAY YOU'RE SORRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The presidential power to issue pardons and
reprieves represents the ultimate constitutional act of forgiveness
_ unreviewable and absolute. But as the outcry over President
Clinton's offer of clemency to 16 Puerto Rican nationalists
demonstrates, it is not immune from second-guessing.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 16 were members of the FALN, the Spanish acronym for
the Armed Forces of National Liberation, a militant independence
group believed to be responsible for scores of bombings in the
1970s and 1980s in which six people were killed and many others
wounded. Their original sentences ranged from 35 to 90 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Clinton's decision came under heavy political attack
from Republicans and Democrats alike. The House of Representatives
voted 311-41 to condemn the leniency offer, with 93 Democrats
crossing party lines to endorse the Republican-sponsored measure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied that his decision had been influenced by the
political ambitions of the first lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who
is weighing a bid for a U.S. Senate seat from New York. Mrs.
Clinton had sided with her husband's opponents to urge him to
rescind the sweeping offer of leniency, saying that after three
weeks they had had enough time to meet the conditions that they
renounce violence and abide by parole restrictions. Clinton, saying
he acted independently, set a deadline, and by the weekend 14 of
the nationalists had accepted the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Clintons viewed the entire episode as an effort
to maneuver votes in Mrs. Clinton's behalf among New York's 1.3
million residents of Puerto Rican descent.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference, Clinton suggested that his grant of
leniency should be viewed as a routine matter, one he never
discussed with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   But the offer appears to be far from routine for Clinton. He has
granted fewer clemency petitions _ including commutations of prison
sentences or pardons for past crimes _ than either of his
Republican predecessors, Presidents George Bush and Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The number of presidential clemencies has steadily declined
since World War II, particularly since the Ford administration as
the intensity of partisan political debate over fighting crime has
heated up. ``Mr. Clinton's record in clemency matters reflects a
trend that began during Ronald Reagan's presidency,'' said Margaret
Love, the pardon attorney at the Justice Department from 1990 to
1997. ``It had been very much an operational part of the criminal
justice system. Now clemency has been taken hostage in the war on
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemency grants plummeted further during Reagan's first term,
when a change in Justice Department procedures effectively placed
control of pardons and commutations in the hands of prosecutors,
including Rudolph Giuliani, who was then an associate attorney
general. As mayor of New York City, where many of the attacks took
place, and as a likely opponent of Mrs. Clinton in the Senate race,
Giuliani has criticized the president's Clinton's offer to the
imprisoned Puerto Ricans.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Love said that during the Clinton administration, the White
House has relied less on the Justice Department's recommendations
in clemency cases and more on its own judgment of a case's merits.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, there is little incentive to grant clemency. ``As
a general rule, there's nothing in it for a president or an
attorney general to do anything for anybody,'' said John Stanish,
who was a pardon attorney under President Jimmy Carter. ``They can
only be humiliated or embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's offer of clemency to the imprisoned Puerto Ricans on
the condition that they renounce violence was unusual but not
unprecedented. Conditional clemency is rare, though not unheard of.
When Carter commuted the bank robbery sentence of Patricia Hearst
in 1979, she was required to agree not to take part in militant
politics. When President Richard M. Nixon commuted Jimmy Hoffa's
racketeering sentence in 1971, the labor leader had to agree to
refrain from union activities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's offer represents the first time a president has
granted conditional clemency to prisoners convicted of crimes
related to terrorism, though none of those offered clemency were
directly responsible for deaths or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Clemency applications have piled up during the Clinton
administration. While Justice Department records of the 3,042
clemency petitions filed during Clinton's presidency do not
distinguish between serious and frivolous or repetitive requests,
they show that Clinton has reduced the sentences of only three
people.
</P>
<P>
   Two of these people, Jackie Trautman of Ohio and Johnny Palacios
of Florida, were convicted of drug offenses. A third man, Ernest
Krikiva of Nebraska, , was a hog farmer who had been convicted of
perjury in a bankruptcy proceeding and had won the support of
family farm groups.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department figures show that, as of April, 884 people
had filed petitions for commutations that were pending, waiting to
be acted on by the Justice Department and the White House. It
remains unclear how the cases of the 16 Puerto Rican militants were
culled from these requests _ although their supporters, including
Carter and retired South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu had been
advocating their release for years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton explained his decision by saying the sentences were much
longer than those they would have received under the more recently
enacted federal sentencing guidelines for crimes committed after
1987. Most of the imprisoned nationalists were convicted of
offenses like interstate transportation of firearms or armed
robbery and were not accused of explicit terrorist acts, even
though law enforcement officials have said their crimes were meant
to support the violent activities of a militant group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 0838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6289 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-CLEMENCY-REVIEW-ART     09-13 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLEMENCY-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARDONS MEAN HAVING TO SAY YOU'RE SORRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
