<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9874 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-DROUGHT-BENEFITS-RE     09-13 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-DROUGHT-BENEFITS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, A SILVER LINING IN THE DROUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With good reason, farmers, home gardeners and many others cursed
the severe drought that hit the Northeast this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But some others managed to make hay while the sun shone. Among
them are wine-makers, well-diggers, building contractors, seashore
landlords, apple, peach and blueberry growers, wild-turkey lovers,
cops looking for illicit marijuana crops and good neighbors like
Frank Rudisill of Absecon, N.J., who found an ecologically
acceptable way to paint his brown lawn green.
</P>
<P>
   First, let us hear from Rudisill, a financial planner and avid
gardener, who took ``the logical approach'' and asked for
professional advice after New Jersey announced criminal penalties
for watering a lawn. He found a spray called Lesco Green, which is
used at dozens of sports stadiums to tone up grass for the color
television cameras. Voila, Rudisill found. Instant emerald lawn!
</P>
<P>
   Initially, there was some muttering among neighbors, who
suspected he'd been secretly sneaking out at night with the garden
hose. ``I got a nasty letter put in my mailbox that basically
accused me of being a drought criminal,'' Rudisill said.
</P>
<P>
   But once the truth became known, jealousies disappeared. ``Some
neighbors of mine have a really nice yard, and about six months ago
friends of theirs asked if they could have their wedding in their
yard,'' he said. ``Then, bang, along comes the drought. So I told
them I'd paint their lawn for them this weekend. You use this stuff
and it's like playing God. Let there be green!''
</P>
<P>
   The artificial lawn-coloring industry aside, other industries
have weathered the drought well. From Massachusetts to Maryland,
well-diggers have been flooded with calls. Companies that deliver
jugs of water for coolers or tankers of water for well and cistern
replenishment are drowning in orders. Balmy coastal tourist towns
said they had one of their best summers in years, and seashore
rental agencies were swamped in June and July by people who hadn't
booked accommodations earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Building contractors, blessed with so many rain-free summer
days, couldn't hire enough workers to keep up with their orders and
projects. While lawnmower repairs were off sharply, businesses that
specialize in repairing boat hulls and propellers sailed on
prosperously as boats ran aground or hit rocks on lakes where water
levels had dropped sharply. And pest exterminators made a killing,
as more ants and other parched insects found their way indoors to
look for water.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, wine growers in the Northeast, now about to harvest
their grapes, say that 1999 will be a banner year _ assuming you
like Northeastern wines. The grapes do well in dry, hot weather
(for one thing, because less rain means fewer weeds and funguses)
and the result is smaller, juicier grapes with higher sugar
content.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same holds true for apples. Shelley Page, a spokeswoman
for the New York State Apple Association, said the bushel total for
this year's crop (New York is second to Washington in total apple
production) will be about 30 percent larger than normal, with
crisper and sweeter apples to boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting back in May, with those warm sunny days, we had
perfect conditions for blossoming and pollination,'' she said. ``If
it's rainy and windy, the bees stay home, and icky weather wrecks
the blossoms. The bees were incredibly happy and industrious this
spring.'' With the hot, dry summer, she said, ``there's a great
crop on the trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Other crops that did well this summer, for similar reasons, were
peaches and blueberries. (Blueberries are an early crop, harvested
in June mostly, and so were not as affected by the drought.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there was good and bad news for another crop:
marijuana. The hot and dry conditions were conducive to robust
growth of marijuana plants, hardy weeds with shallow roots that can
sop up even small amounts of moisture. On the other hand, police
and federal drug-enforcement agents who use airplanes to look for
marijuana crops in isolated areas had an easier job of it this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A green field of pot stands out from the air when everything
else is brown,'' one surveillance officer said. The state police in
rural Maryland and Virginia reported that they were spotting and
seizing more crops this summer. In other major pot-growing states
like New York and Pennsylvania, most cultivation occurs in northern
areas that weren't hard-hit by the drought. ``A lot of yield is in
those places, where everything is still fairly green from the
air,'' said Lt. Col. Chris Cleaver of the Pennsylvania National
Guard, which conducts aerial surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   As the season changes from summer to fall _ autumn's official
first day is Sept. 23 _ the evidence of the drought will likely
linger. Most noticeable, probably, will be a spotty and early fall
foliage season. A spokeswoman for Connecticut's tourist agency
said: ``A lot of the foliage is already starting to turn. It's a
week to 10 days early.'' And hikers all over the Northeast are
being pleasantly surprised to see bursts of wild turkeys in places
they never saw them before. Brad Gunn, a biologist with the
National Wild Turkey Federation, said turkeys _ who are
``opportunists'' as feeders, and whose population is growing
robustly anyway _ are making do in parched, scrubby areas abandoned
by other birds.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of seasonal things, the pumpkin crop is a bust this
year, as evidenced by the gnarled, scraggly offerings just now
turning up in shops and outdoor stands.
</P>
<P>
   And Christmas trees growing in drought-hit areas are not doing
well, farmers say. But not to worry, even if the drought continues
all fall, said Gary Richards of Lasco Inc. in Rocky River, Ohio,
the company that makes Rudisill's grass paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The product also works beautifully on Christmas trees,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 0840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0103 </DOCNO>
