to human rights. Here, when the military ruled, it was a left-wing
military. The two main guerrilla groups waited for the army to
return to the barracks before they staged attacks _ against elected
civilian governments and the very principle of moderate peaceful
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Both rebel groups bombed public places and mocked the civilian
governments when they appointed liberal judges or circumscribed the
army's powers. For the Maoist Shining Path, revolution meant a
bloodletting complete with executions of officials and soccer games
played with human skulls.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few years, the two groups have collapsed under
the weight of their own excesses and popular revulsion. And
Fujimori can take credit for defeating them, a claim that most
Peruvians accept. The conventional wisdom here is that he was
saving the country when he dissolved Congress and the Supreme Court
in 1992, held show trials and otherwise upended the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere deep down in the consciousness of many Peruvians
there is the feeling that human rights have helped the terrorists,
and not the victims of the terrorists,'' said Francisco Diaz
Canseco Tavara, a former congressman and a human rights advocate.
``People tell me all the time that human rights are for
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a general lesson in this, it may be that even after
a Latin American country shucks off military rule, the civilian
government is going to have to maintain order; if it fails, the
voters could be tempted to follow the man on a horse (even if he is
a civilian).
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela, in fact, is beginning to look like another case in
point. Sick of the corruption and failed policies of two centrist
parties that alternated in power for 40 years, Venezuelans this
year elected Hugo Chavez, a former coup leader, as president.
</P>
<P>
   In Peru over the last two months, Fujimori has surged in opinion
polls and is beginning to break away from the two opposition
candidates most likely to run against him. For the first time in
two years, he is considered the favorite in next year's election,
even though Peru is deep in recession and the constitution still
formally prohibits him from running for a third term.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set for this latest comeback in 1997, when he
fired three judges who had upheld a constitutional prohibition of
his expected run. State Department officials, human rights
activists and the Peruvian press protested, but local polls showed
that Peruvians, especially the poor who had been most afflicted by
terrorist violence, were not particularly upset at the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly negative reviews from abroad came last July when
Fujimori withdrew Peru from the jurisdiction of the Inter-American
Human Rights Court after it ruled that four Chileans convicted as
terrorists in Peru had not received a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's approval rating, which had been as low as 33 percent
back in December, rose from 46 percent to 50 percent _ a boost that
was also attributed to the arrest in July of the top remaining
leader of the Shining Path guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of Fujimori rising in the polls every time he abuses
civil liberties goes back to April 1992, when he suspended
democratic institutions and ordered mass arrests of union and
opposition leaders. He was called a tyrant throughout the
hemisphere, Washington cut some aid, and the Organization of
American States approved sanctions. But Peruvians were overjoyed,
and Fujimori's approval rating in a leading Peruvian poll soared
from 53 percent to 81 percent that year. Five months later, the top
Shining Path leaders were arrested, and this served to legitimize
the removal of civil liberties in the eyes of the citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When President Fujimori attacks judges, Peruvians like it,''
said Alfredo Torres Guzman, Peru's leading pollster. ``That's
because in the past judges released so many terrorists for lack of
evidence. Our focus groups show that poor people don't distinguish
between authoritarianism and authority _ and without authority, in
the Peruvian mind, there is chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   The next time Fujimori enjoyed a surge in the polls _ from an
approval rating of 52 percent to 67 percent _ was in April 1997,
when he ordered commandos to storm the Japanese ambassador's
residence and liberate 71 hostages held by Tupac Amaru rebels. When
all 14 rebels were killed on the spot _ some, it is almost certain,
having been executed after they surrendered _ Fujimori was again
criticized abroad. But to the majority of Peruvians, it seems, the
rebels got what they deserved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
