<P>
   1. ALMODOVAR AND HIS WOMEN When Pedro Almodovar learned that the
Hollywood Madam, Heidi Fleiss, once employed a prostitute who went
by the name of Norma Jean Almodovar, he was amused. (And before
that, the woman worked for the police.) Only in Almodovar's
strangely ordered universe would a cop-turned-whore seem honest.
Nearly all of Almodovar's films since his 1980 feature debut are
populated with transsexuals, porn stars, drag queens,
sadomasochists and drug addicts. It's the unconventional subject
matter - freaky characters, sex, drugs - that has helped ensure the
success of his movies in the United States. By Jonathan Van Meter.
From The New York Times Magazine. 1,800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
WHAT'S DOING IN HONOLULU While autumn is the low season for travel
to Honolulu - the wallflower period of the year - savvy travelers
await the benefits lurking in the aftermath of the frenzied summer.
This is also the time when the Aloha Festivals sweep the islands
with more than 300 events, from parades to a Royal Ball. By Jocelyn
Fujii. From The New York Times Way To Go! 1,800 words + photos +
map. _____________________________________________________________
3. HAIR AND NAIL SALONS MAY SPREAD DEADLY VIRUSES Nail and hair
salons may be a source of blood-borne as well as other infectious
diseases. There is good evidence that standard disinfection isn't
doing the trick and razors, nail files, scissors, tatoo needles and
body piercing instruments are risk factors for transmitting
hepatitis B and C and HIV. By Charles Downey. 1,150 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
PORTRAIT OF GOETHE On the 250th anniversary of Goethe's birth, does
this legendary literary figure have anything to offer us? An
indulgent attitude to past errors, a sane optimism and an
un-Teutonic worldliness. By John Armstrong. From Prospect Magazine.
(N/A U.K.) 4,000 words.
