 Monday, Sept. 13, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT NEWS (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-FOOTBALL-SUNDAY (Undated) _ Stretching is an important
preliminary to any sporting routine. Now, television is giving fans
three hours of warm-up exercises for what can be a 10-hour day of
viewing NFL games. By PETE DOUGHERTY.
</P>
<P>
   TV-FOOTBALL-MONDAY (Undated) _ After a dozen years on MNF, Dan
Dierdorf did not have his contract renewed after last season.
Rather than replace him, ABC chose to let Al Michaels and Boomer
Esiason become a two-man crew. By PETE DOUGHERTY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-GOLF-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ If your favorite local
newspaper suddenly partnered up with your favorite local sports
team, you'd have a few things to worry about. That's the new
predicament at GolfWeb, which has been leading the Internet in golf
coverage but has now formed an alliance with PGATour.com, the PGA
Tour's own site. By SUSAN FORNOFF.
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-FISHING (San Francisco) _ For 22 years, Jacky Douglas has
been owner and captain of a 50-foot salmon boat, the ``Wacky
Jacky.'' During salmon season, as the sun little more than glimmers
over the horizon, the 70-year-old Douglas ferries hopeful anglers
out through the Golden Gate in search of salmon. Charter fishing
operations such as Douglas' have moored at San Francisco's
Fisherman's Wharf since the '50s, but the number of boats out
stalking salmon has been on a steady decline. By BOBBY McGILL.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ What if you went to a doctor
about a headache, and to your surprise, the doctor ordered more
studies. Then, the next day, you woke up and found that your right
arm had been amputated? Makes no sense, right? That is exactly what
the fish doctor is proposing in California. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BREAD-MAKERS (Undated) _ In our fast-paced world, even bread has
to keep up with the times. Bread making by hand used to take hours,
between waiting for the yeast to rise and the kneading process.
Automatic bread makers are improving, after being around for a
number of years. More than 20 million U.S. households now have one.
By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The thing about Paul Boden and
the Coalition on Homelessness that makes them super attractive to
some of us is the same thing that makes a lot of other San
Franciscans wish the coalition would get the hell out of town: They
are brutally honest, and they insist that homeless people be
treated as if they are 100 percent human and deserving of genuine _
not virtual _ dignity. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-IDIOM (San Francisco) _ My boss, (I call him ``Sir'') and
I are being driven mad by the way women talk. Especially the young
ones with ``like'' and ``you know'' and ``you know, like.'' They
give him fits. Hearing one too many ``so I said, and he said,''
accompanied by cries of ``oh, puh- leeez'' have made him move to
another table in restaurants. By RAYNE WOLFE.
</P>
