<HEADLINE>
UNFORTUNATELY, 1993 CONCERNS WERE WELL-FOUNDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wrote some words in a column on March 14, 1993, that have
proven to be quite prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, I ended my column with these words:
</P>
<P>
   ``But what continues to bother me the most is the absence of a
neutral party at the battle front. The media have been forced so
far to the rear that they can't actually serve as your eyes and
ears. You and I are simply being spoon-fed information by the
powers in charge. That should worry all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   I was commenting on the siege of the Branch Davidian compound
near Waco by federal law enforcement officers. I was the ombudsman
of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram at the time and devoted several
columns to the prolonged standoff between federal authorities and
members of a religious cult.
</P>
<P>
   I was not alone in my concern.
</P>
<P>
   A number of readers, many of whom said they were often critical
of the news media, also said they were concerned that federal
officers had, for all practical purposes, blinded and muzzled
journalists by keeping them so far away from the action that it was
impossible for them to observe what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction of one Arlington, Texas, man was pretty typical of
the response I received from readers:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lost the only neutral eyes down there. If more shots
are fired, we probably won't know who really fired the first
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears that our concerns were warranted. Had federal
authorities permitted a small pool of journalists to be on the
front line, perhaps we would not have had to wait six years to
learn that the FBI had used pyrotechnic tear-gas canisters to help
end the 51-day standoff. Through the years, federal authorities
repeatedly denied that such canisters had been used during the
siege.
</P>
<P>
   We also are only now learning that the Pentagon's elite Special
Operations Command also had sent observers to the siege. The
command oversees secretive military operations.
</P>
<P>
   Those readers who had wanted the government to place a pool of
journalists close to the action were emphatic in their belief that
the journalists should confine themselves to the role of observers
and not interfere with the sensitive negotiations with cult leader
David Koresh or hinder the operations of the federal officers.
</P>
<P>
   But reporters and photographers were never allowed near the
front during the prolonged siege that ended with a fire that
destroyed the compound and claimed about 80 lives.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the lying by authorities _ and the destruction of
their credibility _ I am not convinced that their actions were
responsible for the deadly fire. That is not to say that there is
no undisclosed evidence that might change my mind.
</P>
<P>
   In one column, I also was critical of the news media for not
taking a stronger stand for the public's right to know. We
permitted ourselves to be pushed around by federal authorities with
only a slight whimper.
</P>
<P>
   I also voiced some concern about some of the behavior of the
news media during the standoff.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, I asked Georgianna Vines, then president of the
Society of Professional Journalists, to appoint a task force to
look into accusations of misbehavior by journalists and how federal
authorities regulated the news media. I was named to the
nine-person task force, which was headed by Bob Steele, director of
the ethics program at the Poynter Institute in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The task force spent months interviewing many people involved in
the standoff before releasing a printed report to the public on
Sept. 8, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Task force members were critical of some of the behavior of
journalists. For example, the members:
</P>
<P>
   _ Criticized a Dallas radio talk show that, the task force
concluded, interfered with the delicate negotiations by sending
messages to Koresh via radio broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   _ Voiced concern about reporting of rumors and using nightscopes
and telescopic lenses in a way that could give away positions or
tactics of law enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Asserted that too many news organizations ``over-covered this
story to the detriment of other stories in their own communities.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The task force also asserted that the FBI prevented
journalists from performing their duties adequately. The task force
stated in its report:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Federal Bureau of Investigation officials made the
decision to move the journalists away from the compound, saying it
was for the safety of the journalists, to get them further
out-of-range from weapons fire. While that concern for safety is
understandable, journalists have long chosen to accept physical
danger as part of their role in covering important stories, whether
it be war, civil unrest, terrorist actions or natural disasters.
...
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of Waco, journalists were kept so far away from
the front lines that they were not able to properly scrutinize the
actions of the law enforcement agencies and negotiators as they
attempted to resolve the standoff. Nor were journalists always able
to obtain as meaningful information as they needed to accurately
update all aspects of an important, evolving story. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Accuracy and perspective were the casualties of the lack of
access to the front lines and the absence of a more meaningful and
consistent flow of official information.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words took on new meaning recently. And that is what I had
feared six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   (Retired ombudsman Phil Record is a consultant to the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram and the newspaper's professional in residence in
Texas Christian University's Department of Journalism. He can be
contacted at precord(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
