<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0016 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     09-13 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD NEWS IS THAT DANFORTH IS IN CHARGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I first encountered John Danforth when he was attorney general
of Missouri and I was a reporter for the Belleville News-Democrat
in Illinois. He was impressive, even back then.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth exudes leadership and integrity in a way that few
politicians do. He was an outstanding U.S. senator. When he decided
not to seek a fourth term in 1994, the Senate lost one of its
finest members; the people of Missouri and America lost a great
advocate.
</P>
<P>
   So take this to the bank: Attorney General Janet Reno couldn't
have made a better choice when she asked Danforth to head up the
latest investigation of the 1993 Branch Davidian fiasco near Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth will do whatever needs to be done to learn the truth.
He will be diligent and objective. He will not be intimidated by
the FBI, by Reno or by Reno's boss at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   And he will not be influenced by political considerations _ no
matter who might try to influence him. Danforth is a Republican,
but he is renowned for his independence.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth only knows one way to a do a job, and that's the right
way.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news. The bad news is, there are people in this
country who will not be satisfied with Danforth's investigation
unless it confirms their belief that the government was responsible
for the deaths of David Koresh and 80 or so Davidians in that April
1993 fire at the cult's Texas headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   And here's a prediction: Danforth's investigation will produce
no evidence whatsoever to contradict the long-known truth of what
happened that day: Koresh was responsible for the deadly fire that
fulfilled his prophecy of a blazing apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   Independent arson investigators determined years ago that the
fire was set inside the Davidian compound, and there is every
reason to believe that the fire was the culmination of a
murder/suicide plot concocted by Koresh and carried out on that
particular day because it was obvious to him that the FBI was on
the verge of taking him into custody.
</P>
<P>
   But the facts are of no interest to the pro-Koresh crowd, which
refuses to accept conclusive evidence that the Davidians had
stockpiled a dangerous and illegal arsenal inside their compound.
The Davidian sympathizers also refuse to believe that the so-called
religion that Koresh preached to his cult revolved around his vile
and illegal use of young girls to satisfy his sexual compulsions _
a fact that was uncovered not only in a Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms investigation but also in a series of investigative
reports published by the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a word to the wise for the Koresh aficionados who've been
firing off letters and e-mails detailing their anti-government
conspiracy theories and their hopelessly fictional depictions of
Koresh as an innocent victim of overzealous federal law
enforcement: Do yourself a favor and stop sending me this junk.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard and/or read it all before. Don't you have something
more useful to do with your time than mindlessly wallow in
nonsensical paranoia and conjure up idiotic justifications for the
psychotic behavior of a child molester/mass murderer?
</P>
<P>
   But back to the investigation. There's certainly nothing wrong
with trying to find out if FBI agents or other federal officials
withheld evidence such as that newly released videotape suggesting
that agents used potentially flammable tear-gas canisters several
hours before Koresh torched the Davidians' compound.
</P>
<P>
   If law enforcement officials covered up lawbreaking or other
inappropriate conduct by federal agents, the public has a right to
know about it _ and anyone involved should be held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   What we don't need is to rehash every detail of this sorry
episode with all the attending political exploitation, media
sensationalism and anti-government hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth has vowed to limit his investigation to the events of
April 19, 1993 _ the day of the fire _ and that's good. But
congressional investigators have made no such pledge _ and that's
bad.
</P>
<P>
   Here we go again.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
