<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0026 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-LANE-COLUMN14-COX     09-13 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't dis dinking around
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I want to speak of dinking around.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, dinking around the house.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to be confused with home decorating. It should not
be confused with home repair. But it does include elements of both.
</P>
<P>
   There are no magazines, no television shows or cable channels
dedicated to dinking around the house. I suspect this is merely a
failure of marketing. More people dink around their house than
restore it, remodel it, redecorate it or fix it up. This has to be
a vast unrecognized audience.
</P>
<P>
   But let us back up and define our terms.
</P>
<P>
   Dink. The word sounds like a straw dropping into an empty cola
can. Since at least the dawn of the century, it has been used to
denote things small, and maybe a little dumb and ineffectual.
</P>
<P>
   Take that verb and add ``around'' to it, a construction that
emphasizes lack of any particular direction, and the result is a
phrase for tending to the small stuff in small ways with an
indifferent level of accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   As in: ``How long are you going to sit there dinking around on
the computer? Isn't time to use it to write something? Like maybe a
column?'' Just an example.
</P>
<P>
   Dinking around on a computer is the No. 1 dinking around
activity of the 1990s. It allows us to dink around at speeds
previously unimaginable. Speeds that might seem too fast even to
allow for dinking.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully changing the wallpaper on Microsoft Windows or
customizing your color scheme (``I'll pick the Desert color group
with just a little light brightening of the active-window boxes'')
exemplifies the spirit of dinking around on the computer. Even if
you are doing it in half a blink of a beady eye at 400 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   Dinking around the house is more relaxing than dinking around on
a computer. Dinking around the Internet can give you muscle strains
that not even dinking around the garden will cause.
</P>
<P>
   For years, I have attempted to dignify dinking around the house
with the phrase home improvement. Everyone saw through me. The
concepts are altogether different.
</P>
<P>
   Putting up drywall is home improvement. Filling nail holes with
toothpaste is dinking around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing a water faucet is home improvement. Removing the dark
gooey stuff that forms around the faucet's base is dinking around
the house.
</P>
<P>
   Putting in a door is home improvement. Putting in a doorstop is
dinking around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Putting in ductwork is home improvement. Replacing an
air-conditioning filter clogged with animal fuzz is dinking around
the house.
</P>
<P>
   Painting the kitchen is home improvement. Getting the stray
pieces of masking tape off the bottom of the kitchen wall is
dinking around the house.
</P>
<P>
   You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean that we should be ashamed of dinking around?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely not. These aren't activities you watch on ``This Old
House'' or read about in Martha Stewart Living, but dinking around
the house is necessary maintenance, needed detail work, the
finishing touches.
</P>
<P>
   In home improvement as in life, politics, philosophy and world
history, people who take on big projects are seldom much good at
finishing them and taking care of the details and damage.
</P>
<P>
   Every great project demands weeks of dinking around afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes dinking around the house actually gives you more of a
feeling of accomplishment than undertaking a serious project. You
get the joy of finishing without the grind of building. A big
project always looks worse halfway through. By contrast, dinking
around the house brings nothing but improvement. Small improvement,
yes, but perceptible improvement.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise that the society that invented motivational
speaking as a paid profession would use the phrase ``dinking
around'' as a term of disparagement and ridicule. This is so wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Someday this attitude will change. But that will happen only a
little bit at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Which is, of course, how dinking around works.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is associate editor at The Daytona Beach News-Journal.
E-mail: marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
