</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: I am a portrait artist. I am thinking about
drawing portraits ofcelebrities and selling them. Is it legal for
me to do this? Do I first need to seek the celebrity I wish to
draw? _ Robert Wuest
</P>
<P>
   A: If you sell these images you need the celebrity's permission.
The right of publicity is protected by most states, which means a
celebrity's persona is protected against unauthorized commercial
use _ the sale of Elvis' image on velvet paintings has been halted
for this reason. Want to put these drawings on the wall of your
living room wall? Fine. Consult with an experienced entertainment
attorney before beginning this venture.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife and I occasionally cook with Mexican vanilla we buy
across the border. At full strength it really livens up dishes.
Someone at work had told me there were scares about toxic
contaminants in it. We like using the stuff, and figure since we
don't use much at a time it's OK. I've seen Mexican vanilla flavor
at Amy's Ice Cream. Is there a source of food-grade Mexican vanilla
here in the United States, or at least a brand on the Mexican
shelves that is considered OK? _ Carl Ponder
</P>
<P>
   A: The Food and Drug Administration does not recommend buying
Mexican vanilla since it often contains coumarin, a blood thinner.
Coumarin has been prohibited in food in the United States since
1940. Read labels carefully. Amy's ``Mexican vanilla'' refers to a
strong vanilla taste obtained from Madagascar beans.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I work for the O. Henry Museum here in town and we are
looking for the address for Arthur Miller. _ Stephanie Seay
</P>
<P>
   A: Arthur Miller receives his mail in care of ICM, 40 W. 57th
St., New York, N.Y. 10019. Congratulations! This year the O. Henry
Museum becomes a national Literary Landmark, the first in Texas.
The North Carolina native (William Sydney Porter) contracted
tuberculosis at 19 and moved to Texas after training as a
pharmacist. The source of his pen name? French pharmacist Etienne
Ossian Henry might have provided it _ or was it the prison guard,
Oliver?
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've noticed the use of ``fishes'' more often recently,
especially on TV, radio and print. Has the plural of fish become
fishes? I've looked it up in a dictionary; it seems as if one uses
fishes when referring to two fish of the same species _ fish when
referring to all species collectively. I certainly don't remember
this ever being discussed in grade school, high school or college _
one fish is a fish, two fish are fish! _ Randy Hawkins
</P>
<P>
   A: Fishes is an acceptable, albeit second, choice for the plural
of fish. Often, but not always, it refers to several species of
fish. Guess the commonality can be traced to Three Dog Night's
lyric, ``Joy to the fishes in the deep blue sea.'' But Felicia
Steele at the University of Texas Writing Center says fishes has
been used as an accepted plural since the Renaissance. The most
common plural question the center receives? How to make a plural
noun possessive when it ends in an s. Example: a witness's dinner
(one witness, one dinner); witnesses' dinners (many witnesses, many
dinners). Q: The American-Statesman publishes a column by Michael
Gartner, editor of The Tribune in Iowa. Could you provide his
address so I may contact him with a question? _ Jim Rankin
</P>
<P>
   A: Choose your mail _ electronic or snail? Contact Gartner at
mgartner(at)amestrib.com or The Tribune, P.O. Box 380, Ames, Iowa
50010. Q: Where might I find a cooktop cover that covers all four
burners at once? I saw one in a catalog but cannot find one in any
stores. _ Teri and Steve D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Various sizes of insulated covers are available from the
Vermont Country Store, which is my pick for all life's basics. Call
(802) 362-8440 to order one of the four sizes (largest is 17'' by
20'' and runs $10.95 plus shipping). Notice this is not a toll-free
call _ guess that's one way this operation has stayed profitable
since 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I suffer from total disinclination for criminal behavior and
don't foresee having to take a lie detector test in the normal
course of my life. But I am very keen to take one _ to satisfy my
curiosity, as a hopefully interesting experience. Where can I take
the test? How much would it cost? _ V.G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Just for fun?! The test can be administered by any licensed
examiner. The Polygraph Examiners Board can tell you whether an
examiner is licensed and if any grievances have been filed. Bob
Temple of Austin Security Agency says a test will take about an
hour and probably run you $250 _ a lot of money for an experience.
In most tests there should be only three to four significant
questions, with the remainder control questions. Temple's advice if
you are ever asked to take a polygraph in a serious matter? ``If
you are going to lie, don't take it; if you are going to tell the
truth, don't worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have lots of Beanie Babies my daughter doesn't want in her
room anymore. Can you tell me the best way to store them? I have
them in a snap-on plastic container. Does it need to be airtight _
like each one in a zipper plastic bag? _ Tish McCoy
</P>
<P>
   A: Hold on a minute, cowgirl. Beanie Babies are fabric, and the
best way to store any fabric is in acid-free tissue paper in an
acid-free box. Pick up both at the Container Store. Air needs to
circulate. In addition, Kim Blanchard of the Kerbey Lane Doll
Shoppe says Beanie Babies should be stored with the tag covered by
a protector to prevent mangling in storage. Always store heirloom
items in a climate-controlled area (not the attic in Texas). Heat
may cause plastic parts to melt. Plastic bags may trap moisture and
cause discoloration or fabric damage.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Horns lost in their opener and I did, too. A bet that is.
Now I have to send steaks to North Carolina. What, if any,
restaurants in town ship their steaks? I know County Line ships
their barbecue, but I'm looking for steak. _ Ella Young
</P>
<P>
   A: Pay off the bet in style with certified Angus beef from Lone
Star Foods. The most popular selection for gifts is the variety
pack (two tenderloins, strip loins and rib eyes). Call (800)
880-3161 or visit www.lonestarfoods.com. Your North Carolina
friends will be impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the geographical center of Texas? _ Steve N.
</P>
<P>
   A: A spot in McCulloch County, 15 miles northeast of Brady, the
county seat. The county was named for San Jacinto battle veteran
Gen. Ben McCulloch. Q: I have been using _ sparingly _ a can of
Glory Professional Strength rug cleaner made by S.C. Johnson. I
have not been able to find it in some years. I want to know if the
product is still being made and where I can get it. Also, I enjoy a
lotion put out by Lord and Mayfair that I have only found in hotels
when traveling. Where can I purchase it?
</P>
<P>
   _ S. Free
</P>
<P>
   A: Glory is no longer being made by S.C. Johnson; however, its
new product, Carpet Science, is. This is recommended as the
replacement to Glory. (You are not the first reader to sing its
praises.) Lord and Mayfair is made for the hotel trade. But you can
purchase their products from KMK Supply. Call (562) 531-2150 or
visit www.kmksupply.com. You will have to purchase an entire case.
But hey, Christmas is just around the corner!
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ Need a breather from a constant stream of junk mail and
unsolicited telemarketing calls? Send me a stamped self-addressed
envelope for the address (Internet and otherwise) to get some
relief.
</P>
<P>
   _ Several readers chided me for not mentioning a poem discussing
the importance of the dash on a tombstone. The dash represents the
years between one's birth and death and how these days are whiled
away. ``For that dash represents all the time/ That she spent alive
on earth. And now only those who loved her/ Know what that little
line is worth.'' For a complete copy, send me a stamped
self-addressed envelope.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
