<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Talking politics with the
Washington elite
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I'm sitting in a bar after work, chatting up some
big-time Washington reporters I've just met. They're drinking
Scotch, I'm drinking cola. How we split the bill is going to be
tricky.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a very nice bar. I particularly like the location _
part of a steakhouse. The bartender passes along a platter of
little sirloin sandwiches, about two-bite size. Nobody ever said
there's no free lunch, leastwise not in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters are talking politics. I'm listening politics. The
conversation comes around to Bush. Of course, they think I ought to
know something they don't, being from Texas. They expect too much.
</P>
<P>
   I tell them what I always say about our president-in-waiting.
Semi-quoting Gertrude Stein, who was the Molly Ivins of her day and
then some:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get there, there's not much there there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmm,'' I hear somebody say. I think I've made a point, then I
realize I've made a mistake. I misheard the remark:
</P>
<P>
   Not ``Hmmm'' but ``Mmmm'' _ that from a reporter in the process
of consuming another demi-sandwich. So much for meaty comments.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion farther down the bar puts Bush in the same catbird's
seat that Dukakis occupied in 1988, when Jesse Jackson was his only
serious competition for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   An African-American couldn't win, conventional wisdom ordained,
not even a tall, handsome, well-spoken candidate like Jesse. The
party had nowhere else to go but Dukakis. As it turned out, a short
Greek-American couldn't win either.
</P>
<P>
   Lest we forget, that was the election in which an incumbent vice
president was victorious. On the other hand, it was a fellow named
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Whether George W.'s fortunes rise like his father's before him,
or fall like the erstwhile Democratic frontrunner of a dozen years
ago, remains to be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   But it's difficult at this point to envision Gore suddenly
triumphant at the finish line, stumbler that he is.
</P>
<P>
   I know little about Gore other than what I see on television,
but whenever he's appearing before the cameras, it seems as if the
man loses the power to speak in contractions, such is his stilted
syntax.
</P>
<P>
   I once shared a table with Bush at an Austin newspaper luncheon
where he was speaking. He's an easygoing guv, easy to like on a
one-on-one basis and impressive from the podium. What I've seen of
him at the national level _ again, only on TV _ I'm of the opinion
that he's ``y'alling'' it a bit much.
</P>
<P>
   That down-home style is better received back home than it is
across the country. Lyndon Johnson, who couldn't shake his Texas
twang, suffered accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's not so much how they talk as what they say. One
of the reporters with whom I was sharing beverages complained that
none of the candidates could answer the hard questions.
</P>
<P>
   He gave abortion as an example. That's a hard one, all right.
I'm not so sure there is an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'm least satisfied with the candidate who says he's
against abortion, but he's also against banning abortion. Never
mind that's as close as I've come to having an opinion about
abortion myself.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe I expect too much from people who think they're
qualified to be president.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe too much, too, from people who are big-time reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa! Did I say that? Surely not. Must have been the cola
talking.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
