</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Miami evicts the First Amendment
 &HT;    (For release Sept. 15, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It was more than just an interesting question the woman
asked, it was profound and perplexing. She wanted to know why Miami
does not possess the First Amendment as does the rest of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   She was the promoter of a now-canceled Oct. 9 Miami appearance
of the renowned Cuban dance band Los Van Van, currently on tour
across the United States. The concert is not to be, shot down by
politicians and bellicose Cuban exiles.
</P>
<P>
   The exiles rightfully say they have a right to the First
Amendment, too, but the way they use that right denies the right to
others. Frankly, I thought this issue was decided years ago when
the Supreme Court ruled that Nazis had the right to parade through
Jewish-dominated Skokie, Ill., no matter how much the offended Jews
complained.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, in Miami, those decisions are adjudicated on
Spanish-language radio, at coffee counters, and at parochial
commission meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Clamorous Cuban exiles, in cahoots with their elected
compatriots, have done considerable damage to the community by
emulating a totalitarian state, accepting no dissent, shutting down
what they feel objectionable _ including events that are clearly
constitutional and, more recently, specifically allowable by the
U.S. government in its relationship with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   In the Los Van Van situation, the city forced the city-owned
theater to withdraw its booking date.
</P>
<P>
   Some Cuban exiles like to boast that Miami was a sleepy little
town until they got here beginning in 1960 _ it was far more
advanced than they like to think _ but what has happened in the
last three decades is that Miami's politics has fallen under the
control of a cabal, elected and self-appointed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest fiasco is but another in a long series of events in
which exile behavior has stifled the rights of the overall
community. Non-Hispanics, reaching minority status, are left to
ponder how much more they can take before fleeing elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Miami had to withdraw as a potential host for
the 2007 Pan American Games when the County Commission voted to
remove any aid to the games if Cuban athletes competed.
</P>
<P>
   There have been orchestras, singers, dancers and academicians
from Cuba traveling freely across the U.S. under the existing
U.S.-Cuba cultural exchange policy, but rarely in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   On those occasions when they did appear, bands of exiles also
would appear, spitting at and cursing the patrons as they entered
the theater.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Los Van Van, reportedly Cuba's top dance band,
the argument from the politicians and exiles is that Los Van Van
works for Fidel Castro and whatever money they earn, they earn for
Fidel _ and the exiles don't want their money going to Fidel.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a position as hypocritical as Hurricane Floyd is large.
While they may have prevented Los Van Van from wiring bucks to
Fidel, they do the same themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Cuban exiles have been returning to the island to
bring to relatives food, medicines and money. They don't even have
to go there to get money into relatives' hands in Cuba. By existing
U.S. law, they are permitted to send $300 via Western Union every
three months.
</P>
<P>
   A not-long-ago story referred to the fact that Cuban exiles,
principally from Miami, annually bring millions of dollars in cash,
goods and medicines to Cuba. While they may think the money is
going to the family, and stopping there, they are blind to reality.
Their families cannot eat the money; they buy things with it. As a
result, much of that money winds up in Fidel's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Miami's reputation _ under constant assault regarding
crime, immigration woes and political corruption _ sinks lower and
lower as the exile community, now in political power at both the
city and county level, enforces its narrow version of the First
Amendment, despite the fact that when many of them were at their
naturalization ceremonies, they swore to uphold and defend the
Constitution of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
