<HEADER>
A0034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN14-COX     09-13 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting some ideas about fashion off my chest
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Global warming is a serious problem. I know
full well that somewhere north of Lake Erie an icecap is melting
that will one day float my garage to Terre Haute. But it is not the
big news of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The communications breakdown between Hillary and Bill on the
clemency thing is dead serious because it's costing the lady votes
in her bid for a Senate seat, and if she loses the race that means
she and Bill are stuck with a big house in Westchester, a $1.35
million mortgage, and not a job between them. But that's not the
(SET ITAL)really(END ITAL) big news either.
</P>
<P>
   Even the graphic description of 16 different ways short people
can die from airbag impact (I'm five-three) that I heard on PBS
news on my drive home from the gym where I go daily to inflict pain
upon myself in an attempt to live a longer and healthier life, was
not front page stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, the headliner this week is the debate over where
or not television personality Kathie Lee Gifford is guilty of
showing up for work without a bra.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the network denies receiving viewer complaints that
their lady of the morning is going on camera sans restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Regis Philbin, Kathie Lee's co-host, will neither confirm nor
deny the naughty rumor, but is not above a double entendre or two.
``We've been together for 15 years,'' the gentleman quips, ``and
she likes to stay, pardon the expression, abreast of the fashion
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, I don't get the brouhaha over a bosom, but I must
admit it is not without historical precedent. Throughout the
centuries, women's chests have been points of contention to be
alternately flaunted then flattened, usually by fashion, but
occasionally by self-appointed guardians of society's morals.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth century B.C., Greek women were encouraged to keep
their bosom in check by tying a wide rag around it to be sure
nothing was going to break loose and jiggle. Historians blame this
on the Greeks' passion for beauty and harmony. Bouncing bosoms
disturbed the delicate balance.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of the Roman Empire, bosoms were bound in an
attempt to slow their growth, but if that didn't work, the
offending objects were squashed into leather bras called
mamillares. Less well-endowed ladies could get away with wearing a
thing called a strophium _ a scarflike cloth tied around the chest
that also came in handy for hanging oneself in a jail cell should
she be caught plotting to overthrow Nero.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, women's chests have been either ignored or adored,
according to who was running the show. In the early Middle Ages,
Christian women gave up binding and went braless for several
hundred years, but by the 12th century, things had gotten so out of
hand that German ladies were told to cover 'em up, tie 'em down,
and STOP hanging bells from them.
</P>
<P>
   In the 13th century, The Church ignored lowering necklines but
railed vehemently against women whose dresses allowed a glimpse of
their feet. The ladies countered, and the longer the train on their
gowns, the deeper the neckline plunged.
</P>
<P>
   By the 18th century, women were being tugged, laced, tied, and
strapped into contraptions that made the Iron Maiden look like
weekend wear. Whalebone corsets were in such demand that the Dutch
fishermen could hardly ever get home from the North Sea. As a
result, ribcages were crushed, ribs broken, and women were dying _
all in the name of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere in the late 1700s, the daring Mme. Tallien, queen
of Paris chic, showed up at a ball wearing a sleeveless silk tunic,
sandals, and NO underwear. The town reeled but the revolution did
not begin.
</P>
<P>
   Since it has long been my theory that wars are caused by folks
suffering from
</P>
<P>
   flatulence brought on by their underwear, I suggest we cut
Kathie Lee a little
</P>
<P>
   slack. Maybe she's on a peace mission.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett (AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
