<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buildings go up at Baylor as generation's labors bear generous
fruit
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Either it's the best of times to be a college
fund-raiser, or like a marathon dancer you just want someone to put
you out of your weary misery.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's the best of times. Just ask Baylor University.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a pretty good time to be renting out cranes. Not to
besmirch any reputation, but with all those heavy lifters rocking
and reeling this year, Baylor is one swinging place.
</P>
<P>
   Almost $80 million in construction has been going on _ 10
projects, including the most pricey Baylor capital project ever, a
$21 million Student Life Center opening Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The center will feature an indoor pool with water slide, ``lazy
river'' and spa, four basketball courts, racquetball and squash,
sand volleyball and a 52-feet-high indoor climbing rock that looks
like a life-form cloned by Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   A 1,000-car parking garage is going up. A new baseball-softball
complex is wrapping up. Plans are to break ground next year on a
new home on University Parks Drive jointly for the Strecker Museum
and Ollie Mae Moen Discovery Center. The Hankamer School of
Business and two dormitory dining halls have gotten makeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Groundbreaking is on the horizon for the four-year-old Truett
Theological Seminary, now housed at First Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Also coming up: a new law school and a new science building, the
latter a project to compare in scope and cost to the Student Life
Center.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all. Locals are accustomed to calling Waco a
one-skyscraper town. Well, look at what's gone up at Floyd Casey
Stadium. With new luxury boxes and a new press box rising over the
west stands, pair this high-rise with the 22-story ALICO building
to the east and say, ``Look, twin towers.''
</P>
<P>
   To further astound: All this is being built without debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baylor has for decades had a policy and a practice that it did
not build buildings for which it did not have cash in hand or
pledges to be paid,'' said Jonathan Lindsay, director of donor and
information services for Baylor's Office of University Development.
</P>
<P>
   That's no debt, fiscally. But institutionally Lindsey
acknowledges a heavy debt _ to a World War II generation that's now
coming through for Baylor like tanks in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   These are entrepreneurs and professionals who started with
little and made more than they ever imagined, building on a higher
education. Now they give back.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back and research,'' said Lindsey, ``you can find
tales from the '40s and '50s like, `I came to Baylor with a
cardboard suitcase and all my clothes in it, and Baylor took me in
and loved me and taught me, and now I feel a responsibility to
return to that institution a portion of that which I have been able
to earn because of what that institution did for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far the baby boom generation, said Lindsey, is harder to
crack as a donor class, possessing a more consumerist attitude: I
paid for my education; call back when I'm old.
</P>
<P>
   But Baylor has to give credit to at least two boomer alums,
Harold Nix and John Eddie Williams, who along with elder litigator
Walter Umphreys, rode home from the Tobacco Wars with much loot in
their saddle bags. They combined to donate $20 million to plans for
the new law school from Texas' $3 billion settlement against Cancer
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In almost every case a major donor has served as the pulley
needed to raise the new roofs at Baylor. But giving has been
broad-based. Up to 2,200 donors gave toward the Student Life
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Many things, besides charity itself, have contributed to the
giving boom. A bull stock market has contributed immensely, with
universities across the country getting gifts in highly productive
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   A key tax law change earlier this decade made a big difference.
It allowed appreciated stock donated to charities to not count as a
capital gain (added tax liability) for the giver, while the
receiving institution got the stock's real value.
</P>
<P>
   But tax advantages aren't the story, said Paul Marx, who
monitors these things as Baylor's director of taxes and compliance
accounting.
</P>
<P>
   The real difference, he said, has been salesmanship and the fact
that when Herbert Reynolds was succeeded by Robert Sloan as
president in 1995 Baylor didn't lose a president, it gained a
chancellor and a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real difference has been Sloan and Reynolds (as
chancellor) both out there working hard raising funds.'' He also
cited the role of Vice President for Development Richard Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one heavy hitter before in Dr. Reynolds. Now we have
three,'' said Marx.
</P>
<P>
   And though the green-bloods grow weepy with pride at the sight
of the gold-helmeted throng that goes to battle on Saturdays in the
fall, another team, 20 full-time development officers, plus a
separate contingent in the athletic department, sweats buckets
behind the scenes year-round _ working seven days in the week in
the fall _ helping raise all this money.
</P>
<P>
   Stand up. Bear claws all around. $80 million cash _ now, that's
a Baylor line to which anyone can sing.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
