<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even on Web, all eggs don't hatch
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So, who wants to be a millionaire?
</P>
<P>
   You do, and you're pretty sure you don't have to spend 30
minutes sitting across from Regis Philbin on that TV game show to
be a millionaire. No, not you. You've got a better way.
</P>
<P>
   You have an idea for a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just any Web site. You're thinking about an e-commerce,
interactive, user friendly, full-service-technology solution,
filled with every whiz-bang gizmo and gadget all the big guys have.
It's a winner. You know it is. All you have to do is find somebody
to give you a few bucks to get this revolutionary site up and
running.
</P>
<P>
   Now, plenty of firms are willing to give money to fledgling
Internet companies, but they tend to want to see things like
business plans, profit-and-loss statements and all kinds of other
paperwork before they will throw millions of dollars at you. Sure,
it's unfair, but that's how it is.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, Jeff Levy, one of the founders of Relevant
Knowledge, came along with an idea for a new Internet incubator
called eHatchery. The Atlanta-based company will work with Internet
start-ups to help them not only get their ventures off the ground
but also give them the day-to-day business savvy to run a company.
</P>
<P>
   His idea is very simple. Levy, founder of the Web measurement
firm Relevant Knowledge, which later merged with Media Metrix,
knows that even the best ideas have to be honed before you can ask
anyone, even your grandmother, for money.
</P>
<P>
   eHatchery's plan is to give entrepreneurs a grounding in
business practices and how the Internet industry works so ideas can
become companies that won't be laughed out onto the street when
they go looking for serious money.
</P>
<P>
   Although eHatchery makes it very clear on its Web page
(www.ehatchery.com) that the company is serious business, somehow a
``come one, come all'' feeling seems to have gripped everyone from
legitimate Web developers to the people who actually watch those
``Make tons of money on the Internet by selling the products we
tell you to sell'' infomercials.
</P>
<P>
   Calls and inquiries to eHatchery were pouring in, according to
one eHatchery staffer, and here at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, callers wanted to know how to contact Levy.
When they were told that the best way was via the company's Web
site, some people actually seemed surprised this was the Internet
incubator's preferred method of communication.
</P>
<P>
   Some callers to the newspaper were looking for a fax number to
send ideas to the company, but the rules for idea submission are
laid out on the Web site, and if you want to start a Web company,
filling out a form on the Web is a pretty good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wrong to think the only people who are calling
eHatchery or any other incubator or venture capital firm are people
with get-rich-quick schemes. Quite a few people out there are
working on what could be the next Yahoo!, WebMD or Relevant
Knowledge just waiting to be discovered. Once they have the tools
to do business and form partnerships, they could actually make it
big.
</P>
<P>
   The surprising response to eHatchery's debut says a lot of
things about how people still think about the Internet. Many people
still see it as the Wild West where anybody can ride into Dodge
City and become Marshal Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the millions of articles devoted to technology and the
Internet and all the people moaning about how commercial the Web
has become, some people still think a Web site is a ticket to
financial freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it for a minute. Even Yahoo! has trouble turning a
profit, and Internet service provider MindSpring has decided to
forgo making a profit in favor of expanding the company. Take a
look at the registration statement for Salon's initial public stock
offering. They say, for everyone to see, that they might never make
any money on the Web. Ever. And this is one of the Web's most
popular sites.
</P>
<P>
   EHatchery already has a few companies under its wing and
probably will sign on quite a few more. Many of them probably have
great ideas that one day will become household names to both
consumers and stockholders. But a pile of money and a vague idea is
not enough to make anyone an online millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes even a good idea and a pile of money aren't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
