<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-ONLINEBUDDIES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online `friends' may not be what they appear
 &HT;    By Anne Y. Meyers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lindsay Taylor, a teen-ager from Dallas, logs onto
America Online about five hours each week. She visits with her
friends and knows how to avoid strangers.
</P>
<P>
   On one particular night, Lindsay goes online about 9 p.m. She's
receives three instant messages. Since she knows the senders, she
replies back. But it's not long before someone in New York is
asking what she looks like. ``Ughh,'' she says. ``It makes me mad.
I don't want to spend my time talking to him. I either ignore them
or put a rude message back to them.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all possible online threats may be so obvious _ online
strangers may seem like ``friends.'' More than 5 million kids under
age 12 surfed the Net in the United States in 1998, and many are
sharing information that seems safe. However, even the simplest
facts about your interests, family or community can be too much to
tell a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is not like a video game or a TV show,'' says Kim
McCreery, spokeswoman for America Online. ``You are dealing with
real people out there. There are good people and there are bad
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Do not be afraid to venture online. But be leery of strangers
just as you would in a ballpark or mall. Here are some simple tips
to help keep you safe online:
</P>
<P>
   Protect your privacy. Do not give your name, address, school
name, phone number, church name, sports team, arts class or any
other specific details that would allow someone to find you.
</P>
<P>
   Do not accept e-mail attachments from strangers. Viruses that
can damage your computer can be sent via e-mail. Delete e-mail from
an unfamiliar address without even opening it.
</P>
<P>
   Never accept photographs from online ``friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell adults if someone makes you uncomfortable online. With some
Internet providers, you can forward inappropriate messages to their
security departments.
</P>
<P>
   You must never give your password online, even if a person says
they work for your Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Do not meet an online friend in person without your parents'
permission.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the person you are talking to may not be who they
say they are. Have fun on the Web, but beware of wolves in sheep's
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Morning News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
