<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    East Timor wants freedom
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a place most of us have never heard of, but its
story sounds all too familiar: In the region of East Timor, the
people want to break away from the Asian nation of Indonesia, and
now armed groups of Indonesian thugs are attacking the Timorese.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Indonesia announced it would allow an international
peacekeeping force to restore order to the devastated territory of
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was unclear what type of force would be sent to the
territory, and how soon it would arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Until now Jakarta had refused to permit outside forces into the
former Portuguese colony, insisting as late as Saturday night that
it could quell the violence itself. However, that stance crumpled
under pressure from governments around the world upset about the
slaughter sweeping East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Ads target cheaters
</P>
<P>
   A TV ad campaign was launched last week to try to get kids to
quit cheating on schoolwork.
</P>
<P>
   The first two commercials in the campaign have a sports theme.
``Do the work, take the test, listen to the ref in your head,''
they say. ``Cheating is a personal foul.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads are aimed at students 10 to 14 years old. Studies have
shown that more students than ever are cheating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are doing it because it's easy. Some are doing it because
they just don't want to be left out,'' said Donald McCabe, founder
of the Center for Academic Integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton authorizes gun buyback
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is making $15 million available to local
police departments to buy guns that might otherwise be used in
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been reminded in recent months, from Los Angeles to
Littleton to Atlanta, gun violence is still too much a part of
America's life,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   If the police pay $50 apiece to buy the guns, they would be able
to collect 300,000 weapons with the money.
</P>
<P>
   The president also announced grants to allow cities to hire
about 1,600 more police officers, including 750 to monitor hallways
and classrooms in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Noggin knocks can hurt memory
</P>
<P>
   Playing football and soccer could be bad for your brain.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists found that young athletes suffer thousands of brain
injuries, called ``concussions,'' every year. Concussions,
particularly for people who have more than one, can cause long-term
brain impairments.
</P>
<P>
   Football is a leading cause. But scientists also reported that
soccer players scored lower on tests of memory than other athletes
did.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the problem may be ``heading'' the ball, but
experts believe a more likely explanation is frequent collisions
between players and players' heads hitting the ground or a
goalpost.
</P>
<P>
   So be careful out there!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
