<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mavis Beacon's bottom line: Still a good typing program
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Those of you who have been involved with computers for
15 years or so will be glad to know that Mavis Beacon still Teaches
Typing.
</P>
<P>
   Mavis looks as good as ever. Actually, she doesn't look like the
Mavis I remember from previous editions, but after all, this is
Version 10. How many Version 10s have you see lately? Not even
MS-DOS made it to Version 10.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund's Mavis Beacon Teaches Typing is by far the
longest-lived program I know. The copyright goes back to 1987, but
somehow it seems older to me.
</P>
<P>
   As far as I can tell, nothing has changed, basically. After all,
typing is typing is typing, and this is amply illustrated by the
fact that Mavis' versions 5, 8 and 9 still are available. The
keyboard still is the same, unless you use one of those Microsoft
keyboards, and Mavis makes allowances for that.
</P>
<P>
   It also asks the student at the outset what sort of skills are
required _ ordinary typing or 10-key typing, in which one hand is
used to enter numerals only.
</P>
<P>
   After deciding how good you want to be, i.e., how much better
than the basic 40 words per minute, you enter Mavis' classroom and
take a test.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose it makes a certain amount of cold, cruel sense to
force the student to type nonsense words; this presumably puts
everyone on a level field. Typing complete sentences might allow
some students to go faster than others, although this isn't a
competition. I suppose I'm just whining because Mavis cut me off
after the first of a dozen or so lines and said she had seen enough
to know how to tailor a program for me.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently I went to the bottom of the class, because we began
with our little hands on the home row, typing words like fasd, dsf
or safd. Mavis was most encouraging; I had the feeling that in
another 10 minutes of this, had I retained my sanity, her manicured
hand, short fingernails and all, would have emerged from the
monitor to offer me a piece of candy.
</P>
<P>
   So you can see that learning to type hasn't changed a whole lot
in 40 years or so, which is why I never learned. I taught myself
(the Warner method) and I can fairly fly with a good keyboard and
the wind in the right direction. Uncharitable editors would tell
you that I average five typos to the sentence, but in my view
that's what editors are there for _ and it would be churlish to
deprive them of work.
</P>
<P>
   Mavis Beacon has a lot more than basic drudgery up her sleeve,
at least on the DeLuxe version. At the media center, you can go to
a practice center and type actual sentences (some of which might
even have some meaning to you). There are a number of subjects from
which to choose, from astronomy to poetry.
</P>
<P>
   You also can get the latest views on ergonomics for typists. You
can take a test to judge the ergonomics of your own setup. I shut
off the video before it was finished discussing my desk, chair and
so forth, but the general opinion seemed to be that only the
Hunchback of Notre Dame could long survive it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a whole bunch of typing games test speed, accuracy
and, in some instances, patience. By and large they are good fun,
and anyone using this program to learn typing will find them a
welcome break.
</P>
<P>
   Mavis is a strict taskmaster. You cannot swap in and out of the
program, and the task bar is unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   I would assume that Mavis Beacon has the software typing
tutorial market pretty much to itself by now. Certainly a lot of
typing programs have come and gone over the years, some of them
rather bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   Mavis V10 Deluxe lists for $50 and includes a soft rubber ball
for strengthening your hands (one at a time) and a rather strange
mouse pad with a big padded speed bump at one end. You should have
no trouble finding Mavis in stores, but in case you want to check
out the older versions, go to www.mavisbeacon.com _ it even has an
essay on the history of typing.
</P>
<P>
   I could not, however, find the answer to the biggest question of
all _ is Mavis Beacon merely the Betty Crocker of the keyboard, or
was she a real typing teacher?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
