<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When cell phone rings, turn off beeper and smell the cherries
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To my grandfather, the height of technology amounted
to an old GE television that only displayed colors in pastel _
everyone from Lawrence Welk's piano lady to Fran Tarkenton
scrambling for a few extra yards was one pastel shade or another.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have a computer or a fax machine or an e-mail account.
The closest thing to a wireless phone came about the time my
grandmother tripped and ripped the cord to the black rotary dial
phone loose from the wall.
</P>
<P>
   A chat group for him was a Sunday on the front porch with my
grandmother. They'd sit in identical cane-bottom rocking chairs and
talk. They didn't need nicknames, and there was no need to check
the connection; it was always good.
</P>
<P>
   Something else he had, compared with me, was time. There was
time to sit on the porch, time to lie back in his hammock and watch
the way the birds got drunk on the fermented berries from his wild
cherry tree.
</P>
<P>
   As I grow older, I grow more nostalgic for the days when life
didn't need modems or cell phones. It was a life pretty much
without words composed of initials. There were no ISPs, no OS to
choose, no IP addresses _ just the sort of life that seems so odd
when we visit it on a black and white movie.
</P>
<P>
   I know that, by saying all this, I risk this reaction: Hey!
You're supposed to be an advocate of technology, not some grouch
who thinks anything that plugs in and beeps is a tool of the devil.
</P>
<P>
   That's the point. I don't think that technology is bad. I have
the usual assortment of cell phones, Internet providers, computer
games, cable modems and even a dusty old ham radio station. I know
to grab a soldering iron by the cool end, and I can recite Ohm's
Law and tell you the difference between a PNP and NPN transistor.
Ask my friends. I'm in love with technology. But it's not blind
love.
</P>
<P>
   My problem with technology isn't the gadgets. There are times
when the cell phone has saved me great misery; the computer keeps
me in touch with friends all over the world; and even the computer
games can be great ways to spend a Sunday _ a lot less mindless
than watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   My problems are aimed at two groups:
</P>
<P>
   _ The people who create technology. What a wonderful tool it
truly is. And what a terrific failure it has been in some key
areas. The model for new technology ought to be the telephone. It
comes without a user's manual; it works most of the time; and no
real upkeep or knowledge is required from the user. Most of the
technology these days comes with a thick manual written in a
language only vaguely reminiscent of English.
</P>
<P>
   _ The users of technology, a group that includes most of us. I
think that, instead of using technology as a tool to solve real
problems, most of us have given over too much of our lives to
living better electronically. We spend too much time online, too
little time in the real world. Our gadgets have become chains. If
you think I'm wrong, pay attention to the people around you who
carry cellular phones to the golf course or Disney World, afraid
they'll miss a call. All this instant communication by cell phone
and e-mail overloads us, I think, creating a world where the
messages come at the speed of light, and every problem has to be
solved instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us can't do much about the
too-complicated-for-ordinary-humans gadgets and computer programs.
We keep buying them and _ as long as we do _ there's no real
motivation for the manufacturers to change.
</P>
<P>
   We can chip away at the other problem: being too dependent on
technology to solve life's problems. We occasionally can run a
systems check to see if our lives have become too plugged in. If we
have, there's always a fine low-tech solution that's still around.
Look for two sturdy rocking chairs and try a leisurely low-speed
connection to life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
