<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sites help to find the right college
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ September has become the real start of the new year
for many of us. After years of going to school, September becomes a
natural beginning. If you or someone you know plans to start to
college in a year, this is the right time to begin planning _ both
for selecting the college and for preparing for the financial
burden college can bring.
</P>
<P>
   While the Web does not offer a replacement for campus visits and
sessions with your banker, it can be a valuable tool.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we'll take a look at some of the sites that offer real
help. The first is All About College at www.allaboutcollege.com/.
It makes a good starting spot because it offers a real variety of
information _ links and advice about financial aid, fraternities,
study abroad, student jobs and even some help on where to go for
spring break.
</P>
<P>
   The real meat here is in the section about individual colleges.
At this site, you'll find links to almost every public and private
college. The links _ arranged by state _ take you directly to the
school's Web page and to e-mail addresses for more information.
Don't expect a critical review of the college here. We'll find
those elsewhere. What you get is at least as valuable, a direct
connection to the colleges of interest and a fast way to find
almost any college on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The next site is a real knockout punch. It's the U.S. News &AMP;
World Report college site at
www.usnews.com/usnews/edu/college/cohome.htm. There are so many
features here that we'll just look at the unique ones. You probably
already realize that U.S. News is known for its reviews of colleges
in the print edition. That means this site draws from a solid
database of information.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best features is the ability to do a side-by-side
comparison of two or three colleges. You simply type in the names
of the colleges that interest you and, at the click of a mouse, get
a very detailed comparison. And, because part of the information
you enter is your ZIP code, you'll also find out how long the
commute home would be for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Other features also take advantage of the magazine's store of
knowledge. You can use a pull-down menu to get a list of what the
magazine considers to be the best colleges or the colleges that
offer the most diversity or the ones that have the most
international students. You also can use a separate pull-down menu
to find out about topics such as considerations faced by older
students, what to look for when you make a campus visit and
information about distance learning.
</P>
<P>
   Spend some time on this page, because this is just a surface
scan of the features offered. Most parents and potential students
probably could make a decent informed decision solely based on what
is offered here.
</P>
<P>
   Our next stop is called Peterson's The College Channel at
www.petersons.com/ugrad/. The quality here also is top-notch, with
enough unique information _ including about financial aid and
preparing for college entrance tests _ to make this a worthwhile
addition to our college tour.
</P>
<P>
   Because higher education doesn't always mean a conventional
four-year program, there are links to information about such places
as culinary arts schools, nursing programs and schools that
specialize in training for the performing arts.
</P>
<P>
   One avenue of financial aid for students is the monetary
assistance offered by some ROTC programs. You'll find a link that
will help you learn if that's a viable option.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
