<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN14-C     09-13 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After 20 years, still waiting for better TVBy Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _ The first time I covered
<TEXT>
the fall TV season, there were 21 new series on three networks.
Some shows were good, some were awful. Only two lasted the entire
season. One was put out of its misery after three weeks.
<P>
   That was in 1979, way back when cable wasn't a factor and Fox,
WB and UPN didn't exist. This is my 20th anniversary as a TV
critic, the 20th time I've previewed the new fall TV shows. Every
year I get excited; most years, my hopes are dashed.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, we'll see 38 new series on six broadcast
networks _ and a few more on the various cable networks. That's in
addition to the growing number of syndicated series. And some are
good, some are awful and many are destined to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Are we couch potatoes better off now than we were then? We
certainly have more choices, but do we want any of those choices?
</P>
<P>
   Sitcoms are cruder and dramas are racier now. That's the most
noticeable change in our ``progress'' over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   A sitcom like Fox's new ``Action,'' riddled with bleeped out
F-words, wouldn't have gotten past the idea stage, let alone on the
air 20 years ago. The top-rated sitcom in 1979 was ``Three's
Company,'' which seems innocent now but was blasted for its double
entendres. Other popular comedies were ``MASH,'' ``Alice'' and the
``Alice'' spinoff ``Flo.'' Not exactly ``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   The red-hot drama was ``Dallas,'' featuring the deliciously evil
J.R. Ewing. But he seems tame now. Why were we so shocked when J.R.
cheated on Sue Ellen, swindled Bobby and duped Miss Ellie? That was
before ``Melrose Place,'' ``Dawson's Creek'' and this season's
ultra-tawdry teen sex show, ``Manchester Prep.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah. Times have changed. The most popular network dramas
are the hard-charging, adult series like ``ER,'' ``NYPD Blue'' and
``Law &AMP; Order.'' Writers strive for reality, but apparently reality
bites: Language is saltier and violence is grislier. People aren't
just shot and stabbed _ they're shot in the face and disemboweled.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ``Dallas,'' the popular dramas in '79 were ``The Dukes
of Hazzard,'' ``Eight Is Enough'' and ``Little House on the
Prairie.'' All would be TV-G.
</P>
<P>
   Of the series that debuted in the fall of '79, one was superb.
Not surprisingly, it was canceled within a month. ``The
Associates'' was a comedy about a snobby law firm headed by Wilfred
Hyde-White. Co-stars were Martin Short, Alley Mills and Joe
Regalbuto. B.B. King sang the theme song. It was first-rate all the
way, but ABC pulled the plug.
</P>
<P>
   That's a familiar problem, a thread that unites decades of
network programming. I still remember (and sometimes even mourn)
several fine shows that were killed before viewers found them _
``Palmerstown U.S.A.,'' ``Frank's Place,'' ``I'll Fly Away,'' ``The
Famous Teddy Z,'' ``Call to Glory,'' to name just a few.
</P>
<P>
   Another change in the past 20 years is the onslaught of
newsmagazines. This fall there are a dozen hours devoted to
newsmagazines. In '79, ``60 Minutes'' and ``20/20'' each had a
single episode a week. ``Dateline NBC,'' which now gobbles up five
hours of prime time, didn't exist until 1992. ``Primetime Sunday,''
the first of NBC's many failed attempts before ``Dateline,''
debuted in '79 with Tom Snyder as host.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the stars of this fall's new series are newcomers. Most
of the stars of '79's new series were well-known, including Eileen
Brennan, Brian Dennehy, Louis Gossett Jr., Jack Elam, Shirley
Jones, Joe Don Baker, James Earl Jones, Jim Belushi, Michael Keaton
and Robert Conrad. TV executives now prefer to hire cheap unknowns
and make them stars.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a trivia tidbit: Dixie Carter played an angel in '79's
new sitcom ``Out of the Blue''; this fall she co-stars in a new
drama, ``Family Law.'' In between, she had the long-running hit
``Designing Women.'' Talk about staying power. Another TV star with
``legs,'' as they say, is Doris Roberts of ``Everybody Loves
Raymond.'' In '79, she co-starred in the new sitcom ``Angie.''
</P>
<P>
   We won't know for a few weeks what this year's big disasters
are, but the fall of '79 produced a trio of notable flops. ``The
Ropers,'' a lackluster spinoff of ``Three's Company,'' was the
first to croak. McLean Stevenson left ``MASH'' to star in ``Hello,
Larry,'' which barely lasted until Christmas. And the wildly
successful ``Columbo'' spawned ``Kate Loves a Mystery,'' starring
Kate Mulgrew as the detective's wife. The spinoff collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   By my calculation, I've seen at least 500 fall previews over the
years. That excludes midseason series, movies and miniseries. You'd
think I'd be visually impaired and crazy by now. I still have my
eyesight, but my sanity, well, that's questionable.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, television has changed a lot. We're up to our
ears in cable channels and on the cusp of the digital revolution,
facing an even bigger explosion of choices. But with the exception
of a few bad words and more gruesome violence, the programs that
spill out of the box haven't changed that much. Maybe they will in
the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   TUNE IN: Rerun season is almost over! Fox's amusingly gritty new
family drama ``Get Real'' airs its pilot again tonight at 7 and
then moves to its regular slot Wednesday at 8. Debrah Farantino and
Jon Tenney star as an estranged duo with a trio of teens ... Beau
Bridges plays the colorful circus entrepreneur in the conclusion of
A&AMP;E's two-part ``P.T. Barnum,'' tonight at 7 ... ``Journey to the
Center of the Earth,'' a two-parter based on the Jules Verne novel
and starring Treat Williams, airs Tuesday and Wednesday at 7 p.m.
on USA ... Fox's foul language-bleeped sitcom ``Action,'' starring
Jay Mohr as a slimy Hollywood producer, debuts Thursday at 8 p.m.
... And ``A Slight Case of Murder,'' a truly wonderful comedy-drama
starring William H. Macy, debuts Sunday at 7 p.m. on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   TUNE OUT: Just when you thought it was safe to watch TV again
... NBC's ``World's Most Amazing Videos,'' Wednesday at 8, shows a
bull kicking a man into the air and a racehorse instigating a
multihorse pile-up on the track ... You'll want to be sure to miss
the second season premiere of Fox's ``World's Wildest Police
Videos,'' Thursday at 7 p.m. ... And Pamela Anderson Lee's fabulous
feature ``Barb Wire'' airs at 8 p.m. on the Sci-Fi Channel.
</P>
