<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUFFDADDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUFF DADDY GOES POOF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He compared himself with Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would last forever.
</P>
<P>
   He hinted that some day he might run for president.
</P>
<P>
   And he called himself the black Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   But after just three weeks into his campaign to recapture the
charts, about all Sean ``Puffy'' Combs is looking for is to sell
some CDs. Quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forever,'' the second CD by the New York
rapper/producer/fashion plate/entrepreneur/multimillionaire, is not
doing nearly as well as was predicted, or hyped.
</P>
<P>
   Released Aug. 17, it sold 205,000 copies its first week,
according to SoundScan. By the second week, sales were nearly half
that, 119,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of more than 200,000 copies are certainly respectable, but
this is an era when superstars from Ricky Martin to Garth Brooks to
the Backstreet Boys have sold more than 500,000 copies their first
week.
</P>
<P>
   Which is about 300,000 copies less than Puff's 1997 debut, ``No
Way Out,'' sold its first week.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more troubling, the CD debuted on the national R&AMP;B
charts at No. 87, a horrible showing in the very market he was
dominating the last time out.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Well, the first problem is that ``Forever'' is
simply not nearly as good as ``No Way Out'': A collection of empty
boasts and threats, it finds Puffy lost amid a sea of guest artists
and railing on and on about unidentified foes who would unseat him
from his position of power.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sort of CD that practically begs usage of the word
``disaster,'' and predictably enough it has received negative
reviews from numerous major publications, ranging from ``The
Philadelphia Inquirer'' to ``People.''
</P>
<P>
   But does the hip-hop nation really care about what Tom Moon or I
have to say about Puffy? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, ``Forever'' isn't doing especially well partially
because of the transitory, here-today-gone-today nature of pop
music, and partially because the first single, ``P.E. 2000,''
didn't light anybody's fire.
</P>
<P>
   But a big part of Puffy's sales woes of late are because he's
simply an easy guy to dislike. He faces the world with a grim,
unsmiling face, his eyes usually hidden behind shades. Many rappers
have acknowledged a stylistic debt to the Italian gangsters of film
and TV (that's where the very term comes from, after all) and Puff
has always seemed cold, remote, unfriendly, with a musical
personality that's one part braggart and one part whiner. It's hard
to decide which is more ridiculous: Comparing himself with Jesus or
with Sinatra, but both speak volumes about his seemingly complete
lack of taste or humility.
</P>
<P>
   And, really, who needs to listen to that? To a very rich man who
just cannot turn loose of playing the
gangster/outlaw/put-upon-homeboy card, even though he's obviously
living in a completely different world?
</P>
<P>
   Some will, of course: ``Forever'' will no doubt sell more than 1
million copies, maybe more. And it's certainly possible that the
just-released second single, ``Satisfy You'' (a duet with R.
Kelly), could boost sales significantly; it is one of the CD's
bright spots, and Kelly is still hot as a pistol.
</P>
<P>
   But it appears that a whole lot of people have sized up the
Puff, seen his act, grown tired of the constant boasts, heard what
he has to say (and tends to say over and over and over) and moved
on. It's hard to blame them.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
