<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0060 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BEETHOVEN-NINTH-TEX     09-13 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEETHOVEN-NINTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `NINTH' WONDER OF THE MUSIC WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One spring day in Vienna in 1824, music changed forever.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig van Beethoven, cantankerous, deaf, depressed and less
than three years away from the grave, gave the world his Symphony
No. 9, a masterpiece encapsulating the most noble aspirations of
humanity, a work that defines _ better than science or theology can
_ the universe and our place in it.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows the story of its premiere: Beethoven, seated on
the stage and facing away from the audience to assist the conductor
(by the standards of the time, the piece was considered difficult
to the point of unperformability), was oblivious to the
overwhelming applause until a singer turned him around to face the
appreciative throng.
</P>
<P>
   Beethoven's Ninth has been at the top of the all-time hit parade
ever since, and for good reason. Few orchestras can allow more than
one or two seasons to pass without presenting it; the Dallas
Symphony will perform it as the opening item on its 1999-2000
classical subscription series Thursday through Sept. 19 at the
Morton H. Meyerson Symphony Center. The Fort Worth Symphony and
conductor John Giordano will showcase its most famous and beloved
section, the fourth movement, at the climax of its New Year's Eve
concert at Bass Performance Hall. It's hard to imagine a better way
to spend the final moments of the millennium than hearing one of
Western civilization's greatest achievements performed in North
America's most beautiful concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the popularity of the piece are manifold.
Historically, it was the first choral symphony; before then, a
symphony was limited to instrumental work. Mendelssohn, Mahler,
Berlioz, Vaughan Williams, Holst, Shostakovich and countless lesser
figures have since followed Beethoven's example by including chorus
in a work officially designated as a ``symphony''; none has
approached Beethoven's Ninth in popularity and audience acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Even composers who never wrote a ``choral'' symphony were deeply
influenced by its structure and its broadening of music's subject
matter. Handel, Haydn and J.S. Bach had made obvious motions toward
a transcendent, universal vision in their oratorios, but never with
the boldness of Beethoven's Ninth Symphony. After Beethoven's
Ninth, composers were liberated to expand form and subject matter
as never before.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not its place in the history books that makes audiences
clamor for Beethoven's Ninth again and again.
</P>
<P>
   First, it's the simple but superb material: infectious, hummable
melodies that flow one from another, arranged in a recognizable,
analyzable, solidly logical musical architecture.
</P>
<P>
   This material, however, is loaded with surprises and
originality. For instance, the electric liveliness of the opening
passages, the audacious timpani solos in the vivace second movement
_ and the reiteration of material from previous movements at the
beginning of the Finale, a structural innovation that echoed
throughout the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   And oh, that choral finale, popularly known as the ``Ode to
Joy,'' after the poem by Friedrich von Schiller from whence it
draws its text. An opening pronouncement calls for a higher level
of music-making _ ``O friends, not these tones! Let us raise our
voices together in more pleasant and cheerful tones!''
</P>
<P>
   Humor, joy, a Turkish march and what Vaughan Williams once
described as the song of a tipsy Welsh soldier follow _ in music
that suggests all humankind, accompanied by the spinning of the
stars, raising a collective voice in praise of a benevolent
creator. There's no plot, but there's indescribable drama.
</P>
<P>
   The reputation for unperformability _ not so much of the
orchestral parts, but of the vocal writing _ lingered for over a
century. It has been speculated that Beethoven, already deaf, was
out of touch with the practical difficulties singers face. The
sopranos _ the soloist and those in the chorus _ get a particularly
difficult assignment in an uncomfortable range. But our modern
symphonic choirs and well-trained oratorio singers have, in my
experience, pretty well learned to overcome the technical hurdles
Beethoven gave them.
</P>
<P>
   And, when modern Euro-American civilization with all its horrors
and errors is judged by posterity, some accomplishments will help
to redeem us. Beethoven's Ninth Symphony, the creation of an ugly,
bad-tempered, barely functional fellow, will be recognized as one
of these enduring achievements.
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay is classical music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
