<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0108 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BONNIEPARKER-TEX     09-13 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIEPARKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-WOMAN PLAY TAKES THE MOLL OUT OF BONNIE PARKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PERRY STEWART 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The image of Bonnie Parker as a coarse, cigar-smoking,
pistol-brandishing outlaw is one that writer/actress Dixie Lee
Sedgwick has been disputing loudly these several months on stages
in Tarrant and Dallas counties.
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick _ who wrote and performs the play ``Inside Bonnie
Parker'' _ made a rigorous study of the short life and violent
death of Parker, who died at age 23 in a rain of bullets on May 23,
1934, when police ambushed the car in which she and bank robber
Clyde Barrow were riding in rural Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   An eye-opener _ indeed, an epiphany of sorts _ was ``The
Fugitives,'' by Emma Parker (Bonnie's mother) and Nell Barrow Cowan
(Clyde's oldest sister). This book drew heavily on Bonnie's diaries
and was a great help to building a character for a play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Parker wrote about Bonnie when she was little, when she
was growing up,'' Sedgwick said. ``She was a normal girl. She was
... like me, and most of the girls I knew. She was high-strung,
very bright, much more intelligent than I am _ I'm sure of that
because of her writing. Maybe emotionally her decisions, as far as
her love life goes, weren't so wise. But look at how many women
make those same choices, even today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I related to her, I saw her as a human being, a real person,
not that cigar-smoking gun moll that the media made her out to be.
Those pictures of her with guns and cigars were posed gag shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the authorities wanted to play that image up for all it
was worth, because they didn't want people helping them. They
didn't want the small-town folk to help Bonnie and Clyde evade the
officers. The newspapers were glad to help promote this image
because it gave them colorful stories and big headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really no evidence that Bonnie ever fired a gun. Her
crime was staying with Clyde. I don't mean to portray her as a
sweet innocent who didn't know what she was doing. She knew. But
it's important to look at this in the context of things happening
to young people today _ how a teen-ager can go wrong, and what the
consequences are.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the revelations in Sedgwick's play are that Bonnie was a
bride at 16 (to the mostly absent Mr. Thornton) and was disabled
for the last year of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was badly burned in a car crash, and her leg never healed
right,'' Sedgwick said. ``Clyde frequently carried Bonnie on his
shoulder the last year because it was so painful for her to walk.
If you notice the pictures in books, she's usually standing up
against a car and has one foot on the bumper. That's because she
couldn't straighten her leg.''
</P>
<P>
   How Dixie Sedgwick met Bonnie Parker is a tribute to
happenstance. Sedgwick studied at the American Academy of Dramatic
Arts and had acted and written screenplays in her native Seattle.
She was new to Texas when she met producer/director Joe Black, then
assistant director of the Dallas/Fort Worth Regional Film
Commission, at a meeting of Women in Film about two years ago in
Dallas. Black had just finished doing extensive research on Barrow
and Parker, in response to a request from England's BBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were putting together a documentary, as someone does
every year, and wanted to film the actual locations of the banks
and stores that Bonnie and Clyde robbed,'' Black recalled. ``So I
read all the books. Dixie had just blown into town and wanted more
work. She struck me as being a lot like Bonnie, both in size and
vivaciousness. I suggested she develop a one-woman show about
Bonnie.''
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick threw her 101 pounds into the enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure what was redeeming about Bonnie Parker,'' she
said prior to a rehearsal for the current run of ``Inside Bonnie
Parker'' at Fort Worth's Circle Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only knew what I saw in the film with Warren Beatty and Faye
Dunaway. I went to the Dallas Public Library archives. I was down
there a lot. I spoke with some historians. I read books like ``The
Fugitives,'' and ``Running With Bonnie and Clyde,'' by John Neal
Phillips. And I spoke with Marie Barrow, Clyde's sister. She passed
away last February. It was really helpful to speak with her. Marie
felt that the characterization was right on. She was quite
straightforward. She told me: `Clyde's eyes weren't blue, they were
brown.' And she said, `Bonnie was not that whiny.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I did sound a little that way when we first started. So we've
grown. Every time we do it, it gets better and better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met this whole group of people through Marie. I met Ken M.
Holmes Jr., the guy who owns the old Ford car they used in the
movie. And I met Boots Hinton, whose father was one of the men who
gunned down Bonnie and Clyde.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's correct. Ambusher descendants and Barrow and Parker
descendants now hang together.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a re-enactment of the ambush every year around May
23 in Louisiana, near where it happened,'' Sedgwick said. ``They
use Ken's movie car, and then they have a dinner. All the
historians come. People come from all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Black, who can be said to have ``introduced'' Dixie and
Bonnie, is the director of ``Inside Bonnie Parker'' (formerly
titled ``Little Blue-Eyed Girl'' after Clyde's pet name for
Bonnie). And he is producing it through his Lone Star Studios.
Black also has had a lot to do with shaping the piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is still a baby,'' he said. ``It's going to grow. We
workshopped it in Mansfield and Dallas and made changes after that.
During this run at Circle, we've added some humor. Bonnie was
witty. We put in some true anecdotes to show this.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Black nor Sedgwick is ambivalent about their hopes for
the play's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tour,'' Sedgwick said. ``In fact, we're talking to
theaters all over the place. Eventually, we want to end up in New
York or LA or both. We're signed with Plano Rep for their season
next year. Also, we're working on producing a docu-drama screen
version.''
</P>
<P>
   Black's ``Bonnie'' wish list includes all of the above, plus a
Southern regional presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take this play to Sulphur Springs and Waco and
Little Rock _ to the places where Bonnie and Clyde hung out and hid
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, Black said, there are nibbles from the other end of the
continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some Montreal interest,'' he said. ``One of the
`Star-Telegram' articles about the show was on the Internet, and
``TheatreScope'' magazine wound up writing about the play.''
</P>
<P>
   (Perry Stewart is theater critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
