<SLUG> BC-TV-FOOTBALL-MONDAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONDAY NIGHT FOOTBALL' GETS CROWDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETE DOUGHERTY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is three really a crowd?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't for Jack Ritter, Joyce DeWitt and Suzanne Somers in
``Three's Company.'' In 28 of the 29 years, ABC's ``Monday Night
Football'' booth has been the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it's too crowded.
</P>
<P>
   After a dozen years on ``MNF,'' Dan Dierdorf did not have his
contract renewed after last season. Rather than replace him, ABC
chose to let Al Michaels and Boomer Esiason become a two-man crew.
That happened only one other time in ``MNF'' annals, when Michaels
and Frank Gifford hooked up in 1986, and that combination caused
the hiring of Dierdorf the following year.
</P>
<P>
   All we have heard is how great a two-man booth is.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take the two personalities as they are,'' producer
Ken Wolfe said in a recent interview, ``we think this is a
wonderful opportunity that opens up the show; lets it breathe a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   We weren't aware of any suffocating, but ABC has been led to
believe that.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the network was bothered by reports that Dierdorf and
Esiason were fighting for air time off camera. I have been in the
company of both over the past year, and either they're seeking
Oscar nominations or they genuinely do like each other.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the joshing that could be seen off camera didn't
translate well on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Esiason and Dierdorf both seem overjoyed about the
chance to be the lone analysts on a telecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``A two-man booth is much easier for me,'' Esiason said. ``It
allows me to analyze the game and give the fan an opportunity to
find out what these players are thinking about and how they're
feeling. ... There's room for humor. There should be some fun in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A three-man booth probably has a redeeming quality if you're
talking about a 35-10 ballgame,'' Dierdorf said. ``When you're an
analyst in a three-man booth, you only have a job. You learn early
on that a lot of the things you'd like to say never make air.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, is a two-man booth better for the viewer? On Sundays, it
probably is. Dierdorf will work CBS games this year with Verne
Lundquist and have the freedom to be much more strategy-oriented,
as the weekend afternoon audience is much more of a hard-core
football fan.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the demographics are more skewed toward women
and more casual fans. There were times where I had trouble
differentiating Esiason's voice from Dierdorf's, but the exchanges
between them could be entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have a lot of lively commentary if each approaches a
situation from a different angle,'' Michaels said. ``On the other
hand, if there's a redunancy, that's a negative in a three-man
situation. In a two-man booth, we have the opportunity to begin a
story, to weave it without having an obstacle placed in our way.''
</P>
<P>
   So everyone's on board for a two-man booth. For now. We'll see
what they're saying at this time next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
