<HEADER>
A0174 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-PROFILE-GUSMAO-BOS &LR;      09-13 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-GUSMAO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL LEADER SEEN AS `MANDELA' OF EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA _ When the rebel leader Xanana Gusmao saw a television
news report Thursday that his 82-year father had been reported as
one of the hundreds slaughtered in a savage revenge campaign on
East Timor, aides tried frantically to reassure him.
</P>
<P>
   The report was not confirmed, they reminded Gusmao, the man
likely to become the first president of an independent East Timor _
if one emerges from the ashes of the orgy of violence last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao sat rod-straight in his chair, silent at first.
</P>
<P>
   Freed from house arrest two days earlier, and depressed by
accounts of the massacre of priests, nuns and other civilians in
his homeland, he had just pleaded in vain with a United Nations
delegation to send troops to stop the rampage by militias and
elements of the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about me,'' he told them. ``I am used to crying
for my family. My family is my people, and I cry for all of them.
Let's focus on who's alive and on getting them food and
medication.''
</P>
<P>
   It was vintage Gusmao, said Ana Gomes, Portugal's diplomatic
representative to Jakarta, who was in the room at the time, and who
recalled the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gusmao remains untested as a political leader, Gomes
and others who know him say he is determined to put the big picture
ahead of narrow interests, to place his people's struggle for a
free homeland over his own suffering, to insist on reconciliation
rather than revenge. These qualities have led people to call him
``the Nelson Mandela of East Timor,'' a description that aides say
embarrasses him.
</P>
<P>
   He has arguably gone a step further toward forgiveness than
Mandela did in South Africa; Gusmao has pledged amnesty for all
political crimes committed in the 24 years since troops from
Jakarta invaded the former Portuguese colony, and he has rejected
calls for a truth commission, saying it would be ``too divisive.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a pledge that is likely to be sorely tested after the
carnage in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The charismatic, grey-bearded Gusmao, whose image seemed
ubiquitious on posters and T-shirts in his poor, agrarian homeland
in the run-up to the Aug. 30 referendum on independence, is
idolized by East Timorese who want self-rule. He is described, even
by loyalists to Indonesia and the regime in Jakarta he fought
against, as the one person who might unite disparate interests and
heal wounds in a new Timorese nation.
</P>
<P>
   It is strikingly difficult to get anyone to say anything
critical about Gusmao. Even his avowed enemies seem to respect him.
On the day of the United Nations-sponsored ballot, Indonesia's
president, its foreign minister, and the head of a pro-Jakarta
militia all made strong statements calling Gusmao a peacemaker and
the future of East Timor, be it independent or a province of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   But some wonder how much reconciliation anyone can promote in
the aftermath of last week's terror. Whether he remains forgiving
will do much to shape East Timor's future.
</P>
<P>
   He has ordered the guerrilla forces he headed for 20 years not
to respond to provocations by militias and soldiers. He is lobbying
the international community, militias, and the Indonesian military
chief, General Wiranto, to halt the violence, to invite foreign
peacekeepers, and to withdraw the army.
</P>
<P>
   But for the 53-year-old Gusmao, like most East Timorese who
regard to him as their leader, last week was an extraordinary
emotional roller coaster, one that will inevitably leave a mark. He
rejoiced over the landslide referendum victory for independence,
and then he watched as East Timor's capital was torched and as tens
of thousands of its residents were forced out at gunpoint. He
celebrated his release from a 20-year prison term, then mourned the
reported, but still unconfirmed, murder of his father. He begged
for international help to stop the killing, and was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   Born Jose Alexandre Gusmao, one of seven children of a
schoolteacher father, he attended Catholic school and a Jesuit
seminary, where he learned Latin and the classics. By the age of
30, he had worked as a chartered surveyor, a teacher and a local
journalist, and was awarded the Timor Poetry Prize.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, the year Portugal decided to cast off its East Timor
colony, Gusmao joined the independence movement. When Indonesia
invaded in 1975, he fled to the mountains. In 1978 and 1979, after
Indonesian soldiers hunted down and killed most of the resistance
leaders, Gusmao emerged as commander of the decimated guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   One East Timor human rights campaigner, Florentino Sarmento, has
accused both Indonesia and the guerillas of committing atrocities
against alleged traitors and collaborators during the war years,
but Gusmao has never been directly linked to the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Gusmao was captured, charged with subversion and
sentenced to life in prison after a summary trial in Jakarta. He
infuriated his followers at first when he appeared on television
after his arrest, and he pledged allegiance to Jakarta. Many
thought he had been tortured and broken, but it turned out to be a
ruse. Gusmao appeared to cooperate with the authorities until he
could make his defense at his public trial.
</P>
<P>
   Until seven months ago, he was held in Cipinang Prison in
Jakarta, then was moved to house arrest after President B.J.
Habibie offered East Timor a choice of autonomy or separation.
</P>
<P>
   In prison, Gusmao, a native Portuguese speaker, studied English,
Indonesian and law; started a trend of prisoners attending lectures
by professors; cultivated bonsai trees, and returned to painting
and poetry. He coached the Cipinang soccer team, cooked Timorese
dishes for fellow prisoners, and was, by all accounts, loved by
other inmates, most of them Indonesian.
</P>
<P>
   A political prisoner worked as his secretary, and an Indonesian
petty thief served as a sort of valet. When both were granted their
freedom, they chose instead to move in with Gusmao and continue
serving him under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao even won over his captors. Guards who had held him under
house arrest, initially wary, befriended him and started making
T-shirts with his photo and the East Timor flag and selling them to
journalists. When Gusmao's sentence was commuted last week, the
prison governor embraced him in a tearful farewell.
</P>
<P>
   Friends say he listens well and admits shortcomings and
ignorance. Diplomats say he is a patient thinker who understands
his enemies. Aides say he rose to leadership without tramping on
others. He refused the Indonesian government's offer of freedom in
exile, remaining in East Timor to fight. His wife and two children,
a son and daughter now in their 20s, fled to Australia in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   What Gusmao lacks is a track record as a political leader. His
career has been as a rebel chief, and some wonder how he can
translate that into running a country or balancing a budget.
</P>
<P>
   When he reorganized the resistance in the 1980s, some people who
were sidelined accused him of being a ``powermonger and dictator.''
But the criticisms faded over time, and today it is hard to find
anyone who is critical.
</P>
<P>
   Some guerrillas have complained that Gusmao has been out of the
hills too long, living comfortably on three meals a day in prison,
and has forgotten what it is like to be a rebel fighter. This year,
he frustrated some of his troops by insisting they stick to a
ceasefire despite attacks on civilians by pro-Jakarta militias;
likewise, he insisted this week that they not engage in battles
with rampaging anti-independence forces.
</P>
<P>
   Some have argued that Gusmao is too ready to turn the other
cheek. But as evidence mounted last week of a military-sponsored
scorched-earth campaign in East Timor, the resistance closed ranks
behind Gusmao and his calls for restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Ramos-Horta, the leader of East Timor resistance in exile
and co-winner of the 1996 Nobel Peace Prize, said Gusmao ``dwarfs
political leaders in the region for his charisma, brilliance,
humility. He's a poet and a painter, but at the same time, he can
be extremely determined and tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Today Gusmao wears a jacket and tie rather than guerrilla
fatigues, and aides say he is more interested in fostering
reconciliation than becoming president.
</P>
<P>
   But Gomes said he has no choice. ``He's the natural leader of
his people. He's not keen on titles,'' she acknowledged. ``But he
will not shun his responsibility to lead his people into peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
