u i BC-IRELAND-POLICE-BOS &LR;      09-13 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-POLICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUNNING THE `PEELERS': AN ULSTER PLAN DISMISSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ At 17, John O'Reilly is smart enough to be anything he
wants. He thinks he wants to be an accountant. He knows he does not
want to be a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in the world that could make me want to become
a peeler,'' O'Reilly said, using the local slang for the police.
Last Thursday, when a government commission released its blueprint
for making the overwhelmingly Protestant police in Northern Ireland
more acceptable to Catholic nationalists, the commission chairman,
Chris Patten, cited the Markets section of Belfast, where O'Reilly
lives, as a place where foot patrols were beginning to replace the
anonymous, intimidating patrols in armored cars that police have
used for the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Catholics make up 43 percent of the population of Northern
Ireland, but only 8 percent of the police, the Royal Ulster
Constabulary. By removing oaths and symbols that Catholic
nationalists find offensive, and by using an accelerated hiring
process, Patten says, the number of Catholics on the force can be
quadrupled in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Patten acknowledged in an interview that if Northern Ireland is
to achieve long-term stability, not only will police need
acceptance in places like the Markets, but also young people like
O'Reilly will have to join the force.
</P>
<P>
   But walking around the Markets, a republican housing project
where 85 percent of the 600 heads of household are out of work,
there is a lack of enthusiasm about the prospect of police change _
or of local residents changing the police. Not only is there is
deep-seated mistrust of the police, but many seem comfortable with
the vigilante justice that republican paramilitary groups dole out
to the neighborhood's chronic troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed from the narrow streets of the Markets, the goal of
transforming the police as a way of transforming Northern Ireland's
divisions seems especially daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Long a hotbed of republican paramilitary activity, the Markets
section has been a dangerous place for police officers. Several
have been shot dead here.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, a nine-man police team began patrolling the
neighborhood on foot. Last year, the team commander, Sergeant Steve
Jones, was named the community police officer of the year for the
United Kingdom. But many people here say they have never heard of
Jones, and some who have accuse him and the police of using them as
props in a public relations exercise. Kathleen Sturgeon, leader of
the local youth club, said she has never met Jones.
</P>
<P>
   There are some people in the Markets who would never give the
police any credit even when it was deserved. But many others speak
of being treated with contempt by the police. They talk of
spotlights being flashed on their windows in the middle of the
night, of enduring humiliating epithets and insults. Mostly, they
complain that police officers who engage in such behavior are not
disciplined. And they say changing the name of the police force and
opening it up to more Catholics changes none of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you say you're from the Markets, people treat you like
you're scum,'' said Agnes O'Reilly, John's mother, sitting on the
couch of the family's small brickfront house. ``I would never have
anything to do with the peelers.''
</P>
<P>
   It is virtually impossible to find anyone in the Markets whose
home has not been raided and searched by the police. Virtually
everyone has a story of police harassment or humiliation. And
virtually no one knows a police officer on a first-name basis.
</P>
<P>
   Sturgeon said the absence of role models, and the lack of
interaction with police officers, makes the idea of young people
joining the police fanciful. ``The young people here wouldn't think
about becoming police officers,'' she said. ``To my knowledge, no
one from the Markets has ever become a police officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Montgomery, a youth worker, disputed the rosy picture
Patten painted of community policing taking hold here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody talks to the RUC here,'' he said. ``People here go to
the paramilitaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice is often rough on the streets of places like the
Markets. A few years ago, Montgomery was unable to intervene when
the IRA kneecapped a boyhood friend, Sean McNally, for ignoring
warnings to curb his penchant for stealing things and raising hell.
The shooting went wrong and McNally lost the lower part of his leg.
He now limps around on crutches, a symbol of the ongoing struggle
for control of the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery acknowledges the need for a regular police force. But
he cannot bring himself to support the new one called for in
Patten's report, nor encourage young people to join it. ``I would
lose all my street credibility if I advised young people here to
join the police,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can young people like John O'Reilly imagine joining a newly
named, reformed police force, even if republican leaders like Sinn
Fein President Gerry Adams decide to urge them to.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly's grievances with the police date back to the womb. His
father, a member of an IRA splinter group, was being held for
questioning by police when John was born. Trying to squeeze out a
confession, the police told his father that John had been born with
brain damage. His father didn't crack, and three days later was
released to find that his newborn son was fine.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, O'Reilly's father was killed, not by the police but
in one of the internecine feuds that decimated the Irish National
Liberation Army. His death at the hands of erstwhile comrades
illustrates one of the contradictions here _ while republicans
sometimes are brutalized by their own, there is no support for a
new police force to quell such activity.
</P>
<P>
   In the Markets, many young people have had scrapes with the law.
Patten's report urges that authorities overlook ``relatively minor
offenses'' committed by young people so they can be considered for
police service.
</P>
<P>
   But the other day, there were no takers.
</P>
<P>
   Sean McNally, 24, who shares the name but so far not the fate of
the Sean McNally who had his leg blown off, figures that he has
been arrested 20 times for minor offenses and beat up by the police
on a dozen occasions. ``I'm no angel,'' he acknowledged, but said
the police have beaten and framed him with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   He also voiced a fear that Catholics from affluent neighborhoods
will join the police to the exclusion of people from places like
the Markets.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery echoed that fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need people from areas like here, not the Malone Road,''
he said, referring to a wealthy section of Belfast. ``Patten made a
few cosmetic changes so that middle-class Catholics can join the
police. But it's not them who'll get it in the neck. It's us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
