<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-VOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While both Bill Bradley and Al Gore are charter
members of the centrist New Democrats, they have reached that
status by different paths. Following is a summary of their
differing positions on several key issues while both served in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION: During his years in the House, Gore opposed federal
payment for poor women's abortions. He changed that stance when he
got to the Senate, joining Bradley in support of federal financing.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET CUTS: Bradley voted for the Reagan administration's 1981
budget cuts, but not its tax cuts. Gore opposed both.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL AMERICA: Bradley gave qualified support to the Contra
war in Nicaragua in 1986, which Gore consistently opposed.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH PENALTY: Bradley voted for the death penalty for drug
lords who murdered or ordered killings, Gore did not.
</P>
<P>
   DEFICITS: When the budget deficit emerged as an issue, Gore
voted for two devices _ the balanced budget amendment in 1986 and,
before that, the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings law in 1985 _ designed to
stem the tide of red ink. Bradley, however, voted against both
measures, which he said were gimmickry.
</P>
<P>
   ETHANOL: Bradley's affection for ethanol price supports, an
issue important to the first-caucus state of Iowa, emerged since he
became a presidential candidate. In 1994 Bradley cosponsored an
amendment that would have ended federal quotas promoting the use of
ethanol, a corn-based fuel. Gore, presiding over the Senate as vice
president, cast the tie-breaking vote that defeated the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   FARM SUBSIDIES AND TOBACCO: Gore has been far more supportive
than Bradley of federal farm programs and subsidies. Gore and the
Clinton administration in recent years have attacked tobacco
interests. But Gore voted in 1985 to subsidize the tobacco
industry. Bradley opposed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL RESERVE: Bradley was one of just two senators to vote
against President Reagan's appointment of Federal Reserve Board
chairman Alan Greenspan in 1987. He supported President Clinton's
decision to reappoint Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   FREE TRADE: Though Gore was a hero of the administration's
battle to pass the North American Free Trade Agreement in 1993 _
debating Ross Perot on behalf of free trade on Larry King's
television show _ it was Bradley who opposed a protectionist
textile bill in 1988, and Gore who voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   PERSIAN GULF WAR: Gore voted to go to war against Iraq; Bradley
did not.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL VOUCHERS: Bradley voted in 1992 to give low-income
parents money to enroll their children at private or parochial
schools, a measure Gore opposed.
</P>
<P>
   SUPREME COURT: Gore backed the nomination of David Souter to the
Supreme Court, but Bradley was one of nine senators who did not.
Both Gore and Bradley opposed the nomination of Robert Bork.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE REFORM: In 1988, Gore voted to require welfare
recipients to work a minimum of 16 hours a week; Bradley opposed
the amendment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
