<HEADER>
A0187 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN &LR;      09-13 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
September 14. If you have any questions, please call The Star's
News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   FIELD _ In the movie ``Field of Dreams'' the ghost of Shoeless
Joe Jackson emerges from a stand of corn and asks: ``Is this
Heaven?'' No such luck, Costner responds. But in the end the film
implies that the hereafter would have a hard time beating foul
lines stretching into a Midwestern cornfield. Fans charmed by the
movie's romance with baseball and farm life have come here ever
since, chasing ground balls and nostalgia on base paths. But this
piece of Iowa is Heaven no more. The field's caretakers _ Becky and
Don Lansing own the most of the infield and right field, Rita and
Al Ameskamp hold deed to left and center fields _ can't seem to get
along. In a conflict perhaps as American as the game the field
celebrates, the Lansings and Ameskamps peddle souvenirs out of
competing shacks and regularly settle scores at county zoning panel
meetings. ``It's a shame,'' said Don Lansing. ``It takes away from
the field and the fun for the fans.'' Scott Canon. 32. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD: Lead poisoning of children always has been a problem in
Kansas City, but it's only been in the past couple of years that
health authorities have taken a really aggressive approach to
prevention. Armed with federal grant money, new equipment and
tougher laws, hundreds more children now are being tested, and
dozens of homes are being cleaned of lead. Health authorities have
had to work at changing attitudes of doctors, who didn't think lead
was still a problem. And they have had to seek out and train
contractors to do the remediation work. In some Kansas City zip
codes, as many as 26 percent of kids tested have high blood lead
levels, which can reduce IQ and cause learning disabilities, high
blood pressure and kidney damage. Graphics, photos. Alan Bavley.
35.
</P>
<P>
   ABORT: A breakdown of the language in the partial-birth abortion
bill, plus an explanation of how each side is interpreting the bill
differently. Kit Wagar. 20.
</P>
