<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0193 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-TRY-TIME-IN-LIFEBEAT-     09-13 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRY-TIME-IN-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRY TIME-IN WHEN TIME-OUT DOESN'T WORK
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color drawing of a child having a tantrum) 
 By SUZANNE BOYNTON 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time Joshua leaves his action figures all over the den
or Jennifer has a tantrum at the grocery store, don't put the child
in time-out.
</P>
<P>
   Use a time-in.
</P>
<P>
   Coined by parent educator Jean Illsley Clarke, the twist of
phrase represents a spin on the parent's role, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Time-in, she says, isn't meant to be a panacea. It's offered as
a tool for parents to use in redirecting their children's
misbehavior and their own responses.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the first book I've ever written because I was mad,''
said Clarke in a telephone interview from her Minneapolis home. ''I
got so angry at the way people were abusing time-out, I had to do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Her book, ''Time-In, When Time-Out Doesn't Work,''(Parenting
Press Inc., Seattle, $10) is trim enough to read between a
toddler's tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with time-out, Clarke said, is that it has been
overused and misused.
</P>
<P>
   Never intended to be a punishment, she said, time-out is a
strategy for giving a child time and space to calm down and think
about what he needs to do or how he can participate in the teaching
that is to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who wanted to stop tantrums and misbehavior without
spanking or screaming became enthusiastic converts to the time-out
method.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Clarke, if a parent finds himself using ''time-outs''
several times a day without noticeable effect, he's probably ready
for time-in.
</P>
<P>
   Time-in shows adults how to engage the child and find out why
she's misbehaving.
</P>
<P>
   The guide is divided into four alliterative sections: Ask, Act,
Attend and Amend. The method is aimed at children ages 1 to 12,
although children under 3 can't be expected to fully respond to
questions (Ask), or to benefit from making amends, Clarke said,
since empathy doesn't appear much before that age.
</P>
<P>
   Time-in isn't just a response to inappropriate behavior. It can
also be used to reinforce positive behavior. And the four stages
can be used in any order the situation requires.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a brief overview of the stages, with examples and tips
for parents:
 &UR; ASK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you see inappropriate behavior, ask yourself what lesson
the child needs to learn. If you can ask a question that will teach
the child the lesson, ask it.
</P>
<P>
   Ask only questions the child can answer, and only as many as
needed. Don't ask questions you obviously know the answer to, such
as, ''Who tracked in the mud?'' The child will suspect a trick. And
don't turn an order into a question by ending it with ''OK?''
unless you're really offering the child the option of not picking
up her toys.
</P>
<P>
   Example: Anna, 7, left her coat on the floor for the umpteenth
time. Mother sat down, calmed herself, and in a clear, firm,
pleasant voice, asked, ''Anna, do you know where Daddy's coat
belongs? ... Right, in the closet. Where does Luke's coat belong?
... Right, on the peg.'' Mom grinned and asked, ''Can you guess
what question I'm going to ask next?'' Anna grinned back and hung
up her coat. Mom gave her a big hug. The discipline lesson: Hang up
your coat.
 &UR; ACT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a child is headed for or threatening physical danger, act
first, then talk. Sometimes the action needs to be placing the
child in time-out before you can teach the needed lesson with
asking, attending or amending. Act when asking hasn't worked.
Action can prevent an outbreak of misbehavior. Sometimes an action
just seems like the right thing to do, such as modeling appropriate
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Example: Dad noticed that the 9- to 12-year-olds playing
basketball were not challenging a player who was cheating. Suddenly
Dad was part of the game, dribbling, shooting baskets and passing.
Just as suddenly he stood still, held the ball to his chest, and
said, ''In this yard everyone plays by the rules.'' He tossed the
ball to the one who had been cheating, grinned, and left. Dad
directed attention to the cheating without a lecture or shaming.
Discipline lesson: Play by the rules.
 &UR; ATTEND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This word has so many meanings that it may be the most versatile
of time-in's tools.
</P>
<P>
   It means both ''paying attention to the immediate situation and,
in the larger picture, of teaching children about values and
responsibility,'' Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
   It also means physically attending to injured children and
broken objects. Sometimes, Clarke said, you must attend to the
environment to help avoid further problems.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, attending is the only way a parent can decide whether
the next step is to ask, act, or amend.
</P>
<P>
   Examples: Mom and her friend were chatting. When toddler
Kendall's Cheerios were gone, she used a demanding grunt to get
Mom's attention. Mom said, ''Your Cheerios are gone. I'll get you
some more, OK?'' and went to the kitchen. Kendall screamed. Mom
attended to her own behavior. She replaced ''OK?'' at the end of
her statement with ''Wait.'' Eventually Kendall learned to wait.
Discipline lesson for children: Delayed gratification. Discipline
lesson for adults: Tell young children what they need to do instead
of asking their permission.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to Dad that his children, 6, 9 and 10, were breaking
the rules more often. He called them together and asked them what
was going on. They replied that there were too many rules to
remember, the rules changed too often, and that he didn't follow
them either.
</P>
<P>
   Together they chose the six most important rules and made a
poster of them and a wallet-sized copy for Dad. Discipline lesson
for parents: Rules must be reasonable, known, understood, and
applicable to all in the family.
 &UR; AMENDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This part of the strategy will delight parents who have wondered
how to make lessons really sink in and rebuild connections between
children without shaming a child who has injured or offended
another.
</P>
<P>
   Making amends, says Clarke, actually builds self-esteem and
social and problem-solving skills while working to right the wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke cautioned, however, that you can't make amends for
everything; save it for serious misbehaviors. ''What you invite a
child to make amends for depends on what you decide is important
and then only if you have the time, energy and patience to carry
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Amends should:
</P>
<P>
   Represent an effort on the part of the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   Help her become a better person. For example, breaking one of
her own toys is not an appropriate amendment for breaking one of
another child's.
</P>
<P>
   Support family values.
</P>
<P>
   Be related to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Be acceptable to the victim.
</P>
<P>
   The most important use of amends, Clarke said, is to make amends
to your own child when you have wronged her.
</P>
<P>
   ''That the child learns the steps of amends may not be as
important as the family habit _ the concept that I live in a family
where, if people do something wrong, they attempt to make it right.
If kids get that concept, then as their cognition develops, they
will be much more adept at figuring out options of what to do,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a culture, I don't think we're very good at it. We get so
much into proving who's right or wrong that we don't ask what we
can do to make it better.''
</P>
<P>
   While time-out loses effectiveness as a child ages, there's no
reason time-in can't be used right through the teen-age years as an
alternative or in addition to grounding, the teen version of
time-out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Suzanne Boynton writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
