<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POISON-PROOF-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POISON PROOF YOUR HOME
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color photo of two children eating medicine in a
bathroom) 
 By SANDY SORTWELL MAKAU 
 c.1999 Sandy Sortwell Makau 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bicycle helmets and car seats keep kids safe while they're on
the go, but safety at home is often taken for granted. Medicines,
cosmetics, cleaning products, and lead are common household dangers
for children.
</P>
<P>
   The National Safety Council states that worldwide, 55 to 75
percent of accidental poisonings occur in children under 6 years of
age. Since 1990, U.S. Poison Control Centers have responded to
approximately 1 million poisoning calls involving children under 5
years old. Most of these poisonings occur in the kitchen or
bathroom while a parent is in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Niezabitowska, poison educator at the University of
California Davis Poison Control Center, says that household
cleansers like bleach and pine oil are the most common culprits.
''About 400 to 800 children per year drink pine oil cleaner because
it looks like apple juice,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Niezabitowska adds that it shocks parents to realize that strong
smells and bad tastes don't discourage children from ingesting
chemicals. ''Children have a big association with color and
familiar foods and beverage containers. Pills look like M&AMP;M's and
bleach bottles are shaped like milk bottles.'' Niezabitowska
advises parents to never put toxic substances into recognizable
beverage containers. Always keep them in a locked cabinet and out
of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Poison centers nationwide can help callers safely manage more
than 70 percent of all poisonings at home. The Maryland Poison
Center received 54,1444 calls in 1995, and 25,189 of those cases
were treated at home.
</P>
<P>
   The U.C. California Davis Poison Control Center claims that they
help callers handle 80 percent of their emergencies at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''Always get proper instruction before treating an emergency,''
Niezabitowska advises. ''Throwing up is not always the best thing
to do. Sometimes it is the worst thing to do.'' She warns
caregivers never to give Serum of Ipecac to an unconscious child
because the child could aspirate the vomit.'' She also advises
against using folk remedies.
</P>
<P>
   To thoroughly poison proof your home, make sure all household
chemicals and medicines are in their original containers. Store
them away from food and beverages, and out of reach, in locked
cabinets. Chemicals in the garage need to be locked out of reach as
well. Keep Serum of Ipecac on hand. It can be purchased at the
pharmacy without a prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Most states have toll free poison control numbers. Find them on
the front page of the local phone book or from your local
pediatrician. The number should be put by the phone for
baby-sitters and grandparents to easily access.
</P>
<P>
   Parents need to help grandparents enforce childproofing when the
grandkids come to visit. Grandparents need to keep their
medications in child resistant bottles whenever possible. Encourage
them to put them out of reach, not on the nightstand or on the
bathroom sink.
</P>
<P>
   If grandparents are giving medications to kids, make sure they
have enough light to read the label correctly. Rewriting the
instructions clearly on a 3x5 card may be helpful for them.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquito repellents are considered an insecticide and can be
toxic to children because they are absorbed through the skin. To
find out the safest amount to apply call the poison center, or
physician, and give them the size and weight of your child.
</P>
<P>
   Lead is an invisible poison. It is a metal found in housepaint
used before 1978, hobby materials like solder, and fish weights. It
can also leach into the household water supply through lead pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Lead can travel home on work clothes, in the form of dust, of
those who work in battery and radiator manufacturing shops. It
settles in the soil from chipped house paints, leaded gasoline, and
around industrial areas that use lead.
</P>
<P>
   Keep toddlers away from paint sources like windowsills and
furniture. Check pottery for leaded glazes. Have children wash
their hands after playing in the soil and have parents remove work
clothes before entering the house if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Evaluate your child's risk for lead poisoning by checking if
your house was built before 1978, or if you live in an industrial
community. Pediatrician Mark Miller suggests getting your child
tested if you are in a high risk category. Often there are no
symptoms of lead poisoning. Contact your doctor or local health
department to request lead testing. Testing is done by a simple
blood test.
</P>
<P>
   Before removing any leaded paint it is necessary to contact a
professional in lead removal. Like asbestos any dust or fumes that
escape can cause bigger problems.
</P>
<P>
   HUD, Housing and Urban Development sponsors a directory of
qualified lead inspectors, risk assessors and lead abatements
contractors. The National Lead Information Center, 800-424-5323,
has information about lead and lead poisoning. Both of these groups
can be helpful along with lead abatement consultants and
contractors that can be found in the local phone book.
</P>
<P>
   Poison proof your home and rest easy that your child's
environment will be safe and poison free.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sandy Sortwell Makau writes from Chico, Calif.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
