<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMERS-TRAGEDY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER'S ALZHEIMER'S WAS HER ULTIMATE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EXETER, N.H. _ He could still read a book, take a walk, and hit
a golf ball long and straight. But the essence of Bob Shaw _ doting
father, legal powerhouse, small-town oracle _ was fading away.
</P>
<P>
   And as he lay awake at night, when his frightening fog would
briefly lift, he knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am actually facing facts that only I am completely aware
of,'' Shaw wrote to his three daughters in fall 1992, before his
suspected Alzheimer's disease worsened. ``To put you on notice
before I make a damn fool of myself, I want to retire before the
problem becomes so serious that I won't have the ability or the
sense to recognize it.''
</P>
<P>
   He forgot names. He got lost on his way to the store. Familiar
faces suddenly grew foreign. This summer, having already given up
his law practice, Shaw saw his zealously guarded independence give
way to around-the-clock care.
</P>
<P>
   As his daughters met in emergency council about how to care for
the man who had selflessly cared for them, he issued a final,
non-debatable edict: I must not, he told his family, become a
burden to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go in there in the middle of the night. And he'd be awake
and more lucid than he had been all day, and he was really
concerned because he said he didn't want to be this burden on us,''
said Peg Shaw, his oldest daughter. ``We were all very concerned
about his well-being, because we all love him so much. He did so
much for us. He was with us for every single moment of every day
when we were growing up. How could we not be there for him?''
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Shaw, 84, who had worked hard to build a respected law
office here, had grown accustomed to having his way _ and he
perhaps received it one last time from the muzzle of a gun held by
one of his children.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Katz, 54, who shared his independent streak and his
appreciation for the unconventional, revered her father, by all
accounts. Eleven days ago, after a buoyant evening of home-cooked
food and hearty laughter at Peg Shaw's home in Washington, D.C.,
Beth Katz pushed herself away from her sister's dinner table. She
walked her father down two flights of stairs and took him for an
evening ride in her 1997 Ford Taurus station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   They never came back.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Katz drove to the nearby Washington Hilton Hotel,
where John Hinckley shot President Reagan in 1981, parked the car
out front, walked around, and got into the back seat. She fired two
shots into the back of her father's head and then turned the
.38-caliber handgun on herself, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what made it so painful for Bob is that he was aware
that Bob Shaw was slipping through his fingers,'' said Stephen
Woods, Shaw's former law partner here. ``I can well imagine Bob
demanding that he never be a burden on anyone. And Bob was a very,
very forceful individual.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of five children of Eastern European immigrants,
Bob Shaw was born Aug. 26, 1915, and grew up in what were then the
Jewish neighborhoods of Boston. His name then was Bob Schneiderman,
years before bigotry and business reasons persuaded him to change
his last name.
</P>
<P>
   He attended Roxbury Memorial High School and chummed with
neighborhood pals Maurice Searle, who later became his business
partner, and Theodore H. White, the historian and journalist who
would win a Pulitzer Prize for the first in his series of books on
``The Making of the President.''
</P>
<P>
   In those Depression years, Schneiderman combined work and
school. He studied law at night at Suffolk Law School and worked
for a furrier during the day. In the summers, he, Searle, and White
opened a bicycle rental and bath house business in York Beach,
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   When White left to begin his journalistic career in China,
Schneiderman and Searle began an adventure of their own: They
purchased a dance hall next to a golf course in Newmarket, N.H.,
where their first chore was to repair the roof blown off by the
Hurricane of '38, one of the century's most violent storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of people from the Portsmouth Navy Yard,'' Searle
recalled. ``We'd have private parties for submarine crews and serve
them sandwiches and soft drinks. The good ol' days.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2,800-square-foot dance floor, built of rock maple resting
on a bed of springs, fairly rocked as Tommy Dorsey, Glenn Miller,
and the Fenton Brothers put their bands through their paces.
</P>
<P>
   After a stateside stint in the Army, Schneiderman's fledgling
law practice began to demand more of his time. When his application
for membership in a local Chamber of Commerce was rejected because
of his Jewish name, Scheiderman withdrew his application, but he
changed his name to Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was like a hit in the head for him,'' Searle said. ``He
thought it would be easier on his children.''
</P>
<P>
   As his courtroom triumphs grew, so did his family. Shaw and his
first wife, Selma, raised their children first in a two-family
house across the ballroom parking lot and later at their house in
Exeter, where he quickly became a presence in local politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Town Meeting, he defeated so many budget items over the
years that he didn't believe in, they finally put him on the budget
committee,'' Peg Shaw said. ``He was very persuasive.''
</P>
<P>
   He read Supreme Court decisions late into the night and reserved
Sunday morning for father-daughter civic tutorials at which he read
aloud to his girls from the Week in Review section of the New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of lawyers were afraid of him because of his
brilliance,'' said David C. Engel, a local lawyer and Shaw's
occasional courtroom opponent. ``He was one of those lawyers who
was very clever in bringing out facts that no one had thought of
and often turning losers into winners.''
</P>
<P>
   The rough edges he sometimes displayed at work, where he
specialized in personal injury law, were softened at home, where
Selma and his daughters endured his temper tantrums and made him
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pretended to be mean _ like a bear _ but he wasn't,'' said
Mildred Wool, a longtime friend. ``He loved his daughters, and Beth
was really his favorite. She was his baby. I can remember him
helping her with her math. He used to teasingly call her his little
knucklehead.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Bob Shaw betrayed a special affection for his youngest
daughter, the feeling was mutual. By all accounts, Beth Lois Katz
idolized her father.
</P>
<P>
   Like him, she tried to champion the causes of the dispossessed.
What he sought to accomplish in the courtroom, Katz did in the
streets, volunteering with peace groups, protesting the US bombing
in Yugoslavia, and marching in gay rights parades.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
