<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ALZHEIMERS-TRAGEDY-2N     09-13 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMERS-TRAGEDY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 EXETER, N.H.: ... rights parades.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``She believed that her father represented those who needed to
be represented and fought for the common man and the underdog, so
that would be her cause, too,'' said Liz Signell, a neighbor and
longtime friend.
</P>
<P>
   Divorced a decade ago, Katz lived three blocks from Michigan
State University in East Lansing, where her former husband is an
associate professor. With her two children grown, she took in
graduate school boarders to supplement her income.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was willing to give to other people in a capacity that
most people don't allow themselves to,'' said Jamie Boyce, a former
student who lived with Katz. ``She was very passionate, with a
great sense of humor and a great love of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz also struggled with her self-esteem, said friends and
relatives. If her father had been just teasing when he called her a
``knucklehead,'' the appellation nevertheless may have cut too
deeply.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could be really down on herself,'' said Judith Katz, her
oldest child and a student and artist in Chicago. ``She would
criticize herself really meanly sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   A former high school French teacher, Beth Katz conducted teacher
workshops to promote writing in every subject, including math and
science. For 20 years, she was the one-woman star of the Red Rug
Puppet Theater, delighting children with characters like Frilly
Frog, who danced across the stage she wore on her shoulders during
shows in 18 states, Puerto Rico, and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was like a huge burst of energy in any room,'' Judith Katz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Hood, a friend of Beth Katz's for years until their
friendship fractured after a fight earlier this year, said Katz was
torn by conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was performing or presenting, she was euphoric,''
Hood said. ``But at home she was often depressed. . . . She
preached nonviolence but kept a gun in the house for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Signell said she spoke with Katz about her father's declining
health in June, after the family took preliminary steps toward _
but made no decision about _ placing him in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she came back from that visit, she said, `I'm not going
to have my father in a lockup. My father is not going to be in a
lockup,' '' Signell recalled. ``She couldn't stand the idea of her
father being in a place like that. She was very, very opposed to
that idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Katz said her mother bought a handgun in 1997, a purchase
she told no one about. She attended classes sponsored by the
National Rifle Association and honed her shooting skills on a
firing range, her daughter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very determined,'' Judith Katz said. ``When she put
her mind to something, that was that. She had a very strong will.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four million Americans are severely afflicted with Alzheimer's
disease, which has no known cause or cure. Millions more are
affected by milder forms of dementia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disease where you gradually lose all the parts of your
mind and personality that really made you a person in the family,''
said Marcelle Morrison-Bogorad, associate director of the
Neuroscience and Neuropsychology of Aging Program at the National
Institute on Aging. ``The family is disrupted because this family
member is there physically but not there mentally. Relationships
are gradually torn apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Shaw's family was determined that would not happen to them.
They had seen their father's increasing frustration _ sometimes his
fury _ as he struggled against the disease that was robbing him of
his sense of identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a has-been,'' he told his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw had spent two months earlier this year with a daughter in
Central Massachusetts, who has asked that her name be withheld. But
no longer able to drive, Shaw found that life in rural
Massachusetts only fed his growing sense of isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, he moved in with his daughter Peg, a former
newspaper reporter who is now a lawyer practicing in Washington.
She hired a caregiver and was willing to host her father as long as
it was practical.
</P>
<P>
   He visited the White House, rode the Metro trains, went to the
zoo, and delighted in his ability to still enjoy a lifelong
passion, hitting golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really into taking care of him and doing it right and
doing it well,'' Peg Shaw said. ``I know that he was going
downhill. But I was not into being hopeless or institutionalizing
him. Beth's perception was so different from mine, apparently.''
</P>
<P>
   As Peg Shaw kept watch, Shaw's other two daughters maintained
constant contact by telephone. ``We were having `grampy'
conversations for the last six months,'' Peg Shaw said. ``The phone
bills have been kind of horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   His oldest daughter recalled a heart-breaking conversation her
father had with a visiting social worker one evening in late July.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so clear and graphic about what was happening to him
and how terrible it was to him that he was losing a little piece
here and a little piece there,'' she said. ``If you don't have your
memory, it impacts on your intellect. . . . So, obviously, it
concerned him. And it might have been that he had a conversation
with Beth about that in the last couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final days of his life, Bob Shaw, who had doted on his
daughters, had that attention repaid. Beth was visiting Peg's
Dupont Circle apartment. There were family meals and funny stories.
</P>
<P>
   On the day before he was killed, Shaw went for a walk, hit some
golf balls, and read aloud from William Manchester's ``The Glory
and the Dream.'' Peg Shaw's husband, Gary Sikora, prepared a lovely
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laughed. We joked. It was a beautiful evening,'' Peg Shaw
said. ``Then Beth took him out for a ride, and neither of them came
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before 9 p.m. on Sept. 1, police were called to the
Washington Hilton Hotel. Bob Shaw's body was slumped in the front
passenger seat. His daughter, dead from a single gunshot to the
head, was found in the seat behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hell,'' said Judith Katz, Beth's daughter. ``He was
suffering tremendously, and my mother was suffering with him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the murder-suicide, Peg Shaw said, she has
realized that she had never detected the depression that must have
racked her youngest sister. But the lifelong link between a father
and his devoted youngest child was unmistakeable, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to know whether Beth Katz acted out of
compassion or to fulfill her father's final request.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beth would never have hurt my father,'' Shaw said. ``She must
have perceived this as the ultimate act of love and generosity. She
adored him. She loved him. All her life, he was so important to
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess she thought I was a cock-eyed optimist and in deep
denial about how miserable our father was. It's clear that she must
have thought that this was the best thing for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
