<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-HUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE STUDENTS SAY THEY'LL TAKE MANHATTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The ubiquitous U-Hauls compete with out-of-state
station wagons for double parking spots along the streets. On the
sidewalks, students push industrial-size laundry carts piled high
with posters, pillows, and plants. Stereos and computers sit
curiously unattended, waiting for someone to carry them into the
dorms.
</P>
<P>
   It could be Kenmore Square, the Fenway, Cambridge, anywhere in
back-to-school Boston, except that it's Morningside Heights, New
York, and this picture isn't such an anomaly here anymore.
</P>
<P>
   In its long-running regional inferiority complex with its more
cosmopolitan neighbor to the south, Boston has comforted itself
that it will always be the hub of higher education, home of the
nation's oldest and most renowned university and scores of others,
a mecca to scholars and students worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Start spreading the news: The place where they put tomatoes in
the chowder is threatening to eclipse Boston again.
</P>
<P>
   Lured by internship opportunities they hope to turn into
lucrative careers, a dramatic decline in the crime rate, and of
course, the heady challenge to ``make it there,'' college students
from across the country and around the world have flooded New York
schools with a record number of applications over the past five
years, prompting the Chronicle of Higher Education to declare it a
``Hot College Town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to think Barnard is attractive in its own right, but
we recognize that surely the city is a huge part of it,'' says
Judith Shapiro, president of the women's college.
</P>
<P>
   This year for the first time, New York University overtook
Boston University in attracting the nation's largest number of
international students. Applications at New York's most prominent
colleges have doubled, some almost tripled, since 1991, dwarfing
increases of about 15 percent at Boston's better-known schools, and
even a decline one year at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Higher education is also an important part of the city's
economy. A study earlier this year that for the first time ranked
the nation's metropolitan areas on a range of higher education
indicators found New York City highest in nearly all. Colleges and
universities here, the study found, receive more federal funds,
spend more research money, enroll more students, and employ more
staff than those in any other city. The Boston area ranked about
fifth in most categories.
</P>
<P>
   Boston does rank highest in number of students when adjusted for
population; that is, if it feels as if there are more students,
it's because there are fewer people overall. Still, New York comes
in a surprisingly close second: There are 43 students to every
1,000 residents of Greater Boston, 40 students for every 1,000
residents of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The fortunes of New York colleges began to rise as the city's
crime rate, which peaked with 2,245 murders in 1990, dropped
sharply in the mid-1990s. A notable milestone came in 1993, when
George Rupp arrived as president of Columbia University and began
referring to the school again by its full name, Columbia University
in the City of New York, in speeches and promotional materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an extremely conscious effort,'' said Chris Colombo,
Columbia's dean of student affairs. ``In the public eye, when we
had stories about people running through Central Park being mugged,
this was not the place you wanted to visit, much less go to school.
That's changed a great deal, and we've taken a role in running with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   By last year, New York was so plausible a college town that the
WB television network set its drama of college life, ``Felicity,''
at a fictional university here.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of New York schools also reflects students'
changing interests, noted by college presidents here and across the
country. Students are interested less in what they learn in the
classroom, and more in getting experience and connections to the
best jobs. In its sheer size and range of industries, New York
offers a larger wealth of internships, and the city's colleges have
highlighted that more over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a day and an age when people are thinking more about their
careers, there's much less of people going to college to find
themselves, or looking at it as some kind of club atmosphere,''
said John Beckman, director of public affairs at NYU. ``New York is
a fantastic place to be if that's uppermost in students' and
families' minds.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Boston may be the victim of its own success.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Jasnow, 18, a Barnard freshman from Smithtown on Long
Island, said she considered going to schools in the Boston area,
especially Tufts, until she talked to a cousin who had done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is, like, a major college area, so when you get out,
it's going to be much more difficult to get positions,'' she said.
``You're going to be just like everybody else looking for a job.
There's more opportunity to go around in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Higher education institutions _ 95 in the five boroughs,
according to the Association for a Better New York, about the same
number as within the I-495 beltway around Boston _ have also put
new emphasis on the city's glamour and diversity of culture. In
recent years, more have developed internships with a range of
companies, and created programs to give students free admission to
museums and concerts across the city. At Columbia, Neil Simon, then
Carly Simon, visited for intimate chats in the dorms. Sylvia, of
Harlem soul food fame, even came to cook a meal.
</P>
<P>
   The school's promotional video divides its footage equally
between Columbia's famed core curriculum and the virtues of New
York. After showing off Tom's Restaurant, the Morningside Heights
facade made famous by ``Seinfeld,'' a group of students boards a
notably graffiti-free subway car to tour the city, showing off
Lincoln Center on the way. In a new PG-rated Times Square, one
student reminisces about an all-night bike ride through the city in
a history of New York class. Another points out the Virgin
Megastore, recommending it for 2 a.m. CD cravings. (What she
doesn't add, but might, is: Try satisfying that in Boston.)
</P>
<P>
   As much as the city is cleaner and more vibrant, the campuses,
too, reflect their new popularity. Around West 116th Street, where
students not so long ago stayed pretty much within Columbia's high
walls, Broadway has become a boulevard of upscale bakeries, bars
and shops. With more students coming from out of town _ about 80
percent at NYU, up from about 50 percent a decade ago, and over 90
percent at Barnard, up from 60 percent _ almost every campus is
building at least one tall, sleek new dorm. St. John's, in Queens,
opened its first dorms this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from Maine, I was a little freaked out,'' admits
Katherine McKenney, a Barnard sophomore from a town she describes
as one stoplight, one mailbox. ``But I feel safe here. And there's
tons and tons of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, it didn't look like the right match at all,'' adds
her mother, Susan, helping to unload the family's Volvo. ``It
didn't seem friendly and nurturing; we never gave it a thought.
Then we came to visit her friend here, and when I saw how happy she
was, I knew Katherine would be happy here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some people still worry about security.
</P>
<P>
   Barnard sophomore Audrey Stegmeyer's mother, nearby in New
Jersey, insists her daughter carry a cellular phone when she leaves
the school's grounds. Barnard orientation includes _ in addition to
a trip to a drag queen dance club _ a mandatory seminar dubbed
``Learn to be a New Yorker in 45 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, the 500 or so freshmen in the crowd don't
seem too concerned. One rearranges pages in her Filofax, others
check out the gleaming new gymnasium around them. Developing
attitude, apparently, is just another part of the New York
experience.
</P>
<P>
   As Jane Finnegan, the school's chief of security, tells the
crowd, ``It's perfectly OK to be rude. If you're a healthy New York
woman, you can be rude, you can be a little suspicious. When you go
home, you can tell people you've become a New Yorker. And that's
OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0162 </DOCNO>
