<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0209 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-13 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING REAL ABOUT GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 30 and earn $115,000 a year. My wife is 27 and is now a
stay-at-home mother. I'm sorry to say I just started investing two
years ago and most of my friends have a huge jump on me, so I feel
I have some catching up to do. We have set a goal of retirement at
age 50 with retirement assets of $2 million, well aware that
inflation over the next 20 years will dictate a need of $200,000 of
income to maintain our current lifestyle. We currently are saving
$1,267 a month for retirement, all invested in equities. We each
have Roth IRAs with Vanguard, invested in its Index Growth, US
Growth, and Health Care funds. With next year's contributions, I
plan to add Vanguard's European Index, and eventually to balance
the four funds evenly. I have just started with my company's 401(k)
plan and have $2,500 in Maxim Index Growth, American Century
Twentieth Century Ultra, AIM Weingarten, and AIM Charter.
Allocations are 30 percent each to Maxim and Charter and 20 percent
each to Weingarten and Charter. I plan on contributing the $10,000
annual maximum. Finally, I have just started building a taxable
account in Janus 20, with an $800 current balance and contributions
of $100 a month. If we maintain a 15 percent annual return (which
may not be realistic and sustainable) will we attain our goal in 20
years? If not, what rate of return must I achieve? What if I waited
until I was 55 or 60 to retire?
</P>
<P>
   B.B., Easton, Pa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your parenthesis says it all: Your growth projection is
neither realistic nor sustainable.
</P>
<P>
   But even if you were to make such a return, you would fall a bit
short by age 50, amassing only $1,890,732. At a more realistic
annual growth projection of 10 percent average returns, you would
accumulate $1,003,651, only a little more than half your target
figure.
</P>
<P>
   (And your assumption that you would need $200,000 income to
maintain your current lifestyle is very close _ it would require
$198,987 in 20 years to buy what $100,000 buys today, presuming a
3.5 percent inflation rate.)
</P>
<P>
   To reach the $2 million level by age 50 with the more realistic
assumption of 10 percent average portfolio growth, you would have
to save more than double your current savings level _ going to
$2,653 a month. If you continued at your current level, you would
accumulate $1,713,581 at age 55 and $2,856,655 by age 60, using the
10 prcent growth assumption.
</P>
<P>
   (To answer your other question, you would need a 15.44 percent
average annual return to build a $2 million portfolio over 20 years
with your current savings level, but, as I indicated, that's just a
dream.)
</P>
<P>
   To be even gloomier, I question if a $2 million nest egg is
enough to guarantee a comfortable retirement at your current
lifestyle beginning at age 50.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you were to gamble that you could keep your money in
stocks that would deliver a 10 percent annual return over the long
haul, you would be withdrawing all of that return to provide your
income stream.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave nothing invested to protect against the
inevitable inflation of your later retirement years _ a factor that
assumes increasing importance the earlier you retire.
</P>
<P>
   So unless you dramatically increase your level of savings, it
would be more realistic to think of retirement around age 60 rather
than at 50.
</P>
<P>
   To quickly answer a few additional questions you asked but which
I edited from your letter:
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is a way to withdraw funds from your tax-deferred
accounts before age 59 1/2 without penalty, but nowhere near at the
level you proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I think your diversification and choice of funds is fine,
and yes, I also like your idea of adding mid-cap and small-cap
funds. Finally, yes, Vanguard offers a fairly new fund called
Mid-Cap Index, which has thus far delivered a solid performance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are in our mid-to-early 70s and are in the
28 percent tax bracket. My taxable savings are invested in mutual
funds, with $10,000 in Vanguard Index 500 and $34,000 in Templeton
Growth fund (which I plan to move into a no-load fund), plus an
additional $25,000 in a savings account, to be added to these
accounts. In my IRA I have approximately $115,000, with 12 percent
of it in stock of America Online, 19 percent in Cisco Systems, 19
percent in EMC Corp., 22 percent in IBM Corp., 17 percent in
Wal-Mart, and the rest in government securities and waiting to be
otherwise invested. With all the above, I am hoping for a five- to
10-year investment time frame. I hope not to take out any funds
except the mandatory withdrawals, which along with my Social
Security benefits I plan to use for travel. What do you recommend?
</P>
<P>
   G.R., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There's an old Wall Street saying that bulls can make money
and bears can make money, but piggies always lose.
</P>
<P>
   I checked the paper for quotes on your five individual stocks,
looking at the statistics as of the closing on Sept. 7. Three were
at prices that were about three times or more of their 52-week
lows; another was at more than double its low; and the most modest
spread (Wal-Mart) showed a 77 percent advance from the low.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the scale, one issue, Cisco Systems, was at
its 52-week high, two others were within 10 percent of their
52-week highs, and one was within 20 percent. Only one issue was
far from its high _ AOL, where the price represented only 53
percent of its 52-week high, but which also was 452 percent of its
low price.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, I would sell all or most of these positions. I realize
you are in a position to take a long-term view of these holdings,
but the idea of having more than 56 percent of your savings in five
individual stocks strikes me as too risky _ not too risky for a
person in their 70s, but too risky for anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Since the individual stock holdings are in your IRA, there would
be no tax consequence of the sales, provided you left the proceeds
in the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted to keep all of the money in stocks, I would
reinvest this money in a portfolio of Vanguard Index funds _
perhaps 40 percent in Vanguard Index Value, 20 percent in its Index
Growth, and 20 percent each in its Mid-Cap and Small-Cap Index
funds.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Templeton Growth holding, I'm not sure why you want
to sell: It has a very solid record. You cite a preference for
no-load funds, but since you already hold this position, you either
have already paid the load or will probably pay a load when you
sell, so there's nothing to be gained by leaving.
</P>
<P>
   You might, indeed, favor a no-load fund when it comes to
investing the money that's now in savings. But if I were in your
shoes, I would maintain at least your current level, a little less
than 20 percent of the total portfolio, on the fixed-income side.
For this I would favor a mutual fund money market or bond fund
rather than a traditional savings account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to establish a fund for my new grandson that I
hope will amount to $100,000 in 15 to 18 years. I have about
$25,000 set aside for this. Can you suggest where I might place
this money to achieve this objective?
</P>
<P>
   L.A., Newton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'll give you two suggestions, both fairly cautious, but one
more conservative than the other.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve a $100,000 accumulation from the investment of
$25,000 over 15 years, you would need to achieve 9.68 percent
average annual returns; to do the job over 18 years would require
8.01 percent average returns.
</P>
<P>
   It strikes me as likely that you could meet the goal with the
more cautious investment _ in a balanced mutual find, which divides
its portfolio between stocks and bonds, typically with about
three-fifths of the money in stocks and the rest in bonds or cash.
Solid examples here would be Fidelity Puritan and Vanguard Balanced
Index Funds.
</P>
<P>
   To be a little more aggressive, and accordingly to assume more
risk, you could go with a value-oriented large-capitalization stock
fund. Solid examples here might be Fidelity Equity-Income II or
Vanguard Index Value funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
