<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``The Adventures of Sebastian Cole'' Pretty routine
dysfunctional-family stuff is lifted beyond the ordinary by the
convincing interiority Adrien Grenier brings to the moody title
character and by the warmth Clark Gregg brings to the most
interesting, appealing, and (so far as Sebastian is concerned)
loving and supportive one, Sebastian's transvestite stepfather.
(R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FL) !! 1/2 ``Stigmata'' An ``Exorcist'' in reverse, as
well-intentioned priest Gabriel Byrne tries to find out what's
ratcheting up the supernatural and dangerous forces taking over
hairdresser Patricia Arquette's life. Good performances, but
over-aggressive direction prevents this one from unnerving us with
the eeriness it could have mustered. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Stir of Echoes'' Solidly and even handsomely crafted, but
also somewhat square and earthbound, brush with the supernatural.
Kevin Bacon's Chicago telephone lineman and his family find
thesmelves being bumped by sinister manifestations and troubling
visions in the old house they just bought. (R)
</P>
