<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WHO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERABO'S DEBUT OFFERS SHORT STORIES OF SUBSTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON ARNETT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WHO I WAS SUPPOSED TO BE 
By Susan Perabo 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, 191 pp., $20 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Short stories are often viewed as beginner's exercises for a
novelist, the way a novice tunes up for the sustained effort of a
full work of fiction. And in their modern incarnation, many a short
story seems a quickly sketched scene, a mere suggestion of a plot
and characters _ much attitude and little substance.
</P>
<P>
   That's not at all the case with the stories of Susan Perabo, who
in her first published collection neatly sidesteps those problems
by concentrating a precise and lucid focus on her characters. As a
result, in stories as short as 6 or 14 pages, people _ some of them
odd, some as ordinary as your next-door neighbor _ gain an
unexpected vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Perabo, who teaches writing at Dickinson University in
Pennsylvania, does have an eye for the quirky that's reminiscent of
Eudora Welty. Like Welty, the 29-year-old Perabo transcends her age
and gender, as when she illuminates a 12-year-old boy who
unexpectedly bonds with a father he feels is nerdy, or an aging
film star whose father's kleptomania shakes his world, or two
losers who find it impossible to sell one of Princess Diana's
ballgowns to make the killing they desperately need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was twelve the summer I watched four men beat up my father
on a softball field at his company picnic,'' begins the title
story. Eddie succinctly describes his bookkeeper father, who was
pummeled by truck drivers he'd turned in for cheating, by
describing his mother. ``Like my father, my mother was little too,
but was that tough, compact kind of little that my father had never
been able to achieve.'' His mother's disdain for his father's
weaknesses puts the boy in the middle, eager to escape from the
sadness and defeat that surround his home. But as things get worse
and his father is let go from his job, the two meet at the bathroom
mirror in the quintessential adolescents' fantasy. ``My father came
back into the bathroom with the rest of the pack of cigarettes and
his prescription sunglasses. He picked up mine off the sink and fit
them onto my head. . . . He lit a cigarette and handed it to me,
then lit one for himself. ``. . . I giggled, trying to be the guy
(in the mirror) but being myself because I was embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . He looked as mean as any guy I'd ever seen. . . .
Through the fog we scrutinized the guys in the mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   A longer story tells of another parent-child relationship, this
one as quirky and as neatly role-reversed. A woman, defeatedly
going through a second divorce, is summoned back to the little
hometown she hated. ``And so I returned to my childhood home of
Carlisle, Illionis, population thirty-five hundred morons.'' A nosy
neighbor has called to tell Kathy that her recently widowed mother
is squandering all she owns on lottery tickets. Which Mother, a
retired schoolteacher, unrepentantly is doing. As the story plays
out, Kathy persuades her mother to go to Gamblers Anonymous
meetings, where mother corrects the participants' grammar. And
Kathy meets Andy, who bets on horses and subtly, but determinedly,
courts her.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kathy had come to save her mother from herself, she finds
her mother chiding her instead, finally telling her to leave. The
ending is as gently drawn as the rest of the story, so that the
town takes on almost as much personality as the characters. But
Kathy seems to have listened to her mother's plea: ``Honey, don't
you ever just want to hope for something?'' There's a whiff of
winning at the end, even for a small-town gambler.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the stories or their characters are so endearing. A few
of the stories stretch on too long, losing the thread of interest
in the character even as the plot unfolds. A man who's been pushed
out of his ex-wife's life tries to win her back by faking amnesia;
by the end of it, he's too unlikable to care about. A story about
two children who shove a bully off a cliff is uncharacteristically
histrionic; in this day of horror-movie cliche, I kept waiting for
the bloody conclusion. And the one about Batman's butler was just a
little too weird.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``Explaining Death to the Dog,'' a woman tries to
convince her dog that her baby isn't coming back, and Perabo
encapsulates grief in the most visceral way in six short pages.
</P>
<P>
   Perabo, who has the distinction of being the first woman to have
played NCAA baseball (and therefore is represented in the Baseball
Hall of Fame), for a few brief moments makes us identify with
unusual and sometimes difficult people. It's a lovely gift.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
