<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DOES IT TAKE SO LONG TO FEEL A STUBBED TOE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why is it that when I stub my toe it takes a few seconds for
the pain message to reach my brain, whereas when I hurt any other
part, the pain is relatively instantaneous?
</P>
<P>
   P.T., Arlington, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You have three different kinds of nerve fibers running from
your touch and pain receptors to your brain. They carry their
traffic, the nerve impulses, at dramatically different speeds.
Think of the slow one as downtown traffic at rush hour, the middle
one as highway traffic, and the fast one as the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Touch and pain signals travel on separate nerve ``highways.''
And in the race to the brain, touch wins. The fastest of the three
types of nerves, the A beta fibers, transmit a signal at roughly
100 feet per second. They run out of the various receptors we have
that sense touch. The main ones just under the skin in our hands
and feet are called Meissner corpuscles. Merkel's disks are most
common in our lips and genital skin. Other touch receptors deeper
down in our skin and in our internal organs are called Pacinian
corpuscles and Ruffini's corpuscles. They all trigger messages
carried by those speedy A beta nerves.
</P>
<P>
   The next fastest fiber is the A delta nerve, which transmits
signals at 9 feet per second. A deltafibers extend out from
nociceptors, pain sensing nerve endings in the skin. Some
nociceptors detect only mechanical stimuli, like the poke of a pin.
Others sense mechanical and thermal input like hot or cold. Others
sense those two, plus chemical stimuli, like capsacin, the fiery
ingredient in hot sauce.
</P>
<P>
   A delta fibers are responsible for what is called
</P>
<P>
   first pain, the sharp, localized, immediate pain you get from a
burn or cut.
</P>
<P>
   The slowest nerve fibers are the C fibers. They transmit
messages at the relatively sluggish speeds of between one-half and
one-and-a-half feet per second. They are also triggered by
nociceptors. C fibers create what is called second pain, the
duller, longer-lasting, less-localized ache of a stubbed toe.
</P>
<P>
   How do these fibers transmit information at different speeds?
The A betas and A deltas are wrapped in myelin, a fatty substance
that acts like an insulator. The insulation let the signal travel
faster. And there are gaps in the myelin coating, called Nodes of
Ranvier which make the signal do a kind of jump to get from one
side to the other, which accelerates it. Because the C fibers
aren't wrapped by insulating myelin, and no Nodes of Ranvier, they
send their signals along more slowly.
</P>
<P>
   So here's what happens when someone six feet tall stubs their
toe. In less than one tenth of a second, the A beta fibers tell you
you've just touched something. In two-thirds of a second the A
delta fibers deliver the first news of the pain. Then along comes
the dull throbbing message from those sluggish C fibers over the
next four to nine seconds telling you to wear shoes next time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FASHION-COLUMN &LR;      09-13 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANYTHING GOES' FOR WOMEN'S FASHION IN THE NEW MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fashion industry is gathering here this week to
observe a watershed moment: the unveiling of the first women's
collections of the new millennium. Foreshadowing lifestyles and
attitudes of the next century, the spring 2000 designs are expected
to emphasize individuality.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no rules, no ``must-wear'' color, no prescribed
hemline. Skirts? Think ankle-length, knee-length, or shorter. Shoes
will be square-toed or oblique, whether high-heeled or flat. The
slogan for 2000, it seems, will be ``anything goes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion now is about taking what is out there and making it
your own,'' said Be Bilzerian, women's buyer at Alan Bilzerian.
``No longer is it true, `If you don't have this outfit, you're out'
or `I only wear this length skirt.' The mentality is changing. It's
a natural progression in the story of fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly a far cry from the 1990s, which treated fashion
as a groupthink experience. To be counted among the stylish, you
had to wear items like black pantsuits, cardigan sweaters, and
sheath dresses. The Gap, for one, has a new ad campaign that may
best sum up the decade's conformity. Its billboards _ targeted to
men, women, and children _ read: ``Everybody in vests.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the independence movement, which started this fall
with the hippie-chic trend, is emerging for a variety of reasons.
For one thing, the casualization of the workplace has allowed women
to feel comfortable breaking traditional rules of dress. And
greater sartorial freedoms have come as more women have risen
through corporate ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole '90s was about getting away from the power '80s,''
said Mary Lou Andre, president of the wardrobe management company
Organization by Design. ``Women made great strides and were not
afraid to express themselves (in more feminine clothing).''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, perhaps more than ever, consumers of all
backgrounds are better educated about fashion now that there are
fashion TV programs like E! Fashion, Internet sites operated by
designers like Helmut Lang, dozens of monthly magazines like Vogue
and Elle, and multimillion-dollar ad campaigns by designers like
Calvin Klein. With such exposure comes a confidence to take risks
and make personal style choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion is a lot more in your face,'' said designer Sigrid
Olsen, 84.5 percent of whose company is owned by Liz Claiborne Inc.
``It's not just a territory that belongs to people in the fashion
industry and people under 21. This is a monumental change. Women of
all ages and sizes now feel there is something out there for them
that's fashionable.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, economics and the natural cycle of fashion play a
part in the trend too. The fate of designers like Isaac Mizrahi (a
popular New Yorker who went out of business last year) and Todd
Oldham (who shut down his primary couture collection last year)
taught the industry that women want wearable clothing and they want
variety. ``We all have a closet full of black clothes,'' said
Patricia Warner, a costume historian and associate professor in the
consumer studies department at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are very, very bored with the same things
everywhere. How many black slip dresses can you see from how many
designers?'' said Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of moving to a ``new black,'' many designers say they
plan to be more creative in 2000, using colors from the entire
spectrum of the rainbow, as well as floral prints and other print
designs. ``I like to think that designers are getting away from the
kooky and doing just beautiful, beautiful clothing,'' said South
End designer Denise Hajjar, who sells to local TV personalities Liz
Walker, Liz Brunner, and Hank Phillippi Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Innovation at the start of the new century may not be in
silhouettes, she said, but in interesting fabric choices. ``You're
going to see fabrics used all year 'round now,'' said Hajjar.
``You'll see leather in spring, in ice tones and pale colors,
combined with chiffon or a tissue-weight wool. You'll see more
prints. People are starting to like prints again.''
</P>
<P>
   New York designer Donna Morgan plans to encourage customers to
``play with her clothes,'' mixing and matching the unexpected.
Customers ``can wear a beaded shell with jeans or a wonderful
evening skirt with a T-shirt on top,'' said Morgan, whose clothes
are sold in stores like Filene's and Lord &AMP; Taylor. ``There needs
to be an attitude change in the customer that she has the
confidence to do it. You probably need to make (fewer) purchases
when you learn to work with your wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   William Calvert, one of more than 70 American designers to show
his spring collection during New York fashion week, featured gowns,
suits, and skirts in his show Sunday, with elements such as
iridescent fabrics, satins, and pearl accessories.
</P>
<P>
   His hope? To encourage people to dress up a little more _ and on
their own terms _ in the new century. ``I think that since people
are face-to-face so much less now _ you don't see a bank teller,
the only people you see are the people who cut your hair _ when
people do meet up together, there should be more ceremony put into
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the race to get ahead, people forgot that they need to . .
. look good for each other. I would like to see more effort. It's
not always the end result that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Shari Thurer, a psychologist at Boston University, said the move
away from fashion uniformity and rules reflects a postmodern
sensibility that has been reflected in film, art, music, and
architecture. ``One of the ideas of postmodernism is that it plays
with the rules and makes them visible.
</P>
<P>
   ``In `Pulp Fiction,' (director) Quentin Tarantino plays with
expectations that these criminals are going to act criminal.
Instead he has them arguing over the price of hamburgers.'' In
music, she added, rappers are taking songs from various eras, such
as the '70s, and inserting their own voices on the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   And in fashion, designers are deliberately exposing the seams of
clothing, rather than hiding them. ``That which was hidden and
subtle becomes exposed and privileged,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Postmodernism is inherently cynical and ironic. It questions
all the norms because many of the norms are false. Suddenly, you
can wear something this way or that way. The genders are no longer
distinct. Women's clothing will incorporate qualities that were
once men's, like a fly on boxer shorts or women in military gear. .
. . Olive drab used to signify war and men. Now it signifies Chanel
and upscale. It's all playing with metaphors. I like this better
than minimalism. It makes fashion a lot more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what looks consumers come to embrace, spring will
almost certainly spell individualism. Said Olsen, ``There's going
to be a lot more choices out there for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be eclectic, you can be. If you want to be more
modern and updated, you can be. (The point) is to feel that you're
making some statement of individuality. Yes, choices have always
been there, but they were not always fashionable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
