<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHADOW OF THE CLINTONS IS A COLD, DARK PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Texas Gov. George W. Bush appears to have a relatively
easy ride at this early stage in the Republican presidential
nomination process, Vice President Al Gore is finding it tougher
going on the Democratic side of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign is being eclipsed not only by the unexpected
strong showing of Democratic rival Bill Bradley, but also by the
high-profile media presence of two of his stalwart supporters,
President Bill Clinton and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Even when on vacation or house hunting, the Clintons seem to be
capturing more media space than Gore. So, too, Clinton's battles
with Republicans over his promised veto of the GOP's major tax cut
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton's controversial agreement to grant clemency to
jailed Puerto Rican nationalists (also called terrorists) has also
held the media spotlight, although not always flattering, on the
president and the First Lady.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary's apparent flip-flop on the clemency issue _ first she
supported it, but when that angered the powerful voters in upper
state New York, she said it should be rescinded _ made both upper
New York voters and Puerto Rican voters in New York upset with her.
The GOP is also saying that Clinton's offer of clemency was
politically motivated to help gain the Puerto Rican vote in New
York for his wife.
</P>
<P>
   While such controversies continue to rub off on Gore _ forever
linked to Clinton as his vice president _ Bush's campaign is
rolling along, despite a few bumps in the road over how he handled
questions of past drug use.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' high media profile is not, of course, the only
source of all of Gore's campaign problems. As he demonstrated
during his recent visit to Boston, he can create his own problems
without anyone's help.
</P>
<P>
   At the Boston visit, he announced $5 million in emergency aid
for New England fishermen, suggesting the help was primarily of his
own doing. However, the all-Democratic Massachusetts congressional
delegation found out that Gore was talking about a grant that was
not only more than a year old, but was the result of a lot of hard
work by members of the delegation. Gore later called US Sen. John
Kerry to apologize, but he will have to do more to earn the strong,
active support he will need to win big in the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's major dilemma is how to separate himself from the
negatives of the Clinton administration without disconnecting
himself from the administration's economic success story.
</P>
<P>
   As popular as Clinton is with the electorate, there are signs in
various polls that voters would like to see his administration come
to an end. Bush's current lead in the polls over Gore may reflect
voters' view that a Gore presidency would be an extension of the
Clinton administration, not a new Gore era. If that perception
continues to next November, Gore could be in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's clean image does not appear to help him in his battle
with Bradley, who also has a clean image, or against Bush, who is
slightly tainted with the alleged drug use issue in his earlier
days. Bush's decision to go no further than his statement that he
has not been involved in drugs for 25 years may even be helping him
with voters, who like the way he has challenged the media on the
topic.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, Bush's ability to connect at this early stage with so
many voters makes him more like Clinton who, with his flaws, still
kept his strong appeal among a wide range of voters. And like
Clinton, Bush can be forgiven for any early drug use as the voters
forgave Clinton for his past misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is still likely to be the Democratic nominee for president.
Bradley will gain more support as the campaign rolls along, but
most of the delegates at the Democratic convention are expected to
support Gore over Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore, with all his stiffness and his current inability to
articulate a clear message, will have the strong backing of
organized labor. Gore will also need the help of key people such as
the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson, who can help him gain a strong black
vote and Hillary Clinton, who can help him gain support among women
in New York and across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps sparring with Bradley may help get Gore in shape _ make
him less stiff, quicker on his feet _ for the big fight with Bush
next year.
</P>
<P>
   And it may be just what Gore needs to fight his way out of
Clinton's shadow. In the end, however, his biggest challenge will
be to win the support of the electorate. If he is to have any
chance of doing so, he had best start loosening up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
