<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOOTBALL-SUNDAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS VIE TO GET MORE YARDAGE OUT OF PRO FOOTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETE DOUGHERTY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stretching is an important preliminary to any sporting routine.
Now, television is giving fans three hours of warm-up exercises for
what can be a 10-hour day of viewing NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   From 10 a.m. to 1 p.m. (the time when most Sunday games kick
off), five national networks will produce NFL pregame shows. Fox
Sports Net joins the congestion this season with the ``NFL This
Morning.'' CBS, whose ``NFL Today'' trailed Fox's ``NFL Sunday'' by
37 percent in the ratings last season, overhauled its lineup. CNN,
which airs ``NFL Preview'' uncontested in the 10-11 a.m. slot, and
ESPN, whose ``NFL Countdown'' is the only two-hour presentation in
the bunch, have tweaked their shows.
</P>
<P>
   It is all part of a frenzy spurred in part by NFL fans _ many of
whom are mindful of their fantasy-league players _ and their thirst
for information.
</P>
<P>
   A viewer trying to catch all of this could be weary before the
games even begin. ``People watch them, which is why they produce
them,'' CBS Sports president Sean McManus said. ``If they weren't
being watched, if the advertising revenue wasn't significant, they
wouldn't be produced.''
</P>
<P>
   So how much is too much? ESPN asked that question 20 years ago
when it created the first all-sports network, and it still hasn't
found the answer. The NFL keeps expanding its menu to see how much
its viewers can take.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the day of the game, I don't know that there is a
saturation point,'' said Chris Myers, who will anchor Fox Sports
Net's new show. ``The true football fan, that's why they go
tailgate a couple of hours before the game. They just want to be
around football and talking about it. On Sunday morning, when
people wake up, that's what they want. I think there will be a
24-hour NFL channel in our future somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The infusion of pregame programming invites problems into the
mix. Each show wants to be different, but how many directions can
they all go? Fox emphasizes entertainment. ESPN specializes in news
and information. CBS, which replaced three rookie studio analysts
with TV-savvy veterans, is looking for a mix. CNN, which had the
lowest-rated of the four shows last year, and Fox Sports Net are
hoping not to get lost in the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets back to the old CBS `NFL Today,''' said Fox executive
producer Ed Goren, who produced that CBS show before moving to his
Fox in 1994. ``We said if we only had a hour show, wouldn't life be
wonderful from a producer's point of view. Then we started an hour
show here five years ago, and there isn't a week that goes by where
we're not saying wouldn't it be great to have an hour and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Affiliate problems prevented Fox from expanding ``NFL Sunday,''
so the network's cable arm became the newest player in the game.
``We feel like we can do the best show out there,'' Fox Sports Net
executive producer Arthur Smith said. ``That was our motivation for
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN became the first to go with an hour show back in 1986, when
CBS and NBC, which no longer is involved in the NFL, had half-hour
pregames. When the over-the-air networks went to an hour, ESPN
expanded to 75 minutes, then to 90, and last year to its current
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas it once had the 11 a.m.-noon hour to itself, ESPN now
competes with Fox Sports Net's show. ESPN, which added Stuart Scott
and Suzy Kolber to its cauldron of on-air personnel this year, has
always had the problem of trying to hold its early viewers once the
CBS and Fox shows come on the air at noon. Should the network run
its best stuff in the first hour or save it for a better
competitive posture against the two big networks?
</P>
<P>
   ``In a different week you'll juggle differently,'' said Bob
Rauscher, senior coordinating producer for ESPN. ``It could be a
little different this year with Fox Sports Net having a show.
You'll have to be a little more aware of the competition than you
were before.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just start off and say we'll put our (weaker) stuff
in the first hour and we'll save all the good stuff. People might
just say this show's not that good. On the other hand, you can't
use all your stuff early, because then the other shows come on and
they might have a better presentation. It's a fine balance. You
hope to get good material overall.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not always possible in the current environment. Imagine a
week in which four networks arrive at, for instance, Miami Dolphins
practice, looking to do a feature on Dan Marino. If you've seen one
version, is it as good as seeing them all?
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to show these players in a personal light,'' said Bill
Galvin, executive producer for CNN, which added former University
of Nebraska linebacker Trev Alberts to its team. ``We try to show
them away from the field, without the helmets, without the pads.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope that your relationship makes it a personable
interview in that case,'' said Craig James, a CBS studio analyst
and former NFL running back. ``If I'm doing it or (Fox's) James
Brown is doing it or one of the ESPN guys is doing it, they're
going to answer us all nicely. What I'm going to do is then talk to
a lot of players and maybe get support for what I'm doing. You've
got to work that little bit more because it's very competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition will be as intense as ever. Each network has its
``information men,'' reporters who are responsible for breaking
stories before they become public. ``It has become pretty much a
ruthless, cut-throat, dog-eat-dog business,'' said Peter King, an
``NFL Preview'' reporter. ``The hardest thing is to find something
out at Friday at 4 o'clock and have nobody find out by Sunday
morning at 10. It's virtually impossible anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the competition is stronger than it's ever been, and
all of us who are in the information business right now look at it
and say that if we don't bring our `A' games to the table every
week, we're going to get slaughtered.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
