<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0222 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-TOXIC-BOS &LR;      09-13 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TOXIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLUTION IS DOWN, SO SHOULD LAWS GO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the kind of news story that gives corporate executives
nightmares: the government release of a ``worst polluters'' list.
Being on ``the list'' means protesters at the gate, more regulators
prowling around, and the simple embarrassment of explaining to
friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto President Richard Mahoney got his nightmare in 1989,
the first year the federal government required major companies to
tally up how much pollution they were creating and make the figures
available to the public. To his chagrin, the chemical giant was
ranked one of the worst air polluters in the country, prompting
Mahoney to angrily order a 90 percent emissions cut even before the
bad news hit the press.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed since public humiliation first became a
tool to clean up the environment. From 1990 to 1997, Massachusetts
manufacturers reduced toxic releases to the land, air and water by
80 percent, part of a national trend as manufacturers become
increasingly sophisticated and proactive in their approach to
pollution control.
</P>
<P>
   Now, corporations say they deserve a break from some of the
toxic chemical reports that are so often used against them. Earlier
this year, they helped fight off a federal proposal to describe
potential worst case disasters at their plants on the Internet,
while, in Massachusetts, they are fighting to weaken or repeal the
nation's strictest chemical reporting law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious that industry has demonstrated a tendency toward
enlightened environmentalism over the past 15 years . . . We
deserve a chance,'' said Ed Jamro of Solutia Inc. in Springfield,
formerly part of Monsanto, at a recent hearing in Boston on changes
to the state's Toxics Use Reduction Act.
</P>
<P>
   Jamro argued that the law straitjackets companies by forcing
them to report toxic chemicals they use and their plans to reduce
them. He and other chemical industry officials said they could do
more to help the environment if the law were scrapped and replaced
by a voluntary initiative aimed at environmental issues such as
water and energy conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Even the environmentalists who pushed for the chemical reporting
laws in the first place agree that companies such as Solutia are
much better environmental citizens than they were 15 years ago. But
they say that only proves the basic soundness of the existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people who say, `Gee, corporate America is
wonderful, so why don't we just get rid of all these laws?' It's
like people saying the crime rate is down, so let's lay off some
cops,'' said James R. Gomes, president of the Environmental League
of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gomes said Massachusetts ought to reward companies with
the best environmental records by reducing their chemical reporting
requirements or cutting state fees. In exchange, the firms would
have to prove that they really were turning their attention to
other environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over how much companies should tell the public occurs
amid a general trend toward more and wider disclosures about
hazardous chemicals. Since 1995, the Environmental Protection
Agency has doubled the number of chemicals whose release must be
reported in its Toxics Release Inventory, and required more
industries to join the program.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the EPA is considering following the Massachusetts
law by requiring firms to report not only pollution levels, but
also the chemicals they use as ingredients in their products.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the rise of the Internet has made these disclosures
more powerful, bringing detailed, easily analyzed information about
manufacturing plants into homes and offices around the world. The
Environmental Defense Fund has even created an Internet
``Scorecard'' (www.scorecard.org) where visitors punch in their zip
code to get detailed reports on every nearby toxic chemical source.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Chemical Manufacturers Association, trade group
for the industry most affected by all this reporting, say they
accept the public's right to know about potential health and safety
hazards. They have even set up their own Internet page
(www.chemicalguide.com) to provide both economic and health and
safety information about chemical companies.
</P>
<P>
   However, they argue that some information governments want is
either misleading or potentially dangerous. For instance, national
security agencies and members of Congress joined manufacturers in
opposing an EPA plan this year to post on the Internet descriptions
of ``worst case'' accidents at 36,000 facilities, and how the
owners would respond to them.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorists ``from Boston to Baghdad, from Los Angeles to Libya''
could learn how to kill the most people from the risk management
plans, complained US Rep. Tom Bliley, a Virginia Republican.
Congress passed a law in July blocking the Internet posting of the
risk management plans for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists counter that the chemical industry is using
fear of terrorism to mask a broader agenda to limit access to
information about their operations. Only four years ago, activists
point out, chemical companies tried to greatly reduce the amount of
pollution information they must file with the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of the people in the chemical industry's own
poll thought they should have a right to know about chemicals used
in their community,'' said Paul Orum, coordinator of the Working
Group on Community Right to Know.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that reason, the chemical industry has used secondary
issues such as the threat of terrorism'' to limit the information
flow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Massachusetts' Toxic Use Reduction Act, chemical
industry officials say the release of information about chemicals
used in products gives people the idea that chemical use itself is
bad, rather than focusing on the actual exposure to people and
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Solutia's Springfield plant was held up as the
second largest toxic chemical user in Massachusetts in literature
passed out by environmentalists at last week's hearing in Boston.
But there was no mention that the plant has dropped from first to
sixth in toxic releases to the environment, which industry
officials say is more meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain interest groups have focused on chemicals, and they
have decided that they are going to paint them as the evil of
society. That is absolutely false,'' said Michael DeVito of the
Massachusetts Chemical Technology Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Burns of the Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group,
which collected 11,000 signatures this year in defense of the state
reporting law, denies his group is anti-chemical. However, he said
the public needs to know the amount of toxic chemicals used at
manufacturers to understand the accident risk as well as the amount
of toxic material in the final products.
</P>
<P>
   And Burns dismissed industry grumbling about the law, saying
``they don't like anything that gives the public a potential
hammer'' over them.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Massachusetts law also faces criticism from some
academics who fear that if the EPA follows the Massachusetts
example in requiring companies to disclose chemical ingredients,
American companies will become more vulnerable to spying.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I know what chemicals you are using, I can figure out what
you're making and how much you're making,'' said William H. Lash, a
law professor at George Mason University in Virginia and an
authority on public disclosure issues.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, The Massachusetts law allows companies to withhold
trade secrets from the public _ and less than 2 percent of
manufacturers have even asked. But Lash said that only shows that
industry doesn't fully appreciate the risk. ``One thing about
espionage, unless you catch them,'' it's hard to tell when spying
has even happened, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, regulators, academics and environmentalists
alike say that the Toxic Use Reduction Act has been too successful
to toss out now. A study by University of Massachusetts at Lowell
officials found that the 1989 law's combination of education and
embarrassment helped industry cut toxic chemical waste by about 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that after ten years of proven success, the toxic
use reduction program should be emulated, not eliminated,'' wrote
Environmental Affairs Secretary Bob Durand to the legislature's
Joint Committee on Natural Resources and Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Durand's office is expected to produce a bill that
will streamline the reporting and planning requirements, especially
for companies with good records, but also put more focus on the
most dangerous chemicals as well as non-chemical issues such as
over all waste reduction.
</P>
<P>
   The message, say observers, is that industry deserves some
credit for improved environmental performance, but not all the
credit. Said Gomes of the Environmental League, ``It didn't happen
out of the goodness of the heart of corporate America but because
we put in place some significant laws and some significant
penalties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
