<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HENRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EDUCATION OF HENRY SMART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
A STAR CALLED HENRY 
Volume One of ``The Last Roundup'' 
By Roddy Doyle. Viking. 
342 pp. $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his great dark wit sweeping the streets of Dublin for its
hard-earned truths, Roddy Doyle is renowned for his comic gifts _
he's emerged in recent years as one of the eminent straight men of
Ireland's literary renaissance. But Doyle is funny the way the
finest humorists dare to be, using comedy to make bearable the
grimmest of human realities. His laughs aren't satire and they're
never cheap; they're more like a howitzer aimed at the usual
suspects of poverty, greed, despair. If the unfortunate title of
``Paddy Clark Ha Ha Ha'' (which won the Booker Prize in 1993)
suggested something uproarious within, the name was only a wiseacre
front for a wrenching story _ a boy's life told in a gunmetal-tough
voice, his sense of humor the elixir vitae that keeps him alive.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle's fiction has gotten progressively bleaker with each work;
his most recent, ``The Woman Who Walked into Doors,'' delivered a
triumphant but agonizing soliloquy from a narrator whose husband
beat her nearly to death. Now comes the first volume of a projected
trilogy spanning the 20th century, with yet another splendidly
conceived voice in charge of the tale. Henry Smart is not just a
big, handsome lug who takes liberties with half the women he meets;
he's also cheeky enough to tell this story any damn way he pleases.
``I don't know any of this,'' he concedes in the middle of a
rhapsodic passage about his mother, and you realize his words are
an homage to the metaphoric reach of the imagination _ that the
story he's about to tell is either true or ought to be, whether or
not he was there to witness it. Our acceptance of Henry's deeply
interior voice is the narrative feat of ``A Star Called Henry,''
for the Dublin he delivers _ an underground world of sewer rats,
love stories, and political drama _ is a close-focus place so real
and seductive that only a fool or a genius could have invented it.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, of course, is a bit of both: a big, strapping boy born in
1901 to his birthright of the Dublin slums, his father a hit man
with a wooden leg, his mother a wreck of a woman who loses another
piece of her mind with each infant she buries. The children die
from consumption and cold and the crime of being hungry, and when
they die, she gives their name to the next baby born. She consoles
herself by believing that her dead ones turn into stars. ``God took
them all,'' remembers Henry. ``He needed them all up there to light
the night. He left her plenty, though. The ugly ones, the noisy
ones, the ones He didn't want _ the ones that would never stay
fed.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he's 5, Henry has taken his little brother Victor
and headed for life on the streets, where they can find more to
eat. The first third of ``A Star Called Henry'' is devoted to this
childhood, if you can call it that, and it's ferociously powerful;
Doyle captures the desperation of the slums with the intimate
authenticity of a poet, not an anthropologist. A quick, robust boy
who stands out sheerly because of his health, Henry knocks on the
door of a schoolroom after a few years, telling the woman who
answers that he's come for his education. Miss O'Shea will take in
Henry and Victor until the nuns get wind of her subterfuge, but not
before she has taught Henry to read. It won't be the last time a
woman instructs him in the finer things of life, and Miss O'Shea
will always be his unforgettable first.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Star Called Henry'' is broken into discrete sections that
trace Henry's young life through Ireland's own tumultuous history;
poised at adolescence, he stands 6-foot-2 and is carrying a rifle
for Michael Collins. It's the morning of the Easter Uprising in
1916, and Henry has found a place in the republican army _ he's got
someone worth believing in, and a good fight to avenge the death of
Victor, who died in his arms from tuberculosis. From his father,
Henry has learned the cruel necessities of violence; from Collins
and the other heroes of the republic, he's learned about a
brotherhood that has a higher order in mind. And from a poor beauty
named Piano Annie, who shows him every kind of comfort, Henry gets
a political lesson that will come back to haunt him: that ``the
times never get better for the likes of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his physical mass and his do-or-die intelligence, Henry
finds work easily enough on the docks; the hiring stevedore's palm
is also greased by the likes of Piano Annie. Such connections are
all over the place in Henry's universe: favors and friendships and
sidelong winks, whether they show up as a job or a roll in the hay
or a casual murder on the banks of the River Liffey. This is
Doyle's Dublin _ he has read buckets of Irish history to get it
right, and used his imagination to give it life _ and the geography
of ``A Star Called Henry'' pulses with the same energy as its
unruly protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   Less convincing is the political atmosphere of the novel _ not
because it isn't authentic, but because it often pales in
comparison with Henry himself. This is a difficult area for anyone
but the most Tolstoian of novelists, for social structures and
ideological factions rarely lend themselves to the introspective
particularity of the creative mind. Doyle's brilliant abilities
with laconic dialogue and narrative voice are wasted when he
overloads his story with historic detail; it sings a far better
song through its individual tones _ through the wisdom of Piano
Annie, say, or the woman who will eventually be known as ``Our Lady
of the Machine Gun.'' The bloody history of Ireland has happened
one body at a time, and that is the story that Doyle tells best.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the danger that surrounds him and his own recklessly
wild ride, we know from Doyle's well-placed hints that Henry will
long outlast the thugs in pursuit of him, whether Britain's hired
killers or the republic's opportunistic turncoats. Besides, even
the Black and Tans are no match for a kid who carries around his
dead father's wooden leg to protect him, who knows how to disappear
in the watery underground tombs of Dublin's rivers. Henry may have
become, for a while, the very worst of his father, but he's also
managed to hang on to that vision of the stars _ his ma's painful
reach toward the only light in the sky, even while the earth wept
at her feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book critic for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
