u e BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS &LR;      09-13 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Gesture Life'' by Chang-rae Lee (Riverhead, $23.95). A
beautifully realized novel about the reticent life of an elderly
Japanese-American. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Why Read the Classics?'' by Italo Calvino (Pantheon, $26). In
these essays, a literary genius confronts other geniuses _ and
reveals more of himself than of them. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Listener'' by Allen Wheelis (Norton, $25.95). A strange,
beautiful puzzle of a book, in which a psychoanalyst examines his
life. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Life'' by Claire Messud (Harcourt Brace, $24). A
haunting novel of a family's flight from Algeria to France. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Places Left Unfinished at the Time of Creation'' by John
Phillip Santos (Viking, $24.95). A lyrical memoir of a life on both
sides of the Texas-Mexico border. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Flowers in the Dustbin: The Rise of Rock and Roll, 1947-1977''
by James Miller (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $26). A guided tour of the glory
days of the music that parents were never meant to like. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrack'' by James Bradley (Holt, $25). In this novel of
southern Australia, an archeologist looks for an ancient lost ship,
but finds a not-so-ancient body. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Painting Religion in Public: John Singer Sargent's `Triumph of
Religion' at the Boston Public Library'' by Sally M. Promey
(Princeton University Press, $45). A fascinating study of Sargent's
unfinished murals and of changing attitudes toward the display of
religious belief. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hostage to Fortune: The Troubled Life of Francis Bacon'' by
Lisa Jardine and Alan Stewart (Hill &AMP; Wang, $35). A rich and
detailed biography of the Elizabethan courtier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
