A0230 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-13 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEATY ROLES DON'T GO TO WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I love the reviews Alec Baldwin has been getting for his role in
``Outside Providence.'' Who cares if he's ``a little chunky in the
midsection,'' or if he ``bears more than passing resemblance to the
Michelin man''?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody cares, because when Baldwin packs on the pounds and plays
against his usual leading man type he's a brilliant actor turning
in what one critic described as ``an Academy Award-worthy
appearance . . . stripped down to his boxer shorts, and sporting a
patch of graying stubble, a beer belly and a permanent sneer of
boozy contempt on his jowly face.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course even with a beer belly and stubbly jowls Alec Baldwin
still looks pretty good. But that's beside the point, which is that
when a male movie star gains weight it's a career-extending move.
But when a female movie star gains weight it's a career-ending
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine Baldwin's wife, Kim Basinger, gaining 100 pounds
for ``The Kate Smith Story''? Can you even imagine her on screen
looking ``a little chunky in the midsection''? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Pregnancy is the only circumstance in which a female star is
permitted to put on pounds, and she can't put on too many. If she
knows what's good for her she'd better be back in trim 20 minutes
after she delivers or she can kiss her career goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Robert De Niro was a genius when he porked up to play
out-of-shape boxer Jake LaMotta in ``Raging Bull.'' Isn't it
amazing how far he's willing to go to for a role?
</P>
<P>
   Erstwhile pretty boy John Travolta resurrected his career when
he cultivated a double chin and starred in ``Pulp Fiction.'' Who
knew he was a brilliant character actor?
</P>
<P>
   Even Sylvester Stallone's career was enhanced by the fat factor.
He let himself go for ``Cop Land'' and proved he's not just a human
action-figure.
</P>
<P>
   I'm trying to think of a female movie star who enhanced her
career by gaining weight. Are there any? When female stars expand,
their careers contract. They disappear. They go into hiding so they
won't end up with their photo in The National Enquirer with a
caption in which the word ``former'' figures prominently.
</P>
<P>
   We look to Hollywood for something to divert us from our own
lives and what do we see? Often we see older actors, some of them
``chunky in the middle,'' paired with much, much younger actresses
who look as though they might vanish if they turned sideways. Whose
fantasy is this?
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood men can go on indefinitely. A woman's career is
over when she's 30. Or it's over when she looks 30, which may not
be until she's 40-ish. If she looks over 30 and overweight, she
might as well hit the dinner theater circuit. And they may not want
her there, either.
</P>
<P>
   The double standard about weight isn't confined to the
entertainment business. I remember an Esquire magazine article that
explained what separates someone who is fat from someone who is
``attractively corpulent.'' It boiled down to this: women are fat;
men are attractively corpulent. Some men, at least, are
attractively corpulent. Others are merely fat, because fat isn't
just a sex issue, but a class issue too, for men anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Fat women, no matter how successful they may be, are fat. Men
who are powerful, wealthy, brilliant, or famous can be attractively
corpulent. Thus the character Baldwin plays in ``Outside
Providence'' is fat, but Baldwin the movie star is attractively
corpulent. Actually, he may be just attractive. I read that he's
been dieting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
