<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MANSON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S DRIVEN BY DATA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The working-mother decor in Dr. JoAnn Manson's office
_ brightly-colored crayon drawings of dinosaurs and solar systems _
gives little hint to the volume, or the magnitude, of the work that
comes out of it.
</P>
<P>
   A big chunk of the health advice Americans now follow to lower
their risk of heart disease _ from taking antioxidant vitamins or
postmenopausal hormone replacement therapy, to an aspirin a day, to
the much lauded brisk walk _ come from studies that Manson has
either headed or collaborated on.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Manson, 46, was named chief of preventive medicine at
Brigham and Women's Hospital. The appointment ended months of
speculation about who would fill the position left by Dr. Charles
Hennekens, who severed both his Brigham and Harvard ties when he
resigned from the institutions last March amid allegations he
sexually harassed co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Manson was promoted to full professor at Harvard
Medical School, where only 9 percent of professorships are held by
women.
</P>
<P>
   Manson, who heads seven grants totaling more than $20 million,
is best known for her work on the Women's Health Initiative and the
Nurses' Health Study, which has established, among other things,
that fiber prevents heart attacks in women, and that adult-onset
diabetes can be largely prevented through weight control, diet and
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The Nurses' study and the others are among the largest
``observational'' investigations in the world. Data from these
studies are culled from detailed questionnaires filled out by tens
of thousands of volunteers over many years and sometimes decades.
</P>
<P>
   Although Manson spends a good part of her life poring through
data, to her patients, she does not resemble the methodical
scientist that she is.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Andrews, 74, of Peabody, says that when Manson walks into
the office, she immediately becomes a friend. ``I have a white coat
syndrome. My heart beats harder just at the sight of it, but the
first thing she does is give you a big smile, and says `let's
talk,''' said Andrews, who diligently clips out every newspaper
article that mentions Manson's name and keeps them in a manila
folder. ``She's never rushed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the last few weeks, Manson, a board-certified
internist and endocrinologist with a 400-patient medical practice,
has managed to add even more papers to the 300 or so she's
published, including the August 26 report from the Nurses' Health
Study in the New England Journal of Medicine that brisk walking, at
least three hours per week, is as effective as vigorous exercise in
reducing the risk of heart attacks in women.
</P>
<P>
   Manson is convinced that low-tech approaches to disease
prevention, such as exercise, have as much to offer as high-tech
innovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heredity is not destiny when it comes to risk for most chronic
diseases. The role that lifestyle factors play in heart disease,
stroke, diabetes and many forms of cancer is truly astounding,''
says Manson, who spends a large percentage of her time treating
people with diabetes, a disease that has interested her since her
cousin developed it at 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the major technological advances in medicine,
there is probably nothing you can do that will improve your health
more than being physically active,'' says Manson. Ever the
public-health missionary, Manson would like to see her example made
easier to follow in the community. ``People are more likely to bike
or walk if they have convenient paths. We need more parks with good
lighting and police protection, where it's just safe to be walking
around,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Manson is also a firm believer in following one's own advice:
she and her husband make sure that they and their two children
spend at least an hour each Saturday and Sunday hiking or biking.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians should also be more proactive in advocating
life-style practices that have been very clearly linked to reducing
disease-risk, says Manson, who believes the key to getting patients
off the couch is to recommend something they like to do. .
</P>
<P>
   And, she's as ready to take up the prescription pad to outline
an exercise regimen as to specify a medication. A few weeks ago,
she penned a prescription for Virginia McElroy, 74, of Georgetown
that read: ``Gradually increase walking. Begin 5 minutes per day
for 3-4 days. Then 10 minutes a day for 3-4 days, and then 15
minutes a day. Gradually increase to 15 minutes two times a day, as
tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   McElroy, who has seen Manson every three months for at least 13
years, keeps the prescription on a table next to her ``TV chair,''
a swivel rocker, and has been spending less time in the rocker as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't written down, it would go out of my mind _
fast,'' said McElroy, who now takes daily walks around her
neighborhood as prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   Manson says that she has been better able to empathize with her
patients since she endured a few medical crises of her own. Five
years ago, she was diagnosed with melanoma and was successfully
treated. She also had gestational diabetes requiring insulin
injections and three hospitalizations for kidney stones.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard epidemiologist Julie Buring, who is the principal
investigator of the Women's Health Study and a long-time colleague
of Manson's, says the bouts with illness underscore how exceptional
Manson is. ``She's been going the same speed she always has, even
while battling health problems,'' Buring says.
</P>
<P>
   Manson, who grew up in northern Ohio, says she knew early on
that she wanted to go into medicine. Already influenced by her
mother, a medical social worker, and father, a NASA engineer, she
was encouraged by her high school chemistry teacher to pursue her
interest in science. Yet her classmates, she says, thought of her
more as an artsy type, since she painted, sculpted and played the
harp.
</P>
<P>
   She went on to do pre-med at Harvard, where she was a dance and
theater reviewer for the Harvard Independent, and where she met her
husband Christopher Ames, now a lawyer. The artwork that decorates
her office walls were done by their children, Jenn, 12, and
Jeffrey, 10.
</P>
<P>
   Friends have learned that if they want to invite the couple
over, Manson probably won't be calling a babysitter. ``They are
really magical children. It is absolutely our top priority in life
to be with the kids,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Case Western Reserve University School of
Medicine in Cleveland, Manson chose endocrinology, the study of
hormones, as her internal medicine subspecialty and returned to
Boston for her internship and residency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Endocrinology interfaces with almost every other medical
discipline and health condition...which is intellectually
stimulating,'' Manson explains. The field is also rewarding from a
clinical standpoint, she says, because it can enable doctors to
treat and reverse health problems rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1979, Manson's focus began to shift from clinical
practice to women's health and preventive medicine. During Manson's
first week of internship that year, her mother was diagnosed with
ovarian cancer and died several months later. After her residency,
Manson enrolled in an epidemiology and biostatistics program at the
Harvard School of Public Health, receiving a doctorate in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Manson is known nationally for her work in the prevention
of cardiovascular disease and diabetes. ``She has done a very
impressive amount of work in a short period of time,'' said Ross
Prentice, senior vice president of the Fred Hutchinson Cancer
Research Center in Seattle, which is the coordinating center for
the Women's Health Initiative, the largest women's health study to
date. Manson heads up the study's Brigham site.
</P>
<P>
   Younger colleagues describe Manson as a strong role model and
nurturer of their careers. Janet Rich-Edwards, an instructor at
Harvard Medical School's department of ambulatory care and
prevention, points to Manson's ability to work with a multitude of
different _ and often difficult _ personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Like Rich-Edwards, Dr. Simin Liu describes Manson as one of the
senior faculty who treats junior colleagues with respect. Liu says
that Manson was always one of the first to get back to him with
comments on his dissertation, which, he adds, ``is unusual for
someone with her seniority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
