<HEADLINE>
REP. KING'S CAUTIONARY TALE ABOUT IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Maine man went back into action last week in an effort to
revive the dangerously frayed peace process in Northern Ireland.
Former Senator George Mitchell, whose good will and common sense
was the foundation for last year's Good Friday agreement, is now
laboring to jump-start the agreement's implementation.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mitchell began a private exercise in crisis diplomacy,
Boston College was playing host to another figure of serious repute
in Ireland whose latest contribution to the situation has been the
publication of a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Peter King, a conservative Republican congressman from Long
Island, is as major a player in Irish affairs as you can find on
Capitol Hill. And he has been a voice for justice and not merely
nonviolence as a route out of The Troubles. This latest
manifestation of his passion has oddly impeccable timing.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is the perfect American manifestation of the insistence
that reason must find the way to begin implementing a power-sharing
government in the North that is free of direct rule from London.
But King is the perfect American manifestation of the reason people
of all backgrounds should care about this mess. He reminds us why
it is a mess _ because of injustice.
</P>
<P>
   King wrote ``Terrible Beauty'' (the title is a Yeats line from
``Easter, 1916'') in draft form several years ago, when nearly all
the news was bad, but when its portrayal of the injustice and
oppression suffered by the Catholic minority in the North would
have inevitably been seen as partisan.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out now, the novel is meant to serve an instructive
purpose, as a cautionary tale of what going backwards would mean.
``There's a danger of a return to violence and suffering that is
always just beneath the surface,'' King said. ``It wouldn't take
that much to set it off, despite the fact most people want peace to
work. We need to understand how dangerous these forces are and how
easily they can spiral out of control again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrible Beauty'' is no congressional drivel-novel. It has
awkward moments when you can sense the hand of someone who has read
an appropriations bill, but for the nonexpert reader, it is a
riveting portrait of Belfast life in the early 1980s _ hunger
strikes, internment without trial, Margaret Thatcher at her worst,
trials that mock Anglo-American principles, hideous violence among
paramilitary organizations that catch civilians in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   His heroine, Bernadette Hanlon, is a housewife who labors to
stay away from the tension and violence for the sake of her kids'
future, but who is drawn relentlessly into it by the injustice at
its core. She has already lost a brother who is blown up by the
bomb he was making for the Irish Republican Army. But her attempt
at life begins to unravel when her husband, Dermot, is rounded up
for IRA activities and than faces trumped-up charges of murder. It
is a story right out of the dirty pages of all-to-recent history.
</P>
<P>
   Here she is describing the ``justice'' system her husband faces:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, for one thing, he's not allowed to have a jury. He'll be
tried before a judge who in most cases is either a former unionist
politician or a British army officer . . . In my husband's case,
the only evidence against him will be the statement of an admitted
perjurer and criminal. There's no corroboration whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what it was like. King was a regular visitor to the North
during the 1980s _ at the time of the hunger strikes by IRA
convicts, when he served on an international panel examining the
use of plastic bullets for ``crowd control'' by the police and
British forces. One of the novel's gut-wrneching scenes is of the
casual shooting of the daugher of Bernadette's neighbor, her head
shattered by one of those humane-sounding bullets.
</P>
<P>
   King's novel foreshadows the more arid report last week by a
British commission that the Royal Ulster Constabulary be stripped
of its unionist name and colors, reconstituted with a far more
Catholic presence than its currently 92 percent Protestant makeup,
and supervised by a panel from the new government of the North,
which by the numbers would include people from Sinn Fein, the
political wing of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the leader of the Ulster Unionists, David Trimble,
complained, but his complaint once again is over having to actually
go through with power-sharing, which means ending the overt
discrimination that led to The Troubles in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Compromises and good-faith gestures on all sides are required
now, and Mitchell's job is to help all the parties step up. But
that cannot obscure the fact that an evil system must be
dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   King is the son of a New York cop, whose grandparents came here
from Galway and Limerick early this century. A product of the
Sunnyside section of Queens, he followed so many out of the city,
onto Long Island and into the Republican Party. He's also the other
kind of Republican, a passionate believer in a united Ireland, but
one who has used his influence to shove other believers toward
peace, power-sharing, and faith in the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   His novel has a bittersweet ending _ a legal vindication and two
more hideous murders. It doesn't have to be that way again, but
``Terrible Beauty'' is a study in how easily it can happen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
