<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOOTBALL-SUNDAY-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: x x x to get slaughtered.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   That competition explains part of CBS' thinking in revamping its
``NFL Today'' team. Back in the NFL business last year after a
four-year absence, CBS placed veteran host Jim Nantz in the studio
with George Seifert, Brent Jones and Marcus Allen. All were light
on TV experience. Seifert left before the season ended and now
coaches the Carolina Panthers. Jones was moved to game analysis.
Allen remains in the studio but now will be joined by James,
veteran analyst Randy Cross and former Fox game analyst and NFL
coach Jerry Glanville.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't create chemistry,'' Cross said. ``There's absolutely
no way. You want this sizzling, popping, wonderful, sparkling
little thing, but you can't create it. You just put it together and
hope it works that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very uncomfortable comparing last year to this year,''
Nantz said. ``I'm back. I feel very loyal to the people I've worked
with. Our team last year was put in a tough situation. First year
back into pro football. First year as a television broadcaster. I
know the show really improved as the season went on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox had the most-watched pregame show last year, generating an
average Nielsen rating of 3.7 (one rating point represents
approximately 9.42 million U.S. homes). CBS finished at 2.7, while
ESPN had a 2.2 cable rating and CNN 0.6. The network that covers
the NFC, which has teams in eight of the top 10 TV markets, has
virtually always had better pregame ratings than the AFC
rights-holders. Fans who follow a particular team generally watch
that network's pregame show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think since the game's on that network, they will
do more on my game,'' said ESPN's Rauscher. ``Other people think,
`I don't want to miss anything,' so they put on that station when
they first get up and just leave it on so they won't miss
kickoff.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS enjoyed that ratings edge before 1994 _ when Fox took away
the NFC package _ and now fights an uphill climb as the AFC
network. ``Ratings-wise, there is an advantage to having the NFC
markets,'' said Eric Mann, coordinating producer for the CBS show.
``In the production of the show, hopefully you're on an even
keel.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross, a three-time All-Pro in a 13-year career with the San
Francisco 49ers, said the pregame shows have a built-in audience:
current players. ``I know players watch them,'' Cross said. ``There
are a lot of people who want to know either what's going to happen
or why it's going to happen. The only real resource you have is the
pregame look. I played on the West Coast, so at 9 o'clock the
pregame shows were on.''
</P>
<P>
   Former players say they work hard to make sure they're as
prepared for a Sunday in the broadcast booth as they were on the
field. The quest for credibility drives many of these pregame
performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like Chris Mortensen,'' James said, referring to an ESPN
reporter who did not play in the NFL, ``I know when Chris says
something, he's not just pulling it out. I know Mort's out there
doing his homework. That's why it's so important for me to work
hard. I don't want anybody to say, `This guy's out there throwing
mud against the wall.' I've worked hard to get to the position I'm
at. I want to keep it, so I've got to double up my efforts more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I missed about coaching was the
competition,'' said retired Buffalo Bills coach Marv Levy, who will
be part of the Fox Sports Net show. ``If there are a lot of shows
out there, it's good for the game, just as a lot of teams are good
for the game. I'm going to welcome the competition. I hope our show
is something people say is something special, just like they say
the Denver Broncos are something special.''
</P>
</TEXT>
