<HEADLINE>
HOMELESS PEOPLE ARE HUMAN, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The thing about Paul Boden and the Coalition on
Homelessness that makes them super attractive to some of us is the
same thing that makes a lot of other San Franciscans wish the
coalition would get the hell out of town:
</P>
<P>
   They are brutally honest, and they insist that homeless people
be treated as if they are 100 percent human and deserving of
genuine _ not virtual _ dignity.
</P>
<P>
   They also refuse to do the humble Uriah Heep bit because
somebody deigns to write a check or volunteer an hour's time for
the poor and downtrodden. They appreciate it, of course. But they
see help and charity as simply the decent thing to do for a just
society.
</P>
<P>
   Take the organization's fund-raiser on Wednesday at the Somarts
Gallery: a live and silent auction of dozens of stunning works
donated by some of the Bay Area's most talented artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we don't make money, it's going to be a positive
experience for all of us,'' Boden said. ``Last year, we netted
about $25,000 on the Willie (Brown) Roast. That money might be what
you want as a non-profit, but it was a hell of a price to pay. We
lost control of our message. The event just wasn't us. It was the
kind of event that _ if somebody else did it _ we'd probably
protest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Willie Roast _ a $150-a-ticket lambasting of the mayor at a
tony downtown hotel _ commemorated the coalition's 10th year of
existence. The art auction _ $15 a pop _ is in honor of the 10th
anniversary of the coalition's official newspaper, the Street
Sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Angry, irreverent and provocative, the newspaper is sold for $1
by poor women and men as an alternative to flat-out panhandling.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to volunteers, contributors and donors, the sellers get
to keep every cent of every buck.
</P>
<P>
   Several donated pieces came from artists like Art Hazelwood and
Roberta Loach, whose work has appeared over the years in the Street
Sheet. Others, such as Debra Koval's vibrant abstract ``Dream
Home'' (evocative of Miro and Kandinsky), are some artists' answer
to a cause they believe to be righteous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work full-time and I'm a single parent,'' Koval said. ``This
is my way of volunteering.''
</P>
<P>
   The scope and quality of the 135 art works that will be
auctioned off is impressive enough to anchor any fund-raiser, be it
the symphony's or the coalition's. Landscapes, portraits, still
lifes, abstracts, folk art and primitives offer something for every
taste.
</P>
<P>
   Cityphiles with a hankering for new perspectives on our gorgeous
old town should be especially tempted to bid. Craig Nelson's tiny,
traditional oils, like ``Palace Pond,'' are exquisite.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Hanlon's haunting pastels, like ``Where Do You
Live?'', are quiet knock-outs.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the contributing artists, Hanlon is an instructor
at the California Academy of Arts. Unlike many, she was once
homeless herself _ when she was in graduate school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, she was vehicularly housed,'' said the auction's
planner/coordinator, Kathleen Gray. ``She lived in her car.
Homelessness can happen to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   That set of facts _ Hanlon was homeless, now she's not, and
she's been a creative force wherever she has lived _ basically sums
up Paul Boden's attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``The homeless are always being lumped into one big mass. Their
homelessness is used to define their entire life, their
individuality is ignored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen through the Street Sheet what happens when people
can create their own vehicle for expression and put it out there
and see if it resonates with others. The Street Sheet has shown us
we resonate, that we're not alone. It wouldn't be here 10 years
later if people weren't reading it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it works for many charitable organizations, the idea of
peddling pity is anathema to the Coalition members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between being written about as a
homeless person and writing your own stuff,'' Boden said. ``To have
a thought or an experience, to put it out there, whether it's an
editorial, a poem or art, and see the ripple effect of it, to
communicate directly with the community _ THAT'S power. That's what
this auction and the Coalition are about.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
