   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   GOVS-ENERGY _ MEMPHIS _ Southern Governors Association meets in
Memphis through Tuesday. Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes delivers a morning
address on energy and participates in session on regional air
quality. (Pruitt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   ABERNATHY-TRIAL _ ATLANTA _ More testimony in trial of former
state Sen. Ralph D. Abernathy III. He is accused of stealing more
than $13,000 from taxpayers since 1994 by billing the state for
phony expenses as well as violating his oath of office, forgery and
influencing a witness. Fulton County trial expected to run about a
week and a half. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SKOL-PRAYERDAY _ Sept. 15 is the annual ``See You At the Pole''
day when students are invited to pray around the flagpoles at their
schools. This year, after months of shocking school violence,
adults are becoming more involved. Southern Baptists are
coordinating an activity called ``Campus Prayer Journeys,'' in
which adults are being asked to gather on public school grounds to
pray for students and school staffers at 7 p.m. on the evening
before the Sept. 15 observance of See You at the Pole. (White,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-RELATIONS _ Hal Saunders, a former asst. secretary of
state, worked with the Arabs and Israelis on peace accords in the
'70s. He mediated with civil war parties in Tajikistan in the '90s.
But what he found, in his work in the government and in the
Kettering Foundation, is that real people's attitude matters more
than treaties and promises. So Saunders is tackling race relations
in America now, with the lessons he learned about dialogue abroad.
He'll talk about his book on these issues at Books &AMP; Co. in
Kettering, and talks with us now. He also invites Dayton to contact
him on starting deep dialogue here. (Lee, Dayton Daily News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-EXPLOSIONS _ MOSCOW _ Declaring that ``terrorism has
declare war on us,'' President Boris Yeltsin on Monday ordered
increased security across Russia after an early-morning bomb
leveled an eight-story apartment building in Moscow, the second
such attack in four days. At least 45 people were killed and scores
were missing after the latest explosion. A blast last Thursday at
another apartment block killed 93. Authorities suspect that
bombings are the work of terrorists aligned with Muslim insurgents
fighting federal troops in the southern Russian republic of
Dagestan. The United States has pledged to help Russia battle
terrorism. Russian authorities believe Osama bin Laden _ accused of
masterminding the twin bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania last year - is helping to bankroll the Islamic insurgents
in Dagestan. (Holmes, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ ATLANTA _ The first refugee family to arrive
in Atlanta has decided to return to Kosovo, and other families
assisted by Jubilee Partners gathered Sunday to wish them well. The
family hopes to be on a Sept. 18 flight, but could go sooner. At
least four other families at the Jubilee facility also want to
return. Will include an update how many from Atlanta and the U.S.
have signed up to go back. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-REPORT _ WASHINGTON _ Fearing that the Republican
Congress would slash Title I funds if the program for economically
disadvantaged K-12 students became controversial, the Democratic
Clinton administration lets states get away with using lower
academic standards for poor inner-city children than for
middle-class suburban children, charges a 169-page report issued
Monday by the private Citizens' Commission on Civil Rights, a
30-year-old bipartisan watchdog group. (Mollison, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   FARM _ WASHINGTON _ Farmers from across the United States hold a
rally to urge Congress to replace the 1996 Freedom to Farm Act,
which had ``caused economic disaster'' in rural America. The rally
precedes a House Agriculture Committee hearing on Tuesday. (Dart,
Cox News Service). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS-POLITICS _ WASHINGTON _ The Congressional Hispanic
Caucus Institute holds its 1999 issues conference. Dolores Huerta,
secretary-treasurer of the United Farm Workers of America, delivers
luncheon remarks on ''Will the Hispanic Community be Organized for
the 2000 Election?'' (Shepard, Cox News Service). 29.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washingbton and (p) politics categories.
</P>
