<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, Sept.
14.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE-TIMES &LR;  (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SALMON-CRISIS (Undated) _ The wild Atlantic salmon
population is in what appears to be an accelerating downward
spiral; the numbers that are returning to spawn in their native
streams have plummeted to what some scientists say is an all-time
low. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SCIENTIST-FEUDS (Undated) _ Though the casual reader would
never know it from the textbooks, beneath the flapping banners of
feuding scientific ideas, as often as not there are feuding
scientists. Some skirmishes do little more than quicken the pace of
research, as when Albert Einstein and the German mathematician
David Hilbert raced each other for the first correct formulation of
the equations of general relativity in 1915. Other spats have the
effect of both drawing attention to an important research question
while souring many scientists on ever working in the field. By
James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DYSLEXIA-BRAIN (Undated) _ Some entrepreneurs and brain
scholars say they have found ways to fix dyslexia and other brain
problems. But the big problems is that virtually all the scientific
research is by the people pushing the programs: those who stand to
make money from them. By Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHIMP-SURPLUS (Undated) _ A controversy is swelling over a
surplus of research chimpanzees and how they should be kept. By
Shannon Brownlee &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LAUGHTER-MUSCLES (Undated) _ The phrase ``falling down with
laughter'' exists in many languages, and there's a scientific
reason for that. Laughter, it turns out, seems to trigger a reflex
that can bring many of the muscles of the body to the point of
collapse. The phenomenon can actually be measured by sending
electric signals through the muscles and gauging their response. By
Eric Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HYPERSPECTAL-CAMERA (Cooke City, Mont.) _ The hyperspectral
camera or a hyperspectral imaging spectrometer is one of a new
generation of instruments that experts predict will transform many
areas, including ecosystem management, agriculture, diamond and
gold mining, hazardous waste cleanup, even wildland firefighting.
The device not only picks up the difference between a pine tree and
a fir tree but the difference between a healthy pine and one
stressed by drought or incipient disease, even if it is invisible
to the naked eye. By Jim Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARTHQUAKE (Undated) _ Despite occurring within 400 miles of
each other, the major earthquakes that struck Turkey and Greece are
unrelated and linked to different types of faults. By Henry
Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH &AMP; FITNESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SICKLE-CELL-PAIN (Cleveland) _ Patients with the agonizing
and intractable pain of sickle cell disease should get better and
more consistent relief because of new treatment guidelines that
call for comprehensive management of the pain, experts say. The
guidelines, aimed at doctors, nurses and other health professionals
who treat sickle cell disease, call for aggressive use of drugs
along with behavioral, psychological and physical therapies to
relieve patients' suffering. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YOUTH-SOCCER (Undated) _ As the fall soccer season begins,
legions of schoolchildren are taking to the fields with images of
the stunning World Cup victory by the United States women's team
still fresh in their minds. But many doctors have other matters on
their minds: how to make soccer safer for children in light of
recent reports linking it to repeated concussions and diminished
mental functioning. By Susan Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MILK (Undated) _ In recent years, a vigorous campaign by
some vegetarian and animal rights groups, along with new research
suggesting that even a lifetime of milk drinking may not be
sufficient to guard against bone disease, has put milk's advocates
on the defensive and left ordinary consumers to wonder who is
right. By Mary Murray.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STANDARD FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (UNdated) _ Science notes and news: Items on dancing
peafowl, the laundry room of the cell and deforestation. By Henry
Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health: According to
reports in the medical literature, as many as 98 percent of
patients have excellent results from laser eye surgery. But growing
numbers of patients are painting a less rosy picture and warning
others to weigh the risks carefully. Many say they were not
sufficiently warned about what could go wrong and that mishaps,
when they occur, may not be correctable by wearing glasses or
contacts. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Health and Fitness notes and news:
Items on doctor-patient relationships, leg ailments and lead
exposure at indoor shooting ranges.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions and answers. By C.
Claiborne Ray.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-ARATON-COLUMN (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ Sports column on the Jets,
who had been considered favorites in the American Conference but
now must contend with losing their starting quarterback and running
back/kick returner. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES-BLUEJAYS (Toronto) _ Yankees at Toronto, 7 p.m.
After being swept by Boston over the weekend, the Yankees lead the
Red Sox by only three and a half games. Monday night, the team
faces Toronto and David Wells, the player traded away for Roger
Clemens. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   METS-ROCKIES (Denver) _ Mets at Colorado, 8 p.m. The Mets, who
trail Atlanta by two games, hope to continue their success out
West. By Judy Battista.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-NY-RACES (Undated) _ On Baseball column: Could it be that
the Yankees are no longer a lock for the post-season while the Mets
are streaking along? The Mets, who are still in the thick of the
division and wild-card races in the National League, do own the
best record in town. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GIANTS (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ The Giants got their
victory in Game 1, but not without reviving a lot of questions
about their offense that they thought and hoped they had buried in
preseason. By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ Coach Bill Parcells has to get his
team physically and mentally ready to face Buffalo next week in the
wake of the season-ending injury to Vinny Testaverde. By Gerald
Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-QUARTERBACKS (Undated) _ On Pro Football column: The
quarterbacking situation around the league: The Jets pointed up the
obvious fragility of the position, but other teams have problems
even with veterans _ like San Francisco and Steve Young. Still,
there is promise in players like Peyton Manning, Jake Plummer,
Steve McNair and even the unknowns like Kurt Warner and Shane
Matthews. By Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BRONCOS-DOLPHINS (Denver) _ Miami at Denver, 9 p.m. Monday
night football debut featuring defending Super Bowl champions. By
Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-OPEN (Undated) _ U.S. Open folo: This Grand Slam tournament
showed that women's tennis is able to regenerate itself. The
Williams sisters and Hingis and Seles and Davenport are ready to
rule even as Graf and Novotna bow out, with Sanchez-Vicario and
Mary Jo Fernandez right behind them. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE/ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (`e' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-DIGEST (Waldoboro, Maine) _ Tradition treads lightly
here at the eclectic, contemporary home of The Maine Antique
Digest, widely called ``M.A.D.'' (not to be confused with the
satirical magazine Mad). A family-run newspaper with two staff
reporters and an army of freelancers and tipsters, this
independent, influential and successful monthly manages the trick
of policing as well as serving the nation's unruly
multibillion-dollar annual trade in antiques and collectibles. By
Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   EMMY-AWARDS (Undated) _ Follow-up on the unexpected results in
the Emmys. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   MILAN-ARTS (Milan) _ Arts Abroad: Five hundred years to the day
after French soldiers destroyed a work in progress by Leonardo da
Vinci of what would have been the largest equestrian statue in
existence by using it for crossbow practice, a 24-foot-high, 15-ton
silicon bronze sculpture of the stallion was unveiled in a garden
that forms part of the city's horse racing track. By John
Tagilabue.
</P>
<P>
   MCCOURT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Tis,'' by Frank McCourt, is
reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   SHORT-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Martin Short Show'' is
reviewed by Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FASHION (`l' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-FASHION (New York) _ Review of fashion shows of Susan
Cianciolo, Diane Von Furstenberg, Versus, and Carolina Herrera. By
Cathy Horyn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS-FASHION (New York) _ Fashion notes and news: The return
of Amy Wesson. By Ginia Bellafante.
</P>
