<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0267 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-WOMEN-IDIOM-HNS &LR;      09-13 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-IDIOM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE, YOU KNOW, LEARN TO TALK, PUH-LEEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAYNE WOLFE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ My boss (I call him ``Sir'') and I are being
driven mad by the way women talk. Especially the young ones with
``like'' and ``you know'' and ``you know, like.''
</P>
<P>
   They give him fits. Hearing one too many ``so I said, and he
said,'' accompanied by cries of ``oh, puh-leeez'' have made him
move to another table in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more annoying to Sir than the speech patterns of
young women are those of more mature one who, like Catskills
comedians, pepper their monologues with ``yaddah, yaddah, yaddah,''
``Hel-lo?'' or, ``Get a clue, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Sir and I agree that these speech patterns are learned _ but
from whom? There was a time when we could confidently blame the
Valley Girl phenomenon, but that impact has faded. Are movies and
television the source, offering up chatterboxes as models?
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to point a finger at anyone. Certainly, no one is
blaming Meryl Streep, who always speaks like a sip of amber
whiskey. Even the omnipresent Oprah, who has never shied away from
mugging at the camera, speaks in a dignified manner.
</P>
<P>
   Sir adds, ``If you could explain to me why it's the women and
not the men who insist on this childish nattering, you would, like,
totally make my day.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to focus our ire properly, Sir and I have a running joke
about how modern women should study old movies to learn how to
speak well. Conversely, we wonder which movie stars' careers would
have been smashed had they delivered their lines like Starbucks'
clerks.
</P>
<P>
   So tell us. Why would any woman choose to speak like Cyndi
Lauper if she'd ever heard Lauren Bacall? Can you imagine the young
Bacall saying to Humphrey Bogart: ``Hey, Pal! You know, like uh,
how to like whistle, doncha? Hel-lo-oh? You go like this. Like,
just pucker your lips and _ blow! Duh!''
</P>
<P>
   Had Bacall spoken like most of the female marketing executives
we know, Bogart would have borrowed a good book from the captain's
library and curled up with it for the duration of the voyage. Fur
sure, mon. When Bette Davis delivered her famous line, ``Buckle up.
It's going to be a bumpy ride,'' in ``All about Eve,'' the audience
tittered in anticipation. She was a woman to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   But would she have made the same impact had she said, ``You
know, I'm like feeling, like really awesome, hella bad vibes
tonight. Like, beam me up, Scotty!''?
</P>
<P>
   Or remember in ``Rear Window'' when Grace Kelly explained softly
that she brought the nicest little Mark Cross case that held all
she needed for a sleepover? James Stewart nearly forgot he was in a
wheelchair with a broken leg. But had Kelly squeaked, ``OhmyGod,
look at this, like, totally cute bag I got today!'' he might have
chosen instead to hook up with Thelma Ritter, the visiting nurse
who gave him his sponge baths.
</P>
<P>
   Sir and I agree that women who speak in this petulant teen-speak
should not expect to be taken seriously _ by anyone. So you tell
us. Given the choice of sounding like Fran Dresher playing a
gangster's moll or Audrey Hepburn as Holly Golightly, why are so
many American women turning their backs on the guaranteed allure,
not to mention the benefits, of mellifluous speech? You got me,
man. It's like, totally weird, you know?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Rayne Wolfe, a free-lance writer, is a columnist for the San
Francisco Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
