<HEADER>
A0324 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV1     09-13 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV12-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER TABLE MAY SOLVE A PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)  
 (For release Sunday, September 12, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My house is 20 years old with original Masonite (hardboard)
siding. The two bottom strips of hardboard are rotting. A
contractor suggested putting up primed siding or vinyl, first
removing all the hardboard. Is removing the old hardboard
necessary?
</P>
<P>
   H.M., Marlborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Your contractor thinks so, and so does the handyman, if you
are going to put on any new siding. And, cedar, white or red,
clapboards or shingles, is better than vinyl, which in this
handyman's opinion is no better than the hardboard. The reason all
hardboard should come off is that it may decay under any new
siding; hardboard is notorious for decaying when it gets wet; that
is why it is so heavily painted. Also, new siding will lie smoothly
and evenly on the sheathing if the hardboard is removed.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another idea: If the hardboard is intact above the two
boards that are decaying, you can try this and save a bundle of
money: Take off the two decaying hardboard boards, and install a 1
x 10 or 1 x 12 pressure-treated board (whatever size will cover the
area of the two bottom boards that were removed). Put flashing
between the new board and the hardboard above. You are creating a
water table, which is the New England term for such a board. Let
that board weather or paint or stain it the same color as the trim
or hardboard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have weeds growing in the cracks of a very long hardtop
driveway. You have mentioned using vinegar to keep them away. I
don't think vineger will kill the weeds or the seeds that they are
storing. Would a torch work?
</P>
<P>
   MARGO LONG, Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. A torch (like an acetylene torch or similar fire-spewing
tool) will work, but could melt the hardtop. Better I think is a
hot-air gun. It too could melt the asphalt but any weed, and seeds,
should be dead by the time the gun threatens to melt the asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I just put up a new deck with a mahogany railing. I would
like it to weather. What can I do to make it weather nicely and
stand up to the weather?
</P>
<P>
   HOWARD LEVY, Swampscott, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's start with the mahogany railing. And this goes for the
floorboards, too, if they are mahogany. Mahogany is naturally decay
resistant and will weather to an attractive, even, silver color.
But, according to recent studies, it should not be left to weather
without some protection because ultraviolet rays break down lignin
in the wood, the ``glue'' that holds the wood together. When lignin
breaks down, the wood deteriorates.
</P>
<P>
   So, treat the wood with a clear sealer to prevent this. This
sealer should be renewed once every year or so; there is nothing
maintenance-free about a wood deck.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly important on horizontal surfaces such as
floorboards and railings. Vertical surfaces are less likely to
deteriorate, but it is a good idea to seal these as well.
</P>
<P>
   This all applies to any other wood: pressure-treated, cedar,
Douglas fir, and all pines.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative to sealing and allowing the wood to weather is
to apply one coat of a semitransparent stain. You will get a color,
and the wood will not weather, but such stains last longer than
sealers; three or more years is typical for some semitransparent
stains; at that time, apply another single coat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I want my brand new mahogany deck to keep its mahogany color.
I applied CWF (Clear Wood Finish) which is designed to keep wood
new-looking, but it didn't do very well. What can I use?
</P>
<P>
   KEITH FLAHERTY, Wilmington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Nothing, other than trying other brands of a CWF-type finish.
Keeping wood new-looking outdoors goes against the natural tendency
of wood to weather; but people want such a new look, and
manufacturers are eager to accommodate their desires _ for money.
If you are unsatisfied with the CWF (or the even better CWF-UV,
which resists ultraviolet rays), go to a semitransparent stain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are the pros and cons on garage doors: wood or metal?
The bottom panel of my custom-made door has rotted out and a
custom-made replacement costs $290. I can get a metal door for $550
to $750. Is it worth getting a new metal door?
</P>
<P>
   BARRY STEARNS, Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, how long did the bottom panel last: 20 years? 10? The
point I'm getting at is that for $290 you will be set for another
10 to 20 years, or as long as the old panel lasted.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the steel doors are good, well painted, and light in
weight, and the price is right for a custom unit. They will dent,
and must be kept painted to prevent them from rusting; removing
rust and repainitng is a pain. Now you can make your choice. I
personally would opt for the replacement panel.
</P>
<P>
   Some garage doors are insulated. That is not a good argument for
buying such a door. Garage doors need no insulation because garages
are unheated; the insulation will do no good at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
