<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0329 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      09-13 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSTY CLOSET NEEDS VENTILATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. One of the upstairs closets in my Cape Cod-style house smells
funny, sort of dampish and musty. And a white shirt hanging in the
closet developed brown spots where it was closest to the wall. How
can I get rid of the smell, and the brown spots on the shirt, and
prevent them both from returning?
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS EVANS, Franklin, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Ah yes, moisture and mold rear their ugly heads again. Your
closet smells funny because it is closed. Water vapor builds up in
it; that causes the musty smell. When it condenses on a cool
surface, that causes mold to grow. The brown stain on the shirt is
probably rust, caused by a wet steel hanger.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, keep the closet door open, or install a louvered
door so that air can circulate and prevent the buildup of water
vapor. That should take care of a lot of the problems. Also, hang a
100-watt light bulb in the closet; this will provide enough warmth
to help dissipate the water vapor and prevent condensation. Keep
the light on, of course.
</P>
<P>
   If you see black smears in the closet, or little black dots, you
know you have mildew, and should wash it with a solution of 1 part
bleach and 3 parts water. This mildew treatment may be old hat to
the handyman, but many people are discovering it for the first
time, so it's always worth repeating. Also not old hat is this
necessary warning: wear skin and eye protection when working with
bleach.
</P>
<P>
   For the brown spots on the shirt, try treating them with Whink,
a rust remover sold in supermarkets. Avoid hanging a shirt on a
metal hanger, and keep it and other clothes a little farther away
from that cool wall. I know that might not be easy or even
possible, but clothes should be kept away from cool walls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The wallpaper in one room of my house was badly stained by
leaks from an ice dam. The paper is fairly old, and I don't think
it is vinyl-coated, but that stain really shows. How can I clean
it?
</P>
<P>
   TOM SANTORO, Malden, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Nothing that I know of will clean it, because water stains
are indelible. I don't think you can even disguise it, although you
can try erasing it with a gum eraser. If you have any spare paper
tucked away, you could use it as a patch or replace the entire
strip. This is your best chance for a match, because the spare
paper is just as old as that on the wall. It might be lighter,
however, because it has been rolled up all these years. Patching
with new paper, even if you can find the same pattern, is unlikely
to work because the old will be much darker than the new.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to this brilliant idea, if all else fails:
Repaper the entire wall with new paper of a similar pattern, or a
plain pattern. It might sound kind of funny to do one wall, but
what the heck, you solved the problem inexpensively, and such a
situation can be lived with until you are ready to redo the entire
room.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q Should I seal my new driveway after one year? It will cost
$800 to seal because it is so large (it cost $3,200 to install).
</P>
<P>
   A.R., Foxborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Save yourself $800, because it is not necessary to seal a
driveway, new or old. It is mostly for appearance's sake. That is
not just the handyman's opinion either, because one caller who
asked about it told the handyman that her driveway contractor said,
``Forget about it. It is only cosmetic.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
