<HEADER>
A0330 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-BREAD-MAKERS-HNS &LR;      09-13 0306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAD-MAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKING BREAD IS A CHORE NO MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In our fast-paced world, even bread has to keep
up with the times. Bread making by hand used to take hours, between
waiting for the yeast to rise and the kneading process.
</P>
<P>
   Automatic bread makers are improving, after being around for a
number of years. More than 20 million U.S. households have one,
according to Association of Home Appliance Manufacturers in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Bread makers can be found in almost any appliance store and
catalog, but take your time and shop around, noting various
features so that you buy a model that meets your baking
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Bread machines cost from $70 to more than $200. Models start
with very basic functions (making a single loaf of white bread) and
add more sophisticated features such as cycles for bagels, pizza
dough, batter breads and cake and jam bread. Delayed timers let you
set the bread to be ready when you want it. Some models can produce
a 2-pound loaf in less than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Most make a 1-, 1 1/2- or 2-pound loaf in the nonstick pan.
Because consumers were not as happy with square loaves, many
machines now come with a horizontal style baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   With some bread machines, you can set the shape of the loaf and
color of the crust, from light to medium or dark. Most models have
a viewing window so you can watch the bread taking shape. The
display timer will tell you how much time is left until the dough
becomes bread.
</P>
<P>
   Other features include a power failure backup, fruit and nut
add-in beeper, whole wheat bread or multigrain cycles,
13-to-24-hour delay bake timer and cycle combinations.
</P>
<P>
   You get the flavorful aroma and fresh taste without the messy
cleanup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
