r f BC-Y2K-PREPARE-$ADV19-CO     09-13 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-PREPARE-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'PRUDENCE, NOT PANIC' IS WATCHWORD FOR Y2K PREPARATIONS
 &HT;    With Y2K. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
for release Sunday, Sept. 19.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With little more than 100 days left until the Jan.
1 deadline when computers might malfunction because of the
so-called Y2K bug, experts say individuals must join in the battle.
</P>
<P>
   All Americans can make responsible contingency plans to cope
with difficulties that might arise in early January, according to
Rep. Stephen Horn, R-Calif., chairman of the House Government
Reform subcommittee, which monitors Y2K efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prudence, not panic'' is his motto.
</P>
<P>
   Like most other Y2K experts, Horn says each household should
prepare for possible disruptions in the delivery of electricity,
water, phone service or heat. While utilities and other companies
have made enormous progress in reprogramming computers and chips
embedded in equipment, no one can guarantee there won't be
scattered service breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream experts say Y2K tests show that significant problems
almost certainly can be fixed within 72 hours, so there is no need
for hoarding of water, food or cash. Even worst-case scenarios call
for only two weeks of disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   But while problems are not likely to be long in duration, even
one night without electricity in January can be dangerous unless
contingency plans are in place.
</P>
<P>
   By setting aside some water, fresh batteries, warm blankets and
nutritious foods that need no significant preparation, families can
protect themselves, according to the American Red Cross and other
relief organizations.
</P>
<P>
   And if Jan. 1 does pass quietly, as it will for the great
majority of Americans, then no harm will have been done. Households
with emergency supplies will be better prepared for the next
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
