<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Tuesday, Sept. 14
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-DIGEST (Waldoboro, Maine) _ Tradition treads lightly
here at the eclectic, contemporary home of The Maine Antique
Digest, widely called ``M.A.D.'' (not to be confused with the
satirical magazine Mad). A family-run newspaper with two staff
reporters and an army of freelancers and tipsters, this
independent, influential and successful monthly manages the trick
of policing as well as serving the nation's unruly
multibillion-dollar annual trade in antiques and collectibles. By
Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   EMMY-AWARDS (Undated) _ Follow-up on the unexpected results in
the Emmys. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   MILAN-ARTS (Milan) _ Arts Abroad: Five hundred years to the day
after French soldiers destroyed a work in progress by Leonardo da
Vinci of what would have been the largest equestrian statue in
existence by using it for crossbow practice, a 24-foot-high, 15-ton
silicon bronze sculpture of the stallion was unveiled in a garden
that forms part of the city's horse racing track. By John
Tagilabue.
</P>
<P>
   MCCOURT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Tis,'' by Frank McCourt, is
reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   SHORT-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Martin Short Show'' is
reviewed by Caryn James.
</P>
