<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTIN-LAWRENCE-INTERVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  (NOTE TO EDITORS: Resending to fix BAD SLUG)  
 
  
 
 
MARTIN LAWRENCE: OUT OF A COMA ... AND INTO A THEATER NEAR YOU  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you're Martin Lawrence these days, you've got
to be wondering if it's all worth it.
</P>
<P>
   His career long dogged by controversy and contention, the
hyperactive funnyman has recently emerged from an extended downward
spiral. Following a series of highly publicized personal
malfunctions, Lawrence, 34, did some serious self-assessment,
re-established his mental/spiritual equilibrium and got his
professional life back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Having executed a challenging performance in the spring film
release ``Life'' and earning high preview audience marks for the
action comedy ``Blue Streak,'' which opens Friday, Lawrence was in
understandably positive spirits during an Aug. 8 interview.
</P>
<P>
   Little did he know that, two weeks later, he'd be in a
heatstroke-induced coma after jogging in heavy clothes on a
sweltering Westlake Village morning. He was trying to get in shape
for an upcoming movie job _ another comedy, ``Big Momma's House,''
in which he's still scheduled to play a cop who goes undercover as
a grandmother _ doing the conscientious, professional thing.
Lawrence was finally released from the hospital Thursday, 2{ weeks
after his collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to keep myself well-conditioned and focused for the
movies,'' Lawrence had said earlier last month, naturally not
expecting those words would take on an ironic ring. But when asked
if fame was a good thing, he also revealed why he might eventually
push himself too hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all the time, it can be a pain,'' Lawrence answered. ``It
cuts your privacy sometimes, you can't always go where you want.
There's just a lot that comes with it, always being questioned
about your weight, or whatever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence certainly was in top physical shape for ``Blue
Streak,'' in which he plays a jewel thief masquerading as a police
detective and almost every scene requires him to act out some
demanding bit of body or behavioral humor. The film's makers, in
fact, weren't worried about Lawrence's capacity to perform; they'd
seen his astoundingly energetic work in such feature films as ``Bad
Boys'' and ``Nothing to Lose,'' in his lightning-paced comedy
concert film ``You So Crazy'' and on five seasons of ``Martin,''
the raucous Fox sitcom he created and headlined.
</P>
<P>
   No, they didn't care about the not-even-chubby star's weight.
And if there were concerns from the ``whatever it is'' category,
they were quickly dispelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin was all about the job _ he was ready. He was physically
in great shape; I would sign up for another film with him in a
second,'' said ``Blue Streak'' director Les Mayfield, adding that
Lawrence's winning screen personality went a long way toward making
the movie's criminal protagonist palatable. ``He brings to this
film an inherent level of charm; he has a smile that's so
disarming, it lets him get away with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't always been the case when the cameras aren't
running. Sure, Lawrence's irrepressible impishness has served him
well since childhood. He'd use it to cheer up his two-job-working
mom (who supported her six children after her military-man husband
walked out). He got one teacher to actually give him the last five
minutes of class to test out his comedy routines (though she
threatened detention if he wasn't funny). He worked his way out of
a Maryland housing project on dirty jokes and that smile, rising
through the D.C.-area club circuit to a key appearance on ``Star
Search'' to a star-making hosting gig on ``Russell Simmons' Def
Comedy Jam.''
</P>
<P>
   But once Mr. You So Crazy actually went kind of nuts, the only
solution was to go more than grin deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no choice, at this point, but to keep my head up and to
keep my focus on what I do,'' said Lawrence, who in the mid-'90s
saw a short marriage fail, was arrested several times (including a
1996 incident that involved running across Ventura Boulevard
screaming at passing motorists), and was accused of sexual
harassment by ``Martin'' co-star Tisha Campbell. ``I've spent the
last two years just getting myself back together, my life in order
and learning to understand that you can have trying times like that
in your life, but that doesn't mean that you can't pick yourself
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence credited his new-found stability to the usual good
influences. But he acknowledged that, when it came down to it, only
he could be responsible for changing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My will, my strength, my wanting to grow, my faith in God and
truly believing in it'' are what he says helped him straighten out.
``Sometimes you get so jaded and cloudy, there's no room for those
things. But through God's grace, I was able to find that again, and
I could hear my family talking to me and my friends trying to
uplift me, even when they were just saying that I didn't want to
get up.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other things worth living life right for, high among
them Jasmin, the 3-year-old daughter he tries not to spoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a lot of things, so she let's me know what she wants,
but I try to pace it,'' he says of the girl who's being raised in
drastically different circumstances than he was. ``It's most
definitely different, but I look at it as truly a blessing. I know
that. So that's what allows me to work as hard as I do. It's all to
make a better way for her. I thank God for helping me to be in a
position to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Lawrence harbored no delusions that life could
suddenly be perfect. He's still wary of commitment after the
disastrous marriage to Jasmin's mother, former Miss Virginia
Patricia Southall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a special friend, but I'm just living right now,'' he
said, cryptically yet revealingly. ``There's no date things going
on. I won't be seeing no altars or no wedding cake _ none of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though things were looking good on the career front,
Lawrence noted that several television projects he wanted to
produce were going nowhere _ an outgrowth, he reckoned, of the
networks' widely criticized turn away from ethnically diverse
programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a problem, period,'' he said. ``There's no
opportunity to show the diverse talent out here, amongst people,
when you just deal with white shows. That's not the norm out here,
or what America has been heading for for a long time. There should
be more minorities of whatever color; that's why we have so many
different channels, so you should be able to put on whatever you
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not just any old program of color.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be good shows,'' he cautioned. ``If they're
comedies, they have to be funny _ I ain't talking about just
putting some bull on. I'm talking about stuff that makes sense, but
you've got to give them that opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Lawrence's own sitcom was often praised as a generally
positive look at young urban professionals, its raw (for the
mid-'90s, anyway) humor brought criticism from some segments of the
African-American community, most notably Bill Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   But despite maintaining a bad-boy attitude when the subject of
media censorship came up _ ``You see more violence in a supermarket
(than in films), depending on which supermarket you're in'' was one
dubious stance _ Lawrence wanted to make sure that playing a
crook-turned-cop in ``Blue Streak'' did not send the wrong message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not cool to be a criminal, period,'' he said. ``I think
this guy is a likable, good-natured person who just happened to
choose the wrong line of work. I think, when they see the movie,
people are gonna be going, `Why do you think you have to be a thief
when you seem like such a nice guy?'''
</P>
<P>
   Like everything about his life in show business, concern about
the image he projects is one more pressure Martin Lawrence is
constantly forced to deal with. He was asked if he ever considered
giving up the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably did at some point,'' he figured, ``when contracts
don't go right and movies are not coming in where you want, or
television series are not coming in where you want. I think every
entertainer in this business goes through that. It's just a matter
of your patience and your understanding of how to maximize your
time off, when you are away from things. It's constantly learning
how to grow; that's what's going to better you and strengthen you
in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   And even after his most recent setback, it's hard to imagine
that Lawrence would give up that growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I think you always have pressures,'' he says. ``This is
just such a big industry, a major industry, and it's been going on
since the end of time. So yeah, it puts pressure on you. But that's
part of growing, is learning how to deal with those pressures,
having the right outlets and all that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1551EDT &QL; 
