<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0395 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-YOUTH-SOCCER-ART-     09-13 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-YOUTH-SOCCER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SOCCER SEASON AND NEW SAFETY CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich.)   (The Science Times)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By SUSAN GILBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the fall soccer season begins, legions of schoolchildren are
taking to the fields with images of the United States women's
team's stunning World Cup victory still fresh in their minds. But
many doctors have other matters on their minds: how to make soccer
safer for children in light of recent reports linking it to
repeated concussions and diminished mental functioning.
</P>
<P>
   A central question surrounds the practice of heading _ hitting
the ball with the head. In a two-year study of 60 soccer players
ages 11 to 14 in Ann Arbor, Mich., Dr. David Janda, an orthopedic
surgeon, found that nearly half had symptoms of concussion _
blurred or double vision, headaches, nausea and ringing in the
ears. The symptoms were most common in the children who headed the
ball most often, Janda said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the second year, the children with repeated
symptoms did slightly worse than a control group of children on
neurological tests of memory and information processing, said
Janda, who has submitted his study for publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we think happens is that kids first start to experience
concussive symptoms, and then as the amount of heading goes up
their information processing and memory diminish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Janda's conclusion is similar to that of a report in the current
issue of The Journal of the American Medical Association, in which
researchers in the Netherlands compared the brain functions of 33
adult amateur soccer players with 27 other athletes, like runners
and swimmers. Thirteen of the 33 soccer players had an impaired
performance on tasks requiring planning, and nine had memory
impairments, rates three times those of the other athletes. The
more concussions a player had suffered, the lower the score on the
neurological tests.
</P>
<P>
   While experts agree that repeated concussions can cause
permanent brain damage and even death, they disagree over the role
of heading. In a second study in The Journal of the American
Medical Association, Dr. John W. Powell, an assistant professor of
kinesiology at Michigan State University, found that most of the
concussions of high school soccer players occurred when players
collided or fell while trying to head a ball. Powell said more
research was needed to determine whether heading itself was
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   There is also disagreement over when heading should be taught.
Doug Semark, executive director of the American Youth Soccer
Organization, recommends that coaches not teach heading to players
younger than 12 because their necks may not be strong enough to
remain steady during a blow to the head and protect the brain from
movement and injury.
</P>
<P>
   But Semark says many coaches disregard such recommendations. ``I
have witnessed on more occasions than I could count well-meaning
soccer coaches extolling heading as one of the great things you can
do even with 5- to 7-year-olds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Semark also said his organization, which oversees about 20
percent to 25 percent of the country's youth soccer leagues, had
been under pressure from parents to teach heading to younger
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We frequently hear complaints from parents that coaches aren't
teaching heading and therefore their kids are being denied the full
benefit of participation in soccer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Heading aside, there are things parents, coaches and trainers
can do to protect young athletes from head injuries and
neurological damage.
</P>
<P>
   Guidelines issued last May by the Federal Consumer Product
Safety Commission say soccer goals should be securely anchored so
they do not tip over. The commission found that 23 deaths and 38
serious injuries have occurred since 1979 from soccer goals falling
on children.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the American Academy of Neurology recommends that
any player who suffers a blow to the head be evaluated immediately
for possible concussion. Players with mild symptoms, like confusion
but no loss of consciousness, may return to the game if symptoms go
away within 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, they should not play or practice until they are free
of symptoms for one week, since the greatest risk of brain injury
comes from getting a second concussion before the first one has
healed.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
