<SLUG> BC-SCI-EARTHQUAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 RECENT EARTHQUAKES UNRELATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)  (The Science Times) 
(af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For anyone who believes that airplane crashes and other
disasters come in bunches, the earthquake that struck Athens on
Tuesday, just three weeks after a major tremor about 400 miles away
in Turkey, provided plenty of grist for debate.
</P>
<P>
   But seismologists say there is no connection between the Athens
quake, which measured 5.9 on the Richter scale and killed at least
83 people, and the one in Turkey, which was centered near the city
of Izmit, measured 7.4 and killed more than 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to think that the stress put on the end of
the fault in Turkey would be felt in Greece,'' said Dr. Tom Holzer,
an engineering geologist at the United States Geological Survey in
Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The two quakes occurred on faults of different types. The North
Anatolian fault responsible for the Turkish quake is of the
strike-slip type, in which the earth moves laterally. The Greek
tremor occurred on what geologists call a normal fault, where the
movement is primarily vertical.
</P>
<P>
   Holzer noted that the Turkish quake was 175 times as powerful as
the Greek one, and that there was really no comparison between the
two. ``It's like fog and hail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is also no reason to believe that earthquakes are
occurring unusually often. The Greek tremor was classified as a
moderate quake, and about 1,200 of them occur annually worldwide.
Through August of this year, fewer than 600 such quakes had been
recorded.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
