<HEADER>
A0412 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w BC-MILITARY-RECRUITMENT-     09-13 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-RECRUITMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON SEEKING WAYS TO INCREASE ENLISTMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an effort to replenish the thinning ranks of the
armed forces, the Pentagon and Congress are looking at everything
from slick advertising to improved pay and benefits to a revival of
the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1973, when President Richard Nixon ended the draft
amid national disillusionment with the Vietnam War, has a young
American been conscripted into the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   So lawmakers and Pentagon recruiting experts are hoping that
efforts to bolster incentives, improve pay and do more to market
the services will keep some members of Congress who advocate a
resurrection of the draft from opening up what is sure to be an
explosive political issue.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the problem is the military's increasing
difficulty in filling its ranks with qualified personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Army expects to miss its recruiting goals this year by 7,000
and the Air Force by 2,500. The Navy expects to meet this year's
goal, but only after lowering educational requirements. Only the
Marine Corps consistently meets its recruiting goals, having hit
its target number for the last 50 months.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines don't use promises of big bonuses, guarantees of
college tuition or even training opportunities in their advertising
campaigns. Instead, they have focused for years on the challenge of
becoming a Marine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their message has been consistent over the years; it's all
about a personal transformation,'' said Rob Cherof, who manages the
Marines account at the J. Walter Thompson advertising agency in
Atlanta. ``It's about somebody becoming better, meeting challenges
and growing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marines, he said, are constantly trying to understand the
likes and dislikes of young Americans and finding ways to get their
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Marines will sell themselves,'' he said. ``You just have
to get a kid to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force, which lately has been more successful in
vanquishing Yugoslav air power than in meeting recruiting targets,
has taken a tip from the Marines and started a new sort of air war.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in years, the Air Force is buying TV spots in
an effort to attract recruits. One difference between its campaign
and those of the other services: The Air Force uses its own
personnel instead of actors.
</P>
<P>
   The total cost of the effort, to run for 18 months, will be $54
million.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Talbert, director of Air Force advertising, said the
military is finding it increasingly difficult to capture the
attention of young people. Fewer members of the recruit pool have
parents with military experience and many potential recruits have
very clear career goals, Talbert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young people today are very proud of who they are and what
they are,'' Talbert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that they bring something to the table, also. They
know they bring value and worth to the military and they want to
know what the military is going to do with that and how they are
going to be treated. We have to craft our messages around that
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pentagon studies show that military recruiters face an
uphill battle in persuading young people to sign up:
</P>
<P>
   _ The proportion of 16- to 21-year-old men and women who enlist
in the military has dropped from 34 percent in 1991 to 27 percent
today.
</P>
<P>
   _ Unemployment rates are the lowest since implementation of the
all-volunteer force 26 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ More young people are going to college than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Clinton administration has dispatched U.S. troops on more
overseas deployments than any other administration since the end of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``The all-volunteer force is a strong force, but it is also a
fragile force,'' said Rep. Tom Udall, D-N.M. ``It relies on
recruiting and retaining quality people. Our armed forces have been
reduced to the point where the military struggles to meet all the
commitments we place on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind., chairman of the military personnel
subcommittee, has said he believes that Congress should at least
examine a revival of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, American service personnel are deployed in numerous
contingency operations around the globe,'' Buyer said. ``This is
truly alarming, given the future uncertainty of military manpower
as a result of the service's recruiting and retention problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone in Congress is convinced that the draft is the
answer to the Pentagon's recruiting woes. In fact, a bill aimed at
abolishing the Selective Service System recently passed in the
House, although it is expected to die in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers and Pentagon brass believe that recruitment
problems can be eased by spending more money on recruits and
improving the quality of life for active military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Among the proposals being considered by Congress: increasing
pay, giving bigger bonuses to recruits, and spending more on
college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   The military spending plan for fiscal 2000, now before Congress,
contains an entire section on ways to attract the nearly 200,000
young people the Pentagon needs to fill vacancies left by retiring
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would increase the Pentagon's advertising budget by
$53.1 million, add $17.5 million to equip recruiters better, and
provide an additional $22 million for recruiting bonuses. The bill
would also raise pay across the board by 4.8 percent and establish
a Thrift Savings Plan similar to a 401(k) retirement savings
account.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Mac Thornberry, R-Texas, a member of the military
personnel subcommittee, said, ``Money alone will not fix the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornberry, who opposes reviving the draft, said the Pentagon
must improve the quality of life for members of the military and
the administration must re-examine how it uses the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to look at the number of things we are asking people
in the military to do and how much time they have to be away from
their families and how hard they have to work,'' Thornberry said.
``They are being stretched too thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Some military experts believe that, if the all-volunteer force
is to survive, the Pentagon must reconsider its structure from the
ground up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military is fighting a double uphill battle,'' said David
Segal, a military sociologist at the University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Segal advocates the use of more civilians in jobs normally held
by military personnel. For example, he would have the Air Force
hire civilians for aircraft maintenance, allowing more of its
military personnel to be used for tasks directly connected to
fighting wars. Fewer recruits would thus be needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Segal also said the Pentagon and American universities should
collaborate in training students to serve in military jobs, many of
which now require a high level of technical skill.
</P>
<P>
   Some at the Pentagon and in Congress believe that such an
approach might work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to look at a variety of things and examine whether it
is essential to have military personnel perform a particular
function,'' Thornberry said. ``I have no doubt that there are a lot
of things we ask military members to do now that could be done by
private contractors and probably could be done cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   But some military experts do not believe there is a connection
between improving the military's quality of life and recruiting
results.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Maj. Gen. William Nash, who led U.S. peacekeeping
troops in Bosnia in 1995, said: ``You can throw a lot of money at
it, but the most important thing they need to throw is prestige.
You have to make it a prestigious, honorable, respectful pursuit.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
