<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0413 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SCIENTIST-FEUD-AR     09-13 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SCIENTIST-FEUD-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT FUELS SCIENTIFIC PROGRESS? SOMETIMES, A FEUD 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The crabbed handwriting emerges from the fax machine
like a communication from another time, a dispatch from a great
battle that has passed into history. Yet Sir Fred Hoyle, the
British cosmologist who, five decades ago, derisively coined the
term ``Big Bang'' for a cosmic theory with which he did not and
does not agree, makes plain in his faxed letter that for him, the
battle lives on. And it is not just a fight against a theory.
</P>
<P>
   With seemingly equal tenacity, that fight is directed at the
late Sir Martin Ryle, a British radio astronomer and Nobel laureate
who espoused the Big Bang theory. Observations that Ryle used in
the 1950s to attack Hoyle's alternative theory turned out to be
flawed, notes the letter, which then thunders that the Big Bang is
``a huge facade based on no real evidence at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it a personal feud or just a rousing scientific debate? The
two themes may be inextricable: All aspects of the clash stirred up
interest in the relevant science, spurring decades of fresh
observations that seemed to settle the issue in favor of what is
now officially called the Big Bang, a theory that assumes the
universe began in a colossal explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Though you would never know it from the textbooks, beneath the
flapping banners of feuding scientific ideas, as often as not there
are feuding scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think that scientists would have a degree of saintliness
that would be almost unbearable,'' said Dr. Leon Lederman, a Nobel
Prize-winning physicist at the Fermi National Accelerator
Laboratory. ``It doesn't work that way. The competition goes on at
all levels _ the international, the national, the institutional,
and finally the guy across the hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the unhappy families of Tolstoy's ``Anna Karenina,'' which
were all unhappy in different ways, no two scientific rivalries
have precisely the same causes and consequences. Some skirmishes do
little more than quicken the pace of research, as when Albert
Einstein and David Hilbert, the German mathematician, raced each
other for the first correct formulation of the equations of general
relativity in 1915.
</P>
<P>
   Other spats have the effect of both drawing attention to an
important research question while souring many scientists on ever
working in the field. The classic case involved Dr. Allan Sandage
of the Carnegie Observatories in Pasadena, Calif., and the late Dr.
Gerard de Vaucouleurs; the pair feuded with ceaseless rancor in the
1970s and '80s over the rate at which the universe is expanding,
called the Hubble constant. The consequences of that battle are
still ricocheting through the world of scientific research today.
</P>
<P>
   Still other feuds appear to be entirely destructive, with little
redeeming value for scientific research _ like the bitter personal
and professional split between Drs. Tsung Dao Lee and Chen Ning
Yang, who won the Nobel Prize for collaborative work in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Many scientific feuds have certain human elements in common,
said Dr. Virginia Trimble, an astrophysicist at the University of
California, Irvine, who used the Hoyle-Ryle case as an
illustration. ``I knew them both. Neither person was overwhelmingly
easy to get along with,'' she said, choosing her words carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``And indeed, nobody who does something earth-shaking is likely
to be,'' said Dr. Trimble. ``You only achieve things like that by
being more single-minded than your friends and relations are likely
to regard as totally reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the scientific penchant for feuding is offset by
mutually supportive alliances that are not quite as noisy, said Dr.
Karen Johnson, a historian of science at St. Lawrence University,
who has studied the fruitful intellectual exchange between the
physics Nobelist Maria Goeppert Mayer and her husband, Joseph E.
Mayer, a chemist. But even that sort of interaction is seldom
explored in official accounts, said Dr. Johnson, perhaps because
``it doesn't fit the nice, neat, one-great-person idea of
history.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure whether the large teams characteristic of
end-of-millennium research have fostered more alliances of all
types, or created even more friction. But some scientists have a
hunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more agony, perhaps, in modern times,'' said Dr.
Gerard 't Hooft, a particle theorist at Utrecht University in the
Netherlands, who is considered a Nobel Prize candidate for
discoveries he made with Dr. Martinus Veltman, another Dutch
scientist. Following a dispute over credit for the work, the two
scientists have ``floated apart,'' in 't Hooft's words.
</P>
<P>
   There was already plenty of agony to go around during the
scientific revolutions of Elizabethan times. Early feuds involved
everything from courtly status and sheer snobbery to overheated
competition and charges of plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In 1588, for instance, the Danish astronomer Tycho Brahe
proposed a radical theory of the heavens in which the sun orbited
an immovable Earth while all the other planets whirled about the
sun. A few months later, a mathematician named Ursus, who had risen
from extremely humble beginnings to prominence in the court of
Rudolf II in Prague, published a book with a similar theory under
his own name.
</P>
<P>
   Tycho branded Ursus a thief and a vituperative exchange ensued,
followed by a lawsuit. Even though the controversy got other
astronomers interested in the problem, far more than just science
was in play, said Dr. Owen Gingerich, a historian at the
Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tycho was of noble birth,'' said Gingerich, ``and he felt that
it was improper for a sometime swineherd to have his own
cosmological system.''
</P>
<P>
   A frequent brawler of the time was Galileo Galilei, who
developed the telescope and first turned it to the heavens, said
Dr. Noel Swerdlow of the University of Chicago. ``Galileo despised
Tycho Brahe,'' Swerdlow said, probably because Tycho was the most
effective opponent of the view that all the planets including Earth
went around the sun, as Galileo correctly believed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the angriest of all feuds pitted Sir Isaac Newton against
Robert Hooke, a brilliant scientist seven years his senior. Decades
of antipathy began when Newton and Hooke disagreed about the nature
of color. Eventually an aging, infirm Hooke accused the
hypersensitive genius of pilfering from him Newton's most famous
ideas on the theory of gravity. ``That fight was just nasty,'' said
Dr. Alan E. Shapiro, director of the program in history of science
and technology at the University of Minnesota. ``That had no happy
resolution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent and public English scientific feud in modern
times has been the Hoyle-Ryle split. The scientific debate revolved
around observations of faint and presumably distant radio sources
in the sky. More of the faint sources were to be expected in a Big
Bang universe than in the one favored by Hoyle _ a ``steady state''
cosmos with no definite beginning or end.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ryle eventually declared that he had demolished the steady-state
theory by discovering vast numbers of the faint sources. After one
particularly high-profile announcement in early 1961, the story ran
in the London papers, and ``for the next week, my children were
ragged about it at school,'' Hoyle wrote in ``Home is Where the
Wind Blows: Chapters from a Cosmologist's Life'' (University
Science Books, 1994).
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Ryle's early analysis turned out to have
mistakes, and the claimed numbers fell sharply. The standoff
captured the attention of a host of other astronomers, who turned
up many apparent inconsistencies between their observations and the
predictions of steady-state theory. But Hoyle, who defends a
modified version of the theory in a new book titled ``A Different
Approach to Cosmology: From a Static Universe Through the Big Bang
Towards Reality,'' to be published by Cambridge University Press
later this year, still believes the consensus on the Big Bang was
rash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The really interesting question is why the world was so ready
to believe in this story,'' Hoyle wrote in his faxed letter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The fight between Sandage and de Vaucouleurs involved the rate
at which the cosmos is flying apart as a consequence of the Big
Bang explosion. Their answers persistently differed by a factor of
two, with Sandage getting the lower value. Sandage eventually
became so upset by the dispute that he stopped attending most
scientific meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. John Huchra of the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for
Astrophysics remembers that one verbal exchange between them, at a
conference in Paris in 1976, helped spark his own interest in the
field. ``They got up, and they were duking it out in front of the
audience,'' Huchra said.
</P>
<P>
   Huchra was later among the founders of a Hubble Space Telescope
team, called the Key Project, that recently announced what some
regard as the most reliable measurement yet of the expansion rate.
But the number falls about midway between the original poles of the
dispute and is still too high for Sandage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a controversy, and this isn't going to settle
it,'' he told Science magazine when the results appeared.
</P>
<P>
   That uncompromising approach puts off some researchers, but Dr.
Wendy Freedman, a leader of the Key Project at the Carnegie
Observatories in Pasadena, said that such conflicts are inevitable
in cutting-edge science. ``I don't take it personally,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A somewhat less positive view was offered by another member of
the Key Project, Dr. Barry Madore of the California Institute of
Technology, who is married to Dr. Freedman. The original feud,
Madore said, ``was a battle not so much of the titans as of the
grumpy old men.''
</P>
<P>
   Few scientific benefits have flowed from the blow-up between
Lee, of Columbia University, and Yang, of the State University of
New York, Stony Brook, who have scarcely spoken to each other for
more than 35 years. They have published conflicting accounts of
their collaboration, each claiming the lion's share of credit for
the idea, called parity violation, that won them a Nobel Prize in
1957. Parity is a kind of right-left symmetry that physicists had
thought was a property of every subatomic interaction. The pair
quarreled about the ordering of their names on joint papers and in
a lengthy profile of the duo that appeared in The New Yorker in
1962. Prophetically, the article was titled ``A question of
parity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, scientists do get along. Even then, however, the
story is seldom free of strife.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the century's more embarrassing episodes of gender
discrimination, the University of Chicago refused to pay a salary
to Maria Goeppert Mayer, a German-born and educated professor at
the university. It was a situation she had faced repeatedly, and
``there were periods in the 1930s when she would have given up,''
said Dr. Johnson of St. Lawrence University. But her husband, the
American chemist Joseph E. Mayer, would not hear of it. ``Joe was
the one who was really adamant,'' Dr. Johnson said. ``He wanted her
to stay in science,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In an essay titled ``Science at the Breakfast Table,'' published
earlier this year in the journal Physics in Perspective, Dr.
Johnson also traced how Mayer gradually absorbed some of his wife's
mathematical wizardry, while she picked up some of his skill in
interpreting experimental data. Both used those breakfast lessons
in their most noted work _ including the discovery of the shell
structure of atomic nuclei that won Maria Goeppert Mayer a Nobel
Prize in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Science has had more than its share of collaborations _ they are
just quieter than the feuds, said Dr. James Hartle of the
University of California, Santa Barbara, who has worked on
cosmological problems with Dr. Stephen Hawking, the Cambridge
University physicist, since the 1970s. Generally, ``it's the
science that drives it,'' while friendship naturally follows,
Hartle said.
</P>
<P>
   In this collaborative, combative age, there are even scientists
who still prefer to work alone, said Dr. Vera Rubin, the astronomer
at the Carnegie Institution of Washington who discovered that
galaxies are filled with a mysterious sort of dark matter. Dr.
Rubin, who has a particular aversion to being rushed by
competition, said that she had carefully chosen to observe aspects
of the sky that no one else was interested in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally,'' Dr. Rubin said, ``I have spent my life looking
for problems that I could do and nobody would bother me while I was
doing them.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
