   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WACO-REPORT (Dallas) _ A report by the Texas Rangers cites shell
casings found at a location where an FBI sniper could have fired at
the Branch Davidian compound outside Waco on the day a fire
destroyed the cult's holdout. But the casings also could have been
left from shots fired by other federal agents on the first day of
the standoff in 1993. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Bryan, Texas) _ Texas prosecutors say that murder
defendant Russell Brewer was so proud of his participation in the
gruesome killing of a black man last year that he wrote about it.
Brewer, 32, is the second of three white men accused of killing
James Byrd Jr., 49, of Jasper. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS-CENSUS (Washington) _ Hispanics risk losing
congressional seats and federal funds distributed through
population-based formulas if the 2000 census misses minorities in
areas with large Hispanic populations, Rep. Charles A. Gonzalez,
D-Texas, tells the Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute. By GARY
MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ With Mike Hampton on the mound, the
Houston Astros will be going for a franchise-record 11th
consecutive victory tonight at the Astrodome against the
Philadelphia Phillies. Hampton will be bidding to become the
Astros' second 20-game winner in three days. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BRONCOS (Denver) _ The Denver Broncos open their quest for a
third consecutive Super Bowl title at home against the Miami
Dolphins in the Monday Night Football season opener. By JOHN
McCLAIN.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COWBOYS (Dallas) _ Coming off one of the most exciting games
in the storied history of the Cowboys-Redskins rivalry, the Dallas
Cowboys believe that comeback win may prove to be the key to their
season. By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN (New York) _ Houston and Los Angeles are
vying to receive a football expansion team. By DALE ROBERTSON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Among the 23,000 fans watching the
U.S. Open championship between Andre Agassi and Todd Martin Sunday
was Walter Cronkite, wearing a jacket and tie. He was the only one
spotted in the crowd attired so spiffily. Cronkite, bless his
heart, is a generational throwback. Dress codes are vanishing, even
here at the Washington Opera. The new sloppiness, one of the few
things we can't blame on President Clinton, is here to stay. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
