<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DANCE OF THE PEAFOWL  
 WHICH WAY TO THE LAUNDRY?  
 WHEN FORESTS ARE CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mating, animal behaviorists are fond of saying, is a dance. For
some species, it's the hustle; for others, the shake or the shimmy.
For peafowl, the dance is of the ballroom variety, ladies' choice.
The males gather in a group, known as a lek, and the females size
them up as potential partners.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the scenario at the local Arthur Murray, where the
instructor insures that everyone gets a chance to fox-trot, only a
few very attractive males get mates (and lots of them). Many
peacocks are called to the floor, it seems, but few are chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a less attractive peacock keep participating in this
ritual? Researchers in England studying 200 peafowl in a park near
London think they have some answers.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, writing in the journal Nature, discovered
through DNA that peacocks tend to be more closely related within
one lek than among different leks. They even found that siblings
separated before birth managed to link up with their kin for mating
displays.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggest that lekking may have an evolutionary
basis. By displaying themselves in a group, peacocks increase the
number of peahens that show up. So by teaming up with more
attractive relatives, a plain peacock may not get a mate but at
least will help insure that its kin do and thus pass on the family
genes. Or the evolution of lekking could be driven by the peahens,
who may prefer to choose mates from among peacocks with similar
traits.
</P>
<P>
   The endoplasmic reticulum is the laundry room of the cell. It is
there that newly manufactured proteins are folded. The long,
unwieldy molecules are twisted and turned into their final,
functional shapes.
</P>
<P>
   And just as some people like their shirts folded just so,
exactly how a protein is folded can be critical for a cell. A
misshaped protein can cause damage or disease.
</P>
<P>
   That is what happens with mad cow disease (formally known as
bovine spongiform encephalopathy) and a related human illness,
Creutzfeld-Jacob disease. A protein, known as prion protein, folds
abnormally and causes degeneration in the brain (resulting in the
progressive loss of mental functioning that is characteristic of
these diseases).
</P>
<P>
   Now, scientists at the University of Chicago have discovered the
reason prion protein misfolds: The protein never makes it to the
endoplasmic reticulum.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, prion protein has a particular structure, or label,
that is recognized by other proteins in the endoplasmic reticulum.
But for some reason this locating system does not work, and the
proteins are misdirected. The protein then does not fold properly
and cannot carry out its usual tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The next step for the scientists, who described their work in
the October issue of Nature Cell Biology, is to figure out why the
proteins are being misdirected.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate effects of the steady deforestation that is
occurring in the Amazon and elsewhere have been well documented.
But deforestation is not always an all-or-nothing thing: when land
is cleared for timber, grazing, agriculture or settlement, some
patches of mature forest are often spared.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a study by a Georgetown University scientist shows that
deforestation has a long-term effect on the trees left behind,
limiting seed dispersal and making the remaining forests more
genetically uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The scientist studied genetic variation in a type of Brazil nut
tree in a forest near Manaus, Brazil, that was partially cleared in
the early 1980s. Maternal genes, which are carried only in seeds,
were studied; paternal genes are carried in pollen, and other
studies have shown that pollen is dispersed over long distances in
such circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The study, reported in Nature, showed that forest fragments as
large as about 25 acres had a single maternal lineage. The
deforested zones effectively prevent the influx of other seeds that
might diversify the genetic makeup of the remaining forested
areas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
