<HEADLINE>
THERAPIES: LEARNING TO SEE BEYOND A PATIENT'S CHART  
 CAUSE AND EFFECT: SINUSITIS ATTACKS PINNED ON FUNGUS 
SIDE EFFECTS: INDOOR SHOOTERS, LOOK OUT FOR THE LEAD 
SYMPTOMS: LEG PAINS, BAD VEINS AND FREE SCREENINGS
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times) 
(ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dr. Ronald Epstein counseled a patient who was considering
genetic screening for breast cancer, he confronted questions his
medical knowledge had not equipped him to address. What difference
would knowing the results make? How much was the patient guided by
fear and depression? What approach would be most helpful?
</P>
<P>
   What helped him, he wrote in the Sept. 1 issue of The Journal of
the American Medical Association, was what he called ``mindful
practice.'' In the article, he urged fellow doctors to make
``attending to the ordinary, the obvious and the present'' part of
their practice.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, he wrote, doctors focus on technical aspects of
medical care at the expense of reflection, self-awareness and
sensitivity to patients' feelings and values. Just as a musician
plays and listens at the same time, a physician must incorporate a
whole range of technical abilities with an awareness of the patient
as a person, wrote Epstein, who plays the harpsichord.
</P>
<P>
   He cited one striking instance: a trainee, ``mistaking the chart
for the patient,'' reported a patient's having a history of ``BKA''
(below-the-knee amputation), never noticing that the patient still
had both feet.
</P>
<P>
   -MICHAEL PORTER
</P>
<P>
   CAUSE AND EFFECT: SINUSITIS ATTACKS PINNED ON FUNGUS
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Mayo Clinic who were looking for the most
common cause of chronic sinus infections say they have found what
they were seeking _ and it was not the culprit most doctors had
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, doctors thought the disease was usually a
bacterial infection, with perhaps 6 percent of cases caused by a
reaction to fungus. But after a two-year study of 210 chronic
sinusitis patients, the researchers found that more than 90 percent
of the cases arose from an immune-system response to a common
fungus.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who published their findings this month in the
Mayo Clinic Proceedings, a peer-review journal, said the discovery
was an important step to finding a more effective treatment. Dr.
David Sherris, a co-author of the study with Dr. Eugene Kern and
Dr. Jens Ponikau, said they were investigating treatments that
would both keep fungus levels low and counter the immune-system's
response to the fungus. He estimated that ``a potential treatment
will probably be available within two to four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronic sinusitis, an inflammation of the membranes of the nose
and sinus cavities that lasts three months or longer, affects 37
million Americans, the clinic says. Symptoms range from a
long-running cold to total nasal obstruction. It is different from
acute sinusitis, which lasts a month or less and is typically
caused by bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Sherris said the discovery was made possible by improved
techniques for testing for fungus in samples of mucus. The types of
fungus that was detected by the researchers ``is ubiquitous,'' he
said. While only some people react badly to the fungus, he said,
``It is in everybody's nose.''
</P>
<P>
   -JOHN SULLIVAN
</P>
<P>
   SIDE EFFECTS: INDOOR SHOOTERS, LOOK OUT FOR THE LEAD
</P>
<P>
   Annie Oakley did most of her dead-eye shooting in the healthy
outdoors. But teen-agers and others who want to emulate her need to
be concerned about the hazards of lead exposure at indoor firing
ranges.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sept. 9 issue of The New England Journal of Medicine, Dr.
Michael Shannon, director of the Pediatric Environmental Health
Center at Children's Hospital in Boston, reported the cases of four
girls, ages 14 to 16, who had significant lead poisoning. The
condition can damage the kidneys, bone marrow and nervous system
and can harm a fetus during pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   None showed symptoms, but went for testing because they had been
warned about the possible danger at firing ranges.
</P>
<P>
   The girls competed at the same indoor range, and the exposure
occurred even though they followed the range's precautions,
including washing their hands and changing clothes after practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``An indoor firing range is an enclosed, tight, poorly
ventilated room that is blanketed with lead powder,'' Shannon wrote
in an e-mail interview. ``Those inside are not only inhaling it,
absorbing lead through their lungs, but also getting it on their
clothes, hair and fingers,'' which they might put in their mouths.
Lead is not absorbed through the skin, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon said he was concerned about a possible increase in the
number of female rifle team members as a result of the growth of
women's athletics.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the National Collegiate Athletic Association
said that in the 1997-98 season, there were 11 intercollegiate
women's rifle teams with 50 athletes, and another 339 shooters on
40 mixed and men's teams.
</P>
<P>
   _MICHAEL POLLAK
</P>
<P>
   SYMPTOMS LEG PAINS, BAD VEINS AND FREE SCREENINGS
</P>
<P>
   People in their 50s and older who feel cramping or pain in their
legs while walking may dismiss the symptoms as inevitable signs of
aging.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, they are the common signs of peripheral vascular
disease, which is caused by blockages in leg arteries that in turn
increase the risk of heart disease and lead to 100,000 leg
amputations each year in the United States, according to the
Society of Cardiovascular and Interventional Radiology, a medical
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Research by the radiology group estimates that the condition is
undiagnosed in about a quarter of the eight million Americans who
have it.
</P>
<P>
   To increase diagnosis and lower the risk of complications, the
group has organized a national campaign, Legs for Life, in which
more than 500 hospitals and other health care centers around the
country are offering free screenings for peripheral vascular
disease this week. Screening sites are listed on the Webat
www.legsforlife.org.
</P>
<P>
   The screening begins with a questionnaire that assesses a
person's risk for the vascular disease. Risk factors include
smoking, high cholesterol, high blood pressure, being over 50 and a
history of heart disease or diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the person has an ankle-brachial index, a painless
10-minute exam that uses ultrasound to measure the ratio of blood
pressure in an ankle and an arm. Lower blood pressure in the ankle
is considered a sign of a blockage in a leg artery.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lynn Smaha, president of the American Heart Association,
says that the vascular condition can often be controlled with
changes like quitting smoking, and modifying diet to lower blood
pressure and cholesterol, the same measures that also help protect
against heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Standard medical treatments for peripheral vascular disease
include cholesterol or blood pressure medicine or, as a last
resort, surgery to unblock the arteries.
</P>
<P>
   -SUSAN GILBERT
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
