<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-EXPLOSIONS-0914-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TERROR STRIKES MOSCOW AS BLAST LEVELS SECOND APARTMENT BLOCK
 &HT;    725&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Conceding that ``terrorism has declared war on us,''
President Boris Yeltsin on Monday ordered increased security across
Russia after an early-morning explosion leveled an eight-story
apartment building in Moscow, the second such devastating attack
here in the capital in five days.
</P>
<P>
   At least 70 people were killed, including six children, and
dozens were missing after a pre-dawn explosion flattened the
building in southern Moscow. Authorities said the blast was the
result of a bomb apparently planted on the first floor. A similar
explosion last Thursday ripped apart an apartment block on the
southeastern outskirts of the city, claiming 93 lives.
</P>
<P>
   While there were no plausible claims of responsibility for
either explosion, Russian authorities suspect the bombings are the
work of terrorists aligned with Muslim insurgents from the
breakaway republic of Chechnya. Federal troops have been engaged in
fierce battles against the guerrillas since last month, seeking to
drive them from the southern Russian republic of Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever the culprits are, their campaign of terror was working.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous authorities strengthened controls at airports, oil
depots and nuclear power plants amid a widespread heightening of
security. Police street patrols and roadblocks were stepped up here
and other major cities.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow _ a city of 10 million people, the vast majority of
them apartment dwellers _ residents were scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is this happening? Who in Moscow will sleep soundly
tonight knowing such a thing could happen?'' said Vladimir
Alexandrov, 46, a store clerk who lives near the destroyed
building.
</P>
<P>
   In all, a string of four recent bombings have left more than 200
people dead. Apart from the apartment building explosions in
Moscow, a Russian military residence compound in Dagestan was
destroyed by a car bomb on Sept. 4, killing 64. In Moscow on Aug.
31, a bomb ripped through a crowded shopping mall near the Kremlin,
killing one and wounding dozens.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not concluded who was behind the Moscow
bombings, though they are searching for a man named Mukhit Laipanov
who allegedly had rented office space at both apartment buildings
destroyed by explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Theories have focused on Islamic militants seeking to bring the
war in the southern province of Dagestan to the Russian capital.
</P>
<P>
   But some politicians also have expressed concerns that the
bombings could be the work of ruthless political forces in Russia
out to disrupt national parliamentary elections scheduled for
December and the presidential election to chose Yeltsin' successor
set for next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on national television, Yeltsin appealed to Russians to
remain ``vigilant and calm'' as he promised a prompt and tough
response by the federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Extra police details were ordered to search the basements and
vacant apartments of buildings in the capital. Additional
roadblocks were set up to search vehicles and check identity
papers, particularly of those from the southern border region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main aim of the bandits is to intimidate the people, to
sow panic and fear. I am sure they will not live to see that,''
Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has pledged to help Russia battle terrorism.
Defense Secretary William Cohen was visiting Moscow on Monday and
offered Russian officials ``to share whatever information we can to
share whatever abilities we have to wage an effective fight against
terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities believe Osama bin Laden _ accused of
masterminding the twin bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania last year _ is helping to bankroll the Muslim insurgents
in Dagestan. The guerrillas want independence for Dagestan, where
they intend to establish an Islamic state. Russia fought _ and lost
_ a similar bloody war in Chechnya from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin vowed ``tough, swift and decisive'' action in
investigating the explosions and protecting Russia's people. He
stopped short of declaring a national emergency, which would give
the Kremlin the sanction to impose martial law. Some of Yeltsin's
political rivals have feared he would use the authority of
emergency rule as a pretext to extend his final term in office,
which expires next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Monday had been declared a day of national mourning for the
victims of the Sept. 9 apartment blast and the Sept. 4 bombing of a
Russian military housing complex in Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Muscovites awoke to a grim scene on their television screens as
emergency workers once again clawed their way through rubble and
twisted wreckage in a search for survivors. The brick building
destroyed Monday, on a busy highway in Moscow's southern fringes,
had 142 residents and about 30 had not been home at the time of the
blast, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 workers searched the debris and one man was pulled
out alive and relatively unharmed. But the routine was more
gruesome as the workers slowly uncovered dead body after dead body
throughout the day and into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone is left alive it would be an absolute miracle,''
said Vladimir Legofhin, a federal emergency services official.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, representing Russia at the
Asian-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum in New Zealand, cut short
his trip to return to Moscow to deal with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to refer to these people as humans,'' he said
of those responsible for the bombings. ``One can't even describe
them as animals. But if they are animals, then they are rabid
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   A Russian newspaper in an article in Monday's editions claimed
the Chechen guerrillas fighting Russian forces in Dagestan were
behind the bombings. The article in Novaya Gazeta had no sources,
but said the Chechen warlords had recruited about 30 ethnic Slavs _
some of them former Russian soldiers _ to carry out the bombing
campaign because they would not be conspicuous in Moscow or other
Russian cities, as would Muslims from the Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
   But officials in Chechnya and a Muslim rebel leader in
neighboring Dagestan on Monday denied any involvement in the two
apartment-building explosions in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
