<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0504 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MILK-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      09-13 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MILK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADS RAISE QUESTIONS ABOUT MILK AND BONES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wis., N.Y., Mass., S.D.)   (The Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By MARY MURRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was nowhere near as splashy or ubiquitous as the ``Got
Milk?'' advertising campaign, with all those celebrities and their
milk mustaches. But the advertisements that greeted riders of the
Washington Metro and newspaper readers in Wisconsin and upstate New
York last spring were arresting: They showed a picture of a woman
being fitted with a full-arm cast beside the headline ``Milk Does
Not Protect Against Bone Breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   That is hardly conventional wisdom. Milk may not agree with you
(if you are lactose intolerant), or may make you gain weight (if
you have not switched to skim). But doesn't it at least help build
strong bones and prevent osteoporosis, the deterioration of bone
tissue that comes with advancing age?
</P>
<P>
   Most American doctors and scientists say it does _ along with
the United States Department of Agriculture and the dairy industry,
which are trying to encourage Americans to return to the dairy
case.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mustache advertisements, milk consumption has
dropped 25 percent per capita since 1970. Public health officials
say this is an important reason only 1 in 3 Americans _ and only 1
in 10 women _ gets the recommended daily intake of calcium, a
critical element in maintaining bone mass.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, a vigorous campaign by some vegetarian and
animal protection groups, along with new research suggesting that
even a lifetime of milk drinking may not be sufficient to guard
against bone disease, has put milk's advocates on the defensive and
left consumers wondering who is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the research,'' said T. Colin Campbell, a
nutritional biochemist at Cornell University who is on the board of
the Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine, the organization
responsible for the antimilk advertisements, ``you have to start
wondering what it is about this food. Is it really as good as we've
been told?''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that people need calcium, not only for building
bones but also for managing such day-to-day cellular activities as
contracting muscles, maintaining the nervous system and absorbing
vitamin B12. They also agree that milk packs a fairly high dose of
calcium: 300 milligrams in an eight-ounce glass.
</P>
<P>
   But they emphatically disagree when it comes to osteoporosis, a
disease that leads to a million and a half bone fractures a year,
at a cost of $14 billion in health care and lost wages. The most
contentious issue is to what degree the calcium in milk can fortify
bones and, as a result, prevent fractures in the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of milk say that because people can also get calcium
from many other foods, including tofu, turnip greens, black-eyed
peas and bok choy, it makes no sense to focus on milk.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is complicated by the fact, also accepted by both
sides, that calcium is not the only factor in osteoporosis. Other
nutrients, including vitamin D, magnesium, phosphorus and zinc,
help build bones. Smoking and immoderate alcohol consumption can
weaken bones.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic predisposition plays a key role in osteoporosis. And
scientists are increasingly coming to appreciate the importance of
exercise in making a sturdy skeleton.
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly does milk do? Diane Feskanich, a nutritional
epidemiologist, addressed this question as part of her work on
Harvard's large and continuing Nurses' Health Study. She observed
about 78,000 nurses over 12 years, asking them about their lifelong
milk consumption, monitoring their diets and keeping track of their
bone fractures. Contrary to expectations, she found that the women
who drank two or more glasses of milk a day had a ``modest but
significantly increased risk'' of hip and forearm fracture compared
with those who drank less milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly the opposite of what the dairy industry would
suggest,'' said Dr. Neal Barnard, founder of the Physicians
Committee for Responsible Medicine. ``I can't imagine anyone
actually dissing this study. The difference in fracture rates was
statistically significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Milk defenders argue that Dr. Feskanich's study was only one
study, and that it was inconclusive because the researchers did not
actually control the subjects' calcium intake but merely asked them
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That type of study is very valuable for making hypotheses, but
it doesn't establish cause and effect,'' said Bess Dawson-Hughes,
director of the Calcium and Bone Metabolism Laboratory at Tufts
University in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Feskanich, who avoids taking sides in the milk debate,
agrees that her study did not show that calcium consumption causes
osteoporosis, but it did at least raise the question of whether
consuming a lot of the mineral can prevent fractures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that the benefits that have been seen for calcium,
which are strong, might not be of enough magnitude to prevent hip
fractures,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   More useful, say milk advocates, are the dozens of random
controlled trials in which one group of test subjects is given
calcium supplements and the other group is given placebos. Then,
after a year or two, their bone density is measured, or their
fractures are counted.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dawson-Hughes says dozens of such studies, some of which she
has conducted, provide conclusive evidence that calcium can help
prevent bone loss and fractures. Her colleague Dr. Robert P. Heaney
cited a study of 1,800 elderly French women, which found that those
who took calcium supplements had 30-percent fewer hip fractures
than those who did not take the supplements.
</P>
<P>
   It was such evidence that two years ago led Drs. Heaney and
Dawson-Hughes and their fellow members of the National Academy of
Sciences calcium committee to raise the recommended dietary intake
of calcium by 50 percent for older Americans. The official
recommendation now stands at 1,200 milligrams a day (the amount in
four glasses of milk) for men and women age 51 and older, 1,000
milligrams a day for adults 19 through 50, and 1,300 milligrams a
day for children 9 through 18.
</P>
<P>
   It is in childhood that bones grow most, in length and in mass.
When children consume calcium, they absorb 75 percent of it into
their bones. By the time they reach their 20s, the absorption drops
to 30 percent to 50 percent. At this point, the calcium is used not
to build but to maintain bone density, to replace the calcium that
is lost as the bones constantly rebuild themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you reach adulthood, what you're trying to do with
calcium is minimize the rate of loss,'' Dr. Dawson-Hughes said. For
women, menopause marks the beginning of relatively rapid bone
deterioration, as much as 3 percent a year, caused by a drop in
estrogen, which helps maintain bone mass. Eighty percent of the 10
million Americans with osteoporosis are women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calcium isn't the only thing that's needed,'' Dr.
Dawson-Hughes said, ``but you're going to lose without it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell, the nutritional biochemist at Cornell, points out
that in other countries, including China, where he has done
research, women consume significantly less calcium than American
women yet suffer fewer fractures late in life. If calcium is so
important, he asked, how can that be? ``If you look at intakes of
calcium around the world, you find the higher the intakes, the
higher the osteoporosis rates,'' he said. ``Dairy won't protect
against osteoporosis.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other antidairy scientists suggest that high calcium
intake may actually cause osteoporosis, by conditioning bones to
become too efficient at unloading the mineral.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates of milk argue that comparisons to other countries
prove nothing about calcium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asian women, until very recently, have been disproportionately
rural,'' said Eileen T. Kennedy, a deputy under secretary of
Agriculture who has studied nutrition in Asia. ``They're more
physically active, they have long workdays, they have more
vegetables in their diet, and there's no smoking and no alcohol. To
say they have less osteoporosis because they don't drink milk is
simplistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that calcium intake is not the only factor in
bone health. Exercise is also important in the prevention of
fractures. Elderly people who exercise build muscle strength, which
leads to greater coordination, fewer falls and, as a result, fewer
broken bones.
</P>
<P>
   Regular exercise also works with calcium to strengthen bone
tissue. Bonny L. Specker, a professor of nutrition at South Dakota
State University in Brookings, analyzed 17 studies of physical
activity and bone density and found that exercise did not
contribute to bone density unless people also consumed at least
1,100 milligrams of calcium a day.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, people who consumed large amounts of calcium but
were sedentary did not build bone. ``Calcium isn't going to do any
good if you're lying on the couch doing nothing,'' Dr. Specker
said. ``And exercise doesn't help you if you have inadequate
calcium. They both work together.''
</P>
<P>
   How much exercise does it take to build strong bones? Most
experts suggest following the Surgeon General's guidelines: half an
hour of exercise a day, five days a week. But the exercise must be
``weight bearing,'' in which the body is not supported against
gravity; swimming and cycling are less effective than walking,
jogging, lifting weights or jumping rope.
</P>
<P>
   When you're finished, go ahead and have a glass of ... something
cold to drink. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
