<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Sept. 14, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy showers and gusty winds will begin to affect the Southeast
Coast Tuesday as Hurricane Floyd brings damaging winds and heavy
rain to the Bahamas. High clouds will become more abundant during
the morning from southeastern Virginia to the east coast of Florida
as Floyd approaches. In addition, the strong winds of the hurricane
will create very large swells, leading to increased beach erosion
to the Southeast Coast. Indeed, portions of the Outer Banks of
North Carolina that were recently ravaged for an extended period by
Hurricane Dennis will once again be pounded by heavy surf from
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Father north, a weakening cold front will cross the Northeastern
states. A narrow band of clouds and some scattered showers will
accompany the front in the northern Appalachians. Following another
cool start, much of New England will have readings near normal
under ample sun. To the south, sunshine will abound from the Ohio
Valley to the Tennessee Valley as high pressure builds into the
region. Meanwhile, a jet stream disturbance will continue to slowly
trek north of the Great Lakes, bringing unseasonably cool air and
scattered showers to the northern Plains and western Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, a weak disturbance passing through the southern
Rockies will trigger a few showers and an occasional rumble of
thunder in the deserts of Nevada and Utah. Meanwhile, winds blowing
up the sloping terrain east of the Rockies will lead to showers and
clouds in north Texas. Offshore breezes in the Northwest will
weaken, allowing a few clouds to return to the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: On the Cusp
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Hurricane Floyd was on the cusp of entering the
fiercest class of the most powerful storm on earth. Hurricanes are
categorized according to the five-step Saffir-Simpson scale which
is based primarily on the highest winds near the storm's center.
Sunday, with sustained winds of 155 mph, Hurricane Floyd was at the
top of Category Four. Category Five storms have winds over 155 mph
Only two Category Five hurricanes have reached the U.S. coast this
century, the Labor Day storm of 1935 in the Florida Keys and
Hurricane Camille on the Mississippi coast in 1969.
</P>
</TEXT>
