<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0516 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MCCOURT-BOOK-REVIEW-N     09-13 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCOURT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
' TIS: FOR AN OUTSIDER, IT'S MOSTLY SOUR GRAPES IN THE LAND OF
MILK AND HONEY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Frank McCourt's luminous 1996 memoir, ``Angela's Ashes,'' the
dream of America beckoned like a bright fairy-tale promise to the
author sunk in a miserable childhood in Limerick, Ireland.
Listening to Billie Holiday on the radio, the young McCourt would
think: ``Oh, Billie, Billie, I want to be in America with you and
all that music, where no one has bad teeth, people leave food on
their plates, every family has a lavatory, and everyone lives
happily ever after.''
</P>
<P>
   In `` 'Tis,'' the eagerly awaited sequel to ``Angela's Ashes,''
that dream seems to have come true _ at least, the 19-year-old
McCourt has made it to New York and launched himself on a new life
that will eventually see him becoming a writer and a public high
school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such developments, `` 'Tis'' is a considerably angrier
book than ``Angela's Ashes.'' Whereas that ``epic of woe'' was
remarkable for its lack of bitterness and self-pity, `` 'Tis'' is
largely animated by the feelings of resentment and envy that the
young McCourt experienced in trying to overcome his family's legacy
of poverty and deprivation. Given the difficulties he faced, it's
hard to begrudge him such emotions; it's just that this sour tone
of complaint does not make for particularly engaging or sympathetic
reading.
</P>
<P>
   McCourt recounts how he frequently walked about New York with
what his mother would have called ``the gloomy puss,'' grappling
with his ``daily deadly sin, Envy.'' Working as a janitor in the
Biltmore Hotel, he resents the privileged young people he sees
there, wishing he could break his ``dustpan and broom over their
heads till blood spurted and they begged me to stop.'' And
listening to Columbia students talk about existentialism, he wishes
his parents ``had lived respectable lives and sent me to college so
that I could spend my time in bars and cafeterias telling everyone
how I admired Camus for his daily invitation to suicide and
Hemingway for risking the bull's horn in the side.''
</P>
<P>
   He resents the grandmother of his girlfriend, Mike Small, for
having ``plenty of food and drink and clothes and furniture and hot
and cold running water and no shortage of money''; and when he
becomes an English teacher at Stuyvesant High School, he resents
his students, ``the privileged, the chosen, the pampered,'' for
being able to go to school, ``get into a money-making racket'' and
grow into their ``fat 40s.''
</P>
<P>
   When he marries Mike, he complains that he didn't know how to be
``a certified member of the middle class'' _ he didn't know ``how
to dress, how to chatter of the stock market at parties, how to
play squash or golf'' _ and when that marriage collapses, he
complains that ``slum-reared Irish Catholics have nothing in common
with nice girls from New England who had little curtains at their
bedroom windows.'' Never mind that he turned his wedding day into
an alcohol-fueled debacle, or frequently stayed out drinking with
friends instead of coming home to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly McCourt's feelings of class rage stem not only from
his harrowing childhood, described so indelibly in ``Angela's
Ashes'' (three siblings who died in infancy, a father who drank
away the family's food money, a mother reduced to begging), but
also from the daunting hardships he faced in New York: having to
work several jobs (at warehouses and on the docks) to make ends
meet, having to live in cramped boarding houses where as many as 12
men shared two towels, having to use an extension cord to borrow
electricity from a neighbor to stay warm in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Although such descriptions are enlivened by McCourt's resilient
sense of humor, they do not possess the lyricism or searing
intimacy that fueled his childhood reminiscences in ``Angela's
Ashes.'' For that matter, the narrative of this volume is largely
reactive: Instead of the formative dramas that shaped the young
McCourt's life, instead of his conjuring of the remote world of
small-town Ireland, we are simply given his responses to a familiar
New York. We repeatedly hear about the embarrassment he feels over
his bad eyes and pronounced accent, the shame he feels over his
ignorance of American social mores, and the sense of alienation he
experiences as an immigrant and perpetual outsider.
</P>
<P>
   As for the supporting cast of `` 'Tis,'' it's made up mainly of
friends and eccentrics encountered during McCourt's peregrinations
around New York. There's Andy Peters, a fellow NYU student who
works part time at Manufacturers Trust Co. and who changes a few
loan applications every night ``to prove how stupid a bank can
be.'' There's Bill Galetly, a friend who uses McCourt's apartment
as a crash pad, babbling endlessly into the night about Plato and
St. John and his own desire to lose weight and get down to a
hundred pounds. And there's Harry Ball, an 85-year-old neighbor who
spends many of his days sitting in an aluminum beach chair near his
car, scouting possible parking spots for the following day.
</P>
<P>
   Though these cameo sketches attest to McCourt's instinctive
storytelling gifts, they cannot compete with the wonderfully
nuanced portraits he drew of his parents in ``Angela's Ashes.'' In
`` 'Tis,'' McCourt's Mam and Dad appear only intermittently, and
they seem to spark in him an ambivalent mixture of rage and
irritation and dismay. By the end of the book, both of them are
dead, and McCourt and his brothers, Malachy, Michael and Alphie,
are all embarked on lives of their own in the United States.
McCourt has begun to enjoy his work as a teacher, and he has begun
to dream about becoming a writer _ like the well-known poets and
novelists whose book jackets he sees on the walls of the Lion's
Head bar in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   He would achieve that dream at the age of 66 with ``Angela's
Ashes,'' a book that would win the Pulitzer Prize and become a No.
1 best seller.
</P>
<P>
   As his mother, Angela, might say: ``That's your dream out now.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   'TIS, A Memoir
</P>
<P>
   By Frank McCourt 367 pages. Scribner. $26.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
