<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-DIGEST-ART-5     09-13 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-DIGEST-ART-580(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PUBLISHER KEEPS A KEEN EYE ON THE ANTIQUES WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALDOBORO, Maine _ Still lifes of dead fish adorn the walls. A
stern bronze bust of the abolitionist and suffragist leader Parker
Pillsbury is draped with a vintage 1940s necktie patterned in
warplanes. Over the staircase hangs an ancient political artifact,
``The Official Ronald Reagan Doormat.''
</P>
<P>
   Tradition treads lightly here at the eclectic, contemporary home
of The Maine Antique Digest, widely called ``M.A.D.'' (not to be
confused with the satirical magazine Mad). A family-run newspaper
with two staff reporters and an army of freelancers and tipsters,
this independent, influential and successful monthly manages the
trick of policing as well as serving the nation's unruly
multibillion-dollar annual trade in antiques and collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people we've done tough stories on advertise and are
friendly with us,'' said the publication's patriarch and publisher,
Samuel Pennington, 70, a scrappy and folksy editor in khakis and
sneakers who straddles cyberspace and newsprint to cover the
industry and search out scandal. Of course, not everyone is always
charmed with the results.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, after a federal mail fraud investigation and
guilty plea in a case exposed by The Maine Antique Digest, Charles
G. Moore, a New York auctioneer, was sentenced to two years in
prison and ordered to pay $584,000 in restitution for defrauding
people who had consigned him antiques and artworks for sale.
</P>
<P>
   But the paper sometimes stumbles. July's issue had just gone out
with a long article by a prominent dealer in Civil War artifacts,
Russ Pritchard III, when a civil jury in federal court leveled an
$800,000 judgment against him in the purchase and lucrative resale
of items from George E. Pickett V, a descendant of the Confederate
general who led a disastrous charge at the Battle of Gettysburg.
``Timing is everything,'' the paper editorialized red-facedly,
noting at the same time that lawsuits were a fact of life in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a couple of snide letters,'' acknowledged Pennington.
``The snider the letter, the further up we print it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the paper is also busily serving an industry aboom with new
electronic salesrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers and collectors need only log on to the paper's Web page
(www.maineantiquedigest.com), for example, to register and call up
images of 13,000 objects and their prices, an explosion of data
generally welcomed in the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet and electronic media have come into this
business, I could not believe how fast,'' said Pennington, tilting
back in a swivel chair in an office cluttered with publications,
old airplane models, sculptures and what he calls his ``dead-fish
paintings,'' his meager concession to collecting. Dealers, he said,
no longer have to sit in their shops waiting for customers to walk
through the door. In the process, The Digest has already lost some
advertising to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But far from fighting the trend, the 26-year-old paper,
published in this quiet mid-coast community of 4,500 west of
Rockland, has joined it, with its Web site and Internet ad sales
and with the purchase of a 10 percent share in Ehammer, an online
auction service.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the heart of the operation remains the newspaper, a
no-frills product in black and white that is hardly likely to win
awards for design, not that Pennington cares about that. A lesson
he learned early in the publishing business, he said, was: ``Never
give them more than they'll pay for.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Priced at $3.75, the paper, which has been as big as 408 pages
in nine sections, bulges with ads, photos, show and auction news
and scattered investigative articles. The October issue, about to
be mailed out, contains an advisory about pseudo-antique iron
snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Hard reporting has helped make The Digest a mainstay of the
antiques field, with wide reach. Circulation is at a high of
33,000, almost all by subscription. ``It's an essential tool in the
field of Americana because of its access to the marketplace,'' said
Gerard C. Wertkin, director of the Museum of American Folk Art in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 Pennington served as guest curator of an exhibition of
folk art fakes and forgeries, presented by the folk art museum at
Hirschl &AMP; Adler Folk, a gallery on Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Smith, a producer and manager of art and antiques shows,
including the Fall Antiques Show at the Seventh Regiment Armory in
New York, said The Maine Antique Digest was ``the only paper in the
American art field that actually does investigative reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many other antiques newspapers, magazines and
newsletters, including another family enterprise, The Antiques and
the Arts Weekly of the Bee Publishing Company in Newtown, Conn.,
which happily leaves the feather ruffling to The Digest.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as digging into personalities, we leave that up to
Sam,'' said R. Scudder Smith, the weekly's publisher and editor,
who was the first to accept ads for Pennington's upstart
publication. ``Our policy is if it's between two people, it's not
public business. Let them work it out themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Smith said, ``I think Sam's on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   To Pennington and his family _ his wife, Sally, is on the
masthead, along with three of their five grown children _ there is
nothing anomalous about applying high technology to the antiques
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole antiques business is a matter of transportation,''
he said, ``getting something from where it isn't valuable to where
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an imperfect market,'' he said. ``The stock market is
perfect. One share is the same as another.'' But with no such
standardization in the antiques market, ``information is the key
factor,'' Pennington said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a dealer myself,'' he said, ``I found it easier to sell to
someone in the know than someone who didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child in Baltimore, Pennington grew up with antiques in a
Victorian house left to his great-aunt and grandmother. ``They were
Tilghmans,'' he said. ``Lots of lineage, no money.''
</P>
<P>
   His father was a car salesman, his mother a teacher. The
furniture in the house was so old, he recalled, that once a year a
cabinetmaker came in with his gluepot to make repairs. Then during
the Depression the family lost it all.
</P>
<P>
   He rediscovered antiques when he was stationed in Bangor, Maine,
as a navigator in the Air Force. In 1959 he and his wife bought a
1775 house in Waldoboro and began raising a family. Later they
opened an antiques shop. ``There's no real entry barrier,'' he
said. ``You can open a business with one object.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Vietnam War he served on Guam and in Thailand, making
B-52 bombing runs over the Ho Chi Minh Trail, an effort he now
derides as futile, ``really dumb.'' He retired from the Air Force
in 1973 and the family moved into the house in Waldoboro while he
sought financing for his antiques publication and opened a
furniture-restoring business. ``It's amazing what you can teach
yourself,'' Pennington said.
</P>
<P>
   He started The Maine Antiques Digest just as offset printing was
revolutionizing publishing. By a stroke of luck, he said, the debut
issue of 28 pages contained a last-minute article by a noted Maine
antiques dealer, Chris Huntington, that drew widespread attention
for its inside information and candor.
</P>
<P>
   The logo consisted of a rooster weather vane that provided the
``i'' in Antique, and the word was not given an ``s'' but kept
singular so that it would fit more neatly above ``Digest.'' ``I got
a complaint from a teacher that it was grammatically incorrect,''
Pennington recalled. ``But I said it was a beautiful logo, and it
fits.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple lived on Pennington's $12,000-a-year Air Force
pension, and the ads covered his business expenses. ``It took three
years to make money, but at least it didn't cost us anything,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple divided responsibilities. ``I did the business
letters, he went on the road,'' Mrs. Pennington recalled in her own
office, which is decorated with women's rights memorabilia. ``We
made it clear neither one would be boss over the other.''
</P>
<P>
   With a typewriter and three cameras and a load of floodlights
and backdrops, Pennington drove to dealers from Vermont to
Connecticut, photographing their stock free for ads in the first
issue. A full-page ad cost $100 at the beginning. (It is now $750.)
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote the news articles, sometimes adopting a pseudonym
so the paper would not look like the one-man show it was. One name
he chose was Lance Poulet, for chicken on a stick: his weather
vane. But he said he always kept a strict division between the ads
and editorial copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep them separate,'' he said. ``Otherwise you get
no respect.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1975 he hired his first reporter, Lita Solis-Cohen of
Philadelphia, a writer on antiques for The Philadelphia Inquirer
and other publications who was to burn out four computers in a
torrent of reporting. She soon began breaking exclusives. ``People
call and tell us things, and we pinch ourselves,'' she said. ``Why
are they telling us this? Because we do it fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Her greatest scoop came in 1985, when a collector tipped her off
that he had been offered the Holy Grail of American collecting: a
copy of ``Oath of a Free Man,'' a broadside printed by the
Massachusetts Bay Colony in 1639 that was known only by references
in other documents; no copy had ever been found. It turned out to
be a forgery, but it put Ms. Solis-Cohen and The Digest's other
staff reporter, David Hewitt, on the trail of the nation's most
notorious forger, Mark Hofmann, who had also fabricated
embarrassing Mormon Church documents and killed two people with
bombs before the schemes unraveled and he was sent to prison for
life.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington, meanwhile, was dazzled enough by his success to
attempt a local weekly general-interest newspaper. But his appetite
for dogged reporting provoked a backlash when he insisted on
delving into the suicide of a local police officer who, in a
strange twist, had caught his wife with an older man.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington also ran into opposition closer to home, from his
wife, when he wanted to photograph a woman who collapsed and died
at a town hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say she gave up her right to privacy when she died at a
public meeting,'' he said. Mrs. Pennington threatened to sue her
husband and went so far as to consult a lawyer. ``So I backed
down,'' Pennington said.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly lost $90,000 over three years before he shut it down
in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985 Pennington moved The Maine Antique Digest out of leased
quarters and into a new, high-ceilinged 6,200-square-foot building
he built on Main Street. Soon afterward he sold his 1775 house and
built a new one, along the lines of The Digest's building. ``Old
buildings are for young people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 he ran for the school board, which covers five towns in
two counties, and won a three-year term. ``He's become an important
citizen,'' said a neighbor, the art critic Hilton Kramer, who lives
part of the year in Waldoboro.
</P>
<P>
   In a concession to mortality, five years ago Pennington hired
his son, Sam, a college drama graduate called by his middle name,
Clayton, to avoid confusion in the office, and handed him the
editing reins this year. A daughter, Kate, is managing editor, and
another daughter, Sarah McCleary, is business manager. Two other
daughters do not work at the paper but are also shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I each own _ what do we own?'' Pennington shouted
to his wife in the next room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We each own 35 percent,'' she replied. ``The five kids each
own 6 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not voting stock,'' Pennington said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
