<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0527 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e BC-SHORT-TV-REVIEW     09-13 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHORT-TV-REVIEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENDING UP TALKS SHOWS (SORT OF)
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ms) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At its hilarious best, which it often was during the first 40
minutes of its premiere Monday, Martin Short's new comedy-talk show
is like a fresh edition of ``Saturday Night Live'' with interviews.
Always funniest when he is mocking types, especially show-business
types, Short turned up as half a dozen characters in the filmed
sketches that are the most engaging part of the show.
</P>
<P>
   He played Martina Navratilova as a secret agent, swinging her
tennis racket and stomping on a villain with her enormous feet, in
a failed television pilot called ``La Femme Martina.'' For a spoof
of tabloid television called ``Prime Time Edition Tonight,'' he did
a wickedly funny impression of Janeane Garofalo campaigning to save
a serial killer. And he was engagingly sly as himself, wading into
the audience singing ``Too Marvelous for Words'' and pulling off a
supposed audience member's toupee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its promise, though, there is a big question the show
has yet to figure out: How do you mock show biz and remain a
mainstream part of it? The more straightforward Monday's show
became, which it did with a nose dive in the last 20 minutes, the
flatter it seemed. The future of ``The Martin Short Show''
(syndicated nationally) will depend on how cleverly he can satirize
talk shows even while he is doing one.
</P>
<P>
   With a cast of little-known comic performers, the show promises
plenty of sketches. The glimpses of failed television pilots were
among the best moments. There was ``Mike Angelo, Police Sculptor,''
about a temperamental artist who chisels likenesses of suspects out
of marble, and ``The Falsettos,'' about mobsters with high-pitched
voices.
</P>
<P>
   With his first guest, Billy Crystal, Short showed too many clips
from their ``Saturday Night Live'' days. They redeemed themselves
by breaking into a brief version of ``Kate and Ali,'' a goof on the
old ``Kate and Ally'' show, with Kate Hepburn and Muhammad Ali as
roommates. It was almost a throwaway, but any time Short does his
priceless Hepburn impression and Crystal his Ali it's a treat.
</P>
<P>
   When Short veered away from comedy, though, it became apparent
the talk-show mold wasn't being shattered after all. The last
segments were so conventional, anyone could have been sitting in
the host's chair, on the bland living-room set. The model and
actress Rebecca Romijn-Stamos brought a clip of her appearance on
``Just Shoot Me.'' Clips are not a good sign for the future. When
the author of a book about survival techniques demonstrated how to
cook a chicken in a backpack with hot rocks, Short tried futilely
to wring some laughter out of it.
</P>
<P>
   The television landscape is cluttered with the bodies of recent
talk shows that are dead (``The Howie Mandel Show'') or dying
(``Roseanne''). What ``The Martin Short Show'' has in its favor is
its star's great satiric imagination and some inventive friends.
Tuesday's scheduled guest is Steve Martin, who uses a talk show as
an excuse for sketch comedy better than anyone. (His routines with
David Letterman are classics.) If viewers are lucky, Short will
come up with a long list of guests willing to play along with him
rather than slog through the usual talk-show babble.  &QL; 
THE MARTIN SHORT SHOW  &QL; 
CBS, Monday through Friday &QL; 
(Channel 2 in New York at 4 p.m.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martin Short, host. Martin Short, Bernie Brillstein and Stuart
Krasnow, executive producers. Peter Johansen, supervising producer;
Claudia Cagan, senior producer. A production of King World
Productions.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
