<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-REPORT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CIVIL RIGHTS GROUP SAYS CLINTON LOST HIS NERVE ON SCHOOL REFORM
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON The Clinton administration's ``massive failure of
will and nerve'' lets many states illegally use lower academic
standards for poor inner-city children than for middle-class
suburban children, charges a report issued Monday by the private
Citizens' Commission on Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is sheer nonsense,'' responded David Frank, director of
public affairs for the Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Such a policy could leave poor children, many of them from
racial and ethnic minorities, under-educated at a time when most
decent jobs require advanced skills in reading and math.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Elementary and Secondary Education) Act was passed in
October 1994 and the Republicans won control of Congress in
November 1994,'' said William L. Taylor, vice chair of the
30-year-old watchdog group. ``From then on, major elements of the
act were ignored by the department.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he suspected that the Democratic administration eased up
on regulation of the states in order to have as many allies as
possible in its epic battle during 1995 and 1996 with the House GOP
majority, which was trying to abolish the Department of Education,
end federal regulation of public schools and slash federal
education spending by as much as 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The commission concluded: ``The bad news is that the Clinton
administration, once a prime advocate of standards-based reform,
has since had a massive failure of will and nerve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the contrary,'' replied Frank, `` There's been a sea
change, and 48 states already have statewide assessments in
place,'' although federal law doesn't require that until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that state standards ``are to some extent
uneven,'' he said the administration has ``urged rigorous state
standards,'' and has asked Congress to require that school
districts spread their resources, including assignments for the
best-qualified teachers, more evenly between schools in affluent
and poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But the 169-page report stated: ``In the administration's
readiness to countenance differing standards and expectations for
children one set for children in more affluent suburbs and another
for poor children in inner cities there are disturbing echoes of
the old racially dual systems of education that the Supreme Court
(outlawed) in Brown v. Board of Education, and of the two-tiered
system of advanced versus basic education that the 1994 Title I
reforms were designed to eliminate.''
</P>
<P>
   Title I is the section of the 1994 act through which the federal
government splits more than $8 billion a year among the 50 states
for use in bolstering academic performance in schools with many
poor children.
</P>
<P>
   The act requires that a state accepting Title I funds create a
single set of high standards for all its students and public
schools, and require them to make progress toward those standards.
</P>
<P>
   States like California, Colorado, Maine and Missouri allowed
districts to pick their own ways of assessing academic performance,
which often meant that wealthy districts had higher standards than
poor districts, the commission said. Some others adopted vague
standards, or tests that were not aligned with what was being
taught in their schools.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, the report praised the policies of Texas,
Maryland and other states that had been moving toward
standards-based reforms before 1994. It singled out school
districts in San Antonio, Philadelphia and Memphis as prime
examples of successful, standards-based efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the commission's bipartisan board range from
Republicans such as former Indianapolis Mayor Will Hudnut and
former Attorney General Elliot Richardson to Democrats such as
former Secretary of Labor Ray Marshall and Gus Hawkins, former
chairman of the House Education and Labor Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
