<SLUG> BC-CHAMBERLAIN-Q&AMP;A13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3 questions with ... Richard Chamberlain
 &HT;    By Kathy Janich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When you hear the voice, the characters come flashing
back. Young Dr. Kildare. The tormented Father Ralph de Bricassart.
The manly John Blackthorne.
</P>
<P>
   The voice is the same, but the actor, Richard Chamberlain, is no
longer a boyish intern at Blair General taking sage advice from his
mentor, Dr. Gillespie.
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Chamberlain has swashbuckled his way through a mini-series
or two since then (``The Thorn Birds,'' ``Shogun,''
``Centennial''), done time on the London stage and traveled to
``Chaillot'' with madwoman Katharine Hepburn.
</P>
<P>
   And although he sings onstage, he's more music lover than
practitioner _ the music of jazz pianist Marian McPartland shares
his CD player with Ella Fitzgerald, Tony Bennett and Sarah Vaughan.
</P>
<P>
   At 64, the Hawaii resident has a decade or two on those who've
preceded him as Captain von Trapp (Broadway original Theodore Bikel
was 35; the movie's Christopher Plummer was 38), but he still
relishes the challenge of live theater.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed easily one recent afternoon as he answered a few
questions about life in the Alps:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Doing eight shows a week can be grueling, especially on the
road. How do you cope?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nobody's supposed to know it's hard work. It's supposed to
look like fun. And it is fun, but it's also hard work. It's a
rather monastic life. It's about maintenance. Sleeping. Eating the
right thing. Vocalizing. There's little time to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You called ``My Fair Lady,'' which you did in Atlanta in
1993, a classic of musical theater. Where does ``The Sound of
Music'' rank?
</P>
<P>
   A: Obviously, it's also a classic. It's easy to underestimate
``The Sound of Music.'' In fact, it's got a lot of guts. It's a
very moving show. The audiences are invariably moved by it on a
number of occasions. The book isn't in the same class as (George
Bernard) Shaw, but it's lovely.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your favorite moment?
</P>
<P>
   A: I love the scene when (the Captain) confesses to Maria that
he's in love with her. And she to him. And I like that song
(``Something Good,'' added from the movie) very much. I also like
singing ``Edelweiss.'' It's a little scary, but I like that moment.
Singing is still kind of foreign. I'm doing all right, I think, but
there is a certain suspense about it. Will I or won't I make it
through the song?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sound of Music''
</P>
<P>
   Through Sunday. 8 tonight-Friday;
</P>
<P>
   2 and 8 p.m. Saturday-Sunday. With Richard Chamberlain, Meg
Tolin and Jeanne Lehman. $15-$43. Theater of the Stars, Fox
Theatre, 660 Peachtree St. N.E. 404-817-8700.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
