<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talk tones down a bit from debut
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is not likely to be as much talk about the second issue of
Talk ($3.50) as there was about the debut of Tina Brown's magazine.
This time there are no revelations by Hillary Rodham Clinton about
her husband's sexual escapades, just a mix of celebrity profiles,
political articles and New York gossip. Never one to hide her light
under a bushel, Brown devotes eight pages of celebrity-studded
photos to Talk's debut party at the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   In the cover story on Elizabeth Taylor, author Paul Theroux
takes a helicopter ride with the actress over Michael Jackson's
Neverland ranch and Theroux offers his opinion about what makes the
film star tick. It's all about having more, Theroux says, and adds
that if Taylor had her way, she would supersize her life the way
she does McDonald's fries.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the magazine, James Surowiecki goes to the mat with
World Wrestling Federation promoter Vince McMahon, who has
transformed professional wrestling from a somewhat seedy enterprise
to an $850 million company. Despite his success, McMahon still
carries a grudge against Ted Turner after a deal with Georgia
Championship Wrestling and TBS went sour in the mid-'80s. ``I don't
like the way he treats people,'' McMahon says. ``I don't like him
as a human being.'' Turner had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More on Ted: Speaking of Turner, the media mogul has dropped
out of the Top 10 list of Vanity Fair's ($3.95) New Establishment.
Ranked fifth last year, Turner is now No. 16. Bill Gates holds onto
his No. 1 spot, while Turner's rival Rupert Murdoch is No. 2.
Rounding out the Top 5 are Viacom Chairman Sumner Redstone, Time
Warner Chairman Gerald Levin and AT&AMP;T Chairman C. Michael
Armstrong. Four women made the list _ eBay CEO Margaret Whitman
(31), Oprah Winfrey (33), Paramount Chairman Sherry Lansing (38)
and Hewlett-Packard CEO Carly Fiorina (46).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Changing styles: With the opening of the New York fashion
shows this week, The New Yorker ($3) devotes its cover and a
sizable chunk of this issue to clothing trends. Photographer Herb
Ritts has a 10-page portfolio of the new styles _ outfits that
include everything from turkey leather capelets to hats that look
like sparrow nests. Everyone acknowledges that designers leave
their mark on fashion, but CNN's Elsa Klensch has left her mark on
designers. Now, with more coverage on television, New Yorker writer
Rebecca Mead says ``designers are aware that they now need to
produce not just great clothes, but great video.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  George continues: Eighty percent of the last issue of George
($2.95) that was edited by John F. Kennedy Jr. is a typical blend
of celebrity and politics. The cover story is on actor Rob Lowe.
Until now, Lowe jokes, his most memorable role was in a videotaped
three-way sexual encounter in an Atlanta hotel room during the 1988
Democratic National Convention. How newsworthy was it? ``Tiananmen
Square was the second item on the news,'' he says. Also in George,
CNN reporter Christiane Amanpour and soccer's Mia Hamm make the
list of the 20 ``most fascinating'' women in politics.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Time ($3.50) explores the growing phenomenon of
J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter books and reveals that there will be
deaths in the next four novels. The only way to show how evil it is
to take a life ``is to kill someone the reader cares about,''
Rowling says.... In a special commemorative issue, Vibe ($2.99)
remembers fallen hip-hop legends Tupac Shakur and Christopher ``The
Notorious B.I.G.'' Wallace. Family and friends recall the slain
stars frankly and fondly.... The Web continues to weave its
influence over our lives. Newsweek ($3.50) reports on how the
Internet is changing the way we shop, seek medical care and have
sex. More than half of the requests on search engines are
``adult-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
