<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EMMY-AWARDS-780&AMP;ADD-N     09-13 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMY-AWARDS-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE EMMYS, STILL FAVORING MORE OF THE SAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Picture this: Academy Awards are presented three or
four years in a row to Steven Spielberg, Tom Hanks and Jodie
Foster. The outcry would be deafening among rival actors and
directors, as well as critics and studio executives.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the 51st annual Emmy awards for television, given by voters
of the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences, were notable not
only for their repetition but for an obvious reluctance to break
new ground and recognize ``The Sopranos,'' the lavishly praised HBO
series about a Mafia family with middle-class values in suburban
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``The Sopranos'' has been the most widely discussed
television series of the year and was expected to gather numerous
prizes, the show created by David Chase won only two awards Sunday
night. One went to Edie Falco, who played the Mafia wife. The other
went to Chase, along with James Manos Jr., for writing in a drama
series.
</P>
<P>
   By mostly bypassing ``The Sopranos'' and rewarding so many
familiar faces that had been repeatedly honored, the Emmy voters
seemed to be expressing resentment toward HBO for its
envelope-pushing treatment of language and sex, and for its having
become the darling of critics.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, the awards plainly reflected the paucity of
creative vision on television. Quite simply, except for the
constantly honored king makers like David E. Kelley and Steven
Bochco, the Emmy voters have few places to go.
</P>
<P>
   This year it was Kelley's turn. He became the first producer in
Emmy history to take home awards for both a drama and a comedy. The
drama, ``The Practice,'' about a struggling Boston law firm, beat
``The Sopranos'' in the category of best drama series. Kelley's
show also won the drama Emmy last year. A second Kelley show,
``Ally McBeal,'' won the top comedy prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm genuinely surprised for both,'' Kelley said. Kelley, who
writes as well as produces, said he had been convinced that ``The
Sopranos'' would take the drama prize. ``There was so much heat
surrounding that show, and it's so different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas O'Neil, author of the book ``The Emmys,'' said that
Kelley was the favorite son of the Emmys because of his sensibility
and that Chase was not the favorite son, for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelley wins virtually every time because he can put together
an uncanny combination of brilliant writing, quirky plots that are
suspenseful and amusing, and very appealing characters,'' O'Neil
said. ``Kelley is especially deft at writing effective sentiment.
Contrast that with `The Sopranos,' where the characters are
unsympathetic. The show's cynicism hurt David Chase. The show just
didn't have those classic elements that Emmy voters like, which is
sentiment and sympathetic characters.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO executives would argue that Tony Soprano and his family are
as strangely sympathetic and dramatically compelling as, say, the
Corleones in ``The Godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   Overlooked in the Emmys ceremony as an obviously unhappy James
Gandolfini, who plays Tony Soprano. Gandolfini lost to Dennis Franz
of ``N.Y.P.D. Blue.'' Nancy Marchand, who plays Tony's mother,
Livia Soprano, was defeated by Holland Taylor of ``The Practice''
for best supporting actress in a drama.
</P>
<P>
   What was unusual, even strange, about the Emmys was how the
academy honored previous winners and longstanding shows and seemed
to avoid at all costs the adventurous and risky.
</P>
<P>
   As one top television executive pointed out, the academy gave an
Emmy for best variety show to, of all things, the 1998 Tony awards
show on CBS, a thoroughly conventional and often tedious
production. In giving the award, the academy passed over three
provocative HBO specials: one starring George Carlin; another, John
Leguizamo; and the third, Jerry Seinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Just as puzzling was the academy's selection of Helen Hunt for
the fourth year in a row as best actress in a comedy series, even
though her show last season, ``Mad About You,'' had hit near bottom
in the ratings. Franz's Emmy for ABC's ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' was his
fourth. David Hyde Pierce of NBC's ``Frasier'' won his third Emmy,
as did John Lithgow of NBC's ``Third Rock From the Sun.'' Franz
seemed genuinely surprised, and so did Ms. Hunt and Lithgow.
</P>
<P>
   Lithgow candily acknowledged the situation Sunday night. ``It's
hard for dazzling new shows to score at the Emmys,'' he said. ``I
guess the big example this year is `The Sopranos,' which I consider
to be as good as television can get. It did get one wonderful
award, I guess a few. I guess the big ones eluded it for now. We
feel like veterans. The old guard never seems to like new kids on
the block.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One element that displeased supporters of ``The Sopranos'' is
the way the winners are picked. Unlike the Academy Awards or the
Grammys, for which members of their respective academies select the
winners en masse, the Emmy system is quirky.
</P>
<P>
   The 9,500 members of the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences
pick the nominees in 77 categories. After that each winner is
selected by panels of volunteers ranging from seven to 70 people
who watch tapes of nominated shows in a Beverly Hills hotel suite
and then vote. The volunteers are academy members.
</P>
<P>
   The positive _ or some would say negative _ side of the
selection process is that the panels seem impervious to buzz and
media hype and the kind of momentum that leads to Oscar sweeps for
films like ``Titanic'' or ``Forrest Gump.'' Another side of the
equation, though, is that the panels, as industry volunteers, are
often unemployed or retired and may have an ax to grind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panels tend to have more women than men and they often have
problems with unsympathetic and unsentimental characters,'' said
O'Neil, the Emmy specialist. ``The David Kelley wins last night
were in line with all of the Emmy biases.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO tried to put a positive face on the Emmy awards and ``The
Sopranos.'' The cast flew back to New Jersey on Monday to resume
filming episodes for the new season, starting in January. Jeff
Bewkes, chairman and chief executive of HBO, sat quietly eating
breakfast Monday morning in the dining room of the Peninsula Hotel
in Beverly Hills. He shrugged off any disappointment. ``I think
James Gandolfini is the best dramatic actor on television this
year,'' he said. ``He'll be back again next year. I guess it takes
time to know Tony Soprano.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
