<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER URGES HISPANICS TO STAND AND BE COUNTED FOR CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hispanics risk losing potential gains in Congress
and federal money distributed through population-based formulas if
the 2000 Census misses minorities in areas with large Latino
populations, a Texas congressman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes from representation and redistricting to allocation of
federal funds,'' Rep. Charlie Gonzalez, D-San Antonio, told
Hispanic leaders attending a conference sponsored by the
Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The caucus seeks an accurate 2000 Census and the use of the
sampling to estimate the number of people missed by traditional
methods used by the U.S. Census Bureau: door-to-door canvassing and
mailed questionnaires. Historically, the Census has missed 2
percent of the population but more than 5 percent of Hispanics and
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hispanic leaders are calling on Congress to provide
full funding for the decennial head count.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt has estimated the 2000
count will cost roughly $6.8 billion, more than double the $2.6
billion in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials estimate that there was an undercount of roughly
500,000 people in 1990, costing the state $130 million over 10
years in federal funding for programs such as education, Head
Start, housing and medical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Hispanics has continued to grow over the past
decade. Arturo Vargas, executive director of the National
Association of Latino Elected and Appointed Officials, said
Hispanics could see increased representation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the chance to pick up a couple more Latino seats,''
Vegas said.
</P>
<P>
   One of those seats could be in South Texas, where population
growth could mean another congressional seat once 2000 population
figures are adjusted for redistricting. Growing states, such as
Texas and California, would likely see more congressional
representation.
</P>
<P>
   Texas now has 30 House representatives and California has 52.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said that in addition to congressional seats, Hispanics
are nationally poised to win more elections to state governments,
city halls and school boards coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the importance of an accurate census, various
Hispanic- and minority-rights groups have launched public relations
campaigns to inform minorities that they need to stand and be
counted.
</P>
<P>
   A number of cities and neighborhoods are developing their own
campaigns ``because the Latino community is so diverse,'' said
Marisa Demeo, a regional counsel for the Mexican American Legal
Defense and Educational Fund.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that Hispanics are counted in the next census, the
organization has launched a national outreach effort called ``Make
Yourself Count!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
