A0561 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      09-13 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews:
</P>
<P>
   ``THE COMPLETE STORIES OF EVELYN WAUGH'' &QL; 
(Little, Brown, $29.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``His style,'' said Edmund Wilson, ``has the desperate
jauntiness of an orchestra fiddling away for dear life on a sinking
ship.'' Evelyn Waugh was wicked and funny, and his fellow writers
were happy to apply the same tactics to him. Here are his works of
short fiction, 39 stories collected for the first time in hardcover
for American readers (the book was adapted from a scholarly edition
published last year in Great Britain). They include ``By Special
Request,'' in which Waugh suggests an alternative ending to his
novel, ``A Handful of Dust,'' and ``Charles Ryder's Schooldays,'' a
chapter in the life of the hero of ``Brideshead Revisited,''
published 16 years after Waugh's death. To coincide with this
volume, Back Bay Books has reissued ``Brideshead Revisited,''
``Decline and Fall,'' ``Vile Bodies,'' ``A Handful of Dust'' and
``Scoop'' in paperback. The books are like Waugh himself _
handsome, with viciously funny stories inside. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``A LITTLE MORE ABOUT ME'' &QL; 
By Pam Houston (Norton, $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this is a LOT more about her, and it is dumbfoundingly
interesting. Houston does nothing, really, except talk about
herself in these essays, yet unlike her filmed recitations for
television's ``Sunday Morning,'' these monologues pull you in, and
before you know it, you've stayed for the duration. Maybe it's the
swagger in what she has to say, the stockpile of experience, the
competence at things that are foreign to many women, and many men,
for that matter. If you've read her short-story collections
(``Cowboys Are My Weakness,'' ``Waltzing the Cat''), you know that
Houston is on intimate terms with adventure, with wilderness, with
danger, and with difficult men who thrive on all three. She has
been a hunting guide in the mountains of Alaska, and she has run so
many white-water rivers in so many countries that she can't
remember them all. She was addicted to risk for a long time, but
she's getting over it. She has a ranch now, and is learning to call
it her own. Finally, she has good friends and, it seems, a
boyfriend who goes against type. In one of these essays she takes
him winter camping and he admits that he has never slept on the
ground before. What's amazing is that she doesn't hold it against
him. Her essays are about mountains, rivers, horses, dogs, hunters
and _ we sure didn't see this one coming _ her lifelong obsession
with her weight. ``Even to this day,'' she writes, ``call me stupid
and I'll laugh in your face; call me a bad writer and I'll discuss
art with you all day long; but call me fat and you'll send me
sobbing to the bathroom, and I'll wear tent dresses for the next
six days.'' It might be the most ordinary thing we've ever heard
about Pam Houston. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``BEST SHOTS: THE GREATEST NFL PHOTOGRAPHY OF THE CENTURY'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(DK, $30) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at Barry Sanders on Page 70,'' writes Joe Namath
in his foreword. ``Just look at his feet, his legs, his body
movement, his motion _ how his body weight is leaning so hard to
one side. Look at that right foot of his! And he's still going at
full speed, you know, he's not falling down. I mean, he's exploding
somewhere.'' It's true, you'll be impressed. Sanders, photographed
in 1995 by Allen Kee, is cutting so hard that his body is hanging
out over thin air and the twist of his pivot foot has distorted the
leather of his shoe _ AND HE'S NOT FALLING DOWN. Or look at Lynn
Swann on Page 84, making, in 1976, one of the most spectacular
catches in Super Bowl history. Or at Terry Glenn, turning to draw
in a Drew Bledsoe pass that has just emerged from a dense fog that
hides anything more than a few feet above the field. Or at
linebacker Chuck Bednarik celebrating over the prostrate form of
Frank Gifford, who looks like road kill in a helmet. There's lots
of drama here, but our favorite is a quiet photograph that puts the
others to shame. It shows, quite simply, Walter Payton running a
path created for him by his Chicago Bears teammates. It's an
understated moment that reveals football at its best _ the
precision teamwork, the finesse, the choreography of the game.
(That's the Giants' Mark Ingram on the book jacket, celebrating in
the end zone.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
``LISTEN TO THIS!'' &QL; 
By Alan Reder and John Baxter (Hyperion, $16.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reder and Baxter spent four years interviewing popular musicians
about their favorite artists and recordings. The result is this
volume, which offers educated and honest opinions (Dave Matthews
says he listens to Keith Jarrett's album, ``The Koln Concert,''
because ``it calms me down, like watching windshield wipers'')
about today's music from some of the people who know it best. The
Beatles are mentioned more than any other group or artist. Other
favorites include James Brown, Joni Mitchell, Hank Williams, Muddy
Waters, the Rolling Stones, John Coltrane, Otis Redding, Elvis
Presley, Charlie Parker, B.B. King, Howlin' Wolf, Jimi Hendrix,
Aretha Franklin, Miles Davis, Lightnin' Hopkins, Ray Charles and
Bob Dylan. But not all of the names are famous, so it's possible to
discover new territory for your own listening pleasure. The authors
note, for example, that Dave Matthews, Ani DiFranco and Victoria
Williams all list among their favorites ``an obscure but very
special album'' by Mary Margaret O'Hara called ``Miss America.''
The book includes a master list of artists, and its index will
inspire you, too. Among the musicians polled are Pat Metheny,
Waylon Jennings, Joan Armatrading, Vassar Clements, Michael Doucet,
Pete Seeger, Sonny Rollins, Willie Nelson, Branford Marsalis, Bobby
McFerrin, Herbie Hancock and Dr. John. &QL; 
You can reach Anne Stephenson at amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1752EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-POLICE-MILITARY-NYTR &LR;      09-13 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-MILITARY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS WARN OF BLURRED LINES BETWEEN SOLDIER AND COP 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The renewed attention on Waco underscores what some
critics see as a troubling trend in U.S. law enforcement _ the
increased militarization of police departments.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by Congress and recent administrations, local law
enforcement agencies have turned to the military for equipment and
training, particularly when it comes to fighting drug crimes. Over
the past 20 years, lawmakers and presidents have chipped away at
the landmark Posse Comitatus Act, a post-Civil War law that banned
the military from enforcing civilian laws.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, in fact, is poised to pass a bill that would make it
even easier for local police departments to call on the military
for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a growing problem,'' said Gregory Nojeim, an attorney
with the American Civil Liberties Union's national office in
Washington. ``Increasing numbers of local law enforcement agencies
are forming SWAT teams and adopting SWAT team tactics that are
sometimes used when they're not necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, it is not uncommon for the Defense Department to share
its military equipment. In 1981, Congress passed the Military
Cooperation with Law Enforcement Officials Act, which authorized
the military to ``assist'' civilian police in enforcing drug laws.
President Bush later established six regional task forces within
the Department of Defense to work with police agencies to combat
drug activity.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1995 and 1997, the Pentagon distributed to police
departments approximately 1.2 million pieces of military hardware,
including 73 grenade launchers and 112 armored personnel carriers,
according to a report released by the Cato Institute, a libertarian
think tank. In 1994, the departments of Justice and Defense signed
a joint agreement to develop and share technology and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials say the equipment sharing and training is
justified in light of the heavy firepower used by some modern
criminals. They also defend it as cost effective.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, say the line between soldier and police
officer is becoming dangerously blurred. An unusual coalition of
civil libertarians, gun-rights advocates and even some former
police officers are decrying the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been incremental, but it's actually an incredible
fundamental change in American policing,'' said Joseph D. McNamara,
a retired New York City police officer who also served as chief in
departments in Kansas City, Mo., and San Jose, Calif. McNamara, now
a research fellow at the Hoover Institution in California, said the
development of specially trained tactical units has encouraged a
``kick butt'' attitude among some officers that runs counter to the
notion of settling conflicts peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sharing of training and technology is producing a shared
mind-set,'' said Diane Cecilia Weber, a graduate student in
criminal justice in Virginia who wrote ``Warrior Cops'' for the
Cato Institute. ``The problem is that the mind-set of the soldier
is simply not appropriate for the civilian police officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike soldiers, Weber said, police officers are trained to use
deadly force only as a last resort, and they must always be mindful
of the constitutional rights of all citizens. ``The police mind-set
is one of more restraint,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The military influence on police departments will likely be part
of new investigations into the disastrous 1993 raid on the Branch
Davidian compound near Waco, Texas. The military provided some
training and aid for agents with the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   But even as a new independent panel prepares to take a look at
the role of the military in the Waco raid, a defense authorization
bill would make it easier for local enforcement agencies to turn to
the military for help in certain situations.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which is working its way through Congress, includes a
little-noted provision that eases restrictions on police
departments calling in the military. Currently, the military can
only be called in under emergencies involving biological or
chemical weapons. Even in those operations, soldiers cannot be
involved in any arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new language, which is included in the final version
of the defense bill now headed for passage in the House and Senate,
the emergency designation is no longer needed. And soldiers would
only be barred from direct involvement in arrests.
</P>
<P>
   In what would be another break with current policy, local law
enforcement agencies would not have to reimburse the military for
aid, a change that would likely encourage more joint operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think most lawmakers even know this is in the bill,''
said the ACLU's Nojeim, who is trying to get the new language
removed.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials acknowledge that they have turned to the
military for training and equipment, but they said it's an
exaggeration to suggest that police departments have adopted a
military mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there ever a time in police operations in which military
type tactics can be appropriate? The answer to that is yes,'' said
Edward Flynn, the police chief for the 360-strong force in
Arlington, Va. ``Should police departments behave like military
units? The answer to that is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn, who also serves on the board of directors for the Police
Executive Research Forum in Washington, said that on ``rare
occasions'' specially trained teams can use ``sophisticated
weapons'' to intimidate criminals and diffuse potentially violent
situations.
</P>
<P>
   But McNamara, the retired police chief, is wary of the
intermingling between the military and police departments because
it can create an ``elite'' force that is distant from the
community. ``These units have taken on a life of their own,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin is in the Washington Bureau of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
