<HEADER>
A0574 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-ROBIN-WILLIAMS-IN-JAK     09-13 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBIN-WILLIAMS-IN-JAKOB-THE-LIAR-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUTH ABOUT `JAKOB': ROBIN WILLIAMS FACES HIS MOST DANGEROUS
ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Robin Williams with Bob Balaban and
Armin Mueller-Stahl in a scene from ``Jakob the Liar.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Robin Williams can laugh about almost anything, but he wasn't
ready to joke about the Holocaust.
 &HT;    Most people never have this problem, but the Oscar-winning actor
couldn't avoid it during the weeks he spent in Poland filming
``Jakob the Liar,'' a drama/comedy that will open on Sept. 24. It
casts him as a pancake vendor who lifts the spirits of his fellow
Jews in a 1944 Polish ghetto with encouraging radio reports _
reports which happen to be lies.
 &HT;    When the subject is genocide, even Robin Williams is at a loss
for a joke.
 &HT;    ``For the first time in my life,'' he says, ``I was afraid of
the laughter.''
 &HT;    Finally a real-life Holocaust survivor working as an extra
offered him some crucial advice.
 &HT;    ``One day he told me not to be afraid of humor in the worst
possible situation,'' Williams says. ``He said that, in the death
camps, people actually did smile and laugh. It was the only way to
survive.'''
 &HT;    To do the role justice, Williams immersed himself in research
into the Nazi occupation. To his surprise, he found that there was
much about the period that he hadn't known.
 &HT;    ``I learned that these ghettos were different from the death
camps,'' he said. ``The Germans would literally jam as many people
as they could into a small area before sending them to the camps.''
 &HT;    The biggest surprise, however, was the deceptive normalcy of
life in the ghetto.
 &HT;    ``I couldn't believe that people in these ghettos would carry on
this illusion of a normal life,'' Williams marvels. ``People were
still going off to work during the day, and then at night they
would attend theater performances. They were still trying to
maintain a certain human dignity _ but yet always hovering over
them was the idea of liquidation.
 &HT;    ``At any moment, the Germans would walk in and kill an entire
neighborhood,'' he says soberly. ``Yet life went on. Children went
to school. Parents made their kids study the classics. The
rabbinical council was still pretending to run things like business
as usual.''
 &HT;    Williams lost 20 pounds for the role, he says over breakfast at
Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel.
 &HT;    ``I had to lose the weight because I couldn't be like, `Ohhh,
I'm suffering. Pass the cookies,''' he says. ``I wanted to look a
little emaciated. But it was rough _ I would run around sneaking
cookies before I left for the shoot. My big excuse was, `Hey, I'm
not in Poland yet.'''
 &HT;    For a man best known for being funny, it's been an unusual
couple of years. Death and despair also have figured prominently in
his previous two movies _ ``What Dreams May Come'' (1998) and
``Patch Adams'' (1998).
 &HT;    Is this Robin Williams' blue period?
 &HT;    ``It's more the taupe and teal,'' the actor jokes.
 &HT;    And a bit of gold, too: The 46-year-old Williams won a Best
Supporting Actor Oscar two years ago for his role as a
compassionate psychologist in ``Good Will Hunting'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``It was a welcome relief,'' he says, puffing imaginary smoke in
the air, ``after all those years of going, `Daniel Day Lewis, I am
so happy for you!'''
 &HT;    These days, he adds, he counts his blessings regularly.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes I get up and figure I have it so good because in
another life, I was somebody named Sid,'' he says with a chuckle.
``That's it. I had a small clothing store. I was miserable. This
life is the universe's way of making it all up to me!''
 &HT;    Actually, Williams has had plenty of misery in his current life.
The proverbial poor little rich boy, Williams grew up in affluent
surroundings _ his father was an executive with Ford Motors _ but
spent his days lonely, an only child in a 40-room mansion.
 &HT;    ``My parents basically gave me the entire third floor and said,
`Have fun,''' he recalls. ``What I remember the most is that the
house had a huge stone wall outside of it. It was like the rest of
the world was outside that wall, but I was inside trapped and
alone.''
 &HT;    Short, fat and unusually hairy, Williams wasn't popular at
school.
 &HT;    ``I was tormented,'' he says simply. ``I remember being in the
sixth grade and being called `leprechaun' and `dwarf' on a daily
basis. I would go home crying and say, `But I'm not those things.'
The truth was, I was fat, hairy and pasty.''
 &HT;    At night, Williams found his only moments of happiness.
 &HT;    ``I would go into my mother's bedroom and do anything to make
her laugh _ jokes, stunts, pratfalls. And it worked. For those few
minutes when she was laughing, it was like everything was suddenly
right with the world.''
 &HT;    A career in comedy was a natural result, peaking when ``Mork and
Mindy'' made him a household name in the 1970s. Always ambitious to
extend beyond comedy _ at New York's Juilliard School he had
participated in improv-comedy workshops, but also taken serious
acting courses _ he turned his eyes toward film.
 &HT;    Though his early films mixed hits and flops _ ``Moscow on the
Hudson'' (1984) being one of the former, ``Popeye'' (1980) one of
the latter _ it was his personal life that suffered most.
Longstanding recreational drug use turned into a serious addiction
shortly after he hit Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``That was hell on earth,'' he says quietly. ``Everything seemed
like it was crashing in on me in those days.
 &HT;    ``It's so much pressure when you first arrive in Los Angeles,''
he explains. ``You watch the box-office numbers take a slide on one
film, and life seems like it's over. Waiters tell you, `Better luck
next time.'
 &HT;    ``My mind was constantly racing in those days. I couldn't do
enough. I knew I had to keep going, keep moving, never stop. I
thought it was all going to end.''
 &HT;    It almost did. It took the 1982 drug-overdose death of his
friend and fellow comic John Belushi _ and the roughly concurrent
birth of Williams' son, Zachary _ to turn things around. He quit
drugs cold turkey, and says he has been clean ever since.
 &HT;    It is probably no coincidence that his movie career began to
catch fire soon afterward. ``Good Morning Vietnam'' (1987) earned
him his first Oscar nomination, and ``Dead Poets Society'' (1989),
``The Fisher King'' (1991), the animated ``Aladdin'' (1992) and the
goofy comedy ``Mrs. Doubtfire'' (1993) established him as a major
star. The Oscar for ``Good Will Hunting'' was mere icing on the
cake.
 &HT;    When his name was announced, he recalls, he hardly knew what he
was doing.
 &HT;    ``A lot of things go through your mind,'' he says, laughing. ``I
grabbed Marsha, my mom, Ben (Affleck), Matt (Damon) and some
strange lady in the aisle who kept screaming, `Stop touching me. I
don't even know you!'
 &HT;    ``Meanwhile, I'm looking at her going, `I love you! I just love
you!'''
 &HT;    The congratulations poured in, and for a while he thought
everything had changed.
 &HT;    ``A month later,'' he says mock-sourly, ``people were back to
going, `Mork!'''
 &HT;    On the whole, though, he isn't complaining.
 &HT;    ``I feel lucky to have landed where I am right now,'' Williams
says. ``I can't think of one man who had it better than me.''
 &HT;    Well, maybe one.
 &HT;    ``I envy Einstein's life,'' Williams says. ``He was a great
scientist and an outrageous human being, which I think is the
perfect combination.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Jakob the Liar,'' consult the
official Website at www.sony.com/jakobtheliar. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
