<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0575 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-MANDY-PATINKIN-IN-CHI     09-13 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANDY-PATINKIN-IN-CHICAGO-HOPE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDY PATINKIN: THE DOCTOR IS BACK IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Mandy Patinkin in a scene from ``Chicago
Hope.'') 
 By MICHAEL J. BANDLER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    When Mandy Patinkin was a kid growing up in Chicago, he lived
for the day before every Jewish holiday when, with a running start,
he could zoom across his mother's freshly waxed floor, laying down
a brand new set of skid marks.
 &HT;    Four decades later, he's still gliding along, slipping as easily
from television to films to recording to the concert stage as he
ever did across that floor.
 &HT;    ``For whatever reasons, I've ended up trying different things _
and I like them all,'' he says. ``And they all feed each other.''
 &HT;    On Sept. 23 he will return to CBS' ``Chicago Hope,'' resuming
his role as the brilliant yet domineering cardiothoracic surgeon
Dr. Jeffrey Geiger, now chairman of the hospital board. On Oct. 1,
he'll surface on the big screen, surrounded by Muppets, in ``Elmo
in Grouchland.'' And early next year he'll return to the stage for
the first time in years for ``The Wild Party,'' a new Off-Broadway
musical.
 &HT;    In between, he's carving out time to record a new CD, to perform
his one-man concert act of Broadway and Yiddish music, and even to
help promote his mother's new cookbook.
 &HT;    ``It's sort of like having different children,'' he says. ``You
want to see them all, you want to spend as much time as you can
with each one, do things with them. But something's going to have
to give here and there.''
 &HT;    Back in the spring of 1995, what had to give was ``Chicago
Hope.'' Despite winning critical plaudits, an Emmy award and high
ratings as Geiger, Patinkin decided that it still wasn't worth
being away from his wife, actress/playwright Kathryn Grody, and
their sons Isaac and Gideon, then 13 and 9 respectively. So he
walked away.
 &HT;    End of story until last winter, when the show's creator, David
E. Kelley, told Patinkin that he was returning as the show's chief
script writer, bringing the show back to its medical roots, and
asked Patinkin to reprise his role in about half of the season's 22
episodes.
 &HT;    ``I told him I couldn't be there full time,'' Patinkin recalls.
``He said, `Don't worry, you won't have to.'
 &HT;    ``And I told him, `If you'll be there, I'll be there.'''
 &HT;    This year's Geiger isn't necessarily the same one fans knew
before, however. He's changed _ ``as much as any human changes in
four years,'' the actor says.
 &HT;    ``He's extremely well-meaning, extremely brilliant in the
operating room,'' Patinkin says. ``But he continues to be extremely
crippled in the arena of life. He now has a great teacher in his
6-year-old daughter, a wonderful reservoir in which he can place
his love and affection.
 &HT;    ``But I wouldn't say he's mellowed, or that he is going to be
nominated for any human-being award,'' he adds. ``He has a long way
to go before his name even gets on the ballot.''
 &HT;    His ``Chicago Hope'' schedule will allow him to spend time with
his family, as well as continuing his highly successful concert
tour. It's rare for a Broadway headliner _ winner of a Tony Award
for ``Evita'' (1979) and star of ``Sunday in the Park With George''
(1984) and ``The Secret Garden'' (1991) _ to tour concert halls,
but Patinkin sees himself as a singer first and foremost.
 &HT;    ``If you forced me to make a decision about only one thing to do
professionally, I would choose concertizing on the live stage,'' he
says. ``It's the most immediate form. The songs have a simplicity.
They were written by geniuses _ ironically, people who struggled so
much in their own lives, yet put down on paper such a wonderful,
idealistic view for themselves and the world, about how to have a
good life and make the world a better place.''
 &HT;    He is least comfortable, he adds, in front of a film or
television camera.
 &HT;    ``The crew doesn't take the place of an audience _ they're busy
doing their job, and if they're good, they stay nonjudgmental,'' he
explains. ``It's very disconcerting to me, after playing a
difficult scene, that you don't have the rest of a play to bring it
to fruition, to cleanse you, to make you understand. And you don't
have the audience to finish it off.
 &HT;    ``Also, in the film world you don't get a chance to do over what
a night's sleep would give you, with some reflection,'' Patinkin
adds. ``You've got to move on. I like moving on, but I also love
having another crack at looking at the same thoughts and ideas. The
theater and concert world allow me to do that.
 &HT;    ``But so does a television series _ where, if you're
collaborating with the writers, as I am, you can adjust the next
scene to continue the conversation.''
 &HT;    A different kind of conversation underlies his involvement with
the upcoming ``Grandma Doralee Patinkin's Holiday Cookbook'' (St.
Martin's Press, 1999), the second cookbook in as many years by his
mother, Doralee Patinkin Rubin.
 &HT;    ``We were always on the phone with her,''' the actor recalls.
```Do you put the turkey breast up or down?' _ `How do you make
potato pancakes?' I never remembered what she told us, and we
couldn't find the little index cards when we did write something
down.
 &HT;    ``We told her to write the recipes down for her grandchildren,
and she wrote a 300-page book!
 &HT;    ``It's given her a whole new lease on life,'' he adds, laughing.
``It makes me feel great to help her out, because it's something I
can give her. And she's given me my whole life.''
 &HT;    Family is central to Patinkin's view of himself _ how many
actors would really have given up a plum television role for family
considerations? _ and he admits that he and Grody have struggled to
find the right balance.
 &HT;    ``For years, I would talk to older people who traveled in their
business, and ask, `How do you do it? How did you work it out?'''
he recalls. ``I never got a good answer. Finally, I realized that
if all these wonderfully gifted, talented, wiser, older people
didn't have an answer, there is none! So I've stopped looking for
it.''
 &HT;    As the years have passed, he says, he's been astounded by the
growth of his sons _ Isaac is nearly college-age, and Patinkin
recently took time out from his imposing schedule to take him on a
tour of Oberlin College, an Ohio-based liberal-arts school with a
strong musical program.
 &HT;    ``Kathryn and I literally lose our breath,'' he says. ``The
boys' voices have changed. They're now men. I'm overwhelmed by
seeing things through their eyes _ I guess it's the whole aging
thing.
 &HT;    ``Just this morning,'' he recalls, ``I was working out, trying
to buff my butt to stay in shape so I can do what I do. My wife
came in with an old pair of bell-bottoms of mine, with 13 buttons
around the flap in front.
 &HT;    ``My son, with not an ounce of body fat, put them on,'' Patinkin
says, laughing. ``I said, `Are those mine? Did I fit into those
once?' My wife said, `Yes.'
 &HT;    ``So I turned the running machine up a little higher.''
 c.1999 Michael J. Bandler  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael J. Bandler is a Silver Spring, Md.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Chicago Hope,'' consult the
CBS Website at www.cbs.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
