<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0577 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-NAMING-TELEVISION-CHA     09-13 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAMING-TELEVISION-CHARACTERS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 SALLY McBEAL? ALLY McDUFF? HMMM ...   
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of David Duchovny with series creator Chris
Carter on the set of ``The X-Files.'') 
 By CRAIG TOMASHOFF  
 c.1999 The New York Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All right, so you're about to launch the best television program
in decades. The setting, the characters, the plot lines are each
and every one a winner. You've got a great cast, and a major
network plans a huge publicity splash on your behalf. The Neilsen
families are practically lining up to hand you untold millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one thing more, though. Before your characters
become household names, they need to have names _ and that's not as
easy as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming up with names for your characters is more stressful
than you would think,'' says Joey Gutierrez, consulting producer
for ``The Drew Carey Show.'' ``It really is like naming a baby. The
name you choose is going to be around you for a long, long time, so
you have to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Brancato, creator and executive producer of the Sci-Fi
Channel's ``First Wave,'' agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to come up with the perfect name, one that won't
predispose audiences against the character you've just come up
with,'' Brancato says. ``For instance, you don't want a name that's
going to remind anyone of a serial killer.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming up with a name is generally the last thing writers do for
a character, but it is usually the first thing viewers are going to
learn about the person. So it's essential to make that first
impression count _ something that is not easy to do when even the
simplest name can be fraught with unintended meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You end up having these arguments like, `He can't be Jim
because that sounds too normal' and `Calling him Billy makes him
sound like too much of a kid,''' Gutierrez says. ``Then you'll come
up with a name like Carrie, and some people think it sounds nice
while others think it sounds slutty.''
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to finesse the question, of course, is to use
the performer's name. Who's going to tell Lucille Ball that
``Lucy'' sounds too old-fashioned? And there's the added advantage
that it's less likely that an actor will blow a take by using the
wrong name _ addressing ``NYPD Blue's'' Det. Andy Sipowicz as
``Dennis,'' for example.
</P>
<P>
   Hence Jerry Seinfeld played a comic named Jerry Seinfeld. Drew
Carey became Drew Carey. Sammo Hung, star of ``Martial Law,'' is
called Sammo. Ray Romano goes by Ray in ``Everybody Loves
Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that strategy can backfire if the performer doesn't
actually wind up with the part. Kathy Kinney's character on ``Drew
Carey'' is called Mimi because her part was originally intended for
Mimi Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the more personal approach. Agent Fox Mulder, as
played by David Duchovny, inherited his last name _ it's the maiden
name of the mother of Chris Carter, creator and executive producer
of ``The X-Files.'' All those names of victims that used to fill
the big board on ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' were relatives
and acquaintances of the cast and crew _ at least until they ran
out and started picking randomly from the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   Homer was the name of the father and grandfather of Matt
Groening, creator of ``The Simpsons.'' His mother was named
Margaret, which can be shortened to Marge, and his sisters were
Maggie and Lisa. And this season Jamie Luner's new detective
character on ``Profiler'' is Rachel Burke, sharing the first name
of the daughter of executive producer Stephen Kronish and the last
name with one of his former writing partners.
</P>
<P>
   Not all ways of naming a character are so obvious. Carter may
have drawn on his family for Fox Mulder's last name, but his first
name comes from a boy Carter knew as a child, while Agent Scully is
named after sportscaster Vin Scully, longtime announcer for the Los
Angeles Dodgers _ and a longtime hero of Chris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   No, ``The Sopranos'' wasn't suggested by singers. Series creator
David Chase happened to recall hearing about a New Jersey clan of
that name when he was growing up, and on a whim used it for the
name of his series' mob family.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Rosenthal, executive producer of ``Everybody Loves
Raymond,'' had a favorite high-school teacher named Mr. Barone, so
that became the surname for Romano's family in the series. Romano's
boyhood dog, Nemo, inspired the name of the pizza joint where Ray
Barone likes to hang out.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Flanders, Homer Simpson's neighbor, and the town bully
Kearney take their surnames from streets in Portland, Or., where
Groening grew up. The title character in ``Felicity'' is named
after a girl the series' executive producer, J.J. Abrams, knew in
high school.
</P>
<P>
   The process isn't always personal. Sometimes inspiration comes
from whatever is handy. When Brancato needed a macho first name for
his ``First Wave'' hero, he found it in the sports pages _ in an
article about UCLA quarterback Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   Luanne Platter, the title character's daffy niece in ``King of
the Hill,'' shares both first and last names with a dinner special
at the Luby's restaurant chain in Austin, Texas, home town of the
show's executive producer, Mike Judge. The streetwise neighbor
Tarnell on ``The PJ's'' was named when a writer picked up an office
stapler and saw the name underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jacobs, creator of ``Boy Meets World,'' was inspired to
name the show's free-spirited character Topanga by the Los
Angeles-area exit sign for Topanga Canyon Blvd., which he regularly
drives by.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, no matter what the inspiration, the names must
accomplish at least one minimal goal: They must at least seem
logical if viewers are to accept the character as likable and
realistic.
</P>
<P>
   And if that's the case, then would somebody please explain Stone
Phillips and Willow Bay?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Craig Tomashoff is a Sherman Oaks, Calif.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0580 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HISPANICS-POLITICS14-     09-13 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS-POLITICS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2000 ELECTIONS SEEN AS KEY FOR SHAPING HISPANIC CLOUT
 &HT;    400&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Next year's presidential and congressional
elections are pivotal to the political development of America's
Hispanic population, Latino leaders and policy experts suggested
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is absolutely critical if we're going to have a
strong impact on the public policy decisions of the next century,''
Rep. Lucille Roybal-Allard, D-Calif., said as the organization she
chairs, the Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute (CHCI), began
developing legislation to present to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Although the gathering was ostensibly bipartisan, the keynote
speaker, Dolores C. Huerta, secretary-treasurer of the United Farm
Workers of America, urged Hispanics to join forces with organized
labor, civil rights groups and other pro-Democratic organizations
to achieve political success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we have to do we have to do in coalition with
others,'' she said as she turned her speech into an old-fashioned
labor rally of cheers for themselves and jeers for opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the role of 500,000 ``new voters'' in defeating
anti-labor initiatives in California in the 1998 congressional
election, Huerta said, ``A coalition of labor and Latinos kicked
some butt. And if we did it over there, we can do it almost
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the policy summit, which has drawn hundreds of
influential Hispanic officials to Washington, is ``coalition
building.''
</P>
<P>
   It coincides with Vice President Al Gore's planned announcement
Tuesday of the endorsement of his presidential campaign by Latino
officials and activists from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of meetings focused largely on the same issues
Gore has been pushing in appearances before Hispanic audiences:
more spending on education, eliminating health disparities,
protecting Social Security and assuring an accurate count of
minorities in next year's census.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in a scheduled address to the CHCI's ``gala'' Wednesday
night, is expected to echo the institute's demand for including
more Latinos at all levels of the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   A two-week boycott of the four major television networks began
Sunday. The so-called ``brownout'' was organized by the National
Latino Media Council, a group formed this summer to protest the
shortage of Latino talent in new shows premiering this month on
ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Democratic front-runner, and Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, the overwhelming favorite to win the Republican nomination,
have been courting Hispanic voters with a vigor never before seen
among presidential candidates _ a measure of the growing political
importance of the population.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2000 presidential election, Hispanics are projected to
cast 5.5 million votes, according to a recent study by the Tomas
Rivera Policy Institute, a California-based Hispanic research
organization. In 1980, less than half that number voted in the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the Hispanic votes are concentrated in
California, Florida, Illinois, New York and Texas, states with a
combined total of 166 electoral votes, more than half of the 270
needed to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The 31 million Hispanics in the United States make up 11 percent
of the population. By 2005, they will outnumber non-Hispanic
blacks, becoming the nation's largest minority group. And by 2050,
one in four Americans is projected to be Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   With support for both parties fairly balanced nationwide, it is
possible ``for the Hispanic vote to become the balance of power for
the next decade,'' Republican political consultant V. Lance
Tarrance Jr. recently concluded.
</P>
<P>
   No modern Republican presidential candidate has ever received a
majority of the Hispanic vote. The previous high-water mark was the
40 percent Ronald Reagan got in 1984. In contrast, GOP nominee Bob
Dole got only 21 percent in 1996, largely due to what Hispanics
viewed as anti-immigrant legislation in Congress following the GOP
takeover in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But Harry Pachon, director of the Tomas Rivera Policy Institute,
noted that ``the roots of partisanship are not deep'' among
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   And Republicans touting Bush's campaign have repeatedly cited
the Texas governor's performance among Hispanics in his 1998
re-election bid _ 49 percent, according to television network exit
polls. Only his brother, Jeb Bush, did better among Hispanics,
winning 61 percent in his successful gubernatorial race in Florida
that same year.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Roybal-Allard noted that congressional Republicans
have largely abandoned their anti-immigrant rhetoric and are likely
to be much more open to the legislation the CHIC is expected to
propose in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is working hard for our votes now,'' she said.
``We're not an after-thought any more.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
