   More important, the Hispanic votes are concentrated in
California, Florida, Illinois, New York and Texas, states with a
combined total of 166 electoral votes, more than half of the 270
needed to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The 31 million Hispanics in the United States make up 11 percent
of the population. By 2005, they will outnumber non-Hispanic
blacks, becoming the nation's largest minority group. And by 2050,
one in four Americans is projected to be Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   With support for both parties fairly balanced nationwide, it is
possible ``for the Hispanic vote to become the balance of power for
the next decade,'' Republican political consultant V. Lance
Tarrance Jr. recently concluded.
</P>
<P>
   No modern Republican presidential candidate has ever received a
majority of the Hispanic vote. The previous high-water mark was the
40 percent Ronald Reagan got in 1984. In contrast, GOP nominee Bob
Dole got only 21 percent in 1996, largely due to what Hispanics
viewed as anti-immigrant legislation in Congress following the GOP
takeover in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But Harry Pachon, director of the Tomas Rivera Policy Institute,
noted that ``the roots of partisanship are not deep'' among
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   And Republicans touting Bush's campaign have repeatedly cited
the Texas governor's performance among Hispanics in his 1998
re-election bid _ 49 percent, according to television network exit
polls. Only his brother, Jeb Bush, did better among Hispanics,
winning 61 percent in his successful gubernatorial race in Florida
that same year.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Roybal-Allard noted that congressional Republicans
have largely abandoned their anti-immigrant rhetoric and are likely
to be much more open to the legislation the CHIC is expected to
propose in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is working hard for our votes now,'' she said.
``We're not an after-thought any more.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
