<SLUG> BC-ASSISTED-LIVING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE COMPANIES LEAD WAY IN PROVIDING ASSISTED LIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRICIA DURYEE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If the number of senior citizens in the United States
is growing _ and it is _ the companies providing those seniors a
place to live also should be growing.
</P>
<P>
   And they are, with three Seattle-area companies leading the way
in an important segment of the senior housing market: assisted
living.
</P>
<P>
   At a third of the cost of a nursing-home facility with the level
of independence that many senior citizens want, assisted living has
become a choice for seniors who need some help in day-to-day
activities. Staff is on-site 24 hours a day, and can offer special
services to those with diseases such as Alzheimer's, but they won't
administer or prescribe drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Emeritus Assisted Living of Seattle is the nation's
second-largest assisted-living company with interests in 145
communities. At the No. 12 spot is Leisure Care Inc. of Bellevue,
with 29 communities operating and 13 more under development.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Seattle-based Merrill Gardens, which has been
around only since 1993 and didn't even make the top-20 list at the
end of last year. But it now operates 56 communities with a total
of 5,043 units in 14 states, and made a major acquisition in August
by buying Texas-based TORCH Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   How did the Northwest get to be home for three leaders in the
retirement-housing industry? ``There are some good long-term
companies that set some precedents'' and acted as schools for
others, said Dan Madsen, president of Leisure Care, which was
founded in 1976. ``We're one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Those three are part of a broader industry trend. In the past
three years alone, 14 assisted-living facilities have gone public,
according to Andrew MacPherson, an analyst from Volpe Brown Whelan
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that perspective, it's grown really rapidly,'' he said.
``The number of old people that will be in the country in the next
30 years is what the industry is designed to cater for.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry estimates show that demand for assisted-living
facilities will increase 150 percent by 2005, and that's before
baby boomers turn of age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our market for senior housing is for those over 75,'' said
Bill Pettit, president of Merrill Gardens. ``They get to a point
where they are healthy but experiencing some difficulty in daily
living and could use a little help in dressing or bathing.''
</P>
<P>
   With the additional TORCH units in the South, the company will
have a greater presence in states where it expects that
75-and-older market to be largest, including Washington,
California, Arizona, Texas and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Before the acquisition, the company expected revenue in the $60
million range. Now, the additional units will push the company into
the $80 million to $90 million range.
</P>
<P>
   Emeritus has been climbing the growth ladder, as well _ so
rapidly, in fact, that it has yet to generate a profit since its
founding in 1993. Last year, Emeritus reported a loss of $31
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be the second-largest, we've grown rapidly,'' said Kelly
Price, Emeritus' chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   So have a lot of companies, to the point that the market may be
a little flooded with assisted-living facilities until more baby
boomers reach prime age for retirement living.
</P>
<P>
   MacPherson said there has been a huge influx of capital into the
market, prompting a construction boom. Recently that capital flow
has dried up, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some companies have grown too quickly and have experienced
operational difficulties'' such as hiring and retaining staffers,
Madsen said. After failing to meet earnings expectations,
``companies have cut back on expansion and focused on operations.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies may be national, but the markets are strictly
local, added Andrew Heyward, who follows the assisted-living
industry for Ragen MacKenzie Inc. in Seattle. People like to retire
in the communities they've lived in, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly some companies that are struggling to get
in balance,'' he said. ``They must reach an equilibrium before they
can meet profitability. ... It's a local business that is highly
variable from place to place.''
</P>
<P>
   Excess capacity also means consolidation, which in turn means
opportunity for some companies such as Leisure Care. ``We're
looking for opportunities to acquire small companies and one-off
projects, as well as develop ourselves,'' Madsen said, adding that
the company hopes to add six to eight new projects a year.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Gardens also expects to grow by acquisition and
development. It recently received a $15 million round of equity
funding, which will enable the company to continue its growth. Each
year, Merrill Gardens aims to add five more buildings, Pettit said.
</P>
<P>
   While they're waiting for baby boomers to age and fill up their
facilities, assisted-living companies face some more immediate
problems, such as explaining what they are to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a bit of an identity crisis,'' Madsen said. ``There
are so many levels of assisted living, it's tough to say what it
is. We face the challenge of confusing the customer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
