<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0592 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-PRIMERICA-COX     09-13 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMERICA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Providing for needs while increasing purchasing power is key for
Primerica
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John A. Addison Jr. may sound like a television
preacher.
</P>
<P>
   But the exhortations by the president and chief marketing
officer of Primerica Financial Services _ delivered weekly via
satellite from Duluth,, Ga., where the company is based, aren't a
gospel of salvation.
</P>
<P>
   They're meant to rally the company's zealous agents, most of
them part-timers, to sell more life insurance and other financial
products, to recognize top producers, and to recruit others into
the sales force.
</P>
<P>
   That sales force of 153,000, including many husband-wife teams,
is likely to grow next year as the Citigroup unit expands out of
North America for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Germany and Spain are the most likely beachheads. Japan, the
world's largest life insurance market, will come later. It's a more
difficult market to enter, from a regulatory standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be very successful if we could have an international
operation equal to the size of the U.S. operation,'' observed D.
Richard Williams, chief financial officer. He estimated Primerica
could capture 10 percent of the German life insurance market in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   The move overseas comes at a time when the global life insurance
business has experienced its highest rate of growth in nine years,
according to a recent study by the economic and research arm of
Swiss Reinsurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   The study noted that some of the fastest growth rates have been
in western Europe and in emerging markets such as Latin America and
South and East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Primerica already is one of the top-five life insurance
providers nationally, with more than $392 billion of term life
insurance in force. Its market share ranges from a low of 1.44
percent in New York to a high of 7.28 percent in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of life insurance typically are driven by marketing. And
over the past five years, Primerica has been flexing its
considerable marketing muscle in a new direction charted by
Chairman and Chief Executive Joseph J. Plumeri, who recently
assumed responsibility for Citibank's branches in north America as
well.
</P>
<P>
   While Primerica's business still centers on term life insurance,
its agents now sell an array of financial products, chiefly those
of sister Citigroup companies. These include Smith Barney mutual
funds and CitiFinancial home-equity loans.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup was formed last year with the merger of Citicorp and
Travelers Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've changed the positioning of the company,'' said Addison,
whose live TV broadcasts continue a tradition begun by founder
Arthur L. Williams, who no longer is involved in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a former football coach, founded the company in 1977
and and sold it in 1989. He exhorted people to ``buy term and
invest the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivals howled when consumers heeded the pitch and began
replacing cash-value life insurance policies, which combine death
benefits with a low-yield investment fund, with cheaper term life
policies that only offer death benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had said A.L. Williams (then), people would have said
insurance,'' Addison said. ``Our goal is to get you to think of
Primerica as helping you with your financial needs, of being your
'financial guy' instead of just your 'insurance guy.'''
</P>
<P>
   That shift may have been dictated to some degree by changes in
the market for financial products and services. Over the past two
decades, the number of middle-income Americans with life insurance
has declined, according to a study by Hartford-based Conning &AMP; Co.
In 1967, one household in eight bought insurance from an agent,
compared with one in 17 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   If they're not thinking about buying insurance, they're thinking
about debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask the average middle-income American, 'What is the
single thing you worry the most about financially?,' most of them
will say 'I'm overwhelmed in debt,''' Addison said. He noted that
Primerica is doing close to $200 million a month in
debt-consolidation loans.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Primerica's strategy is a ``financial needs
analysis'' performed for every client and prospect. It's the
recognition that before customers can make financial choices, they
must first be able to identify the problem areas.
</P>
<P>
   Products and services are then tailored to meet the client's
needs, with the hope they ultimately will enhance the customer's
purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
   That innovative approach, now emulated by other financial
services providers, has paid off. Primerica's mutual fund sales
jumped 90 percent over the last four years to $2.94 billion in 1998
from $1.55 billion in 1995. Loan originations more than doubled
over the past three years to $1.46 billion in 1998 from $726
million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Primerica's agents now sell about half of all the home-equity
loans sold by CitiFinancial, and as much as 25 percent of the
variable annuities sold by Travelers Life &AMP; Annuity.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Primerica's profits _ which stumbled earlier
this decade before Plumeri's arrival _ have doubled in five years.
They're expected to reach $450 million to $460 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Financial Officer D. Richard Williams, who isn't related
to A.L. Williams, expects the trend to continue, noting Citigroup's
desire to see its units grow at a 15 percent annual compounded
rate.
</P>
<P>
   Key to the company's continued success is its sales force, which
include many of Primerica's own clients seeking to improve their
incomes. About 90 percent are part-time and pay their own business
expenses, including training and education costs.
</P>
<P>
   Agents get a commission not only on their own sales, but also on
the sales of people they recruit to sell, and so on, up to as many
as six levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to succeed and help our clients, we've got to help our
people in our sales force achieve their dreams and succeed,'' said
Addison, 42, who has spent all but two years of his career at the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very interesting as I've grown in the company,''
said the Covington native. ``We're now a part of such a huge
company in the industry from this little fly-by-night outfit in
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Luke writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
