<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-TRANSSEXUAL-2TA     09-13 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRANSSEXUAL-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING PUBLIC GIVES TRANSSEXUAL SOME COMFORT IN BEIJING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ When she walks down a city street, Jin Xing
effortlessly draws attention with her noble bearing and her elegant
clothes. But there is something else about her, and many people
seem to sense it.
</P>
<P>
   Jin Xing is a transsexual.
</P>
<P>
   At 32, Jin Xing (pronounced gin SHING) already has an impressive
resume: a prize-winning dancer and choreographer, a former colonel
in the army, founder of China's first independent dance troupe,
owner of one of Beijing's hottest nightspots.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is Ms. Jin's leap across the gender barrier, from male to
female, that fascinates many people here. Ms. Jin is the first
transsexual in China to talk about it openly, and it is making her
a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people pay more attention to my dance because of who I am,
that's fine,'' Ms. Jin said between sips of cappuccino at an
outdoor cafe near her home. ``If more people think about who they
really are, because of me, that's fine too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jin evidently revels in the attention she is attracting,
voraciously soaking up publicity in any form. In addition to a
cascade of requests that she choreograph or direct stage
performances, spurred by her fame as well as her talent, she is
also accepting invitations to pose for magazine photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being famous,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of people are undergoing sex change operations
in China, and several have thanked Ms. Jin for setting such a
public example, saying it gave them the courage to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Although no precise statistics have been made public, sex change
operations have become numerous enough that Beijing Medical
University recently published guidelines for people requesting the
surgery, including a five-year waiting period, extensive
psychological counseling and a year of hormone treatment before the
operation. One doctor at the university has performed 26
operations.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem remarkable that a government as conservative as
China's allows sex change operations, though the medical
authorities recently disclosed that the first one was performed, in
secret, in 1983. No law ever expressly forbade or permitted such
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what seems an even greater surprise is the ability of
someone like Ms. Jin to operate freely in Chinese society, a
distinct sign of how permissible unconventional lifestyles are
becoming here.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, China's control-obsessed government made sure that
all nonapproved ways of life were kept out of view, including
homosexuality and even premarital sex, reflecting the authorities'
distinctly puritan attitude.
</P>
<P>
   But deep social change in recent years, forced by economic
loosening, has meant that ordinary Chinese have gained more freedom
over private life and that transsexuals and the more eccentric
branches of youth culture like punk rockers can express themselves
without fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel any discrimination,'' Ms. Jin said. ``Many people
do not understand, but no one is saying, `You can't do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Chinese society is highly homogeneous, and individual expression
is often snuffed out at an early age. Putting the group first and
the individual last is often portrayed by the authorities as a
lofty concern, though it also masks a deep intolerance that is
frequently manipulated by people in power.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, overcrowding and a lack of privacy also put a
premium on discretion. As long as no one feels threatened, Ms.
Jin's sex change is apparently regarded with fascination but also
with acquiescent respect.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As a man, Jin Xing emerged as China's top dancer in 1987,
winning a national competition and then going to New York for four
years of study. Living in the Chelsea section of Manhattan, he
opened his eyes to American society, among other ways by spending a
night in jail when a rival Chinese dancer falsely accused him of
robbery to try to keep him out of a dance competition.
</P>
<P>
   Real artistic distinction came in 1996, a year after Ms. Jin's
sex change operation, when she established China's first
independent dance troupe and began performing a set of startlingly
original pieces that explored issues of love and identity, winning
accolades as China's leading modern choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   China's state-run media, reporting on her performances that
year, also wrote about her sex change, a sign of official approval.
</P>
<P>
   Like many transsexuals, Ms. Jin said she had known from
childhood that she had a gender conflict. Living in New York and in
Europe, where she spent three years, Ms. Jin became aware that a
sex change was a realistic possibility, though she said she had
thought about it abstractly long before.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole being is female,'' she said. ``I always knew I should
be a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from a military family, Jin Xing joined a dance troupe
run by the army at age 9 in the northeastern city of Shenyang.
</P>
<P>
   Dance instructors remember a willful child, fiercely determined
and extraordinarily talented as a dancer. And crafty, too. One time
the young dance student went on a hunger strike for a week when the
army blocked a move to study with a more advanced dance troupe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sent me in to talk to him, and I told him he was hurting
his body by not eating,'' recalled Zhang Aijuan, a dance teacher at
the military troupe. ``He looked at me with a long face and
whispered, `I'm not stupid, I'm sneaking chocolate.'''
</P>
<P>
   The military superiors eventually relented and allowed the
transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jin credits her success, in part, to the discipline learned
in the army.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you give, the more you get,'' she said. ``Success
takes three things: talent, hard work and opportunity. I am very
lucky to have had all three.''
</P>
<P>
   She did not discuss her decision to become a woman with her
parents until she was about to go ahead with the operation,
performed in a Beijing hospital in 1995. She was most terrified
about telling her father, a military intelligence officer and a
professionally conservative man.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he surprised her, congratulating her for being so brave. His
help was needed to get the sex designated on Ms. Jin's national
identity card switched from male to female, which she says has been
the most difficult bureaucratic obstacle she has faced. She felt no
need to change her name, which means ``gold star'' and unlike many
names in China is not gender specific.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jin said she had not undergone the psychological therapy now
required of sex change patients in China, and had refused to take
hormones for fear they would make her fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a dancer,'' she said. ``My appearance is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jin, whose broad shoulders and strong hands hint at a
masculine past, said she had become accustomed to standing out in a
crowd. Most days, she wears a qipao, a long body-hugging gown.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look very carefully at me,'' she said. ``I have it much
harder than ordinary women. They can dress sloppily, but I have to
be perfect every day. People are looking for my faults.''
</P>
<P>
   She also feels that she grew up in a discriminatory atmosphere
as a member of an ethnic minority, since her parents are ethnic
Koreans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese people can be very racist,'' she said. ``I felt a lot
of discrimination as a child. My teachers were always telling me:
`Don't let anyone know you are Korean. You will never get into
competition.'''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right mate is never easy, Ms. Jin also said,
pointing out that even the most open-minded Chinese men were often
intimidated by a strong woman.
</P>
<P>
   Although dance has been her life, Ms. Jin says she would like to
become an actress and perhaps a talk-show host. She was recently
cast as a Chinese dance instructor in a Hungarian-Chinese film, to
be shot next year. She also dreams of playing Jiang Qing, the
leftist leader and former actress who was Mao's last wife, and Sai
Jinghua, the widow of a leading diplomat during China's last
imperial dynasty, who became a successful spy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to play a spy from a young age,'' said Ms.
Jin. ``In all the old movies we watched as children, the
Nationalist spies were dashing and good-looking. I wanted to be
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After she won an award from the Culture Ministry last year, a
seal of official approval, many government-backed organizations
commissioned her to choreograph performances. She recently staged a
performance of monks from Shaolin Monastery who practice martial
arts and is currently working with a children's acrobatic troupe of
children at the military academy where she herself studied.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't dare approach me until they knew that the
government approved,'' she said. ``It has taken a lot of work, but
I am finally getting there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
