<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0608 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-13 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD THE TIE BIND? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The great Walter Cronkite, bless his 82-year-old
heart, watched the U.S. Open championship match between Andre
Agassi and Todd Martin spiffily attired in jacket and tie.
</P>
<P>
   He was the only one visible on television in the packed crowd of
23,000 at the Flushing Meadows, N.Y., center court in such
dignified garb. It was a telling moment. And what it told is kinda
sad.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite is a generational throwback to a more dignified era,
when well-bred men and women wouldn't dream of being seen at public
events in tee-shirts and sneakers. Nowadays, anything goes so long
as the person is half-way covered up with something.
</P>
<P>
   Dress codes are going the way of the dodo bird, vanishing even
in places like the Kennedy Center here, where fancy duds were once
part of the price of entry. I guess one still usually wears a
floor-length gown to White House state dinners, but female evening
pants have been spotted there, and the mandatory long white gloves
disappeared decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   My handsome grandson, a young computer deep-thinker who earns
more than I did until well into my middle-age, doesn't own a tie
and wears to the office the same tee-shirts branded with odd
messages on front and back that he wears to wash the car. The
shirts are clean. They just aren't alluring.
</P>
<P>
   He's in tune with his times. Some studies estimate that more
than half the nation's office workers dress just as casually.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, my handsome husband, who is of Cronkite's
generation, feels uncomfortable without a tie and jacket. In
practically every restaurant, he is the only man in the room so
illustriously attired. He does it anyway, a stubborn salute to an
older, more formal way of life.
</P>
<P>
   When the Washington Opera sent out notices that it was
abandoning all dress standards for attendance at its tony
performances, USA Today thought this shocking development so
culturally newsworthy it put the story on the cover of its Sept. 7
Life Section. But this is merely confirmation of a trend long in
the making.
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands' Prince Claus was widely cheered last year when
he ripped off his tie in public and threw it at the feet of veddy
proper wife Queen Beatrix. Although he growled that it was a
``snake'' around his neck, it appeared to be but a temporary royal
rebellion. He has since been photographed with similar silk
reptiles around his throat.
</P>
<P>
   We love to blame all signs of cultural decline on President
Clinton, but this one is too great a stretch. Spending money to
meet rigidly defined clothing standards is simply not as important
to the Baby Boomers and their generational successors as other
lifestyle factors, such as swell cars, day care centers for the
kids, tickets for rock concerts, good wine in restaurants and
vacation travel abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion industry, which hasn't had a good idea for two
decades, has only itself to blame here. The designers have sent too
many idiotic costumes down their runways, as even industry leaders
are beginning to admit. Ordinary women look stupid in mismatched
outfits with clashing patterns and colors meant to transform them
into gypsies, bohemians, druggies, waifs, tarts, sadomasochists and
street peddlers.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has put us in skirts so short they barely cover our
behinds and now wants us to wallow in skirts so long they trip our
feet going up stairs. After seasons of clunky platform shoes, now
they promote high, high heels so thin they are not useful for
walking but very handy for toppling.
</P>
<P>
   Exposing a navel by wearing too-short sweaters is the latest
sexy look for skinny young females. Ugh.( Equally ugh, the
counterpoint for young males is to wear pants that hang low enough
to show their underwear, although not quite low enough to expose
real flesh.)
</P>
<P>
   One mainstream fashion magazine had no less than two dozen
pictures of models whose navels were the focal point of the
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Help! None of this works in an office, if a woman wants to be
taken seriously. By these standards, tee-shirts, slacks and
sneakers seem downright attractive. Not to say sensible.
</P>
<P>
   The 700-page September issue of Vogue calls the latest madness
sixties-boho style, by which the magazine means the ``nomadic
chic'' of big boots, taffeta, embroidered peasant tops, sequins and
everything in bad taste all thrown together at the same time on one
body. Vogue's rival Harper's Bazaar goes in for wearing big
blankets as clothes, calling the concept ``bed-head chic,'' and
confesses it can't find a name for the current trend in which
``everything goes together.'' Or, actually, doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   No mystery here why sensible people have opted out of the
fashion game. Fashion mavens writing about the fall designer shows
in New York this week are hesitating to push the line that this
expensive display matters much beyond its publicity shock value. It
is all too clear that this silliness does not sell clothes.
Eyeballing what everyone wears on the street is far easier and more
comforting.
</P>
<P>
   Men are more resistant to shifting clothing oddities than women,
but the genders are embracing the new casual look with equal
enthusiasm. Bustles for women and lace cuffs for men vanished a
century ago when their wearers decided they were more trouble than
they were worth.
</P>
<P>
   So it is today. We are stuck with jeans and tee-shirts, for
better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
