<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SMITHSONAN-EXEC-ART-N     09-13 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITHSONAN-EXEC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT OF FANNIE MAE CHOSEN TO LEAD SMITHSONIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawrence M. Small, a banking executive who was
invited by the Smithsonian Institution to advise it on selecting a
new leader, was chosen Monday to lead it himself.
</P>
<P>
   Small, 58, will leave his post as president of Fannie Mae, the
government-chartered mortgage company, to take one of the nation's
leading cultural positions, that of secretary, or chief executive
officer, of the Smithsonian. He will take office in January,
succeeding I. Michael Heyman, who announced his retirement earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his plans for the Smithsonian, a collection of 16
museums and other entities, mostly in Washington, Small said,
``This institution already touches the lives of 30 million people a
year: visits, members, the Web site, courses, tours. And with 142
million items in the collection there is a vast potential for
developing partnerships throughout the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Such partnerships, which include sending parts of the
Smithsonian's collection to other museums, have already been
established, but Small said he would greatly expand the practice,
especially since only 2 percent of the collection can be on display
in Smithsonian museums at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that you would see a lot of arrangements with
local institutions throughout the United States,'' Small said.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he mentioned the Smithsonian's new American
Indian museum, for which construction is to start on the Mall this
month. Part of that collection will also be shown at the
Smithsonian's exhibition space in the Custom House in lower
Manhattan, but Small said that museums around the country would
welcome the chance to display some of the artifacts as well,
especially those in the West and the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Small began his career at Citibank in 1964 and by 1980 was
supervising corporate banking in the United States and Canada. When
it became apparent in 1991 that he was not going to get the
chairmanship of Citibank, he left to assume the No. 2 post as
president at Fannie Mae, the nation's largest investor in home
mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   When Heyman said he planned to retire as secretary of the
Smithsonian, Small was part of a panel of management specialists
who were called in to advise the committee on what to look for in a
successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called back and said they were interested in my
candidacy, and I said that I was also interested,'' Small said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Smithsonian, David Umansky, said Small's
salary was under negotiation. But it appears he will have to face a
big salary cut. It is unlikely that the Smithsonian will be able to
match Small's Fannie Mae compensation, which last year totaled more
than $4.25 million in salary and performance bonuses, according to
the annual statement that corporations must file with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Smithsonian regents' executive committee, Barber
Conable Jr., a former congressman from upstate New York and a
former president of the World Bank, said, ``It's hard to imagine a
better person to lead the Smithsonian into the next millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of his interest in the post, Small said, stemmed from his
background. Although he is in banking, he said, he has studied
music, art and anthropology. While he was a student at Brown
University, from which he graduated in 1963, a sympathetic
professor helped him to talk his way into Smith College's junior
year abroad in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I studied flamenco guitar in Granada and Madrid,'' he said.
But after listening to the competition, he decided that he would
never fulfill his teen-age ambition to become the world's greatest
flamenco guitarist. He did, however, become fluent in Spanish, and
that led to overseas positions at Citibank.
</P>
<P>
   Small, who said he still practices his flamenco guitar every
day, and his wife, Sandra, met in Chile. She is a Spanish-English
interpreter at the U.S. District Court here. The couple have two
children, Martin, a law school student who also plays the guitar,
and Amy, a fine arts student.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0616 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l BC-SPRING-FASHION-SPI &LR;      09-13 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-FASHION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHIONABLY ASKEW WILL BE LOOK FOR Y2-K  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fashion shows here often range from unsettling to
downright screwy, with just enough beautiful and/or wearable
collections to keep audiences coming back.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as fashion designers unveil their spring 2000 designs
to fashion writers and retail store buyers, things are simply
askew.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a conventional hemline or straight seam is a challenge,
as is finding a garment made entirely of a single type of fabric in
a single color.
</P>
<P>
   There are so-called garments being shown that don't appear to
have been sewn at all. They resemble pieces of fabric tied, or
draped and tied around bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces of clothing that are actually sewn are also usually
askew. Handkerchief hems _ where the hemline takes a dive at one
point or several _ abound. And it isn't only hems that are jagged.
Tank tops, shells, apron tops and bandeaus seem to be cropped at
odd angles.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Tomez, an Austrian who created a Latin-inspired
collection, showed a wrap skirt that was mini on one side, maxi on
the other. He even managed to make an asymmetrical shirt for men.
</P>
<P>
   Angular exploration continued at Mark Montano's show. Cotton
lace tops cut randomly across the bottoms, dropped lacy little
daisies over skirts with handkerchief hems. Montano also attached
odd pieces of fabric _ pleated red chiffon, for example _ to float
around shoulders or hips.
</P>
<P>
   Moet &AMP; Chandon, the champagne company, sponsored a show to
introduce young new designers _ talents who could never afford the
five or six figures (we're talking money, not models here) it takes
to stage a show.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Alexandra Lind, tied blocks of fabric together in
ways that left pieces of skin exposed _ a skirt that left squares
of flesh over the hips bare, an evening ensemble that showed off
large triangles of skin front and back. Models move carefully in
these costumes.
</P>
<P>
   At a ``Salute to African American Designers,'' clothes from the
Epperson boutique in SoHo mixed assorted white fabrics into
wrapskirts and other items of clothing that literally swathed the
body. They looked like remnants assembled by a genius.
</P>
<P>
   Han Feng, a designer known for her evening apparel, showed what
appeared to be large tubes of smocked silk worn as skirts. It
appeared that the models stepped into the tube, then wrapped the
excess fabric across the front where it was secured by a hidden
snap or hook.
</P>
<P>
   The hemlines may be skewed, but there are messages here: Mix
fabrics. Never make a garment with just one piece of cloth. Use at
least two, preferably contrasting ones. Think texture. Mix colors.
Put a sheer over a solid, such as yellow tulle over red cotton. Use
a contrasting fabric for a fringe or ruffle.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend that is joyous and interesting when it works. It
didn't fare particularly well at the Versus show _ a branch of the
Italy-based fashion empire of the late Gianni Versace. Gold tulle
ruffles across the backside of white pants fell into a category of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   With a room stuffed with celebrities, however, who cared about
the clothes? Madonna was trying to hide under a leopard-print
cowboy hat. Diminutive Sylvester Stallone had trouble standing out
in this crowd of fashion giants, and Lisa Marie Presley simply
looked very young and dazed.
</P>
<P>
   Natasha Richardson _ zipped into a tight red leather jacket (it
was 72 degrees outside) _ smiled and posed for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Sarandon was front-row center at the Han Feng show dressed
in baggy black linens like most of the audience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0617 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WORLDSPAN-COX     09-13 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDSPAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Worldspan names Blackney to top job
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Worldspan on Monday ended a six-month search for a new
chief executive, naming travel industry veteran Paul Blackney to
the post.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based travel reservations system, jointly owned by
Delta, Northwest and Trans World airlines, said Blackney's
appointment takes effect Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   He replaces Mike Buckman, who left Worldspan in March for an
Internet real estate venture in California. Since then, Worldspan
has been led by a pair of interim CEO's, general counsel Doug
Abramson and operations chief Sam Galeotos.
</P>
<P>
   Blackney was most recently senior vice president for publishing
and business services at the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   But he's spent most of his career in the travel industry,
including executive stints at United Airlines and Apollo Travel
Services, partly owned by the Chicago-based carrier. Apollo has
since become part of Galileo International, a Worldspan rival.
</P>
<P>
   Abramson, in a prepared statement, said Blackney ``has been at
the forefront of significant developments in travel marketing
technology, from the creation of computer reservations systems to
leveraging the power of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Worldspan provides reservations and booking software to travel
agencies, as well as computer support to airlines. It has 3,100
employees, including 1,800 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, trade press reports had Worldspan on the verge of a
merger with Europe-based rival Amadeus, but the deal never
materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Abramson and Galeotos will resume their normal duties under
Blackney, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
