A0628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-NETWORLD-COX     09-13 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Networld+Interop conference opens doorsBy Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Georgia World Congress Center is, once again, a
good place for connections.
</P>
<P>
   This week it is home to Networld+Interop, the world's largest
technical conference focused on the burgeoning networking
technology that links the communications systems that carry voice,
video and data.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, various crews were still constructing booths and
exhibits for the approximately 500 companies that will showcase
their products. Also on the bill are a host of educational and
training sessions, as well as some high-profile talks by industry
heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   About 50,000 people are expected to attend _ more than half
coming from within 500 miles of downtown Atlanta, according to
Valerie Williamson, vice president and general manager of
Networld+Interop.
</P>
<P>
   Just who is coming?
</P>
<P>
   Most attendees are information technology professionals, she
said. For them, it does not seem esoteric to talk about virtual
private networks, digital subscriber lines, network intelligence,
remote access or extranets. It is likewise not alphabet soup to
speak of SQL, XML, SLA, IPSEC, ERP or NSP.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 50 percent of attendees work for corporations of more
than 1,000 employees, and the rest come from small- and
medium-sized businesses, Williamson said. ``That is why Atlanta is
so important. It's a high-tech hotbed of innovative companies using
technology to advance their own businesses overall. More and more,
technology is a strategic part of their operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Among general subjects for discussion this week are network
management, operating systems and security _ where Atlanta-based
Internet Security Systems joins Network Associations, Checkpoint
and others in offering solutions. Their booths are likely to be
crowded, Williamson said. ``When you are transferring your business
to an electronic business, you better make sure the first thing you
have is security.''
</P>
<P>
   The show floor will feature ``start-up city,'' a section of
about 50 new companies with cutting-edge technologies.
</P>
<P>
   As for training and tutorial sessions, the show features seven
different ``tracks'' focusing attention on different aspects of
networking. For instance, you could spend the week immersed in the
issue of transmitting voice using Internet protocol.
</P>
<P>
   One track is co-sponsored by the Metro Atlanta Chamber of
Commerce, said Jennifer McClure, spokeswoman for Ziff-Davis, which
owns the 10-year-old trade show.
</P>
<P>
   Although the show has been here annually for several years, this
is the first such arrangement with the chamber, she said. ``We feel
the Southeast is a growing technology hub and we want to forge
stronger relationships here.''
</P>
<P>
   Networld+Interop will be back in Atlanta next year, she said.
``We have no plans to leave the Georgia World Congress Center.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is the marriage of Interop and Networld, which came
together in 1995. The event is held twice a year in the United
States _ in Atlanta and Las Vegas _ as well as in Canada,
Australia, Singapore, Brazil and France.
</P>
<P>
   Keynoters today are Lucent Technologies Chief Executive Richard
McGinn and Intel Vice President Mark Christensen. On Wednesday,
Nortel Networks President Dave House speaks at 9 a.m., while at 5
p.m., the speaker is Network Associates Chairman and CEO William
Larson.
</P>
<P>
   For $50, a walk-in attendee can traipse through the exhibition
floor, listen to the keynote speakers and catch a few of the other
talks. To catch most of the more high-powered and technical
sessions, however, costs a bit more _ between $595 and $2,700.
</P>
<P>
   The conference runs through 5 p.m. Friday. The exhibition floor
opens today at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
