<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, Sept. 14, 1999, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMERICA _ John A. Addison Jr. may sound like a television
preacher. But the exhortations by the president and chief marketing
officer of Primerica Financial Services _ delivered weekly via
satellite from Duluth, Ga., where the company is based, aren't a
gospel of salvation. They're meant to rally the company's zealous
agents, most of them part-timers, to sell more life insurance and
other financial products, to recognize top producers, and to
recruit others into the sales force. That sales force of 153,000,
including many husband-wife teams, is likely to grow next year as
the Citigroup unit expands out of North America for the first time.
Germany and Spain are the most likely beachheads. Japan, the
world's largest life insurance market, will come later. (Luke,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDSPAN _Paul Blackney is named new CEO at Worldspan, the
atlanta based travel reservations system partly owned by delta.
Blackney was a senior vp at the American Medical Association. He
replaces Mike Buchman, who left a few months back for an Internet
venture. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NETWORLD _ ATLANTA _ NetWorld+Interop hosts its ``Infrastructure
for the New Economy'' conference. Speakers include Lucent
Technologies Inc. CEO Rich McGinn and Network Associates CEO
William Larson. Sept. 13 - Sept. 17. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 0911 PLAY IT AGAIN _ Call him TiVo, the television
genie. By whatever name, he makes all of us, the couch potatoes and
the no-time-for-TV crowd, take a brand-new look at the medium and
its entertainment potential. (Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 3-column color illustration of a
genie coming out of a television set.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ A gentle touch comes in handy when opening up the
back of your computer for repairs. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 1 column color sig of
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS _ A site that lets you compose great apologies is
one of the Web's most useful sites, according to a computer
magazine. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes
1-column color photo of the cover of Yahoo! Internet Life.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET BIRTHDAY _ The Internet turns 30 this month and it's
time to reflect on the past and look ahead to the future. (Gallaga,
Austin American-Statesman) Art includes 6 pica color illustration
of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: Don't be a slave to technology; enjoy
the flowers every once in awhile. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Mavis Beacon still
Teaches Typing. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ What's new on the Web. This week: Launching a Web
site won't automatically make you a millionare. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
