<HEADER>
A0641 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-HEARST-APPOINT-HNS &LR;      09-13 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-APPOINT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST NAMES DEBRA SHRIVER AS VICE PRESIDENT FOR COMMUNICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Debra Shriver, 42, former senior vice president of
marketing communications for Hearst Magazines, on Monday was
appointed vice president and chief communications officer for The
Hearst Corporation, the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   Frank A. Bennack, Jr., president and CEO of Hearst, who
announced the appointment, said the new post was part of the
company's plan to centralize communications within its New York
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Shriver's promotion gives her responsibility for coordinating
all external and internal communications, public relations, events
and corporate advertising activities for The Hearst Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Shriver will report to Bennack, and will also continue to work
with Cathleen P. Black, president of Hearst Magazines, in
overseeing business communications and marketing efforts for the
company's magazines group, which is the world's largest publisher
of monthly magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Paul J. Luthringer, formerly executive director of marketing
communications for Hearst Magazines, has also been promoted to
executive director, corporate communications, and continues to
report to Shriver.
</P>
<P>
   Also reporting to Shriver are: Judith Bookbinder, executive
director of creative communications; and Denisha Altmann, director
of events marketing (both of whom worked for the Magazines unit,
and now assume those duties for both the Corporation and Hearst
Magazines). Patrick Phillips, manager, internal communications,
will also report to Shriver.
</P>
<P>
   Shriver joined Hearst in 1996, following two years as senior
vice president of communications for the NAA, the largest trade
group representing the $46 billion newspaper industry. Since that
time, Shriver, among other achievements, worked to launch a widely
heralded new advertising campaign for Hearst Magazines, entitled,
``We Read America,'' which features 17 of the magazine company's
editors.
</P>
<P>
   From 1989 to 1994, Shriver worked for MCI Communications
Corporation (now MCI WorldCom) as director of communications. She
created the first consumer public relations division for the
company and was responsible for all communications efforts for the
mass-market and consumer segments.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, she was director of public affairs for the Corcoran
Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C., where she was responsible for
media and public affairs for the oldest private art museum in the
United States. Before that, she was for six years a senior
associate with Ogilvy &AMP; Mather, Washington, D.C., where her clients
included AT&AMP;T, The John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts
and the French Ministry of Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Early in her career, Shriver was a newspaper reporter for
Gannett Company, Inc., and holds an M.A. in journalism, and a B.A.
in communications, both from the University of Alabama, Tuscaloosa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
