<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS14-COX     09-13 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chandler's injury makes him 'doubtful,' Reeves said
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler was in a better
mood Monday than he was last year after injuries, but his limp told
more of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler strained his right hamstring on the Falcons'
next-to-last offensive play in Sunday's 17-14 loss to the Vikings
and had to be helped from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably would be doubtful right now'' for the next game,
coach Dan Reeves said. The Falcons play Monday night in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler first strained the muscle on the back of his right leg
Aug. 25, and although he practiced the next day, he missed a
preseason game Aug. 27 at Tennessee because of it.
</P>
<P>
   Team doctor Andrew Bishop doesn't suspect a tear, and the team
did not do an MRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extra days are really going to be beneficial,'' Chandler
said. ``Doc said, `We'll see what you can do Thursday morning, and
go from there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who completed 17 of 30 passes for 258 yards and a
touchdown Sunday, said he didn't hear the muscle pop, but he felt
it. ``It felt like a knife got stuck in there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are 19-5 when Chandler starts and finishes games,
and 4-9 otherwise. On Sunday, though, the team only had one more
offensive play after his departure.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Falcons' two regular-season losses last year came
when Chandler missed a road game against the Jets with shoulder a
rib injuries. They lost 28-3 in a game that Tony Graziani started
and Steve DeBerg relieved.
</P>
<P>
   If Chandler can't play Monday, Graziani will start. The
third-year veteran lefthander has a career passer rating of 24.4 _
75 to 80 is considered good _ and his preseason rating was 53.9.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than going in the middle of the game,'' Graziani
said. ``I can get my mind ready early. I'm a lot more experienced
now. The last two games'' _ losses in 1997 and `98 _ ``I don't
think I was as ready as I could have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler is not counting himself out.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, his injury was treated with ice, electrical stimulation,
``ultrasound and just about anything they could find,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's game, wide receiver Tim Dwight strained his
right hamstring, as the Falcons continued their preseason run of
pulled muscles and strained groins.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said the problems do not result from over-training.
``It's not that,'' he said. ``I don't know what it is, because . .
. we've worked less because of the pulls and all. We've done less
conditioning. I think the heat (at training camp) had something to
do with it (as players dehydrated, and stressed their muscles).
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winklejohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
