<SLUG> BC-FBC-VOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tennessee hopes to finally slay Swamp demonBy Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ During Tennessee's 13-0 run to the national
championship in 1998, the Volunteers exorcised a lot of demons. But
they still have to slay one more monster.
</P>
<P>
   With all Tennessee has accomplished in the 1990s _ a 90-19-2
record, three SEC championships, one national championship _ it has
not won at Florida's Ben Hill Griffin Stadium, better known as the
Swamp. Four times this decade, Tennessee has marched into
Gainesville, Fla. with a team ranked eighth or better. Four times
it has lost.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 2-ranked Volunteers get their final chance to win in the
Swamp in the '90s on Saturday. The game against No. 4 Florida will
go a long way, as always, toward determining who wins the SEC East
and plays for the conference title in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, which has lost six consecutive games in Gainesville,
dating to 1971, had a breakthrough last year when it beat Florida
20-17 in overtime in Knoxville and ended the Gators' five-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   But as quarterback Tee Martin said recently, ``It's not a real
rivalry until we win down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer says he has had some talented
teams struggle in the Swamp, but he points out that the Vols have
not been alone. Since Steve Spurrier became coach 1990, the Gators
are 55-2 at home. They have a 29-game winning streak dating to
1994, when Auburn won 36-33. Florida's only other loss at home was
to Florida State's 1993 national championship team, 33-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Florida) is a difficult place to play, but no more difficult
than any of the other places we go,'' Fulmer said. ``Their stadium
is pretty much like ours when it's rocking. But the thing that
makes it tough is the caliber of players Florida puts on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tennessee's players feel any trepidation about Saturday, they
haven't shown it. The Volunteers were off last week after opening
the season with a 42-17 win over Wyoming. They say they have been
putting the time to good use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, it's been business as usual, but that's the way this
team is,'' said Martin, 14-0 as a starter. ``We know that the team
that plays the best is going to win. We know the crowd is going to
be loud, but after everything this team has gone through, we should
be able to handle things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee sees itself as a veteran team with resolve steeled by
last season's championship run, which required several
come-from-behind victories. In previous years the coaches and
players would be visibly tight during Florida week.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, for example, Fulmer took his team to Florida a
day earlier than normal with the stated intent of getting it better
acclimated to the heat. In retrospect, some said, it was another
sign of how big the game was to the Vols and another source of
anxiety for the players. Tennessee fell behind 14-0 after Tony
George returned a Peyton Manning interception 89 yards for a
touchdown, never recovered and lost 33-20.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those ideas that, if it had worked, it would
have been pretty smart,'' Fulmer said. ``But it didn't, so it
didn't look too smart.''
</P>
<P>
   But last year, things changed. Tennessee was a looser and more
confident team before the Florida game. And it showed on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think beating Florida last year and the way we finished up
the season gave this team a certain amount of confidence,'' Fulmer
said. ``That's certainly what we try to build on. We got over one
hump last year, and now we're trying to get over another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, (this team is) as good a team as we've ever taken
down there. When we're healthy, there are no apparent weaknesses.
Now, whether we're really that good remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE AT FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   _ When; where: 8 p.m. Saturday; Ben Hill Griffin Stadium,
Gainesville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: CBS.
</P>
<P>
   _ Records, rankings: Tennessee is 1-0 and No. 2 in both major
polls; Florida is 2-0 and No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   _ Series: Tennessee leads 16-12-0.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: Tennessee's Jeff Hall made a 41-yard field goal
in overtime, and the Vols won 20-17 for their first win in the
series since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   _ Story line: Tennessee has not won at Florida in its past six
trips, dating to 1971, but coach Phillip Fulmer says this team
could be the best he has taken to Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
