<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0653 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CHINESE-U.S.-BABIES-A     09-13 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-U.S.-BABIES-ART-1115(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANTS' CHILDREN ARE OFTEN SENT BACK TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She spent her days at home with her newborn son,
knowing that every day she did not work was another day without
money to pay back her $20,000 smugglers' debt. She spent her nights
awake, hushing the baby so he would not disturb her husband or the
three other restaurant workers who shared their three-room
apartment. She named the boy Henry, and for four precious months
she nursed him, even after friends warned that she would soon have
to let him go.
</P>
<P>
   On the second Thursday in July, the woman, Xiu, finally did so.
Fastening a tiny gold bracelet around his wrist, she placed her son
in the arms of a friend of a friend, who, for $1,000, agreed to
take him to China.
</P>
<P>
   Xiu's mother is raising him there now, along with the
10-year-old daughter left behind last year when Xiu joined her
husband in New York. She plans to bring Henry back when he reaches
school age. But until then, she remains here, waiting to be a
mother to her child. For weeks after Henry was shipped off, she
thought she heard him cry at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like she just gave up the baby to a complete
stranger,'' said Sara Lee, a social worker at the St. Vincent's
Hospital Chinatown Clinic, interpreting for Xiu one recent morning.
``It's really killing her. She said no words can express her
sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   Xiu's story has become increasingly common among the city's
newest Chinese immigrants. Working long hours in garment factories
for paltry pay, lacking affordable child care and the safety net of
an extended family, growing numbers of Chinese immigrant women _ a
great many of whom, like Xiu, are here illegally _ are sending
their infants back to China, according to social workers and labor
organizers who work with them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the mothers are married. Some of their pregnancies,
though not all, are planned. And many give birth knowing that soon
they too may end up sending their babies away.
</P>
<P>
   The children, U.S. citizens by birth, are usually raised by
grandparents, a practice that is customary in China, as it is in
many other parts of the world. The expectation, though hardly a
guarantee, is that the children will be summoned back when they are
old enough to begin school. It is a reunion that often comes at
considerable emotional cost to parents and children, in the opinion
of doctors and social workers.
</P>
<P>
   Their story is another example of the way families have been and
continue to be fractured by immigration. Men and women from all
over the world come to the United States, leaving children with
relatives back home until they gain a foothold in this country. And
some immigrant parents send their American children, particularly
teen-agers, to the old country, hoping to save them from troubled
city streets.
</P>
<P>
   Sending infants to the old country is not unique to the Chinese.
But social service agencies working in other immigrant communities
say that while it is not unheard of, the practice is still uncommon
and is usually limited to cases of extreme hardship. Among
Dominicans, for instance, it is generally young, single mothers who
send their children back, social workers say.
</P>
<P>
   For Chinese women, there is an additional cruel dilemma: Having
left China and its rigid one-child policy, they are finally able to
have larger families without fear of penalties or recrimination.
But as poor, illegal immigrants here, they say, they are hard
pressed to take care of their young.
</P>
<P>
   That more of these mothers are sending their babies back, people
who work with them say, reflects the tougher working and living
conditions facing Chinese immigrants today.
</P>
<P>
   With the threat of factories moving abroad and a steady supply
of cheap, illegal immigrant labor, mostly from Fujian province in
southern China, a new generation of garment sweatshops has
blossomed across the city in recent years, according to garment
workers' advocates and those who study Chinese immigration. As a
result, piece-rate wages have steadily fallen, and it is
increasingly common for garment shops to require employees to work
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people simply have no time for their children,'' said
Joanne Lum of the Chinese Staff and Workers Association, who works
with garment workers in Chinatown and the Sunset Park neighborhood
of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Since her son was sent home, Xiu has returned to work. She sews
women's pants six days a week and sends home $200 each month. At
least every other week, she calls home. Every time, her daughter,
Kei Wan, asks her to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Kei Wan's chances of coming here any time soon are slim at best,
her mother said, since she would have to be smuggled in at great
expense.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the picture Xiu had in mind when her husband
summoned her here. They had been apart for eight years _ she
raising their little girl in a small town in southern China, he
working as a cook at a Chinese restaurant in Manhattan. When Xiu
finally arrived, she brought with her little more than nervous
dreams: to work hard, save money, raise a bigger, more prosperous
family than she could imagine back home.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of months, Xiu became pregnant. And that is when she
learned of this unforeseen aspect of the immigrant trajectory.
``It's not easy,'' she said, fingering the pictures of her children
that she keeps in a plastic picture album, ``to be a mother here.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not illegal to send these American-born children to China.
They are U.S. citizens and can travel on U.S. passports; their
couriers are legal residents and so are allowed to travel back and
forth. But while social workers and others say the practice is well
known and widespread in New York's Chinese immigrant community,
that is not to say that the mothers are eager to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while workers at clinics across the city said they knew
of many cases, only a handful of mothers agreed to speak to a
reporter, and they would give only their first names. None agreed
to be photographed.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly most Chinese immigrants do not send their babies back.
They manage by staying home, imploring an elderly relative to
baby-sit or paying for child care. Day care costs at least $20 a
day in Chinatown these days _ a formidable amount for a garment
worker like Xiu, who, even in a good, six-day workweek, takes home
less than $300.
</P>
<P>
   How many women send their babies back is not known. At the
Chinatown Health Center, 10 percent to 20 percent of the babies
delivered last year were sent back, according to Celia Ng, the
nursing coordinator. And at the St. Vincent's Hospital Chinatown
clinic, according to Ms. Lee, one-third to one-half of the women
who seek prenatal care say they plan to send their children to
China.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, Ms. Lee saw a flier in the clinic
bathroom: For a fee _ the going rate these days is $1,000, plus air
fare _ someone was offering to take babies back to China.
</P>
<P>
   Around that time, she began to notice an increase in the number
of women sending their babies to China. And she made it a part of
her practice to ask all her prenatal patients what they planned to
do after giving birth.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she tells each one how painful it can be for a mother to
send an infant back _ and for a father as well, though fathers are
more likely to have been separated from their children for many
years. She explains how difficult it can be when the child finally
comes back _ but as a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine being separated from my kids,'' confessed Ms.
Lee, whose own children are 1 and 3. ``But they have a problem, no
matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, a single woman from Guangdong province, says that sending
her child home is the only way she can imagine surviving in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Just before her first child, Thomas, was born last month, Zhu,
36, gave up her job as a home health aide in Brooklyn. Since then,
she has lived on her savings, but she fears they will soon be
exhausted. So when the Lunar New Year rolls around in February,
Zhu, unmarried and alone in New York, plans to take the child to
China, where her own mother will raise him for a few years, until
Zhu can afford to have him by her side once more.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Zhu, she has a green card. She can take Thomas back
herself. From time to time, she can even visit.
</P>
<P>
   That good fortune is beyond Xiu's reach. The other day, the two
mothers sat next to each other at the St. Vincent's Hospital
Chinatown clinic _ Xiu keeping her eyes on baby Thomas, sleeping
against his mother's belly, Zhu admiring the pictures of Xiu's
children.
</P>
<P>
   They were talking of the choices they had made, and Xiu was
wiping away irrepressible tears.
</P>
<P>
   How hard it was, she said, to walk into the clinic that morning
and see babies in their mothers' arms. How hard it was, she said,
when the woman who took Henry home called to say that he had cried
incessantly on the one-and-a-half-day journey. At least, she said,
she had nursed him for the first four months of his life. She would
feel so guilty otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Would it have been easier, she wondered aloud, if she had been
younger? From across the table came a quick reply from Angel, an
immigrant from Guangdong. Five years ago, when she was only 28, her
husband chose to send their daughter back home. It wasn't any
easier, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Angel said, she felt she had no choice. She had a
good job at a photo shop in Chinatown, and her boss had agreed to
let her take a month off after the pregnancy. There was no one to
watch the baby all day, and not enough money for a baby sitter.
Barely 4 weeks old, the baby was sent away.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, when Angel managed to bring her back to New
York, the little girl seemed as miserable as her mother had been
when she sent her away. She sat on the sofa in the living room of
their apartment in Queens and cried quietly and without
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   A small, sprightly woman who looks half her age, Angel still
cries when she summons the memory. If nothing else, it has taught
her one lesson. She says she is not planning to have any more
children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
