<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0655 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-CLASSIC-PREVIEW-C     09-13 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLASSIC-PREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tenn. St. seeks end of losses to FAMU
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Florida A&AMP;M and Tennessee State meet Saturday in
the 11th annual Atlanta Classic at the Georgia Dome, the longtime
rivals will be fighting for cloth as well as for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will take home a unique flag that captures the
essence of both schools _ thus, the theme of the game: ``The Fury
for the Flag.''
</P>
<P>
   TSU third-year coach L.C. Cole's team has taken two impressive
victories over SWAC teams as it comes to town for the classic,
sponsored by 100 Black Men of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering what FAMU has done to us the last few years, it
would really be great if we could take that flag back home and hang
it up somewhere,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers have beaten the Tigers eight years in a row,
including five times in the Classic. A crowd of 51,742 watched FAMU
win 31-23 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach (Billy) Joe has a great program,'' Cole said.
``Hopefully, we've closed the gap on them going into this game.''
</P>
<P>
   In its first two games of the season, TSU knocked off Alabama
State 41-8 and defeated highly regarded Jackson State 48-33.
</P>
<P>
   FAMU last weekend reached 1-1 after doing to Norfolk State what
No. 8 Miami did to the Rattlers the week before. Behind sophomore
quarterback Quinn Gray, who took a shot to the rib cage early in
the first quarter against Miami and sat out the rest of the 57-3
loss, the Rattlers waxed their MEAC rival 56-7.
</P>
<P>
   Gray threw for 381 yards and four touchdowns against Norfolk
State.
</P>
<P>
   His primary receiver has not been often double-teamed
All-American junior Jacquay Nunnally (12 catches, 106 yards) but
senior Cainon Lamb, who had five receptions for 111 yards and a
touchdown against Norfolk. Unlike 1998, when its offense produced
Division I-AA-leading averages of 521 yards and 45.7 points per
game, FAMU's success this year might lie with its defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense is much improved,'' Joe said, noting the size,
speed and strength of his players. ``We've also got more depth than
we've had before.''
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA CLASSIC
</P>
<P>
   _ Who: Florida A&AMP;M (1-1) vs. Tennessee State (2-0).
</P>
<P>
   _ When, where: 3:30 p.m. Saturday; Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tickets: $20 and $25, available at Ticketmaster outlets and
Georgia Dome box office.
</P>
<P>
   Earnest Reese writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
