<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0660 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES14-COX     09-13 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quarterback questions put possible contenders in limbo
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Jets and Tampa Bay Bucaneers were considered
playoff contenders, but after Week 1 both teams already are
fighting for survival because of concerns at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, looking for their first trip to the Super Bowl since
1968, lost starter Vinny Testaverde for the rest of the season
after he ruptured an Achilles' tendon in their 30-28 loss to New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde, the AFC's leading passer last season who hadn't
missed a game since 1997, was injured in the second quarter.
Testaverde fell to the artificial turf after tailback Curtis Martin
fumbled and was injured with no one within five feet of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never in pain until I reached the locker room,''
Testaverde said Monday after he underwent surgery. ``It was knowing
that my season was over, and it was just frustrating for me. I will
stay positive about it and continue to support my teammates and try
to fulfill our expectations and goals for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Journeyman Rick Mirer, a No. 1 pick of the Seattle Seahawks in
1993, will take over at quarterback. tMirer joined the Jets only
three weeks ago in a trade with the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, the quarterback doesn't need to make tons of decisions
at the line, just execute plays,'' Mirer said. ``I just need to get
up to speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy isn't saying who will
start at quarterback in Sunday's contest at Philadelphia. Starter
Trent Dilfer looked like an amateur in throwing three interceptions
in the Bucs' 17-13 loss to the New York Giants. His backup, former
Georgia star Eric Zeier, also was ineffective, completing only 3 of
11 passes and throwing one interception.
</P>
<P>
   Rough start
</P>
<P>
   The expansion Cleveland Browns weren't expected to win many
games this season, but no one expected them to play that poorly in
their debut. The Browns had only two first downs and failed to
convert a third-down play in their 43-0 loss to Pittsburgh.
Cleveland, outgained 460-40, had just nine rushing yards, its
lowest output since a six-yard effort against the Giants in
November 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Rough start II
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, playing its first game under new coach Mike Holmgren,
was an eight-point favorite at home against Detroit, which lost
All-Pro tailback Barry Sanders to retirement and wideout Herman
Moore to a knee injury in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Seahawks took a nose dive under Holmgren. Quarterback
Jon Kitna was sacked on the first play _ a failed flea flicker _
and former Georgia kicker Todd Peterson missed a 32-yard field-goal
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The special teams also were abysmal, as former Georgia Tech star
Charlie Rogers fumbled a punt return at his own 5, which led to a
Detroit touchdown. Later, long-snapper Deems May sent a snap over
punter Jeff Feagles' head for a safety, giving Detroit an 18-0 lead
with nine minutes left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tops
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis left tackle Orlando Pace held Ravens defensive end
Michael McCrary without a sack and only three tackles. McCrary,
coming off knee surgery, looked out of shape and winded. . . .
Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman threw for 362 yards and a
career-high five touchdowns. . . Indianapolis left tackle Tarik
Glenn held Buffalo end Bruce Smith to only three tackles. Colts
quarterback Peyton Manning, who threw for 284 yards and two
touchdowns, wasn't sacked in 33 pass attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tops
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore linebacker Ray Lewis had 14 solo tackles and returned
an interception 60 yards. . . . Patriots defensive end Willie
McGinest took advantage of the Jets' inexperienced offensive
linemen for two sacks and a fumble recovery. . . . Giants free
safety Percy Ellsworth intercepted two of Dilfer's passes in the
fourth quarter. New York had four interceptions, including one by
rookie Andre Weathers, who returned it eight yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Truly special
</P>
<P>
   Speedy Jacksonville wide receiver Alvis Whitted beat San
Francisco's kick-return coverage and forced R.W. McQuarters to
fumble. Jaguars reserve cornerback Jason Craft scooped up the ball
and returned it 23 yards for a touchdown and a 17-3 lead in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville cornerback Fernando Bryant, a first-round draft
pick from Alabama, made his first start in the Jaguars' 41-3
blowout of the 49ers. Bryant was matched up against his boyhood
idol _ San Francisco wide receiver Jerry Rice. Bryant still has an
autographed picture of Rice, whom he held to two catches for 17
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Stat stuff
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 39 games _ a drought that extended into
November 1996 _ Dallas scored a touchdown on its opening drive.
Cowboys tight end David LaFleur capped the nine-play, 80-yard drive
with a 15-yard scoring grab.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia All-America cornerback Champ Bailey gave up a
34-yard pass to Dallas wideout Michael Irvin on his first play, but
he held Irvin in check for most of two quarters. However, Bailey
missed the final three minutes of regulation and all of overtime
with cramps. . . . The Cowboys have 20 consecutive wins when Irvin
and running back Emmitt Smith each have 100-yard games. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Dallas owner Jerry Jones says that an NFL official told him the
length of defensive tackle Leon Lett's suspension will be announced
today. ``I haven't heard what the length will be,'' said Jones, who
declined further comment. In July, the NFL announced that Lett
would be suspended indefinitely for violating the league's
substance-abuse policy for the third time since 1995. Lett is
expected to receive a suspension of at least four games. . . .
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans defensive end Brady Smith, who replaced injured star
Joe Johnson, had 2 1/2 sacks against the Panthers. . . . The
Cowboys put former Alabama star Michael Myers on the inactive list
before Sunday's game, after he fell behind Nathan Davis and rookie
Brandon Noble at defensive tackle. . . . New Dallas left tackle
Flozell ``Hotel'' Adams gave up a sack to former Georgia Tech star
Marco Coleman on the first play but blocked well on running plays.
Coleman finished with six tackles. . . . The Packers have taken the
first steps in recovering 80 percent of a $3.5-million signing
bonus to retired wideout Robert Brooks, who played just one season
of a five-year deal he signed in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The last word
</P>
<P>
   ``To list all the little things that made (Cowboys wide
receiver) Raghib Ismail's 76-yard overtime touchdown possible would
require a sheet of paper longer than the distance between (Dallas
cornerback) Kevin Mathis and the receivers he can't cover.'' _
Dallas Morning News columnist Tim Cowlishaw on Ismail's
game-winning grab in overtime in the Cowboys' 41-35 victory at
Washington
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
