<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0662 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     09-13 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WACO NEWS NO SURPRISE _ FBI LACKS RESTRAINT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His email address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(jt) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY    
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why should anyone be surprised at the inquiry into the Federal
Bureau of Investigation's role in the siege of the Branch Davidian
compound in Waco, Texas, in 1993?
</P>
<P>
   Why should anyone be surprised that the FBI and the Department
of Justice may have attempted to cover up the use of incendiary
tear gas projectiles that might have started the fire that killed
80 members of the Davidian group?
</P>
<P>
   This nation has paid a price every time Congress has granted the
FBI too much power and exercised too little oversight.
Accountability is the issue here. Congress must at least share the
blame for not reining in the enormous powers of the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has a difficult job fighting organized crime, public
corruption and terrorism aimed at Americans. One of its tasks is to
protect us from the militant radicals among us who would kill for
some political ideal. For the most part, the FBI does its job well.
For the most part, it has resisted petty corruption. But as with
any law enforcement agency, it needs strict oversight. And it needs
to be held to the legal standards required by the Constitution and
the Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Where law enforcement confronts the suspect is where
constitutional protections of the individual come into play. And a
law enforcement agency subject to little oversight is likely to
overlook the niceties of constitutional law.
</P>
<P>
   We do no favors to any law enforcement agency by not holding it
accountable. Someday the facts will come out. But the damage will
have been done. And the agency responsible for acts of lawlessness
will lose its credibility and its effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement depends upon the cooperation of the citizenry.
When citizens are too scared to cooperate or too skeptical of a law
enforcement agency, then important information may be delayed or
even lost.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the spectrum, when a law enforcement agency
is on a loose tether, it may build a tradition of ignoring the
rights of suspects -- an underground, unspoken tradition that is
all too difficult to break, as a number of major urban centers,
like Chicago and New York City, have come to realize.
</P>
<P>
   This is a nation born of dissent. It is a part of our character.
Most of us cherish this aspect of liberty. There is little doubt,
when one looks at the history of our nation, or any nation, for
that matter, that dissent is a significant part of political
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   At key junctures, movements of political and social dissent have
changed the direction of our nation, made us open to greater
diversity and helped us include segments of our society that had
been ignored, excluded, or forced into ghettos.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who saw or participated in the civil rights movement
of the 1950s and '60s know that it was essential in order to make
white Americans face their darker brothers and sisters. The
movement helped secure a semblance of equality for racial
minorities, though the battle is not over yet. Still, it was a step
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that communists had infiltrated the civil rights
movement, the FBI played a sinister role during those years,
tapping civil rights leaders' telephones, manufacturing phony
evidence against them and attempting to discredit the leaders of
that great movement. It was an out-of-control FBI run by a man who
had been in power too long, J. Edgar Hoover.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who saw or joined the `free love/free drugs`
protesters of the 1960s understood the movement as a reaction
against the straightjacket militarism and anti-communist hysteria
that had gripped our nation in the '50s. We may not have welcomed
the extremes to which the dissenters took us, but we understood it.
The FBI was there, too, taking photographs, wiretapping phone lines
and interfering with the free speech rights of demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   The political dissent of the 1970s against the Vietnam War,
whether we agreed with it or not, played an important role as a
check on our elected leaders and the nation's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental movement that began with the celebration of
the first Earth Day, April 22, 1970, was also under surveillance
and infiltrated by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Frank Church, D-Idaho, chaired a Senate committee to
probe FBI activities and found that in the mid-1970s, the FBI had
conducted a widespread campaign of monitoring and disrupting
political groups engaged in legal demonstrations and activities.
The target groups were as disparate as Vietnam protesters and the
women's liberation movement.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of our long and honorable tradition of political
dissent, the FBI conducted a massive campaign against these
dissenters: breaking into homes and offices; bugging them; placing
wiretaps on home and office phone lines; spreading misinformation
to discredit the groups; and FBI infiltrators attempted to provoke
protesters to commit illegal actions.
</P>
<P>
   The Church Committee published a six-volume report that
documented these despicable FBI's tactics. With all their
activities, the FBI produced very little evidence of criminal
conduct on the part of political protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Congress initiated a series of reforms after the Church
Committee report, but they didn't last. And congressional oversight
once again became blind.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the FBI continues to investigate Muslims, Arab-Americans,
Palestinians, environmental activists, those protesting America's
policies in South America and even members of Amnesty
International.
</P>
<P>
   The Antiterrorism Act of 1996 has made it possible for the FBI
to deport foreigners based upon secret evidence, that not even the
defendant's lawyer can see. The law has made it a criminal act to
support the humanitarian activities of selected foreign groups. And
the law has made it possible for the FBI to, once again,
investigate those who are exercising their First Amendment rights
of free speech, dissent and freedom of association.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wise for Congress to conduct an in-depth probe of
FBI activities after the independent review of the Waco disaster,
headed by former Republican Sen. John Danforth, is completed. The
FBI needs the restraint of careful oversight -- the nation needs
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
