<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-GE-ART-2TAKES-N     09-13 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-GE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GE CAPITAL ACCUMULATES $15 BILLION ASSETS IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Six years ago, GE Capital's Japanese presence consisted
chiefly of Taketo Yamakawa, a one-man show in a small office,
scrambling to come up with business opportunities in a stifled
economy.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital, the biggest and most profitable unit of General
Electric, one of America's biggest and most profitable
corporations, had just bought a Japanese credit card company that
it saw as its gateway to Asia and had put Yamakawa in charge. ``I
was struggling, trying to identify businesses and companies that GE
could do,'' Yamakawa recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, GE Capital has done plenty. Barely in the time it
has taken for Asia to begin to recover from its economic collapse,
GE Capital has gone on an acquisition binge that has solidified its
position as a global financial powerhouse, left many of its
competitors in the dust and bestowed a much-needed vote of
corporate American confidence on the ailing but now improving
region.
</P>
<P>
   The last two years alone, it has made at least eight major
investments in four Asian countries, expanding its assets to about
$20 billion in the region. Acquisitions included two
consumer-credit businesses, a life insurance company and a $5
billion leasing company in Japan, a consumer-credit business and a
portfolio of car loans in Thailand and a life insurance unit in the
Philippines. It also has its sights on a stake in a South Korean
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Though its GE parent has operated in Japan for more than a
century, GE Capital traditionally had been weak in Asia, Japan
included. So, company executives began sniffing around the region
in the early 1990s with an eye to setting up corporate alliances or
building companies from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Then the 1997 Asian financial meltdown and resulting recession
turned the area into a vast bargain basement. Here was GE Capital's
chance to buy up distressed companies and establish itself in the
one part of the world where it lacked a strong presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that financial turmoil has resulted in an
environment that facilitates deal creation,'' Denis J. Nayden,
president of GE Capital, said in a telephone interview from the
company's headquarters in Stamford, Conn. ``Yes, we have moved into
that opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, weaving those disparate businesses into the GE
corporate net has not been easy. Throughout Asia, and particularly
in Japan, culture clashes and resistance to foreign dominance have
historically curbed the market for acquisitions, and some companies
that have swooped in have crash-landed.
</P>
<P>
   But GE Capital has had a lot of practice in business
integration. Over the last 12 years, it has absorbed more than 300
companies, growing into the world's largest nonbank financial
institution, with $300 billion in assets. In the process, it has
mastered the art of identifying and acquiring underperforming
companies and using its management expertise to turn them into
moneymakers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first plums that GE Capital plucked in Japan in the
wake of the economic crisis was the consumer-finance business of
the Lake Corp. Yamakawa, who today oversees GE Capital's
consumer-finance operations in Japan, had long been impressed by
Lake's lending business but believed its expansion into real estate
and stocks was a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   As the company's financial problems worsened in late 1997,
Yamakawa pounced. Though GE Capital would not say what it paid, it
folded Lake's profitable operations _ its 2,800 people, its
computer network, its buildings and its customers _ into a new
company last year that it named the Lake Co., leaving the golf
courses and other sagging properties in the original one.
</P>
<P>
   Yamakawa then visited as many of Lake's 564 branches as he
could, often making the rounds on weekends. He centralized some of
the back-office operations and set up a call center, raising
productivity and cutting costs. Most important, he brought in
discipline _ in planning the business, budgeting for costs and
charting out both short- and long-term strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally a Japanese company does not have discipline,''
Yamakawa said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the new Lake wants to become Japan's most efficient, most
profitable consumer-finance company. Already, it is achieving
double-digit growth, using giveaway umbrellas or lottery tickets to
coax 1.5 million customers into transferring their accounts from
the old Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Lake charges 27 percent on its unsecured consumer
loans, compared with Japanese bank-deposit rates of around
three-tenths of a percent, customers are flocking to its automated
loan machines. What drives them is the ease of the transactions: If
their applications are approved, the machines spew out the cash on
the spot. Indeed, borrowers often pick up the cash in the morning
and repay in the evening at another machine.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
