<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-GE-ART-2NDTAKE-     09-13 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-GE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
TOKYO: another machine.
<TEXT>
<P>
   While GE Capital has accumulated an estimated $5 billion in
assets elsewhere in Asia, Japan is the main arena of action. Its
assets here total around $15 billion, and it has set a target of
earning $500 million a year from its Japanese operations within two
years, up from last year, though the company refuses to disclose
figures. That growth would far outpace the time it took to reach a
similar figure in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Another Japanese prize for GE Capital was a joint venture last
year with Toho Mutual Life, an ailing insurer. Basically, GE
cherry-picked the best employees and most profitable operations and
put them into a new company called GE Edison. It then sent in an
advance team headed by one of its so-called integration
specialists, Masanori Miyajima, to coach Toho Mutual executives on
the ``GE way.''
</P>
<P>
   Miyajima introduced the GE practice of using graphs and charts
in presentations and explained the principles of Six Sigma, a
statistical-control management method that GE has embraced for
achieving high quality and minimal defects in its products.
</P>
<P>
   The integration team initiated studies of Edison's problems and
ways to improve operations. It also helped draw up 90-day, one-year
and 18-month plans for restructuring the business, setting the
stage for its review process. (Typically, if an acquisition falls
short of targets for an 18-month plan, GE concludes that something
serious is wrong and reassesses the acquisition.)
</P>
<P>
   By August, GE Capital was examining how to redesign the business
practices at Edison's headquarters and at all 56 of its branches.
The old system was unwieldy: A customer seeking a benefit payment
at a branch office would fill out a form, the office would enter
the claim in its computer and then send the form by mail to the
head office, which would retype it into its computer.
</P>
<P>
   Miyajima's group transferred the claims operation to a central
location in the city of Yokohama, outside Tokyo. Now, branch
offices relay all information to the new customer care center. As a
result, said Rone Baldwin, the former president of GE Japan who now
runs GE Edison, claims are paid more quickly, productivity has shot
up 30 percent and overhead has gone down.
</P>
<P>
   Miyajima also sought to instill the more informal GE culture at
a company that had long been obsessed with protocol. He instituted
casual-dress Fridays and instructed employees to dispense with
honorifics like ``director'' for their superiors and replace them
with the simple ``Mr.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Japanese seemed to adapt to the new openness, their
American managers said they had remained vigilant. ``I find that a
larger proportion of people tend to think in hierarchical kinds of
terms,'' Baldwin said. ``People are sometimes more reluctant to
speak up or be aggressive to senior people. I have to engage them
more. I always worry about what I'm not hearing than what I'm
hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin is trying to change other Japanese habits as well, like
the practice of branch managers' greeting him at the train station
when he comes to town. He tells them he would rather they stay in
the office and work, and his campaign has apparently paid off. A
regional manager in Osaka drew cheers from the other participants
at a strategy meeting not long ago when he turned to him and said:
``Baldwin-san, please understand if I don't escort you back to the
train station. I'd rather use the time to work on my strategy
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a small but significant triumph in GE Capital's effort to
instill a global GE culture wherever it goes. Daniel H. Mudd,
president of GE Capital Japan, says that driving home its core
concepts across its global empire is a key engine for the company's
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some companies have a very strong financial system that
regulates and governs what they do, and some companies have a very
strong marketing orientation: Coca-Cola, American Express,'' Mudd
said. ``My own view is that the way GE uses its levers is with
culture, the business culture. It's not national culture. It's not
an American culture, not an Anglo-Saxon culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is taking that set of values and keeping their
meaning the same, but adapting the interpretation to work in
different countries,'' he added. ``We want employees to intuitively
share and understand a set of values and that GE culture, whether
they're in Mexico, Japan, Spain or the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, of course, the GE way can seem downright bizarre to
the American company's new Japanese employees. A few months ago, GE
Capital held one of its signature let-your-hair-down workout
sessions at Japan Leasing, which it acquired late last year for $5
billion. These discussions, aimed at breaking apart a business and
drawing up new approaches that focus on the customer, have been a
successful tool for integrating Asian businesses into the company,
and in this case they led to fiery debate, with sheets of paper
covered with captions and colored ink pasted up around the room.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese rarely air their dirty laundry in public, so it was a
bit intimidating for Japan Leasing's managers to be summoned to an
open forum to discuss what was wrong and how to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language of the workout is very new to Japan, and the
discussion style is also new to Japanese,'' said Kohei Tanaka,
president of the new Japan Leasing. ``When we gave notice to people
to please join the workout, people thought, `What the heck is this
thing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Now employees regularly try to break apart the business to find
new solutions, and these organized debating sessions are becoming a
way of life at Japan Leasing. That is a departure from the old
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan, we understand each others' intention, even without
saying anything,'' Tanaka said. ``All employees join the company at
the same time in April and midcareer employees are not common. It's
a homogeneous culture. The culture is to expect without saying
anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
