<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LIFE FOR OLD MILES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn.)   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Feeney of New Canaan, Conn., is a frequent flier devotee.
Or more correctly, a frequent buyer obsessive. Feeney, who works in
financial data, says he buys almost nothing if he cannot get
frequent flier-buyer or guest points on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a requirement for the colleges my daughter is considering
that they allow payment with a Visa card,'' he said. ``Fortunately,
I guess, that seems to let out most of the Ivy League.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So there have been things for him to think about of late. Last
month, United, American and Delta eased up on rules governing the
expiration of accumulated miles. They will now maintain miles in an
account if they see virtually any evidence the participant is still
using the account. At Continental, Northwest and US Airways, miles
did not expire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American started the ball rolling the first week in August by
saying that miles would no longer expire for its members so long as
they earned or redeemed a mile every 36 months. But pre-1996 miles
that have expired remained gone. The airline explained its policies
at www.aaa.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   United, the giant among frequent-flier programs, came along Aug.
10 and went one step better. Many United participants saw miles go
up in smoke with the report that covered Jan. 1, 1999, when
accumulations from 1995 were wiped out. United said that even these
could be restored if participants took two steps. First, they need
to register at offers.mileageplus.com/mpw049h or by calling (800)
645-4502 and entering promotion code 49. The second step, after
registration, is to take two paid domestic round trips or one paid
international trip before Dec. 31. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, United said, no post-1995 miles will expire
provided the member registers activity on the account every 36
months: takes a United trip or redeems miles or earns miles through
United partners, and they include resorts, hotels, long-distance
telephone services, car rental companies and all the rest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delta, whose miles did not expire provided the member took a
Delta flight every 36 months, joined the parade Aug. 26, saying any
activity at all would preserve miles. ``Buy a house,'' said John
Kennedy, a spokesman. ``Use a co-branded credit card. Make a phone
call.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the airlines had changed their minds, Randy Petersen,
editor of Inside Flyer, said that more than half of the miles
earned today come from activities other than flying; frequent
buyer, he said, was probably a more accurate description than
frequent flier.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines have to look at these miles as prepaid seats,''
he said. ``And also they have been feeling pressure from their
partners.'' In still another change, American Express announced in
July that Membership Rewards points could now be cashed for cash.
In this step, 20,000 points can be redeemed for $100 up to three
times a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One peculiar annoyance has emerged, but it may not emerge a lot
further. Feeney, who's sharp-eyed on taxes, noted an extra federal
tax of 36 cents on the charge for a car he rented from Hertz in
Fort Myers, Fla., last year. He wrote to this department about it
in April 1998, saying that the blip represented a pass-along of the
7.5 percent federal tax on Hertz for buying frequent flier miles to
award Feeney and other free-trip devotees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The federal tax became effective in October 1997. Soon after its
inception, some experts predicted that frequent flier programs
might be taxed to death or abandoned. But nothing of the kind has
happened and the tax, while annoying, is minimal because it is
based on the amount the partner companies, like Hertz, pay the
airlines for the miles and that is pennies a mile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hertz, according to a spokeswoman, Lauren Garvey, began passing
the tax along to renters right away. Other companies joined later;
some, like Avis, are still swallowing the tax, while keeping an eye
on the situation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere down the line, if Feeney shifts into an airline
account some of the mileage he is earning from MCI at the rapid
rate of five miles to the dollar, he will again meet the federal
excise tax. MCI Worldcom began passing it along in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Claire Hassett, an MCI spokeswoman, said her company bundled
this tax with other federal taxes on the bill, and for three months
has been inserting a notice about it into its bills. Ms. Hassett
also said MCI found the tax distasteful. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The federal tax throws into the spotlight the complex frequent
flier links among hotels, car rental companies, airlines and credit
card companies. As an example, Hertz, the biggest car rental
company, has 11 airline partners: Alaska, American, Continental,
Delta, Hawaiian, Midwest Express, Northwest, Southwest, TWA, United
and US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   These lines, in turn, have partnerships with foreign airlines on
which it may be possible to earn further miles or just take an
awards trip. Hertz, like everyone else, negotiates a price for
miles from each line, possibly 1.5 to 2 cents a mile, although no
one will state the price. It then must award the miles under the
rules set by the airlines.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rules vary according to whether the renter is a commercial
company or a private person. Although in days gone by Hertz awarded
500 miles per rental, its rate for private people is now generally
two miles to the dollar spent. But American Airlines' agreement
with Hertz holds this to one mile to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   For the Northwest program, Hertz awards 50 miles per rental day.
Except for American and Northwest, the airlines all require that
the car rental be booked in conjunction with a flight on their
lines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garvey of Hertz said that since June 1998 the federal
frequentflier tax has been passed along to individual customers at
the rate of 11 cents to every $50 spent on a mileage-earning
rental. That is, a renter earning 100 miles finds an added tax of
11 cents along with the array of other taxes and charges. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dollar Rent-A-Car, according to Emily Gill, a spokeswoman, adds
the 50 cents as a ``frequent flier tax recovery surcharge'' to each
rental involving mileage. Dollar has partnerships with America
West, American, Continental, Delta, Northwest, TWA and United. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Express, whose Membership Rewards program is linked to
Continental, Delta, Southwest, TWA and US Airways as well as Virgin
Atlantic, Cathay Pacific and other overseas lines, is not passing
the sales tax along to card holders ``for now,'' although Judy
Tenzer, a spokeswoman, said that the organization was keeping its
eye on the issue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the new Starwood Preferred Guest program, according to
Hoyt Harper, a spokesman, does not intend to pass the tax along
when points earned at Westins and other hotels in the group are
turned into airline miles. This program is linked to seven domestic
airlines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Petersen of Inside Flyer said he did not expect any hotel
program to start passing along the tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hotels have been very attached to their frequent guest
programs,'' Petersen said, adding that they did not want to
alienate their loyal visitors. Hertz, he pointed out, dropped out
of frequent flier programs at one point, but discovered it was
worth the cost to keep the customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
