<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING THE NET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOR WOMEN ON THE GO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.women.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women who travel, whether alone or not, can find a wealth of
travel information here, along with much other advice not related
to taking trips.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the featured journeys were value vacations (``20
Affordable Trips for Your Family'') and Pacific Rim romances
(``Honeymoon Hot Spots in Tahiti''). Other suggested trips included
Paris, three-day weekends in five United States cities, and cruises
to the Galapagos and Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   You can search for vacation ideas by region and activity. There
are also the usual resources, like a foreign-currency calculator
and a newsletter, but you can't book rooms or seats.
</P>
<P>
   The site's travel expert, Leslie Martin, answers questions. One
woman asked for suggestions for a place where it would be ``both
fun and safe to travel alone.'' Ms. Martin liked Bali: ``The
Balinese men are gracious and respectful, and because of the
island's popularity with travelers _ especially Australians _
you'll find English speakers just about everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the travel section, women.com has 19 ``channels,'' from
careers to weddings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FINDING A HOTEL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.expedia.com &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.hoteldiscount.com &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.usahotelguide.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can't reserve a hotel room or airline seat at the women's
Web site, but there are innumerable other places where you can do
both. If you are a fan of Expedia, Travelocity, Priceline or
whatever, my advice is to stick with it. They change constantly
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   This month, for example, Expedia enhanced its hotel price
matcher. You enter the price you want to pay for the class of hotel
in a city you want to visit and if Expedia can find it, you are
immediately booked.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not committed to such a site, however, two that
specialize in hotel accommodations are hoteldiscount and
usahotelguide. Hoteldiscount lists rooms in 38 cities worldwide _
there were 48 hotels in London alone _ at more than 1,500
properties, at less than list prices, as the name implies. At the
Kensington Hilton in London, a room for two adults was going for
$249.95 a night; a similar room cost $353 a night on Hilton's Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Usahotelguide adds detailed property and rate information _
including discounts _ for 30,000 hotels and resorts worldwide, and
its site was revised last month to simplify things. Indeed, the
service was as smooth to operate as any travel site I have tried.
You can check for Internet specials, as well as senior citizen,
AAA, and other discounts. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AIR DISCOUNTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.travelzoo.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is fairly well known that airlines offer deep discounts at
their Web sites, but it is not well known that they sometimes
withhold these low fares from the standard online booking services.
Travelzoo _ what a name _ searches more than 20 airline sites for
these discounts, and posts them so you don't have to spend hours
searching.
</P>
<P>
   The first time you enter the zoo, you are asked to list your
first name, ZIP code, nearest airport and, optionally, e-mail
address. But you can use the service without going through all
that. There were two New York-London round-trip flights when I
looked, one at $355, the other at $497. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
