<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0675 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV19-NY     09-13 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OH ZONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 19)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
Jack Rosenthal is editor in chief of The New York Times Magazine.
He has been a vacation pinch-hitter for William Safire since, ah,
the early '80s. 
 By JACK ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word of the '90s is probably  &UR; millennium &LR; . It has not always
been spelled correctly (n.b. Maidenform's Millenium undergarments).
But the Western world is devoting energetic attention to the event,
about 100 days hence, when three historic zeros click into place.
Meanwhile, a practical problem remains concerning the first word of
the next decade: what to call it.
</P>
<P>
   The '90s can be characterized in many ways _ a decade of
unimaginable American wealth, perhaps, or of Balkan savagery or of
China's steady emergence. But whatever the label, the '90s have a
name, just like the '80s that came before. The decade that comes
after still does not, so here's a formal nomination:  &UR; the '00s &LR; ,
pronounced the Ohs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The '00s &LR;  is, for one thing, numerically logical. For another,
the rival possibilities fall short.  &UR; The Aughties &LR; , for example, is
how people referred to the first decade of this century. Today,
that clanks quaintly, evoking a world of corsets and hot-water
bottles.  &UR; The Zeroes &LR; ? That's disfigured for older Americans: To
them, it refers to Japanese fighter planes in World War II.  &UR; The
Oh-Ohs &LR; ? Too timid, implying a fearful anticipation of danger
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Ohs &LR; , by contrast, conveys a positive expectation of wonder
and surprise. In that spirit, let me urge its adoption, if not by
acclamation then at least by usage.
</P>
<P>
   The new edition of The New York Times Manual of Style and Usage,
due out next month from Times Books, is silent on the subject.
Allan M. Siegal, The Times' style czar and the manual's co-author,
with William G. Connolly, wishes to wait and see how popular usage
develops. In other words, all who concur in ``the Ohs'' would do
well to vote early and often. The more people there are who start
using the term, the sooner it will win the respect it is, well,
owed.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDS RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   For most of its life as America's national language, English was
governed by writing. The only way to communicate across distance,
after all, was by books, periodicals or letters. And written
language meant formal language. The people doing the writing were
likely to be educated, perhaps even inclined to flaunt their
education hypercorrectively _ grammarians vs. vulgarians.
</P>
<P>
   So pronounced was this formal dominance of written English that
it endured long after the telephone, radio, talkies and television
spread the spoken word across the land. Many people still recoil
from colloquialisms and contractions that pass comfortably in
speech. The times, however, they are a-changin'. The dominant form
of English is now oral, largely as spoken on TV. And even that's a
moving target.
</P>
<P>
   Not many years ago, the sentences delivered by orotund
newscasters were read from scripts edited by skilled journalists
like Gilbert Millstein, once an editor at The New York Times
Magazine. Indeed, some broadcasters depended so totally on scripts
that they were caricatured by, for instance, the vacuous Ted Baxter
on ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Television, meanwhile, was changing, in a way that caused the
spoken language to trump writing in another way. ``Now,'' says Tom
Brokaw of NBC, ``there's so much more spontaneity that people don't
write scripts any more. They're encouraged to be good at the `live
pop''' at the scene. And at times like the John F. Kennedy Jr.
plane crash, the TV anchors have to extemporize for hours.
</P>
<P>
   With the profusion of mass media, TV and movies started trumping
the written language in yet another way, as entertainment English
has increasingly overshadowed newscast English. It may have started
with ``Beavis and Butt-head,'' ``The Simpsons'' and ``Seinfeld'' on
television and ``Wayne's World'' and ``Clueless'' on the big
screen. They spread colloquialisms ( &UR; as if &LR; ,  &UR; whatever &LR; ,  &UR; yadda
yadda &LR; ) and vulgarities ( &UR; kick butt &LR; ,  &UR; bastard &LR; ,  &UR; shagged &LR; ) from
locker room to living room.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the latest turn, informal spoken English has infected
the newest form of writing. Hardly anyone using e-mail bothers with
capital letters or complete sentences, let alone grammar. And why
should anyone? E-mail is not only instantaneous but friction-free;
the faster you can type what's on your mind, the better.
</P>
<P>
   Is there still hope, given such inroads, for maintaining
standards for written English? The New York Times works at it
daily; the forthcoming stylebook testifies to a determination to
preserve rules while avoiding rigidity.
</P>
<P>
   That task is harder than it used to be; there's reason to
believe that written English is not taught as widely or as well as
in the past. Fewer and fewer people understand the difference
between  &UR; like &LR;  and  &UR; as &LR; ,  &UR; which &LR;  and  &UR; that &LR; , let alone when to use
the subjunctive. Preserving rules is no mere stuffy exercise.
Writing freezes thought. Maintaining standards minimizes
misunderstanding. Even something that sounds right can write wrong.
</P>
<P>
   FRIENDLY ANTS
</P>
<P>
   Just how easily verbal misunderstandings can blossom is
demonstrated by what William Safire calls ``mondegreens'' (from the
folk-song lyric ``and laid him on the green,'' once misheard as
``Lady Mondegreen''). My long-time favorite was how a little boy in
Lynn, Mass., when called on to describe the Heimlich maneuver,
spoke of the ``Time-Life remover.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, mondegreens have so proliferated that they have been
collected on a Web site (kissthisguy.com). At last count, there
were 1,783, including patriotic gems like ``Oh beautiful for
spaceship guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone listening to ``Michael, row the boat ashore'' thought
the singer was saying, ``My goat knows the bowling score.'' To
someone else, the folk lyric ``Parsley, sage, rosemary and thyme''
said, ``Parsnips say Rosemary is blind.'' More than one contributor
told of hearing Bob Dylan sing about the answer blowing in the
wind, but thought he was declaring, perhaps a bit oddly, that ``the
ants are my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, overwhelmed, is now temporarily closed to new
submissions, but here's one for the reopening, drawn from Marlene
Dietrich's unforgettable, slightly slurred rendering of ``Falling
in Love Again,'' in which she reports that ``men cluster to me like
moths around a flame.'' It's even more memorable when heard as
``... matzoh balls in flame.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all mishearings are so dramatic, but neither can all
misunderstandings be laughed off so easily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
