<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAW CLOSER TO ACCEPTING CONTRACTS WITH 2 AUTOMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ With the auto industry fat and happy, and both labor
and management eager to keep it that way, the United Automobile
Workers union has moved closer to agreeing to new labor contracts
with both DaimlerChrysler and the General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The auto industry's three-year labor contracts covering nearly
400,000 factory workers expire at midnight Tuesday, and with that
deadline fast approaching, talks between the union and the two
companies continued through the weekend and Monday. If no deal is
reached Tuesday, the union is likely to extend the talks rather
than call a strike, labor experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a last-minute snag, a deal is expected first at
DaimlerChrysler, which is further along in bargaining with the
union. Once the union reaches a deal with one automaker, it is
expected to follow its custom of pressuring the other two
automakers to accept the same terms. The deal is expected to
include hefty wage gains for workers, labor experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen significant wage gains since the mid-1970s,''
said David L. Gregory, a labor law professor at St. John's
University School of Law in New York. He expects raises of perhaps
4 percent for each year of the contract. ``The companies can well
afford it,'' he said, given their recent record profits.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, unions might accept lower raises in exchange for
increases in other benefits, like beefed-up pension packages,
additional time off, or better job security.
</P>
<P>
   The auto industry is racking up record sales this year, on track
to eclipse a mark set in 1986 of sales of 16.03 million vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The German automaker is viewed as the front-runner because
Stephen P. Yokich, the union's president, attended negotiations at
the company's American headquarters in suburban Detroit this
weekend and Monday, along with his key lieutenants. If a deal were
reached first at DaimlerChrysler, ratification could take as few as
10 days, with the union then trying to reach a similar agreement
with General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler all said talks
continued Monday, but refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The union has been conducting simultaneous negotiations with
DaimlerChrysler and with GM for more than a week. Talks continued
at the Ford Motor Co., but at a more leisurely pace: There were no
talks at Ford this weekend or last weekend, while talks were held
then at GM and DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   That is a turnabout for GM and for Ford. GM has traditionally
had the most contentious relationship with the union, but has
sought to mend fences since a strike last year cost it $2 billion.
Ford has had particularly smooth labor relations for the past
decade, and has reached a deal first with the union in the past two
sets of talks. But this year, tension arose because of Ford's
ongoing attempts to sell its Visteon auto parts unit. Ford auto
parts workers worry that a separate company might someday try to
pay lower wages.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, however, the Canadian Auto Workers union chose Ford
as its ``target'' company, and plans to try to reach a deal first
with Ford, then force GM and DaimlerChrysler to agree to those
terms. Labor contracts in Canada expire Sept. 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WACO14-COX     09-13 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWLY RELEASED WACO DOCUMENTS MAY INDICATE COVERUP
 &HT;    BY REBECCA CARR AND JENA HEATH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New documents released Monday show that the Justice
Department admitted four years ago that federal agents used
flammable devices in the fiery 1993 siege of the Branch Davidian
compound near Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That revelation from the ranking Democrat on the House
Government Reform Committee is seen as important because top
congressional Republicans have accused Attorney General Janet Reno
of ``covering up'' the use of combustible tear gas canisters during
the raid and they have demanded her resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a cover-up about what was in these documents, you
could say that the Congress was covering up these documents just as
much as the attorney general was covering up the documents,'' said
Rep. Henry Waxman (D-Calif.), whose staff found the documents
during a search of the committee archives last Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Democrats attempted to gain ground with those
documents, new evidence released by the Texas Rangers indicates
there will be more questions coming about the 51-day raid that left
80 people dead, some two dozen of them children.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers released a 13-page report to Congress stating
that more than a dozen spent rifle cartridges of a type used by
professional snipers were recovered from a house used by both the
FBI and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms during the
raid.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has denied firing shots from the house. ATF has admitted
shooting from the house during its initial gun battle with Branch
Davidian Leader David Koresh and his followers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the shell casings came from ATF agents or FBI agents,
``We don't know,'' an ATF spokesperson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers report stated that a dozen .308-caliber
casings, two dozen Israeli manufactured .223-caliber casings, and
one 22.250 casing were recovered at the house used by the FBI's
hostage rescue team during the stand off.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the Justice Department were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to both developments, Republicans hotly disputed
Waxman's characterization of a ``cover-up'' and they vowed a
vigorous investigation of Texas Rangers' report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that Henry Waxman chose partisan attacks over
a serious attempt to get at the facts,'' said Mark Corallo,
spokesperson for Rep. Dan Burton (R-Ind.), chairman of the
committee, referring to Waxman's documents.
</P>
<P>
   Burton was not the chairman when the Justice Department turned
over evidence to Congress some three days before the 1995
Government Reform hearings into the raid, Corallo said. It would be
understandable to overlook the five examples of using incendiary
devices amidst the 100,000 pages turned over to the committee, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing more outlandish than Mr. Waxman's assertion
that the Government Reform Committee somehow covered up evidence is
the fact his accusations are given any credence by the media,''
said Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), a member of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has admitted launching combustible tear gas canisters
into a concrete bunker near the compound last month, but the agency
still maintains that it did not ignite the deadly fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Waxman is looking for anyone to blame for an incomplete
investigation in 1995, he need go no further than his own
colleagues who obstructed the process in the first place,'' Barr
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Texas Rangers discovery, Republicans said that it
would be a top priority in their investigation. The finding has
also been turned over to former Sen. John Danforth (R-Mo.) who is
leading an independent inquiry into the FBI's role in the deadly
fire at the compound.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers report also found that sound and flash cells,
often used to create diversions in hostage rescues, were used the
final day of the siege. But they may not have been altered to
ensure they started a fire, as some critics of the government have
alleged.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
