<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0685 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CHICAGO-DELAYS     09-13 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CHICAGO-DELAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K? O'HARE WANTS TO FORGET 1999  

</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It has direct flights to everywhere from Tokyo to
Fargo, and its amenities include automated antiseptic toilet seats,
but O'Hare International Airport here has not had a very good year.
</P>
<P>
   Extraordinary flight delays have plagued O'Hare for months now,
and passengers are understandably disgruntled. The Federal Aviation
Administration reported recently that in the first five months of
1999, 23,141 O'Hare flights were delayed or canceled, nearly double
the 11,646 flights during the same period in 1998. Passenger
complaints against airlines have nearly doubled, too _to 6,582 this
year, from 3,681 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The situation got so bad that in mid-August, the two airlines
that run the most flights out of O'Hare decided they needed to take
steps to pacify customers.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, which is based in Chicago and accounts for 40
percent of O'Hare's air traffic, sent letters of apology to the
970,000 members of its Mileage Plus Premiere program _ coupled with
a bonus of 2,500 frequent flier miles. In the first six months of
1999, United had to cancel or delay 4,677 flights at O'Hare because
of weather and air traffic control problems.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines, which canceled or delayed 2,645 flights in
the first six months of the year, has sent mea culpa letters to its
frequent fliers on those flights. American's planes make up about a
third of the flights at O'Hare, which is the only airport in the
country that is a hub for two major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Airports across the country have been saddled with delays, due
in part to weather, the installation of new air traffic control
equipment and record numbers of passengers _ 614 million in 1998,
up from 275 million when deregulation began 20 years earlier. But
the problems at O'Hare, the world's busiest airport when measured
by takeoffs and landings, have been worse than those at other major
airports.
</P>
<P>
   FAA statistics show that O'Hare's records for on-time arrivals
and departures during the first six months of this year were either
the worst or the second worst (behind either Boston or Newark) of
the nation's 29 biggest airports.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1988, O'Hare had the moniker of being the airport with the
most delays in the country,'' Mary Rose Loney, Chicago's aviation
commissioner, said. ``Over 10 years, we achieved a 40 percent
reduction in delays. We've worked hard to be that efficient, only
to see that erode in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Loney has been so troubled by the situation that in early
August she wrote to Jane Garvey, the FAA administrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is alarming that Chicago is experiencing a perplexing
amount of air traffic delay during the first half of 1999, beyond
those attributable to thunderstorms and this past winter's snow
events,'' Ms. Loney wrote. ``Some delays are related to the process
of replacing older radar systems with new air traffic control
equipment. But peak-hour flight schedules have not changed to a
degree that might warrant such an increase in delays.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Loney said in an interview that airline officials had told
her that part of the problem was a result of local air traffic
controllers, apparently uncomfortable with new equipment,
instructing planes to fly farther apart than the minimum required
distance _ 5.68 miles at altitudes above 18,000 feet. Other
preventable delays might have been due to the F.A.A.'s holding
planes on the ground longer than necessary, she said _ well beyond
the duration of a thunderstorm, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA did not respond directly to Ms. Loney's letter, but some
of her concerns may be allayed by changes that the FAA announced on
Aug. 12, which would affect airports nationwide. They include
examining and trying to minimize the number and duration of
``ground stops'' (when planes are held on the ground) and trying to
limit orders for extra flying space between planes.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA also said it would seek more consistency in decision
making by centralizing air traffic control authority in its
national command center in Herndon, Va., instead of allowing local
air traffic control centers to act independently.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, the FAA also plans to install new software to
modernize air traffic control systems in Chicago and elsewhere,
said an agency spokesman, Eliot Brenner.
</P>
<P>
   The delays have fueled the longstanding arguments by some state
officials and members of Congress that Chicago build a third
airport (Chicago's second airport, Midway, which is smaller and
situated south of downtown, had 1,195 flights delayed in the first
five months of 1999, compared with 499 for the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But city officials oppose a third airport, partly because so
many passengers who fly into Chicago would need to make connections
out of O'Hare anyway, and because the increase in delays, Ms. Loney
said, was not caused by lack of runways or airport capacity.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, travelers might be smart to book flights that
arrive or depart before noon or after 11 p.m., the hours with the
fewest delays, FAA statistics show. Passengers flying between 5
p.m. and 11 p.m. are the most likely to be kept waiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
