A0687 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV19-     09-13 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 19)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Champs-Elysees as Sculpture Garden
</P>
<P>
   The Champs-Elysees is the backdrop for monumental sculptures by
50 contemporary artists through Nov. 14. Artists from five
continents are participating in the second edition of Les Champs de
la Sculpture, a free event showcasing work created since 1970 and
serving as an international fin de siecle follow-up to a 1996
exhibition of European art on the Champs-Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   The French artist Daniel Buren is creating the show's largest
work: a giant rainbow of flags extending from the Place de la
Concorde to the Arc de Triomphe. Palestinian and Israeli flags are
draped over an olive tree in ``Sukat Shalom'' (``Peace Cabin''),
designed by the Tel Aviv-based artist Dani Karavan. Wind generated
by rushing traffic helps levitate a silver Kevlar sphere in a
fountain created by Manolis Maridakis of Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Images run the gamut from tribal to techno. Sokari Douglas Camp
of Nigeria draws on traditional Yoruba costume for her mixed-media
``Sword Fish Masquerade.'' Nam June Paik, the Korean-born artist,
features 12 blaring television sets in an installation that he
describes as a counterattack against the televised image.
</P>
<P>
   Others include Cuba's Kcho, one of the stars of the recent
Venice Biennale, whose ``Columnar Infinida'' stacks a series of
flat-bottom Loire boats atop each other, and the Americans George
Segal, Jessica Stockholder and Red Grooms, who is sending an
aluminum and enamel ``Hot Dog Vendor'' to the Paris show.
</P>
<P>
   New Baby Seats on British Airways
</P>
<P>
   British Airways offers bulkhead infant seats for children
younger than 2 who are too active for the line's bulkhead cots.
Twelve of these seats can be used on each Boeing 747 long-distance
flight; they are available in economy class by reservation. There
is no charge beyond the regular trans-Atlantic fare for children
under 2, which is 10 percent of the applicable fare.
</P>
<P>
   These seats, manufactured by Britax, allow infants to see their
parents. The seats can be adjusted from horizontal to upright; in
the cots, the infants lie flat.
</P>
<P>
   The airline's director of marketing, Martin George, said that
passengers had asked for some way to hold larger infants other than
on a parent's knees for a whole flight, without having to pay a
full child's ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Children still must be held on laps for takeoff and landing.
Parents who wish children under 2 to be restrained in a true safety
belt for takeoff and landing, as safety experts recommend, must buy
the child a ticket and take along a seat approved by the government
for use in an airplane. On British Airways, such a ticket costs 75
percent of the adult's economy-class ticket or 50 percent of a
business- or first-class ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Four Seasons Opens First Mexican Resort
</P>
<P>
   Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts is in the midst of a growth
spurt. On Sept. 1, the company opened a resort in Punta Mita,
Mexico, the second of six openings of new or renovated hotels
scheduled for this year. It opened the Four Seasons Hotel Las Vegas
in March and plans by the end of the year to unveil a renovation of
the George V in Paris, and new properties in Cairo, Egypt;
Scottsdale, Ariz.; and London
</P>
<P>
   The Punta Mita resort, the company's first in Mexico, has opened
with 100 rooms overlooking the Pacific about 30 miles northwest of
Puerto Vallarta; 40 more are to open next year. It includes a golf
course designed by Jack Nicklaus that has an unusual optional third
hole with an island green 194 yards into the Pacific. The green is
reached by a stone path at low tide and by six-wheel amphibious
vehicle at other times.
</P>
<P>
   Guest rooms and suites are in 13 Mexican-style casitas, with
ocean views from balconies or terraces. There is a beach, pool,
fitness center and spa, and four lighted tennis courts.
</P>
<P>
   Standard rates are $350 to $475 a room, double occupancy, and
$500 to $2,200 for suites, plus 17 percent tax. An introductory
package is $275 a night, double occupancy, for three nights, with a
fourth night free, until Dec. 17. For reservations, call (800)
332-3442. Greens fees are $125 for guests and $180 for others with
a letter to Sam Logan, the golf director, on club letterhead
attesting to membership in a golf club.
</P>
<P>
   A Museum That Is at Home on the Range
</P>
<P>
   The image of the cowboy evokes that unruly and romanticized time
when westward expansion offered the promise of fortune, and danger
at every turn. The National Cowboy Hall of Fame and Western
Heritage Center in Oklahoma City has declared this the year of the
cowboy, since the museum has opened three new permanent exhibitions
about cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity Junction, the first of the new exhibitions that
visitors encounter, is a 13,500-square-foot re-creation of a
19th-century cattle town at dusk. It is an attempt to capture the
mood and structure of pioneer life with a livery stable, saddle
shop, train depot, cattle company, photography studio, bank,
marshal's office, saloon, school house and church.
</P>
<P>
   Next is the American Cowboy Gallery, focusing on the people who
worked the ranges and the ranches. The gallery showcases the tools
(cattle brands, saddles, spurs), clothing, techniques and
traditions of ranching culture and tells the story of some of the
best-known cattle trails and ranches. The gallery explores the
diversity of cowboy culture, looking at vaqueros, women,
African-Americans and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   In the last of the new exhibitions, the American Rodeo Gallery,
patrons can sit in bleacher seats to watch vintage rodeo footage
and listen to a brief history of the sport. Kiosks display
biographies of all Rodeo Hall of Fame members and presentations on
women in rodeo, rodeo clowns and the sport's various events. A
trophy room houses some of rodeo's most coveted awards.
</P>
<P>
   The National Cowboy Hall of Fame is open daily. Admission is
$8.50, $7 for those over 62, $4 for children 6 to 12 and free for
those under 6. Information: (405) 478-2250.
</P>
</TEXT>
