<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-TIMOR-RDP-ART-NYT &LR;      09-13 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TIMOR-RDP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. SAYS INDONESIA HAS AGREED TO INQUIRY INTO EAST TIMOR
ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add map note)  (ART ADV:  Locator map  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ With reports of killings and forced
deportations continuing to emerge from East Timor on Monday,
President B.J. Habibie of Indonesia agreed to the creation of an
international commission to investigate possible atrocities there,
the U.N. High Commissioner for Human Rights, Mary Robinson, said.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with him Monday, Robinson said Habibie had
accepted her proposal for Indonesian and foreign officials to join
in ``a commission of inquiry, a commission of experts to look at
the evidence of human rights violations.''
</P>
<P>
   This concession to concerns about Indonesian abuses came the day
after Habibie bowed to international pressure and agreed to the
deployment of a U.N. peacekeeping force in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   A nationalist backlash has begun to grow here already, which
could complicate the deployment of the peacekeeping force and, if
it intensifies, weaken Habibie's hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   An inquiry into human rights abuses could lead to the creation
of a war crimes tribunal similar to those investigating abuses in
Rwanda and the Balkans, Robinson said. ``It may be, in due course,
the question of a tribunal,'' she said. ``I have heard many
accounts that name names.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan hinted at the
possibility of war crimes trials for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   In a blow to Indonesia's national pride, East Timor, a former
Portuguese colony, chose overwhelmingly two weeks ago to become
independent of the nation that has occupied it since 1975 at the
cost of some 200,000 lives. The referendum was organized by the
United Nations, fueling conspiracy theories here about the
intention of foreigners to break Indonesia apart.
</P>
<P>
   Since the results of the vote were announced, irregular militias
backed by the military have reportedly killed hundreds or even
thousands of people and have caused as many as 300,000 people from
the territory of 800,000 people to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
   No amount of foreign pressure seems to have slowed the rampage
of the militias, and with the killings reportedly continuing, and
with tens of thousands of refugees facing starvation in the barren
hills, where many are hiding, concerns grew here over possible
delays in deploying the force.
</P>
<P>
   In this interim period, aid workers and diplomats said, the
militias could carry out a final cleansing of their enemies and
huge numbers of people could begin to starve.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds of thousands of refugees in various parts
of East Timor clustered in mountains without adequate food or with
no food at all, living on roots, living on whatever they can
scavenge'' a U.N. spokesman, David Wimhurst, said in Darwin,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   In the streets of East Timor's capital, Dili, witnesses said
scavengers were picking through the ruins of burned and vandalized
buildings in search of food, water and other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   In a message from a remote stronghold of guerrillas who support
independence, a senior commander, Tuar Matan Ruak, sent a message
pleading for aid for refugees who have gathered there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have milk for the children _ this is a serious
problem,'' he said. ``In the small villages, the fires are the same
as Dili or even worse _ total chaos. The population has no help, no
protection, no food, no water and no medical supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing to the international force on Sunday, Habibie said:
``We cannot wait any longer. We have to stop the suffering and
mourning now.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister John Moore of Australia, which is leading the
planned force, said it's members could begin arriving within three
to five days of approval in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But both Indonesian officials and street protesters here,
seeking a voice in this extraordinary compromise of national
sovereignty, have begun demanding that several key nations be
excluded because they are seen to have pushed Indonesia too hard on
the issue of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The armed forces will simply not accept the involvement of
Australian forces because there have been clashes of opinion
between some groups in the two countries,'' said the military's
chief spokesman, Brig. Gen. Sudradjat, speaking on television.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Such opposition could seriously compromise plans for the
peacekeeping force, which is expected to consist largely of
Australian troops and which is already being put into place in
Darwin, Australia, just 250 miles from East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Though Indonesia's compliant parliament formally endorsed the
deployment Monday, a number of its members spoke out against what
they called interference or bullying by foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As demonstrators in Jakarta and the country's second city,
Surabaya, staged the latest in a series of protests against
Australia and the United States, a parliamentary defense commission
said it objected to including those nations as well as New Zealand
and Portugal, the former colonial power in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence of these countries could lead to new disorders
because it has been clear they are not neutral,'' said the
commission chairwoman, Aisyah Amini. ``We have to reject them.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The influential daily newspaper Kompas joined the nationalist
backlash. It noted Monday that some of these same Western
governments had supported Indonesia's invasion of East Timor in
1975, one year after it was set free by Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international reaction to East Timor's problems has
whipped away the mask of Western governments,'' it wrote.
``Previously they supported invasion; now they threaten us.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One diplomat said he could sympathize with the sense of national
hurt. Indonesians have been far less well-informed than the outside
world, both now and over the years, about military abuses in East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Most here do not share the outside outrage over the violence and
many are bewildered at the intense pressure that has been put on
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge loss of face here,'' the diplomat said. ``It is
an extraordinary thing for any nation to accept.'' He noted that
previous U.N. peacekeeping forces had been deployed in countries
that had broken down completely, such as Lebanon, Somalia, Haiti,
Rwanda and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of another real country that peacekeepers have
been sent to,'' he said. ``The world really leaned on this place.
There's got to be a backlash to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
