<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST TALKS ENTER FINAL, MOST DIFFICULT STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli and Palestinian negotiators laid out widely
divergent positions Monday on the core issues of their dispute as
they opened the final and most difficult chapter in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   At a largely symbolic event at the Erez Crossing between Israel
and Palestinian-controlled Gaza, Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy and Palestinian negotiator Mahmoud Abbas shook hands after
mapping out their positions on the status of Jerusalem, the fate of
millions of refugees, control of water resources, and other thorny
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony took place on the anniversary of the 1993 signing
of the so-called ``declaration of principles,'' which got the peace
process underway with a historic handshake in Washington between
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin, who was later assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   After a six-year year journey often detoured by violence and
delays, the two sides will now begin to navigate the most profound
and complex aspects of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at the border, Levy said, ``We've accomplished a lot
toward mutual reconciliation and cooperation in these years. . . .
Now we are facing the final status talks that are supposed to bring
an end to 100 years of conflict between the two nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Yasser Abed Rabbo said he believed that
with goodwill on both sides, they could ``achieve the impossible''
and meet the goal of striking an agreement by next September. But
Rabbo said the talks would go nowhere if Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak sticks to hard-line positions he took on the issues of
Jerusalem and refugees in the May election campaign that brought
him to victory.
</P>
<P>
   US Middle East envoy Dennis Ross and European Union envoy Miguel
Moratinos attended the ceremony in the dusty patch of land, strung
with barbed wire, that separates Israel from the
Palestinian-controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
   The rekindling of the peace process followed a signing ceremony
last week in which Arafat and Barak agreed upon a modified ``land
for security'' deal that laid out the steps to be taken before
final status talks. The deal was based on an agreement brokered by
President Clinton last year at the Wye River plantation in
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Those steps, which include further withdrawal of Israeli troops
from 11 percent of the West Bank, release of Palestinian prisoners,
and permitting Palestinians to travel freely between the West Bank
and Gaza, will be carried out in tandem with the talks on the final
status issues.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the two sides agreed to try to resolve the final
status issues by Sept. 13, 2000. Israel and the PLO initially
planned to reach a final deal by May of this year, but the process
largely deadlocked for three years under Barak's predecessor
Benjamin Netanyahu, and the deadline came and went with no
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Although the peace process now seems reinvigorated by the
breakthrough, analysts on both sides are skeptical about the
ability of the Palestinians and Israelis to resolve such powerfully
emotional issues as Jerusalem and the refugees within one year.
</P>
<P>
   The skeptics point out that interim phases of the process have
been mired in deep mistrust and delays, and that there is little
reason to believe the more difficult issues will be any different.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing these doubts, former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon
Peres, who now serves in Barak's Cabinet, said Monday, ``The old
problems need new creative solutions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
