u f BC-3COM-PALM-NYT &LR;      09-13 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3COM-PALM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3COM SPINS OFF PALM COMPUTING INTO SEPARATE COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Exploiting the surging demand for calculator-sized computers,
the 3Com Corp. said Monday it would spin off its Palm Computing
subsidiary, maker of the popular Palm Pilot, as a separate company
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   3Com's main business is making complicated gear that routes
digital information from one computer to another. That business has
made 3Com the No. 2 maker of data networking equipment, second only
to Cisco Systems Inc., but it has little in common with selling
consumer-friendly electronic devices that fit in a breast pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to maintain their focus on handheld computing, some
senior Palm executives lobbied Eric A. Benhamou, 3Com's chairman,
for a spin-off as long ago as last year. Benhamou resisted, arguing
that such a move would be premature, but Monday he said the time
had come and Palm would be better off on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to spin off a business that would have critical
mass, that could stand on its own two feet,'' Benhamou said in an
interview Monday. ``The timing for it last year was premature.''
</P>
<P>
   An independent Palm would join Psion PLC of Britain, one of its
competitors, among the thin ranks of publicly traded companies
devoted to handheld computing.
</P>
<P>
   In 3Com's last fiscal year, which ended in May, the Palm
operation generated $569.9 million in revenue, an increase of 116
percent over the pervious year and about 10 percent of 3Com's
overall annual revenue. Four years ago, in September 1995, before
the first Palm Pilot had even been introduced, Palm Computing
agreed to sell itself to the USRobotics Corp. for $44 million.
(3Com agreed to acquire USRobotics, and Palm, for $6.6 billion in
1997.) While 3Com's divisions that sell modems and network cards
for PCs are stagnating, and while the company's core switch
business slogs through unceasing battles against Cisco, Palm has
become the company's star operation.
</P>
<P>
   After Palm is spun out as an independent company next year, it
will be worth billions, analysts said. The growth in Palm's
financial value over the last few years has been matched perhaps
only by the growth in popularity of its products. About 5 million
people use Palm devices, and the company controls perhaps
two-thirds of the worldwide market for handheld computers. Among
the technically literate, Palm Pilots, which cost at least $229 and
which can store hundreds of phone numbers and appointments, have
replaced the Filofax as the de rigueur information accessory.
</P>
<P>
   Palm's success, especially in the United States, has come in the
face of a concerted challenge from the Microsoft Corp.'s Windows CE
operating system for handheld devices. It is one of the few
companies to thrive in direct competition against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Benhamou's vision for Palm's future is even more grand. Like
others in the high-technology world, he forsees a moment when
mobile, pocket-sized devices capture much of the power and
functionality of desktop computers. In as few as three years,
Benhamou expects, most of Palm's revenue will come not from sales
of Palm Pilots but from licensing deals that allow other companies
to use Palm's operating system and from services including sale of
the use of a national wireless network.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, Palm seemed destined to reach for that future as
part of 3Com. Jeff Hawkins and Donna Dubinsky, who developed the
original Palm Pilot, left 3Com last year to form a new company,
Handspring Inc., after failing to persuade Benhamou to split Palm
from 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, perhaps, 3Com's announcement Monday came only a
day before Handspring was scheduled to unveil its first products.
Based on the Palm operating system, Handspring's new device may
cost as little as $150 and include the ability to to be upgraded
with new programs and capabilities using small hardware cartridges,
according to people who have seen the device.
</P>
<P>
   ``My overall reaction is that it's still the right thing for
them to do,'' Ms. Dubinsky said Monday, referring to the Palm
spin-off. ``We proposed it a year ago, and I think it took a little
longer for them to see it At the time, Eric thought Palm was very
strategic to 3com's future. We just felt it was a different
business than the networking business and required its own focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investors and analysts appeared to share Ms. Dubinsky's
opinion, but Benhamou spoke sharply in defense of his timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have made Donna more happy then, but it might not
have been in concert with our goals to maximize shareholder
value,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By way of explanation, Benhamou said an earlier spin-off might
have incurred a significant tax liability, while his plan would
hopefully avoid taxes and special charges.
</P>
<P>
   3Com's acquisition of USRobotics, Palm's parent, was accounted
as a pooling of interests, an accounting method for takeovers that
often allows the acquiring company to avoid charges against its
future earnings. But a company must wait two years after completing
a pooling before selling any of the significant assets it acquired.
Because 3Com acquired USRobotics in 1997, a spin-off of Palm before
this year might have incurred big charges against either Palm or
3Com.
</P>
<P>
   The same issue may complicate the future of 3Com sans Palm. For
at least a year, 3Com has been thought to be a potential
acquisition target itself, despite its difficulties competing
against Cisco. By slimming 3Com's profile and increasing the
company's focus on networking, a spin-off of Palm could make 3Com
even more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Benhamou declined Monday to discuss any potential takeover
offers but said the spin-off might actually make 3Com less
attractive as a target because it could prevent 3Com from being the
target of an acquisition that uses pooling accounting for two years
after the divestiture is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Under Benhamou's plan, 3Com will sell up to 20 percent of Palm
to the public in an initial stock offering sometime around January.
Up to six months after the offering, the remaining shares in Palm
will be given to existing 3Com shareholders. Benhamou said a chief
executive for Palm could be named within weeks but refused to say
what value the stock offering would place on the new company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
