<SLUG> BC-CANCER-TESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUMOR-SHRINKING DRUG TO BE TRIED ON HUMANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Texas, Wis.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The first human tests of a highly-publicized new
cancer drug, endostatin, are on track to begin in Boston within a
few weeks, despite a report questioning the drug's effectiveness,
say medical and company officials.
</P>
<P>
   The much-anticipated clinical trial of human endostatin, a
substance that shrinks tumors by cutting off their blood supply,
has been slowed somewhat by the need to devise a fair system for
selecting which patients will receive the drug, said an official at
Dana-Farber/Partners Cancer Care. Only patients who cannot be
helped by conventional therapies will be eligible, but it's
expected many will want to enter the initial human tests.
</P>
<P>
   The endostatin that will be given to a small number of patients
in the first tests is being supplied by EntreMed, a Rockville, Md.
company that has licensed the right to develop the drug and is
sponsoring the clinical trial in Boston. Mary Sundeen, a company
spokeswoman, said the endostatin has been thoroughly tested and
continues to show success in shrinking tumors in mice.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dr. Judah Folkman, in whose laboratory at Children's
Hospital endostatin was discovered, criticized as distorted a news
report Monday saying that scientists at the National Cancer
Institute had failed to document in its own laboratory in
Frederick, Md., the effectiveness of mouse endostatin.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman, in an interview, said he was to have shipped some
endostatin made in his laboratory to the NCI lab for testing there,
but because of previous experiences showing that the drug does not
withstand transportation well, he decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   The NCI scientists have already shown that they could duplicate
Folkman's results when they visited his Boston lab earlier this
year and worked under his supervision. The next step was to attempt
similar results in their own laboratory, but using Folkman's
endostatin.
</P>
<P>
   That step was never taken, both Folkman and Entremed said.
``It's not a case of tried and failed, it's a case of never
tried,'' said Sundeen at EntreMed.
</P>
<P>
   NCI officials could not be reached for comment but Sundeen said
the institute may release a statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report in the Wall Street Journal, which raised questions
about endostatin's ability to fight cancer, failed to say that
scientists in six other laboratories have published reports
documenting the drug's effects in animals, Folkman said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the laboratories reporting success is one at Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center in Boston, where Dr. Vikas P. Sukhatme has
been testing endostatin and reported last year that it halted or
shrank kidney tumors in mice.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman said the other labs that have replicated his endostatin
results are in the United States, Italy and Sweden, Endostatin
belongs to a category of drugs, angiogenesis inhibitors, that
selectively attack new blood vessels that grow around and into
tumors and are necessary for the cancers to spread. In mouse
experiments, endostatin has dramatically shrunk mouse tumors into
invisibility and has done so without toxic effects.
</P>
<P>
   Other, less potent angiogenesis inhibitors are in early testing
in human patients, and reports thus far suggest the drugs are
well-tolerated by patients and seem to combat tumors, though there
remains too little evidence to say how valuable they will be.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Boston, sites where endostatin will begin testing
this fall in patients are M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Texas and
at the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
