<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0735 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BAXTER-WACO-COX     09-13 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-WACO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Waco raises concern about `warrior' police
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Sen. John Danforth last week launched his investigation
into the enormously complicated question of how to ascribe blame in
the 1993 destruction of the Branch Davidian compound near Waco,
Texas, with a distinction subtle enough to stump a philosopher.
</P>
<P>
   It would be his task, Danforth said, to decide whether what
happened constituted ``bad judgment'' or ``bad acts.'' In other
words, he seemed to be saying, did federal agents merely stumble
into the deadly fiasco, or was there some element of premeditation
and subsequent cover-up involved in the government's role in the
tragedy?
</P>
<P>
   Possibly Danforth, a respected, independent figure who brings no
political baggage to the job, can clarify many of the troubling
issues surrounding the Waco case. But it's unlikely any
investigation will ever be able to completely assign responsibility
on the slippery slope between judgment and acts in this case.
</P>
<P>
   As great as the need is to put these nagging questions to rest,
there is an even bigger responsibility to insure that similar
incidents don't happen in the future. A paper released last month
by the Cato Institute, ``Warrior Cops: The Ominous Growth of
Paramilitarism in American Police Departments,'' makes a
provocative argument that current trends in law enforcement are
planting the seeds for another Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The study, written by analyst Diane Cecilia Weber, traces the
way in which the war on drugs over the past couple of decades has
brought not only military equipment but a military mind-set into
the realm of domestic law enforcement. The study pays less
attention to the increasing anxiety over terrorism, but obviously
that is also a factor in this trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``State and local police departments are increasingly accepting
the military as a model for their behavior and outlook,'' Weber
writes. ``The problem is that the mind-set of the soldier is simply
not appropriate for the civilian police officer. Police officers
confront not an `enemy' but individuals who are protected by the
Bill of Rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The blurring of the constitutional distinctions between military
and law enforcement has gone forward at the urging of Congress, the
study points out, and with an escalation of ``martial rhetoric''
within both political parties.
</P>
<P>
   This has not only led to the use of military forces for domestic
law enforcement purposes, as in the 1998 razing of 42 crack houses
by Indiana National Guard engineering units, but the proliferation
of military-style SWAT units in police departments across the
country, many with high-tech equipment supplied by the Department
of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   The latest revelations concerning the Waco case only lend
credence to the alarm raised in the study. On Friday, to cite just
one example, Texas officials successfully blocked a request by the
Austin American-Statesman to release a Texas Department of Public
Safety report on evidence collected at the Davidian compound by the
Texas Rangers, claiming it contained military secrets and would
need to be reviewed by other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   It has been relatively easy for politicians to point fingers
over an incident of such evident ``bad judgment'' as Waco. But it
has been hard to resist the appeal of sweeping measures that seem
to be justified by the societal threats of drugs and terrorism,
even though those measures blur the important distinction that
helps define us as a nation, between defending the country and
insuring the rights of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
