<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-APEC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CALLS APEC FORUM `A SUCCESSFUL MEETING' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ The United States' three biggest
headaches in Asia _ Indonesia, North Korea and China _ all eased a
bit Monday as a Pacific Rim summit ended with the White House
declaring victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work we've done in the past few days will help build a
more secure, more prosperous, more integrated Asia Pacific
region,'' President Clinton told reporters Tuesday. He called the
APEC forum ``a successful meeting'' following the advancements on
East Timor, North Korea and China.
</P>
<P>
   The annual session ended with the 21 members sporting black
sailing jackets with a silver fern leaf, encompassing New Zealand's
sports teams colors, posing for a group picture. They issued a
declaration embracing free trade and pressing for a new round of
world trade talks.
</P>
<P>
   But it was security, not economics, that drew the focus of the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's initial refusal to halt the killings by pro-Jakarta
militias in independence-minded East Timor dominated the two-day
conference but also gave a renewed purpose to the Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation summit.
</P>
<P>
   Members rallied international opposition and, under Australia's
lead, assembled a peacekeeping force for the island.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia, whose population is largely Muslim, invaded East
Timor in 1975 and annexed it the following year. An estimated
200,000 East Timorese have died in two decades of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the United States and North Korea being held in
Berlin also ``increased the potential for reduced tensions in the
Korean Peninsula,'' said Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, the president's
national security adviser. North Korea pledged to suspend testing
of long-range missiles in return for the United States easing
economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The isolated communist nation, its people suffering from famine,
repeatedly has threatened to develop a nuclear capability and its
test of one long-range missile over Japan sent shockwaves
throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said administration officials would soon provide Clinton
with recommendations on what economic sanctions should be lifted
against North Korea. How to handle North Korea was the topic of a
private session between President Clinton and South Korea President
Kim Dae-Jung and Japan Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   And, Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin held their first
face-to-face session since the United States mistakenly bombed
Beijing's embassy in May in Yugoslavia. Clinton and Jiang agreed to
resume talks immediately for China's entry into the World Trade
Organization, which would require the world's most populous nation
to play by international trade rules.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Taiwan remains a sensitive issue between the two
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tensions in the U.S.-China relationship affect this entire
region,'' Berger said. ``I can't tell you how many leaders came up
to the president today and said that they were pleased that our
relationship was back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and China failed to resolve the WTO issue
during the summit but agreed to continue negotiations, which had
been halted following the embassy bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of these issues can be resolved in one giant step,''
Berger said. ``Each requires patient work and persistent
engagement. But we feel that on balance, on the major issues that
threaten stability in this region, this week has witnessed a
genuine progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the president's economic adviser, said the United
States also achieved its goals in the APEC declaration issued by
its members at the close of the session.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling said the United States wanted a strong statement from
APEC in support of a new global trade negotiation that will begin
in November in Seattle. ``Things could not have gone much better in
that regard,'' Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in two years, the APEC forum was not burdened
by the crushing recession that devastated so many Asian ecomonies.
The United States and others used the recession as an opportunity
to foster more open and honest markets in several countries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, accompanied by his daughter Chelsea and mother-in-law
Dorothy Rodham, flew early Tuesday to scenic Queenstown, birthplace
of bungee jumping, to take a break at a New Zealand resort. Later,
he will visit Christchurch for a working visit with Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley. The president returns to Washington on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
