<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-SKIERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAYING OF NEW ENGLAND SKIERS SHOWN IN STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Skiing, the sport once associated with bums and
bunnies, is turning gray fast in New England, a tourism consultant
and researcher told a meeting of regional ski industry leaders last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1994 and 1998, the average age of skiers in New England
rose from 36.2 to 40.6, while the nationwide average rose more
slowly, from 37.6 to 38.7, according to pollster Bill Siegel's
company, Longwoods International. Meanwhile, during a period when
overnight travel grew by 22 percent, overnight ski trips in New
England grew by 11 percent _ less than half as fast as the ski
trips nationally, Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mount Attitash lodge in Bartlett, N.H., where Siegel
delivered his news to 150 members of the New England Ski Industry
Summit, some listeners shrugged off the numbers, which don't
account for the day trippers, who are typically younger and less
affluent. Others looked at the bright side, congratulating
themselves on keeping skiers in the sport longer, with features
like Attitash's ``Thank Goodness I'm 50'' promotion.
</P>
<P>
   But Siegel, who puts out an annual breakdown of Americans'
leisure, said he had been shocked by the rapid aging on New
England's slopes. During the five-year period his survey followed,
the number of 18- to 24-year-olds who went on ski trips dropped by
5 percent, and the 25- to 34-year-olds dropped by 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is throw the red flag up,'' he said. ``But I
think the industry had better jump on this one, because it looks
like a significant trend.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longwoods survey showed that the ski vacation is
increasingly a carriage trade, in which typical enthusiasts have an
average age of 38.7 and earn a salary upwards of $70,000.
Meanwhile, the number of ski vacationers who earn less than $25,000
dropped precipitously, from 13 percent to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While this upscaling trend is good news for resorts branching
into real estate, the long view could spell trouble, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them may not have wanted to hear what I was saying,''
he said, emphasizing that if young people stop skiing, the sport
could go downhill fast.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel's presentation started a buzz at the Summit, but his
audience dispersed to their respective mountains without a sense of
panic. Greg Sweetser, executive director of the Ski Maine
Association, which commissioned Siegel's talk, prefers what he
calls the ``glass-half-full theory.''
</P>
<P>
   From his own perspective overseeing 16 ski areas in Maine,
Sweetser has drawn very different conclusions. The 55-and-up skiing
population _ which rose from 8 percent in 1994 to 21 percent in
1998, according to Siegel's results _ typically vacations longer
and spends more than their younger counterparts for a product that
has improved vastly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   And without calculating day trips, ``I'm not sure we aren't
replacing the skiers on the other side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Alice Pearce, the executive director of Ski New Hampshire,
said she is aware of the intangible buzz that made windsurfing hot
in the 1980s and snowboarding hot in the 1990s, and worries that
skiing has lost its sizzle. Pearce herself learned to ski under the
luminous influence of Jean-Claude Killy and Suzy Parker, and
transferred her affection in the 1990s to the Olympian brothers
Phil and Steve Mahre.
</P>
<P>
   But as ski promoters learned when snowboarding hit the industry
in 1995, even the best marketers have a tenuous control of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you control what sport is going to be hot next? No, not at
all,'' she said. ``The opinion-makers say pogo-sticking is going to
be cool, and then the pogo stickers get access to media, and the
18- to 24-year-olds take up pogo sticking, and the high-schoolers
emulate the 18- to 24-year-olds, and the elementary schoolers
emulate the high schoolers.''
</P>
<P>
   With an increase nationwide of 26 percent, the ski trip was the
fourth fastest-growing form of vacation, after casino vacations,
which increased by 48 percent, and cruises, which increased by 30
percent. And despite the Northeast aging statistics that surprised
Siegel, skiing is in much better shape than, say, the group bus
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their problem is a demographic one that is more severe,''
Siegel said. ``The person who would take a group bus tour is
basically a widow, a 70-plus widow. When you have a situation like
this, it becomes a self-fulfilling prophecy, because the kids
aren't going to be caught dead doing something for old people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
