<HEADER>
A0746 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-SHOWS14-COX     09-13 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SHOWS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Designes from Carolina Herrara patently elegant
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ever tasteful, Carolina Herrera set herself apart
from the 100-plus designers staging spring/summer 2000 previews
during this Fashion Week by demonstrating how to bring a little
sensual elegance to patent leather. Highlighting Herrera's
52-ensemble show were: a motorcycling-inspired white patent leather
jacket paired with a tan crepe skirt with a ruffled hem; a
sleeveless beige patent top paired with hip-riding white pants; and
a knee-length white patent skirt worn with a pink camisole
featuring Moroccan tile-inspired embroidery.
</P>
<P>
   The patent pieces drove home Herrera's message about gloss;
further support for her shiny forecast came in the form of second
skin dresses and camisoles in glistening silk/jersey knits,
slim-fitting separates slathered in sequins, chintzed linens and
silk shantungs.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera says ``individuality, self-confidence, originality and
chic are the hallmarks'' of her collection. And it would indeed
require a unique sense of style to adopt some of the color
combinations (pink-and-brown, for instance) that she proposed.
What's more, her clothes were rather revealing in the upper thigh,
back, cleavage and love-handle areas. Skirts were knee- to
floor-length, but slit high. Tab closure pants, asymmetrical
necklines, intricate embroidery, and ruffled shirtfronts were the
most notable details.
</P>
<P>
   The actress Lyn Whitfield looked mesmerized as she made her way
backstage to congratulate Herrera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very much impressed,'' said Whitfield. ``I loved that
citron taffeta shirt with the ruffles. And all those asymmetrical
halter tops with the jeweled orchid brooches were divine.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsey Johnson
</P>
<P>
   What do grandmothers, cross-dressers, fire-eaters and
bandleaders have in common?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing really. But that didn't stop non-comformist designer
Betsey Johnson from using them to model her spring/summer '00
designs.
</P>
<P>
   Among those strutting around Johnson's Pepto pink showroom in
outfits befitting belly dancers, burlesque queens and beach bunnies
were producer/composer Quincy Jones' daughter Kidada, rocker Steven
Tyler's daughters Teresa and Chelsea, stripper Candis Cayne and the
designer's 50-something sister, Sally Banulis.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's denim jeans were skintight, cropped below the knee and
appliqued with flowers and sequins. Her mini-floral print dresses
were semi-sheer, form-fitting and long. Done up in cotton candy
shades of pink, blue, yellow and green _ with some racy reds and
brazen blacks thrown in for spice _ Johnson's was a ''sweet''
collection that should appeal to the ''girl'' in every woman.
</P>
<P>
   -------------
</P>
<P>
   THE SCENE
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful (people) show of support for Versace
</P>
<P>
   By A. Scott Walton
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Celebrities crowded into Donatella Versace's show
Sunday night for the unveiling of her spring/summer Versus
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Sly Stallone, Lisa Marie Presley, Natasha Richardson and Madonna
_ all of whom had place cards marking their turf for the event _
dutifully showed up to support the glam-rock designer.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based record producer Dallas Austin was one of the many
celebs seated in the first four rows. (Fame is relative though: his
spot was marked: ``Friend of (``Blade'' co-star) Stephen Dorff.'')
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a hi-tech hodge-podge of streetwear, his trademark
wraparound sunglasses and his spiky hair bleached strawberry
blonde, Austin admitted he was a novice to the runway show
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''For one thing,'' he said, ''it's a Versace show. And for
another, I was just hanging out with Stephen and we decided to come
by.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't wear much Versace,'' Austin added, ''but I admire her
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The producer of platinum-selling records by the likes of TLC,
Madonna and Michael Jackson, Austin had come to town for last
week's MTV Video Awards and stuck around to work on rock priestess
Stevie Nicks' next album. (''It's going to be called, 'Trouble in
Shangri La,'' he said of Nicks' comeback effort. ''So far, it's
going great.'')
</P>
<P>
   Things appear to be going great for Donatella as well. Though
she was never one to shun the limelight, she was thrust into the
chief design post of her family-owned business when her brother
Gianni was gunned down two years ago in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Throngs of autograph-seekers and paparazzi waited outside her
standing-room-only show, which was enlivened by music from the rave
band Les Rhythmes Digitales. The designer came out for her
post-show bow looking exceedingly youthful in a tiny green tank and
stretch pants.
</P>
<P>
   For spring, Versace favors wraparound skirts that flash lots of
leg, cheekily short shorts, transparent T-shirts with floral
appliques, lightweight leather separates, cropped pants that flare
out at the knee and snow white cotton separates covered in copper
eyelets or sequins. The color scheme included acid-bright shades of
pink, yellow, orange, blue and green. Details included copper
zippers, pants pleated on the diagonal and high-heeled shoes with
fluorescent soles.
</P>
<P>
   Other celebs in attendance included: ''My Best Friend's
Wedding'' co-star Rupert Everett, actresses Juliette Lewis and
Minnie Driver, Aerosmith's Stephen Tyler, Mary J. Blige,
photographers Herb Ritts and Steven Meisel, Spike Lee, and a Will
Smith-less Jada Pinkett. The tiny actress, whose hair has grown out
into a curly afro, wore a sheath so tight and so sheer that
onlookers agreed she couldn't have had on underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's by a young, African-American designer I found named
Rona,'' Pinkett said. ''Her label's called Nude.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton is Fashion Editor for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
