<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTER SUES BOSTON, CHARGING `HOSTILE' WORKPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Boston's first black female firefighter has slapped
the city and its fire department with a federal civil rights suit
alleging that she has been forced to work in a ``hostile''
environment, while her complaints of harassment have long been
ignored by higher-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Karen L. Miller, who was suspended for four weeks last year for
appearing in a racy skit about fire prevention on public-access
cable televison, also alleges in the suit that she was disciplined
harsher than white colleagues who committed more serious offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire department refuses to admit there are any problems on
the job,'' said Miller, 43, who in 1985 became the first black
woman to join the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to acknowledge that there are still some very
nasty attitudes toward women on the job, toward gays and toward
minorities,'' Miller said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Miller received the month-long suspension without pay last
November for her appearance on ``Fire Spot,'' a show that offered
fire safety tips to children and a few sexual innuendos geared
toward parents.
</P>
<P>
   While pretending to be a little girl, Miller pulled a fire
detector, underwear, whipped cream and a funny-shaped balloon from
a magic box while cracking jokes with another firefighter. Two
other firefighters received written reprimands after the broadcast
and the show's producer was suspended for five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show was innocuous, but the department wanted to make it
seem like it was pornographic,'' said Miller, adding that she
believed she was singled out for the harshest discipline as
``retaliation'' for lodging a complaint against the Fire Department
with the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The MCAD complaint filed in 1994 by Miller and three other
female firefighters mirrors many of the allegations in Miller's
federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said another firefighter who took a department car to a
New Hampshire racetrack without permission while off-duty received
only a four-day suspension.
</P>
<P>
   And she says firefighters who brought a blow-up doll and a
``nasty'' cake to a bachelor party at Fire Department headquarters
in January received only a written reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a possibility that if I was a white male up there doing
this show it probably wouldn't have been a big deal,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Fire Department nor Mayor Thomas Menino would
comment on the suit Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which names the city as well as the fire
department, alleges a pattern of harassment spanning 14 years.
Miller says that when hired, she was required to undergo a
psychiatric evaluation in which she was subjected to offensive and
inappropriate questions about hypothetical situations involving sex
in the fire station.
</P>
<P>
   While assigned to Ladder 10 in Jamaica Plain from 1985 to 1993,
Miller said she was prohibited from using bathrooms reserved for
officers, which were the only ones with locks. Miller said male
firefighters deliberately walked in on female firefighters while
they were showering or using the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Although Miller spent six years in the US Army Reserves, where
she operated heavy equipment, she says she was prohibited from
driving fire trucks while working at the Jamaica Plain station.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 Miller transferred to the Fire Prevention Division at
headquarters. Her job was to lecture about fire safety at schools
and offices and conduct on-site fire inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Miller says her superiors refused to allow her to attend
training sessions, even when she offered to pay her own expenses to
attend the national fire academy.
</P>
<P>
   When she complained to a captain about being called derogatory
names by a colleague, Miller said she was told, ``Don't be so
thin-skinned, we can't make everybody like you.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is the only woman assigned to Engine 48 in Hyde Park. In
fact, she is one of only 11 women on the department, including five
whites, six blacks and one Hispanic, according to officials.
Minorities constitute 29 percent of the 1,592-member force, but
only 3 percent of the upper ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the job,'' Miller said. ``There are a lot of nice guys
on the job. It's just a few that make it miserable for everybody
else. And that's all it takes. Then the administration doesn't take
a no-tolerance stand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
