<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0749 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-13 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY:   A LIGHT UNTO THE NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A friend in Israel remarked that over this past
weekend, the weekend of the New Year, people spoke of their country
turning a corner in its history. They were talking not about
politics or the peace process but about a decision of Israel's
Supreme Court: one that barred the use of painful physical methods
in the questioning of suspected terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   It was a remarkable decision, and not just for Israel. The
opinion for a unanimous court, by its president, Justice Aharon
Barak, spoke to judges and lawyers everywhere _ and really to the
citizens of all democracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although a democracy must often fight with one hand tied
behind its back,'' Barak wrote, ``it nonetheless has the upper
hand. Preserving the rule of law and recognition of an individual's
liberty constitutes an important component in its understanding of
security. At the end of the day, they strengthen its spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Several coercive physical interrogation techniques used by
Israel's security services were at issue. One is shaking, defined
as ``the forceful shaking of the suspect's upper torso, back and
forth, repeatedly, in a manner which causes the neck and head to
dangle and vacillate rapidly.'' An expert opinion given in the case
said such shaking could ``cause serious brain damage'' and ``harm
the spinal cord.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government argued that shaking and other methods of
physical pressure did no permanent harm to the suspect. It argued,
as Barak put it, that such methods were ``indispensable to fighting
and winning the war on terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   The court said it had to balance the need to fight terrorism
against the need to respect human dignity. ``A democratic,
freedom-loving society does not accept that investigators use any
means ... ,'' Barak wrote. ``An illegal investigation harms the
suspect's human dignity. It equally harms society's image.''
</P>
<P>
   That approach is familiar in American constitutional law. Long
before the modern era the Supreme Court barred the use of
third-degree methods by the police. But the Israeli court had over
the years refrained from deciding claims against security
interrogations.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's court held only that physically coercive methods were
unlawful because they had not been authorized by Israel's
parliament, the Knesset. It was there, Barak said, that the
``pointed debate'' must occur. If there is such a debate, the
Knesset will have to face up for the first time, as a result of the
court's words, to the hard questions about the values of Israeli
society.
</P>
<P>
   A right-wing American commentator, writing in The Wall Street
Journal, saw the decision as ``a form of unilateral disarmament by
Israel.'' The headline asked, ``Has Israel Lost Its Nerve?''
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis feel, to the contrary, that in the Supreme Court's
judgment Israel found its soul. Dan Meridor, a former leading
figure in the conservative Likud Party, said it ``constituted a
certificate of honor for the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine judges who decided the case had no illusions about the
terrorist threat to Israel. ``We are not isolated in an ivory
tower,'' Barak wrote. ``We live the life of this country. We are
aware of the harsh reality of terrorism.'' He foresaw also that
critics would attack the decision without reading the opinion. But
judges, he said, ``must act according to the law ... When we sit to
judge, we are being judged.''
</P>
<P>
   The hardest issue facing the court was whether security
interrogators could put physical pressure on a suspect who might
know about a ``ticking time bomb.'' Years ago Jacobo Timerman, who
was tortured by interrogators under an Argentine military
dictatorship, asked me what I would do in that very situation. I
said that torture might be justified. ``No!'' he said. ``Never!
Once you start down that road, there is no end.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the position the Israeli court has taken. In doing so it
has defined its country, as our Supreme Court defined the United
States when it decided Brown vs. Board of Education. It has turned
Israel toward the role that Justice Louis D. Brandeis and other
early Zionists saw for a Jewish state: to be a light unto the
nations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
