<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ABERNATHY-TRIAL-COX     09-13 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABERNATHY-TRIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury hears Abernathy discussing expense payments
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jurors listened Monday to the voice of former state
Sen. Ralph David Abernathy III trying to convince his public
relations adviser that it would be ``no big deal'' for her to say
he actually gave her $2,700 in expenses the state paid out for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows I didn't pay you the money I said I paid you?''
Abernathy asked Zee Bradford on one of two tapes played for the
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if you say you got it, it ain't a big deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford, who now works in Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell's office,
was the state's star witness as it concluded its theft, false
swearing, oath betrayal and forgery case against Abernathy, son of
the famous civil rights leader. He is accused in 35 counts based on
10 incidents of alleged chiseling on his Senate expense account.
</P>
<P>
   The defense's presentation is expected to be brief since
Visiting Superior Court Judge L.A. McConnell told the jury it might
get the case today. He also indicated he is strongly considering
granting a motion for a directed verdict of acquittal on the
state's six weakest counts.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford testified she agreed to handle Abernathy's public
relations in the 1998 session of the Legislature for $9,000.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Stacy Hydrick showed Bradford two
vouchers Abernathy turned in to the Senate Fiscal Office, one
saying she had been paid $1,200 and another saying she had received
$1,500 for personal services.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, Hydrick asked:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that your signature on that document?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it is not,'' Bradford replied each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever receive $1,500 from Ralph Abernathy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To date in all my life I have only received $300 from him, in
three payments, as God is my witness,'' Bradford replied.
</P>
<P>
   She said Abernathy came to her house the night of July 30, 1998,
showed her the documents and said that if anyone asked, she should
say she received the money. ``I told him I would not lie,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, GBI agent Fred Mays came to her office to ask
her about the vouchers. Bradford denied signing them or receiving
the money, she said, and Mays asked her if she would tape any phone
conversations she had with Abernathy.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Mays given her a tape recorder, she said, than a
television reporter called and asked her if she had signed her name
to $9,000 worth of vouchers for Abernathy.
</P>
<P>
   Panicked, Bradford said she hooked the recorder to her telephone
and called Abernathy. On the tape, he tells her the $9,000 amount
is impossible, because there is a $4,800 per-session cap on
legislative expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-seven hundred is not a lot of money,'' he told her,
aghast, ``but 9,000 is almost 10 grand!''
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to say is that you received the money,'' he tells
her soothingly. ``I need you to say you received the money from
me?'' Bradford protested that she already had paid her income
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to your house and I showed you what I signed for in
your name,'' he said. ``Why don't you just go ahead and ask your
CPA to file an amendment and I'll pay you for whatever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   On several occasions, he asked, ``What if I just brought you the
$2,700 now?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford moaned repeatedly that she didn't want to get involved
in the problem and didn't want her name ``in the media.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to go to the mayor and let him know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief silence, Abernathy said in a flat voice:
</P>
<P>
   ``Let him know what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want him blindsided,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to go to Bill, say, `Bill, they called and said I
received $9,000 from Ralph and I didn't receive $9,000. I received
about $2,000.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph, I don't want to lie now,'' Bradford said. ``I didn't
get the money and I don't want to lie and say I did . . . I don't
want to lie, Ralph.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tell the truth, it's over,'' Abernathy said, his voice
alternately wheedling and badgering. ``It's going to be a great big
deal and your name is going to be spread all over the media in this
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
