u a BC-GEORGIA-DROUGHT-COX     09-13 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-DROUGHT-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Riverbeds, lake shores at record lows in Georgia
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Seabrook
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The searing drought has left stretches of several
major rivers and lakes in Georgia at near record-low levels, and
state environmental officials are considering emergency water
restrictions for more than a dozen communities.
</P>
<P>
   Some stretches of the Flint River have barely enough water to
float a canoe. The flow in the Oconee River at Dublin in Middle
Georgia is only a fourth of what is typical for this time of year.
Several streams in South Georgia have dried up completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are approaching the conditions we had in the droughts of
1986 and 1988,'' said Nolton Johnson of the state Environmental
Protection Division. Those droughts were Georgia's worst dry spells
since records began at the beginning of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, water levels on Lake Lanier and other reservoirs on
the Chattahoochee River continue to decline with no relief in
sight, says the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers. The corps is
projecting that Lanier's level will be1,060 above mean sea level by
the first week of October _ about six feet down from its normal
1,066-foot level for October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boaters should be especially cautious as declining levels may
reduce clearance over underwater constructions,'' said corps
spokesman Patrick Robbins. ``Shallower water conditions could
expose rocks or stumps to those swimming or boating on the lakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Corps and state officials are expected to meet within the next
few days to determine if more water conservation measures should be
put in place for Lanier and other reservoirs. Those measures could
include storing more water in the reservoirs, and reducing the
amount that goes through the dams to generate electricity. A
certain amount has to be released from Lanier to dilute waste water
from sewage treatment plants downstream.
</P>
<P>
   The drought predictions for the state could change if powerful
Hurricane Floyd churning in the Atlantic and other tropical storms
dump a lot of rain on the state. Any relief, however, may be
temporary. ``September and October are usually our driest months of
the year,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Low water flow in the Tallapoosa River and its tributaries
already has prompted the EPD to issue emergency conservation
measures for Haralson County and the cities of Bremen and Welaska.
Haralson has issued a total ban on outdoor water use. Conditions
have also led the EPD to grant Bremen an emergency permit to tap a
special reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, sandbags were used to create a small reservoir in a
section of Tallapoosa to build a water supply for peak use in
Haralson County and Bremen.
</P>
<P>
   The EPD also is considering emergency water conservation
measures for more than a dozen other communities beset by low
stream flow. They include Clayton County, Fayette County, Forsyth
County and Heard County; and the cities of Griffin, Hogansville,
Manchester, Newnan, Roswell, Royston, Bent Tree, Dublin and
Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Bennett, which is upstream from the city's drinking water
intake, has shrunk to a fraction of its normal size. The water
level in the lake and Whitewater Creek, which feeds it, dropped so
low the Fayetteville water system stopped pumping from the creek
last week and hooked on to the county's water system.
</P>
<P>
   In Dublin, the Oconee is at its lowest flow since records have
been kept. Normally, the flow would be about 1,600 cubic feet per
second (cfs) this time of year. Right now, however, the flow is
hovering around 400 cfs. The lowest one-day flow for the river at
Dublin on record is 428 cfs. One cfs is equal to about 7.4 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   Walton Smith, an Atlanta lawyer, said he canoed a stretch of the
Flint last weekend from Marshallville to Montezuma and found it
``very hazardous'' because of numerous uprooted trees and other
snags exposed by the low water.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
