u a BC-MA-NURSES-OVERDOSE-BO     09-13 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-NURSES-OVERDOSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13 NURSES IN OVERDOSE CASE TO RETRAIN, RECERTIFY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Thirteen nurses involved in a tragic 1994 chemotherapy
overdose episode involving two patients at Dana Farber Cancer
Institute have accepted formal reprimands from the state nursing
board and have agreed to undergo retraining or recertification.
</P>
<P>
   The board's disciplinary proceedings against the Dana Farber
nurses are controversial among nurses nationally. In Massachusetts,
the board's action against the chemotherapy nurses has become
linked with its proposed new regulations that, many nurses feel,
make them more vulnerable to shortcomings that are more
institutional than individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relieved that the Board of Registration in Nursing has
decided that the appropriate response for the Dana Farber nurses is
retraining, not some more severe action,'' said Judith
Shindul-Rothschild, a Boston College nursing professor. ``Still,
the proposed new regulations present grave problems around holding
individual nurses accountable for systems failures.''
</P>
<P>
   The nursing board's reprimand of 13 Dana Farber nurses is the
latest in a four-year series of official actions and reactions to
the Dana Farber overdoses, which led to the death of Boston Globe
health columnist Betsy A. Lehman, 39, and disabling heart damage in
a North Andover woman, Maureen Bateman, 53. Bateman subsequently
died of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether the nursing board cited 18 Dana Farber nurses
involved in the overdoses.
</P>
<P>
   Three other nurses involved in the overdoses have refused to
accept any sanctions from the state board. A disciplinary hearing
on their cases is scheduled for Oct. 6. Last December, two other
Dana Farber nurses accepted a year's probation to avoid formal
charges and a full-scale hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13 nurses who recently accepted a reprimand and
retraining requirement, four administered the improper doses, seven
monitored the chemotherapy as it was being delivered, and two
signed off on the erroneous medication order.
</P>
<P>
   Written by a physician-trainee, Dr. James Foran, the order
mistakenly called for four times the intended dose of a highly
toxic cancer drug called cyclophosphamide. The Massachusetts
medical licensure board subsequently suspended Foran's license
retroactively _ an action with no immediate practical effect, since
the suspension period had expired by the time the board acted.
</P>
<P>
   The state pharmacy board in 1997 formally reprimanded three Dana
Farber pharmacists for their role in the overdoses.
</P>
<P>
   The state's action against the nurses alone has sparked
controversy. Dana Farber officials have consistently said the
nurses were not culpable because the hospital did not require
nurses in 1994 to check physicians' chemotherapy orders against
written ``protocols,'' the documents which spell out the conduct of
experimental chemotherapy. In 1995, after the overdoses became
public, the hospital did institute such a requirement.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 investigation by the state Department of Public Health
did not find fault with individual nurses, but it did call the
nursing board's attention to issues involving nurses' role in
administering experimental chemotherapy, which involves unusual
risk to patients.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Registration in Nursing, which licenses
nurses, maintains that proper nursing standards require nurses to
verify correct medication doses even if the institution they work
for does not require it.
</P>
<P>
   An important issue in the case involved the lengths to which
nurses should go to double-check doses. The wording of the recent
consent agreements makes clear that the nursing board expected the
nurses to ``verify the. . .dose with the entire written protocol.''
This presumably will be the board's position in the upcoming
hearings against the remaining three nurses.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Frank E. Reardon, who represents all 18 nurses in the
case, said Monday that the nurses ``did verify against the
appropriate records available to them,'' not ``the entire
protocol.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the nurses feel they complied with both the hospital's
policy and with the board's policy on the verification of
medication orders,'' Reardon said.
</P>
<P>
   To many authorities in nursing and the growing field of medical
error-prevention, the case of the Dana Farber nurses goes to the
heart of a growing dilemma: How to apportion blame or
accountability between individual licensed professionals and the
institutions or ``systems'' in which they work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case represents the whole difficulty nurses face right
now with being accountable for their practice within systems that
are setting them up for errors,'' said Diana Mason, editor of the
American Journal of Nursing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurses are working under almost battlefield conditions these
days,'' Mason said. ``Given the loads they're carrying, it's very
easy when errors are made _ and they will be made _ to want to
blame an individual nurse rather than looking at the system.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Mason is sympathetic to the Dana Farber nurses, she
also supports the nursing board's decision to commence disciplinary
proceedings against them _ a stand unpopular among many nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the state board for nursing had to review the
nurses,'' Mason said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the nurses and the hospital should be held accountable
for having a policy that violated standards of practice for
nurses,'' Mason said. ``If they weren't required to do a check,
that should have signaled something to the nurses that something
was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason editorialized in March that nurses ``should never accept
an institutional policy that removes them from adequately checking
medications they will be administering.'' That generated a reply in
the current issue of the American Journal of Nursing from Susan M.
Grant, chief of nursing and patient care services at Dana Farber.
</P>
<P>
   Grant wrote that the Dana Farber nurses relied on what they
thought was correct information when they failed to question the
four-fold overdoses they administered to Lehman and Bateman.
</P>
<P>
   The nurses who recently settled their cases with the nursing
board are: Shelly H. Autor, Mary Edson Cowell, Heidi L. DiPetro,
Nancy M. Hopkins, Donna Joseph, Rolf. W. Ludwig, Kelly McNeill,
Christin O'Brien, Karen Anne Poreda, Sheila B. Rozanski, Leslie Rae
Spencer, Maria Minks Wadsworth, and Robyn V. Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   Cases are still pending against Susan Aikey, Ilene A. Galinsky,
and Maura A. Murray.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
