<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0753 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-PROFILE-ART-1135     09-13 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-ART-1135(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS SAY BUSH MUST STILL PROVE HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Gov. George W. Bush of Texas first hit the
presidential campaign trail in June, he wore monogrammed cowboy
boots, the perfect accessory for his folksy affability and casual
self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   But when he visited New Hampshire early last week, he was shod
in a pair of conservative, shiny black loafers that seemed to
reflect more than the pant cuffs above them. They suggested an
impulse by Bush to put at least a bit of a damper on his brash
irreverence, which has been a potent magnet for affection but is a
less certain invitation for respect.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush presses forward with his almost preposterously charmed
quest for the Republican presidential nomination, he has plenty of
confidence, evident in his easy swagger. He has more than enough
money _ about $50 million and counting, an unprecedented,
calculator-boggling sum. And he has a wave of early support in
polls that looks tidal.
</P>
<P>
   But what political analysts, some of Bush's advisers and Bush
himself say he must still do is prove to voters, many of whom will
begin to take a closer look at candidates in the coming months,
that he has the maturity, poise and sheer heft to lead a nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge step,'' said Bush, who had never held elective
office before 1995, in an interview in New Hampshire last week.
``And in all of my speeches, I say it's a big step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big step,'' he repeated, stressing his understanding of
the point and perhaps trying to project the kind of humility that
has not been considered one of his trademarks. ``And I know it's a
big step. I think the real question, though, and the important
question that the American people are going to look at and answer
is: Is the person prepared? You know, more importantly: Is the
person prepared to make the big decisions for America? That's the
big stage. And that's the fundamental question _ of trust.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to answer all of that in the affirmative, Bush
recently began what might be called the substance phase of his
campaign. Nearly two weeks ago he delivered an education address in
Los Angeles; on Wednesday he is scheduled to sketch out some of his
plans for national defense at the Citadel in Charleston, S.C. Other
policy speeches will follow at roughly two-week intervals.
</P>
<P>
   At several appearances in New Hampshire last week, Bush invited
audiences to throw questions at him, a process obviously intended
to counter impressions that he has been fuzzy and evasive and to
show voters _ and the many reporters in tow _ that he could think
on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``To close the sale,'' said one adviser, ``he needs to
demonstrate that he has the grasp and depth and breadth _ that he
is not simply a popular man who has caught the wave.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been a few missteps that have underscored how
unfamiliar Bush is with the intensity of the scrutiny he is now
under, despite his lineage and proximity to his father's various
national campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Most political analysts agree that Bush faltered when, after
saying he would not indulge specific questions about whether he had
used illegal drugs as a younger man, he began playing a numbers
game about how many years into the past he could certify himself as
drug-free.
</P>
<P>
   On a much less serious level, he was caught flat-footed when,
during a visit to an elementary school in Florence, S.C., three
weeks ago, a student asked him what his favorite book was in his
childhood, and he could not name one. Bush has made educating young
children a top priority. Literacy was the issue held dear by his
mother, former first lady Barbara Bush, and it is the mission of
his wife, Laura Bush, too.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last week, when bad weather delayed Bush's flight from New
Hampshire to Rhode Island, he arrived in Providence well after his
visit to an elementary school was scheduled to take place, and
headed to a fund-raiser that was just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers explained that Bush was simply trying to stay on
schedule and that the schoolchildren had already gone to lunch. But
the decision opened the door for Vice President Al Gore, the
front-runner for the Democratic presidential nomination, to make
his own journey to the school, where he told students exactly which
book _ ``Mr. Popper's Penguins'' _ he had favored as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running for president is a unique experience,'' said Bob
Teeter, a Republican pollster, adding that it is rare for someone
so new to the race to emerge as far ahead of the pack as Bush has.
``People don't know how hard it is _ how constant, how persistent.
And he hasn't been through it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, Teeter said, Bush has handled himself
well. ``All the indications are good,'' Teeter said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said that the way Bush manages the awkward,
embarrassing and tense moments that are inevitable in a
presidential campaign will be a signal to voters of whether he is
ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a crucible, it is a gantlet, and part of what people
want to see is how you handle it,'' said Mark McKinnon, Bush's
media consultant. ``That's something people look for in a
president.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Bush seems to be striking a careful balance between
the flip, saucy playfulness that comes naturally to him _ and lends
him his distinctive charm _ and a more watchful, dignified
demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   He still gives vent to his insouciant side. ``Some people say
that I proved that if you get a C average, you can end up being
successful in life,'' he said with a smile last week when he was
asked, by a child at an elementary school in Bedford, N.H., whether
he had been a good student.
</P>
<P>
   He still immediately assigns nicknames to the people he meets _
his own quirky way of trying to topple the barriers of formality
between him and anyone in his orbit.
</P>
<P>
   But when two reporters who regularly follow him on the campaign
trail recently joked that they were around each other so much that
they had begun sleeping together, Bush made an exaggerated gesture
of clamping his mouth shut and banishing any discernible expression
of emotion from his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not supposed to react to that,'' he told them in a
deliberately robotic tone.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as he rumbled through southern New Hampshire in a
small Winnebago, Bush said, ``Part of my treating somebody as a
human being is I like to needle them and tease them at times, and
there was a moment when I just, I just, you know, probably
withdrew, because I didn't want somebody to misconstrue what I was
saying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a pretty lighthearted fellow,'' Bush added. ``But I
understand that this is a serious business we're talking about. And
I understand the gravity.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he also understands _ or, at least, constantly
tells himself _ that today's good political fortune could dissipate
tomorrow.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there were chapters from political history that he
summoned to remind himself of this, Bush said, ``Let's start with
1992,'' referring to year his father, President George Bush,
watched his poll numbers tumble and lost the White House to Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a miserable year, when I watched a great man, a man I
love more than life _ you know, one of the really fundamentally
solid, decent people _ go from 92 to 38 in a very quick period of
time,'' Bush said of his father's standing in the polls. ``History
is full of reversals of political fortunes, and I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was determined to show that he was working as hard
as, or harder than, his Republican rivals to make his case to
voters; Bush's advisers trumpet the fact that unlike some of his
challengers, Bush must spend a significant amount of time in many
locations _ in New Hampshire and South Carolina and Iowa _ lest he
be accused of taking victory for granted and coasting to the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm expected to be in all states, and I will be,'' Bush said.
``Some candidates can pick and choose where they campaign and where
they put resources, time and effort, and I'm expected to be in all
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   That very gentle swipe at his Republican opponents is about as
combative as Bush gets toward them. In speeches, Bush zings
Clinton, saying that the Oval Office should not be a mirror for
public opinion, and he zings Gore, saying that Democrats no more
invented prosperity than they invented the Internet. (The gibe
refers to Gore's comment in March that he ``took the initiative in
creating the Internet.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Bush does not take aim at anyone else in the crowded field
of Republican contenders, which at times suggests that he is
already gazing beyond the primaries to November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking ahead,'' Bush said. ``I promise you that. I am
focused on getting the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, he or any other nominee would be badly hurt in the
general election if the Republican Party fractured along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to be in a position, should I earn the nomination, to
bring our party together, to consolidate our party rapidly so that
I can then go out and do what I need to do, which is to go out and
attract independent and discerning Democratic voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the most striking elements of Bush's oratory _
and of his campaign schedule up to this point _ is its studious
inclusiveness, its insistence on reaching out to voters not
typically in the Republican fold.
</P>
<P>
   He has visited many social programs and schools with largely
minority populations. When he talks about the value of religious
institutions in widening the social safety net, he does not simply
mention churches _ he invariably invokes synagogues and mosques as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The task now, his advisers acknowledge, is to demonstrate for
voters that there is something real behind those words, actual
visions and prescriptives for what the federal government should
and should not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of a process, and while we've had great
success so far, there's a lot to be done,'' said Karl Rove, the
campaign's principal strategist.
</P>
<P>
   Among the works in progress, political analysts said, is Bush
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a whole series of things that he has to
project to ratify what for most Republicans has become an
instinctive ballot choice, and that's everything from a grasp of
foreign policy to a sense of what kind of people he'd appoint to
Cabinet posts,'' said Peter Roff, the former political director for
Gopac, a Republican fund-raising and strategizing group.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that this is exactly what he is trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens in a campaign is there are moments, there are
different ways for candidates to assure people, to earn the
trust,'' he said. ``I'm earning the trust.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
