<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO ARE THESE GUYS, ANYWAY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The dogs are barking, and this baseball caravan is
moving on. And wherever the Boston Red Sox go, people ask the same
questions.
</P>
<P>
   What's with that lineup? Where is the power? What's a Trot? Is
Jimy Williams for real? What did he do with that other ``m''? What
exactly is going on here?
</P>
<P>
   There is one great pitcher and one great everyday player. It is
possible _ not necessarily likely, but entirely possible _ that
they will become the first team to enter postseason play with just
one pitcher posting 10 or more wins.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the lineup Mike Hargrove will put on the field in this
three-game series should laugh at anything Williams answers with.
Jim Thome or Mike Stanley at first? Roberto Alomar or Jose Offerman
at second? David Justice or Trot Nixon in right? Kenny Lofton or
Darren Lewis in center? Harold Baines or Reggie Jefferson at DH?
These aren't difficult decisions to make. I mean, gee, Manny
Ramirez (target of many HBPs of late) and his 144 ribbies weren't
even in it, and you still had to like their lineup a whole lot
better than Boston's. They might even say that while Nomar
Garciaparra is a pretty nice player, we're quite happy with Omar
Vizquel, Mr. Gold Glove himself, at short.
</P>
<P>
   But all of this firepower made the Indians only 6 1/2 games
better than the Red Sox over the season's first 143 games. That's
really not much over 23 weeks. So what the Red Sox are doing with a
lot of non-marqueee players proves, um, proves, um, proves, well,
what exactly?
</P>
<P>
   ``That we have a situation in which a couple of guys don't have
to carry the team,'' suggests Stanley. ``Aside from the pitching,
which has been phenomenal, the story of this team has been the
contributions of various people throughout the lineup. But coming
into spring training, we knew that was the way it would have to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say we're a National League-type team,'' observes Rod
Beck, who jumped onto this moving train via a bizarre save against
Kansas City back on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out there slugging a lot of home runs,'' Beck says.
``But we have a lot of guys hitting .270 and we have a lot of
interchangeable parts. Dusty Baker always said, `Give me a lineup
of .270 hitters and I'll win.' I think that's a truism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox do a little bit of biceps-flexing every once in a
while (e.g. five homers Saturday in Yankee Stadium), but Home Run
Derby is not their thing. Suppose, for example, that someone had
told you in 1959, 1969, 1979, 1989, or even this past Opening Day
that the Red Sox would some day hit zero home runs in a seven-game
homestand but still go 6-1. You would have dismissed it as some
sort of Jules Verne/George Orwell fantasy. But that's exactly what
happened when this team played Anaheim and Kansas City from Aug.
27-Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   They play minimalist baseball, and that seems to fit the
temperament of their oddly minimalist manager. Deep into the third
year of his tenure as Red sox manager, Williams relentlessly
preaches the value of a pitch-by-pitch approach to the game. He
never seems to see or care about the broad arc of anything. He
leaves all the fancy talk, all the historical implications, and all
the what-ifs to the fans and the media. He has a set of built-in
blinders that shield him from situations and controversies that
might distract others in his position.
</P>
<P>
   If Williams had Ramirez or Alomar, he'd happily play them. He
doesn't. So he plays Trot Nixon and Offerman and never asks them to
be anyone but themselves. There's a skill in that.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Lewis may be the quintessential Williams player. He went
into Monday night's game hitting .251, and by every normal measure
you would say he is in a slump (8 for 54). But his batting average
is irrelevant. He is a superb center fielder, and he was batting
second because, 8 for 54 or no 8 for 54, he always has value. He is
the best bunter on the team, as the Yankees found out over the
weekend when Lewis got down four successful sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly does some things with that bat,'' acknowledges
Williams. ``Hit-and-run, advancing runners. I put the (hit-and-run)
sign on for him twice in one at-bat the other day. Bunting, he's
gotten some big ones down for us. No hesitation. No doubt. He gets
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd tell you they don't pay him to drive in runs,'' adds
Stanley. ``They pay him to play defense and do all those other
things. He does not get caught up in his own numbers. He's out
there to help the team, and that's what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with a Pedro Martinez on the mound, the 1999 Red Sox
routinely play the role of David to the Goliaths in New York,
Cleveland, and Arlington. You can easily understand why a Jimy
Williams, while never expressing the sentiment publicly, gets a
special glow watching his ``kids,'' as he calls them, win games the
old-fashioned John McGraw way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love watching them play,'' he says. ``I really enjoy
watching them play. You can come into every game they play, and if
there were no scoreboard, you could never tell if they were winning
or losing, because they play the same way all the time. They may
have bad days, but they never let their guard down. Every day, they
go to the last pitch, the last swing, the last out. They're still
right there.''
</P>
<P>
   You would still trade the Red Sox lineup for the New York
lineup, the Cleveland lineup, the Texas lineup, and maybe some
other lineups. But we're very close to the end and the Red Sox are
still, yes, right there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
