<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0765 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SKOL-PRAYERDAY-COX     09-13 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOL-PRAYERDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School flagpoles become prayer sites this week
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Millions of students will be getting to school early
on Wednesday to stand around outside and talk. To God.
</P>
<P>
   It's the day of See You at the Pole, an annual gathering of
Christian teenagers around school flagpoles for prayer. Three
million students around the world participated last year, mostly in
the United States. This year, in the wake of highly publicized
cases of school violence, organizers are expecting more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that happened last year has fueled a movement among
kids to seek answers in life,'' said Mike Crandall, metro Atlanta
director of Student Venture, the high school division of Campus
Crusade for Christ. ``I think there's a great hunger now for God
among kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Also this year, the Alpharetta, Ga.-based North American Mission
Board of the Southern Baptist Convention is encouraging parents and
other adults to gather Tuesday night for their own organized prayer
for the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Combined with See You at the Pole, this effort will get the
entire church praying that God will make a difference in the
campuses of our land,'' said board President Robert Reccord.
</P>
<P>
   Some adult groups will meet in churches; others will conduct
``prayer walks'' around their children's schools. North American
Mission Board spokesman Martin King said parents are asked to
notify school administrators of any intention to be on campus, and
to remain on public streets and sidewalks if there is any
objection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access is not the issue,'' King said. ``Prayer is the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Youth ministry leaders say most metro Atlanta communities will
be participating to some degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'd be hard-pressed to find a school in metro
Atlanta where some kids did not gather to pray this Wednesday,''
said Wes Cantrell, an organizer in First Priority, a group of youth
ministers of different Christian denominations. First Priority has
about 19 ``networks'' in communities representing about 110 high
schools and middle schools in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   See You at the Pole began in 1990 with the prayer activities of
a Southern Baptist church youth group in the Fort Worth suburb of
Burleson, Texas. The idea spread across Texas, across the United
States and now into more than 20 other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The event is legal because it is student-organized and
student-led on a school-by-school basis, organizers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do think it's inappropropriate for students to be doing
this, but there's not a lot you can do about it,'' said Annie
Laurie Gaylor, editor of Free Thought Today, the newspaper of the
Freedom From Religion Foundation, based in Madison, Wis. The
foundation is an organization of atheists and agnostics that fights
what it considers inappropriate public expressions of religion.
</P>
<P>
   For many students, See You at the Pole is only a highly visible
version of an activity they engage in weekly or daily.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 students at Heritage High School in Rockdale
County are expected to pray before school on Wednesday. But the
only difference between Wednesday and any other day at Heritage is
that they'll be outside instead of inside.
</P>
<P>
   Every day a group called the Fellowship of Christian Youth meets
half an hour before school begins, sometimes drawing as many as 90
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing I can tell you is we're making a commitment
every day to learn and grow and to take time out of the day to
worship,'' said James Shaw, 16, one of the worship leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Shaw said, Heritage students are accepting of their
peers who particpate. ``We do have a few kids who will be negative
about anything religious,'' he said. Those students refer to the
classroom where the Christian youth gather as the ``clappy-clappy
room,'' he said, because of the peppy guitar music and singing that
pours into the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I walked through those doors, I was scared,''
said Shaw, now a junior. ``People don't know what to expect. It's
hard to pull people in there.''
</P>
<P>
   More people will come to prayer around the flagpole because they
can walk up, pray for a minute, and then leave, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Six students were injured in a shooting at Heritage on May 20.
Fellow student Anthony ``T.J.'' Solomon is charged with several
felonies in the incident. Shaw said the number of participants in
the Fellowship of Christian Youth has increased some since the
shooting. ``I'm impressed with the number of freshmen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is also hearing from friends at the county's Salem
and Rockdale high schools that more youth are attending Christian
activities there.
</P>
<P>
   Crandall said he sees a similar trend toward increased
participation and Christian ``activism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not anything anybody's doing,'' he said. ``It's something
God's doing. The kids are responding.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
