u i BC-MOSCOW-FEAR-BOS &LR;      09-13 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSCOW-FEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARS GROW AS NEW BLAST LEVELS APARTMENT BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV AND BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris N. Yeltsin ordered security tightened
in cities across Russia Monday after the second deadly blast in
four days rocked the Russian capital, flattening an apartment
building, killing at least 73 people and trapping possibly dozens
more.
</P>
<P>
   Officials pressed for a crackdown against ``foreigners'' after
the predawn explosion in southern Moscow, which Russian security
officials quickly termed a terrorist act.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's blast put a gruesome twist on what had been declared a
national day of mourning for the victims of Thursday's explosion,
also in an apartment building, which killed 94 people. No one has
claimed responsibility for either explosion, and that has only made
the fear worse for stunned Muscovites.
</P>
<P>
   The two bombings are the deadliest in Moscow since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means you can never sleep in peace, you cannot know what
they will hit next,'' said Misha, a resident of a building next
door to the 9-story tenement flattened by Monday's blast, as he
watched rescue workers desperately search for survivors in the
smoldering and tangled ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers held out little hope for survivors in the rubble
of the building, which housed more than 125 people. Police said
they hoped many residents were away at country cottages when the
blast struck.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin ordered tight security at airports, nuclear power
stations and other possible targets in Moscow. He said the country
faced a major terrorist threat, but did not say who or what was
behind the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrorism has declared war on the Russian people,'' he said in
an address on Russian television. The best response, he said,
``will be your vigilance and calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin gave Moscow police 24 hours to check airports, railway
stations, cellars and attics across the capital. Quick to comply,
police began searches of apartments and set up checkpoints around
the city.
</P>
<P>
   The second explosion in less than a week fueled rumours the
Kremlin was about to introduce a state of emergency in Moscow and
other parts of Russia, a move that would cast into doubt the
parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's police chief, Nikolai Kulikov, appealed for help in
finding a man he said could be linked to Monday's explosion and the
blast last week. Officials and analysts said they believed both of
the apartment explosions, as well as a recent blast at a shopping
mall and a car bomb in southern Russia last weeek that killed 54,
were linked to federal troops battling against Islamic militants in
the southern Russian region of Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   The Interfax news agency reported that two unidentified suspects
have been detained in connection with Monday's blast. No further
details were available.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who lived in neighboring apartment buildings watched
through shattered windows as rescue workers carried the bodies of
victims away from the charred rubble and twisted metal. Books and
clothes lay scattered on the ground and hung in branches of nearby
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family members rushed to the square behind the
ruined building where the bodies were laid out. Some people,
desperately trying to find a missing relative or loved one, tore at
the plastic sheets that covered the victims as rescue workers tried
to fend them off.
</P>
<P>
   Other survivors cried openly, shaking from shock and grief as a
young policeman read out descriptions of those who had just been
found. Still more stunned neighbors stood in the cold drizzle,
staring at the white smoke billowing from the mound of rubble,
watching as trucks hauled away rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the blast, police cleared people from three adjacent
buildings after reports that explosives had been found in them,
although the reports turned out to be false.
</P>
<P>
   For bystanders, survivors and the bereaved alike, the common
denominator was fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am scared for my child, I take her to school and don't know
whether she will come home,'' said Nadezhda Narkova, 45, who passed
the scene of the blast on her way to shop.
</P>
<P>
   Leading officials blamed Islamic militants from Russia's
breakaway region of Chechnya, where Moscow fought a disastrous war
against separatists from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen-backed Islamic militants are now fighting Moscow's
forces in Dagestan, a Russian region next to Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo specifically named Chechen
rebel commander Shamil Basayev and the Jordanian-born guerrilla
Khattab as the culprits.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in Moscow was done by Khattab and Basayev and
their people. There is no doubt about it,'' Rushailo, leading the
investigation into the blasts, told NTV television.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the weekly newspaper Novaya Gazyeta reported, citing
unidentified sources, that a Chechen-led terrorist group _ composed
mostly of ethnic Slavs _ was behind the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   In a front page article titled ``We know who carried out this
bloody raid,'' journalist Vyacheslav Izmailov wrote that Khattab
and Basayev promised to pay participants in the bombing campaign up
to $50,000 each. He said the militants' plans called for seven more
bombing attacks in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday Basayev denied responsibility for last week's attack.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised address, Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov said he would
seek to deport undesirable elements from the capital and force all
non-Muscovites to re-register with the police within three days.
Anatoly Tyazhlov, governor of the region surrounding Moscow,
threatened to put anybody caught without a residency permit in a
detention camp, RIA Novosti reported.
</P>
<P>
   Several American residents of Moscow have been reported to the
police by their neighbors for looking ``suspicious.'' Some elite
downtown apartment complexes have also begun locking their outside
doors at night and requiring tenants to ring a doorbell to be
admitted to their own building. In one such building, a note to
tenants asks them to report any guests that may be visiting to the
doorman in advance and to be present when the guests arrive.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to normal police patrols, plainclothes officers
combed the Moscow subway checking the documents of anybody looking
suspicious _ which in Russia often means anyone with the dark
complexion of Caucasus natives.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians have connected the bombings to battles among
political groups in the capital as national elections approach.
Monday's edition of the newspaper Moskovsky Komsomolets, which went
to press before the latest explosion, suggested that Russia's
security services may have been behind last week's explosion _ and
were preparing another one.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling one of Moscow's favorite rumors, the paper speculated
that the Kremlin was trying to provoke a crisis and use it as a
pretext for declaring emergency rule and cancelling elections.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
