u a BC-GOVS-ENERGY-COX     09-13 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVS-ENERGY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EPA officials call for new pollution standards at Southern
Governor meeting
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ Atlanta may be the poster child for dirty air,
but other Southern cities are brewing their own pollution problems
that threaten continued growth, federal environmental officials
warned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The number of unhealthy air days has doubled or tripled in
Charlotte, N.C.; Richmond, Va.; Knoxville, Tenn.; and Washington,
D.C., over the last five years under a stringent new federal
standard, Environmental Protection Agency officials told members of
the Southern Governor's Association meeting.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, Atlanta's number of bad air days each year
quadrupled from 13 to more than 50, but ``they're catching up in
terms of pure numbers,'' John Seitz, director of the EPA's Air
Quality Planning and Standards office, said of the other Southern
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't consider air quality an issue in your state at
the current time, at the rate you're growing, I guarantee you it
will be _ unless you grow clean,'' he cautioned the governors.
</P>
<P>
   This year alone, there have been at least 34 days where 10 or
more eastern states experienced excessive smog. Even
long-recognized natural areas aren't immune: The Great Smoky
Mountains recorded 37 days of unhealthy ozone levels that make
breathing difficult.
</P>
<P>
   While the new, stricter standard is ensnarled in litigation,
even by old measurements pollution is multiplying quickly in the
South, officials said. The EPA should decide within the next month
whether to temporarily reinstate a less-rigorous air-quality
standard. If so, a handful of cities now in compliance would run
afoul of the older regulation, Seitz said.
</P>
<P>
   But getting chief executives of Southern states to cooperate
with federal officials _ and each other _ to clean up the air has
proven difficult. It's that parochialism the governors of 17 states
and two territories hope to overcome with gatherings like this that
stress the need for regional fixes cut emissions from industry,
power plants and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   In the thick of it are Georgia officials, who are providing some
guidance, even as they grapple for solutions themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we're all in this together,'' Gov. Roy Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes was hailed for the second time in as many months as an
innovator for his Georgia Regional Transportation Authority, which
has power to veto transportation projects and some major
developments in 13 counties plagued by pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Kathey Pruitt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
