<HEADER>
A0789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOREA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      09-13 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN REWARD TO NORTH KOREA, U.S. PLANS TO REMOVE SOME TRADE
SANCTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Tuesday in lede cq) 
(ms) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Rewarding North Korea for a tentative
agreement to stop testing its new long-range missile, President
Clinton said Tuesday he was preparing to lift some of the trade
sanctions that have barred commerce with the North for close to
half a century.
</P>
<P>
   The move is the first concrete step by Clinton to begin lifting
economic sanctions that have been in place since the Korean War
began in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   But the gesture revives the question, raised by congressional
critics of the administration's negotiations with North Korea, of
whether the administration is rewarding the hard-line Communist
government in Pyongyang for defusing a crisis that it created _
perhaps for negotiating advantage _ when U.S. spy satellites
detected that a missile launching appeared imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement on missile testing, disclosed on Sunday, is
limited, far from explicit and of unknown duration. In talks in
Berlin with Charles Kartman, the State Department's chief
negotiator with North Korea, the North Koreans agreed to suspend
long-range missile testing while negotiations are under way on a
more permanent ban.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing binds the North to the agreement, other than the
fear that whatever sanctions the United States lifts in coming
weeks could be reimposed.
</P>
<P>
   The text of a statement released in Berlin makes no clear
mention of the missile test ban, saying only that both countries
will ``endeavor to preserve a positive atmosphere conducive to
improved bilateral relations and to peace and security.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, speaking to reporters here Tuesday morning before
boarding a plane for Queenstown on New Zealand's South Island,
said, ``We understand and expect North Korea will refrain from
testing long-range missiles of any kind while our discussions
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the tentative accord ``an important initial step.'' In
return, he said, he is looking at ``easing sanctions'' and moving
toward a normalization of economic relations.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, working on the fringes of the Asian
economic summit meeting that ended Monday evening, portrayed the
accord as a modest but important victory at a time of sudden
instabilty throughout Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we feared,'' one administration official here said
Tuesday, ``was a new crisis in Korea at the exact moment that
there's heightened tension between China and Taiwan and the
insertion of peacekeeping troops in Indonesia. That would have been
an ugly combination, and we may have ducked it.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefing reporters Monday evening, Sandy Berger, Clinton's
national security adviser, played down the scope of the sanctions
to be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially North Korea would be in the same status as
Syria,'' he said, meaning that the types and amount of commerce
would still be strictly controlled. In theory, the eased sanctions
will allow some American companies to invest in North Korea _
though few American companies appear very eager to enter one of the
world's last Stalinist nations, and one of the poorest.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials, speaking in Washington, said it
would also be possible to transfer money to North Korea from family
members in the United States. Most cash funneled into the country
flows through Japan, which has a large Korean population centered
in Osaka.
</P>
<P>
   The lifting of the sanctions appears to be the first step in
carrying out a strategy developed by former Defense Secretary
William J. Perry, acting as a special envoy to North Korea for
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The report that Perry gave to Clinton has never been made
public. But those familiar with it describe a proposal for a finely
tuned series of moves to lift sanctions as North Korea begins to
freeze its missile arsenal and end sales of missile technology to
countries that Washington regards as rogue nations.
</P>
<P>
   A 1994 accord froze activity at North Korea's biggest nuclear
weapons plant, but it did not deal with the missiles that could
carry small nuclear weapons. Berger suggested Tuesday that if the
North Koreans made the moratorium on missile launchings permanent,
a greater easing of sanctions could follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to embark on a different course,'' he said, ``a
course which could conceivably lead to a long-term moratorium on a
missile program, that suggests the possibility of a different kind
of relationship with North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if that's the case, it's appropriate for us to take
some steps which would ease some of the sanctions that we have in
North Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``if they tested, obviously we would be going down
a different path.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how quickly a long-term ban on testing might be
negotiated, but past experience with North Korea suggests that it
could take years.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's president, Kim Dae Jung, also here for the
economic conference, praised the North Korean commitment and
characterized it as a victory for his own ``sunshine policy,'' a
series of modest economic openings to the South for North Korea.
``We view this as a sign of sincerity in the North,'' Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has been by far the most concerned about another missile
test, especially after a previous test, in August 1998, crossed
Japanese territory and created a political uproar. Japanese
officials were distinctly more muted in their reaction Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Japan has said it would consider returning to the kind of
economic relationship the two countries had before the 1998
launching, but it has offered little else in the way of incentives.
</P>
<P>
   The launching bolstered the position of conservatives in Japan
who have long argued for a more robust military. The strong
domestic reaction to last year's missile test also cleared the way
for Japan to announce that it was joining an American-led project
to develop a ``theater missile defense'' system.
</P>
<P>
   One theory about the new North Korean missile, the Taepodong 2,
is that it was invented as a negotiating chip, not an offensive
weapon. Many times in the last decade North Korea has created a
crisis, then sought its reward _ usually food aid _ for defusing
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
