<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMEX-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMEX MAY SOON FACE COMPETITION FOR SOME BEST-SELLING PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SARA ROBINSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The American Stock Exchange is facing some
fierce competition for its most popular securities, exchange-traded
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays Global Investors, which is the leader in these funds,
plans to introduce dozens of new ones next year, in what has been
regarded as a boon for the Amex.
</P>
<P>
   But Barclays has also been talking with the Chicago Board
Options Exchange about the new listings, a spokeswoman for the
options exchange confirmed Monday _ potentially creating a rival
for the Amex in a crucial market where none existed before.
</P>
<P>
   Exchange-traded funds _ which go by arcane names like SPDRs (for
Standard &AMP; Poor's depository receipts) and WEBS (for world equity
benchmark shares _ blend the characteristics of mutual funds,
closed-end funds and stocks. Each share of the fund tracks a basket
of stocks in some index, which can be traded throughout the day,
bought on margin or even sold short (a bet that their price will
decline).
</P>
<P>
   The most popular funds are SPDRs, or spiders, which are based on
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index and are owned by the Amex and
managed by the State Street Corp..
</P>
<P>
   ``The trade volume on the Amex doubled, and it's almost
completely because of these,'' Nathan Most, the former senior vice
president for new products at the Amex, said of the spiders'
introduction in 1993. ``I think it did save the Amex.''
</P>
<P>
   Barclays Global Investors, a unit of the British bank Barclays
PLC that is the leader in creating these products, declined to
comment on its discussions. But the talks open up a new battlefield
between the Amex and Chicago, which are also waging a war over
options listings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a very serious challenge to the American Stock
Exchange,'' said John C. Coffee Jr., a securities law professor at
Columbia University. ``If CBOE were able to divert trading from the
Amex in these products, then it would be an devastating blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Amex officials declined to comment on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Competition between the exchanges heated up on Friday when the
Chicago exchange, the nation's largest options exchange, said it
would list 43 options contracts now listed on the Amex starting
next Monday. Among those listings will be options on the Intel
Corp., the Amex's most active contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Amex retaliated by saying it would start trading 35 options
contracts, including those for the AT&AMP;T Corp., now the domain of
the Chicago exchange, on Tuesday and Wednesday. Until recently,
options listings were governed by a sort of gentlemen's agreement,
under which each exchange restrained from trading each other's
products. Regulators have been investigating those business and
trading practices.
</P>
<P>
   How well the Amex handles these challenges will be the first
test of its new chairman and chief executive, Salvatore F. Sodano,
who was appointed last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put together this challenge and their challenge to
the Amex's special status on trading options such as Intel,''
Coffee said, ``I'd say that you have a full-scale frontal attack
from CBOE on the core of the Amex's franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition in its core business comes at a difficult time
for Amex. Tensions are lingering from its merger in November with
the National Association of Securities Dealers, parent of the
Nasdaq market. The association made bold promises to the Amex,
saying it would invest in technology and help attract new stock
listings. But it has been slow to show results.
</P>
<P>
   Exchange-traded funds have been the Amex's mainstay in recent
years, accounting for 49 percent of its total trading volume and
almost $21 billion in assets. These products have been gaining in
popularity, even as Amex has had trouble retaining the stock
listings of successful corporations and attracting new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays, which already manages 17 country-specific Webs funds
traded on the Amex, has made preliminary filings with the
Securities and Exchange Commission to offer 51 new products early
next year, though it may bring fewer to market. About 30
exchange-traded funds now trade on the Amex, and at least some of
the new Barclays funds will probably trade there. But at risk is
the virtual monopoly that Amex now enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays is expected to file a registration statement and
prospectus for its new products this fall. The prospectus will
probably state where they will be traded, though the document could
be amended later.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the Barclays funds will be in direct competition with
existing Amex products, including funds based on the S&AMP;P 500, the
S&AMP;P 400 of mid-sized corporations and several Dow Jones indexes.
One new Barclays fund will track the S&AMP;P 500 index, as do spiders,
Amex's reputed lifesaver. The Barclays fund will be structured as
an open-end fund, allowing continuous reinvestment of dividends, an
advantage for some investors. Spiders, with more than $13 billion
in assets, are structured as a unit investment trust, paying out
dividends quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   The Amex profits from the trading generated by the products, so
having two competing products listed there would be no problem for
it. But Barclays might prefer to list its product on an exchange
where it does not have a direct competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Ed McRedmond, an analyst at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis,
said, ``I wouldn't expect that someone would necessarily sell their
spiders and buy this. But someone buying in for the first time
might choose the Barclays fund over the spider.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
