<HEADER>
A0797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS-COX     09-13 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Thrasher's Stefan hopes to be the NFL's noteworthy grown-up kid
</P>
<P>
   By Jeff Schultz
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The first sensation he felt was, dare we say,
dizziness. Patrik Stefan hadn't played in a game in six months.
Even toddlers from Pribham who make that swift transition from
crawling to centering the power play can feel like they are in a
fog after significant down time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very strange at beginning,'' Stefan said, his English
words fighting through his Czech accent. ``When you don't play, you
lose your feeling about the game. Where you have to be on defense,
on offense. It's hard, these kinds of things. But as the game went
on, I felt much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefan's NHL career is exactly one exhibition game long _ a bit
early to gauge how shrewd the Thrashers were to trade from the
second drafting position to the first to select an 18-year-old
center who suffered concussions twice last year in the
International Hockey League. The comforting news is that after a
week of full-contact scrimmages and Sunday's pre-season game in
Grand Rapids, Mich., against St. Louis, Stefan: 1) post-concussion
syndrome hasn't found its way onto the Thrashers' injury report; 2)
the head-spinning Stefan encountered Sunday was merely attributed
to not playing a game since last March.
</P>
<P>
   Stefan was pointless in the game, which is not to say his game
has been pointless. Nervous, by his own admission, at the outset of
training camp, he grew more comfortable by the day in scrimmages in
Orlando, Fla., twice scoring winning goals and another while his
team was shorthanded. He has impressed teammates with his deceptive
speed, his vision on the ice, his passing ability, the ease and
quickness with which he moves the puck. He also has shown uncommon
maturity and resolve for someone who turns 19 on Thursday. They are
traits seldom attached to young draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't always see 18-year-olds who want to listen and work
hard,'' said Kelly Buchberger, the 32-year-old winger who has been
paired up with Stefan since camp started. ``A lot of kids from the
juniors come in and don't really appreciate what it takes over here
and that it's a privilege just to play in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The common refrain since the draft has been that the Thrashers
drafted either the next Eric Lindros (a league star) or Brett
Lindros (who had to retire prematurely because of concussions).
Focus on the head blows during Stefan's abbreviated two seasons
with the Long Beach Ice Dogs increased when agent Rich Winter would
not release the player's most recent medical reports, which at
least partly contributed to Tampa Bay's decision to pass on Stefan
and spark a series of draft-day trades. The Thrashers relied on
Winter's word and their own research.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach John Van Boxmeer said he told Bob Owen, the
Thrashers' director of player development, a week before the draft
that Stefan was fine. ``Our doctors were comfortable there was no
problem with Patrik,'' Van Boxmeer said.
</P>
<P>
   Most important to the Long Beach coach was Stefan's attitude in
the IHL, where the majority of players were five to 10 years older
than him, bigger and stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players took shots at him because he was a dominant player and
he was a young European in our league,'' Van Boxmeer said. ``When
your opponent has a pre-game meeting, they're saying, 'Here's a
young kid _ hit him.' But Patrik didn't take a step backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Few know Stefan better than Owen. Before being hired by the
Thrashers, Owen ran a scouting service and helped place underage
Europeans in the IHL as a hockey prep school for the NHL draft.
Most European players opt for the Canadian juniors. The players are
younger and the style is less physical and more free wheeling. The
IHL was looking for publicity and Owen suggested signing some
Europeans. He recommended Stefan to Van Boxmeer. He had been
scouting Stefan since he was 15, and the player didn't think twice
about leaving home for North America, even though he spoke little
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that strikes you about Patrik is he's a
grown-up,'' Owen said. ``Knowing the makeup of the kid, I knew it
didn't matter if he was in Palm Springs _ he wanted to be a hockey
player. I saw him in the Czech Republic, playing against kids five
years older than him.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefan stayed with a family in Southern California and his
mother and father took turns coming out to visit from his hometown
of Pribham. The belief is that the two years in the IHL will ease
Stefan's transition to the NHL. But when Stefan was dazzling
spectators in training camp, team officials went out of their way
to say, ``No big deal,'' in hopes of keeping expectations in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to make it difficult for this kid to
succeed,'' Waddell said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Boxmeer said, ``He's not going to be playing with Jaromir
Jagr or Brett Hull. How many guys as rookies face the other team's
best checkers? That's what he's going to be facing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefan said intent on not voicing any projected point totals
this year. What's Czech for media-savvy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to put too much pressure on myself,'' he said.
``I'm trying to take things easy and slow.''
</P>
<P>
   He credits Buchberger with ``helping me with the small things on
the ice,'' and with ``yelling at me'' _ in the good way.
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger foresees greatness, just no right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to be Wayne Gretzky overnight,'' said
Buchberger, a Gretzky teammate in Edmonton. ``He's capable of being
a star in this league but it takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   PATRIK STEFAN FILE
</P>
<P>
   _ Position: Center.
</P>
<P>
   _ Age: Turns 19 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Home: Pribram, Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   _ Size: 6 feet 2, 205 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Career: Taken by the Atlanta Thrashers with the No. 1 overall
pick in the NHL entry draft in June. Played with Long Beach in the
IHL last season, scoring 11 goals and adding 24 assists for 35
points. Missed rest of the season after suffering second concussion
in March.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
