<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS AND PALESTINIANS BEGIN FINAL ROUND OF NEGOTIATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Six years to the day after Yasser Arafat and Yitzhak
Rabin shook hands at the White House and agreed on a blueprint for
peace, Palestinian and Israeli authorities Monday formally began
what both sides say should be the final but most difficult round of
their protracted negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In an evening of ceremonial cordiality at the border between
Israel and Gaza, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and Abu Mazen,
the Palestinian Authority representative, said they hoped to agree
on terms for a permanent settlement within just one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement will end _ God willing _ the bloody feud
between our two people for the past 100 years,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Mazen, a principal architect of the 1993 peace agreement, also
spoke of ``a historic reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet neither man played down the challenge for negotiators
confronting the most contentious of the many unresolved issues
here: borders, armaments, Jewish settlers, Palestinian refugees and
_ most explosive of all _ the political future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   There are other daunting problems. Ancient property disputes
must be redressed, and competing claims to religious sites
adjudicated. What will be even more critical is an equitable
allocation of water resources in desert territories with growing
populations and shrinking aquifers.
</P>
<P>
   In just five months, the two sides are supposed to produce a
``framework agreement'' detailing all outstanding issues, with
proposed timetables and formulas for their resolution. By Sept. 13,
2000, the Israelis and Palestinians say they hope to have a final
peace pact ready for signature.
</P>
<P>
   What was unstated in Monday's ceremony was the underlying
Palestinian expectation that shortly after such an accord, the
Palestinian Authority could declare statehood, under terms to which
Israel and the United States had already agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Many Palestinians remain dubious. They note that this is, in
effect, the third renegotiation and rescheduling of peace
commitments made at the White House in 1993. Under the terms of the
1993 pact, the ``final status'' phase of the negotiations was to
have begun no later than 1997 and concluded by May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Ross, the State Department's veteran Middle East
negotiator, suggested after attending the inauguration of the talks
Monday night that the one-year deadline may be unrealistic. ``It's
definitely going to be very difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Prime Minister Ehud Barak, elected in May on a promise to
forge a secure peace, has moved more quickly than skeptics
expected. Almost immediately after renegotiating the last stalled
land-for-peace deal, he began withdrawing Israeli troops and
administrators from more disputed corners of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   He gave Palestinians the long-delayed go-head to build their own
commercial seaport, and promises to open the first bus-and-taxi
corridor between the West Bank and Gaza within three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to emphasize our partnership with Ehud Barak, which
will enable us to reach a common goal,'' Mazen said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   As the contours of compromise become visible, the Barak
government and the Palestinian Authority are prepared for a bitter
backlash, including violence, from opponents of the peace deal in
both communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``While implementing the agreements to which we have committed
ourselves, the Israeli government will face difficulties, and maybe
even dangers,'' Levy warned cabinet colleagues last week.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Levy's concerns, Mazen said Monday night that the
``faces of terror are still interested in destroying the peace
process and in killing innocent people.'' He repeated the
Palestinian Authority's vows to continue collaborating with Israel
on eradicating terrorism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
