<HEADLINE>
THE FINER ARTS OF DRINKING AND EATING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women are better at tasting wine than men, writes wine importer
and expert  &UR; Kermit Lynch  &LR; of Berkeley in Food &AMP; Wine. Lynch,
apologizing for generalizing about gender, claims that men approach
the tasting ``with cartfuls of excess baggage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When they stick their nose into a glass of wine they think it
would be unmanly to say something wrong or stupid. So they get
uptight. It is difficult to taste properly when you are uptight.
Fear constricts the flow of blood to the taste buds.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman, on the other hand, says ``the first thing that pops
into her head, fearlessly, and it is amazing how often such
spontaneous responses are appropriate and interesting. Women
approach wine with their noses wide open, and the directness of an
unself-conscious reaction can be refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, American men generally want what Lynch calls a
``big'' wine. Lynch says that ``size'' is relevant only with
respect to the food served with the wine. ``You wouldn't select a
light wine with dinosaur stew and you wouldn't want a big clunker
with oysters. ... Choosing a wine is not like a caveman choosing a
club, but a lot of men cannot get past that stage of development.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MISS AMERICA ALTERATIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The board of the Miss America Organization has voted to allow
women who are divorced or who have been pregnant to run for Miss
America, beginning next year. Since 1950, contestants have had to
swear that they were free from any such taint; contestants will
hereafter sign a document swearing to be unmarried and unpregnant
at contest time.
</P>
<P>
   The change was necessitated by New Jersey discrimination laws,
and would have come a year earlier had it not been fought by
individual state pageants. ``Miss America has a long history of
high moral standards and traditions and I'm opposed to anything
that changes that,'' said  &UR; Libby Taylor &LR;  of the Miss Kentucky
pageant.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this year's contestants were equally indignant. ``The
most important thing Miss America does is she's a role model,''
said Miss West Virginia  &UR; Lucy Ours &LR; . ``If she's been married and
divorced by age 24, people might not look at her as a very good
role model.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOOD WORKS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sharon Stone &LR; , who was scheduled to co-host Macy's Passport
fashion show on Friday, night two of the AIDS fund-raiser, has
agreed to fill in for  &UR; Elizabeth Taylor &LR;  on opening night,
Thursday. Stone will read a message from Taylor, who is laid up
with a fractured vertebra.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Young Musicians Program at the University of California at
Berkeley, which provides free music lessons to young people, is
collecting (tax-deductible) donations of frequent-flier miles, to
be used to buy airline tickets for travel packages to be auctioned
at an October 25 fund-raiser. More information is at (510)
642-9394.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Vanessa Redgrave &LR; , UNICEF special representative for the
performing arts, is presiding over a three-day festival of the arts
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Friends of &UR; Victor Perera &LR; , the Bay Area writer and
intellectual who a year ago suffered an incapacitating stroke, are
holding an evening of Sephardic and Middle Eastern Jewish music to
raise money for him on September 26 in Portola Valley. Call (650)
493-0563 ext. X &LR; 250 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   _ A California Lawyer story on big firms' summer associate
programs _ designed to entice law students to postgraduate jobs _
lists such perks as long lunches, pool parties, whitewater rafting,
wine tasting, cooking school, weekends at Yosemite and the Napa
Valley, rock concert tickets and cultural excursions.
</P>
<P>
   But 11 associates at Townsend and Townsend and Crew were taken
one Saturday to the Youth Guidance Center in San Francisco, where
they pitched in to give Juvie a new coat of paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law students come onboard and expect that the world is a
certain way,'' the firm's  &UR; Tina Nasseri &LR;  said. ``It's good for them
to see the way the rest of the people are living.''
</P>
<P>
   _ At the Solano Stroll on Sunday, the Peace and Freedom Party
invited people to vote on the death penalty by each putting one
bean into one of the glass jars labeled either ``Abolish the Death
Penalty'' or ``Kill! Kill! Kill!'' A few brave souls dared place
their beans in the latter, but  &UR; Steve Finacom  &LR; says the party needs
help ``in conducting unbiased elections!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``After Sandor observed a dozen Hasidic Jews watching her fish
in the Colorado River, she was compelled, because of her own Jewish
ancestry, to research the relationship between Jews and fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Publishers Weekly description of an essay in Marjorie
Sandor's ``The Night Gardener: A Search for Home'' (Lyons; $22.95),
culled by Betsy Nolan.
</P>
</TEXT>
