<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-U.S.-ART-NYT &LR;      09-13 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARER OF THE TOUGH NEWS: CHAIRMAN OF JOINT CHIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TIMOR-RDP, TIMOR-U.N.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the violence in East Timor worsened, the
Americans relied on one person to deliver a tough message to the
the Indonesian government, senior administration officials said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The go-between was the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
Gen. Henry H. Shelton, who dealt on the phone with his counterpart,
General Wiranto, the head of Indonesia's powerful military.
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton condemned the Indonesian military's
refusal to stop the violence in East Timor, Shelton spoke three
times with Wiranto, culminating on Friday with what senior
officials called an ``ugly message.''
</P>
<P>
   Using specific and emphatic language, Shelton said the United
States would block the International Monetary Fund from delivering
the billions of dollars that Indonesia needs to recover further
from the Asian economic crisis, senior administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Wiranto asked the United States to wait 24 hours
while he visited East Timor to see if his army was maintaining
order, these officials said. If he thought the Indonesian army was
lax, Wiranto promised to ask for international peacekeepers to come
in.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday morning, Wiranto phoned Shelton with his report
from East Timor, which was not good, and with the news that he was
recommending that President B.J. Habibie ask immediately for the
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   The administration late last week decided it had to step up the
pressure on Indonesia, officials said, to counteract a growing
public perception that the White House was dealing timidly with the
crisis, in order to preserve a relationship with Indonesia, a
country of 200 million people that has rich natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't looking very valiant, and nobody liked that around
here,'' said an administration official. ``Our spine got
stiffened.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Clinton administration shifted from a policy of resisting
sanctions to making a serious threat to the Indonesian economy,
Shelton relayed the increasingly urgent messages that the
Indonesian army had to end the killings and destruction in East
Timor. That message was underlined by Adm. Dennis C. Blair,
commander in chief of the U.S. Pacific Command, who traveled to
Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Pentagon is beginning preparations to provide logistical
support for a multinational peacekeeping mission for East Timor,
and the Clinton administration is arguing that the channel to the
Indonesian military speaks to the value of the the years of
training given to Indonesia's future military leaders in the United
States and the millions of dollars that the United States spent on
military aid to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big plus to have someone who could call the
Indonesian military _ they were the ones calling the shots,'' said
a senior administration official. ``We had a unique asset and I
don't see how our military could have done it without their past
history with these generals.''
</P>
<P>
   As the crisis deepened and it became clear that only Wiranto
could halt the massacres and destruction to the small territory,
and not Habibie, the administration leaned on the military to
convey its messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that General Wiranto could have turned off
the violence much sooner,'' said a senior Defense official. ``But
he and the rest of the government were waiting to see if their plan
to get something less than full independence for East Timor would
work.''
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the White House, Shelton placed his first call
to Wiranto last Monday, and received assurances that, with the
imposition of martial law in East Timor, there would be peace in
two days.
</P>
<P>
   But when militias and elements of the army continued terrorizing
and murdering civilians, Blair went to Jakarta for a tense
30-minute interview with Wiranto. They allowed no aides in the
meeting and spoke in English to avoid the need for interpreters.
</P>
<P>
   Blair informed Wiranto that the administration was cutting off
the remainder of American military relations with his country,
according to administration officials, and he then left the
country, canceling a speech he was to deliver before a military
academy in Bandung.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, after Wiranto traveled to East Timor with a team
of diplomats from the U.N. Security Council, he phoned Shelton with
his decision to yield to international pressure and ask for
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first credible sign that Indonesia would allow in
peacekeepers,'' said a senior administration official.
</P>
</TEXT>
