<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0815 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TIMOR-U.N.-560(2TAKES     09-13 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-U.N.-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA CONCERNED ABOUT COMPOSITION OF U.N. PEACEKEEPING FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TIMOR-RDP, TIMOR-U.S.) 
(js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Indonesia's foreign minister told the U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the Security Council Monday that
his government would welcome the speedy deployment of an
international force for East Timor but had some questions about the
nationalities of its commander and troops.
</P>
<P>
   The council, which is expected to act in the next day or two,
worked late into the night Monday on a draft resolution submitted
by Britain that would give the force the strongest military
authority under the U.N. Charter. The draft indicates that an
Australian would be designated the overall commander, a decision
strongly backed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, in Darwin, an Australian port city 250 miles
from East Timor, preparations for action have already begun, with
the Australians apparently confident that they will lead the force.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian foreign minister, Ali Alatas, said that his
country would set no conditions but that it would prefer soldiers
from neighboring Asian countries that are members of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations. Some of those nations,
including Thailand, Malaysia, Singapore and the Philippines, have
said they would participate. British Gurkha troops based in Brunei
are also on call.
</P>
<P>
   For many Indonesians, however, Australia is a provocative and
politically explosive choice because it has been a strong supporter
of East Timorese independence leaders, and the two countries had
very rocky relations until relatively recently. Some Security
Council members have qualms about this choice, a diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Australia has named a commander, Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove, a
Vietnam War veteran, and is assembling ships, helicopters and a
high-speed catamaran capable of carrying more than 500 troops.
France has sent four military officers to advise the Australians,
and 10 U.S. military experts are also in Darwin to help draw up
plans. At the Pentagon, Adm. Craig R. Quigley, a spokesman, said
that the United States was preparing to use its huge cargo planes
to transport troops and equipment but had not selected ships or
soldiers for duty, pending action by the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The council, which appears united on the need for a quick
deployment of troops, is unlikely to specify the number or
nationalities of soldiers in the force apart from the commander.
Those decisions would be left to the troop-contributing countries
and U.N. peacekeeping experts.
</P>
<P>
   In Jakarta, Indonesian nationalists are demanding that no
Americans, New Zealanders or Portuguese take part. Portugal was the
former colonial power in East Timor, and Americans, New Zealanders
and other non-Asians are apparently viewed as prejudiced against
Indonesia. A diplomat suggested that Indonesia's long years under
often harsh Dutch rule had left a legacy of revulsion against
European domination, which explains a persistent cultural or racial
subtext to the debate about peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Annan told the Security Council Monday that Indonesian
``sensitivities'' had to be taken into account, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come here to prevent any country from
participating,'' said Alatas, but he hinted broadly that the issue
should be weighed. ``It is up to the countries themselves to
consider whether it is appropriate, whether their presence would or
would not exacerbate the situation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Mobs in Indonesia have been attacking Australian diplomatic and
trade missions over the last week, including an attack Monday in
Surabaya. Alatas said Monday that these are responses to Australian
attacks on Indonesian consulates and its embassy in Australia,
which he said is being boycotted and can't get basic supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the outside chance that mounting political pressures
will cause President B.J. Habibie to balk at the last minute,
diplomats here were relieved to hear Alatas' message Monday and are
more or less optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if I'm optimistic or pessimistic,'' Richard C.
Holbrooke, the U.S. representative, said in an interview after
Monday's Security Council meeting. But he said he saw no real
opposition in the council to quick action, and he marveled at the
speed with which the situation had turned around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty-eight hours ago we were looking at the worst,'' he said.
``Twenty-four hours ago we were trying to parse the meaning of
Habibie. Now we're working on implementation. That's a pretty
impressive record for the Security Council and for Kofi.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, even if we got there too slowly,'' Holbrooke said,
``the last 48 hours have been a major step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's envoy, Antonio Monteiro, said that he welcomed
Alatas' assurances that he was not seeking to set conditions. ``We
are very encouraged,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Jeremy Greenstock, Britain's U.N. representative and a
member of a team of five ambassadors sent to Indonesia last week to
urge the government to accept outside help in East Timor, where a
vote for independence by the territory's population set off a week
of terror inflicted by pro-Indonesian militias, said Monday on his
return from Jakarta that he thought Indonesian government officials
had underestimated the scale of the crisis and had needed to be
persuaded ``to think again'' about their resistance to foreign
military assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Alatas told reporters Monday that while he would like more
discussion on the composition of the force, ``what is important is
that Indonesia would like to see this security cooperation, the
sending of a force as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that an international peacekeeping force had been
authorized under the May 5 agreement on the future of East Timor.
But the troops been called for only in the third phase of the
process, after the Indonesian parliament had ratified the
referendum results, probably in November, and the United Nations
would take over administration of East Timor until the new
country's first elections. Until the ratification, Indonesian
troops were supposed to be responsible for law and order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, however, the situation is different,'' Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a multinational force with Security Council backing
rather than an full-dress U.N. peacekeeping operation is essential
to the Clinton administration because of congressional restraints
on U.S. participation and payments for official peacekeeping
operations. A multinational force does not require congressional
notification and the bills for it go to the countries involved and
not to member nations of the United Nations, which would pass 31
percent of the costs on to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Another unknown factor in the Indonesian political environment
now is the attitude of Megawati Sukarnoputri, whose party came in
first _ but without a majority _ in the Indonesian assembly
elections in June. The daughter of Indonesia's first president,
Sukarno, who was an uncompromising nationalist where the unity of
Indonesia was concerned, Ms. Megawati initially opposed the
decision to allow the East Timorese to vote on their future in a
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Although she later seemed to soften that view, the Security
Council mission that visited Indonesia last week said in its report
Monday that she had again criticized Habibie strongly for agreeing
to sign the May 5 agreement with Portugal and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``She declined to go public in support of the idea of
international intervention,'' the report from the five ambassadors
said. She told the team that Habibie's legitimacy as leader of
Indonesia was ``fading away.''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie, like Ms. Megawati, is also a likely candidate for the
Indonesian presidency, when a choice is made by indirect election
through the assembly later in the year. Experts say that she could
attract support from the armed forces and other strongly
nationalist groups opposed to any foreign presence in what they
regard as Indonesia, even if East Timor was always a separate case,
incorporated without being internationally recognized as part of
Indonesia since it was seized by Jakarta's troops in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   It is not inconceivable, some U.N. officials and diplomats say,
that a strong nationalist tide could undo the East Timor agreement
or at least weaken it and allow a civil war to break out in the
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Alexandre Gusmao, the East Timorese rebel leader known as
Xanana, told the Security Council mission last week that the
conditions for an outbreak of fighting between his forces and the
Indonesian army already existed. Gusmao, who was in Indonesian
custody for seven years before being released last week and taking
refuge in the British Embassy, urged a quick deployment of an
international force.
</P>
<P>
   In their recommendations to the Security Council, the envoys who
returned Monday from Jakarta said the government of Indonesia
should continue to be pressed to curtail the militias that have
terrorized East Timor and driven hundreds of thousands of people
from their homes and should insure that the militias do not provoke
fighting with Gusmao's rebel troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
