r a BC-WACO-TEX     09-13 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS HAD EVIDENCE OF TEAR GAS CANISTERS IN 1995, DEMOCRAT SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
And GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congress was given evidence four years ago that pyrotechnic tear
gas canisters were used in the FBI raid on the Branch Davidian
compound in 1993, Democratic Rep. Henry Waxman of California said
on Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Congressional investigations into the 1993 standoff were
triggered by recent news reports that the FBI had failed to
disclose the use of the military-style canisters until this year.
But Waxman said congressional investigators were told about the
canisters during the last round of investigations in 1995. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The documents repeatedly refer to military canisters without
specifically mentioning the possibility that they can generate
fire. No evidence has surfaced linking the tear gas to the fatal
fire, which the government says was started by Davidian leader
David Koresh and his followers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess, hypothetically, maybe the staffs read over these
documents and didn't understand the terms. Maybe they didn't think
much about it,'' Waxman said. ``But the facts seem to be that the
attorney general and her Department of Justice and the FBI sent the
Congress, in 1995, documents that military tear gas was used.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Waxman is ranking Democrat on the House Government Reform
Committee, chaired by Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., who said on Monday
that he is expanding his committee's new investigation of the
standoff to look into whether FBI snipers fired into the compound
on the final day of the standoff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burton announced the expansion of the investigation after the
Texas Rangers disclosed that they had collected a dozen spent rifle
casings from a house used by FBI snipers during the 1993 siege. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the evidence was far from conclusive because the same house
also was used by agents from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms during their firefight with sect members on the first day
of the standoff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And the Rangers' report cites concerns raised not by the
Rangers, but by Colorado film researcher Mike McNulty, who last
year was allowed to review the evidence being held by the Texas
Department of Public Safety. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike McNulty has questioned .308 Winchester cases located at
the undercover house, which may show that the FBI snipers fired
rounds on 04-19-93,'' the report states. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials have repeatedly said that their agents did not
fire during the 51-day confrontation that ended when a devastating
fire roared through the compound. Koresh and about 80 of his
followers died in the siege. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the evidence gathered by the Texas Rangers ``raises
new concerns that require further investigation by Congress.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other Justice Department critics said Waxman's findings
concerning the pyrotechnic tear gas canisters do not exonerate
Attorney General Janet Reno or her subordinates because federal
agents never highlighted the information. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, three days before the hearings, they dumped over
100,000 pages worth of documents on the committee staff,'' Burton
spokesman Mark Corallo said. ``I think it was up to them to point
it out to us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corallo also noted that Reno has said that she was unaware of
the incendiary canisters. Responding to news reports late last
month, Reno expressed outrage that she did not know about their use
in Waco. She had no immediate reaction to Waxman's disclosures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The report from the Texas Rangers opens a new line of inquiry by
raising the possibility that FBI snipers shot at the Branch
Davidians. The Texas law enforcement agency released its report on
the Internet late Sunday after delivering copies of the document to
Burton's committee and independent investigator John Danforth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers said in their report that they reviewed selected
items from the 24,000 pounds of evidence after questions were
raised about the use of the pyrotechnic canisters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 11-page report contains highly technical information
that breaks down the type of casings found, the manufacturers who
produce the ammunition and quotations from manuals explaining the
chemical breakdown of various tear gas canisters found at the
scene. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the spent casings was from a 40mm cartridge reportedly
used to knock down a door so gas could be dispensed, the report
says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And as was expected, the report confirms the FBI's use of the
pyrotechnic tear gas grenades, which burn at 500 to 700 degrees
Fahrenheit and can ignite flammable items. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The report repeatedly cites concerns raised by McNulty, a
longtime critic of the government's handling of the siege. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike McNulty has advised me that other evidence held by the
DPS is crucial to proving some of his suspicions that the FBI and
ATF have not been truthful in their account of the Branch Davidian
investigation,'' Rangers Sgt. Joey D. Gordon wrote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, McNulty asserts that a blue knit cap worn by a
Davidian killed during the ATF raid might provide evidence that the
man was shot at close range, which contradicts reports by ATF
agents, who say he was shot from a distance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers report includes several other photos and documents,
including a letter Assistant U.S. Attorney Bill Johnston wrote to
Attorney General Janet Reno in August in which he alleges a
government cover-up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``... I have formed the belief that facts may have been kept
from you _ and quite possibly are being kept from you even now, by
components of the Department.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The report also includes a June 1999 interoffice memo from
Rangers Sgt. George L. Turner, who says he recovered a ``Thumper
Round'' from the scene, which was later identified as the 40mm
cartridge believed to have been used to knock down the door. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Thumper Round, which Turner's report says is highly
explosive, reportedly was fired by the FBI. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turner notified Rangers and FBI officials of his findings, but
did not pursue the matter any further. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I never came forward with the information that would seem to
indicate that an explosive projectile was fired on April 19,
1993,'' Turner says in his memo. ``But I was never asked the
question. If I had been, I would have naturally responded with the
truth.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turner said Rangers officials who testified in the 1995 Senate
subcommittee hearings were reminded of the ``possibility that an
explosive round having been fired.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, appointed last week by Reno to investigate the final
day of the siege, declined to comment on the Rangers' findings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He is no longer commenting on anything,'' an aide to the St.
Louis lawyer said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a related matter, justice department attorneys asked on
Monday for a two-week extension in turning over information about
expert witnesses scheduled to testify at a lawsuit brought by
Branch Davidians, the Associated Press reported. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Caddell, lead attorney for the Branch Davidians, told AP
that while he does not object to the extension, it's another reason
to delay the trial set for Oct. 18. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter Smith Jr. has not ruled on the
motion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
