<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BURNETT-AD-COLUMN-ART     09-13 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNETT-AD-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEO BURNETT IS REORGANIZING ITSELF ON TWO FRONTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago, the agency company known for
warm, whimsical and character-driven campaigns for blue-chip brands
like Hallmark, Keebler, Kellogg and Maytag, is making two big
changes, a corporate reorganization and a realignment of senior
management.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are the most significant at Burnett since a palace
coup in March 1997 that toppled two top executives. That shake-up,
unprecedented for Burnett, came after difficulties that included
the loss of large creative accounts like Miller Lite beer as well
as large creative and media-services assignments for marketers like
United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there has been a marked upturn in Burnett's fortunes
_ fortuneately for Burnett, a privately held company that must
strive to keep up with bigger, publicly traded competitors like the
Interpublic Group of Companies, Omnicom Group and WPP Group PLC. A
good deal of the credit for the improvements goes to Richard B.
Fizdale, the chariman who retook the reins of power as chief
executive in the coup.
</P>
<P>
   Fizdale, a Burnetter since 1969, helped Burnett land additional
work from clients like Coca-Cola, Heinz and Procter &AMP; Gamble as
well as new accounts from advertisers like Delta Air Lines,
Motorola, G.D. Searle and Toys ``R'' Us.
</P>
<P>
   He also presided over the spinoff of Burnett's media services
operations as an autonomous unit, Starcom Worldwide; the
acquisition of a 49 percent stake in Bartle Bogle Hegarty, a
so-called creative hot shop, and the formation of specialty units
like Vigilante, for urban marketing; Lapiz, for campaigns aimed at
Hispanic consumers, and TFA/Leo Burnett Technology Group, for
high-technology clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to stop the bleeding,'' Fizdale said in a
telephone interview Monday after the changes were formally
announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nineteen-ninety-six was one of the worst years we've had, but
since 1997, we've won a lot of business,'' he added. ``And where
the agency did not have a global plan, we do now.''
</P>
<P>
   An agency's state of health is ``never perfect,'' Fizdale said,
``always fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a lot to feel really good about,'' he added,
seemingly undaunted even by a visit to the dentist before his
interview.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the shifts this time around are by all accounts
more characteristically Burnett-like: collegial, low key and
harmonious.
</P>
<P>
   Effective Jan. 1, Fizdale, 60, will again relinquish his duties
as chief executive _ for good, he promised, laughing that ``I
guarantee there will not be another coup unless it's to get rid of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizdale will remain chairman for what he described as an
open-ended period, focusing on tasks like determining Burnett's
place in the digital and interactive media arenas.
</P>
<P>
   Roger A. Haupt, chief operating officer, will assume Fizdale's
duties as chief executive. Haupt, 51, who joined Burnett in 1984,
has been considered Fizdale's heir apparent, overseeing management
of the important Motorola and Procter &AMP; Gamble accounts in addition
to Burnett's administrative, financial and information technology
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working together a long time,'' Haupt said in a
separate interview, referring to his relationship with Fizdale,
``and we both feel pretty good about where we stand, the momentum
we have.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I will carry that on as aggressively as we have
been, becoming more diversified, more global. And there'll be more
innovation, I hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Haupt is considered one of the strongest supporters of plans by
Burnett to sell at least 10 percent of the agency to Dentsu Inc. in
Tokyo, the Japanese advertising giant. Those discussions continue;
an agreement is expected before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the talks, Burnett will remain an
independent, privately held company, Haupt said, adding: ``That
status is unchanged. And I don't have any plans to change it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also effective Jan. 1, Haupt will assume the additional duties
of president from James G. Oates, who will retire at the end of
1999. Oates, 56, had previously agreed to delay by two years his
departure from Burnett, where he has spent his entire 33-year
advertising career.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the management realignment is the formal adoption
of a holding company structure for Burnett, which is ranked No. 12
among the world's agency companies by billings, with an estimated
$7 billion, and No. 9 by revenue at $949.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   From now on, Leo Group will be the name of the ultimate parent
company, owning units like the Leo Burnett Co., specializing in
advertising, and Starcom, specializing in media services, and
managing the 49 percent stake in Bartle Bogle.
</P>
<P>
   Those inclined to make jokes about Leo Group ``roaring'' into
existence may do so here. The reference is of course not to the
M-G-M lion but to Leo Burnett, who founded Burnett in 1935 and was
named one of the most influential industry leaders of the century
by the trade publication Advertising Age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be Gizmo Inc. or Oxycon,'' Fizdale said,
adding: ``One day we were sitting around trying to come up with a
name for the holding company and someone _ Chris Kimball, I
believe, our chief administrative officer _ opined that if it's the
name of a person, it's easier to clear globally. So we said, `How
about Leo Group?' and it never changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Leo Burnett is known for a speech he gave in 1967 addressed to
his successors titled ``When To Take My Name Off the Door,''
admonishing them to adhere to his principles.
</P>
<P>
   Even though such abandonment of the founder's ways would now
require his name be scraped off two doors rather than one, there is
nothing to worry about, according to Fizdale: ``It's not time yet.
And it never will be.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
