<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAPANESE YEN RISES 2.2 PERCENT IN A RALLY AGAINST THE DOLLAR
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese yen resumed its more than two-month rally against
the dollar, jumping 2.2 percent to a three-year high. Analysts said
the rally should continue. In New York, the yen settled at 106.44
to the dollar, up from 108.81.
</P>
<P>
   The surge came after the Bank of Japan intervened in the
foreign-exchange market on Friday and staved off the rally for a
day. But the selling of yen for dollars worked for only one day
because Japanese officials made clear that they were not trying to
change the direction of the yen, only to slow its rise.
</P>
<P>
   GIANT SECURITIES FRAUD IS SUSPECTED
</P>
<P>
   Martin A. Armstrong, chairman of an investment and economic
research company and its brokerage firm subsidiary in Hong Kong,
has been charged with engaging in an enormous securities fraud that
U.S. prosecutors say has left Japanese companies with more than
$500 million in losses.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA SEEKS SET-TOP BOX MAKER
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, long a dominant player in the semiconductor and
cellular-telephone markets, is trying to acquire General
Instrument, the leading maker of cable set-top boxes, people close
to the talks said. In doing so, Motorola is trying to be a leader
in merging voice, data and video applications and funneling them
directly into homes through one broadband cable device. Shares of
Motorola fell $8.375, to $90.375.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED AS NASDAQ RETREATS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended mixed as investors stepped back from Friday's rally
in technology shares. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 1.90
points, to 11,030.33. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell
7.53 points, to 1,344.13, and the Nasdaq composite index fell 42.29
points, or 1.5 percent, to 2,844.77.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR SECURITIES FIRMS BACK PRIMEX
</P>
<P>
   The four largest securities firms in the United States have
joined forces to back Primex Trading, which is aiming to be an
electronic version of the New York Stock Exchange. The support
gives Primex a jump-start in the world of electronic trading.
</P>
<P>
   VENCOR IN CHAPTER 11 BANKRUPTCY
</P>
<P>
   Vencor, the troubled nursing-home chain, filed for protection
Monday under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy laws.
</P>
<P>
   LEO BURNETT REALIGNS MANAGEMENT
</P>
<P>
   Leo Burnett in Chicago, the agency company, is making two big
changes, a corporate reorganization and a realignment of senior
management. Effective Jan. 1, Richard Fizdale will relinquish his
duties as chief executive but will remain chairman. Roger Haupt,
the chief operating officer, will assume Fizdale's duties as chief
executive. Accompanying the management realignment is the formal
adoption of a holding-company structure for Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   TALKS PROGRESS ON UAW PACTS
</P>
<P>
   With the auto industry fat and happy, and both labor and
management eager to keep it that way, the United Automobile Workers
moved closer to agreeing to new contracts with DaimlerChrysler and
General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   INCYTE SHARES FALL ON PATENT RULING
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Incyte Pharmaceuticals plunged and shares in
Affymetrix soared after a ruling in favor of Affymetrix in a patent
dispute over gene-chip technology.
</P>
<P>
   AMEX COULD FACE RIVAL FOR FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   The American Stock Exchange is facing some fierce competition
for its most popular products, financial instruments known as
exchange-traded funds, which blend the characteristics of mutual
funds, closed-end funds and stocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
