<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RANGERS ISSUE REPORT ON SIEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With WACO-DOCUMENTS) 
(af) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The report released Monday by the Texas Rangers
will not definitively answer any of the ``dark questions'' about
the Branch Davidian siege that John Danforth has promised to answer
in his independent investigation. But it makes plain the awkward
role facing the Rangers as the different Branch Davidian
investigations begin to gather steam.
</P>
<P>
   Initiated three months ago on orders from James B. Francis Jr.,
the chairman of the Texas Department of Public Safety, the Rangers
report was narrowly focused by design. Last month, a spokesman for
the Rangers, Mike Cox, pointedly said the agency was not
investigating the FBI or the Justice Department. Instead, Cox said,
the inquiry focused on key pieces of evidence believed to be
sitting inside state storage rooms in Austin and Waco.
</P>
<P>
   But nonetheless, the persistent probing of the Rangers and the
outspoken comments by Francis have played significant roles in
applying the pressure that has resulted in the new Washington
investigations into the 1993 events near Waco. Much of what was
included in Monday's inch-thick Ranger's report was not new: the
uncovering of a potentially flammable incendiary device had been
disclosed last month; the significance of rifle shells found inside
a house near the compound that had been used by the FBI Hostage
Rescue Team has been a subject of dispute for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beginning rather than an end,'' said Michael Caddell,
the lawyer representing families of deceased Branch Davidian
members in a wrongful death lawsuit against the government. ``It is
the first time that any government officials have looked seriously
at these issues. I think it raises more questions than it
answers.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, where the Rangers, the state's top law-enforcement
agency, enjoy a nearly revered status as throwbacks to the state's
cowboy origins, the release of the report had been widely
anticipated as the renewed investigations into the siege dominated
local headlines and newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, The Austin American-Statesman obtained a copy on
Sunday, a day before the Rangers' planned to release it, after
filing a lawsuit Friday to force its immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   But the inquiry's narrow focus reinforces the uncomfortable
reality that the Rangers are potentially uncovering evidence that
could ultimately be used against the federal government in the
wrongful death lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got into the case in 1993 at the behest of federal
prosecutors in Texas, who asked them to take charge of the crime
scene after the fire and collect evidence from the compound. The
evidence was then used by federal prosecutors in the 1994 criminal
cases against several Branch Davidian members who were convicted of
killing four agents with the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   For the last six years, an estimated 24,000 pounds of the
evidence has remained in storage rooms in Austin and Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, the Rangers asked the federal judge in the
wrongful death lawsuit to take control of all the evidence, a
motion the judge granted. Then, Francis, a political appointee of
Gov. George W. Bush, ordered an investigation into the evidence
itself after questions were raised by an independent filmmaker,
Michael McNulty, who had toured the storage rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Francis has questioned the role of the military on the day of
the fire. The Pentagon has said that three members of an elite
military unit were at the compound, as observers, on the day of the
fire. But a recent deposition filed by the Justice Department in
the civil lawsuit revealed that as many as 10 soldiers were present
at the compound at different times during the 51-day siege.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     09-13 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AFTER MIRER, PARCELLS HAS DOUBTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ On the morning after one fateful step led to a
frightful snap, which begot much frustration and sorrow, Bill
Parcells made it clear that he was not exactly counting on Rick
Mirer to write a fantastic sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was the situations,'' Parcells said Monday, when
asked about Mirer's less than scintillating career. ``We'll see.
I'll try to give him the best chance to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   This didn't sound like a coach going out of his way to assure
his team that all was well, that Mirer could step in and be for the
Jets what Vinny Testaverde was last year. Despite the obvious
parallels of underachievement elsewhere, despite Testaverde's sunny
assessment of Mirer's ``identical'' circumstances to his own last
fall, Parcells' queasy expressions and coach's careful-speak were
an admonishment against trying to anticipate Mirer into something
he's not.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, remember, recruited Testaverde before the 1998 season
because he never believed Glenn Foley had the body to survive. When
he spoke of Testaverde last summer, he frequently endorsed his size
and skills. He cited Testaverde's playoff run in Cleveland, his Pro
Bowl season in Baltimore. You suspected Parcells strongly believed
the veteran from Long Island could flourish with the offensive
weaponry the Jets had assembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' was the best he could do on the sudden hot
subject of Mirer, the 1993 rookie of the year in Seattle, who was
also unceremoniously dumped by the punchless Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's right to assume that, offensively, we're
not going to function,'' Parcells also said Monday, as the Jets
regrouped for re-evaluation, after being sacked Sunday on first
down, by fate. On the other hand, for those wishing to second-guess
Parcells for being caught in the predicament of not having a
trustworthy backup with the benefit of a full training camp, he
pointed out that he had pursued early-summer deals for Eric Zeier
and Rodney Peete. Which I guess could also be interpreted as
Parcells' admitting that Mirer was not even on his radar screen
until The Great Zolak and Ray from Rutgers had been ordained
preseason flops.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't dial a quarterback into the system,'' Parcells
said, although his SOS to Ron Wolf, his buddy in Green Bay, did
result in the routing of Mirer to Weeb Ewbank Hall.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Parcells did not blame the artificial turf at
Giants Stadium for Testaverde's torn Achilles' tendon. But then,
how could he? He has always said he prefers grass, but has also
rejected the notion of being ``part of any experiment'' that might
result in the Jets playing on a bad grass field, which, he argued,
is worse. The result is that Wayne Chrebet is out six weeks, Leon
Johnson for the season and Testaverde for who knows how long after
that?
</P>
<P>
   Of course grass should be installed, turf qualifying as a
serious workplace abuse the players' union should have taken on
years ago. Yet Dan Marino suffered the same Achilles' injury, on
grass. This is what usually happens, almost inexplicably, in the
bodies of men and women past their athletic primes.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a doctor out there who can accurately advise Patrick
Ewing how much rest it will take before his feet are pain free? Who
can assure David Cone that his right arm won't play dead when
post-season comes? Testaverde. Ewing. Cone. That's merely the Super
Bowl, National Basketball Association finals and World Series
perhaps turning on the health of three 30-something stars.
</P>
<P>
   In a season that begins with the return of the pitiful and
futile instant replay, the Testaverde injury is also a jarring
reminder that human frailty cannot be legislated out of sports. ``I
just pushed off to go get the ball,'' said Testaverde, a class act,
even hours out of surgery that cut away his dream. ``My last
thought was, `My Achilles popped and I'm out for the season.'''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde out. Mirer, for now at least, in.
</P>
<P>
   In New England six years ago, Parcells took Drew Bledsoe first
in the draft over Mirer, who went second. Parcells, who rode
Bledsoe to a Super Bowl, made the right choice there, as he made
with Testaverde over Foley here. Then came Sunday, Bledsoe and the
Patriots, Giants Stadium, Testaverde and Mirer, Parcells at one of
those mysterious intersections of yesterdays that he has always
navigated so well.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the one where his reputation finally takes a hit, or
even crashes and burns? Or does he make something out of Mirer and
become a bigger genius than ever?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' said Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, for once, has no clue. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
