<SLUG> BC-PILOT-CRASH-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA PILOT LANDS DISABLED PLANE IN GALVESTON SURF 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to correct lead to 175 sted of 182) 
(Attn: La.) 
(Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ A Louisiana pilot glided his disabled Cessna
175 airplane several miles before crash-landing in calm surf before
noon Monday on Galveston's beachfront.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Bennett Cairns Jr., 65, of Covington, La., and a
passenger walked away uninjured from the crash, which ended with
the airplane upside down in shallow water, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like he was going to the sand, but there were people
there and he moved back over the water,'' said Galveston Beach
Patrol lifeguard Tony Pryor. ``He was in a gradual incline and he
hit the water, and it slowly flipped him over on the top side.''
</P>
<P>
   Cairns, who was identified as the pilot by the Texas Department
of Public Safety, was unavailable for comment late Monday. The DPS
did not have the name of the passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston International Airport interim director Hud Hopkins
said Cairns told him the passenger was his sister and the two were
traveling to Galveston to visit a relative. Hopkins did not have
the sister's name.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said Cairns confirmed Pryor's assessment of the landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were too many tourists on the beach to make a landing
without injuring anybody; so he put it in over the water a
little,'' Hopkins said. ``As soon as he touched water, he flipped
over. But they were completely fine, other than being shaken up.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's pretty incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pryor said he first noticed the airplane as it passed his
lifeguard stand. The plane was silent as it swept down the beach
and landed four blocks away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he did a real good job of landing it, because he
avoided people, and it looked pretty much under control,'' said
Pryor, the first person to reach the overturned plane. ``By the
time I got there, they were both out and going back in getting
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were real calm,'' Pryor said, adding that the top of the
cockpit was barely underwater in the surf.
</P>
<P>
   Cairns radioed a ``mayday'' minutes before the crash, according
to one person who monitored radio traffic among pilots in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Cairns told other pilots in the area his engine failed, he was
four or five miles from the Galveston airport and he did not expect
to make it to a runway.
</P>
<P>
   At least three helicopter pilots in the area began looking for
the disabled plane when the emergency call went out and one was
shepherding the aircraft when it hit the beach and rolled over,
witnesses said. The plane was flying parallel to the beachfront,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration investigators were at the crash
scene and were inspecting the airplane in a hanger after it was
hauled off the beach and lifted up over the city's seawall.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the plane's propeller and nose appeared to have
suffered the most damage from the crash-landing but the aircraft's
fuselage and a wing were broken in half during the salvage
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said FAA officials plan to examine the engine this week
to find out why it quit running. The plane belonged to Cairns,
Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
