<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINA-OIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOTAL FINA TAKES OVER ELF TO FORM FOURTH-BIGGEST OIL COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
 repeating to fix coding  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ After fighting off a hostile takeover for
the last two months, Elf Aquitaine SA of France capitulated Monday
and agreed to be acquired for roughly $48.8 billion by a domestic
rival, Total Fina SA.
</P>
<P>
   If completed, the deal would create the world's fourth-largest
oil company _topped only by the proposed Exxon-Mobil combination;
the Anglo-Dutch oil giant Royal Dutch/Shell; and the planned merger
of BP Amoco and ARCO.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement announced Monday is another milestone in Europe's
fast-changing corporate culture. It is the Continent's second huge
hostile takeover in the last few months, following Olivetti SpA's
successful $65 billion bid for Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the first time a big European company invoked a
``Pac-Man'' takeover defense, in which a company tries to acquire
the company that wants to acquire it.
</P>
<P>
   Both Elf and Total Fina had acknowledged for weeks that they
would merge in one form or another. The big questions were who
would be in charge and whose strategy would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   The clear victor Monday was Thierry Desmarest, the chairman of
Total Fina, who surprised Elf with a hostile bid worth nearly $43
billion on July 5.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal reached Monday, after a long weekend of
bargaining, Total Fina sweetened its all-stock offer by about $6
billion. Desmarest will run the combined company and the chairman
of Elf, Philippe Jaffre, will step down.
</P>
<P>
   The new price works out to about 190 euros, or about $197.60,
for each Elf share, compared with about 170 euros a share in
Total's original bid. Shares of Elf jumped 3.15 percent, to 186.5
euros, after Monday's announcement, while Total Fina slipped
four-tenths of 1 percent, to 129.5 euros.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also appear to be following Desmarest's basic
strategy, which was to retain control of the two companies'
chemical operations. In his counterbid against Total Fina, Jaffre
had proposed spinning off most of the chemical operations and
focusing more closely on the oil business.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came after two months of tense struggle between
the executives of the companies, whose headquarters are within a
short walk of each other near La Defense, a huge office and
shopping complex, in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Desmarest, who had met with Jaffre occasionally over lunch,
began his unsolicited bid after failing to persuade his rival that
the acceleration of oil-industry mergers made a merger of their two
companies logical.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffre quickly denounced the bid as both hostile and inadequate,
and then fired back a few weeks later with his own plan.
</P>
<P>
   The French government, which once owned Elf, played an important
role by refusing to interfere with Total Fina's offer and quietly
warning Elf not to seek a foreign partner as a ``white knight.''
</P>
<P>
   That severely limited Jaffre's options. More than a month ago,
he had made it clear he was willing to compromise to get a peaceful
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies began serious negotiating late last week and
worked through the weekend, company executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Edouard de Royere, a former president of Air Liquide and a
friend of both Jaffre's and Desmarest's, acted as a mediator.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the negotiations were handled by two board members from
each company. Total Fina's team included Serge Tchuruk, chairman of
the electronics conglomerate Alcatel SA and Desmarest's predecessor
at Total Fina; and Jerome Monod, chairman of Suez Lyonnaise des
Eaux, the large French utility.
</P>
<P>
   Elf's team was led by Michel Pebereau, chairman of Banque
Nationale de Paris, and Bertrand Collomb, chairman of La Farge SA,
one of France's biggest producers of construction material.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday in Paris, Jaffre appeared tired but
sought to put the best possible light on things. He noted that
Total Fina was now offering a significantly higher premium for Elf
_ 26 percent over Elf's stock price on July 2, just before the
original offer, versus just 15 percent earlier.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the agreement would create a French oil company
with enough influence to compete with the giants in today's
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal creates a major French champion in both oil and
chemicals,'' Jaffre said. It ``assures a great future for a company
that holds a very great place in the history of France,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Desmarest, smiling broadly as he took the lead in outlining the
agreement Monday, insisted he was not interested in ``size for
size's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the company needed more scale to keep up. ``When we
examine our competitors, they are even larger,'' he said. ``That's
why we feel a small push in the race for expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   Desmarest said the merger would produce annual savings of about
1.5 billion euros, or about $1.56 billion. The companies plan to
eliminate about 2,000 jobs in France, but they said those
reductions would be made through early retirement, attrition and
voluntary incentives.
</P>
<P>
   The deal announced Monday was the latest in a series of brash
moves that have distinguished Desmarest since he took command
several years ago of what was then called Total SA.
</P>
<P>
   Though educated in France's best schools, he spent years in the
oilfields. He infuriated the American government two years ago by
signing an oil deal with Iran. This year he took over Petrofina SA,
a big Belgian oil company, which promptly put his company in the
same ranks as Elf Aquitaine.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Desmarest suggested he was still on the lookout for
potential acquisitions, saying he would not ``close the door'' on
other deals. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s repeatingtofixcoding &LR;      09-13 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AFTER MIRER, PARCELLS HAS DOUBTS 
</HEADLINE>
 repeating to fix coding  (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ On the morning after one fateful step led to a
frightful snap, which begot much frustration and sorrow, Bill
Parcells made it clear that he was not exactly counting on Rick
Mirer to write a fantastic sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was the situations,'' Parcells said Monday, when
asked about Mirer's less than scintillating career. ``We'll see.
I'll try to give him the best chance to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   This didn't sound like a coach going out of his way to assure
his team that all was well, that Mirer could step in and be for the
Jets what Vinny Testaverde was last year. Despite the obvious
parallels of underachievement elsewhere, despite Testaverde's sunny
assessment of Mirer's ``identical'' circumstances to his own last
fall, Parcells' queasy expressions and coach's careful-speak were
an admonishment against trying to anticipate Mirer into something
he's not.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, remember, recruited Testaverde before the 1998 season
because he never believed Glenn Foley had the body to survive. When
he spoke of Testaverde last summer, he frequently endorsed his size
and skills. He cited Testaverde's playoff run in Cleveland, his Pro
Bowl season in Baltimore. You suspected Parcells strongly believed
the veteran from Long Island could flourish with the offensive
weaponry the Jets had assembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' was the best he could do on the sudden hot
subject of Mirer, the 1993 rookie of the year in Seattle, who was
also unceremoniously dumped by the punchless Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's right to assume that, offensively, we're
not going to function,'' Parcells also said Monday, as the Jets
regrouped for re-evaluation, after being sacked Sunday on first
down, by fate. On the other hand, for those wishing to second-guess
Parcells for being caught in the predicament of not having a
trustworthy backup with the benefit of a full training camp, he
pointed out that he had pursued early-summer deals for Eric Zeier
and Rodney Peete. Which I guess could also be interpreted as
Parcells' admitting that Mirer was not even on his radar screen
until The Great Zolak and Ray from Rutgers had been ordained
preseason flops.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't dial a quarterback into the system,'' Parcells
said, although his SOS to Ron Wolf, his buddy in Green Bay, did
result in the routing of Mirer to Weeb Ewbank Hall.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Parcells did not blame the artificial turf at
Giants Stadium for Testaverde's torn Achilles' tendon. But then,
how could he? He has always said he prefers grass, but has also
rejected the notion of being ``part of any experiment'' that might
result in the Jets playing on a bad grass field, which, he argued,
is worse. The result is that Wayne Chrebet is out six weeks, Leon
Johnson for the season and Testaverde for who knows how long after
that?
</P>
<P>
   Of course grass should be installed, turf qualifying as a
serious workplace abuse the players' union should have taken on
years ago. Yet Dan Marino suffered the same Achilles' injury, on
grass. This is what usually happens, almost inexplicably, in the
bodies of men and women past their athletic primes.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a doctor out there who can accurately advise Patrick
Ewing how much rest it will take before his feet are pain free? Who
can assure David Cone that his right arm won't play dead when
post-season comes? Testaverde. Ewing. Cone. That's merely the Super
Bowl, National Basketball Association finals and World Series
perhaps turning on the health of three 30-something stars.
</P>
<P>
   In a season that begins with the return of the pitiful and
futile instant replay, the Testaverde injury is also a jarring
reminder that human frailty cannot be legislated out of sports. ``I
just pushed off to go get the ball,'' said Testaverde, a class act,
even hours out of surgery that cut away his dream. ``My last
thought was, `My Achilles popped and I'm out for the season.'''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde out. Mirer, for now at least, in.
</P>
<P>
   In New England six years ago, Parcells took Drew Bledsoe first
in the draft over Mirer, who went second. Parcells, who rode
Bledsoe to a Super Bowl, made the right choice there, as he made
with Testaverde over Foley here. Then came Sunday, Bledsoe and the
Patriots, Giants Stadium, Testaverde and Mirer, Parcells at one of
those mysterious intersections of yesterdays that he has always
navigated so well.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the one where his reputation finally takes a hit, or
even crashes and burns? Or does he make something out of Mirer and
become a bigger genius than ever?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' said Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, for once, has no clue. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
