<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0860 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-PILOT-CRASH-2NDLDWRIT     09-13 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOT-CRASH-2NDLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA PILOT LANDS DISABLED PLANE IN GALVESTON SURF 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: La.) 
(Eds.: Updates throughout, quotes from pilot) 
 
By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ A Louisiana pilot glided his disabled Cessna
175 airplane several miles before crash-landing Monday in calm surf
on Galveston's beachfront.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the beach because he saw people there, the pilot,
Adrian Bennett Cairns Jr., 65, a physician from Covington, La., and
his only passenger walked away uninjured from the crash, which
ended with the airplane upside down in shallow water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel incredibly fortunate neither I nor my sister were
injured at all,'' Cairns said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had shoulder harnesses on and we were strapped in pretty
good, and I feel sure the harnesses kept us both from being hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Cairns and his sister, Mary Sue Lanaux of Mandeville, La., were
flying to Galveston International Airport. He said they were
approaching the eastern end of Galveston Island when the trouble
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked down at the ferry coming in and commented on what a
beautiful sight that was and the engine hiccouphed'' he said.
``About a minute later it quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Cairns said the engine restarted once and then died for good. He
switched fuel tanks to see if there was a fuel problem and that
made no difference. By then, he was over the city and decided to
head for the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I didn't want to stay over land because I didn't
want to take the chance on running out of air speed before I got to
the airport and taking out somebody's house or running into someone
on the street or ramming a building. So I thought the safest place
to be was out over the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Once over the water, he turned along the beachfront toward the
airport, gliding as far as he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got everything I could out of it,'' he said. ``I thought I
might be able to make it to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   An aerobatic pilot, Cairns said that experience helped him
maneuver the plane. When he saw people on the beach, he decided to
land in the water. As soon as his wheels touched down, the plane
flipped he said.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston Beach Patrol lifeguard Tony Pryor saw the landing:
``He was in a gradual incline and he hit the water, and it slowly
flipped him over on the top side.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane was silent as it swept down the beach and landed four
blocks away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he did a real good job of landing it, because he
avoided people and it looked pretty much under control,'' said
Pryor, the first person to reach the overturned plane. ``By the
time I got there, they were both out and going back in getting
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were real calm,'' Pryor said, adding that the top of the
cockpit was barely underwater in the calm surf.
</P>
<P>
   Cairns, who radioed a ``mayday'' minutes before the crash, said
later that his plane has a new engine, but he has no idea what
caused the failure.
</P>
<P>
   At least three helicopter pilots in the area began looking for
the disabled plane when the emergency call went out and one was
shepherding the aircraft when it hit the beach and rolled over.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration investigators were at the crash
scene and were inspecting the airplane in a hanger after it was
hauled off the beach and lifted up over the city's seawall.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the plane's propeller and nose appeared to have
suffered the most damage from the crash landing but the aircraft's
fuselage and a wing were broken in half during the salvage
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston International Airport interim director Hud Hopkins
said FAA officials plan to examine the engine this week to find out
why it quit running.
</P>
<P>
   Cairns and his sister remained in Galveston on Monday night to
visit a brother, Robert Cairns of Houston, who is in John Sealy
Hospital for surgery. The pilot noted that he had cancer surgery
himself in Galveston five years ago
</P>
<P>
   Apparently his decision to avoid a beach landing was not lost on
others.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked up the steps from the beach to the seawall, a
couple who had been on the beach said simply: ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
