their property. (Ernst Peters/The Lakeland Ledger)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) MELBOURNE, Fla. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- HURRICANE-FLOYD-4,
09-13 --People wait in line outside a Home Depot to buy supplies to
protect their homes on Monday. As Hurricane Floyd neared the
strength of a Category 5 storm and headed west towards Florida's
Atlantic coast, residents began to stockpile essentials as well as
purchase materials to protect their property. (Ernst Peters/The
Lakeland Ledger)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- TEN-OPEN, 09-13 -- Serena
Williams signs autographs after her match against Kim Clijsters at
the U.S. Open on September 4. This year's Grand Slam tournament
showed that women's tennis is able to regenerate itself. The
Williams sisters and Hingis and Seles and Davenport are ready to
rule even as Graf and Novotna bow out, with Sanchez-Vicario and
Mary Jo Fernandez right behind them. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- CHINESE-U.S.-BABIES, 09-13
-- Sara Lee, a social worker at the St. Vincent's Hospital
Chinatown Clinic. Working long hours in garment factories for
paltry pay, lacking affordable child care or the safety net of an
extended family, growing numbers of Chinese immigrant women - a
great many of whom are here illegally - are sending their infants
back home to China, according to health care providers, social
workers like Lee and labor organizers who work with them. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- NY-BLISS-TRIBUTE, 09-13 --
A floral tribute to Henry Hale Bliss on Manhattan's West 74th
Street and Central Park West on Monday. The flowers were placed
near the street corner where 100 years ago Bliss became first
recorded traffic fatality in America. ( Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- FARM-3-COX, 09-13 -- One
year-old Mason Senter and his mother Pattie join the farmers
protesting at the U.S. Capitol on Monday to urge Congress to
rethink the 1996 Freedom to Farm Act. ``I wish my grandsons would
have had a chance to farm,'' says Mason's grandfather, David
Senter, lamenting how his family had been forced to sell a Fort
Worth spread where he and his forebears had raised cotton and
cattle for a century. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- FARM-2-COX, 09-13 --
Farmers demonstrating at the U.S. Capitol on Monday are reflected
in the sunglasses of singer/songwriter Neil Young, one of the
founders of the Farm Aid concerts. In a ritual nearly as regular as
plantings and harvests, hundreds of family farmers from across the
heartland assembled here to protest federal agricultural policy.
(Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) TOKYO -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- JAPAN-GE, 09-13 -- Taketo
Yamakawa, president of GE Capital in Japan, meets with his managers
at the company's Tokyo headquarters. As Asia has begun to recover
from its economic collapse, GE Capital has gone on an acquisition
binge that has solidified its position as a global financial
powerhouse and bestowed a much-needed vote of corporate American
confidence on the ailing but now improving region. (Stuart
Isett/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LAKELAND, Fla. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- HURRICANE-FLOYD-3,
09-13 -- Adam Hawk prepares to pay for water and tape at a store on
Monday. As Hurricane Floyd neared the strength of a Category 5
storm and headed west towards Florida's Atlantic coast, residents
began to stockpile essentials as well as purchase materials to
protect their property. (Scott Wheeler/Lakeland Ledger Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- EMMY-AWARDS, 09-13 -- Nancy
Marchand and James Gandolfini of the HBO series ``The Sopranos.''
The 51st annual Emmy awards for television were notable for an
obvious reluctance to break new ground and recognize ``The
Sopranos,'' the lavishly praised HBO series about a Mafia family
with middle-class values in suburban New Jersey; the show, created
by David Chase and nominated for 16 Emmys, won only two awards
Sunday night. (Anthony Neste, HBO/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- FARM-COX, 09-13 --
Hundreds of family farmers from across the heartland assemble at
the U.S. Capitol on Monday to protest federal agricultural policy.
The farmers blamed many of the problems in rural America on
corporate agricultural giants like Archer Daniels Midland,
Smithfield, Conagra, Tysons, and Cargill Inc. and Continental Grain
Co., which have announced plans to merge. (Rick McKay/Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) FORT PIERCE, Fla. -- Sept. 13, 1999 --
HURRICANE-FLOYD-2, 09-13 -- Michael Oliver is assisted by his
daughter Diane in moving a shutter towards his front door on
Monday. As Hurricane Floyd neared the strength of a Category 5
storm and headed west towards Florida's Atlantic coast, residents
began to take measures to protect their property and themselves.
(Paul J. Milette/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- SMITHSONIAN-EXEC, 09-13
-- Lawrence M. Small, a banking executive who was invited by the
Smithsonian Institution to advise it on selecting a new leader, was
chosen Monday to lead it himself. Small, 58, will leave his post as
president of Fannie Mae to take over as secretary, the chief
executive officer, of the Smithsonian. He will take office in
January, succeeding I. Michael Heyman, who announced his retirement
earlier this year. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNIONDALE, N.Y. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- FBN-JETS-2, 09-13
-- Bill Parcells, head coach of the New York Jets, speaks to
reporters during a news conference on Monday. Parcells' starting
quaterback, Vinny Testaverde, ruptured his Achilles' tendon on
Sunday and will miss the rest of the season. The injury was a
crushing blow for a team that is considered a Super Bowl contender.
(Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MT. VERNON, N.Y. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- SCI-YOUTH-SOCCER,
09-13 --Jorge Amat, 16, bouncing a soccer ball on his head at Mount
Vernon High School. As the fall soccer season begins, legions of
schoolchildren are taking to the fields with images of the World
Cup victory by the United States women's team fresh in their minds.
But many doctors are more concerned with how to make soccer safer
for children in light of recent reports linking it to repeated
concussions and diminished mental functioning. (George
Gutierrez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Mont. -- Sept. 13, 1999 --
SCI-YELLOWSTONE, 09-13 -- Measuring spectral information along a
river at Yellowstone National Park to see if it matches
hyperspectral-camera data. The human eye sees three bands in the
visible spectrum, while Landsat, called a multispectral instrument,
records six bands of light. The hyperspectral instrument used in
Yellowstone records 128 bands, in information blocks, or pixels,
one meter square. (Jim Robbins/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- SCI-SCIENTIST-FEUD-1-B&AMP;W,
09-13 -- Tsung Dao Lee, left, and Chen Ning Yang shared a physics
Nobel in 1957, but later stopped speaking to each other. They have
published conflicting accounts of their collaboration, each
claiming the lion's share of credit for the idea, called parity
violation, that originally won them the Nobel Prize. (Alan W.
Richard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ANNAPOLIS, Md. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- SCI-CHIMP-SURPLUS,
09-13 -- Dr. Thomas Wolfle thinks chimpanzees no longer needed for
research should be cared for by the government. Wolfle, a former
director of the National Research Council's Institute for
Laboratory Animal Research, says the National Institutes of Health
is ``morally responsible'' for the welfare of the animals. ``I
think they should just bite the bullet and assume lifetime care for
animals they bred and move some out of active research,'' he says.
(Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- SCI-SCIENTIST-FEUD-2-B&AMP;W,
09-13 -- Dr. Gerard de Vaucouleurs challenged Dr. Allan Sandage's
measurements of cosmic distances. Sandage (shown) and Vaucouleurs
feuded with ceaseless rancor in the 1970s and '80s over the rate at
which the universe is expanding, called the Hubble constant. (Bart
Bartholomew/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WALDOBORO, Maine. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- ANTIQUES-DIGEST-2,
09-13 -- Samuel Pennington with his son, Clayton, his daughter,
Sarah McCleary, and a William Zorach sculpture outside the office
of The Maine Antique Digest. Dealers and collectors can log on to
the paper's Web page (www.maineantiquedigest.com), to register and
call up images of 13,000 objects and their prices. (Herb
Swanson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WALDOBORO, Maine. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- ANTIQUES-DIGEST-1,
09-13 -- Samuel Pennington at the office of his family-run monthly
newspaper, The Maine Antique Digest, in Waldoboro. ``Many people
we've done tough stories on advertise and are friendly with us,''
says Pennington, 70, a scrappy and folksy country editor in khakis
and sneakers who straddles cyberspace and newsprint to cover the
industry and search out scandal. (Herb Swanson/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MARIETTA, Ga. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- BUSH-PROFILE-2, 09-13
-- Gov. George W. Bush of Texas greets Carrie Mize at Ministries
United for Service and Training Inc., a religious organization
helping the poor, as Kelly Overduijn, 16, a volunteer, looks on in
the background during a campaign stop in late August. Bush has
shown he has the money and early favor of many voters, and now, as
he heads into the next phase of his campaign and many more voters
begin to pay attention, he must prove he has the substance, heft
and poise to be president, and to make it to the White House. (Andy
Sharp/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MARIETTA, Ga. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- BUSH-PROFILE-1, 09-13
-- Gov. George W. Bush of Texas during a campaign appearance at the
offices of Ministries United for Service and Training (MUST), in
August. Bush has shown he has the money and early favor of many
voters, and now, as he heads into the next phase of his campaign
and many more voters begin to pay attention, he must prove he has
the substance, heft and poise to be president, and to make it to
the White House. (Andy Sharp/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LAKELAND, Fla. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- HURRICANE-FLOYD,
09-13 -- Jim Valle, left, a store manager, helps customer Bill
White load a generator into his car on Monday. It was the last
generator Valle had in stock. As Hurricane Floyd neared the
strength of a Category 5 storm on Monday and headed west, thousands
of coastal residents were ordered to evacuate and NASA began moving
workers out of the low-lying Kennedy Space Center. (Scott
Wheeler/Lakeland Ledger Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNIONDALE, N.Y. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- FBN-JETS, 09-13 --
New York Jets quaterback Vinny Testaverde arrives for a news
conference on Monday. Testaverde ruptured his Achilles' tendon on
Sunday and will miss the rest of the season, a crushing blow for a
team that is considered a Super Bowl contender. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- SCI-MANSON-BOS,
09-13 -- Dr. JoAnn Manson reviews statistics from one of the
studies she oversees. A big chunk of the health advice Americans
now follow to lower their risk of heart disease - from taking
antioxidant vitamins or postmenopausal hormone replacement therapy,
to an aspirin a day, to the much lauded brisk walk - come from
studies that Manson has either headed or collaborated on. (Suzanne
Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- OBIT-MOONDOG-HARDIN-B&AMP;W,
09013 -- Wearing a Viking helmet, leather sandals, and a brilliant
red velvet cloak Moondog, whose real name is Louis Hardin, stands
at the northeast corner of 54th Street and Sixth Ave in 1965.
Moondog, who was celebrated among New Yorkers for two decades as a
mysterious and extravagantly garbed street performer but who went
on to win acclaim in Europe as an avant-garde composer, died
Wednesday in a hospital in Munster, Germany. He was 83. (Allyn
Baum/New York Times Photo)
</P>
