From Han Feng, right, a ribbed cotton undershirt with a loose silk
jacket and obiwrapped silk pants. At left, a spectator at Susan
Cianciolo's show wearing the designer's homemade T-shirt. (Marilynn
K. Yee, Corina Lecca, right/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- CAMPAIGN-FINANCE, 09-13
-- The two principal authors of the Shays-Meehan campaign finance
bill, Rep. Marty Meehan, D-Mass., left, and Rep. Chris Shays,
R-Conn., second from left, give a briefing on their legislation to
Congressional staff members on Monday. As the House prepared to
vote Tuesday on an array of rival proposals to change campaign
finance laws, Republican leaders made a final push to head off
passage of the the Shays-Meehan bill, which would ban unregulated
donations to political parties. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- SKULLFINDER-PROFILE, 09-13
-- Henry Galiano, the self-trained paleontologist out of Spanish
Harlem and owner of the Maxilla and Mandible Ltd. natural history
shop on the Upper West Side. A fossilized skull, probably belonging
to the pre-human species Homo erectus, turned up at Galiano's
little shop behind the American Museum of Natural History this past
winter, in a box of geological curios and tribal masks. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) CHICAGO -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- BURNETT-AD-COLUMN, 09-13 --
Richard B. Fizdale will relinquish his duties as chief executive at
Leo Burnett but remain as chairman. Fizdale, a Burnetter since
1969, helped the ad agency land additional work from clients like
Coca-Cola, Heinz and Procter &AMP; Gamble as well as new accounts from
advertisers like Delta Air Lines, Motorola, GD Searle and Toys
``R'' Us. (Marc PoKempner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- DIANA-NECKLACE, 09-13 --
The necklace worn by Princess Diana weeks before her death on
diplay at the Guernsey auction house. The necklace, made of 164
marquise and brilliant-cut diamonds and five strikingly large South
Sea pearls, will be placed on the block December 16. The auction
organizers have set $500,000 as a minimum starting price. The
necklace was created in 1997 in the London workshop of Asprey &AMP;
Garrard, jewelers to members of the royal family since 1843. It was
worn by Diana at a gala performance of Swan Lake in London just
weeks before her fatal crash. At the time of her death, Diana had
not yet bought the necklace and Asprey &AMP; Garrard reclaimed it,
placing it back in the showcase which was later sold to an
undiscloed buyer. The matching earings were made later and were not
worn by Diana. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) FLAGLER BEACH, Fla. -- Sept. 13, 1999 --
HURRICANE-FLOYD-6, 09-13 -- A couple negotiates heavy surf and
strong winds on Monday. As Hurricane Floyd neared the strength of a
Category 5 storm and headed west towards Florida's coast, residents
began to stockpile essentials as well as purchase materials to
protect their property. (Brendan Fitterer/Palatka Daily News)
</P>
