   (NYT10) ANNAPOLIS, Md. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- SCI-CHIMP-SURPLUS,
09-13 -- Dr. Thomas Wolfle thinks chimpanzees no longer needed for
research should be cared for by the government. Wolfle, a former
director of the National Research Council's Institute for
Laboratory Animal Research, says the National Institutes of Health
is ``morally responsible'' for the welfare of the animals. ``I
think they should just bite the bullet and assume lifetime care for
animals they bred and move some out of active research,'' he says.
(Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- SCI-SCIENTIST-FEUD-2-B&AMP;W,
09-13 -- Dr. Gerard de Vaucouleurs challenged Dr. Allan Sandage's
measurements of cosmic distances. Sandage (shown) and Vaucouleurs
feuded with ceaseless rancor in the 1970s and '80s over the rate at
which the universe is expanding, called the Hubble constant. (Bart
Bartholomew/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WALDOBORO, Maine. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- ANTIQUES-DIGEST-2,
09-13 -- Samuel Pennington with his son, Clayton, his daughter,
Sarah McCleary, and a William Zorach sculpture outside the office
of The Maine Antique Digest. Dealers and collectors can log on to
the paper's Web page (www.maineantiquedigest.com), to register and
call up images of 13,000 objects and their prices. (Herb
Swanson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WALDOBORO, Maine. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- ANTIQUES-DIGEST-1,
09-13 -- Samuel Pennington at the office of his family-run monthly
newspaper, The Maine Antique Digest, in Waldoboro. ``Many people
we've done tough stories on advertise and are friendly with us,''
says Pennington, 70, a scrappy and folksy country editor in khakis
and sneakers who straddles cyberspace and newsprint to cover the
industry and search out scandal. (Herb Swanson/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MARIETTA, Ga. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- BUSH-PROFILE-2, 09-13
-- Gov. George W. Bush of Texas greets Carrie Mize at Ministries
United for Service and Training Inc., a religious organization
helping the poor, as Kelly Overduijn, 16, a volunteer, looks on in
the background during a campaign stop in late August. Bush has
shown he has the money and early favor of many voters, and now, as
he heads into the next phase of his campaign and many more voters
begin to pay attention, he must prove he has the substance, heft
and poise to be president, and to make it to the White House. (Andy
Sharp/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MARIETTA, Ga. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- BUSH-PROFILE-1, 09-13
-- Gov. George W. Bush of Texas during a campaign appearance at the
offices of Ministries United for Service and Training (MUST), in
August. Bush has shown he has the money and early favor of many
voters, and now, as he heads into the next phase of his campaign
and many more voters begin to pay attention, he must prove he has
the substance, heft and poise to be president, and to make it to
the White House. (Andy Sharp/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LAKELAND, Fla. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- HURRICANE-FLOYD,
09-13 -- Jim Valle, left, a store manager, helps customer Bill
White load a generator into his car on Monday. It was the last
generator Valle had in stock. As Hurricane Floyd neared the
strength of a Category 5 storm on Monday and headed west, thousands
of coastal residents were ordered to evacuate and NASA began moving
workers out of the low-lying Kennedy Space Center. (Scott
Wheeler/Lakeland Ledger Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNIONDALE, N.Y. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- FBN-JETS, 09-13 --
New York Jets quaterback Vinny Testaverde arrives for a news
conference on Monday. Testaverde ruptured his Achilles' tendon on
Sunday and will miss the rest of the season, a crushing blow for a
team that is considered a Super Bowl contender. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- SCI-MANSON-BOS,
09-13 -- Dr. JoAnn Manson reviews statistics from one of the
studies she oversees. A big chunk of the health advice Americans
now follow to lower their risk of heart disease - from taking
antioxidant vitamins or postmenopausal hormone replacement therapy,
to an aspirin a day, to the much lauded brisk walk - come from
studies that Manson has either headed or collaborated on. (Suzanne
Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Sept. 13, 1999 -- OBIT-MOONDOG-HARDIN-B&AMP;W,
09013 -- Wearing a Viking helmet, leather sandals, and a brilliant
red velvet cloak Moondog, whose real name is Louis Hardin, stands
at the northeast corner of 54th Street and Sixth Ave in 1965.
Moondog, who was celebrated among New Yorkers for two decades as a
mysterious and extravagantly garbed street performer but who went
on to win acclaim in Europe as an avant-garde composer, died
Wednesday in a hospital in Munster, Germany. He was 83. (Allyn
Baum/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
