<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0867 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-ATLANTA-COX     09-13 1561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATLANTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Detailed notes tell story of vote-buying in Atlanta Olympic bid
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (w) Washington and (s) Sports categories.)By
Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Olympic organizers meticulously compiled
information about the International Olympic Committee members who
held the key to riches for their city. No personal detail was too
insignificant or, apparently, too sleazy to go unrecorded.
</P>
<P>
   From the shoe sizes of the wives of the IOC delegates to the
brand of beer they favored was duly noted, filed away and reprised
when planning for the IOC members' visit to the city or selecting
gifts to deliver to their hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   And now the dossiers compiled by Olympic organizers and stored
away in three dozen boxes of files currently being scrutinized by
congressional investigators are creating a national furor.
</P>
<P>
   According to congressional investigators, the files contain
lists of IOC members whose votes can be bought and suggestions
about the sexual appetites and preferences of some of the members.
</P>
<P>
   For months Atlantans have been made aware of sordid details of
the bid effort and the committee's denials of wrongdoing. Now CNN,
NBC and Newsweek have produced reports on what the newsweekly
labeled ``the shady side of the modern Olympic movement.''
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. Rep. Fred Upton, the Michigan Republican who is
chairman of the House Commerce Committee's subcommittee on
oversight and investigations, is making the rounds. Starting with
CNN and NBC's Today program, he declared the files ``contain quite
a bit of damaging and troubling evidence'' that suggests ``a
pattern of buying votes'' by the Atlanta Olympic committee.
</P>
<P>
   Upton told the Atlanta Journal-Constitution on Monday that he is
planning public hearings to air Atlanta's dirty Olympic laundry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there anyone out there who doesn't think what they did was
unethical or improper?'' the congressman asked. ``I don't think any
of this would pass the smell test from the get-go.''
</P>
<P>
   While the dossiers might make for spicy melodrama, they don't
seem to make a case for the kind of outright bribery that has come
to light in the Salt Lake City vote-buying scandal. And that is
primarily what the congressional committee is looking for in its
investigation of the Atlanta effort.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the ``IOC profile'' on Prince Albert of Monaco, one
of the more noteworthy delegates, suggested he ``likes the good
life, wine, women'' and added that his ``visit to Atlanta should be
low-key with press but an all-out orgy.''
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, the prince and his entourage were shown a good time
during his August 1989 visit. Several private parties were held in
his honor, bags of gifts left in his hotel room. One party was in
Bob Holder's penthouse Park Place apartment, another at country
music legend Kenny Rogers' ranch. After dinner one evening the
Atlanta bid committee rented a private room at a nightclub for
late-night revelry.
</P>
<P>
   When Sinan Erdem, the former volleyball player and IOC member
from Turkey, came for his visit, a private party at a Buckhead home
was planned. A bid committee member dropped a letter to the party's
hosts, Joe and Patty Thomas, offering tips for a successful
evening, which included supplying ``plenty of vodka and invite the
wildest people you know, followed by a trip to the Gold Club after
dinner.'' The Gold Club features nude dancers.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of gathering personal information on IOC members
and then using it to secure their bids, according to Upton, ``has a
fairly large taint of sleaze. It is pretty disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Bid committee spokesman Lee Echols defends the practice.
``Bidding for the Olympic Games was akin to creating a new business
and any new business must conduct research about its product and
audience before it gets off the ground,'' Echols said.
</P>
<P>
   Upton says it's a dirty business that has to stop. ``We need to
have legislation on the books to require it to stop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Upton points in particular to the fat file folders compiled on
each IOC member that fill more than three large cardboard file
boxes. The folders contain copies of correspondence and memorandums
referencing the delegates. Stapled to the inside cover of each
folder is a list of the dozens of gifts received by the delegate
and the dates they were given.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the folders also contain single-page dossiers, written
by an Atlanta bid team member. The profiles include basic
biographical detail, along with the names of family members, the
dates they visited Atlanta and dates bid team members visited them
in their home countries. They also contain ``personal
information,'' which described their likes and dislikes and
personality quirks. A snapshot of the IOC member, sometimes with a
spouse, was usually attached to the profile.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, the profiles were superficial. About Juge
Keba Mbaye of Senegal, one of the most influential members of the
IOC, the bid team wrote: ``Considered by all African IOC members to
be their chief, the leader of them all. A very important and
influential member in the eyes of other African IOC members. A very
warm person with an almost regal carriage . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the profile of Jean-Claude Ganga of the Congo, who
has been expelled from the IOC as the worst offender in the Salt
Lake City vote-buying scandal. His dossier hints at the Atlanta bid
team's all-out effort to secure his vote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Very active in anti-apartheid movement, a political animal. A
very, very important ally and a very good friend of Atlanta. He is
very proud of his association with us especially his relations with
(former mayors) Andy Young and Maynard Jackson . . . Ganga is a
very intelligent man, very politically astute, and a real
character. He will always have a personal interest in Atlanta's
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganga scored well in Atlanta. The bid committee has admitted to
donating at least $30,000 worth of sports equipment and clothing to
Ganga's National School and University Games in the Congo. They
also paid $15,000 _ at Ganga's request _ to send two teenagers from
the Congo to the prestigious Nick Bolitteri tennis camp in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But what seems to disturb Rep. Upton and the Commerce Committee
investigators more are a separate set of profiles, also typically a
single page in length and written by a member of the Anchorage,
Alaska, Olympic bid committee, which lost in its quest to land a
Winter Olympics. These profiles, commissioned by the Atlanta
committee, were more personal and often scurrilous, and offered a
strategy for securing the individual members' votes.
</P>
<P>
   One profile noted that ``Gifts are OK. Gifts of female OK'' for
one delegate from Africa. Another member is ``very influential with
the IOC, has reputation as a sadist.'' About the IOC delegate from
Cameroon, who is a surgeon, it was suggested to use Young, a former
ambassador to the United Nations, in the sales pitch and include
visits to medical facilities and show him ``what the medical
community can deliver to Cameroon. A good shot at getting his
support. Work him hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The bid team was told not to waste too much effort on the member
from Cuba: ``Nice enough but no matter how he feels about a city
Castro tells him how to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   They found that the late Louis Guirandou N'diaye of the Ivory
Coast ``loves honors and flattery from women.'' In its own
research, the Atlanta bid team filled out his profile with ``loves
deferential treatment . . . smokes cigars and while he did not
drink alcohol in Atlanta he did drink wine and champagne in
Barcelona when his wife was not with him. He had dental work done
when he was in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though Juan Antonio Samaranch, the IOC president, did
not vote, the Atlanta bid team knew they had to take special care
of his wife when she visited the city with her husband and later
with two friends. Billy Payne wrote several memos instructing his
underlings how to treat Mrs. Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Samaranch does not like adhering to his very tight
schedule and prefers to shop,'' Payne wrote in February 1990.
``Line up Saks and Lord &AMP; Taylor visit with the store managers and
when she selects something, make them insist that it's on the house
because she is such an important person, etc. Make it convincing by
prior arrangement with the respective stores.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Samaranch profile, the bid team writes: ``JAS is short,
thin and fit (exercises daily). Has a habit of twiddling a buckeye
while talking. His conversation is formal. Strong negative position
on Ted Turner and TBS . . . does not drink alcohol (drinks mineral
water), likes punctuality, dislikes late evenings, does not
smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Echols, the bid committee spokesman, says the scrutiny of the
campaign has been challenging. ``The environment in which we
conducted our bid was an environment that has now been
painstakingly scrutinized and turned upside down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What does he think of the team's marketing plan now? ``In the
future, cities who consider bidding on the Olympic Games should
confine their marketing strategy to ordering some pizzas and
handing out some Beanie Babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
