<SLUG> BC-WORLD-TRADE-ORG-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WONDERS IF CHINA WANTS A TRADE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEENSTOWN, New Zealand _ Two days after President Clinton and
President Jiang Zemin of China rekindled their relationship and
sent their negotiators off to strike one of the world's biggest
trade deals, here's what they came up with: Confusion about whether
China really wants a deal to enter the World Trade Organization
this year and a vague agreement to meet in two or three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It was not exactly the display of urgent resolve that Clinton
had hoped for when he asked Jiang to resume the talks immediately,
perhaps thinking it was possible to close a deal while the two
leaders were still together. And as the negotiators packed up and
left New Zealand Monday night, Clinton's aides appeared mystified
by China's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is quite certain what this is all about,'' one of
Clinton's top economic aides said, wondering aloud whether the
Chinese were posturing, delaying or had decided that a quickly
declining economy at home made this a bad time for Jiang to allow
fierce foreign competition into China's markets. Most theories,
however, center on how China may be seeking to parlay the
accidental NATO bombing of their embassy in Belgrade on May 7 into
some valuable trade concessions from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the negotiations over the conditions for China
to enter the World Trade Organization have been about far more than
trade. Its entry is one of the few areas where the United States
and China can claim real progress in a relationship hurt by
differences over Taiwan's future, charges of spying and
longstanding arguments over human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton argues that further integrating China into the world
economy will force it to operate under global rules, and that if
the deal is good enough he can demonstrate the economic benefits
for U.S. farmers and workers. Thus, Clinton's meeting with Jiang in
Auckland was carefully stage-managed to allow both sides to
announce a resumption of relations after the embassy bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Both Chinese and U.S. officials described their meeting on
Saturday as surprisingly free of rancor, and that China sought no
further apologies for the embassy bombing that killed three people.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before the meeting, Clinton sent a letter to Jiang
urging that the two men use the Asian Pacific Economic Cooperation
meeting to resume negotiations. The message was reinforced by Sen.
Diane Feinstein, D-Calif., who saw Jiang on a visit to China and
told him that if China wanted to get congressional approval of the
deal, he had to act quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an assumption that if Congress can't get this passed
before the presidential election is in sight, it's pretty
hopeless,'' Commerce Secretary William Daley said earlier this
week. Next year Clinton's aides are unlikely to engage in a
divisive argument over trade that could once again split the
Democratic Party and further widen a rift between Vice President Al
Gore and U.S. labor unions, which are opposed to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese understand the calendar,'' Daley said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They may understand it, but they do not appear driven by it. A
round of preliminary negotiations in China last week, and then a
second round in New Zealand between China's trade minister, Shi
Guangsheng, and the U.S. trade representative, Charlene Barshefsky,
never engaged in the substance of the issues dividing the two
countries. Those range from U.S. quotas on Chinese textiles, to the
rights of foreign automakers to enter China's markets, to the rules
that ban the ``dumping'' of Chinese goods in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Clinton implored Jiang at their Saturday meeting to
start serious negotiations the next morning, the talks wandered in
circles, participants say, drifting into differing understandings
of what the two sides had already settled in April. In a private
aside, Clinton raised the issue again with Jiang on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's efforts to implore the Chinese back to the table are a
sharp reversal from April, when he walked away from a deal offered
during an official visit to Washington by Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji. At the time he said it was insufficient, although U.S.
businesses said they were astounded at the breadth of concessions
Zhu was willing to make at the time. When he returned to China, Zhu
was harshly criticized for giving away too much, particularly in
telecommunications and agriculture. It is now unclear whether Zhu's
concessions are still on the table, and many in the White House _
including Clinton himself, some officials say _ now regard the
rejection of the deal in April as a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the National Economic Council, Gene Sperling,
sidestepped questions about the talks, telling reporters that
``we've decided there is little to be gained by negotiating in
public.'' Other officials spent much of the day Monday insisting
that they never expected a deal would be signed _ even though
several top administration officials had told reporters, just a few
weeks ago, that the talks could be wrapped up in days.
</P>
<P>
   The turn of events has put Sperling, Ms. Barshefsky and Clinton
in an extraordinarily difficult position. All week they appeared to
be more eager for China to get into the WTO than the Chinese are.
That is a reversal from April, when China was pressing for
admission, and the United States appeared to be insisting on
ever-greater concessions.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials insist that they will not lower their demands for
market openings simply because of the bombing. ``It's a strategy I
would try as well,'' one top official involved in the negotiations
said Tuesday, ``but in the end it won't work. And if it keeps us
from getting a deal through Congress, it could backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless some U.S. officials concede that Clinton would
probably take a deal that was only slightly better than what he
walked away from in April. The question now is how long it will
take to get both sides to that point.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GETTYSBURG-CONFLICT-A     09-13 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETTYSBURG-CONFLICT-ART-835&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITORS CENTER IS NEW BATTLEGROUND AT GETTYSBURG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GETTYSBURG, Pa. _ Mayor William Troxell personifies the misery
of the modern conflict raging in this historic town as he pores
over his color-coded map of Gettysburg, with the embattled town
souvenir merchants a pink-shaded picket line to the west and the
park headquarters firmly occupying the heart of the Civil War
battleground.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is both for the town and for our national park,''
said Troxell, a descendant of one of the town's founding families
and a licensed battlefield guide, his finger moving along the
bloodless but furious battle lines of contemporary Gettysburg.
``What we're facing could destroy approximately 100 businesses and
be very harmful to our tax base,'' he declared, fretfully
summarizing a wrenching four-year conflict between the National
Park Service and the town.
</P>
<P>
   The core of the conflict is a proposal for the cash-strapped
park system to tap $39 million in commercial and foundation
financing and build a new visitors center a half-mile from the
downtown center and its surrounding merchants. Their outcry is that
the change would drain away their trade. But park officials say the
proposal would reclaim some of the hallowed ground of Pickett's
Charge and aim to better protect the park's huge Civil War
artifacts collection.
</P>
<P>
   Just down the road from the mayor, Dr. John Latschar, the
superintendent of the park and a historian with an appreciation for
skirmish lines, exudes his own air of generalship as he awaits a
crucial decision this week by congressional budget negotiators on
whether the plan might be blocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere in the Park Service mission do you find that I have a
responsibility to protect the commercial enterprises surrounding
the park,'' Latschar said of the shops near the current center that
some visitors find tawdry and others colorful. Rather, he claims a
responsibility to visitors who annually flood 1.7 million strong
into the busiest of the Civil War parks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the less popular figures in this town of 7,000, the
superintendent is determined to move the visitors center, build an
artifacts museum, and restore the battleground terrain at Ziegler's
Grove. The land is occupied by the current center, set atop
Cemetery Hill, a pre-World War II, red-brick building that both
sides tend to agree is worn and cramped.
</P>
<P>
   Latschar is being denounced for his plan because it would allow
a commercial enterprise under the park-service roof. The new center
would be built by a private consortium and operated commercially.
The superintendent stolidly observes that changes in the
park-service status quo often rile merchants, known familiarly in
the park service as the ``rubber tomahawk'' shops.
</P>
<P>
   Town merchants are incensed that the new center would have
theater, cafeteria, bookshop and battlefield guide services and
would be the new site as well for the Cyclorama. This is a major
tourist attraction, built around a light show and Paul
Philippoteaux's 360-degree painting of Pickett's Charge, a vivid
moment in the three days of Gettysburg fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclorama is a 37-year-old building that park officials say
has problems of rain and asbestos leakage. It is next to the
visitors center, opposite the main strip of souvenir merchants
along Steinwehr Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the arrogance of the park service, the way they've run
rough-shod over this community, that permeates this fight,'' said
Eric Uberman, proprietor of the National Wax Museum, a commercial
tourist attraction across from the center's main entrance. He
dismissed as propaganda the park-service estimate that businesses,
far from withering, might expect more than $20 million in
additional tourist cash from a new, more accommodating visitors
center.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle reached the point where the town's 81-year-old
battlefield dowager, Angela Rosensteel Eckert, began a lawsuit to
reclaim the battle artifacts that her forebears donated as the
heart of the park collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Latschar is a very brilliant man, but he's just working
for himself and his new center and is not concerned with the people
here,'' Mrs. Eckert said, complaining that the park had neglected
the collection, housed in the old center, for decades and only
expressed concern lately as a ploy.
</P>
<P>
   The new center would be built on a 45-acre tract barely tinged
with battlefield history. Still, critics say, the park would be
desecrated by the arrival of a commercial developer, Robert Kinsley
of York, Pa. Chosen in a competition, Kinsley would build the
center in a joint venture that Latschar considers a creative way to
deal with what he says is a critical shortage of more than $6
billion in federal money for maintenance throughout the park
system.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the town would prefer to upgrade the existing visitors
building, fearing the shifting of their very center of gravity.
Visitors flow through here to roam the park's 5,800 acres _ a
quiltlike array of glorious fields, historic buildings and crammed
souvenir warrens, motels and food shops.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earlier this year the House stepped into the dispute. Rep. James
Hansen, R-Utah, who heads the subcommittee on national parks,
called the plan ``fatally flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   The House approved an unusual amendment to block the plan,
introduced by Rep. Ron Klink of Pennsylvania, a Democrat who is
expected to run next year against Republican Sen. Rick Santorum.
Santorum supports the park-service proposal and is leading the
fight against the Klink amendment this week in the final budget
conferences between the House and the Senate on the Department of
the Interior.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in the Civil War, the politics of Washington lobbying
and rivalry is a subtext of the current battle. Opponents are
suspicious of the campaign donations to Santorum by Kinsley, but
the developer insists that his support long predates the Gettysburg
venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as long as the Civil War,'' Kinsley said of the
local fight, insisting that he is seeking no personal profit beyond
``the satisfaction of helping the American people put together an
outstanding museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents stress that the issue goes beyond the welfare of
local politicians and merchants to that of ``selling the American
heritage to the highest bidder,'' in the words of Dr. Walter
Powell, a local resident who is president of the Gettysburg
Battlefield Preservation Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart of the problem is the agency itself,'' said Powell,
complaining that the park service's public-hearing process was
rigidly controlled and that critics had to resort to the Freedom of
Information Act to find out critical details.
</P>
<P>
   Latschar insists that the hearings have been open and exhaustive
and that joint ventures with private developers are an accepted
innovation in other national parks. ``I'm not surprised at all the
politics involved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes sense if you see we're in charge of the nation's
most priceless sites,'' Latschar added, waiting in his headquarters
for word from Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
