<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RACE-RELATIONS-COX     09-13 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-RELATIONS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   By Mara Lee
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As an assistant secretary of state, Hal Saunders
mediated between the Arabs and Israelis in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   As director of international affairs for the Kettering
Foundation, he mediated between Estonians and Russians and in the
Tajikistan civil war after the fall of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's applied those lessons about dialogue, and more
importantly, about change coming from the people, not the
governments, to America.
</P>
<P>
   This evening, he'll share his ideas on how to talk honestly
about race, and how to do it in a way that causes deep changes.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders is speaking at Books and Company in Kettering, Ohio, as
part of a book tour for his book ``A Public Peace Process:
Sustained Dialogue to Transform Racial and Ethnic Conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks and whites work together and go to school together, but
they don't have much knowledge about each other, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In America today, it's not so much malevolence as ignorance that
supports the status quo, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest obstacle to race relations is whites' avoidance of
the problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders, who is white, lives in the suburbs of Washington, D.C.
Although he does not live in a gated community, there is no
crossover between that world and the predominantly black and Latino
inner city.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy for him, and others in his community, to forget
about those with less. It's effortless ``to not have my face rubbed
in the inequity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are obvious differences between Saunders' experience
abroad and race relations in the United States. For one, there's no
armed struggle here. But, in his opinion, all these conflicts share
the fact that the competition for power is only a sidelight to the
larger issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're clashes over identity, they're clashes over historic
grievances,'' he said. ``People don't negotiate about their
identity or their hatred or their fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Saunders is confident these chasms can be bridged. A
sizable minority of whites, he believes, agree with him, that
``America can't survive in the long term if large numbers of
minorities are cut out of the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   He plans to host workshops in Dayton for people around the
country who want to learn his method of talking about prejudice.
But spreading intimacy among the races beyond a small committee is
the greatest challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't spread quickly, it doesn't spread dramatically,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But with sustained efforts, particularly in high schools,
Saunders believes America can have less fragmentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people learn to talk with each other in this way, it
becomes addictive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mara Lee writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
