<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0879 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-COMPLAIN-COMPLAIN_SFC     09-13 1627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPLAIN-COMPLAIN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 WEB SITES ARE CROPPING UP TO DO YOUR GRIPING FOR YOU
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Sam McManis &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Hungry, angry and sleep-deprived, Sue Johnson wandered through a
deserted Houston airline terminal at 1 a.m., muttering like a
madwoman.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines had canceled her connecting flight to San
Antonio, failed to give her the proper paperwork to secure her a
spot on a competing carrier, then merely shrugged when telling her
she would have to stay the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nightmare trip,'' recalled the graphic designer from
San Antonio, Texas. ``Unbelievably awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home, too irate to write and too vexed to vent on paper,
Johnson booted up her computer and, for $19.95, hired Complain.com
(www.complain.com) to articulate her gripe for her. All it took was
one tart letter from the Internet consumer advocacy company for
Johnson to receive a $200 voucher from the airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have time myself to deal with it,'' Johnson said. ``I
didn't have to calm down enough to create an eloquent letter. And I
didn't have to search for the right person to send it to. For 20
bucks, they did it all. The good news is, I got $200. The bad news
is, I've got to fly Continental again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyberspace, it seems, has turned into the Whine Country. A half
dozen online ghostwriting companies have sprouted on the Web to
complain on behalf of consumers. The industry still is young,
though, and it remains to be seen just how profitable these firms
can be. In fact, a few already have folded.
</P>
<P>
   Complain.com of Mountain View, up and griping on June 1, is the
latest Internet outfit that, for a fee, will pepper CEOs of
offending companies with letters and faxes until they recompense _
or at least acknowledge _ the consumer. Complaint companies do not
receive commission on refunds, they just serve as the mouthpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer complaining is a &LR;   &LR; growth market, according to several
advocacy groups. Complaints filed with the Better Business Bureau
jumped from 1.4 million in 1993 to 2.04 million in 1997, the latest
year for which results are available. The National Association of
Consumer Agency Administrators, a federation of 280 nonprofit
organizations, reports that complaints about auto sales have jumped
more than 50 percent from 1997 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the vast majority of complaints go unmade,'' said
Steven Ericsson-Zenith, founder of Complain.com. ``It's just too
much trouble for people to do it themselves. Our service is quick _
they've just got to send an e-mail _ and we do the research, write
the letter and send it to the customer to sign. It's really quite
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   So simple, in fact, that some consumer advocates believe paying
for online complaint services is a waste of money.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Wallace, president of the Oakland-San Francisco chapter
of the Better Business Bureau, said his organization provides the
same service as the pay-for-grumble businesses with one major
difference _ it's free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why there would be a market for it,'' Wallace
said. ``If someone sends us a complaint, we follow up on it just
like companies like Complain.com. We get thousands of inquiries a
month at the Better Business Bureau, and we handle it for free and
have 99 percent name-recognition. Who's ever heard of Complain.com
and outfits like that?''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, corporations big and small are receiving consumer
tales &UR;  &LR; of woe with letterheads such as Complain to Us (based in
Somerville, Mass.) Caveat Emptor (based in Austin, Texas), Fight
Back (based in Los Angeles) and Ellen's Poison Pen (based in
Alexandria, Va.). Most companies won't release the number of
complaints they handle, but Ellen Phillips of Ellen's Poison Pen
said she has received 3,000 complaints and accepted 300 as clients.
</P>
<P>
   Internet complaint firms say they are more persistent and
provide more personal service than the Better Business Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new wave of communication,'' said Bill Tran, Caveat
Emptor's president. ``We get a lot better response than the BBB,
which routes complaints to local chapters and then you never hear
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Most complaint firms do not accept advertising, lest they be
perceived as partial to corporate interests. Phillips, a former
English teacher who started Ellen's Poison Pen
(www.ellenspoisonpen.com) out of her home in 1987, said she takes
on any employer, even the government.
</P>
<P>
   Among the successes Phillips cites: obtaining a green card from
the Immigration and Naturalization Service for a client who claimed
to be a political prisoner in his homeland, obtaining a job
transfer for a ``harassed'' government secretary, securing $15,000
in back child support for a single mother, and forcing a school
district to pay a teacher disability for getting injured while on a
field trip.
</P>
<P>
   One of Phillips' proudest successes was getting Ben and Jerry's,
the ice cream-maker, to scoop up $10,000 (to cover hospital bills)
for a customer who had a whole nut lodged in his throat even though
the ice cream container promised ``slivers of nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a consumer revolution going on,'' said Phillips, who
also has published a book, ``Shocked, Appalled, Dismayed: How to
Write Letters of Complaint That Get Results.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers now know that if they complain effectively for a
legitimate problem, it pays off. I even have CEOs who have used me
to complain about other companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the new kid on the Internet block, Complain.com has yet to
rack up as impressive a list of satisfied complainers as Ellen's
Poison Pen. But the firm, housed in a nondescript business park
just off Highway 101, already is receiving a ``steady stream'' of
business, according to President Priscilla Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   Ericsson-Zenith, 44, and Harriman, 42, developed the idea more
than a year ago. Ericsson-Zenith, a veteran of the semiconductor
industry, handles the technological end; Harriman, former teacher
at a private school on the Peninsula, researches, writes and edits
the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Complain.com does not extend its advocacy for consumers beyond
writing complaint letters. But Ericsson-Zenith said he is
negotiating with several consumer attorneys to help customers whose
complaints are ignored by companies.
</P>
<P>
   Harriman said Complain.com's first success shortly after going
online was to help a client return a set of defective golf clubs
for a refund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the letter out,'' she said, ``and the next day, he
hears from the company, which gave him not only a refund and letter
of apology, but a free new set of clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Most complaints at Harriman's firm and other online services
deal with transportation matters _ such as complaints about service
on planes, trains and automobiles. Harriman said airlines respond
quickly to complaints but that automakers are notorious for
responding tardily, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of trouble with a guy who bought a Ford
truck,'' she said. ``It's a new truck; it squeaks. He takes it back
to the dealer, who says to put gunk on it every two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, the customer turned to Complain.com, which has
written letters and sent faxes to Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't heard back from Ford in a long time,'' Harriman
said with a note of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The mighty pen is all the power that online complaint services
have. None provides legal advice.
</P>
<P>
   A bad track record for a company is the advocates' major weapon.
Most of the online services, as well as the Better Business Bureau,
provide clients with databases listing companies prone to consumer
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found that credit-report companies draw the most
complaints,'' said Gary Rattigan, founder of Complain to Us in
Somerville, Mass. ``Credit fixers are the toughest to get any
response out of. The easy touches are the airline companies. All
you've got to do is whine a little, and you get something.''
</P>
<P>
   Complain.com will not turn down any complaint for being too
trivial, but Harriman said she often will tone down the venom in an
irate consumer's screed. ``We let them vent,'' said Harriman, who
writes and edits most of the letters, ``and we leave most of their
exclamation points in. But sometimes, we have to take the heat out.
But if customers want to ask a lot in return, we don't advise them
not to ask. It's their complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   Other businesses, however, weed out greedy clients with
frivolous complaints. Phillips, for instance, chose not to
represent the consumer who wanted monetary damages because
Baskin-Robbins ``put the napkin too high on his ice cream cone and
he licked the napkin by mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say, `Don't be greedy,''' but some people are,''
Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of online consumer complaint companies say the Web
companies themselves are greedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These startup complaint companies charge for what we do for
free and what consumers can do themselves,'' said Wallace of the
Better Business Bureau. ``It's a wild scheme, and I don't think
it'll work.'' Some professional Web whiners already have put down
the poison pen &UR;  &LR; because of poor business. B.L. Ochman took down her
Rent-a-Kvetch site last week, and Rattigan of Complain to Us has
started a side business as an online collection agency to ``keep my
complaint business afloat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ericsson-Zenith and Harriman say they are patient and will let
Complain.com find its niche market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a year or so before we know whether people
are really going to take to this,'' Ericsson-Zenith said. ``We're
still waiting for our first complaint about us. So far, the only
problem we had is one guy e-mailing us about poor grammar on our
Web site. He was quite pedantic.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
