<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-PRESSURE-COX     09-13 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-PRESSURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds on playoff mission
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ They ask about pressure. They whisper the word,
almost reverently, when they ask about p-r-e-s-s-u-r-e. Aren't the
Cincinnati Reds feeling pressure? They win, the Houston Astros win.
They win, the New York Mets win.
</P>
<P>
   With time spinning crazily out of control, the season's end
creeping dangerously close, is the pressure swooping in because no
matter what they do, the Astros and Mets do it just as well?
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jack McKeon looks at his inquisitor as if he had been
asked directions to the Yellow Brick Road and answered, ``You
crazy, man. It's mythical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no pressure on us,'' he said. ``We're not
supposed to be here anyway. Hell, we don't even bring up the
playoffs. I'm not managing and we're not playing any differently
than at the beginning of the year. If you change things, you end up
screwing it up.''
</P>
<P>
   His players deflect the pressure issue, too, just as they
deflect talk of the Houston Astros. They take care of their
business, as they did once again Monday by flicking aside the
moribund Florida Marlins, 7-4, completing a four-game sweep and
winning for the 10th time in 11 games on their inexorable chase of
the Astros in the National League Central and the Mets in the wild
card chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win the games we HAVE to win,'' left-fielder Greg
Vaughn said after his 38th home run in the sixth inning ignited a
three-run rally that brought the Reds from 4-2 behind to 5-4 ahead.
Vaughn singled to start the seventh inning and stole second to get
into position to score.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Stynes, a stand-in at second base for sore-backed Pokey
Reese, drove in the go-ahead run to make it 5-4 in the sixth with a
single, then put it away in the next inning with a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep beating the teams we HAVE to beat,'' Vaughn said,
emphasizing the word 'have' each time he used it, ``Things will
take care of themselves. If we do all we can, like keep winning, we
can hold our heads high. If it isn't good enough to catch Houston,
we tip our hats to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Reds are not in a hat-tipping mood. They are in a
winning frame of mind and general manager Jim Bowden says the word
pressure should be applied to the Astros and Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, our games end before theirs,'' he said. ``You'd
think it would begin to affect them, put the pressure on them. We
keep winning and they have to see that and say, 'Man, the Reds won
again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Starter Steve Parris (8-2) was not the sharpest blade in the
rack Monday, giving up four runs, including Derrek Lee's two-run
homer in the sixth to put the Marlins ahead, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Reds scored three in the sixth and Parris left the
game, he was rewarded with the victory and said, ``It was a nice
vulture win for me. . .come out of the game and get a win out of
it. They did a great job of picking me up when I put them behind,
4-2. The Astros?
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have to do is take care of ourselves because we can't
worry about the Astros until we get down there (two games September
28-29) and play them at the end of the year. It's hard. . .but we
have to keep going out there and winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Stynes is the club's poster child for success. No matter whom
McKeon calls upon to fill-in when an irregular is needed, that guy
produces. Stynes took over for Reese in the first inning Sunday and
contributed three hits, three runs, a double and a stolen base. On
Monday, it was two hits and three RBIs _ driving in the go-ahead
run and two tack-on runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stynes is something,'' Parris said. ``The guy gets put into a
game and does the job. I can't remember the last time he didn't do
the job when he got put into a game.''
</P>
<P>
   In late July, Stynes was hitting an embarrassing .087, but since
August 17 he has ten hits and a sacrifice bunt in 17 plate
appearances, pushing his average to respectability at .240.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like the old Stynes (.348 in 1997) and I wish I could
get him more action, but I just can't do it,'' McKeon said. Stynes
gets another chance tonight in the opener of a three-game series
against the Cubs, another team the Reds HAVE to beat, because the
superstitious McKeon said, ``I'll probably go with the same
lineup,'' giving Reese another day to rest his back.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
