<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0883 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     09-13 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Trading Stocks in An IRA 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Q: Is there any tax penalty if I buy and sell stocks short term
in my individual retirement account? I have been doing a lot of
in-and-out trading in my IRA because I am worried about the market
and don't want to commit my funds for any great length of time and
also because I speculate with risky Internet stocks and try to make
quick profits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Under certain circumstances, you can suffer what amounts to a
tax penalty for trading in an IRA, says Internal Revenue Service
spokesman Jesse Weller.
</P>
<P>
   This could happen if you pay your brokerage commissions with
money from outside the IRA. If you do this and if your commissions
plus the amount you contribute to the IRA in a given year exceed
your annual IRA contribution limit, the excess is subject to a 6
percent excise tax. (Your contribution limit is $2,000 per year or
the amount of your earned income, whichever is less.)
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you instruct your broker to deduct your
commissions from the money within the IRA _ as most IRA holders do
_ then you won't be subject to the excise tax.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of taxes, you ought to reconsider your heavy-trading
strategy. The purpose of an IRA is to build a fund over the long
term to help support you in retirement. If you trade in and out,
you risk hopping from one loser to another and actually diminishing
your retirement fund. In addition, much of your capital will be
chewed up by the commissions.
</P>
<P>
   While some investors consistently profit from trading in and
out, the strategy that seems to work best for most people is to buy
shares in financially sound companies with strong earnings growth
and hold them as long as the companies stay that way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last December, I bought some stock in AboveNet
Communications, an Internet software company. A few months ago, the
company announced that it was merging with Metromedia Fiber
Network, which makes fiber optic communications products. What will
be the impact of the Metromedia merger on the value of my shares? I
tried calling the company, but they do not return my calls.
</P>
<P>
   A: That deal was completed on Thursday. You soon should receive
1.175 shares of Metromedia Fiber Network for each of your shares in
AboveNet Communications. If your broker holds your stock for you,
the Metromedia Fiber shares will be credited to your account.
</P>
<P>
   When the deal was announced June 23, Metromedia was selling at
$37.50 per share, making the AboveNet shares worth $44.06, based on
the proposed exchange ratio. That is more than $18 above the price
AboveNet was fetching the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   However, Metromedia Fiber later plunged as low as $22 and
AboveNet plunged, too, closing on August 10 at $25 per share. By
the time the merger took place, Metromedia Fiber had rallied back
to $32.25, giving each of your AboveNet shares a value of $37.89.
</P>
<P>
   There is no good reason why the terms of the merger should have
been a mystery to you. AboveNet was required to send you a proxy
statement spelling out all the details well before Thursday's
special meeting.
</P>
<P>
   If you ever have any questions about any company in which you
own stock, you should call or write the investor relations
department. Keep badgering them until they give you a complete and
comprehensible answer. It's your privilege as a part-owner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Q: I will reach my 65th birthday in a few months, and I plan to
retire and begin taking Social Security. Will my Social Security
payments be subject to income tax wholly or in part?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  A: I can't answer your question for certain because I don't
know your income and your tax-filing status. But for many people,
Social Security has been partly taxable since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current guidelines, if you are single and your income
_ including half your Social Security benefits _ exceeds $25,000
annually, you may have to pay tax on part of your Social Security
income.
</P>
<P>
   The same holds true if you are married, file taxes jointly with
your spouse and have an income (including half of your Social
Security) greater than $32,000.
</P>
<P>
   The portion of your Social Security income that is taxable _ if
indeed it is taxable _ is capped at 85 percent. However, for most
people the percentage is much lower.
</P>
<P>
   You can determine whether you must pay taxes on your Social
Security income _ and if so, how much _ by completing an 18-step
worksheet included with the tax package you get from the Internal
Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   For a fully detailed discussion of how Social Security benefits
are taxed, take a look at the 24-page IRS Publication 915. You can
download it from the IRS Web site at www.irs.gov or order it by
telephone at (800) 829-3676.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
