<HEADLINE>
POLICE HOPEFUL WITH HIGH IQ MAY GET HIS CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Conn.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Connecticut man who was disqualified from a police recruitment
process in 1996 because he scored too high on an intelligence test
may yet wear a badge.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged at the use of the Wonderlic Personnel Test to weed out
unusually high or low scorers among would-be police officers, the
San Francisco chief of police has extended an invitation to Robert
Jordan to apply for a position on his force.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a federal district court judge in Connecticut
dismissed a discrimination lawsuit Jordan filed in the wake of his
1996 application for a slot on the New London police force. When
Jordan asked why the department had not followed up on his
application, he was told that he had been screened out because he
scored too high on an intelligence test.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ruled that Jordan was not a victim of discrimination.
But the ruling brought Jordan's case back into the public forum,
and when he read the story in the San Francisco Chronicle, that
city's police chief, Fred Lau, decided to take action.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought, `There's something wrong with this, this is a
comedy,' '' said Officer Sherman Ackerson, a spokesman. ``The chief
said, `Why don't you get ahold of this guy?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lau, whose bureau employs 2,200 officers, dropped an application
in the mail to Jordan Tuesday (Sept. 14) and hopes to make a larger
point with the gesture: Even if better-educated police are more
likely to change jobs, their contributions are worth the risk. Some
studies have shown that better-educated officers are less likely to
have excessive force complaints, Ackerson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
