<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-WINE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 VirtualVineyard Swallows Up Wine.com
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
In the first major consolidation among online wine vendors,
VirtualVineyard.com of Palo Alto will announce today that it has
acquired Wine.com of Napa.
</P>
<P>
   VirtualVineyard is buying Wine.com primarily for its name, which
it plans to adopt after the merger.
</P>
<P>
   No purchase price will be disclosed, but sources say it may top
the $3.3 million that Compaq Computer reportedly paid last month
for the name altavista.com. Compaq's search engine subsidiary was
already operating under the AltaVista name but it did not own the
Web address www.altavista.com until it paid what is believed to be
a record price for a domain name.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Wine.com has more than just a name; it also has an
operating business. But Robert Harmon, chief executive of Wine.com,
figures that about 70 percent of his company's value is its name.
</P>
<P>
   VirtualVineyard chief executive Bill Newlands acknowledged that
Wine.com ``is the perfect name for a wine site.''
</P>
<P>
   Wine.com is more of an informational Web site, while
VirtualVineyard focuses on wine sales over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will be ``the first fully integrated wine
portal on the Web combining content, commerce and community on one
wine site,'' said Newlands, who previously led Domaine Chandon and
Simi Winery.
</P>
<P>
   Wine.com has links to more than 200 wineries and is primarily
advertising supported. Unlike many Internet businesses, it has
positive cash flow, said Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Harmon said it made sense to merge with
VirtualVineyard, which has raised more than $40 million in venture
capital since 1994 and now sells wine in 40 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed capital to grow, but I felt why recreate the
wheel,'' said Harmon, who was once Robert Mondavi's chauffeur and
later launched a Napa Valley helicopter tour business that went
bankrupt after his partner was killed in a crash.
</P>
<P>
   Newlands said the merged company will soon be offering 1,500 to
2,000 different combinations of wines in various sizes from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   But it will not have the online market to itself. There are a
few small competitors such as eVineyard, SendWine.com and
Winecast.com.
</P>
<P>
   A major rival will be WineShopper.com, which also is backed by
more than $40 million in venture capital and is expected to launch
its Web site this month. The San Francisco company has
relationships with wineries, wholesalers and retailers that it
believes will allow it to sell wine legally in any of the 50
states.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
