r f BC-PALM-PALM_SFCHRON &LR;      09-13 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALM-PALM </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 3Com to Spin Off Palm Unit
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Seeking to cash in on the cachet of the popular Palm handheld
device, 3Com Corp. said yesterday that it plans to spin off its
Palm Computing Division into a separate publicly traded company.
</P>
<P>
   3Com has spent the past two years building up its handheld
electronic organizer unit into a $570 million business. The Palm
division is the fastest-growing part of the company and accounts
for 10 percent of 3Com's $5.77 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   But while sales of PalmPilot devices have soared, 3Com's main
line of business _ selling networking gear _ has slumped.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Santa Clara networking company said the
spin-off will allow 3Com to refocus its efforts on its core
business _ selling gear that connects computers to the Internet and
other networks.
</P>
<P>
   3Com has struggled to grow its networking business amid fierce
competition from giants such as Cisco Systems and Nortel Networks.
The company, which once was the leader in networking equipment, now
is the in the No.2 spot, having been beaten by San Jose's Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   3Com has faced slower-than-expected sales, inventory problems
and falling prices for modems and network interface cards. 3Com's
stock also has taken a beating, plummeting more than 40 percent
since December and taking 3Com's market value with it. Meanwhile,
companies like Cisco, Nortel and Lucent Technologies have seen
their shares soar.
</P>
<P>
   A spin-off is likely to help 3Com's stock price because the
company's shareholders ultimately will own stock in both companies.
3Com will sell up to 20 percent of Palm to the public in about
three months and then spin off the rest to 3Com shareholders.
Analysts speculated that the value of a Palm spin-off could be $5
billion to $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Benhamou, 3Com's chairman, said the market opportunity for
an independent handheld-computer company prompted the spin-off.
With more than 4 million devices shipped and 17,000 third-party
developers creating products for the Palm, Benhamou said, the
division is ripe for a spin-off.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more importantly, Benhamou said, the separation will
give 3Com the flexibility it needs to regain its strength in the
networking business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people had worried about how we would handle both
handheld and networking, and some had even feared that we might be
distracted by handheld and that resources would be diverted away
from networking,'' Benhamou said. ``The risk of that happening has
now been addressed by virtue of creating two separate companies.''
</P>
<P>
   3Com got into the handheld market when it bought U.S. Robotics
for $7.3 billion in June 1997. U.S. Robotics owned Palm Computing,
which it bought from three developers who invented the Palm
personal digital assistant in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Palm devices have been wildly successful, capturing 68 percent
of the worldwide handheld-computer market. The devices have thrived
in the face of competition from Microsoft's Windows CE operating
system and Apple Computer, which tried to compete with its
disastrous Newton product.
</P>
<P>
   But the handheld-computer business never really jibed with
3Com's core technology _ making gear that links networks together
and routes information across computers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And while the handheld-computer market is expected to be a
multibillion-dollar business, the earnings potential is even
greater within the $50 billion networking industry.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers said shedding Palm will help 3Com in its quest
to capture a piece of the lucrative networking pie while still
getting value from the PalmPilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``3Com officials are in a position right now where they have to
look at their company as a whole and get the most value for the
best parts of their company,'' said Matt Barzowskas, vice president
of FAC Equities in Boston. ``The Palm part of their company has
been doing very well, but it hasn't fit into the overall structure
of the company. The best way to get the value for the shareholders
is to spin it off into its own company.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Kessler, president of Palm Computing, said a separate
venture will help quell anxiety among some 3Com customers who
feared that the company was getting too ``Palm-centric.''
</P>
<P>
   And 3Com officials acknowledged that having to manage two
diverse businesses had become difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palm is a great business, but it doesn't really fit,'' said
Janice Roberts, a senior vice president at 3Com. ``We're talking to
major corporate clients, and they're talking to us about networking
infrastructure, but they see us as a company promoting
handheld-computer devices. It is a stretch for the management
executive team'' to deal with both businesses.
</P>
<P>
   For 3Com, however, losing Palm, means losing the fastest-growing
part of its business. That's likely to create a revenue pinch that
will sting for quite a while, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Splitting off Palm is a necessary evil,'' said Jill House, an
analyst with International Data Corp. ``It is likely to represent a
revenue loss for 3Com ... but in a way, it will make them better
positioned in the networking market because it won't split their
focus. It didn't make any sense for them to be integrated, but I
don't think the split will happen without a little shedding of
tears.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, the potential for an independent Palm is
``tremendous,'' House said, because the company will be better able
to shift direction and tackle new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows them to get into many areas that they weren't in
before. If they want to make a quick, agile move into a new
direction, they will be able to. They won't have the huge overhead
of a massive company like 3Com hanging over them,'' House said.
</P>
<P>
   And Palm will need to be nimble as competition in the
handheld-device market heats up.
</P>
<P>
   Palm faces a challenge from wireless cell phones that can access
the Internet and other electronic organizers, such as HandSpring's
Visor, which hits shelves today. Ironically, the creators of
HandSpring's new handheld device _ which promises to be cheaper and
better than the Palm _ are the same people who created the original
PalmPilot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
