u w BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT &LR;      09-13 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING FREE SPEECH, HOUSE REPUBLICANS URGE VOTE AGAINST BAN ON
DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the House prepared to vote Tuesday on an array
of rival proposals to change campaign-finance laws, Republican
leaders made a final push to head off passage of bipartisan
legislation to ban unregulated donations to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Monday to fellow House members, Rep. J.C. Watts Jr.,
of Oklahoma, the fourth-ranking member of the Republican
leadership, urged lawmakers to vote against the legislation
sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Martin T.
Meehan, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Watts argued that the initiative to curb the flow of
special-interest money into campaigns would violate guarantees of
free speech.
</P>
<P>
   For the bill to be constitutional, he said, the First Amendment
would have to be recast to say, ``Congress shall make no law ...
abridging the freedom of speech unless that speech supports or
opposes a cause or is made anonymously or occurs in September or
October of an even-numbered year or is intended to educate the
public about candidates' voting records, or is communicated over
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the powerful majority whip, has also
sent out letters to Republicans in recent days opposing the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The question of how to regulate campaign spending moved to
center stage after the 1996 presidential campaign, in which both
parties went to new lengths to get around the campaign-finance
restrictions enacted in the 1970s after the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats support the Shays-Meehan legislation, but
Republican leaders have made repeated efforts to kill it, arguing
that it violates the Constitution and that it would end their
party's traditional fund-raising advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The supporters of the bill, who argue that the race for campaign
funds is corrupting Congress, were optimistic Tuesday that their
measure would prevail over several others. ``Hopefully we are going
to have good broad support like we did last year,'' said Rep.
Stephen Horn, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan legislation would ban ``soft money,'' the
unregulated, unlimited donations to political parties that have
escalated in recent years as a way to circumvent limits on campaign
contributions. It would also rein in issue advertisements by
outside advocacy groups during the election season.
</P>
<P>
   The House will also be considering several rival measures: a
less stringent ban on soft money to the national political parties
but not the state political parties; a measure that would repeal
contribution limits and substitute tighter disclosure, and a
measure that would strengthen some of the powers of the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules established for the debate, the passage of any
of those alternatives would serve to defeat the Shays-Meehan bill.
Supporters of the bipartisan bill said they were particularly
concerned that the bill concerning the Federal Election Commission
could prevail because in other circumstances it would have broad
bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the measure to ban soft-money donations passes the House
it still faces an uphill battle in the Senate, where it died in a
Republican-led filibuster last year. Speaker Dennis Hastert made it
a test of his leadership this year to postpone the House debate
until the fall, in order to prevent pressure from building on the
Senate for passage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
