<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARE-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENCOR FILES FOR BANKRUPTCY CITING CUTS IN MEDICARE FEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Del., Ky.) (ms) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blaming cuts in Medicare payments, Vencor Inc., a troubled
nursing home chain that expanded and took on debt at the wrong
time, filed for protection Monday under Chapter 11 of the federal
bankruptcy laws.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which operates 300 nursing homes and 60 hospitals,
also asked the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Wilmington, Del., for
protection for more than 100 of its units.
</P>
<P>
   Vencor, based in Louisville, Ky., lost more than $600 million in
the fourth quarter of 1998 and $64 million in the first half of
1999. In April, it said that survival was an issue. In May, it
missed a $14.8 million payment to noteholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The writing was clearly on the wall,'' said Michael J. Kaplan,
a health care analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's, the credit rating firm,
which no longer rates Vencor's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Edward L. Kuntz, chief executive of Vencor, said the bankruptcy
filing was necessary ``because of dramatic changes'' affecting the
long-term-care industry, notably Medicare cuts. Under the 1997
budget law, Medicare is shifting payments to preset fees for each
patient, replacing payments that covered costs plus an additional
fee.
</P>
<P>
   The filing was also necessary, Kuntz said, to enable Vencor to
``create a sustainable capital structure.'' Vencor also said it was
negotiating to settle government charges that it had overcharged
$90 million for Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Vencor would try to pare down debt and reduce
rental payments on buildings that it leases.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it had agreements from a bank group headed by
the Morgan Guaranty Trust Co. to lend it $100 million to continue
operating. Vencor listed assets of $1.71 billion and debts of $1.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Most nursing homes operated by chains get at least 30 percent of
their revenues from Medicare. Such payments are far less important
for most small nursing homes, which still dominate the industry. A
number of chains borrowed heavily to expand several years ago, when
Medicare was encouraging nursing care as an alternative to
expensive hospital stays.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, when chains like HCR Manor Care and Beverly
Enterprises sold assets to prepare for the cuts, Vencor gave up
flexibility to shrink down, analysts said. It split in two and
transferred properties to a new real estate company, Ventas Inc.,
headed by W. Bruce Lunsford, a co-founder of Vencor.
</P>
<P>
   Ventas said Monday that the outcome at Vencor could
significantly affect Ventas' revenues and ability to repay or
refinance a $275 million bridge loan due on Oct 30. Ventas, which
gets 99 percent of its income from Vencor, suspended payments to
stockholders in July.
</P>
<P>
   Ventas shares fell 6.25 cents Monday, to $3.9375 on the New York
Stock Exchange, down from a 52-week high of $13.75 in January.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Vencor and Ventas did not reply Monday to requests
for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
