A0894 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AIRFORCE-SURVEY-COX     09-13 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCE-SURVEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Uncle Sam wants you...in his survey
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Do you have trouble finding blue jeans that fit?
Feel cramped in stadium seats? Are car radio dials just out of
reach for you?
</P>
<P>
   Well, take heart. Researchers at Wright Patterson Air Force Base
are measuring 9,000 regular folks across the United States, Canada
and Europe, building a massive database that will eventually be
used in designing all sorts of products such as cars, farm tractors
and underwear.
</P>
<P>
   The Civilian American and European Surface Anthropometry
Resource _ CAESAR _ survey has collected body measurements in nine
cities in the U.S. and Canada, including Dayton. Data collection
will finish in the U.S. by Nov. 23 and final results are due a year
later, said Sherri Blackwell, a CAESAR investigator.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of talk about how Americans have gotten heavier
and taller over the years as diets and lifestyles have changed, but
not a lot of hard data, she said. ``When we get all done I want to
know: How heavy are we? How big are we?''
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 companies _ including General Motors Corp., Levi
Strauss, Dayton Hudson Corp., John Deere and Hanes _ are helping to
sponsor the $6 million U.S. Air Force study.
</P>
<P>
   Although the military conducted a study in 1988, the last
comprehensive measurement survey of the civilian population was in
the 1940s, Blackwell said. The CAESAR information will be used to
design products, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers hope to measure 4,000 people in the U.S. and Canada
and 5,000 more in Europe. Participants are recruited by sponsoring
companies and through advertising. They must be between 18 and 65
years old and be able to climb one step.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-one small white stickers are placed on anatomical
landmarks. Participants are weighed and measured for head size and
sitting height before entering a laser-scanner that captures their
shape in 17 seconds. The result is 47 precise measurements such as
waist and hips and shoulder width.
</P>
<P>
   Participants are not paid, but may receive trinkets such as tie
tacks, ball caps or gift certificates from sponsoring companies,
Blackwell said. ``Not really the kind of incentive that is going to
draw you in if you're not interested in the research itself,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, participants will have the satisfaction of influencing
product design with their own bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance for anyone in the population. You can come in
and get measured and your data set will be used,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
