u w BC-COASTGUARD-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      09-13 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COASTGUARD-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COAST GUARD USING SHARPSHOOTERS TO STOP BOATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Updating a tactic last employed during Prohibition,
the Coast Guard is using sharpshooters on helicopters to disable
the engines of drug smugglers' boats with rifle fire, the service
disclosed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The commandant of the Coast Guard, Adm. James Loy, said that the
sharpshooters were deployed in recent weeks and that their bullets
had brought two drug-laden boats to a stop in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Loy also said that law-abiding boaters or fishermen need not
fear getting shot at, because rifle fire is used only after
repeated warnings to stop, and only after a boat's pursuers are
certain it is a drug-runner. ``If there's a new risk on the part of
the bad guys, that's terrific,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The admiral's press aide, Cmdr. Pat Philbin, said the tactic _
reminiscent of the days when the Coast Guard occasionally fired at
rum-runners from aircraft _ was decided upon after Coast Guard
patrols wearied of seeing smugglers' boats race by at up to 60
knots. ``They would go by and wave at us,'' he said. ``Literally.''
</P>
<P>
   Philbin said law-enforcement agencies had noticed an increase in
recent years of super-fast boats, 30 to 45 feet long, equipped with
up to four powerful engines and carrying enough extra fuel for a
700-mile round trip as they brought drugs from Colombia across the
Caribbean to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The boats, usually with a crew of two to five, have been known
to carry up to 3,000 pounds of cocaine, Philbin said. He estimated
that before turning to airborne snipers, the Coast Guard caught
perhaps one boat in 10 _ ``and that might be when they blew an
engine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard estimates that 85 percent of all maritime drug
shipments are made on the new speedboats, whose use has doubled in
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday the Coast Guard was a bit coy, as
Philbin was in a telephone interview. How many airborne marksmen
were there, and from what range did they fire, and what kind of
weapons did they use? ``I'd rather not say much,'' the commander
replied.
</P>
<P>
   One sharpshooter, Charlie Hopkins of Winslow, Maine, was
credited with disabling a smugglers' vessel on Aug. 16 with three
shots from a rifle.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference on Monday featured Transportation Secretary
Rodney Slater, whose department is the Coast Guard's parent agency,
and Gen. Barry McCaffrey, director of the White House's office of
drug-control policy.
</P>
<P>
   They talked of the 53 tons of cocaine that had been seized by
the federal authorities since Oct. 1 (the beginning of the current
fiscal year), and the $17.8 billion that the Clinton administration
wants for anti-drug efforts in the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard officials talked about nonlethal weapons like a
``stingball'' that explodes into a shower of rubber bullets, and a
special net that can ensnare a boat's engines.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the two boats disabled by bullets in recent weeks, two
others surrendered after a helicopter pursuit before bullets had to
be used, the Coast Guard said. Together, the four seizures yielded
about 2,600 pounds of drugs and 13 suspected smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   And would Philbin agree that hitting an engine in a moving boat
on a bobbing sea from a vibrating helicopter required pretty good
shooting, even with a laser sight? ``No,'' he said. ``It's very
good shooting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-STARR-LEAKS-NYT &LR;      09-13 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-LEAKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEAK FROM STARR'S OFFICE WAS NOT ILLEGAL, COURT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court ruled Monday that there was
nothing illegal in discussions by Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel, or his aides with reporters about deliberations over
whether to indict President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous three-judge panel reversed a ruling by U.S.
District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson that the independent
counsel's office had leaked secret grand jury information and told
her to rescind her order directing the Justice Department to
investigate Starr's office and his former spokesman over an article
that appeared in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling disclosed that Johnson had, last July, secretly
ordered the department to investigate the office of the independent
counsel and its former spokesman, Charles Bakaly, who was forced to
resign last March over his role in the Times article.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel said Johnson erred by adopting an overly broad
definition of the kind of grand jury information that prosecutors
may not discuss with reporters. The judges said that any leaks by
Starr's office or Bakaly that may have contributed to the article
were not illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The Times reported in January that Starr had concluded that he
had the constitutional authority to seek a grand jury indictment of
Clinton before he leaves office in January 2001. The article said
Starr had not made a final decision to do so but his conclusion
that he had the authority to indict a sitting president followed an
intense discussion in the office of the independent counsel. The
article's assertions were attributed to ``several associates of Mr.
Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling provides what appears to be a fresh and
expansive definition of what prosecutors may discuss publicly and
with reporters. It came in response to an appeal of Johnson's order
that was brought not only by Starr and Bakaly but also by the
Justice Department itself. The department was concerned that its
hundreds of federal prosecutors could be liable for their regular
discussions with reporters about criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a law that prohibits prosecutors from publicly
discussing ``matters occurring before the grand jury,'' a phrase
contained in Rule 6(e) of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals court ruled Monday that ``internal deliberations
of prosecutors that do not directly reveal grand jury proceedings
are not Rule 6(e) material.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his lawyer, David Kendall, had argued before Johnson
that Starr and his associates were engaging in a purposeful and
illegal campaign to leak damaging information about the president
to aid their investigation. Starr had responded that any
discussions he and his aides held with reporters did not disclose
6(e) material and were therefore permissible.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said Monday he strongly disagreed with the appeals court
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the decision of the panel is inconsistent with
the precedents of the Court of Appeals,'' he said. Kendall said
that he will seek to have Monday's ruling reconsidered by the full
appeals court, a procedure the court employs in a small number of
extraordinary cases.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, a setback for the president, was a victory for Starr
and a more limited one for Bakaly. According to the opinion, Bakaly
filed a declaration that in his discussions with the reporter from
the Times, Don Van Natta Jr., he ``refused to confirm or comment on
what Judge Starr or the Office of Independent Counsel was thinking
or doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Starr ordered an investigation by the FBI of any
leaks even if they were not illegal. After that investigation,
Starr's office withdrew its earlier assertion that it was not the
source of any information in the Times article. Bakaly resigned
shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Editors at the Times have said that they do not and will not
discuss the sources for the article.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was unclear how the appeals court ruling would affect an
earlier decision by Johnson in which she held that 24 other news
articles and broadcasts appeared on their face to show that
prosecutors in Starr's office had leaked grand jury material.
</P>
<P>
   Those 24 news accounts include articles from the Times as well
as Newsweek, Brill's Content, The Washington Post and The Boston
Globe and broadcasts from ABC, NBC, CBS, CNN and the Fox network.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, in a ruling last Oct. 30 said the articles demonstrated
``serious and repetitive'' violations of the law against disclosing
grand jury secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office has appealed Johnson's ruling on the other
articles. The case has not yet been decided on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Times article concerning Clinton's possible
indictment by Starr's office, three appeals court judges, Patricia
M. Wald, Laurence Silberman and Karen LeCraft Henderson, ruled in
their unsigned opinion that the appeals court had never meant that
a ``veil of secrecy be drawn over all matters occurring in the
world that happens to be investigated by a grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said prosecutors' statements about their
investigations are only a problem when ``they directly reveal grand
jury matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0899 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-QUARTERBACKS-NYT &LR;      09-13 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-QUARTERBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-MAN SHOWS PUT THE TEAMS AT RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick, Ray and Tom.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Bill Parcells answered after the floor fell from
beneath the Jets on Sunday when Vinny Testaverde was lost for the
season with a ruptured left Achilles' tendon. Are you going to seek
another quarterback through a trade, he was asked? Certainly, it
could be done all the way up to 4 p.m. on Oct. 19 when the trading
deadline kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells answered: ``No. We'll go with Rick, Ray and Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick and the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Ray and the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Tom and the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   None of that sounds like Vinny and the Jets. No ring to it. For
Jets fans, this is not sweet music. But that is what the Jets say
they will do, run with Rick Mirer, Ray Lucas and Tom Tupa at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Run? Walk? Could be a crawl.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday for the Jets was like a party where every balloon was
popped. Like a ship that ran into an iceberg. Like a train that
jumped off track. Like somebody pulling on a thread until the suit
unraveled, leaving you bare.
</P>
<P>
   Exposed.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are not alone. The first week of the season reminded
everyone of how important quarterbacks are, how they color the
personalities of their teams, gain so much attention and adulation
and blame. How you cannot win without a good one. How wonderful it
is to have a pair of good ones.
</P>
<P>
   Teams used to stockpile at the position before free agency. In
the last 20 years we saw Staubach and White in Dallas, Schroeder
and Williams in Washington, Simms and Hostetler with the Giants,
Montana and Young in San Francisco. We saw more teams deep at the
position with healthy competition and without a huge drop in talent
if the starter was injured. Then as now, teams usually kept a total
of three quarterbacks, but the first two were more often first rate
in quality.
</P>
<P>
   That is much harder to do nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   Free agency means that, at some point in their careers, most
quarterbacks will be free to move to other teams. The salary cap
for each team means that it must decide its allotment of cap money
to spend on quarterbacks and simultaneously field talented players,
especially superstars, around them.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the questions teams have pondered in this new football era
is: Do we spend more on two top-rate quarterbacks and try to get by
on the edges in filling out our team? Or do we sign a great
starting quarterback complemented by only a decent backup and a
handyman as the third guy and try to milk it? Most teams go with a
top guy and try to milk it.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to quarterbacking duos, there are four teams ahead
of the class: Buffalo (Doug Flutie, Rob Johnson), the Giants (Kent
Graham, Kerry Collins), Minnesota (Randall Cunningham, Jeff George)
and San Diego (Jim Harbaugh, Erik Kramer). Kansas City is close
with Elvis Grbac and Warren Moon, but for the other teams, it is
primarily a one-man quarterback show with a prayer that the backup
could step to the forefront.
</P>
<P>
   What does a ``one-quarterback'' team do when the one flops?
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, the 49ers wondered what they would possibly do
without Steve Young and now they are slightly worried about Young _
he was not sharp in a 41-3 embarrassment dished by Jacksonville.
Scott Mitchell, the new starter in Baltimore, started slowly in his
team's 17-point loss at St. Louis. Cleveland's Ty Detmer (6 for 13
passing, 52 yards, 1 interception, 2 first downs gained and no
points) labored against Pittsburgh, which scored 43 points.
</P>
<P>
   But no quarterback on Sunday melted like Tampa Bay's Trent
Dilfer.
</P>
<P>
   It was not just his numbers _ 16 incompletions and 3
interceptions. It was that he helped the Giants score all of their
points in his team's 17-13 defeat. Dilfer was sacked and fumbled,
and the Giants picked up the ball and scored. A Dilfer interception
was returned for a touchdown. Another Dilfer interception set up a
Giants field goal.
</P>
<P>
   He was benched for the team's final four series and his backup,
Eric Zeier, helped his team gain a total of 17 yards in those four
possessions and also threw an interception in the final two
minutes, one that crushed any Tampa Bay hopes. Only the rookie
Shaun King is left for Tampa Bay after Dilfer and Zeier.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that is a quarterback problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to look those guys in the eye,'' Dilfer said of
his teammates. But they are looking him squarely in his eyes. This
is his seventh pro season. He has made 65 consecutive starts. Tampa
Bay entered this season thinking Super Bowl. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, Brett Favre played so coolly and
enthusiastically in Green Bay's last-seconds 28-24 victory over
Oakland that it made him cry. Troy Aikman was superb, winning by
41-35 in overtime at Washington. Peyton Manning for Indianapolis,
Kurt Warner for St. Louis, Drew Bledsoe for New England, Charlie
Batch for Detroit and Kordell Stewart for Pittsburgh enjoyed happy
opening days.
</P>
<P>
   These were among the quarterbacks on Sunday who lifted their
teams with energetic and big plays. But in each scenario mentioned,
if they go down with injury, so will their teams.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us back to the Jets. They are hoping for a near
miracle, one that they have seen happen.
</P>
<P>
   There was a quarterback who played for three teams. He threw 35
interceptions in his second pro season. He had a quarterback rating
as low as 48.8 and never higher than 88.7. And then he joined the
Jets and in his first season, as a starter, threw 29 touchdown
passes, only 7 interceptions and offered a spellbinding 101.6
quarterback rating. He helped lead his team to a division title and
the conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   That was Testaverde last season.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer has played for three teams. He threw 20 interceptions in
1995 in Seattle. He threw six interceptions and no touchdowns in
Chicago in 1997. His quarterback rating has been as low as 37.7 and
never higher than 70.2.
</P>
<P>
   And then he joined the Jets this year. Now as the starter.
</P>
<P>
   Rick and the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Run? Walk? Crawl?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
