<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-ART-NYT &LR;      09-13 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBT AND DESPAIR DEEP INSIDE THE JETS' BUNKER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The doors to the New York Jets' locker room
opened at 12:30 on Monday afternoon, as they do every Monday after
a Sunday game. But the scene inside on Monday was different.
Instead of players sitting in front of their lockers, waiting for
reporters to question them about what went right or wrong on
Sunday, most of the lockers were empty, with players nowhere in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Except, that is, for one section of the locker room, where the
offensive linemen sat in a circle, resembling a self-help group of
300-pounders as they talked to one another about the next step in a
season that began with the unthinkable _ a season-ending injury to
quarterback Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   Circle the wagons. Circle the chairs. ``The guys were just
disappointed,'' said center Kevin Mawae when asked what the lineman
had talked about. He said the team had to ``find some ways'' to
battle back, to keep thinking that this season could still be
special, that the Jets could still be a force.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps the Jets will find a way. But many of them were
still reeling in the wake of Sunday's 30-28 upset victory by the
Patriots, the defeat more or less eclipsed by the loss of
Testaverde, who will be joined on the sideline the rest of the year
by Leon Johnson, the dangerous third-down back and punt returner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now this is a pretty difficult set of circumstances for
us,'' Coach Bill Parcells said at Monday's news conference. He
wasn't asking for sympathy, but he dutifully cited the casualty
list _ the standout receiver Wayne Chrebet, who broke his foot in
the final preseason game and is out for another month; tight end
Eric Green, who was temporarily immobilized by a pinched nerve in
Sunday's game and whose status is uncertain; nose tackle Jason
Ferguson who will miss at least Sunday's game against Buffalo with
a sprained ankle and knee and, of course, Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last eight days we've lost four starters, and one guy,
Leon Johnson, a productive player,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   For Parcells, the immediate reaction to all this misfortune was
to sit tight _ at least at quarterback. No, he said, he is not
bringing in another quarterback to back up Rick Mirer, who, like it
or not, will now direct the Jets' offense. In particular, he ruled
out Jeff Hostetler, who came off the bench to replace an injured
Phil Simms when Parcells was coaching the Giants in 1990 and went
on to be the winning quarterback in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 38 years old,'' Parcells said of Hostetler, who is
currently out of football. ``I don't think so. Not right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were other moves that Parcells made on Monday, or
suggested he might make, to deal with the current situation:
</P>
<P>
   _He may bring back the ageless Keith Byars for the second time
this season, to help at tight end or fullback.
</P>
<P>
   _He re-signed Ernie Logan, a backup nose tackle he had cut on
Saturday. Logan will probably start for Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   _He may reluctantly use Dedric Ward, now starting in place of
Chrebet, in a dual role as a punt returner.
</P>
<P>
   _He may use the recently acquired Bernie Parmalee, a
special-teams stalwart, as a third-down replacement for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, said Parcells, he will activate quarterback Ray
Lucas, making him the No. 3 signal caller. But on Sunday night in
Orchard Park, N.Y., against the Bills, it will be Mirer starting
and punter Tom Tupa as the probable backup. Tupa played relatively
well in that role after Testaverde was injured in the second
quarter Sunday, even connecting on two touchdown passes before
Mirer replaced him in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   So for the now it's Mirer and Tupa, two question marks at
quarterback in a season in which the Jets were being talked about
as strong Super Bowl contenders. How, Parcells was asked, could he
stop the team from feeling sorry for itself in its current
situation?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know that I can,'' Parcells said. ``At least
temporarily.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Parcells would not talk on Monday as if he had given
up, although he has now lost a quarterback who posted a 12-1 record
as a starter last season.
</P>
<P>
   He said his coaching brain trust would start devising strategies
to maximize Mirer's talents. While the 29-year-old Mirer is
basically a pocket passer, he does have more mobility than
Testaverde and has rushed for more than 950 yards in his seven-year
career.
</P>
<P>
   Like Testaverde, Mirer was considered a top college quarterback,
was a first-round draft pick and began his National Football League
career with a struggling team. But while Testaverde gradually
developed into a potentially dangerous quarterback as he moved from
Tampa Bay to Cleveland and then to Baltimore before coming to the
Jets, Mirer has yet to demonstrate that kind of ability.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Parcells contended on Monday that he didn't think it
was right to assume ``that we won't be functioning offensively.''
And linebacker Bryan Cox, who will answer questions through good
times and bad and nearly stole the game for the Jets on Sunday with
a second-half touchdown interception, chafed at any suggestion that
the season has come crashing down:
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we believe and go out and practice with a purpose
and do what we're supposed to do, it doesn't matter what the league
thinks or what the fans think or what the media thinks,'' he said.
``I didn't bust my butt all off season to come here and give up
after one week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
