<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN MAY LEAVE REPUBLICANS FOR REFORM PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Deletes prior 8th graf, ``Indeed, the potential ...'' to
delete how Buchanan might do in a general election.)  
(lb) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They have cajoled him. They have scolded him. They
have floated jobs in a future Republican administration and special
roles in the party.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, top Republican officials seemed all but resigned
to the likelihood that Pat Buchanan, the fiery conservative
commentator, would bolt from the Republican Party and seek the
presidential nomination of Ross Perot's Reform Party, a move they
fear could drain precious votes from the eventual Republican
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Although Buchanan has made no formal announcement of his plans,
he made it clear over the last two days that he was disillusioned
by the Republican Party, calling it a ``Xerox copy'' of the
Democratic Party, and that he was strongly leaning toward a
third-party bid.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks produced a mixture of pessimism and anger among top
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a spoiled little kid who picks up his marbles and
goes someplace else because he doesn't get his way,'' said Robert
Bennett, chairman of the Ohio Republican Party. ``Pat is frustrated
because his message isn't getting out. But if he leaves the party,
he becomes a dead duck as far as Republicans are concerned. He'll
become another Harold Stassen _ every four years he shows up.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry McMaster, chairman of the South Carolina Republican Party,
said: ``There's nothing anyone can do once someone makes up their
mind. This is unfortunate news, because Pat Buchanan's got a lot of
friends in the Republican Party _ and he's going to lose them if he
leaves the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how damaging a Buchanan bid could be, McMaster recalled
Perot's third-party run in 1992. ``It would hurt,'' he said. ``It
certainly hurt George Bush. We lost an election because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican straw poll in Iowa last month, the party's
front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, asked Buchanan to stay
in the party and, according to Bush's advisers, the two have also
discussed the issue on the telephone. But one adviser to Bush said
that the governor had given up trying to persuade Buchanan to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to pull this one off the ledge,'' the adviser
said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``We really believe that
there are things in a campaign that you can control and things that
you can't control.''
</P>
<P>
   The adviser said there had been informal discussions, inside and
outside the Bush campaign, of offering inducements to Buchanan, but
that they had not been offered. ``What are we going to do?'' the
adviser asked. ``Make him chief trade negotiator? We don't want to
insult him by trying to offer him something.''
</P>
<P>
   The adviser said Bush had also tried an indirect approach by
dispatching emissaries, including people Buchanan worked with in
the Nixon White House, to chat with the candidate. But it has been
to no avail. Jim Nicholson, the Republican national chairman, last
met with Buchanan in March. They have set up another meeting,
possibly for nextweek. But many Republicans said it would be too
late.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks Buchanan has resisted meeting with Nicholson. Indeed,
in an interview Monday on the NBC News program ``Today,'' Buchanan
was dismissive of Nicholson. ``I don't know the chairman that
well,'' he said. ``Frankly, I have been in the Republican Party and
fought for it longer than he has. So I'm not sure what he can say
to me to change my mind from where I'm going.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who said he would make a final decision early next
month, asserted that he could no longer distinguish the Republican
and Democratic parties and felt alienated from his party on foreign
policy and other matters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In another effort to distance himself, Buchanan has withdrawn
from a scheduled appearance this weekend with other Republican
candidates at a party gathering on Mackinac Island, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Lyn Nofziger, a veteran Republican strategist who backs Buchanan
for the Republican presidential nomination but opposes a move to a
third party, said he did not expect his friend to stay in the
party. ``I don't think that George W. could talk him out of it,''
Nofziger said. ``I don't think that Jim Nicholson could talk him
out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Kaufman, the party's national committeeman from
Massachusetts, agreed that there was little more anyone could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears likely from what I hear from the folks close to him
and around him that he's going the other way,'' Kaufman said. ``If
he doesn't want to stay, it's a free world out there.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Republicans are particularly unsettled is that
Buchanan, a hard-driving campaigner, won the crucial New Hampshire
Republican primary in 1996. Four years before that, his insurgent
campaign sent shock waves through President George Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call him the front-runner and I'm not kidding,'' Steve
Duprey, chairman of the New Hampshire Republican Party, said of
Buchanan. ``People have made a career of underestimating Pat
Buchanan. He knows how to run and do well in the New Hampshire
primary.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not entirely clear that Buchanan could get the Reform
Party's nomination. ``The only thing that could keep him out of it
is some indication that he may not be able to pick up the Reform
Party nomination,'' Nofziger said.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party's biggest-name elected official, Gov. Jesse
Ventura of Minnesota, has been less than enthusiastic about a
Buchanan candidacy. The party has stayed clear of divisive social
issues like abortion and homosexuality, issues on which Buchanan
holds hard-edged conservative views.
</P>
<P>
   But some in the Reform Party say Buchanan's views on changing
the campaign-spending laws and his isolationist stands on foreign
policy would mesh well.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford May, communications director for the Republican
National Committee, said he still held out hope that Buchanan would
remain in the party. ``We hope that he will recognize that he does
not want to do anything that would benefit Al Gore, Bill Bradley
and others on the left,'' May said, ``or do anything that would
harm that conservative movement for which he has worked so hard for
so many years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
