<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OPEN RECOVERED NICELY AFTER ITS ROCKY START 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - So what if history was not made at the 1999 U.S.
Open, the one that sandwiched itself between two hurricanes and,
like a Broadway hoofer with two sore feet, somehow went on with the
show.
</P>
<P>
   There were great strides, great ratings and a couple of
do-it-yourself stars, one of them a bold 17-year-old who spent her
formative years belting balls and dodging gang-related bullets on
public courts in Compton, Calif., the other a charismatic Las Vegan
who bounced from No. 1 to skid row in the ranking and back again.
Together, they compensated for the headliners who went missing at
curtain time.
</P>
<P>
   As 29-year-old Andre Agassi, the Open's eventual winner, cracked
wise or, depending on the interpretation, waxed humble at the iffy
start of the fortnight, ``It's still going to be a good Open, and
I'll do my part.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, neither the absence of the five-time champion
Steffi Graf, who opted for retirement at 30, nor the early
withdrawals of Pete Sampras and Patrick Rafter because of injuries,
could detract from the final results. After 14 days pulling hard
duty on the hardcourts, Agassi, an iron-pumping guy on the rebound,
and Serena Williams, an iron-pumping gal on the rise, had
commandeered the story lines of this year's Open and hung on tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``So my dad has been right all along, all these years; I've been
a super riser,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a deliberate absence of conventional seasoning on the
junior circuit, Williams not only became the Open's fifth-youngest
winner in her first Grand Slam final but also stretched the
family's two-week Open take to $1.29 million by capturing the
women's doubles title with her 19-year-old sister, Venus.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Sampras, gunning for that record 13th Grand Slam singles
title, was sorely missed (but not by his fellow competitors). Maybe
Graf, who had dreamed about a fairy tale finish to her career in
New York, was sorely missed (but not by her fellow competitors).
Maybe Rafter, with his Road Warrior zinc oxide mask and his macho
acrobatics, was sorely missed (but mostly by the female fans
craving one of his sweaty shirts or wristbands).
</P>
<P>
   No, Sampras didn't break his tie with Roy Emerson for most men's
Grand Slam titles, and Graf didn't collect a 23rd Slam title, the
one that might have jolted her from her self-absorption and
inspired a chase for Margaret Court's career record 24 Slam titles.
Instead, this Open brought novelty to the forefront, and not always
charitably.
</P>
<P>
   Those teen-age divas from Wimbledon, Mirjana Lucic, Jelena
Dokic, and Alexandra Stevenson, were duds on the hardcourts of the
National Tennis Center. Jennifer Capriati's reward for restoring
herself to Grand Slam shape eight years after her riveting run to
the 1991 semifinals, was yet another interrogation session with a
news media more interested in ferreting out what she had done wrong
in the past than noticing what she was doing right in the present.
Lindsay Davenport was an unconvincing defending champion once the
going got rough against Serena Williams.
</P>
<P>
   By the final weekend, when the cast of characters had been
weeded down to eight semifinalists, the difference between the two
sexes was glaring: on the men's side, three of the final four were
29 or older, a graying landscape of veterans in a state of
reinvention. But on the women's side, three of the four were
teen-agers, further proof that the women's game has been
stockpiling fresh talent the way a diligent greenskeeper lays in
fresh sod.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different because the women are young and they're going
to get better,'' said Agassi, who congratulated 29-year-old Todd
Martin, an Open runner-up with designs on a teaching career, on his
longevity. Just as it was five years between Open titles for
Agassi, it had been five years since Martin had reached a Slam
final. Agassi vowed to keep playing as long as he got better, but
not indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career at 29 is lasting pretty long,'' he said. ``Us guys
are kind of tapping into something that we kind of somewhere in the
back of our minds believe won't be around too long. We'll play that
one by ear.''
</P>
<P>
   But not at the 1999 Open: that's history. Of a sort.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
