<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT DISCLOSED USE OF FLAMMABLE CANISTERS, NEW
DOCUMENTS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 4th graf, bgng `The documents...' to clarify and add that
Reno had for 6 years said that FBI did nothing to start fire; 5th
graf to add line on Reno's claim of seeing no documents until 2
weeks ago; 7th graf to add details on types of tear gas canisters;
adds new 8th graf on why Congress was given documents in 1995; adds
new 9th graf with Justice Department response; adds 2ndtake of 440
wds with details of Rangers' investigation, why Waxman released the
documents, and details of documents' contents.) 
(ATTN: Texas, Calif.)  (js) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON and NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Internal FBI documents disclosed Monday by a
Democratic lawmaker show that information about the use of
combustible tear-gas canisters used in the FBI assault on the
Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas, in 1993 had been in the
Justice Department's files for years and was even sent to Congress
no later than 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The documents cast new light on when different parts of the
government first had knowledge about the use of the flammable tear
gas and therefore may alter the dynamics of the renewed outcry over
events surrounding the FBI assault on the compound on April 19,
1993.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI documents were disclosed by Rep. Henry Waxman, a
California Democrat and member of the House Government Reform
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The documents released Monday show that even though the Justice
Department sent U.S. marshals to the FBI's headquarters two weeks
ago to seize infrared videotapes containing references to the use
of combustible tear gas, the department had for years possessed FBI
records that showed such devices were used at Waco. The seizure was
ordered by Attorney General Janet Reno, who was angry because she
had maintained for six years that the FBI had done nothing that
could have caused the fire.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the documents provide evidence that the FBI, which
has been accused of misleading the Justice Department about the
issue by some in Congress and the Clinton administration, did
provide information about the use of flammable rounds to Ms. Reno's
subordinates on several occasions. Ms. Reno has said that she had
never seen any documents on the subject until two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is no indication in the documents made public
Monday that FBI officials had clearly explained the implications of
using the flammable rounds to their civilian counterparts at the
Justice Department. Moreover, FBI officials had never said publicly
that their agents had used the rounds until last month, when they
said a ``very limited number'' of such canisters had been fired at
a concrete bunker hours before a deadly fire swept through another
structure on the compound. Investigators later found the bodies of
about 80 people, among them a number of children.
</P>
<P>
   In the documents, references to the canisters do not clearly
state that they were combustible but refer to them as ``military''
rounds, a type that uses a pyrotechnic device to pump out tear gas.
The vast majority of tear gas fired during the Branch Davidian
incident was in non-flammable canisters known as ``ferret'' rounds.
</P>
<P>
   The documents had been requested by Congress in preparation for
hearings held in July of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials would not discuss the issue on the
record. A senior Justice Department official said that the
documents will be a subject of likely inquiry by former Sen. John
C. Danforth, who is leading an investigation into events at Waco.
``Certainly one thing Danforth will want to consider is whether
anyone at the Justice Department was aware of the significance of
the words on those pages,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, the Texas Rangers released a report
to Congress Monday that said the Rangers, who collected evidence
from the Davidian compound after the tear gas assault, had found
spent cartridges from two different types of sniper rifles. Both
were carried by FBI agents during the 51-day siege.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law enforcement officials said Monday that the shell
casings were collected by FBI agents after they had first arrived
in Texas in March 1993, and that they turned the spent cartridges
over to the Texas Rangers. The long-held position of the FBI was
that agents had not fired a single shot.
</P>
<P>
   Later, officials at the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
said its agents had fired the two types of weapons in question
during an early, ill-fated raid on the compound in February 1993.
But officials said they had never determined whether the shell
casings came from the ATF's weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In the Rangers' report, which had been subpoenaed by the House
Government Reform and Oversight Committee, the Texas law
enforcement agency also released a letter by a federal prosecutor
who had advised Ms. Reno that unidentified Justice Department
officials may have withheld facts from her regarding the FBI's use
of flammable tear-gas canisters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I have formed the belief that facts may have been kept from
you _ and quite possibly are being kept from you even now, by
components of the department,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Bill
Johnston in Waco, Texas, wrote in an Aug. 30 letter.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Rangers began re-examining material from the 24,000
pounds of evidence they collected in a homicide investigation that
followed the FBI assault. The report said that a casing had been
found for a 40 millimeter projectile that ``burns at 500 to 700
degrees Fahrenheit, and is capable of igniting flammable items.''
The contents of the Rangers' report was first disclosed Monday by
the Dallas Morning News.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Waxman said he was releasing the FBI documents because
the chairman of the House Government Reform Committee, Rep. Dan
Burton, R-Ind., had said that Ms. Reno failed to inform Congress
about the combustible weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's assertion came after it was disclosed on Friday that an
incomplete version of a 1993 FBI lab report had been sent to the
government reform panel as the committee was preparing for Waco
hearings in 1995. The FBI had sent the full 49-page report to the
Justice Department, but the Justice Department supplied only the
first 48 pages of the document to the committee. The final page of
the inventory of evidence collected at Waco was the only one that
contained a reference to a flammable tear gas canister.
</P>
<P>
   Burton has said that he would expand congressional hearings into
Waco, and his aides said Monday that they they are still trying to
determine exactly what documents were sent to the panel by the
Justice Department prior to the 1995 hearings.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Waxman acknowledged that the three documents _ two of
which were provided to the Justice Department by the FBI _ refer
explicitly to the use of military tear gas canisters.
</P>
<P>
   One document found in the Justice Department's files that was
sent to the committee in 1995 was an interview report of an FBI
agent dated June 6, 1993. In it the agent, Wayne Smith, recalled
hearing a conversation about ``some sort of military round'' being
used.
</P>
<P>
   The second document was a summary of testimony of members of the
Hostage Rescue Team, the FBI unit that carried out the tear-gas
assault. The summary said that there had been an ``attempt to
penetrate bunker w/1 military round and two ferret rounds. Military
round was grey bubblehead w/green base.''
</P>
<P>
   The third document was comprised of undated, handwritten notes
that appear to have been taken close to the date of the assault. It
said, ``smoke from bunker came when these guys tried to shoot gas
into bunker (military gas round).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
