<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-TESTAVERDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTAVERDE WILL HELP WHEREVER HE IS ABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ This was the image that made the news: Vinny
Testaverde pounding the turf with his right fist. He pounded it as
if trying to grind out the memory of what he knew had just
happened: his season had been ended by a torn Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   His season, yes, but not his career, Testaverde, 35, insisted
Monday. He said he would not spend the next few months feeling
sorry for himself. Instead, Testaverde said, he hopes to help out
the other Jets quarterbacks as a sort of assistant coach while he
prepares for his return.
</P>
<P>
   He did not move Monday like a man who had undergone surgery just
12 hours before: there was no mistaking the athlete on crutches.
But for all the relative ease with which he got around with his
left foot in a cast, Testaverde wasn't going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to go through some rehab for a couple of months,''
he said, with the optimism that has allowed him to last through the
weekly poundings in 12 professional football seasons only to be
hurt on Sunday with no contact.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Testaverde wants to help the quarterbacks coach Dan Henning
work with the backup quarterback Rick Mirer and whomever else the
Jets might use. ``I don't know what my role will be,'' Testaverde
said, ``but I wouldn't mind being an assistant to Coach Henning.''
</P>
<P>
   Tearing an Achilles' tendon is a more common injury for an older
athlete than a younger one. But Testaverde is also a very big man _
6 feet 5 inches and 232 pounds _ and so the healing process might
not be as a easy as it would be for, say, a 150-pounder. Still,
Testaverde said he thought it would not take him the maximum
projected time to rehabilitate his injury: nine months.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's for slow healers,'' he said, ``and I'm not a slow
healer.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, sitting out a year at his age could actually prolong his
career, because he will not take the physical toll of a full season
of football.
</P>
<P>
   But in the moment following the injury _ Coach Bill Parcells
described it as the same type of step people take every day _ none
of these thoughts crossed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde had wanted to pounce on the ball, which had been
bobbled by Curtis Martin midway through the second quarter against
the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I pushed off, I heard somebody falling behind me,''
Testaverde said. ``I actually started to turn to look who was
behind me, all within a split second. I thought, `Somebody fell,
somebody hit my ankle.' And my last thought was, `My Achilles
popped and I'm out for the season.'''
</P>
<P>
   He would not say the artificial turf was to blame. It is the
same carpet the Jets played on last year at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never in pain,'' he said of the dramatic scene Sunday.
``It was just knowing my season was over. I don't know that it was
the turf. We'll never know. I pushed off pretty hard trying to get
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the injury made Testaverde wistful. He said he had
always had to overcome obstacles. ``I didn't play until I was a
senior in high school, waiting for someone else to step down,'' he
said. ``I had to go to prep school because my grades weren't good
enough to get into college, but I excelled there.'' And then, ``I
got into the pros and played 12 years _ my best year was the
12th.''
</P>
<P>
   This season had seemed so promising, not just for the Jets, but
for Testaverde personally, another chance to continue to burnish
his image while winning.
</P>
<P>
   He had thought this season would surpass 1998, that all the
elements to help a quarterback had improved: a more potent tight
end in Eric Green, a healthy third-down running back in Leon
Johnson, a faster offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people still had doubts,'' he said, referring to his
own play. ``But last year was no fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he told his teammates Monday, ``I'm going to live this
season through you.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
