<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOATLOADS OF STARS, BUT IDEAS ARE ELSEWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So many celebrities, so many hot pants to sell ...
</P>
<P>
   Before the Versus show Sunday night at Roseland _ before
Sylvester Stallone was hustled to his seat, causing a tremor of
``ahs'' along the lipstick-red runway, before Madonna plopped into
hers and whispered something to Rupert Everett _ a Versace press
agent redundantly handed out a sheet that said ``celebrity list.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnie Driver, Lisa Marie Presley, Missy Elliot, Steve Tyler,
Mary J. Blige, Julianne Moore, Spike Lee, Jon Bon Jovi, Natasha
Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   It was like being inside In Style magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Donatella Versace, with her wristful of diamonds and
yellow-blond hair _ when she walked into the Four Seasons for lunch
last week it was as if the sun had risen twice that day _ is at her
Vesuvian best when surrounded by stars. She comes alive at the idea
of having all of them in her front row, wearing her clothes,
looking up at her clothes, and, yes, being in the papers the next
morning photographed at her show.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, at the moment in New York, where the spring collections are
under way, there is hardly a young designer who would dream of
stocking his or her show with celebrities, like a trout farm in the
Catskills. It's bogus, it's bush league, but mainly it's just old.
Which is funny, because Ms. Versace, despite her diamonds, likes to
think of herself as young.
</P>
<P>
   The show started with a clang of electric guitars from a live
band on the stage. Then the first model appeared, wearing a white
cotton mesh top and a white denim skirt that looked as if it had
been taken apart and sewn back together sideways.
</P>
<P>
   She was followed by models in tight cotton eyelet pants,
miniskirts with cutie-pie tops in the Lolita genre, and
screen-printed T-shirts that had been slashed open in the back _
the way a teen-age girl will do after she's tossed ``Silas Marner''
under the bed and started hacking away at her old Pearl Jam shirt
with cuticle scissors until it resembles a tank top.
</P>
<P>
   There were flashes of kinky brilliance, like Kate Moss in a
frilly coral top and white hot pants that twinkled up the front and
rear with gold spangles. A tiny triangular white top punched with
grommets looked as if the model had collided with a wet Kleenex and
kept moving.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with all those celebrities to give the show the
atmosphere of cool importance, it is no joke to say the clothes
looked as if they had been designed by a lecherous old groupie on a
break from a Grateful Dead tour.
</P>
<P>
   All this, by contrast, must make Susan Cianciolo, who served
frosted animal cookies at her show Sunday and displayed her
handmade clothes on racks that resembled wooden clothes dryers,
seem like the biggest flake of the week. And outwardly, at least,
Ms. Cianciolo's clothes suggest that she and her artist friends _
among them, Laura Genninger and Tammy Tiranasar, who use nailheads
and dowels to print random polka dots on cotton _ got together one
weekend and, in the spirit of Scarlett O'Hara, made some clothes.
</P>
<P>
   But consider: In the past couple of seasons, as Ms. Cianciolo
has gained a kind of cult following, her ideas, particularly her
naive-looking screened prints and deconstructed T-shirts, have been
widely copied. Clothes frayed or destroyed in the
loving-hands-at-home manner are not a new notion; one has only to
think of Rei Kawakubo of Comme des Garcons and Vivienne Westwood in
her early anarchic years.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Cianciolo is giving the idea fresh currency, and is it
any coincidence that the runways this week are already filled with
torn T-shirts and dangling gossamer threads, as if spun from her
strange cocoon?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cianciolo's inspiration was animals _ hence the childish
fare. Plain-Jane dresses were stitched with crouching cats, while
other shifts and circle skirts were adorned with a menagerie of
detachable animals _ quilted giraffes and dogs of the sort you
would find at a small-town church bazaar. The prints were
ingenious, too, especially a red nailhead print on a white cotton
blouse that had been gathered eccentrically to one side. The
printmaker, Ms. Cianciolo said, called it ``polka dance.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Standing around her husband's art gallery in Chelsea, where the
show was held, Ms. Cianciolo said she liked the novelty of using
plain wooden racks. Models, she seemed to imply, give her a
headache. ``We were trying to present the idea that if you love
clothes, you can hang them around your room on these stands,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean like a Stairmaster?'' someone asked.
</P>
<P>
   The designer smiled. ``That never came into my mind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a double bill on Sunday, Cesar Galindo and David Rodriguez
presented their collections together. Galindo sent out fancy ball
skirts and simple black crepe outfits quivering with jet beads, but
without much bravura. Rodriguez, on the other hand, showed his
cutting skills and eye for color. There were white leather hot
pants with a vivid brocade top, and a white shift printed with
graphic black circles and shown with thigh-high red stretch boots.
</P>
<P>
   The models _ bewigged, Pan-Caked and wearing what looked like
little waffles of Rice Chex over their eyes _ were the equivalent
of dummies. Wild.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere Sunday, Mark Kroeker played with texture and arty
shapes, like frayed edges and a cream hand-knit top tied in back
with yarn strings. The models, carrying clutches that might have
held a flute or a very long cigarette holder, were drenched in
lotion and glitter, while their hair lifted upward from underneath,
like Dorothy's house in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three young design teams presented by Moet &AMP; Chandon, the
Champagne maker, the Wrights _ not brothers, but two sisters,
Angela and Sharon _ showed promise with their minimalist shifts and
asymmetrical suede skirts enlivened with girlish eyelet cutouts.
Equally promising: Gregory Parkinson, who has quietly cultivated a
following, with retailers like Linda Dresner.
</P>
<P>
   Parkinson used denim, cut and pieced together in bias stripes,
and mixed it with simple tops of crinkled silk or homey jersey.
Colors were clear as a cocktail, and the upshot was a refined
collection by a designer whose eye is slightly but delightfully
off.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Diane Von Furstenberg's studio in Manhattan, Fran
Lebowitz, the writer, was lounging on a sofa that someone had put
near the entrance. Drinks were being served, and it was the kind of
scene one finds only in New York on a Sunday night when there is
nothing better to do. Inside, Ms. Von Furstenberg was showing
people around her tableaux vivants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Plant,'' she said, stopping before some models in
green and lavender print jersey dresses. Ms. Von Furstenberg
shrugged. ``It's about the plant.'' She then led the way through
the crowd to displays inspired by the Bird and the Earth, each with
sexy variations on wrap dresses and fluted, ruffled skirts.
Afterward, she introduced a man she called Romeo, a healer, who
handed out beads, which, he said, would ward off aggravating
people.
</P>
<P>
   So the week has begun _ and without a Romeo too soon. On Monday,
Han Feng, in a collection she called ``Reborn,'' presented simple,
beautiful clothes: silk capri pants inset with tiny crocheted
details, loose tops shrugging off the shoulders, trousers and
skirts wrapped obi-style, all made sexy with livid poppy and
panther pink. Susan Sarandon, the actress, was in the audience,
but, really, who noticed?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
