<HEADLINE>
FIVE MORE CHARGED IN UCLA PARKING SCAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former UCLA quarterback Cade McNown was among five
current and former football players charged Monday by the L.A. city
attorney's office for their participation in the disabled-parking
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Former players McNown, tailback Skip Hicks, safety Larry Atkins,
linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo and current safety Eric Whitfield
will be arraigned this morning in municipal court. They face two
misdemeanor charges: illegal possession of a handicapped-parking
permit and providing false information to the Department of Motor
Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   McNown, who has denied any wrongdoing, is playing for the
Chicago Bears. Atkins plays for the Kansas City Chiefs and Hicks
plays for the Washington Redskins. Ayanbadejo was cut by the
Atlanta Falcons. None of the four could be reached for comment.
However, Hicks had spoken of the situation at the start of training
camp in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was young. You do some things you regret when you're young.
Yes, I had one. I never parked in a handicapped spot, but I guess
that doesn't matter. I shouldn't have had one in the first place,''
he said. ``. . .It's one of those things where you've got to say
I'm sorry, learn from your mistakes and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield, a senior from Carson, was 1 of 11 current players
(seven starters) suspended by UCLA for two games for their part in
the scandal. They will play Saturday against Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   Senior tailback Keith Brown, also suspended for two games by the
school, was not charged by city attorney Jim Hahn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thery're still thinking my case over,'' said Brown. ``I have
to write a letter to the city attorney and explain my situation.
Then they'll decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he used the parking placard after having shoulder
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Hahn has now charged 19 current and former Bruins for their part
in the parking scam. Nine of the original 14 received two years'
probation, a $1,485 fine and 200 hours of community service _ 100
hours with the Special Olympics and 100 hours at one of four
organizations that assist people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The nine are linebacker Ali Abdul Azziz, linebacker Robert
Thomas, linebacker Tony White, linebacker Ryan Nece, guard Oscar
Cabrera, safety Ryan Roques, cornerback Marques Anderson and former
players Damian Allen and Deatra Clinton
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was suspended from school for the fall quarter because
of the parking scandal and a previous offense with the dean of
student's office. He will re-enroll in January and return to the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Five players charged July 8 have received two continuances and
will be arraigned this morning at municipal court. They are
fullback Durell Price, guard Jim Ghezzi and three former players:
Mark Reynosa, DuVal Hicks and Craig Walendy.
</P>
<P>
   According to the city attorney's office, all 19 defendants have
been accused of submitting bogus injury information to the DMV in
order to obtain the handicapped placards. In addition, 17 have been
accused of using the signatures of nonexistent doctors.
</P>
<P>
   McNown and Whitfield allegedly used the name of an existing
physician on their applications. However, she told investigators
she had not signed the applications and had no record of having
either player as a patient.
</P>
<P>
   ((Staff writer Rick Orlov and the Associated Press contributed
to this report.))
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
