<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DI-NECKLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PERFECT BIRTHDAY GIFT: BIDDING STARTS AT $500,000 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The necklace that graced the throat of a princess has
passed through Buckingham Palace, the vault of the jeweler to the
British Crown and the hands of a wealthy but modest couple who live
quietly in the English countryside.
</P>
<P>
   But this elegant piece with diamonds and pearls, once worn by
Diana, Princess of Wales, is heading for the place where so much
that has been touched by cult adoration seems to end up these days:
the auction block.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 16, the necklace and a pair of matching earrings, known
together as the Swan Lake Suite, will be auctioned at the Park
Avenue Armory by Guernsey's, the Manhattan auction house that got
more than $3 million for the baseball Mark McGwire hit for his 70th
home run last year. The organizers have set $500,000 as a minimum
starting price.
</P>
<P>
   The necklace has 164 marquise- and brilliant-cut diamonds and
five strikingly large South Sea pearls, but for some, it has added
sentimental value because Diana wore it on her last official public
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The necklace was created in 1997 in the London workshop of
Asprey &AMP; Garrard, jewelers to members of the royal family since
1843. It was worn by Diana only once _ on June 3, 1997, at a gala
performance of ``Swan Lake'' at the Royal Albert Hall just weeks
before her fatal crash.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of her death, Diana had not yet bought the necklace
and Asprey &AMP; Garrard reclaimed it, placing it back in the showcase
for sale, said Tania Foster-Brown, a company spokeswoman. In the
meantime, the jewelers had made the matching earrings, and on the
day the necklace was returned, a valued customer was in the shop to
pick up a bracelet that was being repaired, and he bought the Swan
Lake Suite on the spot as a birthday present for his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was a remarkable coincidence,'' said the buyer, 42,
who recently retired from his job as a managing director in the
London office of Lehman Brothers, the investment bank. He wrote a
check for ``a considerable sum of money'' _ he would not be
specific _ and walked out the door with the necklace and earrings.
Asprey &AMP; Garrard even threw in the bracelet repairs for free.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after leaving the shop, the buyer called his wife and
told her about the present. ``I said something like, `Look, dear,
I've just bought you something, but I've gone a little
overboard,''' he said. ``When she asked me what it was, I told her
that she had better sit down.''
</P>
<P>
   How should a woman feel when presented with a glimmering arc of
diamonds with a drooping fringe of pearls the size of lemon drops?
Thrilled? Flattered? Overwhelmed? The buyer, who asked that his
name not be used, said his wife was all of those at once.
</P>
<P>
   But she was also uncomfortable, he said _ uncomfortable enough
to give up the jewelry. Although the couple live part time in
London, they spend much of the year in a quiet English hill town
where there is little occasion to wear a necklace last worn by the
Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the necklace, but we really weren't doing much with
it,'' the buyer admitted. ``My wife wore it occasionally, but very
privately, just for us or a couple of friends. We're just not in
that circuit where it makes sense to be wearing a major, major
piece. We're not using it, so it would be better if someone else
enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   The auction seemed like the perfect way to dispose of the
jewels, he said, adding that a portion of the proceeds will go to
Unicef.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife's a bit sorry to lose it,'' he added. ``But we're very
conservative English people. We actually feel good about this
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Arlan Ettinger, Guernsey's owner, said the Swan Lake Suite was
the ``gift of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   With a touch of nostalgia, the anonymous buyer-turned-seller
said: ``In the beginning, I bought the thing and we were delighted.
Then, in the middle, we realized we just didn't need it. Now
there's a chance to do something good with it. I guess I just want
a happy ending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
