<SLUG> BC-BBO-NY-RACES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: BOTH YANKEES AND METS COULD MISS THE PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For anyone ready for devilish developments in the
remainder of the baseball season, how about this scenario:
</P>
<P>
   The Mets make the playoffs, but the Yankees don't. The Yankees,
only a year ago the greatest team since Rodgers and Hammerstein,
are the victims of the Revenge of the Red Sox, an overachieving,
unexpectedly solid team getting even 21 years later for their 1978
ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees suffer a double-barreled blow. Not only do the
Red Sox stunningly snatch the American League East championship out
of their expectant hands, but the $22 million Oakland Athletics,
striking a blow for small-revenue teams, edge the $86 million
Yankees for the wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   Someone said the football season began Sunday, but in this
educated view, it's only a rumor. As long as the Mets and the
Yankees are sprinting or staggering toward the post-season,
baseball is the only game in town. Well, figuratively speaking it
is. In reality, there is no game in town Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Is that possible? The Mets are on the brink of their first
post-season games since 1988, the Yankees are suddenly reeling with
a touch of mortality they never experienced last season and neither
team played a home game Monday night and won't play one the next
three days and three nights. Is this any way to make a schedule?
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are in Colorado, the Yankees are in Toronto. Television
and radio will have to suffice. But unexpectedly, the New York area
baseball fan, not the Mets fanatic nor the Yankees zealot, is in a
quandary. No longer are the Mets the only team whose October
schedule is in question, thus making their games mandatory.
Attention must now be paid to the Yankees as well.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of being able to attend one game and listen to the
other, the real fan has to watch one on television and listen to
the other, or, if the appropriate instrument is available, watch
one on the larger part of the screen and the other on
picture-in-a-picture. However it's done, both are required watching
or listening.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets continue to show that they are not the team that
stumbled along the way to the playoffs last year, losing too many
games to weak teams and finishing the season with five consecutive
losses. Their four-game series in Los Angeles made the point.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of August, the Dodgers came to New York and
bruised the Mets by beating them three times in four games.
Considering the clumps of games the Mets had won before that series
and proceeded to win after it, they seemed to be in no danger of
succumbing to the affliction that undermined them last season,
losing to bad teams.
</P>
<P>
   As if to emphasize that point, though, the Mets repaid the favor
last weekend, dumping the Dodgers three times in four games on
their grass. In that brief span, the Mets also lopped a game and a
half off their deficit with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Red Sox were sweeping a three-game series
at Yankee Stadium, and what a revolting development that was for
George Steinbrenner's stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for signs of the significance of that remarkable result?
In 1978, the Yankees and the Red Sox played a four-game series at
Fenway Park Sept. 7-10. Now it's coming back? Yes, the Boston
Massacre. The Yankees, four games behind Boston when they arrived,
won all four games and left tied with the Red Sox for first after
142 games.
</P>
<P>
   This season the teams played their series Sept. 10-12. In each
instance, when the series had ended, the Yankees had played 142
games. Their record then was 86-56, now 85-57.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were too far behind to pull even with the Yankees at
Yankee Stadium, but their sweep sent shock waves through the
Yankees' organization nonetheless. Wake-up call, as David Cone
called it? It was more like substituting a box of TNT for an alarm
clock.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Yankees continue stumbling, should the Red Sox
continue gaining, should the Mets close in on their playoff spot,
Steinbrenner would very likely set off his own explosion. He has
from time to time this season, in an uncharacteristic low-key way,
warned his troops that they weren't playing up to the standards he
expected.
</P>
<P>
   When the month began, the Yankees thought they would spend the
final month playing for home-field advantage in the first two
series of the playoffs. Later this week they go to Cleveland for a
four-game series in which the Indians, the current home-field
advantage leaders, will try to determine that distinction beyond
question. If the Indians succeed in that quest, it will mean the
Yankees' hold on first place could be further weakened.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, meanwhile, will continue their dual quest: catch the
Braves in the division race and stay ahead of the Cincinnati Reds
in the wild-card chase. They can accomplish both by continuing to
win, of course. Actually, they have no other choice considering the
way the other contenders have been playing.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-five or 96 victories may not be enough to make the
playoffs. Never have three teams in one league won 100 games in the
same season, but that development is not beyond the realm of
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   With 18 games left when they began play in Colorado Monday
night, if the Mets matched their .611 winning percentage, they
would win 99 games. That would be enough. And if the Mets made it
and the Yankees didn't, that would be enough to ignite Mount St.
Steinbrenner. The lava would flow all winter long. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
