<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0924 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-PONCIAN-LADN     09-13 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PONCIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONCIANO CONTINUES BATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   McPHERSON, Kan. _ Those intense eyes seem to burn a hole through
the interviewer a second after he hears the question, ``Are you
starting over?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think?'' he answers.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Ron Ponciano, former head coach at Cal State
Northridge and Big Sky Conference Coach of the Year in 1998, left
for Seguin, Texas, where the McPherson Bulldogs opened their season
Saturday against Texas Lutheran.
</P>
<P>
   That night, a few hundred people watched McPherson beat Texas
Lutheran 34-13. About 33,000 saw Kansas hand CSUN its second-worst
loss in school history, 71-14.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years after he became a graduate assistant at Azusa
Pacific, it begins again for Ponciano, at a school with an
enrollment of 400 in a small town in the center of Kansas. This is
a place where residents sit on front porches in the early evenings
and wave as neighbors drive past.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano didn't come to McPherson College as the team's new
defensive coordinator to forget what happened last summer, when he
was investigated and then fired in mid-July for what the university
believes were serious violations of school policy and NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   He slept very little in his first three weeks at McPherson,
because after he finished his coaching duties he would go to the
small house he's renting near campus and meticulously go through
CSUN's 130-page report that described Ponciano as a liar and an
employee with no regard for authority.
</P>
<P>
   Night after night, he re-lived the accusations and conclusions,
which he maintains are false.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get real down at night,'' said Ponciano. ``I think about
what position my family is in now. It's tearing me up. To look at
me, where I am now, is very depressing. Depression is a horrible
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano, 40, no longer reads the report. Last Friday, he
finished his answer to the report, which he is sending to his Santa
Barbara-based lawyer, Scott Campbell, who is expected to file
Ponciano's civil lawsuit within the next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``School (officials) think they're going to slip away,''
Ponciano said. ``They messed with my family. My son (3-year-old
Chad) has been saying, `Where is my white house? Where is my pool?'
They turned our world upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano retreated to coaching, his profession for almost half
his life. Even though the players he teaches now are small and slow
by comparison, Ponciano holds them to the same standards as he did
the Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kazor, a former assistant coach with the Chicago Bears who
is in his second season as the head coach at McPherson, said he's
happy with Ponciano's performance, calling him ``a breath of fresh
air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ponciano's) come in and generated excitement with the
defense,'' Kazor said. ``We will be better defensively in his
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano almost didn't get the chance to make it to the season
opener. A few days after he arrived, McPherson athletic director
Dan Hoffman received newspaper articles in the mail _ sent
anonymously _ about Ponciano's firing. Hoffman spent two hours in
the university president's office, explaining why Ponciano deserved
a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly had some concerns,'' Hoffman said. ``In our
society, we are presumed guilty until proven innocent. I thought we
were fortunate to have him here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __The rebuttal __
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano couldn't wait for his suit to be filed to express his
opinion about several issues, including why he thinks he was fired
and the handling of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   __ Regarding his termination, Ponciano thinks he was a
high-ranking pawn in a university plan to concentrate on other
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear to me there were ulterior motives,'' he said.
``They are going to have a hard time saying I was disobedient, that
I ignored rules. We're dealing with bigger issues. (They fired me)
to de-emphasize football.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The $3,000 worth of expense receipts he was accused of
fabricating as an assistant coach in 1996? Ponciano said he only
was doing what he was instructed. He also attacked the report's
conclusion that he taught assistant coach Rob Phenicie his system
of falsifying receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the possible lawsuit, Ponciano didn't name the people
he said told him to turn in the false receipts. But he said he has
kept the paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the memos,'' he said. ``They don't think I kept them,
but I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Phenicie, who resigned for personal reasons in the middle of the
investigation, was an assistant at Valley College in '96. He came
to CSUN in '97, when Ponciano left to take the defensive
coordinator's job at San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't tell you what Rob Phenicie looked like in '97,''
Ponciano said. ``I never met him.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ponciano's relationship with former assistant Jeff Kearin has
cooled. Kearin, who talked openly last December about someday
coming back to Northridge as the team's head coach, accepted the
head coaching job on an interim basis a week after Ponciano was
fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who my friends are right now,'' Ponciano said.
``I'm surely not perfect, but people do funny things when they see
an opportunity. To this date, Jeff Kearin has never called me. It
wouldn't go well.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin maintains he was never disloyal to Ponciano. He said he
hasn't called Ponciano because of the awkward situation.
</P>
<P>
   __ Contrary to interim university President Louanne Kennedy's
belief, Ponciano said he never tried to fire assistant coaches
Craig Wall and Keith Borges when he thought they were providing
incriminating information against him.
</P>
<P>
   He produced memos he sent to Borges and Wall, which were
approved by Sam Jankovich, the interim athletic director at the
time, that didn't contain any language about termination, just a
list of the pair's deficiencies in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ponciano also pointed out several other passages in the
report which he called ``ridiculous.'' He says he was honest in his
interviews with internal auditor Peter Dinauer, but when he
requested the notes from those interviews several times, he was
denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to be pro-active,'' he said. ``The things I did wrong,
I admitted. I'm looking at this (report), and I can't believe what
I'm reading.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he said, ``Someone meant to get me out and they did.
Things are fabricated and there are flat-out lies.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Heartache in the heartland __
</P>
<P>
   McPherson has a local newspaper that publishes a daily police
log. Last week there was an entry about a resident being visited by
officers because his dog was barking too loud.
</P>
<P>
   When Ponciano drives his pickup truck around town, his thoughts
drift back to his childhood in Willows, a dot on the map in the
upper San Joaquin Valley. But his recent memory works just as well.
He reads about the Matadors on the Internet and wonders how the
players are performing in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss those rascals, big time,'' he said. ``There's so many
things I miss throughout the day. I hope they win the Big Sky
championship. I may be in Kansas, but my football team is in the
San Fernando Valley. I believe in those kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Ponciano is making an impact at McPherson, an NAIA
school that hasn't had a winning season in decades. After a 15-hour
bus ride, the Bulldogs didn't give up a touchdown until the fourth
quarter, when the game was already decided. With the same core of
defensive players last year, Texas Lutheran beat McPherson 50-38.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sweet victory for Ponciano, who is just now coming out
of the darkest time in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest thing is learning the kids' names,'' Ponciano
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
