<HEADER>
A0937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BLISS-TRIBUTE-NYT &LR;      09-13 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BLISS-TRIBUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
100 YEARS OF DEATH ON THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You might say that Henry Hale Bliss was done in by
his own chivalry.
</P>
<P>
   As this old story goes, he had stepped off a trolley car at
Central Park West and 74th Street and was turning to help a certain
Miss Lee also get down when he was run over by an automobile. Miss
Lee became hysterical, and for good reason. Bliss' skull and chest
were crushed. A few hours later, he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Had all this happened in today's New York, Bliss might have
lived. He probably would have kept walking and avoided the auto.
How many men today extend a hand to a woman getting off a bus? For
that matter, how many women welcome the assistance, rather than
telling the guy to keep his bleeping hands to himself?
</P>
<P>
   But Bliss, a 68-year-old realtor, lived in a more chivalrous
day, and his graciousness proved his undoing. It did, however, put
him in the history books, for he is believed to be the first person
in America to be mortally injured by a motor vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   That was on Sept. 13, 1899. Monday, the 100th anniversary of
that awful event, dozens of people flocked to the busy intersection
of 74th and Central Park West _ known as ``Dangerous Stretch'' even
a century ago _ to remember Bliss and to appeal for stricter
enforcement of laws protecting pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   It was a motley gathering.
</P>
<P>
   There was Harris Silver, founder of a pedestrian safety group
called Citystreets, who said most traffic fatalities were avoidable
if drivers would only be a bit more careful. ``We're not fans of
the word `accident,''' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   There was Heward Grafftey, a traffic-safety advocate from Canada
who welcomed the crowd in English and French. Must be de rigueur
for a Canadian these days. He raised a few eyebrows by citing
estimates that motor vehicles have killed 30 million people
worldwide since Bliss.
</P>
<P>
   There was Gordon Stewart, president of the Insurance Information
Institute. His trade group's members hate traffic deaths, Stewart
observed, if only because they hate paying life insurance claims.
No one can accuse him of lacking candor.
</P>
<P>
   There was Henry J. Stern, the city parks commissioner, whose
agency prepared a green-and-white sign marking Bliss' untimely end.
Stern came out foursquare against death. Still, he felt impelled to
affirm his belief that ``the automobile has been a blessing to
civilization rather than a curse.''
</P>
<P>
   A knot of people stood off to the side, not part of the formal
ceremony. They were from another New York pedestrian-safety group,
Right of Way, and they held canvas banners carrying the names of
nearly every one of the 1,020 pedestrians and bicyclists who died
in the city from 1994 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing those deaths in a report issued this year, Right of
Way found that, overwhelmingly, drivers were to blame. Most
typically, pedestrians were knocked down while in crosswalks, where
by law they had priority over cars. Interestingly, drunken driving
was a factor in only 4 percent of the cases. Quite simply, said
Charles Komanoff, who directed the study, the main problem is an
excess of ``dangerous and aggressive driving.''
</P>
<P>
   To get back to Bliss, few New Yorkers will be shocked to learn
that he was run over by a taxicab (whose passenger happened to be
the son of a former mayor, Franklin Edson). Equally few will be
startled to hear that the taxi driver, Arthur Smith, claimed he had
to swerve to avoid hitting a truck that was in the way. Plus ca
change and so on, as Grafftey might say.
</P>
<P>
   One big difference between then and now is that Smith was
marched off to the nearest police station house and charged with
homicide. His ultimate fate is not clear. But we do know that when
a driver plows into a pedestrian these days, a typical police
reaction is to advise him to be more careful next time.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that all is not gloomy. Police figures show
that pedestrian deaths in the city have been declining, to 193 last
year from 277 in 1997. The 1990 figure was 365.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, perfection is far off, a point accentuated on Monday by
the presence of three great-granddaughters of Henry Bliss. The
women stepped into Central Park West, and put pink and red roses on
the spot where their ancestor is assumed to have been struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look both ways,'' a man called out _ an important warning for
anyone in this city and perhaps proof that chivalry is not dead
after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 2246EDT &QL; 
