<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-COMPENSATION-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 VICTIMS OF NAZIS ARE DEALT A BLOW IN LAWSUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ In separate decisions Monday, two federal judges
dealt a blow to efforts by the survivors of Nazi labor and
concentration camps to get reparations and damages from companies
that helped fuel the German war machine.
</P>
<P>
   The two judges dismissed class-action lawsuits brought against
the companies, most of which have sizable operations in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing the lawsuits, both judges seemed to acknowledge
the horrors of the camps but lamented that the issues were not
appropriate for a federal court. The issues, they ruled, concerned
international treaties between nations, and foreign policy, and
were thus in the realm of the executive branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courts may not pass judgment upon the political negotiations
of the executive branch and the international community,'' Judge
Joseph Greenaway Jr. of U.S. District Court wrote in his 120-page
decision in one of the lawsuits, brought against Ford Motor Co. and
its former German counterpart in the World War II era, Ford Werke
AG. ``Such intrusion into the realm of foreign policy would
undermine the executive branch's sole discretion in the field of
international relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing separately in another group of four consolidated
class-action suits, Judge Dickinson Debevoise, also of U.S.
District Court, said every human instinct cried out for remedy in
the cases, but he added that the court did not have the right to
engage in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not accurate to characterize the present actions as
simply controversies between private parties,'' Debevoise wrote in
his 78-page decision as he criticized one major contention of the
plaintiffs. ``In effect the plaintiffs are inviting this court to
try its hand at refashioning the reparations agreements which the
United States and other World War II combatants forged. This is a
task which the court does not have the judicial power to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   The four consolidated cases ruled on by Debevoise included
claims against Degussa AG, the chemicals and precious metals
company that refined gold seized by the Nazis and which
manufactured the deadly Zyklon B gas used in the concentration
camps.
</P>
<P>
   The other cases involved the giant electric company Siemens AG
and its aircraft-manufacturing operations during the war, which,
according to the plaintiffs, used as many as 100,000 slave laborers
provided by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Melvyn Weiss, a lawyer representing plaintiffs in the cases
before both judges, said he was disappointed by the rulings and
added that they would be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that he saw some hope in Debevoise's insistence that
government officials had some responsibility for addressing the
claims of people like his clients in negotiations with Germany, and
that Germany had some legal obligation to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts the Germans in a bad position because they have
insisted all along that they had no legal obligations in such
cases, just humanitarian obligations,'' Weiss said. ``It puts the
U.S. government in a box because they have always insisted that we
had no legal remedies.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that lawyers would press political institutions in
both nations to bring pressure on the governments to settle the
claims.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The rulings came in five of an estimated three dozen cases in
U.S. courts that seek damages from companies said to have profited
in Germany during the war years. Most of the lawsuits were filed in
the wake of the historic agreement by Swiss banks last year to
settle $1.25 billion in claims brought by Holocaust survivors who
accused them of failing to return their stolen assets after the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the companies involved in the cases could not be
reached for comment. But both Siemens and Degussa are among 16
companies involved in negotiations with the Conference on Jewish
Material Claims Against Germany, an international organization of
several groups seeking restitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that this is an issue that is one of morality,''
said Gideon Taylor, executive vice president of the organization.
``For us, the process of finding a just and a fair resolution of
these issues for slave laborers is one that will continue
regardless of court decisions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
