<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINEUP SHUFFLES AS PRODIGALS RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the day the Bruins named a starting
quarterback, they also welcomed back 10 players from suspension and
immediately inserted six into the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Tony White, Robert Thomas and Ryan Nece returned from the
disabled-parking-placard suspensions to fortify a depleted
linebacking corps. All three will start Saturday against Fresno
State.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Roques takes over at strong safety for Jason Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Cabrera slides into his starting spot at left guard.
</P>
<P>
   And Durell Price is back as the No. 1 fullback. He replaces Matt
Stanley, who earned a scholarship but lacks Price's leadership
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need some of that,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Four other suspended players _ guard Jim Ghezzi, tailback Keith
Brown, safety Eric Whitfield and linebacker Ali Abdul Azziz _
return as reserves. The 11th suspended player, cornerback Marques
Anderson, is out for the fall quarter.
</P>
<P>
   __ The defense rests: The return of Roques and Whitfield means
tailback DeShaun Foster and receiver Freddie Mitchell will no
longer play defense in passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   Foster will remain the starting tailback, although his workload
diminishes with Brown's return.
</P>
<P>
   ``DeShaun got tired (against Ohio State),'' Toledo said. ``He
got 42 snaps, and Jermaine (Lewis) got 24. We'll take a few away
from DeShaun and give them to Keith.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Make way for the rookie: True freshman Ricky Manning, UCLA's
best defensive back so far, will start at right cornerback. Senior
Jason Bell won't play Saturday because of a nagging heel injury
that required offseason surgery.
</P>
<P>
   If Bell had been healthy, Toledo said, Manning would have
replaced redshirt freshman Joe Hunter at left cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   __ Position change: Outside linebacker Santi Hall has returned
to defensive end, the position he was expected to play before the
suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, a sophomore, becomes the No. 2 weakside end behind
freshman Rusty Williams _ the spot previously occupied by Travor
Turner, who is out for the year with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: Reserve outside linebacker Billy Pieper will
miss two to four weeks because of a torn medial collateral ligament
in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman guard Mike Saffer is out two to four weeks with a
sprained right ankle. His injury is significant from a personnel
standpoint: He's one of the best players on an inexperienced unit.
Senior guard Matt Phelan, who had been starting for the suspended
Cabrera, slides over to Saffer's spot.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Danny Farmer, who tweaked his sprained left ankle at
Ohio State, is expected to play Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Stanley was named offensive player of the
game. Safety Joey Strycula _ ``He's like a coach on the field,''
Toledo said _ was the top defensive player, and walk-on Adam
Geitner won the special-teams honor. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Roques replaces Mitchell as the punt returner. Mitchell and
Lewis will continue to return kicks. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Right tackle Brian Polak and receiver Brad Melsby were named
captains this week. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Sept. 25 game at Stanford begins at 2 p.m. and won't be
televised live. However, Fox Sports West 2 will show the game
delayed at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
