u a BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      09-13 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASPER SUSPECT SAID HE WAS `HERO' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ Stripping a black man and dragging him behind a
pickup until his body was torn in two made white supremacist
Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr. feel that he was soaring ``like an
eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   A month later, sitting in the Jasper County Jail, he came to
this conclusion about his role in the murder:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the God-damned hero of the day!'' he wrote to a friend at
his old prison unit.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight-page letter, intercepted by jailers and read to the
jury Monday on the first day of testimony in Brewer's capital
murder trial, the defendant wrote of a conversation he once had
with another inmate while serving time for burglary and parole
violations at the Beto I prison unit in Tennessee Colony.
</P>
<P>
   That prisoner, whom Brewer called Jason ``Red Arm,'' had spoken
of ``rolling a tire,'' prison slang for assaulting a black person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I did it; and no longer am I a virgin!'' Brewer wrote.
``It was a rush and I'm still lickin' my lips for more ... ''
</P>
<P>
   But while prosecutors insist the letter is a virtual confession
to the June 7, 1998, murder of James Byrd Jr., Brewer's defense
team was equally as adamant that the letter could be read more
literally to convey that Brewer was referring to having sex.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in a 15-minute, low-key opening statement, Jasper
County District Attorney Guy James Gray told the 12 jurors and two
alternates that Brewer, 32, was the mentor and hate teacher for his
former prison buddy and co-defendant John William ``Bill'' King
when King was approached to join the Confederate Knights of
America, a small prison gang affiliated with the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He schooled the young man,'' Gray said. ``This guy was the
mentor. He took him under his wing and taught him about the
structure of the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   A Jasper jury convicted King, 24, last February and sentenced
him to death. A third defendant, Shawn Allen Berry, also 24, is to
be tried later this fall in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Gray told the jury that Brewer, who would face life in prison or
death by injection if convicted, ``sees himself as a hero, a
star.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He sees that he's accomplished something,'' the prosecutor
said. ``It's really a weird mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Jesus Moran, a prison inmate who met Brewer at the
Huntsville Diagnostic Unit after his arrest in Byrd's killing,
testified that Brewer had expressed no remorse for the crime,
saying only that if he had to do it all over again, he would make
sure he got away with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was up to them, they would like to take the whole black
population and shoot them behind the head _ men, women and
children,'' Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's attorneys, Doug Barlow and Layne Walker of Beaumont,
declined to give an opening statement, but put on a vigorous
defense, cross-examining all eight witnesses who took the stand.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer also seemed animated in court. Wearing a white shirt, tie
and a navy sportcoat that hid his racist tattoos as well as a stun
belt, Brewer sat with his arm around the back of Walker's chair.
Throughout the day, he whispered to his attorneys, and at one point
while waiting for the jury to return from lunch, he laughed out
loud and patted Walker on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and several witnesses described Brewer as a
committed racist who had risen in the ranks of the CKA and had
signed a blood oath to the Klan in 1995. By the time King arrived
at Beto I, Brewer was already the top CKA officer at the prison,
the ``Exalted Cyclops.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving rapidly, prosecutors had put on four witnesses by lunch
time and had shown the nine-man, five-woman jury more than a dozen
color photographs of Byrd's corpse.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs, which have not been made public and which the
Byrd family has never seen, show Byrd's dismembered, decapitated
body lying in the middle of Huff Creek Road east of Jasper, just
outside the gates to a rural black cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   They also show his upper torso and head as it was found the
morning after the murder, in a ditch about a mile down from the
rest of his body. They also were shown photos taken during Byrd's
autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's father, his siblings and other relatives sat in the front
few rows of the courtroom, next to the jury box. Having sat through
the trial of King earlier this year, there were few surprises for
the family in Monday's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But Clara Taylor, Byrd's sister, said she did not realize until
Monday that her brother's pants had been stripped down to his
ankles before he was dragged to his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was pulled down in the dragging,'' she said
afterward. ``It shows the intense cruelty of Brewer and all three
of them. They meant to inflict serious punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
