r f BC-HILTON-CASINO-KAN &LR;      09-13 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILTON-CASINO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATION CASINOS INC. MAKES OFFER FOR FLAMINGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Station Casinos Inc. on Monday announced a
surprise purchase of the Flamingo Hilton Casino for $22.5 million,
leaving its main Kansas City rival Harrah's literally surrounded.
</P>
<P>
   John V. Finamore, Station Casinos Inc. president for Midwest
operations, said the company intends to keep the casino open,
retain its estimated 800 employees and remodel and rebrand the
riverboat as a Station property.
</P>
<P>
   The Flamingo's proposed sale to Trump Hotels &AMP; Casino Resorts
Inc. for $15 million fell apart in recent weeks as the Missouri
Gaming Commission showed signs it was balking at approving the
sale.
</P>
<P>
   When the deal was announced in January, Trump and the Hilton
Hotels Corp. agreed either side could walk away after midnight Aug.
31 if regulatory approval hadn't been granted, and that's what
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happened very quickly, in the last 10 days or so,''
Finamore said Monday, after ``it became very clear the Trump deal
was not going to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Station's proposed purchase still faces approval by the Missouri
Gaming Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Finamore said Station couldn't pass up the deal for a property
that cost an estimated $119 million to build. ``This is a great
deal for our company,'' he said. ``For $22.5 million this was a
no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale calls for Station to assume Hilton's land lease
payments used to help repay bonds issued to develop the Richard L.
Berkley Riverfront Park, Finamore said.
</P>
<P>
   The move is an about-face of sorts for Station, which locally
had put its own expansion plans on hold during a capital spending
slowdown by its Las Vegas parent.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's Entertainment Inc. and a group associated with St. Jo
Frontier Casino owner William M. Grace also were thought to be
among the interested potential bidders.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Fisher, executive director of the Missouri Gaming
Commission, had little to say about Station's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a company in good standing in this state,'' he said.
``We're still digesting the implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Those implications revolve around the prospect of two companies,
Station and Harrah's, dominating Missouri's gaming marketplace with
ownership of 12 of the state's 16 casino properties.
</P>
<P>
   Each company would own three of Kansas City's seven riverboats
(including Harrah's ownership of the now-closed Sam's Town casino).
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, Station would own two boats and Harrah's four,
after the expected approval of its announced purchase of Players
International Inc., which operates the Riverport gambling complex
in partnership with Harrah's in Maryland Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's two big players,'' Fisher said. ``It's certainly
something we will look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher would not discuss the commission's now-ended review of
the Trump bid. But regulators here and in New Jersey, where the
company is based, have expressed concern in recent months about the
Trump company's ability to service its $1.8 billion debt.
</P>
<P>
   Finamore said Station hopes to win state regulatory approval and
close the deal before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a name for it yet,'' he added. ``It will be a
Station property operated by us.''
</P>
<P>
   Station also operates its Station Casino Kansas City complex.
</P>
<P>
   Between Station Casino Kansas City and the Flamingo lies Kansas
City marketplace rival Harrah's North Kansas City Casino &AMP; Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Since last fall Station and Harrah's have vied for the market
share lead, with Station now holding a slim lead.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas-based Station Casinos Inc. intends to spend several
million dollars in installing new slot machines, carpeting and
other upgrades, Finamore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it will go to removing the Flamingo identity and
`Stationizing' it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finamore said it was too early to discuss long-term plans that
might include a hotel and other nongambling amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Trump Hotels agreed to purchase the Flamingo for $15 million _
less than 15 cents on the dollar that it cost to build the purple
and pink gambling palace a few miles north of downtown Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The ownership change was quietly engineered late last year to
take Hilton off the hook with the gaming commission over
still-pending bribery and perjury allegations that have threatened
Hilton's gaming licenses in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year Missouri gaming officials appeared more than
ready to approve the deal and be done with Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1998 Hilton agreed to pay the federal
government $655,000 in fines and penalties to avoid a criminal
trial on federal allegations that Hilton executives provided
financial rewards to associates of then-Kansas City Port Authority
Chairman Elbert Anderson in exchange for his political support for
the casino, built on city-owned land.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton maintains that neither it nor any of its employees did
anything illegal or improper, said Marc Grossman, spokesman for the
Beverly Hills, Calif.-based company.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton remains under threat of being fined, suspended or
stripped of its Missouri Gaming Commission license unless it sells
the property _ soon.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton wrote the struggling casino off its books as a financial
loss in 1997. Since then the market has grown, Sam's Town has
closed, and the Flamingo has held on to a respectable 13 percent
market share.
</P>
<P>
   That, and the imminent prospect of open boarding at Missouri's
riverboat casinos made the Flamingo a desirable if modest
acquisition for expansion-minded gaming companies, Finamore said.
</P>
<P>
   Grossing in excess of $5.5 million a month, ``It's going to be a
nice revenue stream for our company,'' Finamore said.
</P>
<P>
   Station also operates casinos in Las Vegas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
