<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-REPORT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDS SHOW CONGRESS HAD WACO TEAR GAS FILES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
and JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The FBI's use of potentially combustible tear gas
during the 1993 assault on the Branch Davidian compound is outlined
in documents the Justice Department delivered to Congress four
years ago, according to records disclosed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats said the documents cast doubt on
Republican claims that the Justice Department was trying to conceal
the FBI's deployment of the military-style tear gas canisters near
the fiery end of the standoff near Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The documents _ handwritten notes and summaries of interviews
with FBI agents _ were delivered to the House Government Reform
Committee in 1995 along with other evidence related to the 51-day
siege.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic staff members said they found the documents over the
weekend while combing through more than 40 boxes of files put in
storage after the committee's 1994-95 investigation of the standoff
between federal agents and the Branch Davidian religious sect.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery prompted criticism of top-ranking Republicans,
particularly House Government Reform Chairman Dan Burton and Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, who have led the GOP chorus calling for
the resignation of Attorney General Janet Reno, who oversees the
Justice Department and FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to the allegations of a cover-up, substantial
evidence of the use of military tear gas rounds was, in fact,
provided to Congress in 1995,'' said California Rep. Henry Waxman,
the committee's top-ranking Democrat. ``There is no indication that
Chairman Burton or his staff thought to review these documents
before accusing the attorney general of a cover-up.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI acknowledged last month _ after six years of denials _
that agents fired rounds of potentially incendiary military tear
gas at the roof of a concrete bunker near the Branch Davidian
compound. The canisters were fired hours before fire enveloped the
compound, the FBI said, standing by earlier claims that the tear
gas did not trigger the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a cover-up about what was in these documents, you
could say that the Congress was covering up these documents just as
much as the attorney general was covering up the documents,''
Waxman said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who are preparing for new hearings into the Waco
incident, bridled at Waxman's assertion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that Mr. Waxman chose partisan attacks over a
serious attempt to get to the facts,'' said Mark Corallo, a
spokesman for Burton. ``You have to take it with a grain of salt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At worst, what we have is an oversight by congressional staff
in 1995 when they were looking through hundreds of thousands of
pages of documents,'' Corallo said, adding that Republican staff
members still have not found the material. ``Somehow they (the
Democrats) found it right away, in a couple of hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Corallo pointed out that Burton was not committee chairman when
the Justice Department turned over evidence to Congress, much of it
three days before the committee's hearings into the raid.
</P>
<P>
   The documents found by Waxman's staff were turned over to former
Sen. John Danforth, a Missouri Republican who was named by Reno
last week to lead an independent inquiry into the FBI's role in the
deadly fire at the compound. More than 80 people _ including about
two dozen children _ died inside the compound during the FBI
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents was a Justice Department interview in 1993
with an FBI pilot who recalled a radio conversation between agents
on the ground discussing ``utilization of some sort of military
round ... on a concrete bunker'' near the Davidian compound.
</P>
<P>
   Also released by Waxman were copies of handwritten notes
indicating that ``smoke from bunker came when these guys tried to
shoot gas into the bunker (military gas round).'' The notes also
said that ``rounds bounced off.'' One interview summary said an FBI
agent reported that ``smoke on film came from attempt to penetrate
bunker w/1 military and 2 ferret rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Texas Rangers released a 13-page report Monday
indicating that casings from spent ammunition _ the kind often used
by professional snipers _ were found in a house near the Davidian
compound. The building had been used by federal agents during the
standoff.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has maintained that its agents did not fire their
weapons during the final assault on April 19, 1993. Officials at
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms acknowledge that its
sharpshooters used the house during the initial gunbattle with
David Koresh and his Branch Davidian followers.
</P>
<P>
   A Houston lawyer representing plaintiffs in a wrongful death
suit said Monday that the casings may be meaningless unless the
government produces the rifles that fired them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never going to see those rifles,'' said Jim Brannon.
``They've probably been broken down and sold for scrap by now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the report submitted to Congress on Friday and posted on the
Internet on Monday, the Texas Rangers, which had been custodian of
most of the evidence gathered at the scene, said 12 .308-caliber
casings and 24 Israeli-made .223-caliber casings were recovered
from the house used by the FBI throughout the standoff.
</P>
<P>
   The agent in charge of the house was Lon Horiuchi, an FBI sniper
who fired the shots that killed the wife of a white separatist at
Ruby Ridge, Idaho, a few months before the Waco standoff. Another
FBI agent initially reported hearing shots fired from the house on
the last day of the siege, but the agency now says that account was
inaccurate and the agent has changed his story.
</P>
<P>
   Without matching the shells to the guns, Brannon said, it would
be impossible to know if the cartridges were fired by ATF or FBI
agents.
</P>
<P>
   That issue probably will have to be resolved in Congress, and
not in the civil wrongful death suit filed by survivors of the Waco
victims. That suit has been scheduled for trial on Oct. 18 and the
cut-off date for discovery was Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under ordinary circumstances, we would make them cough up
those guns,'' Brannon said. ``But there can be no more discovery
except by agreement. I don't think the government's lawyers will
agree to cough up anything.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter Smith, who presided over the criminal
trials of 11 Davidians accused in the deaths of four ATF agents, is
also hearing the civil case and has not made rulings friendly to
the plaintiffs _ including delaying the trial until all of the
recently disclosed evidence can be studied.
</P>
<P>
   The government Monday asked for an extension to Sept. 24 to turn
over a list of expert witnesses in the suit. Government lawyers
said they could not produce the documents in time because they also
were trying to comply with congressional subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the civil trial, the spent casings could raise new
questions about the credibility of the FBI and the steps it took to
end the siege.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, the Justice Department had maintained that the
Davidians, not FBI agents, started the fire that destroyed the
compound. Two weeks ago, the department acknowledged that its
agents did fire two pyrotechnic tear gas canisters on the last day
of the siege and had withheld that fact from Reno, who had
prohibited the use of such devices.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI made the admission after an independent filmmaker, Mike
McNulty, was given access to the Texas Rangers' evidence lockers
and was preparing to report the use of pyrotechnics in a
documentary to be released this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the report to Congress, the Texas Department of Public Safety
included a memo from Sgt. George L. Turner, who found a 40 mm metal
cartridge near the compound the day after the siege ended and
reported it immediately to FBI agents. It turned out to be a M651
military tear gas grenade that burns at 500 to 700 degrees
Fahrenheit and ``is capable of igniting flammable items,''
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has said that two of those cartridges were fired at the
bunker 40 yards from the compound, not at buildings occupied by the
Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   The Davidian compound burst into flames about six hours after
the FBI decided to end the standoff by breaking through the walls
with armored vehicles and inserting tear gas into the house.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' report _ an inventory and analysis of some of the
24,000 pounds of evidence in their custody _ notes that other
devices capable of starting a fire were used by government agents.
They include flash-bang grenades and military flares.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
