<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: BRITAIN; NORTHERN IRELAND; GERMANY; SRI LANKA;
PAKISTAN; AFGHANISTAN; MEXICO; ECUADOR; ARGENTINA; UNITED NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: SPY KNOWN FOR 30 YEARS
</P>
<P>
   The government said that for more than 30 years it had evidence
of the espionage activities of Melita Norwood, the 87-year-old
woman who admitted giving nuclear-weapons research documents to the
Soviet Union. Home Secretary Jack Straw said MI5 decided not to
interview her out of fear of jeopardizing other investigations. The
agency decided seven years ago never to prosecute her, he added.
Two other people named as agents in a book based on KGB files were
former Labor MPs, Tom Driberg and Raymond Fletcher, both now dead.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: PROTESTANT PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   The ruling executive of Northern Ireland's main Protestant
party, the Ulster Unionists, unanimously condemned the report of an
international commission to restructure the province's police
service and said it would draw up alternative recommendations. But
the 110-man body approved the continued participation of its
leader, David Trimble, in the formal review of the deadlocked
Northern Ireland peace pact under way in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: SCHROEDER UNBOWED
</P>
<P>
   Reeling from defeats in state and municipal elections,
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder vowed to press ahead with an unpopular
austerity program, involving budget cuts of $16 billion. After
several costly months of wavering, he is trying to project the
statesmanlike image of a leader prepared to take tough steps for
Germany's future economic health.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: HIGH TOLL IN CLASHES
</P>
<P>
   In the fiercest fighting in months, 53 soldiers and more than
100 Tamil separatist rebels were killed in the northern Wanni
region as the government began an offensive to expand the territory
in its control.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: TEST-TREATY OPPOSITION
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz told the newspaper Dawn that
Pakistan will not sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty until the
United States lifts all sanctions imposed after Pakistan tested
nuclear devices in May 1998. The United States still restricts the
sale of military equipment to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: REPORT ON WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. monitor for violence against women said after a visit
to Afghanistan that the Department of the Promotion of Virtue and
Prevention of Vice, which applies dozens of prohibitions to women,
was ``the most misogynist such entity in the world.'' However,
Radhika Coomaraswamy of Sri Lanka saw some improvements, especially
in the growth of private home schools and better access to health
care.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: EXPULSION VOIDED
</P>
<P>
   A Supreme Court panel has overturned the February 1998 expulsion
of Tom Hansen, an American accused of violating his tourist visa by
serving as an observer at government peace talks with Zapatista
rebels. The high court found that his expulsion violated
constitutional rights. More than 200 other foreigners have been
expelled from Chiapas on similar grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: 12 FOREIGNERS ABDUCTED
</P>
<P>
   Eight foreign oil workers, including an American, and four
European tourists have been kidnapped by more than 20 armed men in
military uniforms near the northern border with Colombia.
Ecuadorean army officials said they suspect that a left-wing
Colombian guerrilla group may have been responsible, but added that
they could not rule out right-wing paramilitary units from Colombia
or common criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: PROVINCIAL SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   Despite running far behind in presidential polls, the governing
Justicialist Party has won three of four provincial elections for
governor. Its victories in La Rioja, Misiones and San Luis were
expected, as was an Alianza win in Chaco. The results confirm a
trend in which the Justicialists will control most provinces no
matter who wins the presidential vote next month.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   BELLAMY'S NEW TERM
</P>
<P>
   Carol Bellamy was named to a second five-year term as executive
director of UNICEF, the U.N. Children's Fund. Her first term ends
in May. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said that Ms. Bellamy, a
former New York City Council president and former director of the
Peace Corps, had served ``with distinction and devotion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
