<DOCNO> NYT19990913.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1084 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-1STLD-     09-13 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BILL'S LITTLE GIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Changes ``did'' to ``do'' in graf that begins ``The prisoners
...'' Changes ``the Israeli spy Jonathan Pollard'' to ``Jonathan
Pollard, who spied for Israel.'' Deletes last sentence of graf that
begins ``The Clintons ...'' Adds a new final graf.)  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idea that Bill Clinton let members of a terrorist group out
of jail for Hillary's sake is an interesting concept. It's the
political equivalent of giving your wife an anniversary gift of an
untrained collie. There are really a lot of things she could use
more.
</P>
<P>
   I'm in the minority on this, but I tend to believe the Clinton
camp's version of how the president came to offer clemency to
members of the Puerto Rican nationalist organization FALN. When the
choice is between a sneaky plot and all-purpose bumbling, in this
White House it's generally safe to go with Door Number Two.
</P>
<P>
   The president's supporters say he signed off on the clemency
request at the recommendation of aides, and that his wife had
nothing to do with it. Puerto Rican politicians, who are currently
in no mood to protect the first lady, support this version. Rep.
Nydia Velazquez, D-N.Y., says the deal was brokered by the
president's outgoing political counsel, Charles Ruff. ``We had a
very emotional meeting with Mr. Ruff,'' Ms. Velazquez said. ``We
cried. It was very moving. We tried to put a human face on these
political prisoners, people who have not been convicted of killing
anyone, who have spent up to 20 years away from their families.''
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners, all convicted of nonviolent crimes, do seem to
have gotten a raw deal in their sentencing _ who gets 90 years in
jail for bank robbery? They had actually already disavowed
violence, and it seems easy to imagine that the White House was
bowing to the thousands of pleas it had received from church groups
and other prominent figures.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the president, the prisoners turned out to be
less than sympathetic figures for the country at large,
self-righteous and unbending. (You could see how they might have
appealed to Jimmy Carter.) One, Ricardo Jimenez, asked on NBC about
people killed by FALN bombings, basically blamed the proprietors of
the restaurants and taverns that got blown up. ``I think all
precautions were taken, you know, to make sure that all human life
was preserved,'' he said. ``And in the end the measures were not
taken that were necessary by the people who owned those
establishments.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who supported her husband at first, bailed out
when the deal came under fire. People like Velazquez were never
consulted. For all the listening the first lady has been doing, she
has apparently not learned that when you are making a decision
involving Puerto Rican sensibilities, you should at least touch
base with Puerto Rican politicians.
</P>
<P>
   But the whole idea of freeing the prisoners was a political
loser for Mrs. Clinton from the start. She's planning to run for
Senate against Rudolph Giuliani, a man who regards law and order as
his own name-brand franchise. New York has tons of different ethnic
groups, at least half of which have members in jail for allegedly
political crimes. If the president was pandering, as his critics
contended, he was pandering to a constituency already pretty safely
in his wife's corner, while making her appear soft on terrorism in
the suburbs and upstate, and alienating all the other ethnic groups
that failed to get their political prisoners sprung. Sure enough,
the Puerto Rican prisoners had not even gotten out of their cells
before Jewish supporters of Jonathan Pollard, who spied for Israel,
were demanding that Mrs. Clinton get behind his release, too.
</P>
<P>
   The real question may be why there was no one in the White House
protecting Mrs. Clinton's back who could have derailed the clemency
deal early on.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration is supposed to be in the business of
running the country, not electing Hillary senator. Mrs. Clinton has
been trying to have it both ways, basking in the real popularity
the president enjoys in New York and taking credit for his
administration's accomplishments, while distancing herself from the
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons want us to believe that the president never told
Hillary about critical details of the clemency offer that might
have influenced her decision to jump ship. Maybe he didn't. Maybe
for the first time in their married life, they lost interest in
political plotting.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever he said or she said, the conspiracy theorists can't
have it both ways. If Bill Clinton is a purely poll-driven public
official who does nothing without weighing the potential gains and
losses, he could certainly have figured out that offering clemency
to people with even the remotest of connections to terrorism was
not going to be a crowd-pleaser. And if he was now making every
decision with his wife's Senate race in mind, he would never have
made this one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
