<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFYMETRIX-INCYTE-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES SOAR AND SINK AFTER RULING ON GENE CHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares in Incyte Pharmaceuticals Inc. plummeted
Monday and shares in Affymetrix Inc. soared after a judge ruled
last week in favor of Affymetrix in a patent dispute between the
two Silicon Valley companies over gene-chip technology.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, Judge Richard Torczon of the U.S. Patent and
Trademark Office ruled that Incyte had ``failed to establish a
threshold case'' against Affymetrix's patents.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte, which said it would appeal the decision, had sought to
block two Affymetrix patents on the production of DNA microarrays,
glass chips that are coated with genes for use in genetic analysis
and drug research.
</P>
<P>
   Affymetrix had already sued Incyte for patent infringement in
January 1998 after Incyte acquired this gene-chip technology with
its purchase of Synteni, a start-up company. The technology uses
liquid droplets to deposit DNA on glass, while Affymetrix uses
photolithography, the technique used to make computer chips on
silicon. But Affymetrix has always asserted that its patents
covered DNA microarrays regardless of how they were made.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte shares closed at $27.25, down $14.125, or 34 percent.
Affymetrix shares closed at $121.0625, up $19.9375, or 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the ruling indicated that the Patent Office was
taking a very broad interpretation of Affymetrix's patents, which
could effectively block any competitors in the microarray market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does broadly cover the chip technology itself, and that is
why they have had this rise in the share price,'' said Viren Mehta,
an analyst with Mehta Partners. As for Incyte, he said, ``Right off
the bat, their microarray business, which contributed about 7 to 10
percent of their revenues, will suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   The broader question, he said, is how much Incyte depends on
internal use of the technology for its primary products _ databases
of genetic information and related analytical tools.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Bendekgey, Incyte's general counsel, said the Patent
Office's decision ``was based on limited evidence relating to only
two legal issues'' and did not address claims yet to be resolved in
the lawsuit, which is set for trial next year in California. ``We
continue to believe that these defenses will enable us to prevail
at trial,'' he said, ``just as we defeated Affymetrix's earlier
request for a preliminary injunction.''
</P>
<P>
   The injunction would have blocked sales of Incyte's product. But
Affymetrix officials said that they were confident they would
prevail at trial and that the hurdle in winning a preliminary
injunction _ proving irreparable harm _ was difficult because they
had lost few actual sales to Incyte.
</P>
<P>
   They estimated that Incyte's sales of the infringing technology
amounted to only $2 million this year, while Affymetrix had sales
for the first six months of $39.5 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``A lot of the customers now are going to believe we have won
this,'' said Vern Norviel, Affymetrix's general counsel. He said
that Affymetrix had licensed or was negotiating licenses to a
number of companies with microarray products and that he expected
others to follow. ``There are many methods that could be used to
get to a chip,'' he said. ``We have the patent on a chip.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Affymetrix said it had agreed to acquire Genetic
Microsystems Inc., a privately held company in Woburn, Mass., in a
stock swap valued at about $121 million. Affymetrix said there was
demand for Genetic Micro's microarrays, which cost less but contain
fewer genes per chip than Affymetrix's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
