<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAIDLAW-BUSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAIDLAW SELLING TWO BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Canada)  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Laidlaw Inc., the Canadian-based operator of North
America's largest bus fleet, including the Greyhound lines, said
Monday that it intends to sell two major businesses that have
depressed its stock price and no longer fit its core transportation
strategy, and to use some of the $2 billion in anticipated proceeds
to buy more buses.
</P>
<P>
   One of the holdings for sale, a 44 percent stake in Safety-Kleen
Corp., an industrial services provider, is a link with Laidlaw's
past in transporting industrial waste. The other is its health-care
division, which includes the largest ambulance service in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   But industrial waste disposal no longer attracts investors, and
Laidlaw has spent the better part of a year trying to restructure
its ambulance operation, American Medical Response, and has nothing
but expenses to show for it. Over the last year, Laidlaw shares
have dropped by 30 percent in value.
</P>
<P>
   News of the planned asset sale pleasantly surprised investors.
Laidlaw shares gained 75 cents, or 11.4 percent, to close at
$7.3125 on the New York Stock Exchange. Shares of Safety-Kleen,
which is based in Columbia, S.C., rose $1.0625, or 8.5 percent, to
$13.50.
</P>
<P>
   The planned sales mark a strategy shift for James Bullock, the
chief executive of Laidlaw, who oversaw the company's
diversification. After the sales, Bullock said, ``Laidlaw will
focus on expanding our position as North America's largest provider
of specialty bus services.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its school-bus fleet, Laidlaw became a major
operator of intercity buses with the acquisition of Greyhound Lines
in March.
</P>
<P>
   The company has hired Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. as an adviser and it
expects the asset sales to be completed in the next six to 12
months. With the sale of its Safety-Kleen and health-care
operations, the company said it hopes to ``realize net proceeds in
excess of $2 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Laidlaw's increased focus on the bus business comes against a
background of sharply increased competition in the North American
market from British rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Stagecoach Holdings PLC, Britain's largest bus and
railroad company, agreed to buy Coach USA Inc. for $1.88 billion to
become the largest charter-bus and tour operator in the United
States. In July, the British bus operator FirstGroup PLC said it
would buy Ryder System Inc.'s school-bus business for $940 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although Laidlaw began as a trucker of industrial waste, its
stake in Safety-Kleen is all that remains of that part of its past.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been trying to distance themselves from that
particular business,'' said Cam Hon, an analyst at Dominion Bond
Rating Service in Toronto. He said the size of the Safety-Kleen
stake may help Laidlaw sell above the market price.
</P>
<P>
   Laidlaw's financial statements for the year ended Aug. 31, 1999,
will describe the properties to be sold as discontinued operations,
and an expected loss of $1 billion ($3.03 a share) will be taken on
the sale of the health-care division. Besides American Medical
Response, which has annual revenue of $1 billion, this division
includes Emcare, a medical-practice management company with annual
revenue of $475 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
