<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE AND PIAZZA: WHAT A SAGA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Pinch me, please. Wake me from my dream. I'm not on this
planet, am I? Where am I? Is this how it feels to be among the
dearly departed? Is this reality, or a catatonic trance, or
someone's idea of a surrealistic joke?
</P>
<P>
   I read something over the weekend that left me bewildered,
bewitched, befuddled and, yes, bemused.
</P>
<P>
   I read honestly, it was right there on the sports pages of the
largest-circulation newspaper in L.A. that Kevin Malone made
contact with the New York Mets about the possibility of bringing
Mike Piazza back to the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure the next thing I'm going to hear is that Kevin Malone
has asked President Bill Clinton about the possibility of his being
named a special UN envoy to Indonesia so he can help resolve the
conflict in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps Kevin Malone will ask NASA officials about the
possibility of his being included on the next space shuttle to
Mars, or maybe he will call Al Davis up in Oakland and ask Davis
about the possibility of his playing quarterback for the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Outlandish?
</P>
<P>
   Of course.
</P>
<P>
   But no more fanciful than the startling report that Kevin Malone
actually went to the Mets allegedly sound of mind, body and soul
and sought Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Now ol' Kev has set himself up for enough ridicule during his
brief incumbency as chief choreographer of the Dodgers' comedy
troupe, actually predicting during the off-season that this
rollicking team would be spending a portion of October in the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   You would think Malone would now be treading cautiously in his
utterances and actions, but this is a guy with a habit of walking
in the dark in steep terrain and stumbling haplessly into the
abyss.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Kevin Malone actually thinks he can alter the course
of history at mid-stream, reversing the steady flow of past
mistakes perpetuated by himself and by those who employ him.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers were willing to part with Piazza, reasons Malone,
then wouldn't the Mets be willing to partake in the same insanity?
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure as I write this, Kevin Malone is busy talking to the
Boston Red Sox about Pedro Martinez, the sterling pitcher who also
was discarded by the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   And, if the truth were known, I'm sure Kevin Malone during his
meeting with the Mets also inquired about Roger Cedeno, still
another Dodgers retread who's gone on to bigger and better things
outside L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I'm aghast at the revelation that Malone even attempted
to lure Piazza back, considering the Mets just gave Piazza a
seven-year, $91 million contact, considering the Mets have become a
serious National League playoff contender since Piazza's arrival,
considering Piazza is having another banner season, considering the
Mets are desperately trying to close the gap between themselves and
their more successful crosstown rivals, the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Did Kevin Malone actually believe the Mets would be so myopic,
so imbecilic, so crazed, so like, well, the Dodgers, to give up a
commodity of the magnitude of Mike Piazza?
</P>
<P>
   One idly wonders if Malone's bizarre proposal was nothing more
than a flimsy PR gesture at the behest of the gentlemen reportedly
responsible for Piazza's excommunication, Fox executives Chase
Carey and Peter Chernin, and Dodger president Bob (Don't Call Me
Rocky) Graziano.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodger patrons I talk to still are outraged by Piazza's
ouster and aren't appeased one iota by Malone's latest bit of
zaniness.
</P>
<P>
   From what I've been told about this entire farce, the Mets felt
insulted that Malone would come to them with such a proposition in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, do the Dodgers think the Mets are as dumb as they are?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, if nothing else, Kevin Malone is at least injecting a
few early September cackles into a Southern California baseball
season that has been a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Kev.
</P>
<P>
   The guy hasn't got anything right since he was tabbed to succeed
Tom Lasorda as Dodger GM. He got rid of a catcher who could catch,
Charles Johnson, for one who can't, Todd Hundley. He brought in an
aging center fielder playing out the record in Devon White. He gave
a multi-year, multi-million dollar contract to a guy who can't
pitch, Carlos Perez. I have no idea what reason he brought Alan
Mills to the Dodgers other than to give up base hits to opposing
batters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I grudgingly must admit I have a deep fondness and strong
admiration for Kevin Malone.
</P>
<P>
   This is a religious man who displays courage beyond the divine
duty of his calling.
</P>
<P>
   The shocking fact that he actually phoned the Mets and inquired
about Mike Piazza gives you a clear insight into the enlightened
forces now running one of the storied franchises in baseball
history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-99 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
