<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: WILLIAMS SISTERS WINNERS ON AND OFF CENTER COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Was Serena Williams' victory Saturday in the U.S. Open the
tennis equivalent of Tiger Woods' 1997 Masters triumph? Will the
Serena Effect _ or the combined Serena-Venus Effect _ rival Woods'
dramatic impact on television ratings?
</P>
<P>
   The questions are natural in view of CBS' overnight Nielsen
ratings for the women's semifinals and final. The caution, of
course, is that the Woods Effect has proved itself for more than
two years. The Williamses have done it once.
</P>
<P>
   Serena's defeat of Martina Hingis on Saturday delivered a 7.2
rating, doubling the rating for last year's Hingis-Lindsay
Davenport final and the highest such overnight rating ever for a
U.S. Open women's match. After a five-hour rain delay on Friday
that shifted the women's semifinals into a later time period with
more households watching, Serena's victory over Davenport produced
a 4.0 rating, an increase of 48 percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Venus' loss to Hingis, which occurred partly during prime time,
generated a stunning 5.9 rating, an increase of 111 percent from a
year ago when she lost to Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, Venus and Serena have the ability to attract
the casual tennis fan and people who don't watch tennis because of
their larger-than-life personas,'' Rob Correa, a CBS Sports vice
president, said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that few tennis events are on network television _
the U.S. Open, Wimbledon and the French Open chiefly among them _
so the Williams' impact on network television will be somewhat
muted. ``Tiger can be on network TV every Saturday and Sunday,'' he
said, ``which isn't true with tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS should have taken out full-page newspaper ads to thank the
Williamses for their good Nielsen deeds. But that was left to Puma
(``Serena Rocks!''), the footwear and apparel company endorsed by
Serena, and the National Fluid Milk Processor Promotion Board,
which used the sisters to ask, ``Got Milk?'' With the sisters
together, the ad says: ``One Cup. Two Straws, Please.''
</P>
<P>
   The surging careers of the Williams sisters will make the price
tags of their endorsement deals escalate. With Venus' five-year,
$14 million Reebok deal expiring in April, the cost of keeping her
concerns the company. ``She's a key person for us, on par with
Allen Iverson,'' Dave Fogelson, a Reebok spokesman, said. ``We're
looking at making her an overall brand icon in the fitness
category. She's in our plans, but we can't break the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Venus did not win Saturday, Fogelson said, ``The
excitement she and her sister generated is more important than just
one of them coming to the fore, so Reebok and Puma benefit from the
synergy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Davis, the Williams' lawyer, said corporate interest in
the sisters has been strong for several months. ``But every deal is
evaluated on its own,'' he said. ``There's never been a sense of
urgency to rush into deals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Williamses endorse Wilson Hammer rackets and recently
appeared in American Express print ads, a one-shot deal that Davis
hopes to expand. Bob Williams, the president of Burns Sports, which
matches athletes to advertisers, said: ``Up until now there's been
more demand for them to be together, but that will change as their
careers start to diverge. There's great potential for them to
develop a rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said some companies will want one sister or the other, but
others will want them together. But he knows the sisters'
endorsement future depends on their court success. ``You have to
achieve greatness,'' he said. He pointed to the endorsement success
of the sexy Anna Kournikova, who has not won a tournament but who
is co-starring in a commercial for an investment company.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long will it last if she doesn't win?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   `NFL Today' Redux
</P>
<P>
   Last year, CBS' ``The NFL Today'' was a creative dud. By the
evidence of the revamped edition that made its debut on Sunday, the
studio show is alive and well. The three analysts _ Craig James,
Randy Cross and Jerry Glanville _ do not need the host Jim Nantz to
ask them individually what they think, as he had to do with Marcus
Allen, Brent Jones and George Seifert last season. And Glanville
brings an element rarely seen with more sedate studio denizens: He
squirms on a chair that seems to be delivering electric shocks to
his posterior.
</P>
<P>
   The show had a pace that was missing last year because the four
of them speak quickly and appear to genuinely like one another. But
the oddly named ``eye openers'' prediction segment dragged on and a
feature by Allen, now a field reporter, on the Jets and coach Bill
Parcells, lacked the type of insight provided in a segment of
Thursday's ``Real Sports'' on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was with the Oakland Raiders,'' Allen said, ``they told
the players, `Just win, baby.' Bill Parcells tells his players,
`Just win.''' Huh? What separates Parcells from Oakland's Al Davis
is one single ``baby''?
</P>
<P>
   The foremost Parcells interpreter is Phil Simms, CBS' top game
analyst, who was not in Allen's piece. On HBO, Simms playfully
discussed Parcells' harsh motivational tactics and said, ``I'll
never admit to it, but that fat SOB was right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
